<SLUG> BC-NY-TOBACCO-BILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI BALKING AT CIGARETTE FIRE-SAFETY BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ With just hours left for him to act, Gov. George
Pataki made a series of demands before he would sign a bill that
would make New York the first state to require that cigarettes meet
fire-safety standards.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators from both parties predicted that he would sign the
measure by the midnight deadline on Wednesday. The governor's
office said it would not reveal what he had done until Thursday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which has been hailed as a landmark measure by
anti-tobacco groups, passed the Assembly and the Senate more than a
month ago, without a single dissenting vote. But the governor has
repeatedly refused to give his views of it, and he did not inform
the Legislature of his conditions until Wednesday, the last day he
had, by law, to act on it.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats in both houses expressed frustration
with Pataki's handling of the bill, saying that he was trying to
use it as leverage to win concessions on issues not directly
related to it.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki asked the Legislature to delay the fire-safety standards
by several months to make it easier for tobacco companies to
comply, and to impose fines on retailers that violate the law.
Officials in both parties, in both houses of the Legislature, said
they agreed on Wednesday to those demands, which would be addressed
in a follow-up bill.
</P>
<P>
   But the governor also imposed a second set of conditions,
seeking tough new criminal penalties for tobacco ``bootleggers''
who try to import or sell cigarettes without paying New York's
$1.11-per-pack tax, the highest in the nation; and restricting
Internet sales, which are now used to avoid payment of state taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers in both houses said that they did not necessarily
object to his demands, but that such complex issues should not have
been raised at the last minute and should not hold up the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue of fire safety should stand on its own,'' said Sen.
Frank Padavan, a Queens Republican who sponsored the bill in his
house. ``We don't think that is something that has to be done as
part of this process. The governor has indicated that he supports
the general thrust of our bill, which is welcome news, and we hope
he'll sign it.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Grannis, a Manhattan Democrat who sponsored the
Assembly bill, said, ``I'm very confident we will reach an
agreement and the governor will approve the bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Cigarettes have long been made so that once lighted, they keep
burning, even when they are not being smoked. Anti-tobacco
advocates and some firefighters' groups have called for laws that
would require cigarettes to go out if they were not puffed on for a
few minutes, so that they would pose less of a fire risk. That
requirement, they contend, would prevent hundreds of fire deaths
nationally each year.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed by the Legislature instructs the State Office of
Fire Prevention and Control to come up with flammability standards
by Nov. 1, 2001, after which cigarette makers would have 30 days to
comply. Lawmakers said that in response to the governor, they
agreed to change that provision to six months and impose a $1,000
fine on retailers found selling cigarettes violating the standards.
</P>
<P>
   Several brands of self-extinguishing cigarettes are already on
the market, including More, Merit, Virginia Slims, Capri Light and
Eve Lights. Some are based on the use of thicker paper, others on
altered chemical composition of the paper. Internal industry
reports that have been leaked say that making cigarettes less
flammable does not significantly raise the cost of making them or
affect their taste.
</P>
<P>
   But the law would result in lower sales, because a smoker who
walked away from a lighted cigarette for a few minutes would find
not ashes, but a stub that could be relighted.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco industry waged a muted lobbying campaign against the
bill, arguing that it should be subject to a single national
standard rather than state-by-state rules. Such a standard, in
fact, is also the hope of anti-tobacco advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our basic thrust is not only to do something in New York
state, but also to motivate the Congress to act, which they've
spent years and years not doing,'' Padavan said. ``If we can do it
in New York, I think that would have an awful lot of impact
nationally.''
</P>
</TEXT>
