<SLUG> BC-MURDER-LAWYER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW PARTNER CHARGED IN DEATH OF KANSAS CITY ATTORNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAMBE AND CHRISTINE VENDEL  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Kansas City lawyer was accused Wednesday of beating his law
partner to death.
</P>
<P>
   The charges are the latest development in an ongoing mystery
that started May 5 when a daylight attack mortally wounded the
victim in his downtown office.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Jackson County prosecutors charged Richard Buchli,
49, with second-degree murder and armed criminal action in the
death of Richard Armitage.
</P>
<P>
   Charges are mainly based on blood-splatter evidence on Buchli's
clothes. Authorities said there are still many unanswered questions
in Armitage's death, including a motive and a murder weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evidence was sufficient to bring the charges,'' said County
Prosecutor Bob Beaird, but ``this investigation is ongoing.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchli posted $250,000 bond and was released Wednesday night.
Police said Buchli contends he is innocent but cannot explain the
victim's blood splatter on his clothes.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who answered the phone at Buchli's home Wednesday
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Buchli and a secretary for the two lawyers found Armitage, 49,
in his downtown office on May 5, a Friday afternoon. Armitage died
the following Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   At first, even the cause of death was unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Initially police and hospital officials thought Armitage died of
a gunshot wound, but the medical examiner found he died of head
trauma.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested Buchli in his office around 4 p.m. Tuesday. On
Wednesday afternoon, they searched his house.
</P>
<P>
   According to court papers filed Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   Lab tests found Armitage's blood _ ``high-velocity blood
splatter'' _ on Buchli's pants, shoes and shirt. Blood forms a
pattern of small drops and fine mist as it gets farther from a
victim's body. The blood pattern on Buchli's clothes matched that
on a lamp found near the victim.
</P>
<P>
   Buchli told police he left their law office on the 13th floor in
the Power &AMP; Light Building at 1:50 p.m. and went to lunch.
Surveillance video cameras showed him leaving at 2:10 p.m. They
also show Buchli returned at 2:40 p.m., waited outside for the
secretary to arrive and entered the building with her. They both
found the victim a short time later.
</P>
<P>
   Phone records show that Armitage received a California phone
call at 1:46 p.m. and it ended at 2:03 p.m. _ seven minutes before
the cameras recorded Buchli leaving.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, Buchli graduated from the University of Missouri-Kansas
City School of Law.
</P>
<P>
   He worked for the law firm Gould &AMP; Moore before joining the
Popham law firm as an associate in 1988. He did civil litigation.
Later he met Armitage when they worked together on a case, said
Dennis Egan, a director at the Popham law firm.
</P>
<P>
   Egan said Armitage and Buchli decided to form a partnership.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't look like (Buchli) was going to become a partner
here,'' Egan said. ``I think that is something he wanted to do, so
he left here to form a partnership with Richard Armitage.''
</P>
<P>
   Armitage and Buchli opened a 13th-floor office in 1995 at the
Power &AMP; Light Building.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being law partners, the two were friends, said Kathy
Armitage, the victim's widow. She said she and her husband often
socialized and had dinner with Buchli and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   At their firm, Buchli continued civil litigation work. Three
years ago, he represented Pamela Causey in a personal injury case,
and she was impressed with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed like a very nice person,'' Causey recalled.
</P>
<P>
   And around the office the two lawyers never gave a hint that
anything was amiss between them, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw anything that would lead me to believe they didn't
get along,'' Causey said. ``They were friendly and worked well
together.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buchlis live in a two-story house in the 900 block of W.
120th Terrace in an upper-middle class neighborhood. Neighbors said
Buchli and his wife had lived in the home since it was built about
14 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   They recalled seeing Buchli each morning smoking a cigarette as
he sat on a bench on his front porch, reading the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Beaird said prosecutors don't know of any other time a lawyer
was charged with murder in Jackson County.
</P>
<P>
   But ``the law profession is like anything else,'' he said.
``It's made up of human beings, so nothing is ever a surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   The Star's Mark Morris contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
