<SLUG> BC-GORE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS RAISE RECORD $26.5 MILLION TO COME TO AID OF PARTY
</HEADLINE>
 
(Eds.: Rewrites with details thruout; adds 400 words) By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Most people shelled out just 50 bucks, but some
could not help giving or gathering $500,000. So there were
different ``tiers'' of donors in kind of a class system sprayed
throughout the giant MCI Sports Center Wednesday night, but all of
them were part of a history-making event: the biggest political
fund-raiser ever, raising $26.5 million in three hours for the
Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats billed the event as a tribute to President
Clinton, and the donors, from those in black tie to those in blue
jeans, were beckoned by the Midas of fund-raisers, Terry McAuliffe,
who, in the end, squeezed 13,625 people into a space designed for
12,000.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, the designated beneficiary of the
party's treasure chest, hailed McAuliffe as ``the greatest
fund-raiser in the history of the universe.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, dressed in a sage polo shirt with his Palm Pilot clipped
to his blue jeans, also declared that he would make reform of the
campaign finance system a top priority if elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those who had come up with half a million dollars for
the party included representatives of organized labor, fresh from
their defeat on Capitol Hill at the hands of the Clinton
administration on the China trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   But that battle seemed distant as many in the arena emitted
rock-concert-like shrieks when Clinton was introduced and Tina
Turner's pulsating hit, ``You're Simply the Best,'' blared through
the loud speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Gore, this is the tune that his campaign has
been road testing as his campaign theme song. And it underscored a
sad reality for Gore: As at some of the other joint appearances of
the Clintons and Gores in the past, while Gore is meant to be the
star, Clinton steals the show. ``Four more years!'' was shouted
from the crowd as he spoke.
</P>
<P>
   Al DiRienzo, 68, a bricklayer from Maryland, reflected the
sentiment. He said that he was supporting Gore but that his
affection was for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the greatest president we've ever had,'' DiRienzo
said, ``and it's a shame we can't vote for him again.''
</P>
<P>
   After Tipper Gore and Hillary Rodham Clinton spoke, the arena
fell dark for a lengthy video tribute to Clinton and his eight-year
administration. It was a paean to overcoming adversity and was
awash in sentimentality.
</P>
<P>
   And when Clinton took the stage, he opened with a fiery, if
defensive challenge, to an unspoken suggestion that the vast sums
of money the party was raking in was inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that it's corruption to take money to pass the
Brady Bill instead of beat it,'' he said, ``to pass the family and
medical leave bill so 21 million ordinary working people can take
some time off when their babies are born and their parents are sick
instead of beat it.''
</P>
<P>
   And he offered what appeared to be unrehearsed lines, including
bemused commentary on his advancing age.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the video that had just unfolded, Clinton told the
audience: ``I had sort of mixed feelings looking at that film,
actually. I watched myself get grayer and grayer and grayer, and I
thought to myself, before I got into my second term here, I was
always the youngest person who did everything. Now I'm up here in
my old boots and my old jeans, and I'm just kind of an old
gray-haired red neck trying to put in some good months here.''
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe accomplished his task: to beat the Republicans, who
raised a mere $21.3 million at their gala a month ago. He let them
gloat at their treasure chest and low-balled his estimates of what
the Democrats could raise, only to be able to trumpet his success
later.
</P>
<P>
   The money goes to the Democratic National Committee and will be
used to help Gore pay for commercials for his presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Richardson, the secretary of energy, was on hand Wednesday
night and acknowledged that the money would come in handy,
especially when the advertising wars begin on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think neither party is going to unilaterally disarm,''
Richardson said, going on to explain, as he stood by a table of
donors who had raised up to $500,000, ``We're the party of the
small donors, the grass roots.''
</P>
<P>
   Tables for dignitaries were spread across the floor of the
sports arena, where guests were served barbecue from restaurants in
Arkansas and Tennessee, home states of the president and vice
president, along with bottles of merlot and chardonnay. John
Vergos, whose family owns the popular barbecue restaurant
Rendezvous in Memphis, flew in 800 pounds of barbecued chicken and
beef ribs Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Up in the bleachers, guests had to buy their food at the regular
arena prices, for example, $3.75 for a cup of cola.
</P>
<P>
   John Bunting, 56, who works in social services in Baltimore,
paid $50 to attend Wednesday night's party. The Republicans are
trying to cast the presidential race as a ``personality contest,''
Bunting said, ``and that's a much tougher race for Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Surveying the arena, he said that much of the crowd probably
came to pay tribute to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that Vice President Gore falls short,'' he said,
``it's that we're talking about the king.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
