<SLUG> BC-DEMS-MONEY-1STLEDE-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS SET RECORD BY RAISING $26 MILLION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Editors: adds detail in 2nd graph, expands quote in 5th graph) 
 
 
By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even as presidential candidate Al Gore is vowing to
work for campaign finance reform, the Democratic Party Wednesday
shattered fund-raising records by raking in $26 million at a ``blue
jeans and barbecue'' gala.
</P>
<P>
   The take surpassed a single-day record for political
fund-raising set earlier this spring by the Republicans, who
collected $21 million in a tribute to their presidential candidate,
Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The event Wednesday, billed as a tribute to President Clinton,
attracted more than 12,000 supporters to the MCI sports arena,
where they were entertained by such stars as Robin Williams, Stevie
Wonder, LeAnn Rimes and Darius Rucker of Hootie and the Blowfish.
</P>
<P>
   The guest of honor appeared in a video touting achievements of
his administration, then spoke to the gathering. He was
unapologetic about the prodigious fund-raising, saying money from
supporters helps the party accomplish its goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's corruption to take money to pass the Brady
Bill (for background checks of firearms purchases), to pass the
family and medical leave bill, to pass the patients' bill of
rights, to reduce the deficit and get rid of the debt instead of
giving big breaks to special interests,'' Clinton said. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Vice President Gore said, if elected, his first goal will be to
pass campaign finance reform. ``If you elect me, the good news is
when we all come back here in four years, it won't cost as much,''
Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also addressed gun control, noting that Charlton Heston,
just elected to a third term as president of the National Rifle
Association, called Gore ``the No. 1 foe of the gun lobby.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said, ``I wear that as a badge of honor.''
</P>
<P>
   He alluded to Heston's role as Moses in ``The Ten Commandments''
in a reference to his likely Republican opponent, Texas Gov. George
Bush. ``The last time Moses listened to a bush, the people wandered
in the desert for 40 years,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   The gala underscored the growing fund-raising prowess of the
Democrats, who for years trailed significantly behind Republicans
in their ability to generate campaign cash.
</P>
<P>
   The competition was vividly on display in the nation's capital
Wednesday evening, as Republicans held their own event several
blocks from the Democratic gala and expected to raise $11 million
for House and Senate candidates. That fund-raiser featured former
President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In the first 15 months of the 1999-2000 cycle, the Democrats
have raised $76 million in unrestricted ``soft money'' compared
with $84 million for the Republicans. That is a smaller gap than at
a similar point in the 1996 presidential election cycle, when the
Democrats raised $36 million and the Republicans collected $48
million in soft money.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans continue to be far ahead in collecting
restricted ``hard money '' contributions, raising $180 million to
the Democrats' $100 million in the first 15 months of the cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials sought to deflate any suggestion that they
were catering to wealthy contributors by stressing that
three-quarters of the attendees paid $50 to attend the event. The
menu included pork ribs and cole slaw flown in from the Rendezvous
Restaurant in Memphis, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the down-home theme, the event still drew its share of
influential donors who had either given or raised between $100,000
and $500,000. These donors were seated in prime front row tables on
the floor of the vast arena, while the $50 ticket holders sat up in
the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans noted the presence of these top donors as they
dismissed Democrats' claim that they were throwing a grass-roots
rally.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Paulitz, a spokesman for the Republican National
Committee, said that if everyone had paid $50 apiece the
fund-raiser would have had to attract 520,000 people to raise $26
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying to bill this thing tonight as a common folk
fund-raiser. But if you had common sense you would know this is a
sham,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Paulitz said that the fund-raiser also showed the weakness of
Gore because he had to rely on Clinton to help generate campaign
funds.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton has been a tireless fund-raiser for his party,
much of the money he has helped bring in is intended to help his
vice president win the White House. The Gore campaign has proposed
that the party run $30 million in ads promoting his presidential
campaign in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   These party-financed issue ads have been criticized by campaign
finance advocates because they are viewed as a way of circumventing
contribution limits imposed on candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has called for the elimination of the soft money to the
political parties and vowed not to let the Democratic Party run
such ads on his behalf unless the GOP did so first. Gore spokesman
Chris Lehane said that the Democrats are now justified in running
such ads because a series of conservative organizations have begun
airing ads against Gore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
