<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5218 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-LATINOS-1STRESEND-LAD     05-25 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATINOS-1STRESEND-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST RESEND; ORIGINAL WAS GARBLED
</HEADLINE>
 Latino actors routinely overlooked 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hollywood provides few opportunities for Latino
performers and targets few productions to what is America's
fastest-growing minority with a $10 billion-a-year entertainment
appetite, a new study conducted for the Screen Actors Guild said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The study, ``Still Missing: Latinos In and Out of Hollywood,''
found that entertainment executives doubted the economic viability
of Latino-theme productions. It also showed that the industry
tended to revert to racial biases as the periodic outcries for
minority representation died down.
</P>
<P>
   While Latinos make up 11.5 percent of the population, they
``rarely occupy more than 2 percent of the available jobs in the
film and television industry,'' according to the study. Last week,
broadcast networks announced their new shows for the fall, with
virtually no starring roles given to Latino performers.
</P>
<P>
   The study, conducted by the Tomas Rivera Policy Institute for
SAG, gave TV and studio executives, producers, writers and
directors a chance to speak anonymously about the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Several blamed the bottom line as a key reason there are few
Latino roles, pointing specifically to difficulties in marketing to
the geographically and culturally broad group, to the box office
failures of several Latino-theme movies since 1987's ``La Bamba,''
and to the fact that few Latino actors are recognized in foreign
markets.
</P>
<P>
   One studio executive said advocates have built a good ``social
case'' for minority inclusion but they have not effectively
addressed the business side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Studio executives will lend half an ear to a social case, but
the bottom line is that the corporate suites are running a
business, and business is about profits and potential profits,''
the executive said. ``Develop a business case and you will bring
about change.''
</P>
<P>
   The same individual said the industry tends to get fired up
about minority issues, starting internships after organizations
apply pressure, ``but as time passes, these programs fade away.''
</P>
<P>
   Actress Anne-Marie Johnson, national chairwoman of the guild's
Ethnic Employment Opportunity Committee, said part of the problem
is that producers and executives tend to make the whole genre of
Latino-theme movies pay the price for the failure of one film.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have minority-themed or minority-cast films and they
don't do well, the assumption is `Let's not do another one.'''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the guild has not yet examined all the supporting
players in the networks' fall shows, but she called the dearth of
Latinos in leads ``reprehensible.''
</P>
<P>
   She sounded a note of cautious optimism about Showtime's new
series, ``Resurrection Blvd.,'' which will debut June 26. Set in
East Los Angeles, it centers on a working-class Mexican-American
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that many of our members of color are very excited when
projects are created for specific ethnic groups,'' she said, happy
about the many jobs a large-cast series like ``Resurrection Blvd.''
creates.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have to be very careful,'' Johnson added. ``We can't be
content just with employment. We have to make sure that images
progress with the progressions of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,200 actors responded to the mailed questionnaire,
out of 4,800 Latino guild members _ an extremely strong response
level and a good indication that this is a significant concern to
them, said Harry Pachon, TRPI president, who led the research team.
</P>
<P>
   The Latino actors who responded worked an average of 12 days
last year on SAG projects, for an annual income of about $12,000,
compared with about $17,000 for their non-Latino, white colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Pachon said Latino actors said they are consistently passed over
for ethnically nondescript ``crossover'' roles, such as a lawyer, a
doctor, a teacher, a cop. They also are locked out of jobs if they
don't look or sound ``Latino,'' yet if they (ital)do(off) fit
directors' and writers' molds, they are given stereotypical
characters to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty-six percent of our respondents say that stereotype
includes Mestizo features ... meaning a blend of European and
Indian characteristics,'' Pachon told a news conference. ``So if
you're too dark, you won't get cast as a Latino. If you're too
white, you won't get cast as a Latino. You have to pick that magic
midpoint to be cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secondly and very disturbingly, 30 percent of our respondents
say that to be cast as a Latino, you have to have a Spanish
accent,'' he said. ``Because of those two characteristics, perhaps
because of the darker color of skin and the accent, they are cast
in serving-class roles - Jose the busboy, Maria the maid, the
carwash attendant.''
</P>
<P>
   He said an additional 20 percent complained about too many
criminal roles.
</P>
<P>
   Pachon said Hollywood has continued to underestimate the income
traced to Latino consumers. He said in 1998, Latinos spent about
$500 million on movie tickets, enough to ensure the success of five
blockbusters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a giant market out there just waiting to be tapped,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   It also is growing at a faster rate than other market segments.
From 1994 to 1998, according to U.S. Bureau of Labor figures,
Latino families increased their entertainment spending by 5.6
percent while non-Latino, white families actually decreased their
entertainment expenditures by 5.3 percent. In the same time span,
African-American spending remained flat overall.
</P>
<P>
   Bel Hernandez, editor and publisher of the entertainment trade
magazine Latin Heat, said studios have failed to reach the Latino
market because they are relying on the same old marketing firms
that use outmoded approaches to the bilingual, urban and suburban
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez said the success of Ricky Martin and other Latino
music stars seems to have awakened entertainment executives to the
potential market, and that could trigger changes in the movie and
TV segments.
</P>
<P>
   As for solutions, many SAG members asked their union to play a
more aggressive role, whether it is through affirmative action
measures or advocating its minorities with casting directors and
writers.
</P>
<P>
   On the industry side, the consensus was that such changes would
have to come from the top down. But progress isn't likely to happen
overnight. One TV executive, asked how to bring about change,
replied: ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
