<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ROYALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROYALS END RANGERS' WINNING STREAK AT 7
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kenny Rogers pitched pretty well last night
for a guy who has been sitting around 12 days nursing a sore
shoulder and poked eye.
</P>
<P>
   But Kansas City's Jeff Suppan was a little better. His pitching
and a seventh-inning defensive breakdown by the Rangers brought
their seven-game winning streak to end with a 3-0 loss to the
Royals at Kauffman Stadium last night.
</P>
<P>
   Suppan held the Rangers scoreless on six hits and three walks
through eight innings before Jerry Spradlin retired the side in
order in the ninth to complete the shutout. It's the second time
the Rangers have been shut out this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suppan pitched a great game,'' Rangers designated hitter
Rafael Palmeiro said. ``He had good movement on his ball, changed
speeds and hit his spots. See, it doesn't matter if the ball is
juiced or the bat is juiced. If a guy hits his spots, throws
strikes and changes speeds, he can still win, and that's what
Suppan did tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of the hits and two of the walks came in the first three
innings, but the Rangers went 0-for-4 with runners in scoring
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he gave us some pitches to hit in the early
innings,'' left fielder Chad Curtis said. ``Mid-game to late he
started making good pitches, but we had some opportunities early in
the game and didn't take advantage of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, for all their firepower lately, still have some
players in hitting funks. Palmeiro is in a 12-for-60 skid, Ruben
Mateo has two hits in 23 at-bats and Royce Clayton is hitless in 14
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers allowed three runs in 6 1/3 innings but couldn't shake
the physical misfortune that has dogged him through May. After
straining his shoulder on a little flip to first base in his
previous start May 11 and having his right eye poked while playing
with his 3-year-old son, Trevor, on Friday, Rogers had to leave
last night's game in the seventh inning after taking a groundball
off his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   That was one of several plays not made that inning that allowed
the Royals to give Suppan two extra unearned runs of support. The
Rangers' meltdown started with one out when Clayton fumbled Rey
Sanchez's grounder for an error.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kind of cued it, and it took a weird hop,'' said Clayton,
who went 0-for-3. ``I went to get my hop, and the ball stayed down.
It's just the way my game is going lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Damon followed with a grounder back to Rogers, who did
his best Eddie Belfour ``butterfly'' stop to keep the ball from
going through. Instead, it caromed off Rogers' right knee and
toward third baseman Mike Lamb, who made a diving stop but threw
too late to get Damon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to get a little extra on my fastball, and that gave me
less time to react,'' said Rogers, who made a tougher catch on Joe
Randa's line drive in the second. ``Less effort and I would have
had it.''
</P>
<P>
   With runners at first and second, Francisco Cordero took over
for Rogers and got Carlos Febles to hit a double-play grounder
right at Lamb. But second baseman Luis Alicea had trouble on the
turn, and the Rangers got only one out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't get a hold of it; I couldn't get it out my glove
quickly,'' Alicea said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers paid dearly for that when Mike Sweeney doubled to
left-center field, bringing home two runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play well defensively that inning,'' Rangers manager
Johnny Oates said. ``When you play a low-scoring game, defense is
imperative. One run is a lot easier to come back from than three.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers had ice on his right] knee after the game, but the
Rangers don't expect it to be a problem. Rogers was also feeling
better about his shoulder, which gave him no trouble through the
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was glad to go out there and not feel anything,'' Rogers
said. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
