<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5221 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-PRESBYTERIAN-GAYS-SFC     05-25 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESBYTERIAN-GAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PRESBYTERIAN CHURCH APPROVES `HOLY UNIONS' FOR GAYS, LESBIANS  &HT;     By DON LATTIN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a ruling that could spark a conservative backlash, the
highest court of the Presbyterian Church ruled Wednesday that its
ministers may perform ``holy union'' ceremonies for gay and lesbian
couples _ as long as they don't call it ``marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   And in another victory for gay rights advocates, the
denomination's Permanent Judicial Commission ruled that the church
may accept a young gay man in New Jersey as a candidate for
ordained ministry.
</P>
<P>
   The two cases were the first serious challenges to a 1996 church
law requiring all Presbyterian ministers and elders to ``practice
fidelity in marriage and chastity in singleness.''
</P>
<P>
   Church marriage, however, is limited to heterosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Byers, executive director of San Francisco-based Covenant
Network of Presbyterians, a national advocacy group seeking a more
tolerant attitude toward gays and lesbians, welcomed the two
rulings.
</P>
<P>
   Byers noted that neither ruling actually changes church law, but
gives Presbyterians more latitude in ministering to gays and
lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   The church court did not overturn the ban on the ordination of
noncelibate homosexuals, but it chose not to extend the prohibition
to seminarians and candidates for ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the 16-member judicial commission did not clear the
way for gay ``marriage,'' but gave qualified support to church
ceremonies that bless the union of gay and lesbian couples.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can bless boats and pets and retirements, you can ask
for God's blessings on significant relationships,'' Byers said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, conservatives argued the opposite before the high
court, which was considering a 1998 ``holy union'' ceremony for two
gay men at South Presbyterian Church in Dobbs Ferry, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Gordon Fish of Montclair, N.J., told the court that
``holy union'' ceremonies are a ``sham'' and ``a case of semantic
hair-splitting.''
</P>
<P>
   Fish said the two men being blessed ``didn't talk about being
holy-unioned, but about being married. They didn't order a holy
union cake, but a wedding cake.''
</P>
<P>
   Presbyterian Church spokesman Jerry Van Marter predicted the
controversy over ``holy union'' ceremonies will dominate a General
Assembly that convenes from June 24 to July 1 in Long Beach to set
national policy for the 2.6 million-member denomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were already expected to talk about holy unions, but this
will rachet up the debate to the level of hysteria,'' Van Marter
said.
</P>
<P>
   Three regional church bodies, including the conservative
Presbytery of San Joaquin in California's Central Valley, already
had introduced legislation seeking an outright ban on holy union
ceremonies for gay and lesbian couples.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned about an uproar in the pews, the two top leaders of
the Presbyterian Church Wednesday issued an unusual ``pastoral
letter'' about the court rulings.
</P>
<P>
   Presbyterian Church Moderator Freda Gardner and Stated Clerk
Clifton Kirkpatrick acknowledged in the letter that the gay rights
debate has revealed ``deep, and often conflicting, convictions
among Presbyterians.''
</P>
<P>
   They stressed that the court ruling on ordination involved a gay
man in New Jersey ``who is currently celibate but who intends to
participate in a fully sexual way in a future monogamous same-sex
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the decision on ``holy union'' ceremonies, they stressed
the commission's warning that ministers must still ``take special
care to avoid any confusion of (same sex) services with services of
Christian marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, they said pastors should be given ``wide
latitude'' for ``blessing people in a variety of relationships,
life situations and endeavors, including those that might involve
two persons of the same gender.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Davis, executive director of the Presbyterian Forum, a
conservative evangelical group, said the church should prohibit
same-sex ``blessings,'' along with gay marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Citing Biblical condemnations of homosexuality, Davis said,
``God calls homosexual behavior sinful. We should not bless what
God has called sinful.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' organization, based in San Marcos (San Diego County),
describes itself as ``mired in a battle for the soul and
structure'' of the Presbyterian Church. It's one of several
conservative Presbyterian groups expected to play an active role at
next month's national convention.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the United Methodist Church held its
quadrennial convention in Cleveland, where it overwhelmingly voted
to retain its ban on ``holy union'' services and homosexual clergy.
Those issues are also expected to spark lively debate at a national
convention of Episcopalians to be held July 5-14 in Denver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
