<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PLEASE PUT YOUR RINGER ON VIBRATE  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The cell phone user is on the lam.
</P>
<P>
   He has been driven out of restaurants and bars and into back
alleys and bathrooms, like a junkie.
</P>
<P>
   He (or she) is being flipped off on the highways, scorned on the
sidewalks, shushed on buses and trains.
</P>
<P>
   A leper for our times.
</P>
<P>
   And why? The poor guy is just making a telephone call. It's not
like he's smoking or picking his nose or trimming his toenails.
</P>
<P>
   I admit it, the cell people annoy me at times. I'm in the market
selecting a watermelon when a man walks toward me, looks me in the
eye, smiles, says with much enthusiasm, ``Hey, what's going on, how
you doin'?''
</P>
<P>
   I start to reply, but the man brushes past me, and I notice he's
talking on his cell.
</P>
<P>
   And volume? Based purely on observation, I'd say that 75 percent
of cell phone users are talking to their deaf grandmothers.
</P>
<P>
   But what if we could get a little courtesy going? Would it
really be so terrible if the guy at the next restaurant table is
quietly checking in with his stockbroker or baby sitter, as long as
he's not roaring and swearing and pounding the table like a drunken
pirate?
</P>
<P>
   Jim Brandt, who owns the Gold Coast restaurant on California
St., has made a stunning discovery: Scorn and ridicule aren't going
to make cell phones go away.
</P>
<P>
   Brandt went to the top of Mount Sutro and returned with the Ten
Commandments of Cell Phoning, which I herewith edit to the most
vital seven:
</P>
<P>
   When driving, pull over ... When walking, watch out ...
Remember: Even punks have cell phones ... Indoors, put ringer on
``vibrate''... Speak SOFTLY ... Excuse yourself (one-sided
conversations are so dull).
</P>
<P>
   HOW COME New York gets the good stuff?
</P>
<P>
   Steve Beck reports from the Apple: ``Low-tech New York subways
have high-tech ticket machines _ big, shiny consoles with
multilingual screen, color video, they accept bills, coins, credit
cards, ATM cards, IOUs ... And dispense thin plastic magnetic cards
good on subways, buses, ferries. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, our BART ticket machines are so old, they accept gold
dust.
</P>
<P>
   YOU DIRTY RAT: Nicole Bilotti was reading the spring issue of
``Calling,'' the newsletter in your Pac Bell phone bill. An article
titled ``It's an Inside Wire Job'' reveals a common cause of phone
wire problems:
</P>
<P>
   ``When pesky rodents get too cozy with your wiring ...''
</P>
<P>
   Now we have to worry about kinky rats. Used to be they'd be
happy playing with a hunk of moldy cheese.
</P>
<P>
   MORE EVIDENCE that S.F. is the center of the hip universe: Oscar
de la Renta jetted into town to receive an honorary doctorate from
the Academy of Art College, which is gaining a worldwide rep for
its design school.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Oscar handed out two scholarships to work with his fashion
design people in New York and Paris.
</P>
<P>
   For two days this week, Willie Brown was the second-best-dressed
dude in town. And George Hamilton had the second-best tan.
</P>
<P>
   RESCUED from the scrap heap: The Washington Square Penny Pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Moose started the event in '76 at the Washington Square Bar &AMP;
Grill, to raise money for St. Anthony's Dining Room. Ed moved on,
and this year, the Washbag abandoned the pitch.
</P>
<P>
   So Moose took it back, will hold it Monday at 1 p.m. on the
sidewalk in front of his restaurant on Stockton, facing Washington
Square Park. Celebrities, politicians, athletes, chefs, tossing
pennies against a wall.
</P>
<P>
   THE NEW RULES of grammar, as observed by Molly Ditmore of
listen.com, a music downloading biz where the kids also send in
their thoughts:
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never have enough exclamation marks ... It is
apparently acceptable in high school to replace `s' with `z' ...
Asterisks replace vowels to slip naughty words past the profanity
filter ... Forget grammar, and spellcheck is a total waste of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The innernet (cq)  &LR; sure is making kids learn smarter.''
</P>
<P>
   A YOUNG single mother disappeared from the Monterey area more
than a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The local merchants have managed to scrape up $4,000 in reward
money to help find her,'' says Carma Allen. ``It's too bad she
didn't have a dog with her.''
</P>
<P>
   MAYBE GETTING bounced off his longtime gig on radio KNBR has
sent Rush Limbaugh reeling.
</P>
<P>
   Rush confessed that he auditioned for ABC's Monday Night
Football. Insiders tell me Limbaugh won't get the job as announcer
Al Michaels' sidekick, but has a good shot at being offered a
high-profile spot if the Goodyear Blimp decides to retire.
</P>
<P>
   I'M SURPRISED that Chuck Quackenbush was so upset. You'd think
he would have ambush insurance.
</P>
