<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5225 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-TRIBES-MONEY-SFCHRON &LR;      05-25 1523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIBES-MONEY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIAN TRIBES FLEX MONEY MUSCLES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By KEVIN FAGAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Flush with gambling revenue, California's Indian tribes have
paid out about $114 million for political campaigns since 1998, far
surpassing any other interest group to become the nearly invisible
giant of state campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   And though most of that money was spent on their own two
gambling ballot measures _ including Proposition 1A, the initiative
overwhelmingly passed in March to allow an explosion of
Nevada-style gaming on Indian lands _ the cash also went flying in
sizable wads toward politicians.
</P>
<P>
   The state's top 22 Indian gambling tribes or organizations
collectively donated more than $7 million to legislative or
statewide candidates in 1997 and 1998, dwarfing all other interest
groups, according to statistics being compiled by California Common
Cause.
</P>
<P>
   The second-biggest spender in that period was the state prison
guard union, the California Correctional Peace Officers
Association, which gave $1.9 million to candidates. And though
donations from similarly minded law enforcement organizations would
raise that total if added in, ``There is no way they could all come
close to the tribal spending,'' said Common Cause Executive
Director Jim Knox.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an extraordinary amount of money, and it makes Native
Americans the biggest political campaign contributors in the
state,'' said Knox, who expects to issue a report detailing the
expenditures early next month. ``What this shows is that the
state's tribes have very quickly come from relative obscurity to
become the No. 1 political power (in terms of political money) in
the state.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 and 1996, for example, the same tribal interests spent
only $950,000. And if you go back to the late 1980s, before
reservation casino gambling became a cash fountain, Indians spent
virtually nothing _ mostly because they didn't have much to spend.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that there isn't a single self-described Indian
legislator in the state Capitol. That makes the need to have a
voice through campaign donations all the more crucial, Indians say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody took notice of us before, and our issues were never
addressed in Sacramento because we were not able to lobby before,''
said Barbara Gonzales Lyons, tribal council vice chairwoman of the
Agua Caliente Band of Cahuilla Indians, which runs a booming casino
near Palm Springs. ``Ten years ago, we didn't even have the funds
to take care of our own people, let alone donate to campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now that we have gaming, we can move forward and protect
not just our gaming interests, but our people's interests.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Lots of Issues
</P>
<P>
   That means everything from tribal-vs.-state rights on child
custody cases to environmental and fire control issues on local
lands bordering her reservation, Lyons said. It would be nice if
everyone could be heard in Sacramento, regardless of their funding
heft, ``but that would be an idealistic world,'' she said. ``We
have to deal with the way things are.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1995 to 1998, Lyons' tribe gave $1.6 million to statewide
and legislative candidates _ second only, among California gaming
tribes, to the donations from the Morongo Band of Mission Indians,
which gave $1.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   In propelling money toward Sacramento power brokers, the Agua
Caliente and other tribes were merely doing what has always been
done by doctors, lawyers, police officers and every other group
with a vested interest in legislation, Lyons and others said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're only playing by the existing rules, and it's hard to
fault the Indians, or the prison guards, or anyone else who is
spending their money legally,'' said Tony Miller, a former
secretary of state. ``Clearly, money talks, and these are wise
investments.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said the sheer magnitude of donations, Indian and
otherwise, is an example of why campaign reform is badly needed in
California. And he noted that beyond political circles, the growing
spending muscle of Indian tribes seems to have gone largely
unnoticed, outside of brief attention paid to gaming initiative
spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will change,'' he said. ``Most people don't have a clue
about what's happened, but they will soon. We are on our way to
becoming ` &LR; Nevada West,' &LR;  and when people see full-blown gambling
all over the place, they will understand that the Indians have
become real forces.''
</P>
<P>
   That recognition will sit just fine with Dave Baron, spokesman
for the Barona Band of Mission Indians in San Diego County, which
donated $588,300 to candidates in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are active members of society and in Sacramento, that's all
this really shows,'' said Baron. ``We support good government, and
so we help people who want to do good government. ''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the tribal spending is being directed at Democrats, not
surprising considering the traditional alliance between the party
and Indians. And the tribes seem to be getting results.
</P>
<P>
   Knox said that other than the nearly universal legislative
support for Indian gaming, one ``blatant example'' of tribal cash
appearing to buy influence came in the positioning of Proposition
1A on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   It should have been Proposition 12, ``since propositions are
assigned numbers in order based on when they qualify,'' Knox
pointed out. ``But in this case the Legislature passed a special
bill to put it first on the ballot. This could not happen for just
anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The significance of the positioning is that the farther down the
ballot voters go, the more prone they are to either vote no or
simply not mark off a vote at all, Knox said. Legislators said they
put it first on the ballot because they considered it a high
priority, just as they did when they accorded similar positioning
to another Proposition 1A, the 1998 measure that authorized $9.2
billion in school bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The one politician tribes spent the most on in recent years is
the top man in state government, Gov. Gray Davis, who also was the
architect of the state-tribal gaming compact that formed the heart
of Proposition 1A. Indian gaming interests ponied up $902,605 for
his 1998 campaign in cash, in-kind and independent expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, Democratic Lt. Gov. Cruz Bustamante took in
$603,250 in tribal gaming donations. Rounding out the top three
recipients of tribal attention that year, with $832,250 in
donations, was Dave Stirling, the failed Republican candidate for
attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Stirling, a rare Republican to be backed by tribes, was not a
surprising pick considering that his opponent was Democrat Bill
Lockyer _ who, having crafted many of the existing gambling control
laws, was considered only tepidly friendly to tribal gaming
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Lockyer received only $185,350 in 1998, placing him ninth on the
tribal donations list, but since then, he has worked to firm up
relations with tribes. He has taken a gentle hand in setting up
joint tribe-state oversight regulations under Proposition 1A, and
just last month he allowed the Barona tribe to hold a golfing
fund-raiser in his name.
</P>
<P>
   Lockyer donated the $10,000 raised at the event to charity after
critics gored him for getting too cozy with the very industry he
will have a role in regulating.
</P>
<P>
   But that flap was just a speed bump in the Indian nations'
headlong rush toward political power through campaign cash. Now
that Proposition 1A has opened the doors to megabucks Nevada-style
gambling at reservations, tribal money power will continue to grow.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of money spent on the two gaming initiatives is the
clearest indicator of that heft. The $67 million tribes poured onto
Proposition 5 in 1998 _ which overwhelmingly passed but was
overturned by the state Supreme Court _ was a state record for
initiative spending. And the $40 million spent on Proposition 1A
dwarfed the $44,000 raised and spent by the measure's opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Barring future initiatives, it remains to be seen whether the
tribes will continue opening their wallets to candidates. But the
money certainly will be there.
</P>
<P>
   The state's tribes already pull down $1.4 billion a year in
revenue, but because of newly allowed slot machines, the figure is
expected to blossom to $4.4 billion by 2004 _ making California the
biggest gambling state outside Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, whose support for the Indians' gaming venture puts him in
marked contrast to his predecessor, Pete Wilson, makes no apologies
for taking tribal money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's put it in perspective,'' said the governor's senior
political adviser, Garry South. ``In 1998, remember, we spent about
$35 million on the primary and general elections, and when you
raise and spend that kind of money, no one group of donors has
disproportionate standing. We have a very broad base.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, he acknowledged that gaming tribes ``are very
important political players now'' and as such, they deserve
respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``And luckily,'' he said with a chuckle, ``they tend to be
Democratic. It helps counterbalance all the money the Republicans
get from the National Rifle Association and the tobacco
companies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
