<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARTNERS-LEAVE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS VETOES BILL PERMITTING FAMILY LEAVE FOR PARTNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Bowing to business group opposition, Gov. Gray
Davis vetoed a bill Wednesday that would have allowed employees to
use family leave to care for a domestic partner.
</P>
<P>
   The veto brought sharp criticism from the author of the bill,
which also would have expanded family leave to include care for
siblings, adult children and grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's pretty cruel news for working people with loved
ones who are dying at home,'' said Sen. Tom Hayden, D-Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was opposed by the California Manufacturing and
Technology Association, which said the bill would be an
``administrative nightmare'' for employers, and the Committee on
Moral Concerns.
</P>
<P>
   One supporter of the bill heaped criticism on Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm outraged,'' said Jeff Sheehy, director of Equal Benefits
Advocates and an activist who helped draft San Francisco's
domestic-partners benefits law. ``He's denying us our basic
humanity. He's saying our partners aren't as important as his
wife.''
</P>
<P>
   In his veto message, the Democratic governor said the bill
broadens family leave ``far beyond what any other state has
permitted to a relationship outside the family _ specifically to
individuals who live together to share expenses if one of those
individuals subsequently becomes seriously ill.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayden criticized Davis for what he said was kowtowing to
business groups, which complained that such a law would more than
double the number of people qualifying for family leave and create
administrative headaches because employees could take time off in
one 12-week block or an hour at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor's position is that any bill affecting business
has to be signed off by business,'' Hayden said. ``By that point of
view, family leave never would have become law in California or the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's family leave law requires employers to allow family
leave for a birth, adoption or serious illness of a child. Family
leave can also be used to care for a sick parent or spouse or
because of the employee's health.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of VETO25 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Hayden's bill would have added domestic partners, grandparents,
adult children and siblings who depend on the employee for care and
who share a residence with the employee.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Davis) agrees with family leave law for husbands and wives
and their children, but he doesn't want it extended to
grandparents, siblings and domestic partners,' Hayden said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Davis signed a bill creating a statewide
domestic-partner registry and extended health benefits to domestic
partners of state workers.
</P>
<P>
   But he opposed other bills and, since then, has been reluctant
to expand the rights given to domestic partners further.
</P>
<P>
   He will be tested this year. There are bills which, among other
things, allow domestic partners to inherit property, make funeral
arrangements and sue for wrongful death.
</P>
<P>
   Hayden said the genesis for the bill came from a gay member of
his staff whose partner was dying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw very clearly he had to choose between his job and taking
care of a loved one. I could see what he was going through and how
his morale on the job was very strained. We worked it out. But not
every employee can get that kind of arrangement.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayden, who is leaving the Legislature next year, said he has
not decided whether to work with Davis this year on a compromise or
let future lawmakers tackle the issue.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of VETO25 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
