<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5230 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-CHINA-RIGHTS-SFCHRON &LR;      05-25 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-RIGHTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PROVISIONS ON RIGHTS DISPLEASE BEIJING  &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By most accounts, the margin of victory in Wednesday's historic
trade vote was provided by measures that would increase monitoring
of China's human rights record _ and may create new friction
between Washington and Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials reacted angrily early Thursday to human rights
provisions in the bill, calling them ``unacceptable to the Chinese
government'' and indicating that they may be blocked outright _ as
Beijing has done with similar, more limited measures in the past.
</P>
<P>
   At best, many experts say, the measures will produce slow,
bureaucratic baby steps toward reform.
</P>
<P>
   The human-rights provisions were added in the last days of
furious lobbying to pass the bill for permanent normal trade
relations, or PNTR.
</P>
<P>
   The measures' authors, Rep. Sander Levin, D-Michigan, and Rep.
Doug Bereuter, R-Neb., touted them as a formula for two-track
change for China _ bringing human-rights pressure on Beijing at the
same time as American corporations open the way for capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   The vision worked like magic, winning the votes of dozens of
undecided Democrats and Republicans who had feared that by ending
the annual vote on Chinese trade benefits, Congress would lose its
leverage over Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without (the additions), chances are PNTR will not pass,''
warned Commerce Secretary William Daley on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The provisions would do the following:
</P>
<P>
   -- Create a commission appointed by the White House and Congress
to monitor a broad range human rights and make recommendations each
year to Congress. The panel would be similar to the so-called
Helsinki Commission, which watched for human-rights abuses in
Eastern Europe during the latter years of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   -- Create a task force for monitoring prison labor in China, and
authorize U.S. Customs officials to visit alleged convict labor
sites.
</P>
<P>
   -- Help China rewrite its laws to include internationally
recognized labor rights; train Chinese government officials;
educate workers about their legal rights; and fund Chinese and
foreign nongovernmental organizations to work on these issues.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing Thursday, Chinese officials praised the U.S. approval
of PNTR but blasted the bill's human-rights provisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese government strongly opposes any use of human
rights and other issues as an excuse to interfere in China's
internal affairs or to damage China's interests,'' said Foreign
Trade Ministry spokesman Hu Chusheng. ``We urge the U.S. side to
correct its wrongdoing and guarantee the healthy and smooth
development of China-U.S. economic cooperation and trade.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, the Chinese have grudgingly tolerated U.S. criticism
of rights abuses, as long as it was mere talk. But never before
have they allowed direct American human-rights advocacy on Chinese
territory.
</P>
<P>
   American human-rights groups said Wednesday that the new
monitoring and advisory groups created by PNTR will have a tall
order.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all depends on whether these commissions intend to press on
the more core human rights,'' said Mike Jendrzejczyk,
(cq) &LR; Washington director for Asia at Human Rights Watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this program is used to help defend the rights of workers
to assert their own grievances, China will clearly draw a tough
line and not allow any of it. It's going to be a long, difficult
uphill struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   The prison labor initiative, for example, is not new, said Bama
Athreya, director for Asia programs at International Labor Rights
Fund, a Washington-based organization that carries out training
programs in several Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a 1992 U.S.-China agreement to allow visits by American
officials to alleged prison labor, China has routinely refused U.S.
requests. No such visits have been permitted since 1997, despite
constant U.S. pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation does nothing to further the existing
agreement, which is simply being ignored,'' Athreya said.
</P>
<P>
   Even major corporations have been blocked in attempts to coax
the government to loosen its iron hold.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, for example, Beijing has given the cold
shoulder to repeated attempts by three of the largest U.S.
manufacturers in China _ Levi Strauss, Phillips-Van Heusen and
Reebok _ to open a diplomatic back channel to Beijing. The three
firms have been under fire from U.S. activist groups and labor
unions for contracting huge amounts of clothes and footwear
production in China despite the communist government's ban on
independent unions and its jailing of union organizers.
</P>
<P>
   The three firms' CEOs pleaded with Chinese officials to ``work
together'' with them to improve labor rights _ but were given a
series of icy rebuffs this spring. The initiative is now ``dead,''
one company executive told The Chronicle this week.
</P>
<P>
   A broad initiative since 1998 by the International Labor
Organization, a U.N. agency, has resulted in a few high-level
meetings but little else.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, Beijing has quietly allowed some Western
nongovernmental organizations to start work on development
projects, often including advanced Western environmental
technology. And a new State Department aid program, started last
year, is giving $250,000 annually to help China relocate laid-off
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights and other political themes, however, are strictly
forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   ``PNTR is a political gamble, and could create more tension with
the Chinese,'' said Jendrzejczyk. ``It all depends on how much the
United States tries to carry out (the rights provisions) and how
much China feels it needs to cooperate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
