<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5240 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CHINA-TRADE-SFCHRON &LR;      05-25 1561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HOUSE OKS CHINA PACT BY WIDER THAN EXPECTED MARGIN  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration and its free-trade
allies won a huge economic and foreign policy victory Wednesday as
the House approved normalizing trade with China, 237 to 197.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-vote margin was more comfortable than either side had
anticipated, dealing a hard blow to unions, who had made defeat of
the China measure their Rubicon.
</P>
<P>
   A solid minority of 73 Democrats joined 164 Republicans in
voting to end a current annual review of China trade, clearing the
way for U.S. participation in a huge trade pact signed by the
administration last December that will open telecommunications and
other key markets in China in return for China's entry to the World
Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was a huge victory for Silicon Valley high-tech
companies and farmers in the San Joaquin Valley, who insisted that
defeat would have been equivalent to shutting U.S. firms out of
China's vast and fast-growing market, while inviting competitors in
Europe and Japan to fill the void.
</P>
<P>
   The hard-fought China measure marked the first big win in recent
years for the pro-trade bloc, which beat back a loose coalition of
organized labor, environmentalists, human rights activists and
opponents of globalization that helped torpedo WTO talks in Seattle
in December.
</P>
<P>
   For President Clinton, who threw everything in his political
arsenal into the fight, winning permanent normal trade relations
for China capped two terms of narrow and often controversial
free-trade victories, from passage of the North American Free Trade
Agreement with Mexico and Canada in 1993 to approval of a global
trade pact known as the Uruguay Round in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Since those victories, however, Clinton had stumbled on trade
issues, failing to win ``fast track'' negotiating authority for new
trade agreements in 1998. And after the violent protests in
Seattle, it appeared that unions and environmentalists were gaining
a decisive upper hand.
</P>
<P>
   In a Rose Garden statement after the victory, Clinton called the
vote ``a historic step toward continued prosperity in America,
reform in China and peace in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton acknowledged the vote was difficult for many members,
but said it gives China ``a chance _ not a guarantee, but a chance
_ to build a future in the Asia Pacific region for the next 50
years very different from the last 50.''
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizing as he has the past week that the United States
``fought three wars'' in Asia in the past half century, Clinton
said of China, ``We owe it to them, to their children, and to our
children and grandchildren to give the world a chance to build a
better and different future.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and other supporters said that commerce with the outside
world will allow new ideas to seep into Chinese society and empower
reformers and undermine hardliners. Its detractors argued that only
by retaining the annual threat of revoking trade privileges could
can  &LR; the U.S. force China to ease its internal repression.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, a San Francisco Democrat who battled
ferociously to defeat the China measure, conceded that the vote
``was disappointing, I'll tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said China trade ``challenged the conscience of this
Congress, and Congress responded with a cash register.'' She warned
that the ``burden is now on the members of Congress who voted for
this legislation and the president of the United States to produce
some results.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi predicted the U.S. trade deficit with China will continue
to soar and that conditions in China will deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people will be arrested,'' she said. `We have given them
carte blanche. We have demonstrated there is nothing they can do,
including threatening Taiwan, and we will not think of revoking
(trade privileges).''
</P>
<P>
   But Sacramento's Rep. Bob Matsui, who led Democratic supporters,
insisted that rejecting China's overtures could make ``China an
enemy of the U.S. for the next 40, 50 years, so we can have another
Cold War.''
</P>
<P>
   Matsui argued it would be folly to spurn China's market and that
workers should not fear China's opening its markets to U.S. goods.
``One of every five people on Earth is Chinese,'' he declared. ``We
are by far the most powerful economy in the world. We are second to
none. We shouldn't fear anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Emotions ran high as the late-afternoon vote neared, forging
bizarre alliances between the House's most ardent liberals and
conservatives on both sides of the China debate.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Norwood, R-Ga., brought Democrats to their feet with a
rousing denunciation of what he called a ``jobs, bombs and Bibles''
appeasement of China by free traders, who Norwood said argue year
after year that more Chinese commerce will increase U.S. jobs, make
Beijing's communist dictatorship less dangerous and improve
religious freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Accusing proponents of being more concerned with profits than
values, Norwood implored, ``Show that liberty still shines brighter
than gold.''
</P>
<P>
   Gravelly-voiced Harlem liberal Charles Rangel responded that the
United States dare not risk shutting its own industries out of
China's vast market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who can we afford to ignore over a billion people, knowing
that if we do, the Asians and Europeans will not?'' Rangel asked.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to denunciations of China's treatment of its
citizens, Rangel declared that America was ``not without blemishes.
... We have descendants of slaves that sit in this body. ... We
have people living here without education, without hope, without
running water.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangel brought cheers from Republicans, insisting that ``cutting
off communication did not work with that communist, Castro _ he
outlived close to 10 presidents. Don't let it happen in China.''
</P>
<P>
   East Bay Democrat Pete Stark, who managed the debate for
opponents, introduced each speaker with barbed comments on China
trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slave labor is not the American way to get T-shirts at
Wal-Mart,'' Stark said. ``The slogan, `We bring good things to
life,' won't help female murdered children in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley had been terrified of a defeat, especially after
House minority leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., announced the he
would oppose the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very nervous when Gephardt came out against it,'' said
Jeff Modisett, vice president of TechNet, a lobbying group of 200
high-tech executives. ``I think that caused us to redouble our
efforts and motivated a lot of CEOs to get actively engaged in a
way they haven't been before.''
</P>
<P>
   Unions fought just as hard, threatening to withhold political
support from wavering Democrats in the November elections, when
Democrats hope to recapture the House majority with union backing.
</P>
<P>
   The Chamber of Commerce countered with its own threats to deny
political aid to any member who crossed business on China.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has put Vice President Al Gore, the presumptive
Democratic presidential nominee, in an awkward position where he
has managed to infuriate both sides. Proponents accused Gore of
doing only the most perfunctory lobbying for the measure, while
unions blasted him for speaking out in its favor.
</P>
<P>
   United Auto Workers President Stephen Yokich issued a scathing
letter against Gore, urging union support for third-party candidate
Ralph Nader _ whose attacks on the auto industry have made him the
bane of Detroit _ because Nader ``will take a stand based on what
is right, not what big money dictates.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who has long supported the China
trade measure, issued a statement congratulating the House.
``Passage of this legislation will mean a stronger American
economy,'' Bush said, ``as well as more opportunity for liberty and
freedom in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Business had learned a lesson from its hard-line stands on
previous trade measures, this time embracing a key amendment by
Sander Levin, D-Mich., that would set up a process to monitor human
rights and trade violations.
</P>
<P>
   The Levin amendment, derided by opponents as a ``fig leaf,''
provided political cover for Democrats to support the overall bill.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Maibach, vice president of government relations for Santa
Clara chipmaker Intel, said votes began breaking supporters' way in
the last few days leading up to the vote, noting South Bay
Republican Tom Campbell's switch to the ``yes'' column on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Intel employees sent out 5,000 e-mails, letters and faxes to
members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech companies lobbying members ``made the case for the
role of technology in opening up China,'' added TechNet's Modisset.
``It's obviously very difficult to have a totalitarian regime when
you can freely receive and transmit over the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   But David Bonior, the Democrat whip who led the charge against
China trade, predicted that ``the grand coalition'' of labor,
environmentalists and others who protested trade and globalization
in Seattle has ``only just begun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue of globalization is not disappearing,'' Bonior
said. ``These issues of human rights and religious rights and labor
rights and the environment _ we will win this.''
</P>
<P>
   The China trade measure next goes to the Senate, where support
is stronger than in the House. The bill has already cleared the
Senate Finance Committee 18 to 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 0133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
