<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5241 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CHINA-TECH-SFCHRON &LR;      05-25 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TECH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AMERICA'S HIGH-TECH INDUSTRIES CHEER HOUSE VOTE ON TRADE BILL  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Calling it their most important political victory to date,
America's high-tech companies heartily celebrated Wednesday's House
of Representatives vote to give China trade access to the U.S.
market.
</P>
<P>
   The high-tech companies see the hotly contested vote as a key
step toward opening China's vast consumer market to billions of
dollars worth of American computers, software, semiconductors and
telecommunications equipment.
</P>
<P>
   According to the U.S. High-Tech Industry Coalition on China, an
ad-hoc group formed to lobby for permanent normal trade relations,
the revenues at stake are already huge, even though technology has
barely scratched the surface in China:
</P>
<P>
   -- The $8 billion annual semiconductor market in China is
expected become the world's third largest by 2001 and the second
largest by 2010. Annual sales of related equipment and materials
should hit $4 billion by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   -- Exports of U.S. computer and office equipment increased 500
percent in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   -- Internet users are expected to jump from 9 million people
last year to 20 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   -- With 40 million cellular phone subscribers, China is close to
becoming the world's second-largest cellular market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are one step closer to securing (permanent normal trade
relations) that promise to yield a significant boost to every
sector of the high-tech industry,'' said Jim Whittaker, the
coalition's chairman and director of International Public Policy
for Hewlett-Packard Co. of Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   ``The high-tech industry has been a driving force behind the
booming U.S. economy ... our ability to sustain that growth is
dependent upon fair and open access to world markets, including
China,'' Whittaker said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
   The House vote was yet another demonstration of the growing
political muscle U.S. technology companies have in Washington. And
trade with China has generated far broader support than previous
hot button high-tech topics such as raising limits on foreign
worker visas or limiting liabilities for Year 2000 computer
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have big smiles on our faces,'' said Tim Bennett, senior
vice president for international affairs for the American
Electronics Association, which was part of a broad coalition of
high-tech companies that has been applying a full-court press on
Capitol Hill since January.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a statement for our sector that U.S. industries will be
a player in the Chinese market,'' Bennett said. ``It's also a
broader political statement about the leadership role the U.S. will
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel spokesman Chuck Mulloy said about 60 percent of the
company's sales come from outside the U.S. But in China, Intel has
to pay tariffs, must sell through a Chinese trading company and has
difficulty investing in Chinese companies.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by the Senate, the trade bill ``gives us access to
the Chinese market on the same terms that the Chinese have had
access to our market,'' Mulloy said. ``We belive that by removing
the barriers, we are stimulating market growth in China. That bodes
well for us and for the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   China represents about 10 percent of Motorola Inc.'s annual
global sales of $30 billion, said Norm Sandler, the Schaumburg,
Ill., company's director of global strategic issues.
</P>
<P>
   Future revenues are hard to predict, but the lure of burgeoning
markets for cell phone, pager and other telecommunication equipment
will draw competition from companies all over the world, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to be in there competing on a level playing field,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But firms and farmers who lobbied for normal trade with China
should not be ``under the illusion that now they can pop the
champagne corks and watch the money roll in,'' warned Richard
Margolis, senior economist with Merrill Lynch in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   ``American companies have to be realistic,'' cautioned Dong Tao,
senior Asia economist at Credit Suisse First Boston. ``Genuine
market access in China will take years _ probably decades.''
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle Staff Writer Verne Kopytoff and Chronicle news
services contributed to this story.)
</P>
</TEXT>
