<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5246 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-PHILLIES-H     05-25 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-PHILLIES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
The people at Ripley's Believe It Or Not are bound to be clearing
out space for an exhibit. If not, ABC surely must be in the
planning stages for a return of the logic-defying series That's
Incredible.
<TEXT>
<P>
   How else can you explain what continues to happen to the Astros,
who mystified even themselves in Wednesday's 9-7 loss to the
Philadelphia Phillies at Enron Field?
</P>
<P>
   Billy Wagner, who blew only three saves in 42 chances last
season, botched his fourth opportunity in a row and his fifth in
nine tries this season. The Astros led by seven runs after five
innings, marking the second seven-run lead they have surrendered in
a span of four days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazing,'' said Astros first baseman Jeff Bagwell, struggling
to find the right words. ``It's unbelievable. It's not that easy to
lose games the way we're losing them. It's gut-wrenching. But Billy
is my man. I'd want him right back out there tomorrow if we had a
lead.''
</P>
<P>
   After snapping a seven-game losing streak Tuesday, the Astros
reverted to their old ways Wednesday night before a not-so-pleasant
crowd of 32,665. The bullpen has a 6.07 ERA over the last nine
games, and Wagner _ virtually a sure thing throughout his career _
has been one of the biggest culprits.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the team plays hard and scores seven runs, we deserve to
win,'' Wagner said. ``It's not easy to walk into the clubhouse and
look at your teammates when you're the guy who's giving it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame that we're playing good baseball and I (stink)
right now. All I can do is keep going out there and trying to
battle through it.''
</P>
<P>
   After a one-day hiatus, the Astros can once again claim the
worst record (16-29) in the National League. The Phillies (16-28)
have the second-worst mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a part of good teams, and this is a good
team, too,'' Astros outfielder Moises Alou said. ``We're just not
playing very well right now. This is new for me, and it's new for a
lot of guys. Sometimes you go through periods like this, but we
know we're better than this.''
</P>
<P>
   Games like Wednesday's make you wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Facing the bottom of the Phillies' lineup and needing three outs
to notch his first save since May 4, Wagner allowed four
ninth-inning runs on five hits, including a two-run homer by former
Astro Bob Abreu, who delivered what would be the decisive blow. It
was Abreu's second homer of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've run out of ideas,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said.
``When you bring in a guy who throws 97, 98 mph, you don't think
they'll score four runs. You have to give the Phillies credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anyone in the league would like to have Wagner on the
mound in that situation. He's just in a slump right now. The only
alternative we have is to keep bringing him in there.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when an assignment against Phillies ace Curt
Schilling was another way of saying ``better luck next time.'' But
he was easy pickings Wednesday, as the Astros ripped the three-time
All-Star for seven runs on eight hits in 4 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling, who began the season on the disabled list while
recovering from shoulder surgery, has an 8.68 ERA over his past
three starts, proving few pitchers are safe from the offensive
explosion throughout the majors this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies barely touched Astros starter Octavio Dotel over
the first five innings. He retired the first seven batters he faced
and didn't allow a hit until Kevin Jordan led off the fifth with a
single to left. Dotel, who allowed four runs on seven hits in 6
innings, has a 3.26 ERA over his past three starts.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously paying no attention to reputation and credentials, the
Astros jumped on Schilling from the opening bell, stringing
together four hits after he retired Craig Biggio to lead off the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the next six batters reached, including Richard Hidalgo,
who blasted a two-run homer over the fence in left-center field.
Bagwell, Ken Caminiti and Daryle Ward each drove in a run in the
inning. Hidalgo ranks among the league leaders in home runs (14)
and RBIs (39).
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell and Ward, two of Hidalgo's prime competitors for the
club homer lead, piled onto Schilling's misery with a pair of solo
homers in the fifth. Bagwell has 11 homers, and Ward has 10 in just
93 at-bats, the best ratio on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Having fallen behind 7-0, the Phillies finally got something
going in the sixth inning. Doug Glanville reached on a leadoff
infield single and scored on the first hit of Pat Burrell's
big-league career, a single to left. Jordan's sacrifice fly pulled
Philadelphia within five.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker ended Dotel's night in the seventh after the
righthander's 117th pitch sailed over the Crawford Boxes for a
two-run homer courtesy of Glanville. Abreu's first home run of the
night, a solo shot off Astros reliever Doug Henry, trimmed the
Astros' lead to two. Henry has allowed seven home runs, tops in the
Astros' bullpen, in 20 appearances this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I look back on and think I might have done
differently is have someone start the seventh inning instead of
Dotel,'' Dierker said. ``He had thrown a lot of pitches, and he
came to the end energy-wise.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
