<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 02:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5247 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-TWINS-LADN     05-25 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-TWINS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLENTY OF HEROES IN ANGELS VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The Angels got 18 hits, including five from Mo
Vaughn and a game-winning home run from Troy Glaus in their 6-5,
10-inning victory over the Minnesota Twins Wednesday night before
8,633 at the Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   But the play that ultimately won it for the Angels came from the
right arm of Edgard Clemente.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels held a 5-3 lead with two out in the bottom of the
ninth inning, but the Twins had the bases loaded with Jay Canizaro
at bat. Canizaro hit a line drive to right field over the head of
Clemente, who played it off the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Two runs scored and it appeared Corey Koskie, running from first
base, also would score to win the game for the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   Clemente, the nephew of Hall of Famer Roberto Clemente, threw
the ball from deep right field on two hops to catcher Bengie
Molina, who tagged out Koskie and send the game into extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus' leadoff homer in the 10th off Bob Wells gave the Angels a
6-5 lead, and Al Levine pitched the bottom of the inning for his
first career save, but it was Clemente's throw that had the Angels
talking in the clubhouse after the game.
</P>
<P>
   When Angels manager Mike Scioscia was asked who he thought of
when the throw was made, he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Take your pick. The other (Roberto) Clemente or (Raul)
Mondesi. I can't believe from where he threw that ball and how
accurate it was and how much he threw him out by. I was looking for
the relay man, but there was no need for one. That was on a plumb
line.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn was the cutoff man on the play, but there was no way a
relay would get there in time to nail the runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't cut his throws anyway,'' Vaughn said. ``Did you see
that throw he made from center field last week? When it went by me
it was picking up velocity. He has that type of arm.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemente, 24, said once he knew he couldn't catch the ball, he
had to throw it home himself without the help of a cutoff man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I just had to throw it to home plate,'' he said. ``I
threw it with everything I've got. That was all that was on my
mind. I didn't see the cutoff anyway. I didn't have time to see
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemente started in right field to give Tim Salmon a day in the
designated hitter spot. He never saw his famous uncle play, but
he's been told by others his arm reminds them of Roberto's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people who had a father or family who played, if they
used to hit good or throw good, then they do it too,'' Clemente
said. ``It's good to have that.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Vaughn's five hits, the Angels got four hits from Molina
and three each from Darin Erstad and Glaus. Glaus saved his best
for last, leading off the 10th with his 15th homer of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a natural path through the ball that will result in a
lot of home runs,'' Scioscia said. ``He gets the ball in the air
and drives the ball. This guy's been something.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the game it seemed the Angels would have to do better
than their six runs. Starter Jarrod Washburn gave up three runs in
the first inning before recording an out. But after a visit to the
mound from Scioscia, Washburn calmed down and went seven innings
without giving up another run.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn was a little too excited about his start because his
parents and other family and friends made the trip from Wisconsin
to see him pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what (Scioscia) told me, I was too excited,'' Washburn
said. ``I was getting the ball up but the problem was more mental.
I just got myself under control and stopped the bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival (2-2) blew a chance to increase his league-leading save
total to 14, but got the win instead. The Twins' two-run ninth
wasn't all his fault, though, as shortstop Benji Gil's throwing
error allowed Midre Cummings to reach base leading off the inning.
Percival struck out two, but also walked two to load the bases for
Canizaro.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is a mentally tough team,'' Vaughn said. ``The guys
come to battle, and it starts with the manager. Funny things happen
in this game, but we have the type of players to get through it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
