r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTEBOOK-L     05-25 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZERS WON'T ENGAGE IN WORDPLAY WITH JACKSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ As usual, coach Phil Jackson has set the
agenda for the war of words in the Lakers' playoff series against
the Portland Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, he derisively referred to the Blazers as ``jackals''
for laughing on the bench during their Game 2 rout of the Lakers at
Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for the Blazers to take the bait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any team that gets a win on the road is going to be happy
about it,'' Portland coach Mike Dunleavy said. ``We can't all sit
stoically like he does and not react to things. Our guys were
showing a positive emotion. I don't think it was an
over-celebration on our part in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   Rasheed Wallace brushed off the comments as ``tricks and
mudslinging'' and added: ``We don't worry about that, man, because
it's all going to be answered out there on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Blazers forward Scottie Pippen, a Jackson disciple, was wise to
his old coach's methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil's not on the court. He's only a piece of the game,'' he
said. ``The players have to go out there and do our job and not
focus on all the distractions.''
</P>
<P>
   That also includes Jackson's assertion that Pippen is playing
illegal zone defense as he roams the floor, helping to guard
Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to play the way we feel we can defend this team,''
Pippen said. ``We don't think by any means we're illegal, and we're
not going to focus on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Dunleavy: ``If they want to make it retroactive, I'd be
willing to call all our illegal defenses against us and call all of
Shaq's against him and let's shoot it off after the game. That's
fine by me.''
</P>
<P>
   FEELING ROSEY: The Lakers have already survived the NBA's
loudest court Sacramento's Arco Arena, where they went 0-2 in the
playoffs and Jackson said he's not concerned with the hostile
environs of Portland's Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never felt the Portland fans are hostile,'' he said.
``I've always felt they're loud, they're vociferous, they're
boisterous, good fans. But I never felt that they've been hostile.
Many times with the Bulls when we played them in '92 (in the
Finals), they were a very gracious crowd and knew that we were a
better team than they were, and at the end of it felt relatively
comfortable congratulating us as we went on home.''
</P>
<P>
   REQUIRED READING: Usually, it's Jackson who hands out books to
players. But Wednesday, it was veteran John Salley who felt the
Lakers needed some inspirational words. So he brought in his copy
of Sun Tzu's ``The Art of War.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Three guys said they read it. I don't know how and when,''
Salley said, ``because it tells you when you're superior, you're
supposed to attack. And if we're going to believe and think we're
superior, we attack. And today in practice, some guys were kind of
pacing themselves. And we don't have time to pace.''
</P>
<P>
   OUCH REPORT: Glen Rice, bothered by tendinitis in his right
knee, practiced Wednesday, and Jackson said he ``seemed to be OK.
Better today. Not OK, but better today, and he seems to be
improving.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 0230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
