<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 02:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5249 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     05-25 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO WAYS TO LOOK AT DODGERS SUSPENSIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hang onto your hat. And keep your shirt on. The
celebration can wait until October.
</P>
<P>
   But did you hear what happened Wednesday?
</P>
<P>
   Baseball handed the Dodgers the pennant.
</P>
<P>
   On paper _ the fax listing 16 players and three coaches
suspended and fined for their roles in the Dodgers' brawl with
Chicago fans last week _ it looks as if Frank Robinson, the
commissioner's vice president for on-field operations (in plainer
terms: judge, jury and executioner), just choked the life out of a
ballclub.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a way of handicapping the Dodgers, you might say,''
manager Davey Johnson said a couple of hours after the punishments
were handed down by Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Or ... you might say exactly the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   You might say this is the development that will make _ not break
_ a championship team.
</P>
<P>
   You might even say this is the greatest thing to happen on
account of a Dodgers cap since a prankster put eye black in Kirk
Gibson's, and Gibson declared that would be the last of the
tomfoolery in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Why should 60 games worth of player suspensions be a good thing
for the Dodgers? Here's why.
</P>
<P>
   Teams wait all spring and summer _ and fall, if they get that
far _ for rallying points like the one that just came to them
through the fax machine.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a long, hard, winning road trip brings a team
together. Sometimes it takes a brawl to create that
us-against-the-world feeling.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have had two such road trips already in 2000. In the
midst of the second trip, they had the brawl, which began when a
fan at Wrigley Field hit Chad Kreuter in the head and snatched the
catcher's cap as he sat in the right-field bullpen during the ninth
inning of a May 16 game against the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Not coincidentally, the Dodgers won six games in a row after
that incident in the Friendly Confines.
</P>
<P>
   Now they have the unusually harsh suspensions to make them feel
picked upon.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, petty injustices lead to revolutions. This one can
lead to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   If this doesn't kill the Dodgers, it will make them stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told players to channel all their frustrations out on that
(Cincinnati Reds) pitcher,'' Dodgers chairman Bob Daly said before
Wednesday night's game at Dodger Stadium. ``I think they feel more
motivation to stay together.''
</P>
<P>
   Because it must feel as if the commissioner's office is trying
to bust them apart.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have a right to be fighting mad. They knew a few of
them would be punished for going over the line that separates
players and fans. It didn't matter that they were provoked. A
front-page photograph of a player with his fingers around a fan's
throat is not something baseball wishes to encourage.
</P>
<P>
   But suspensions for 19 Dodgers? Even the ones who appeared to
reach into the stands to break up, not inflame, the violence? When,
had they backed off, players would have been ridiculed for failing
to support a teammate? A suspension for the bullpen catcher, for
God's sake?
</P>
<P>
   Baseball seems to be going out of its way to send a message: The
paying customer comes first (except in matters of strikes,
lockouts, ticket prices, World Series starting times ...).
</P>
<P>
   It's an overreaction.
</P>
<P>
   Which is different from saying it's the end of the Dodgers'
pennant hopes, as the house men on talk radio were predicting
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about the three coaches, suspended eight days each.
That's an inconvenience, not a calamity. Then, forget about
starting pitchers Darren Dreifort, Eric Gagne and Chan Ho Park,
suspended three days each. Rearrange the rotation and they needn't
miss a turn.
</P>
<P>
   Now you're talking about 51 games worth of suspensions. Think
about this: If Gary Sheffield's ankle injury had been serious
enough to sideline him for 51 games, would we be saying the season
is over? No.
</P>
<P>
   The Major League Players' Association is challenging the
suspensions, and the Dodgers have requested an appeal. Maybe
they'll be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   If not, look at the bright side.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, as ever a club in search of a personality, have
just acquired one by decree of Major League Baseball. They are the
big, bad Dodgers. A motorcycle gang in doubleknits. Tough guys,
scrappers, public enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly they have the look and sound of winners. Instead of
cursing Frank Robinson, they should doff their caps and say,
``Thanks.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kevin Modesti's column appears in the Daily News three days a week.
He can be reached at (818) 713-3616. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 0251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 02:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5250 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     05-25 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JERMAINE O'NEAL WAITS FOR HIS SHOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The youngest prodigy to play in the NBA feels old
enough to be John Salley.
</P>
<P>
   Jermaine O'Neal, Portland's reserve forward/center, was 43 days
removed from his 18th birthday when he appeared in his first
regular-season game with the Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, O'Neal and Kobe Bryant were the only two high school
players to make the quantum leap to the NBA. Bryant's trajectory
has been plotted and tracked and gasped at, while O'Neal's has been
harder to trace, his luminous tale obscured by all the other
heavenly bodies in Portland's frontcourt.
</P>
<P>
   Once, 51 days (Bryant, an August baby, is the older of the two
by almost two months) and four places in the 1996 draft were
virtually all that separated the precocious pair. But before the
paths crossed again in the ongoing Western Conference Finals, their
careers would go off in different directions.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after the 1996 draft, Bryant was traded from Charlotte
to the Lakers and in Hollywood's glare his wondrous talent rose
like yeast dough in a greased bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, a month older than O'Neal when he made his NBA debut,
became (three months later) the youngest player in league history
to start a regular-season game.
</P>
<P>
   From there, it was a straight shot into the public's
consciousness for Bryant, the youngest player to earn second team
All-Rookie honors, the youngest player to start an All-Star game
and the youngest player to be molded into Michael Jordan's image.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, O'Neal sat on the Trail Blazers' bench growing older
behind Rasheed Wallace and Brian Grant and Arvydas Sabonis, too. In
four seasons, he has started fewer than 20 games while appearing in
over 200.
</P>
<P>
   What O'Neal has learned by watching so much time go by he could
turn into a doctoral dissertation on the space-time continuum.
</P>
<P>
   In his world, it is a state where time doesn't fly, it crawls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm 35,'' O'Neal, a world-weary 21, said the other
day.
</P>
<P>
   It was 75 minutes until the opening tipoff of Game 2 of the
best-of-seven series between the Lakers and Portland and O'Neal was
slouched in front of the locker next to Scottie Pippen's, mentally
preparing for a game in which he figured to have, at best, a cameo
role.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal is good enough to have dropped 14 points and eight
rebounds on Utah in a Portland win in January. His promise remains
sufficiently seductive that the Trail Blazers signed him to a
four-year, $24 million deal last summer.
</P>
<P>
   He believes in his XXL heart that he has the game to go up just
about anybody except for maybe the Lakers' Shaquille O'Neal (no
relation), who gives everybody fits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of getting edgy about playing more,'' said O'Neal,
who has logged 12 minutes and scored eight points (on 2-for-6
shooting) in two playoff games against the Lakers. ``I got my four
years in, just like if I had gone to college.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows I have a lot of talent. But we do have really
good forwards here that I'm playing behind. I'm learning a lot from
them. They keep telling me I just have to keep working hard and be
ready when my time comes.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes O'Neal feels like those baby shrubs sheathed in wiring
so they'll grow into specific shapes. The Trail Blazers are trying
to mold O'Neal into a defensively responsible player and O'Neal's
untamed side just wants to start and put up shots and be free, like
he was at Eau Claire High in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   He sees what his buddy, Bryant, is accomplishing with the Lakers
and the urge to spread his own wings becomes almost as hard to
suppress as a reflex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously Kobe's role on his team is a lot bigger than my
role,'' O'Neal said, a little wistfully.
</P>
<P>
   In his many quiet moments, a thought occasionally creeps into
O'Neal's head. He wonders if maybe things would have been a little
different if he has attended one year of college before striking
out on his own for the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if I had one year of college, I'd have done better
with the mental part,'' he said. ``You don't really notice how
tough it is on you mentally (playing in the NBA) until you see
everything. Just being away from home and everything was hard, at
first. But I never doubted myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The city of Portland has adopted O'Neal and so, apparently, have
Bryant's parents. When the Trail Blazers played in L.A. during the
regular season, Bryant's family had O'Neal over for dinner. It was
a chance for the two prodigies to compare notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jermaine hasn't had the opportunity to kind of grow in the
battlefield like I have,'' Bryant said. ``The timing for him is a
little different. But he'll get there. He just has to remain
persistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a quality ballplayer. I think it's great he's playing
with guys like Scottie, Rasheed Wallace, Brian Grant. He has a
chance to learn some good things.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant is a big believer in the big picture so that's how he
tries to frame things for O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only way you're going to stay sane,'' Bryant said.
``Trust me. I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant laughed, ruefully, and at that moment he sound 35, not
21.
</P>
<P>
   The human impulse is to freeze the young in a single snapshot
that never gets yellowed or faded. That's why, for a good many
people, the most jarring thing about Bryant's recent engagement was
that the Lakers' favorite kid brother was all of a sudden grown up
enough to be one of the country's most eligible bachelors.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, too, is maturing in ways we maybe can't see on the court
or in the statistics. But soon enough we'll know. His development
will become big news. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Karen Crouse's column appears in the Daily News four days a week.
She can be reached at (818) 713-3619. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
