<HEADLINE>
DODGERS CAP ROUGH DAY WITH LOSS TO REDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The order came from Dodgers general managing
partner and CEO Bob Daly, who urged his players in a pregame
meeting to take out their frustrations out on their opponents, the
Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, there was still plenty of frustration to go
around.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers scored three runs in the first inning, then
collapsed in a 10-3 loss Wednesday night to the Reds in front of
31,740 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The day had already been ruined when the commissioner's office
announced that 16 Dodger players and three coaches were fined and
suspended for their actions in last week's brawl at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   Matters only got worse when the Reds scored eight runs over the
final three innings to bust open what once looked to be a pitchers'
duel. Dante Bichette went 5 for 6 with four RBI and Michael Tucker
scored four times.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds bombed the Dodgers bullpen, which wasn't all that much
of a surprise considering all the Dodgers touched turned to rust.
</P>
<P>
   Chan Ho Park pitched four strong innings then fell apart and
former Dodger Juan Castro hit a crucial two-run double after the
Dodgers intentionally walked Hal Morris to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   And, for the third consecutive game, the Dodgers scored early
and slumbered late.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going OK for a while, and then things kind of went
cold for us,'' manager Davey Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers went up early again, just as they did in Monday's
14-inning 4-3 victory and Tuesday's 3-1 loss. With one out, Mark
Grudzielanek singled and Shawn Green walked.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros flew out to left, and the Reds seemed to be out of
the inning when Todd Hollandsworth grounded a ball to the right
side of the infield. Pokey Reese got in position, but the ball
bounced past his glove and Grudzielanek scored from second.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Beltre followed with a two-run double to give the Dodgers
a 3-0 lead, but there would be little good cheer to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Park (4-4) struggled slightly with his control early, but
allowed just one hit through four innings. He retired the first two
runs in the fifth, then struggled. Tucker singled, Ken Griffey Jr.
walked, and both scored when Bichette doubled into the left-field
corner.
</P>
<P>
   Park walked the first two batters in the sixth and got out of a
jam with a double play, but was pulled after Reese led off the
seventh with a home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Chan Ho was great through four innings, but in the
fifth he got a little defensive and the sixth was the same way,''
Johnson said. ``He said he felt fine going back out in the sixth,
but he was a little tentative.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tough one to let get away.''
</P>
<P>
   The game did get away from the Dodgers after Park's departure.
Matt Herges relieved but didn't fare much better. He walked the
first batter he faced, hit the second and gave up three more runs
in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The big hit came courtesy of Castro, a former little-used
infielder with the Dodgers. With the bases loaded and two outs, he
lined a double to right-center field and scored Griffey Jr. and
Bichette to put the Reds up 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Trever Miller made his Dodger debut to start the eighth inning
but could get just one out. The Reds hit Miller hard and added two
more runs in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   That was more than enough on a night when the Dodgers' offense
fell silent after the first inning. Starter Steve Parris pitched
five solid innings and retired 12 of the 14 batters he faced after
the first inning. Scott Sullivan (1-2) allowed two hits in three
innings of relief. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
