r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-KOBE-LADN     05-25 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-KOBE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOBE LEARNING HIS LESSONS WELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ There are no mistakes in Kobe Bryant's
world, only lessons. Each misstep just leads to a new mission.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-point airballs he shot as a rookie against Utah in the
Western Conference finals? Shrugged off.
</P>
<P>
   The missed free throws that could have won a crucial Game 2 of
the semifinals at San Antonio in 1999? Bryant smiled as he walked
off the court.
</P>
<P>
   Others pout. Bryant accepts the failure, learns and atones.
</P>
<P>
   And so months after that playoff loss at Utah, he hit the
winning free throws in another game at Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   And a few weeks ago, one year after missing those foul shots in
San Antonio, Bryant made the game-winning jumper in Game 2 of the
semis against Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't a single failure to point to in the current Western
Conference finals, no demons to exorcise. But there are certainly
lessons to be learned as Bryant and the Lakers head to Portland,
tied 1-1 with the Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant has been held to 13 and 12 points, respectively, in Games
1 and 2 _ his lowest-scoring consecutive games of the season, and
well below the 24.4 points he averaged in the first two rounds of
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers, determined to shut down both Bryant and Shaquille
O'Neal, are sending waves of defenders at both. And it's working.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's just another lesson for the 21-year-old All-Star. And a
difficult one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's trying to adjust, but it's hard,'' said teammate
Derek Fisher. ``I think this is the first time where a team has
consistently, when he touches the ball, (sent a double-team). And
now he's Shaquille _ every time he touches the ball, here comes
Scottie (Pippen). Or here comes Rasheed (Wallace). Or here comes
someone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think for Kobe, it's definitely a big-time adjustment.
Because he's used to having the ability to be able to create off
the dribble and do different things. And they've kind of taken that
away. So it's a process for him, as well as our team, in terms of
getting better and learning more how to be great, regardless of
what the situation is.''
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Bryant hasn't reverted to bad old habits.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't forcing plays _ he's committed just three turnovers in
two games. And he isn't forcing shots _ to the contrary, he's taken
nine attempts in each game after averaging 19.7 in the first two
rounds of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Bryant's own newfound patience is working
against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys are actually asking me to shoot the ball?'' Bryant
said with a laugh, after a reporter suggested he should take more
than nine shots per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just haven't really been as aggressive, as far as going to
the hoop. I've kind of been settling, instead of keeping guys on
the perimeter and when they double, just kicking it out for open
shots instead of trying to break them down. ... I just have to go
through about two or three guys.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bryant shied away from the notion that this was a personal
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a huge challenge from a lot of areas _ losing
home-court advantage, the momentum of the series shifting. Scottie.
Bonzi (Wells). Steve Smith. And their whole team defense collapsing
on guys,'' he said. ``I think it's a challenge, because you kind of
have to beat five guys. You don't have to beat one.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost literally, in Bryant's case.
</P>
<P>
   He's been defended by almost every player on the Blazers'
roster. And at the other end of the floor, he's had to guard an
endless string of them, adjusting from the quickness of tiny Damon
Stoudamire to the big hops of Wells to the physical post play and
shooting range of Smith.
</P>
<P>
   All of it was made more difficult by Bryant's early foul trouble
in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just tough from a fouls standpoint, because Shaq was
obviously in foul trouble. I didn't want to pick up my fourth and
get in foul trouble as well, and ... lose all of our offensive
firepower,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, that happened in Game 2 anyway. Bryant, prevented
from driving, tried the jumper and went 2 for 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think he's not shooting well,'' coach Phil Jackson
said. ``I just think that's a slump that he's in right now,
shooting-wise, that dates back maybe a couple weeks. But once he
gets back and shoots the ball well, he'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the extra bodies blanketing Bryant, Jackson said: ``It's
not a problem. He just has to go ahead, play his game and take his
shots where he gets them.''
</P>
<P>
   So the lesson unfolds, and the reassuring part for the Lakers
is, Bryant is a quick learner.
</P>
<P>
   As veteran teammate John Salley said, ``He'll get it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
