<HEADLINE>
SANTANGELO ISN'T COMPLAINING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ F.P. Santangelo might be stuck in a center-field
platoon with Todd Hollandsworth for the next few weeks, but the
sixth-year veteran isn't about to bemoan his status with the
Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to be playing feels good and to get the opportunity to
contribute,'' Santangelo said. ``Any time you know what your role
is, no matter what it is, it makes things easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo started in center and hit leadoff Wednesday night
against Cincinnati. Santangelo would normally sit in favor of
Hollandsworth against a right-handed pitcher such as Steve Parris,
but Gary Sheffield's sprained ankle forced both players into
action.
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo, signed as a free agent in January, entered the game
hitting just .111 but said he feels more comfortable with regular
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Regular center fielder Devon White has been sidelined since May
5 with a partial tear of his rotator cuff, allowing Santangelo more
time at the plate. White will not be back for at least a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're not playing all the time, it's harder to feel
comfortable out there,'' Santangelo said. ``I'm just trying to see
a lot of pitches, so that when (White) comes back or when
Hollandsworth is playing, I can still go strong.''
</P>
<P>
   DODGER SHUFFLE: On an already chaotic day, Johnson shuffled his
starting lineup slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo started in left field, in place of Geronimo Berroa,
who went 0 for 4 Tuesday night. Chad Kreuter started in favor of
Todd Hundley and batted seventh, and Hollandsworth moved from his
traditional leadoff spot in the batter order to No.5.
</P>
<P>
   DAY OF REST: The Dodgers have an off day today and open a
three-game series with the Philadelphia Phillies at 7:10 p.m.
Friday. Kevin Brown (3-1, 2.41 ERA) will face the Phillies' Paul
Byrd (1-3, 7.75 ERA) in the series opener. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
