<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN WARMING UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Mo Vaughn is on a roll, but he likes to think of
it as simply doing what he is supposed to do.
</P>
<P>
   After playing all of last season on a badly sprained left ankle
and starting this season slowly, Vaughn now is hitting the way the
Angels hoped he would when he signed a six-year, $80 million
contract before the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   He went 5 for 5 Wednesday and now has hit in 11 consecutive
games and 13 of his past 14. During those 14 games, Vaughn is
hitting .448 (26 for 58) with nine homers and 21 RBI. He's hitting
.335 on the season, and with 16 homers and 45 RBI _ on pace to set
Angels records in homers (56) and RBI (158).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get too excited about different stats because I've
done that before,'' Vaughn said. ``My big thing is waking up every
day strong and healthy and able to play the way I want to play.
That's what I'm most excited about.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn also said it helps to have a good approach at the plate _
``Hopefully I'll keep swinging at strikes'' _ and bat with runners
on base.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much who's hitting behind you, but who's in front
of you,'' he said. ``Adam (Kennedy) and Darin (Erstad) are getting
on base. I can do a lot more damage. They can't pitch around me
with guys on base. That's the biggest thing.''
</P>
<P>
   FILL-IN: Ex-USC standout Seth Etherton will make his
major-league debut Friday for the Angels against the Royals in
Kansas City. The Angels need a starting pitcher for the spot
because of numerous injuries and illness to the pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Etherton, 2-2 with a 4.43 ERA in seven starts for Triple-A
Edmonton this season, was selected ahead of a number of other
candidates, including Brett Hinchliffe and Mike Fyhrie, who are
currently pitching for the Angels out of the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Mike Scioscia and pitching coach Bud Black had to
determine whether it was too soon to put Etherton, 23, on a
big-league mound considering this is only his second full season in
professional baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these guys are poised beyond their years,'' Scioscia
said. ``Their youth isn't something that we're going to be
tentative about. Some guys get opportunities out of necessity, but
if we don't think they're ready, we don't want to bring them up in
a situation they're not ready for.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTHING'S CHANGED: It was 8 months ago here at the Metrodome
when interim manager Joe Maddon kept Vaughn, Jim Edmonds, Tim
Salmon and several other starters on the bench in the ninth inning
of Twins pitcher Eric Milton's no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   But Maddon, back in his seat as the club's bench coach, said he
would do it again, allowing Trent Durrington, Andy Sheets and Jeff
DaVanon to hit in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the game means a lot to Eric Milton and nothing to
everybody else,'' Maddon said. ``I pre-plan when I do things and I
liked the way things were going. I wanted to give the young guys an
opportunity to play under the duress of trying to break up a
no-hitter. If DaVanon breaks it up, it's going to impact him more
in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   DANGER ZONES: The dugouts were danger zones at the Metrodome
Wednesday. Twins pitcher Joe Mays got hit on the wrist by a foul
ball and had to go to the hospital. Angels pitching coach Bud Black
got hit on the neck but was OK. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
