<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 03:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5255 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-MERCKER-LA     05-25 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-MERCKER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCKER HAPPY TO BE AROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ One day after being released from the hospital,
Angels pitcher Kent Mercker was in good spirits Wednesday as he
talked about the cerebral hemorrhage he suffered May 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``I defied death,'' Mercker said during a conference call with
reporters. ``It's scary to say, but that's what happened. I'm
living to tell about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news is what happened to Mercker on the Edison Field
mound that night against the Texas Rangers has been determined to
be an isolated incident. There was no aneurysm and there is no
malformation of blood vessels in the brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had every test _ which actually did prove I have a brain, by
the way _ and it showed no structural problems and nothing that
would indicate it would happen again. (Doctors) described it as the
odds of being struck by lightning.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a blood vessel that burst in the brain and it
disintegrated. It's gone. So it's not like there's a weakened
vessel that can rupture again.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker said doctors told him there are no long-term effects of
the hemorrhage, and the only short-term effects are reactions to
the medication he is taking. He had been on a steroid that reduces
swelling in the brain and is taking a medication that prevents
spasms from occurring.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be on the anti-spasm medication for another eight days and
has been told to take it easy. The medication has made him
extremely weak and fatigued, but once he's off it, he hopes to
begin to slowly regain his strength and stamina.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he says he has ``no idea'' when or if he'll be able to
pitch again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is very important to me and I believe I will play
baseball again,'' he said. ``But if I'm not allowed to have it
anymore, it's not the end of the world. I have a wife and two
daughters. I hope to live 60 more years.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker will see doctors today at USC Medical Center, then fly
home with his wife Julie to Dublin, Ohio, tonight. If he's feeling
up to it, Mercker plans to drive to Cleveland to visit his Angels
teammates Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can call me unlucky to have (the hemorrhage), but I'm very
fortunate,'' Mercker said. ``The percentage of people who have
this, only a minute percentage don't have an aneurysm or long-term
effects or surgery. It's amazing. ... It's not like we're talking
about a torn ligament in your elbow. I'm bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   The bleeding in his brain stopped that night, but Mercker knows
he was in danger of losing his life.
</P>
<P>
   After Mercker threw a pitch to strike out Ruben Mateo in the
second inning, ``It felt like my head filled up,'' he said. ``Like
when you're taking off in an airplane. Both my ears popped and I
felt pressure. I could hear, but it was muffled.''
</P>
<P>
   Four pitches later, with Royce Clayton at the plate, Mercker
fell to his knees in pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pain in the back of my neck to my forehead,'' Mercker
said. ``That's when I realized it wasn't normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Once at the hospital, Mercker was told by Angels physician Dr.
Lewis Yocum that his condition was serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I'm going to cut to the chase, you've got a
problem,''' Mercker said. ``My whole life, I've never had a medical
problem. To hear I have internal bleeding, especially in my brain,
was tough to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Mercker admits, the experience of the past two weeks has
been beneficial in that it has helped him put his life in
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``You prioritize a little bit,'' he said. ``I remember in spring
training talking about whether I was going to be in the rotation or
the bullpen. Who cares? Now I look back and I can't even imagine
arguing about being in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a good career. I've won a World Series, I saw Mark
McGwire hit 70 home runs, I threw a no-hitter. But the one thing
I'll take away from the game is the friends that I've met over the
years. ... Every (Angels) player came to see me in the hospital.
(Troy) Percival brought me lunch every day, him and Darin Erstad.
That's what makes this game great.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
