<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-SUSPENSIONS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS HIT HARD BY BASEBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Major League Baseball fined and suspended 16
Dodgers players and three coaches Wednesday for their actions in a
bizarre brawl with fans last week at Chicago's Wrigley Field, a
decision that stunned and angered players and team management.
</P>
<P>
   The suspensions, which were immediately appealed, range from
three to eight games and the fines from $3,000 to $5,000. The
punishment involves four regular starting position players and
totals 84 games and $72,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am totally in shock,'' said Bob Daly, the Dodgers' general
managing partner and CEO, as his team prepared to face the
Cincinnati Reds at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Backup catcher Chad Kreuter was the only player to receive the
maximum penalties of eight games and a $5,000 fine. The incident,
which took place May 16, began when Kreuter went into the stands
after a fan allegedly struck him. Coaches Rick Dempsey, Glenn
Hoffman and John Shelby also received the stiffest penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Others punished included left fielder Gary Sheffield, pitcher
Carlos Perez and outfielder F.P. Santangelo (five games, $5,000),
and pitcher Mike Fetters (four games, $4,000). Dealt three-game
suspensions and $3,000 fines were right fielder Shawn Green;
catcher Todd Hundley; first baseman Eric Karros; pitchers Terry
Adams, Darren Dreifort, Eric Gagne, Alan Mills, Antonio Osuna and
Chan Ho Park; and outfielder Geronimo Berroa.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Onan Masaoka, sent to the minor leagues Monday, also
received the smallest punishment, and bullpen catcher Travis
Barbary, not an official member of the coaching staff, received
five games and a $5,000 fine, which the team will pay.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner's office told The Associated Press that the 19
suspensions were the most ever in baseball from one incident.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers officials unanimously condemned the decision _ manager
Davey Johnson called it ``a way of handicapping the Dodgers'' _ and
expressed confidence that the massive number of suspensions would
be reduced through appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The team insisted that the majority of the players and coaches
acted as peacekeepers or out of self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth inning of the game in Chicago, a fan allegedly
reached over the wall next to the Dodgers bullpen, struck Kreuter
in the head and took his cap. Kreuter charged into the stands after
the fan, and other Dodgers followed. The game continued after a
10-minute delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question,'' Johnson said when asked about the
innocence of many Dodgers. ``My whole coaching staff was trying to
pull people out of there. Todd Hundley, he loves Chicago, and he
was trying to keep people from attacking other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Robinson, baseball's vice president of on-field operations
and a former teammate of Johnson's with the Baltimore Orioles,
handed down the punishment and is expected to be in Los Angeles
later this week or early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Beeston, who serves as CEO of Major League Baseball, will
handle the appeals. The players association will represent the
players, and the Dodgers will assist the coaches in the appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am surprised at the severity of (the punishment),'' Dodgers
general manager Kevin Malone said. ``I'm not sure how (Robinson)
came to this decision, or who influenced him, but I have a lot of
confidence in Paul and his ability to make judgments. I think he
will make some adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone and other team officials were perhaps most upset that
Robinson decided the specific games that each player would miss.
The suspensions were scheduled to begin Wednesday, and Johnson said
he would have been without ``a couple starters'' without the
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's way out of line,'' Johnson said. ``(Robinson is)
dictating who my players can play against and who they can't. He's
managing my ballclub for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who has ever managed, and Frank has managed in the big
leagues, knows what it means to have even one player out of the
lineup,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   A team spokesman said the players decided in a team meeting
prior to the game not to speak with the media regarding the
suspensions, even though they had been instructed to remain silent
only about the specifics of the incident, since civil litigation is
still possible.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Malone confirmed, however, that the players were
upset, surprised and confused, and they weren't alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we found out this morning, I couldn't believe it,'' Daly
said. ``I looked at the video, and I was shocked (at the severity
of the punishment). I thought there would be a couple suspensions
and some fines, but it's easier for me to tell you the people who
weren't suspended.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly expressed concern about the distraction the punishment
would cause to his team, which is battling the Arizona Diamondbacks
for first place in the National League West, and suggested that
baseball officials were making an example out of the Dodgers and
setting a bad precedent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the message is clear ... Players shouldn't be in the
stands,'' Daly said. ``That's OK (with me), but does that allow
fans to decide a pennant race?''
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey has been through this before. He received a 17-game
suspension last year for an on-field incident with the Seattle
Mariners, but defended his actions in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came face to face with some guys who'd had a lot to drink
and wanted to fight,'' Dempsey said, ``and I didn't accommodate
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel this punishment is way, way too harsh, and it just
doesn't balance out,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
