<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A fork on the road
 &HT;    (For release Sunday, May 28.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ I am sitting in a Paris restaurant watching American
tourists (and myself) fumbling with how to hold a knife and fork
while eating. We don't do it the same way as Europeans but we make
fools of ourselves trying.
</P>
<P>
   There's a brief poem that I have long attributed to the late
Ogden Nash but perhaps he didn't write it. In its totality, more or
less, it's this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Use a spoon when eating peas,
</P>
<P>
   If you use a fork,
</P>
<P>
   they will fall on your knees.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's how it is with us Americans trying to eat European
style. We see them balancing all types of food on the curved backs
of their forks (in their left hands, no less!), and we try it, only
to have the food flop back onto the plate, or worse, into our laps.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, according to stereotypical American movies,
we always could separate the Nazi infiltrators from the Americans
simply by asking them Joe DiMaggio's batting average; which they
could not provide, so, BLAM!, one dead Nazi. But I'm sure the Nazis
could discover our infiltrators just by inviting them to dinner;
``Ah, zoh, you move der fork beck to your right hand, mein Herr,
auf Wiedersehen.'' BLAM!
</P>
<P>
   I have given Euroeating a good try, but where I fail is when I
try to emulate that dining habit by using my knife and fork to
assemble multiple foods onto a single forkful (upside down no
less!).
</P>
<P>
   It absolutely bewilders me to see Europeans diddling with their
food, cutting this piece into tiny pieces, adding them to something
else already balancing on the fork, pushing it up against another
type of food _ all with the object of getting the entire load into
the mouth without any foul-up.
</P>
<P>
   This reminds me of my childhood _ and, likely, yours. When we
were kids and we scrambled the food around the plate as do
Europeans in preparation for a swallow, our mothers would slap the
backs of our hands, chastising us: ``Don't play with your food!''
</P>
<P>
   My grandmother's active chastening verb was ``potchkeh,''
defined by the late Yiddish lexicographer Leo Rosten as ``messing
around inefficiently and inexpertly.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Europeans do with their food. They play with it;
potchkeh with it. We Americans, however, we just go about our
business and gobble it up, a chunk of meat now, a forkful of mashed
potatoes next, maybe a spear of asparagus on yet another effort.
</P>
<P>
   But not snippets of all at once!
</P>
<P>
   We try too hard to be like others but we cannot. It's the same
thing in Japanese, Chinese and Thai restaurants back in the States.
Usually, there is that foreboding set of chopsticks that indicates
what should be our primary effort.
</P>
<P>
   So we who have grown up with a spearing fork fumble with rounded
sticks and hope to keep the food balanced between the two. I don't
know about you, but I'm so tense when I try it, I get cramps at the
base of my thumb. Mercifully, forks and spoons are provided for
backup.
</P>
<P>
   Our Asian friends make no pretense of accumulating multiple
morsels of food as do the Europeans. A couple of grains of rice
will do for one mouthful; the bok choy comes up with the next load,
then the shrimp _ and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I admire the Europeans for their ability to hold forks
upside down in the wrong hand and still manage to get food to their
mouths without accidents. Lately, I have noticed that my wife has
taken to handling her silverware and food in that deliberate,
seemingly stylish manner.
</P>
<P>
   You might say that while I eat, she dines.
</P>
<P>
   I have given up trying and forever will be easily identifiable
as an American. Even if I had mastered the upside-down fork trick,
I still would have been exposed for who I am when I had the
audacity to ask for my coffee to be served (italic)with(enditalic)
my dessert. Mon Dieu!
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 1041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
