<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5340 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TRAVEL-OPENBUS26-COX     05-25 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-OPENBUS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TRAVEL: A breezy way to explore big cities
 &HT;    (With photo.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ As the bright green and yellow double-decker bus rounded
the circle at the Trocadero, the impressive full view of the Eiffel
Tower hit us flush in the face. It loomed immediately across the
Seine, its many lights emblazoning ``2000'' across its second
platform.
</P>
<P>
   In minutes, the bus _ having crossed the river _ pulled directly
in front of the massive structure. It was time to exercise an
option: either remain on the open-air upper deck of the bus and
move on to another site, or get off, visit the tower then pick up
another green and yellow bus later at the same corner, and continue
on with the guided tour of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, it is called L'OpenTour; in Vienna, it's the Hop-On
Hop-Off; in London, it's The Big Bus. What they all are are
inexpensive, accommodating ways to tour cities on your own time, at
your own pace. You'll find similar tours in U.S. cities such as
Boston and New York, the Canadian cities of Toronto and Ottawa, in
the upcoming Olympic city of Sydney, Australia. Likely, there are
dozens more. Two years ago, we saw Dublin that way. Before then, it
was Glasgow.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists have diverse options when they arrive in a major city.
They can view the sights on foot, an exhausting practice. They can
hire a private car, an extravagant endeavor. They can go in one of
those pre-packaged tours; five minutes here, two there, quick,
everyone back on the bus!
</P>
<P>
   Or they can take the Hop-On Hop-Off system, which is kind to the
feet, gentle to the pocketbook and uninhibited by the tick of a
clock.
</P>
<P>
   It works this way: In cities with the service, identifiable
signs are posted at bus stops, notably near major attractions. You
climb aboard, pay the driver for the ticket (more about that later)
and take a seat. Aboard you will find a brochure and map explaining
the various stops, and the frequency of the buses. On the 21-stop
tour we took in Paris, the buses arrived every 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   You could get off wherever you wanted (at a designated stop, of
course), visit an attraction, eat lunch, do shopping, take a nap on
a park bench _ whatever you want. Then show up at any designated
stop, flash your ticket, climb aboard and continue on.
</P>
<P>
   On the tours, explanations of the sights are given in several
languages _ including English _ either through earphones or from
the microphone of an on-board guide.
</P>
<P>
   In some cities, such as Paris, the tickets are good for two full
days. What you didn't stop and see today, you could do tomorrow.
The cost was 150 francs apiece for the two days, or approximately
$22. Considering the cost of individual cabs to a full city tour,
or that of a private car (about $600 a day), the price of Hop-On
Hop-Off is quite good. Certainly, the city can be explored by
subway or city bus at a lower price, but it's just not the same _
no guide, no great view from above, but blocks-long underground
treks to make connections and, of course, the jammed rush hours.
</P>
<P>
   During our two days of the Paris L'OpenTour, we circled the
principal sites twice, got off at the Musee D'orsay for a lengthy
visit, again at the Arc DeTriomphe, at the massive Le Printemps
department store, at the area just below the Montmartre (from where
we took the funiculaire, a tram-like cable car, to the top). Had we
not been to Paris multiple times before, we likely would have
disembarked more often.
</P>
<P>
   A second Paris company, Les Cars Rouges, operates similarly with
red double-decker buses but has fewer stops.
</P>
<P>
   Several days earlier, we took advantage of a corresponding
system in Vienna. This time, the bus was single-level, enclosed and
air-conditioned. Also good for two days, the Vienna Line Hop-On
Hop-Off cost 250 schillings each, or about $17.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the audiotaped Paris tour, this had a human guide who
spoke in German, English and Italian. This made it easy to ask
questions _ and get answers. On the two days of this tour, we made
far more stops as we had never before been to Vienna. Always, the
bus was within a few minutes of the promised arrival time at each
easily recognized stop. The brochure included approximate arrival
times for each of the 15 stops on the Vienna tour.
</P>
<P>
   The far-ranging Vienna tour took us from the park with the giant
ferris wheel of ``The Third Man'' movie fame, down to the
Schonbrunn Palace to the absolutely intriguing Hundertwasserhaus
museum alongside the Danube Canal.
</P>
<P>
   Inasmuch as no two city tour systems seem to have the same name,
check with your hotel clerk or concierge for information; they
likely will have brochures.
</P>
<P>
   If your time is short, if you are part of the
If-It's-Tuesday-It-Must-Be-Belgium derangement, and if your
pocketbook is already deeply dented by the cost of eating in
European restaurants and staying at European hotels, then Hop-On
Hop-Off is a moving oasis of information, transportation and
economic moderation.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
