</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-CHIPS-$ADV29-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: in 23rd graf, corrects to read 'DSP' sted of 'DSL'
 &HT;    ISRAELIS BRAINPOWER, MILITARY SAVVY DRAW U.S. CHIPMAKERS
 &HT;    (1000&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With Photos; box attached at of story.
 &HT;    With ISRAEL-INTEL-$ADV29.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Mon., May 29, And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HERZILYA, Israel _ For Hanan Achsaf, president of Motorola
Israel Ltd., the country's occasional ``minor disagreements with
its neighbors'' are not enough to blunt the business attraction of
its brain power.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has worked for Motorola. The company came here first in
the 1960s with an investment of less than $20 million and now
controls assets worth more than $20 billion and 4,100 workers.
</P>
<P>
   The company's semiconductor design center, with 600 workers in
this suburb of Tel Aviv, is its largest in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two years, Israel has become famous for its boom
in software start-up companies. But, Motorola is one of about a
dozen major U.S. firms that have invested here to make or develop
microprocessors, or chips _ the hardware brains to computers,
cellular phones and even anti-lock brakes.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, despite a worrisome shortage of engineers to feed such
growth, the list of firms with development centers here reads like
a hi-tech Who's Who: Intel, which has two manufacturing plants
here; along with Texas Instruments; National Semiconductor; IBM;
3COM and Microsoft. Applied Materials, developing and producing
equipment for semiconductor makers, came here in 1991 and now
employs 650 in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good match. Israel, a country of about 6 million people,
has little natural resources _ no oil like its Arab neighbors. It
has few markets available on its borders, either because its
neighbors are hostile or have small economies.
</P>
<P>
   What it can do is produce knowledge and that's what draws the
big chip firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a combination of things that come from being a country
where existential problems are permanent,'' said Orna Berry, who,
until she stepped down this month, oversaw government support for
hi-tech development as Israel's chief scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Berry sees Israel's battles for survival and need to look for
support beyond its own region as helping foster the boom. Israeli
hi-tech workers are considered innovative, competitive and
hardworking. Though Israel's first language is Hebrew, English, the
first language of technology, is commonly spoken.
</P>
<P>
   And, most Israelis have to spend at least a couple of years in
their lives in what has become a hi-tech incubator _ the army.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the army, you have been exposed to the most sophisticated
technology,'' said Achsaf, once an instructor in the air force's
technical school. The army even has a so-called ``genius unit,'' a
special intelligence branch specializing in hi-tech.
</P>
<P>
   The government also kicks in its share, giving about $400
million in grants to industry _ mostly hi-tech _ each year. It gave
Intel $600 million to build a semiconductor plant that opened last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The results have changed the economy. Of Israel's total $35
billion in exports last year, about one-third, or $12 billion were
in hi-tech.
</P>
<P>
   Figures were not available for electronics specifically, but
consider that Intel alone expects to export more than $1 billion
from its chip plant this year. Motorola last year exported about
$257 million from its mostly-communications facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that the American firms have not only helped the
electronics industry here grow, but have professionalized Israeli
marketing and managerial skills. The American influence, they say,
has also smoothed some of the rough edges on Israeli workers, known
to be gruff and undisciplined.
</P>
<P>
   There is some hype in Israel's selling of itself. Government
ministries frequently promote a graph showing that Israel has the
highest number of engineers and scientists per capita in the world.
Those figures come from 1984 and, according to one researcher, were
statistically flawed.
</P>
<P>
   But, Israel is indeed well-educated; third in the world in
percentage of residents with a university degree. That is the
lifeblood in the industry, where firms lose precious time to their
competitors if they have trouble finding labor.
</P>
<P>
   The big question hanging over hi-tech firms here is what will
happen now that Israel is starting to see a shortage of engineers.
It's not yet as acute as it is in the United States, but the labor
market is tightening.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli engineers still earn about 80 percent of what their
counterparts do in the United States, but salaries are climbing and
many workers are simply moving to America. Economists say the
hi-tech sector is at full employment at about 50,000. Berry said
there is actually a shortage of about 5,000 electronics workers.
</P>
<P>
   The crunch would be worse, had it not been for the highly
educated influx of 1 million immigrants from the former Soviet
Union. Motorola officials say about 20 percent of the workers at
their semiconductor center are from there.
</P>
<P>
   The market was still so tight that, two years ago, a corporate
association asked the government to grant visas to about 1,500
engineers from Asia, mostly India. It was an idea that would not
fly in the Jewish state, as some feared it would cause an influx of
largely non-Jewish immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the shortage, major newcomers still arrive. Last year,
Dallas-based Texas Instruments spent about $415 million to buy two
Israeli companies that develop DSP technology _ specialized chips
for things like cable television systems.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Bernier, TI European manager for communications, said the
company still sees Israel as a ``vibrant center of high-level
expertise.''
</P>
<P>
   The future of Israel's electronics firms may depend on whether
the country can maintain its effort to increase the number of
engineering graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, while Israel's got a hi-tech boost in the past from its
army technology, it may rely more in the future on it's peacemaking
abilities. Israel Kashat, vice president at Motorola's design
center, said peace talks could enable Israel to use the engineering
pools in the countries on its borders.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians, for example, show avid computer affinity and some
already work for Israeli firms. Egypt, with 55 million people, has
a large supply of engineers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real untapped potential,'' Kashat said, ``is our
neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow's E-mail address is: larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------------
</P>
