<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 11:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5352 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-NIGERIA-HOPE-$ADV28-C     05-25 2573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-HOPE-$ADV28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NIGERIA, A YEAR LATER: DEMOCRACY TAKING ROOT, BUT CORRUPTION
HARD TO WEED OUT
 &HT;    (1875&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With photos; box attached at end of story.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., May 28 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGOS, Nigeria _ Just to stay in business, Chuba Egolum must
cope with daily annoyances most Americans would confront only
during a natural catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, people who know Nigeria like to sum things up with a
joke: ``What's the difference between Nigeria and a disaster
area?''
</P>
<P>
   Answer: ``In a disaster area, the Red Cross will come to help
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Egolum isn't laughing. His time in the United States _ including
three years obtaining an MBA in Atlanta _ taught him to appreciate
basic things longed for in a place like Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I have to deal with whether I'm going to have
electricity,'' he says, sitting at his desk in a striped golf shirt
and tan Dockers trousers. His company drills wells and builds water
distribution systems. ``I have to make sure to pump enough water
into the tank on top of the building so we will be able to flush
the toilet.''
</P>
<P>
   Traffic in this immense swirling city is impassable at most
hours. ``It is bedeviling,'' Egolum says. ``When I pick up the
phone, most often it is dead,'' he says. ``This is what it is to do
business in Nigeria.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite it all, Egolum is hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in nearly two decades, Nigeria has a civilian
government. Africa's most populous nation, with 123 million people,
now can carry on without the crushing weight of the corrupt
military regimes that have saddled it for most of its 40 years of
independence.
</P>
<P>
   While the end of military rule is universally praised, a year of
living democratically has been sobering, even disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democracy is a new experience for us,'' says Egolum, who still
considers genuine representative government a distant destination _
a Promised Land. ``We haven't gotten there yet, but we have a
pretty good chance.''
</P>
<P>
   This sentiment is widespread in Nigeria, but it is accompanied
by an uneasy belief that the window of opportunity may shut at any
time. People worry in particular that too much may be riding on the
powers of one man: President Olusegan Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday(5/29), Obasanjo will celebrate the anniversary of his
inauguration as Nigeria's first civilian leader since 1983. A man
who counts among his friends Bill Clinton and former President
Jimmy Carter, Obasanjo, 63, is regarded widely as an honest,
intelligent and dedicated leader. Among his credentials is a period
as chairman of Transparency International, a Berlin-based
organization that promotes honest government.
</P>
<P>
   And by most measures, Obasanjo, a former general who ruled
between 1976 and 1979 before handing power to a doomed civilian
government, has made an auspicious start. He summarily retired from
government crooked military officers, pushed an ethics agenda and
has labored to repair the country's dreadful reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the problems confronting Obasanjo and Nigeria remain both
broad and deep, a perilous combination in a country whose people
have high expectations and little patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nigerians are about getting Nigeria fixed,'' said John Muibi
Amoda, the head of the pro-democracy Africa Peace Support
Initiative. Yet, Amoda cautions that people expect too much and
understand too little. ``Just because you have an internationally
monitored so-called democratic election doesn't mean that you have
a democracy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While reformers demand that Obasanjo do more, the robber barons
who dominated for so long are working to obstruct him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is walking a tightrope with people at both ends
shaking the rope,'' Amoda said.
</P>
<P>
   Western leaders are aware of the president's plight but are
eager for him to succeed because they believe Africa's future may
depend heavily on the success of a healthy and democratic Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration identified Nigeria as one of four
''key democracies'' along with Colombia, Indonesia and Ukraine. It
ended the country's pariah status, and is seeking $100 million in
aid. In January, the administration said it would end its ban on
direct flights from the United States to Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Obasanjo has pledged to deploy his disused but
still potent military to help bring stability to west Africa. He
offered to send peacekeepers to Sierra Leone, so long as Nigeria
receives foreign support _ particularly from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The White House also has responded favorably, if vaguely, to
Obasanjo's anxious pleas for relief from the country's estimated
$35 billion in international debt, which consumes more than a third
of Nigeria's federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   American policymakers take particular note of Obasanjo's
ambitions of doubling Nigeria's oil output to 4 million barrels a
day. The country already produces about twice as much crude oil as
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Obasanjo embraces the free market and has embarked
on a drive to privatize major industries.
</P>
<P>
   And while Obasanjo's momentum has been stalled by an assertive
Legislature _ which will be a year old in June _ many observers
believe the government is at least learning the deliberative,
power-sharing process.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, Nigeria was poised to assume the role of an
African superpower. Today it is a shambles.
</P>
<P>
   For 17 years this vast country _ which is about the size of
Texas, Georgia and Florida combined _ was ravaged by military
juntas that wrecked the economy, impoverished the people and
depleted the national treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of neglect are everywhere. In the primary city Lagos,
skyscrapers stand with broken windows and weedy sidewalks like the
ruins of some flourishing but bygone metropolis. Without reliable
electricity, elevators rarely run in the buildings made stifling by
the lack of air-conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the commerce in this sprawling urban jumble of 11
million is what economists call ``informal,'' meaning individuals
and small businesses hawk whatever they can for whatever they can
get. In many ways, Nigeria is a nation of hardy and hard-bitten
entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   In today's world of e-commerce and automated everything, Nigeria
seems primitive. Banks don't issue credit cards and, with the
exception of the two or three hotels that specialize in fleecing
foreigners, no one accepts them. There are no automated teller
machines and, perhaps most startling, no McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   Crime is a constant companion. Hotel doormen panic when foreign
guests suggest taking a stroll. For a fee, heavily armed soldiers
at the airport will stand guard over newly arrived visitors and
their bags until a taxi or friend comes to gather them up.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking any public transport and little traffic enforcement,
roads in Lagos are choked in a hopeless, chaotic gridlock _ known
here as ``slow-go.'' To keep things moving, whip-bearing policeman
apprehend laggardly drivers and administer lashes on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   And even with its vast oil resources, Nigeria must import
gasoline, creating frequent shortages and a thriving black market.
Without the luxury of being able to worry about the environment,
the air has become brown with dust and pollution and roadsides are
covered with layers of litter. Much of the country's hardwood
forests are gone and the oil-rich Niger Delta is a disaster in the
view of many environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard not to get the impression that nothing works.
</P>
<P>
   Nigerians blame the mess on the run of dictators who were inept,
dishonest or both. Over the past two decades, Nigeria developed the
reputation of being perhaps the world's most corrupt country. (In
1998, Transparency International rated Nigeria No. 2 among corrupt
countries,
</P>
<P>
   trailing only neighboring Cameroon.)
</P>
<P>
   To many outsiders, it often seemed as if the entire nation was
on the take. From passport officers to traffic cops, just about any
problem could be resolved with a ``dash'' _ a bribe.
</P>
<P>
   Nigerian leaders now consider regaining credibility paramount.
``If there is one single thing that has retarded economic
development, it is the issue of corruption,'' said Farouk Lawan,
the chairman of the ethics committee of the Nigerian House of
Representatives. ``We are talking about a situation where the
previous head of state looted vast amounts of money and stifled
</P>
<P>
   the entire economic system of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Sani Abacha, who ruled from 1993 until he died in office in
1998, is accused of personally stealing more than $4 billion. With
the assistance of friendly governments _ including the United
States _ Obasanjo has located several hundred million. But much of
the money may never be recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Despite many small victories, the economy remains in critical
but at least stable condition. Last weekend, Obasanjo announced
that Nigeria was had caught up with $1.5 billion in back payments
to the government's private partners in oil joint ventures,
including Royal Dutch Shell, Exxon-Mobil and Chevron.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, economists worry that a recovery may be impossible
given the poor state of the nation's infrastructure, particularly
the power grid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The confidence in the Nigerian economy cannot be restored
until these basic infrastructure needs are met,'' said Chike
Uchime, the editor of the Nigerian magazine Business &AMP; Finance
Digest. Additionally, the country needs to diversify its economy,
he said. Nearly 90 percent of the country's export revenues and
virtually all its tax income comes from oil.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the greatest internal threat is the continued strife
between Muslims and Christians.
</P>
<P>
   The flashpoint has been the attempt by leaders in the heavily
Muslim northern states to impose Sharia, conservative Islamic law.
Since February the conflict has claimed thousands of lives in
brutal clashes with machetes the weapon of choice. Obasanjo has
been criticized for reacting too slowly and indecisively.
Politicians from both religions express concerns that
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria will disintegrate if Obasanjo cannot gain control of the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   With all the problems, most people seem to believe that the
change toward democracy is irreversible.
</P>
<P>
   On a particularly hot day recently, T. Bimbo Akande sought
refuge in the breeze made by a fan in his office on the 18th floor
in one of the weary old skyscrapers that haunt downtown Lagos.
</P>
<P>
   Akande believes his import-export business will improve only if
Obasanjo can win the trust of foreign investors. He's skeptical but
modestly hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   However, Akande counts his loss to the years of chaos in
personal terms. In November, his 21-year-old son Dapo Akande came
home in the evening to a dark house. As usual, the power was out,
so he cranked up the diesel-powered generator. It burst flames that
engulfed the young man.
</P>
<P>
   Akande found his son and rushed him to the poorly equipped and
scantily staffed hospital. Four days later, he died.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was my loss to the conditions in Nigeria,'' Akande said.
``He was a huge investment for me that I will never be able to
recover. How many souls have been wasted just this way?''
</P>
<P>
   Akande, whose brother lives in the suburban Atlanta community of
Powder Springs, expressed deep frustration at the wasted potential
_ both in his son and his country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've traveled around the world and I know what this country
has to offer, what its people are capable of,'' he said. ``With
good leadership. We should be among the first in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all too obvious, isn't it. There's no going back from
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s E-mail address is: BertR(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://nigeriaweb.odili.net
</P>
<P>
   http://www.nigeriagov.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.nigeria.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.USAfricaonline.com
</P>
<P>
   ----------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA AT-A-GLANCE
</P>
<P>
   President: Olusegun Obasanjo
</P>
<P>
   Area: 356,700 square miles
</P>
<P>
   Population:123,337,822 (2000 estimate); average annual rate of
natural increase: 2.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Capital: Abuja, pop. 339,000.
</P>
<P>
   Largest cities: Lagos: metro area (1996 est.) 10,878,000;
OIbadan, 1,365,000; Ogbomosho, 711,900; Kano, 657,300.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: Naira.
</P>
<P>
   Languages: English (official); Hausa; Yoruba; Ibo; and more than
200 others.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnicity/race: Hausa; Fulani; Yoruba; Ibo; Kanuri; Ibibio; Tiv;
Ijaw.
</P>
<P>
   Religions: Islam, 50 percent; Christian, 40 percent; indigenous,
10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Literacy rate: 51 percent
</P>
<P>
   Economy:
</P>
<P>
   GDP: $106.2 billion ($960 per capita).
</P>
<P>
   Agricultural products: cocoa, peanuts, palm oil, corn, rice,
sorghum, millet, cassava (tapioca), yams, rubber; cattle, sheep,
goats, pigs, timber, fish.
</P>
<P>
   Industries: crude oil, coal, tin, columbite, palm oil, peanuts,
cotton, rubber, wood, hides and skins, textiles, cement and other
construction materials, food products, footwear, chemicals,
fertilizer, printing, ceramics, steel. Natural resources:
petroleum, tin, columbite, iron ore, coal, limestone, lead, zinc,
natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   Exports: $9.7 billion (1998): petroleum and petroleum products,
cocoa, rubber.
</P>
<P>
   Imports: $9.8 billion (1998): machinery, chemicals,
transportation equipment, manufactured goods, food and animals.
</P>
<P>
   Major trading partners: U.S., Spain, Italy, France, U.K.,
Germany, the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   History: First inhabted in about 500 B.C, but Nok people; many
tribes followed. Islam was introduced in the 13th century. The
British annexed Lagos in 1851 and seized control of the rest of the
region by 1886. Britain created Nigeria and made it a colony in
1914. Nigeria gained independence in 1960. Rioting broke out in
1966, and military leaders seized control. In July, a second
military coup put Col. Yakubu Gowon in power. Also in that year,
Muslim Hausas in the north massacred Christian Ibos in the east,
many of whom had been driven from the north. Thousands of Ibos took
refuge in the eastern region, which declared its independence as
Biafra in 1967. In 1970, Biafra surrendered to the federal
government. Gowon's nine-year rule ended in 1975 with a bloodless
coup that made Gen. Muritala Rufai Mohammed chief of state. Gen.
Olesugan Obasanjo assumed power in 1976 and in 1979 handed control
to civilian government of Alhaji Shehu Shagari. An oil boom in the
1970s buoyed the economy, and by the 1980s Nigeria was considered
an exemplary of African democracy. In 1984, the military seized
power, only to be followed by a coup in 1985. Gen. Ibrahim
Babangida said the country would be returned to civilian rule, but
in 1993 he voided the results of election and Babangida resigned.
In November 1993, Gen. Sani Abacha led a coup to restore military
rule. Abacha's regime was condemned for corruption and inefficiency
as well as a harshly repressive methods. Abacha's rule turned
Nigeria into an international pariah. The hanging of writer Ken
Saro-Wiwa in 1995 was condemned around the world. Abacha died of a
heart attack in June 1998, and was succeeded by another military
ruler, Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar. He pledged to step aside for an
elected leader by May 1999. In February 1999, Obasanjo won an
overwhelming victory. He was inaugurated May 29, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Source: www.infoplease.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
