r e BC-BOOKS-EYMAN0526-COX     05-25 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-EYMAN0526-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Found it in `The Movies': Seminal `2001'
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The first four volumes of Modern Library's
``The Movies'' have appeared. Three of them are reprints: ``Agee on
Film,'' by the best movie critic who ever lived (yes, better than
Pauline Kael, because Agee had better taste; you never caught him
writing panegyrics to the 1948 equivalent of Brian De Palma); Rudy
Behlmer's ``Memo From David O. Selznick,'' a truly invaluable
volume that gives us access to one of the few men able to hold the
entire equation of motion pictures in his head; and Vachel
Lindsay's very early (1915) and very interesting ``The Art of the
Moving Picture.''
</P>
<P>
   The Agee and the Behlmer were in print for years before falling
out comparatively recently, and are not hard to find in used book
shops. The Lindsay was last in print nearly 30 years ago, so it is
a most welcome addition.
</P>
<P>
   But the most interesting book is ``The Making of 2001: A Space
Odyssey.'' Initially, I thought it was another reprint, of a book
edited by Jerome Agel that came out when Kubrick's film did.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a new compilation that reprints a few things from
Agel's book and adds a lot of new material about one of the seminal
movies of the last half century. Kubrick's friend Alexander Walker
contributes a piece, as does critic Jay Cocks, who spent a lot of
time with Kubrick as the film was nearing release.
</P>
<P>
   The piece I found most interesting was an interview Kubrick did
with the ``Village Voice'' when the film opened: ``There is a
distant relationship between chess and making a film,'' says
Kubrick. ``With chess you have to explore different lines of play,
and think of different possible outcomes. In films you're always
juggling more than you can ever think about at one time, and trying
to analyze as many moves as deeply into the consequences as you
can. Films are a peculiar combination of the worst circumstances
imaginable for an artist to work in, and the most powerful art form
ever devised. And finding the resultant of those forces is the key
to getting the film done.''
</P>
<P>
   The older books have all been reset and cost between $14.95 and
$16.95. The series, edited by Martin Scorsese, is off to an
auspicious start.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
