<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5364 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-HARRYGOLD0526-C     05-25 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-HARRYGOLD0526-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Novelist paints features onto slate-gray spy
 &HT;    By Tom Blackburn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Harry Gold's name is a nuclear blast from the
national past. He was one of the ``atom spies,'' always identified
in news accounts as a ``chemist,'' who never got close to a
military secret in his job. He was the conduit, the courier, the
guy who picked up and delivered for a real atomic physicist, Klaus
Fuchs, and the Soviet KGB.
</P>
<P>
   Millicent Dillon, an established biographer (of Jane Bowles,
Isadora Duncan and others) was attracted to him as a subject. But
there's hardly anything documented about Gold, and he said little
about himself. He was as reflective as a black boot in a coal mine.
So scratch the biography?
</P>
<P>
   No. Dillon turned it into a novel, improvising freely on the
scant record. And here's the pleasant surprise: ``Harry Gold''
works both as an affecting novel and as a portrait of at least one
secret agent.
</P>
<P>
   Gold didn't do it for ideology. He never joined the Communist
Party. He didn't do it for money. He didn't get any. He was once
shown a Soviet medal and was told it was his. But he couldn't keep
it. It would have been too dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   So why did he do it? To answer that question, Dillon has to
breathe life into an airless and boring existence. Raised in
Philadelphia by refugees from czarist Russia, Harry was a bookish
loner. But he was dutiful and methodical, which later would make
him an ideal steward of chemical experiments that require time,
method and patience.
</P>
<P>
   The Golds were never well-off, and the Depression made things
worse. Harry dropped out of school to support his family. When he
was laid off from his job, a friend of a friend found him another.
The friend's friend was a communist.
</P>
<P>
   The benefactor asked Harry for a favor. Harry, who never said no
to anyone, could hardly say no to the man who had saved his family.
Step by step, he was drawn into being a courier for Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   As Dillon sees him, Harry knew he was being used but didn't
mind. High politics didn't interest him. The hapless, helpless
Philadelphia Phillies were his main outside interest, but he spent
most of his days and nights in the lab, doing consumer chemistry.
He simply liked feeling useful.
</P>
<P>
   Here is Harry, imagined by Dillon, at the time when he was
nearing what would become the high point of his later notoriety:''
As he gets off the train in New York, he slips easily into being
one of a crowd, unseen. He does not delude himself that he is a
special kind of man. Klaus _ now there is someone different. But he
himself is ordinary, one of many. Yet by some strange chance he has
been chosen for a destiny, not at all ordinary. With Klaus he is
caught up in the forces of history, at a critical juncture of life
and matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrast that public appearance with the last picture of the
bomb-planting protagonist of Joseph Conrad's ``The Secret Agent'' :
``And the incorruptible Professor walked, too, averting his eyes
from the odious multitude of mankind. He had no future. He
disdained it. He was a force. His thoughts caressed the images of
ruin and destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the difference between doing or being done-to. When Hannah
Arendt coined the phrase ``the banality of evil,'' she had in mind
Adolf Eichmann, the organizer of the Nazis' ``final solution.'' But
Eichmann was a skilled bureaucrat and a true believer. Gold, in his
spy role, was neither, merely a trained mule, but one who delivered
information that materially sped up Russia's attainment of the
atomic bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of her novel, Dillon does a daring thing. She
weaves into the story the most detailed part of the recorded
factual record she had to work from. The reader can compare it to
the rest of the novel to see how she did. The factual material
seems to flow from the novel, instead of the other way around. So
one could say she did very well.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
