NYT-05-25-00 1114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5365 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-POETRY0526-COX     05-25 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-POETRY0526-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Pure Poetry'' offers up an enjoyable rant and rave
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Lila Moscowitz is the only poet of her
generation who's been featured in People magazine. Her poem, ``At
the Baby Doll Lounge Salome Dances;'' ``The Baptist Tips Her a Ten
Spot,'' gave her a brief flurry of renown as the Camille Paglia of
pentameter, but it's been a struggle ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Lila is a born-again Jew, whose father changed the family name
to Morse, only to have her change it back to Moscowitz. She's had
an unfinished book of poems on her desk for three years. If only
she didn't have to teach for a living, she tells herself, she'd
have the time to complete it.
</P>
<P>
   She likes to think that the problem might be a lingering tsuris
over a disastrous marriage to a relative of Albert Speer's.
Contributing factors might be her therapist, who is a
cross-dresser, or her at-sword's-points relationship with her
family _ because one sister-in-law is named Regan, she insists on
referring to the other sister-in-law as Goneril.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't like her brothers any better than their wives: ``If
modern medicine could reattach the foreskin the way they are now
able to stitch back an arm severed at the elbow, my brothers would
go for the procedure in a skinny minute.''
</P>
<P>
   The Moscowitz tribe has an . . . ambivalent attitude toward
Lila, as is indicated by their neglecting to inform her that her
mother had died.
</P>
<P>
   Did I mention the ghosts? Lila lives with a couple of ghosts,
great-aunts who didn't like her mother any better than she did.
</P>
<P>
   Lila is the sort of brilliant, sexual, funny woman that
self-destructive men oblivious to hostility often fall in love
with. (The male equivalent is the narcissism that manifests itself
as either manic controlling or infantile selfishness.)
</P>
<P>
   Binnie Kirshenbaum's ``Pure Poetry'' works better as character
study than it does as narrative, mainly because there really isn't
any narrative. Lila narrates the story, so we're deep inside her
version of people and events, which is not to say you can't hear
alarm bells in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   For all of her anti-Teutonic rants, she did marry Max, who,
other than an unfortunately anal disposition _ not only is he
German, he's a cartographer _ doesn't seem all that bad.
</P>
<P>
   What gradually becomes apparent over the novel's duration is
that Lila is the classic unreliable narrator, is, in fact,
something of a wack job, albeit a highly engaging one with a
fabulous voice, a distaff Jerry Lewis:
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel about children as I do about dogs. They deserve to have
a warm bed in which to sleep. They have an inalienable right to be
fed tasty and nutritious meals. I want for each of them to have a
chew toy of their own, and it's best for all concerned if they
attend obedience school. Children and dogs deserve to be loved, but
not by me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lila is the female equivalent of one of Philip Roth's Jewish
misanthropes, dragging their rage around as if it were an
overloaded dog sled.
</P>
<P>
   Which is to say she's frequently hilarious company in a novel,
but she would compel you to quietly move to the other side of the
living room were you to encounter her at a party, or eat your gun
were you to marry her.
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding that, ``Pure Poetry'' is an exceedingly
enjoyable rant by a severely damaged character until a
disappointingly conventional ending _ let's just say that
enlightenment for characters who have spent their lives being
impossible occurs much more frequently in fiction than it does in
real life.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
