<HEADER>
A5366 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN0526-CO     05-25 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN0526-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An e-mail list full of questions
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Tx _ I'm on an e-mailing list of a group of friends
who love to chat electronically. Most every day, I get a batch of
messages from this group, which is scattered from Austin to Houston
to Seattle and points in between. They argue philosophy, the
virtues of Macintosh computers vs. IBM-compatible machines, tell
bad jokes, submit poetry and anything else that might amuse or
provoke discussion.
</P>
<P>
   I don't contribute much to the discussion, mainly because I
spend so much time in front of a computer that it's hard to
willingly sit in front of one for grins. But I enjoy reading the
messages, and e-mailing is a great and inexpensive way to keep in
touch with this group of college and high school buddies.
</P>
<P>
   One of the participants sent out the other day a list of
questions to which he wanted answers. He's an attorney, so he's
good at asking questions to which there are no answers. I suspect
somebody is getting billed somewhere for the time he spent
composing this e-mail contribution. Here it is:
</P>
<P>
   _ After eating, do amphibians have to wait one hour before
getting out of the water?
</P>
<P>
   _ How can there be self-help ''groups''?
</P>
<P>
   _ If white wine goes with fish, do white grapes go with sushi?
</P>
<P>
   _ If someone with multiple personalities threatens to kill
himself, is it considered a hostage situation?
</P>
<P>
   _ If instead of talking to your plants you yelled at them, would
they still grow, only to be troubled and insecure?
</P>
<P>
   _ Is there another word for ''synonym''?
</P>
<P>
   _ Isn't it a bit unnerving that doctors call what they do
''practice''? (So do attorneys, I might add.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Just before someone gets nervous, do they experience cocoons
in their stomach?
</P>
<P>
   _ When sign makers go on strike, is anything written on their
picket signs?
</P>
<P>
   _ When you open a new bag of cotton balls, is the top one meant
to be thrown away?
</P>
<P>
   _ When your pet bird sees you reading the newspaper, does he
wonder why you're just sitting there looking at carpeting?
</P>
<P>
   _ Where do forest rangers go to ''get away from it all''?
</P>
<P>
   _ Why isn't there mouse-flavored cat food?
</P>
<P>
   _ Why do they report power outages on TV?
</P>
<P>
   _ Why are builders afraid to have a 13th floor, but book
publishers aren't afraid to have a Chapter 11?
</P>
<P>
   I have a few questions of my own, compiled over the years.
</P>
<P>
   _ How can you tell when sour cream goes bad?
</P>
<P>
   _ Why do the instructions on shampoo bottles urge you to
''lather, rinse and repeat''? Why isn't once enough?
</P>
<P>
   _ Why do businesses always qualify ''No Dogs Allowed'' signs by
adding a line that says ''Except for Seeing-Eye Dogs''? Seems like
if you're blind, you can't read the sign anyway. Maybe the dog can.
</P>
<P>
   If you have any answers, or better yet, if you have some more
questions, drop me a line. You can even e-mail me if that type of
thing floats your boat.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Daily Sentinel in
Nacogdoches, TX. His e-mail address is sentinel(at)tcac.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
