<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5368 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN0526-CO     05-25 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN0526-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Checking the winds on gun control
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Sometimes the weight on a political seesaw
shifts very gradually. But once public opinion shifts solidly in
one direction, it accelerates.
</P>
<P>
   In the 2000 election, gun control may be such an issue. The
presumptive Republican nominee, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, has
mostly opposed more controls on guns. He is taking campaign heat
for, among other things, having signed in 1995 a bill allowing
licensed Texans to pack pistols.
</P>
<P>
   His predecessor, Democrat Ann Richards, in 1993 vetoed a bill to
allow a non-binding referendum on the issue. Some think that veto,
and the reaction of the gun lobby and gun owners, contributed
heavily to her loss to Bush in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   More than half a decade later, Bush is running nationally, not
just in gun-friendly Texas. And after a series of school and church
massacres involving guns and a Million Mom March on Mother's Day
pushing for stricter gun control, things are different.
</P>
<P>
   Or they may be. Politically, the question is whether supporting
stricter regulation of guns is more popular than sticking with the
National Rifle Association and others who contend their right to
keep handguns is protected by the Second Amendment to the U.S.
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   As with many hot issues, Bush has moved toward his opposition.
His Democratic opponent, Vice President Al Gore, is calling for
having gun manufacturers put trigger locks on handguns. Bush
responded by setting up a Texas program, the ChildSafe Project, to
offer free trigger locks for gun owners who want one.
</P>
<P>
   (Texas taxpayers will pay for the $10 locks, which will be
distributed through police and fire departments and other agencies,
Bush says. He'll earmark $1 million a year for five years from the
governor's Criminal Justice Planning Fund to do it, says press aide
Mike Jones. If elected president, Bush says he'll ask for $75
million a year for five years for a national distribution program.)
</P>
<P>
   Bush acknowledged it was no coincidence he announced the program
two days before the Million Mom March. ``As a matter of fact, it's
timed that way,'' Bush said on NBC's ``Today'' show, noting that
gun safety is getting a lot of attention.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has signed legislation blocking cities from suing
manufacturers for damages from gun violence and refused to back a
Texas bill to require instant background checks at gun shows
because he said it required national rather than state attention,
He also has called for stricter enforcement of existing gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   And indeed, while national polls indicate a majority of
Americans want more gun regulation, it ranks midway down the scale
of their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In some polls, more people favor stiffer enforcement of existing
laws than passing new ones _ which echoes Bush's stance. And while
Democrats polled strongly tend to favor stricter control,
Republicans tend just as strongly not to.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush is responding somewhat to those seeking more gun
safety, he doesn't hesitate to charge that Gore's position on gun
control has shifted during his political career.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's staffers show an NRA analysis that says Gore voted with
them three-fourths of the time from 1985 to 1990, when he was a
senator from Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it was convenient politically, he voted one way and when
it was convenient politically, he changed his tune,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore acknowledges he often voted with the NRA during his
early years in Congress, he says he changed after seeing ``the
flood of cheap handguns and the wave of gun violence sweep across
our country.'' Gore aide Doug Hattaway says Gore ``is standing up
to the NRA and its extreme agenda, while George Bush is carrying
their ammo bag.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong words _ which Bush strongly disputes. Even though an
independent gun control group has been running ads featuring a
videotape of NRA first vice president Kayne Robinson saying if Bush
is elected, ``We'll have a president . . . where we work out of
their office,'' Bush says he's never belonged to the NRA and will
call his own shots in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   And so it heads for November. The questions: Do those who want
more gun control finally outnumber politically those who don't? Do
they feel strongly enough to let that determine their vote? And
either way, how much will that affect the election? Too soon to
know.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
