   WITH: REVIEW -- In ``The Devil and Sonny Liston,'' we see Liston
as white America's stereotypical nightmare: a large, illiterate
black man who came through the door promising pain and delivering
retribution. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post) Art includes a 6-pica color
photo of book jacket and a 1-column color photo of Sonny Liston.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PUBLISHING NOTES -- Harcourt Brace will be bringing out a
new translation of Antoine de Saint-Exupery's enchanting ``The
Little Prince'' this summer. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW CARVELL -- You would expect a book by James
Carville to be outspoken to the limit, especially if the subject is
politics. If so you won't be disappointed with Corporal Cueball's
latest: ``Stickin' _ The Case for Loyalty.'' (Milner, Lufkin Daily
News) Art includes a 6-pica color photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BIOGRAPHY -- If you know the conventional wisdom about
Marcel Proust _ i.e., he was a mousy hypochondriac who only left
his bed to gather gossip at society parties _ then you're liable to
panic when presented with this new biography. (Hulbert, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes a 6-pica color photo of book
jacket and 1-column B&AMP;W photo of Marcel Proust.
</P>
