<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 11:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5380 &Cx1f; tab-z
u e BC-IVOR-TV-AMERICAN-DAUG     05-25 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-TV-AMERICAN-DAUGHTER-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASSERSTEIN TURNS REAL LIFE INTO INTRIGUING MOVIE
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of the weekly IVOR DAVIS HOLLYWOOD
STARS feature service. Nonsubscribers can use this article only by
special arrangement. For purchase information, see end of text. 
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Christine Lahti
(alone and with Tom Skerritt) in scenes from ``American
Daughter.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS   
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stage plays that actually improve when transposed to television
are rarer than ethics in a political campaign _ which makes ``An
American Daughter,'' airing June 5 on Lifetime, a particular
pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of Wendy Wasserstein's original play _ and now TV
movie _ couldn't be more topical. The real life resonances ring so
true that when you watch it you keep hearing snatches from recent
history's political discourse.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Lahti (``Chicago Hope'') plays Lyssa Dent Hughes, a
prominent physician and head of a cancer hospital. She is also
daughter of a Republican senator, a fifth generation descendant of
Ulysses S. Grant, wife of a prominent sociology professor and, last
but not least, a concerned and caring mother.
</P>
<P>
   Through a combination of hard work, brilliance and genuine
concern for the nation's health, she has reached the absolute
pinnacle of her profession. So it seems only fitting that the
president should nominate her for the surgeon general's job.
</P>
<P>
   It should be a slam dunk until the manipulative host of a TV
news magazine _ one Timber Tucker (Jay Thomas), shooting a
behind-the-scenes profile of the candidate at a family brunch in
her home, takes a piece of carelessly revealed information _ that
the busy Dent Hughes once neglected to respond to a jury summons _
and blows it up until it becomes a campaign ``issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes' nomination is now fodder for the TV mill. She compounds
her original misdemeanor in a public relations disaster by making a
slighting reference to her late mother's famous icebox cakes, and
stands accused of elitism by soccer moms across America.
</P>
<P>
   In the final denouement, groomed and dressed by political
consultants for mass acceptance, wearing a Hillary-like headband
and with her father by her side, she submits to a televised
in-depth interview by Tucker. He promises to help salvage her
political career and instead subjects her to a final horrible
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Will Lyssa play media games to salvage her career or decide that
ultimately she cannot be someone she is not, even for the job that
her entire life has been preparing her for?
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons I wrote this play,'' explains playwright
Wendy Wasserstein, ``was because I was taken by the `Hillary
Clinton in a headband' interview on `60 Minutes.' She had
previously said she was not someone who was going to bake cookies,
and then she was retracting it in this interview. I thought `God
it's so hard to be a woman. You have to suddenly change who you
are.'''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to shows like NBC's sharply penned ``The West Wing'' _
and well-documented attempts by the Clinton administration to name
women to high political posts suffering death by media _ this story
is familiar territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also sprang from my interest in what happened to Zoe Baird,
President Clinton's first nominee for attorney general,''
Wasserstein says. ``It was thought to be a good idea and then this
information came out about her nanny. There were hearings and that
was the end of Zoe Baird. Then came Kimba Wood and Lani Guinier. I
was interested in what happens to the best and the brightest people
in this country and why they don't go into public office. Why would
you put yourself and your family through this?''
</P>
<P>
   Wasserstein's screenplay makes clear that Lyssa Dent Hughes
would be a superb surgeon general because she believes in service,
she is smart, dedicated, honest and hardworking, but she has one
overriding problem: Her brand of intelligence doesn't work on TV.
And when she's attacked she naively believes honesty is the best
policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's more important,'' Wasserstein asks, ``that these people
are good at public relations or that they're good at their jobs? Do
you want the person who's going to be surgeon general to come on
television and be charming or would you rather have a good health
care system? I'd rather have the health care.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasserstein's movie states the obvious: Women in public life are
subject to different rules than men, especially in the media.
They've got to have something called likeability and they must not
commit the cardinal sin of appearing smarter than the average
person.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the U.S. Senate race for New York,'' Wasserstein
notes, ``Women have specific opinions about Hillary Clinton. What's
interesting is they have very strong opinions about someone they
don't know. So you're dealing with people who should excel at their
jobs, be able to win a beauty contest, then be professional,
competent and a wonderful hostess. Who can do that?
</P>
<P>
   ``Lyssa Dent Hughes is a good, serious person. Is she
immediately likeable? Would you meet this girl and say, `Gee I wish
she was hosting my talk show? She really should take over from
Kathie Lee.' Do you really want a surgeon general who could take
over from Kathie Lee?''
</P>
<P>
   Two interesting sub plots _ illustrating the ways two different
kinds of women view success _ frame Lyssa's story. Her marriage is
in jeopardy from one of them. Quincy Quince (Blake Lindsley) is
Lyssa's husband's most promising student. She is also a wannabe
pundit _ (sort of Arianna Huffington crossed with Camille Paglia)
who uses Lyssa's difficulties to seduce her husband (``Picket
Fence's'' Tom Skerritt) and launch her own TV career.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's another woman of achievement, Lyssa's best friend
Judith Kaufman, played by the wonderful Lynn Thigpen (``Law and
Order''), who won a Tony for the same role on Broadway as a black,
Jewish oncologist whose difficulty having children almost drives
her to suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Lyssa is appalled: ``What gives you the audacity to believe
you've failed if you can't make life or stop death?'' she demands
of Judith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I was taught if I was a good girl and worked hard, I
could,'' Judith answers.
</P>
<P>
   Wasserstein says that is the crux of her story.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a story about the good girls who worked hard and what
happens when you come up against something where working hard and
being a good girl isn't enough.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.)
</P>
<P>
   (EDITOR: For further information on ``American Daughter,''
consult the Lifetime Web site at www.lifetimetv.com. And don't
forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features.
</P>
