<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5384 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-ENGAGEMENT-COL     05-25 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-ENGAGEMENT-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEAR OF DROWNING LEADS TO DOUBLE ENGAGEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Thursday, May 25, or thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of the ROEPER-COLUMN.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oh man. Oh come on. That's really not fair.
</P>
<P>
   How could these women do that to those guys, making them agree
to marriage when their lives were in danger! Talk about
manipulative.
</P>
<P>
   Two couples got engaged April 20th _ but it wasn't one of those
deals involving rings dropped in champagne glasses or guys dropping
to their knees or a surprise message showing up on a baseball
scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   It was fear of drowning that set up this double engagement.
</P>
<P>
   The scene: Bryan Henegar and five friends were bobbing in the
Gulf of Mexico, about 14 miles offshore, after Henegar's boat sank.
For 11 hours, they fought off hypothermia and fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to die tonight, aren't I?'' said Mary Jane Grau,
Henegar's girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to die tonight!'' proclaimed Henegar, just
like Leonardo DiCaprio's Jack said in ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   But Grau played a card that even Rose didn't try with Jack in
that most romantic of movies, saying, ``If I don't die tonight,
we're going to get married.''
</P>
<P>
   I would have tried to change the subject. Something like, ``Boy,
that little Elian really was a tough cookie to survive in this
stuff, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Henegar's a better man than I am. He may have been literally
treading water but he stopped treading water, relationship-wise.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK!'' he said. ``When we get out, we'll get married.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, like Jerry Seinfeld getting engaged because George
Costanza got engaged, Henegar's buddy Bill Daughtery made the same
pledge to his girlfriend: ``You know what, Kathy? I'll marry you.
We're all going to get married.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course they were rescued a few hours later. The caption in
the Chicago Sun-Times under a picture of Grau and Henegar: ``Mary
Jane Grau is comforted by fiance Bryan Henegar at a Florida Coast
Guard Station ...''
</P>
<P>
   See that dude, now you're labeled. Now you're a fiance.
</P>
<P>
   A double wedding ceremony is planned for Labor Day weekend and I
wish everyone the best, but can you imagine the scene if things
don't work out down the line?
</P>
<P>
   Grau: ``I wish I never married you in the first place, you
jerk!''
</P>
<P>
   Henegar: ``Well whose idea was it to get engaged? I'm clinging
to a freakin' life preserver and you're talking commitment!''
</P>
<P>
   Grau: ``You didn't have to say yes!''
</P>
<P>
   Henegar: ``I thought I was going to DIE. Who knew?''
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic engagement does not guarantee wedded bliss. Not
that I have any expertise in this area other than two decades of
spectating, but I'm more partial to what I've always called the
Chicago Irish Guy Wedding Proposal, though the scenario translates
to many other ethnic and cultural backgrounds. It goes something
like this:
</P>
<P>
   Guy meets gal in neighborhood hood pub, a few months after
they've both graduated college. They start dating.
</P>
<P>
   He lives with four buddies, who really don't care if their pal
has a girlfriend, as long as he can still play on the softball,
rugby and flag football teams. And show up for darts on Thurdays at
McHiccupy's.
</P>
<P>
   She has a roommate who doesn't like him. He doesn't care for the
roommate, often making insulting jokes about the fact that she's a
volleyball coach who doesn't shave her legs and listens to Melissa
Etheridge all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the romance blooms. Flowers and dinners and kisses
and hand-holding and happy attendance at family functions.
</P>
<P>
   After that the relationship settles into a comfortable groove.
Bathroom doors are left open and Blockbuster nights outnumber
dinner dates at places with names like Trattoria Expensiva, and
when she asks if he'd like to attend a Mother's Day brunch at 10
a.m., he laughs and says, ``Did you just forget about the Mark
O'Meara putting special on ESPN-26? Like I'm going to miss that.''
</P>
<P>
   His buddies ride him about missing the annual Western Avenue Pub
Crawl. Her roommate asks if he could please not put his feet on the
coffee table.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of year two, she asks how long they're going to
continue as boyfriend and girlfriend. He says, ``Um, six to nine
years?''
</P>
<P>
   Wrong answer. Breakup time.
</P>
<P>
   Her roommate rejoices. His buddies say stuff like, ``You're not
seeing what's-her-name any more? Great, the Bears are home Sunday
and we've got an extra ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   About six months later, he's at McHiccupy's when she walks in
with a date _ a nice lawyer with a BMW parked outside.
</P>
<P>
   He makes a scene. She storms off. He calls her 57 times. After
much drama and lots of crying _ mostly on his part _ they reunite.
</P>
<P>
   A year goes by. And then one morning, after, well, you know, she
says: ``Hope you enjoyed that, buster, because it's the last time
we're doing it unless we get engaged.''
</P>
<P>
   He considers his options and says, says, ``OK, OK, pick out a
ring.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's the right way to get engaged.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for
the Chicago Sun-Times and the author, most recently, of ``Urban
Legends: The Truth Behind All Those Deliciously Entertaining Myths
That Are Absolutely, Positively, 100% Not True!'' Roeper is also a
commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has appeared on programs
such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News with Dan Rather,''
``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'') &LR;
</P>
