u v BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     05-25 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Thursday, May 25, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS:  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Friday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MISSING-ATHEIST (Austin, Texas) _ The world's most famous
atheist was spotted in a restaurant in Romania, stuffing herself
with pasta more than two years after federal agents claim she was
murdered in Texas, a Baptist preacher has testified. By JOHN
MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   CISNEROS-SCHOOLS (Los Angeles) _ The only Latino board member of
the Los Angeles United School District can't hide her glee at the
possibility of recruiting Henry Cisneros to run the nation's
second-largest school system. But Cisneros says he doesn't want to
be recruited. By JEANNE RUSSELL.
</P>
<P>
   COURTS-CASELOADS (San Antonio) _ Overloaded with smugglers and
undocumented immigrants caught along the Rio Grande, the federal
courts from San Antonio to El Paso together shouldered more felony
cases last year than any other region in the nation, data show. By
MARO ROBBINS.
</P>
<P>
   CIGARETTE-SALES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Cigarette sales fell
drastically since an additional 55-cent-per-pack excise tax made
New York smokers the most heavily taxed in the nation, according to
new state data. As sales dropped, state reports show that revenues
from the higher tax grew slightly to $64.6 million in April,
compared with $63.1 million in April 1999. By JAMES ODATO.
</P>
<P>
   STATE-ALCOHOL (Austin, Texas) _ Health advocates concerned about
underage drinking want the Texas Department of Parks and Wildlife
to get rid of alcohol and cigarette advertisements in the annual
guide to the state's hunting and fishing rules. By RUSSELL GOLD.
</P>
<P>
   MINNAMON-OBIT (Undated) _ Pamela Knight Minnamon, whose photo as
a young girl appeared on packages of Kodak's popular Brownie
cameras, died at her home in Tucson, Ariz. Minnamon, who was 68,
died at her home of cancer, said her husband, Paul Minnamon. By
CARMINA DANINI.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ At this time of year, one
statistic that is widely quoted _ and extremely deceptive _ is that
the typical female worker earns about 75 cents for every dollar
that a man earns. In a sense, it's a great statistic because you
can use it to support just about anything you want. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   HOLOCAUST-INSURANCE (San Francisco) _ Four children of people
killed or persecuted during the Holocaust have filed suit against
one of Europe's largest insurance companies, claiming the firm _
Assicurazioni Generali _ has failed to honor policies purchased by
their parents, grandparents and uncles. By MICHAEL DOUGAN.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   VERSATILE-BISCOTTI (San Antonio) _ Biscotti, those crunchy,
twice-baked cookies, usually appeal to our sweet tooth. But they
have their savory side as well. Think, for instance, of a crisp
Parmesan and sun-dried tomato biscotto served for dipping into a
bowl of homemade minestrone. By BONNIE WALKER.
</P>
<P>
   IMPROVISE-COOK (San Antonio) _ A good cook, like the U.S. Marine
Rangers in the Clint Eastwood movie ``Heartbreak Ridge,'' has to be
able to ``adapt, improvise and overcome'' when faced with a cooking
surprise. Here's an example. By RALPH WININGHAM.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER-CLOTHES (San Antonio) _ Summer play clothes don't have to
be fancy. Just be sure they suit the game and combine pizzazz with
practicality. Summer fun begins at home. By MARY BUDGE.
</P>
<P>
   KNITTING (Albany, N.Y.) _ The two middle-aged women entered St.
Peter's Hospital looking as if they were bound for a church bazaar
or country fair, plastic shopping bags bulging with crocheted
blankets, knit sweaters and caps in pastel hues. Passers-by paid
little attention. Which is how these self-described ``yarn ladies''
like it. By PAUL GRONDAHL.
</P>
<P>
   ERIE-CANAL (Albany, N.Y.) _ One hundred and seventy-five years
ago, when it was officially opened, the Erie Canal spurred what
might be considered the e-commerce revolution of its day. The
363-mile ``artificial river'' with 83 locks and 18 aqueducts
altered the nation's economy practically overnight. By PAUL
GRONDAHL.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAR-INDY-GORDON (Indianapolis) _ For all the naysayers
questioning Robby Gordon's second attempt to drive the Indianapolis
500 and the Coca-Cola 600, the Winston Cup regular has just one
word: Baja. Gordon, 31, has driven the famed Baja 1000 race solo on
several occasions and shrugs his shoulders when asked about this
weekend's attempt at the Indy 500 and the Coca-Cola 600. By LEE
SCHEIDE.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-INDY-WATTLES (Indianapolis) _ The battles have always been
from within for Stan Wattles, growing up with dyslexia, dysgraphia
and perception difficulties. Nothing, however, prepared him for May
1, 1999, and the depths to which he would have to plunge to soothe
his soul. By LEE SCHEIDE.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-GIANTS-ROMP (San Francisco) _ The San Francisco Giants
whomped Montreal 18-0, the most one-sided shutout in Giants history
going back to 1900. Even the pitcher hit a grand slam homerun. By
FRANK BLACKMAN.
</P>
<P>
   FLY-FISHING (Albany, N.Y.) _ Even for the most experienced
dry-fly fisherman, the timer starts ticking and the Adrenalin kicks
in when the hatch materializes. The angler has little time to
determine which mayfly or caddis fly it is that's rising; more
importantly, which is particularly interesting to those dimpling
trout. The strategy has to be settled, and fast. At which phase of
the mayfly's well-known cycle will the fisherman attempt to imitate
the natural? On the bottom, under the surface, on the surface, or
falling from the sky after mating? Each phase has its own patterns
of artificial imitations of fur and feathers, threads and snippets.
By FRED LeBRUN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ It's hard to think of a more
appropriate tribute to the life of John Jacobs than a moment of
silence in the California Legislature, a moment of silence called
Wednesday morning by a choked-up John Burton. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   DRUNKEN-DRIVERS (Albany, N.Y.) _ The debate about gun control
rages from left to right. One side marches on Washington. The other
side blitzes the airwaves with ads. But more people are killed in a
year alcohol-related accidents than are murdered. It's time we
treat the combination of a drunk and a car as a lethal weapon, not
an accident. By STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
</TEXT>
