<HEADLINE>
$ADV03 
 FOR RELEASE SAT., JUNE 3, 2000 
 DRIVE IT FOREVER
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by DRIVE IT FOREVER clients. Nonsubscribers
can use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, see end of text. 
 By BOB SIKORSKY 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Bob: I recently purchased a 1996 Buick Roadmaster station
wagon. A month after I bought it, I saw an article in Consumer
Reports' April 2000 issue that lists the 1996 Buick Roadmaster as
one of its ``Used Cars To Avoid.'' Just my luck.
</P>
<P>
   Since I bought it, maybe you can tell me what I should be
concerned about. Thank you. I.H. Conroy, Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, if you had looked a little further in that same issue
you'd have come across its ``Used-Car Reliability'' section, which
features Frequency-of-Repair charts. According to Consumer Reports,
the 1996 Roadmaster shows above average repairs on its cooling and
electrical systems and above average problems with its hardware
(door handles, knobs etc.)
</P>
<P>
   However its engine, exhaust and body rust ratings are tops,
followed closely by a good rating for its A/C system. It rates
average in fuel, ignition, transmission, suspension, brakes,
paint/trim and integrity categories.
</P>
<P>
   So its overall rating may not be as bad as it seems. Remember
the ``Used Cars To Avoid'' list is compiled from reader responses
to Consumer Reports' 1999 Annual Questionnaire, the same source
that the Frequency-of-Repair data was taken from. While these lists
can be helpful when you're in the market for a used car, they are
not the opinion of experts nor are they infallible.
</P>
<P>
   Let me put it this way: I have driven a vehicle that was and
still is rated poor by Consumer Reports. Turns out that it's one of
the most trouble-free, dependable vehicles I have ever owned.
Bottom line, keep an eye on the areas that are singled out as
problem areas, otherwise, just enjoy your Buick.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Bob: I own a 1985 Chevy that has 50,000 miles on it. My
problem is a whining sound that is more pronounced in colder
weather. The whining is also much louder when I turn the steering
wheel.
</P>
<P>
   I have been told that it has nothing to do with the power
steering. Steve Sciani, East Rockaway, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. On the contrary, my friend, it IS the power steering unit
that is doing all the whining. GM has had problems with the power
steering units on early and mid-'80s vehicles and has even issued a
recall on many of them to have the problem fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Your vehicle's symptoms are classic: whining, exacerbated by
cold weather and increasing when the power steering unit is put to
work (that is, when the steering wheel is turned). Check with your
GM dealer to see if you can still have your vehice repaired under
the conditions of the original recall.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Bob: I've heard so many conflicting stories on what an
oxygen sensor does. I've even heard that it isn't really necessary
and one can disconnect it and still get good performance from a
vehicle. Can you please give me the real dope on oxygen sensors?
Wayne Pratt, Longview, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A. An oxygen sensor is a feedback sensor usually located at some
point in the exhaust manifold or exhaust pipe. It continuously
samples the amount of oxygen (that's why it's called an oxygen or
O2 sensor!) in the exhaust stream. Its job is to relay timely
(microsecond to microsecond) information to the engine control
module (computer) about the condition of the air/fuel ratio being
supplied to the engine. On receipt of this information the engine's
computer makes adjustments of the air/fuel ratio to keep it at
maximum efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Because the engine depends on the O2 sensor's feedback for the
most efficient air/fuel setting, it is vital to the car's overall
performance, efficiency and emissions control. Without it,
emissions would soar, fuel economy would drop and engine
performance would be reduced. Disconnecting the O2 sensor is like
messing with the air supply of a deep sea diver _ who may still be
able to operate, but at much lower efficiency than with a constant
supply of fresh air.
</P>
<P>
   With the advent of On Board Diagnostics II, or OBDII, the most
up-to-date emissions control and engine management system, an
additional oxygen sensor has been added on the downstream side of
the catalytic converter. It monitors the efficiency of the
catalytic converter by comparing the amount of oxygen in the inlet
and exhaust sides of the converter. This information also is
relayed to the engine control module for further processing.
</P>
<P>
   Amazing stuff all of this, and to think we take it all for
granted. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Sikorsky, a national-award-winning journalist who has
written several best-selling automotive books, is a consultant in
that field and a member of the Society of Automotive Engineers and
of the Society of Tribologists and Lubrication Engineers. Questions
or comments of general interest should be addressed to Bob
Sikorsky, care of this newspaper. Bob Sikorsky regrets that he
cannot answer questions individually.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
