<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARN THE ESSENTIALS BEFORE YOU AIM FOR A JOB AT MICROSOFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREA AHLES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do you want a job at Microsoft, the software giant in Seattle?
Even though the company might be broken up by the federal
government?
</P>
<P>
   If you answered ``yes'' to the above questions, then pick up a
copy of Rebecca Smith's new book, ``The Unofficial Guide to Getting
a Job at Microsoft'' (McGraw-Hill, 192 pages, $16.95).
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft gets about 12,000 resumes a month, with 70 percent
arriving electronically, so making yours stand out from the crowd
is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   But don't despair if you are not a computer programmer, because
Microsoft has hundreds of jobs _ in areas such as finance,
accounting and furniture design _ that are not directly related to
writing software coding, Smith wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has about 33,000 employees worldwide, but at any given
time there are between 1,000 to 2,000 unfilled positions.
</P>
<P>
   Although Smith gives some generic tips on how to submit a
top-notch resume, the strength of the book is its details about
Microsoft and what sort of workers it is looking for.
</P>
<P>
   Smith spends several chapters describing the ``culture of
Microsoft,'' clearly to help job seekers decide if Microsoft is the
right company for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, there is only one Microsoft,'' Smith writes.
``There is no other company on par with Microsoft in the world.
Joining the Microsoft culture is clearly not a task for the
uninformed or for those content with scoring less than 100 on a
scale of 0 to 100.''
</P>
<P>
   There is enough history about Microsoft to give readers a sense
of where the company came from and where it is headed with its new
mission to ``empower people through great software, anytime, any
place, on any device.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith discusses six core competencies that Microsoft believes
are essential for all job positions: passion for products and
technology; smarts; drive; ability to adapt to change; ability to
get the right things done; and ability to learn and apply new
knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   The author lists top executives and describes business units
within Microsoft where a potential applicant may find a position.
She also provides brief summaries of the business divisions, such
as the Worldwide Enterprise Group, the Business Solutions Group and
the Education Customer Unit.
</P>
<P>
   But like any print book about Microsoft, ``The Unofficial
Guide'' is not up-to-date with the recent Microsoft news. It still
lists Bill Gates as chief executive, even though he gave the title
to Microsoft President Steve Ballmer in January.
</P>
<P>
   The book lists several Web sites where job seekers can find
positions posted and mailing addresses of Microsoft's regional
offices where resumes may be sent.
</P>
<P>
   Smith suggests updating education or training by enrolling in
Microsoft programs, including the Microsoft Sales Specialist
program or the Microsoft Certified Professional credential. The
author briefly discusses internships at Microsoft and how the
company uses contingent staffing.
</P>
<P>
   Smith spends a portion of the text on how to get through a
Microsoft interview, noting that there is no right or wrong answer
to most of the open-ended questions Microsoft poses, such as, ``How
do you test a toaster?''
</P>
<P>
   She lists the types of questions Microsoft asks by category and
how to possibly answer those types of questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real truth is, Microsoft is not looking for your ability
to memorize hundreds of answers to technical questions,'' Smith
wrote. ``Microsoft interviewers are there to see how smart you are,
what excites you, and how you solve problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith also discusses some of the company's employee compensation
plans, including its new ``Compensation 2000,'' which offers 65
percent higher compensation to employees than what other software
companies are offering.
</P>
<P>
   The book is a quick read, one time through, but will best serve
the Microsoft job seeker who reads it multiple times and takes
notes in relevant sections.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is direct and to the point in describing Microsoft,
offering up her book as a primer for getting hired at the No. 1
software company in the world.
</P>
<P>
   (Andrea Ahles reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7695, or e-mail:
aahles(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
