<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUNKEN-DRIVERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GUN CONTROL? WHAT ABOUT DRUNKEN-DRIVER CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Enough already.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it time to stop the killing?
</P>
<P>
   The debate rages from left to right. Gun control. The right to
bear arms. One side marches on Washington. The other side blitzes
the airwaves with ads. The networks, the newspapers, the news
magazines all feed on the frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   So much killing, killing and more killing. Senseless killing.
Somebody has to do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad the national dialogue is about the set of somethings.
But then, why let facts get in the way of a story that doesn't
further enough agendas?
</P>
<P>
   Malik Sealy _ Bronx native, one-time Mr. Basketball of New York,
former St. John's star, starting forward for the Minnesota
Timberwolves _ made the tragic transformation from
husband/father/teammate to cold statistic early Saturday morning.
He died just as surely and violently as if somebody had pointed a
gun in his face and pulled the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   Sealy was on his way home from a celebration of teammate Kevin
Garnett's 24th birthday when his 1993 Range Rover collided head-on
with a pickup truck. The driver of the pickup, 43-year-old
Souksangouane Phengsene, was going the wrong way on Highway 100 in
suburban Minneapolis at the time. The Minnesota State Patrol
arrested Phengsene in his hospital room Monday on charges of
criminal vehicular homicide.
</P>
<P>
   A rescue worker reported smelling alcohol on Phengsene at the
scene. Investigators have not yet received the results of blood
tests on Phengsene, who already has a 1997 conviction for drunken
driving. He paid a $500 fine and spent one year on probation and
...
</P>
<P>
   That's it. That's all. If convicted of vehicular homicide,
Phengsene would face a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   That's it. That's all.
</P>
<P>
   For abruptly ending the life of a 30-year-old man who had so
much going for him. Father of a 3-year-old son, Remi. Newlywed
husband to a former St. John's cheerleader. Popular, respected
teammate on an NBA playoff team. Businessman who had just opened a
recording studio, Baseline Records, in New York. Family man who
operated a tie-designing business with a brother and sister.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Sealy left St. John's, he was the school's No. 2
all-time scorer (behind Chris Mullin). Sealy drifted through three
NBA cities in six seasons before finding a comfortable niche in
Minnesota. He averaged 11.3 points this past season on a
career-high 47.6-percent shooting, helping the Timberwolves to a
franchise-best 50-32 record. The franchise player, Garnett, wore
No. 21 because he idolized Sealy from the St. John's days.
</P>
<P>
   The trip home from Garnett's birthday celebration ended at 4:07
a.m. The skid marks at the scene of the accident were so short,
investigators suspect neither driver had time to veer out of the
way. Sealy probably never knew what hit him.
</P>
<P>
   He died alone, at the scene. But he has way, way too much
company. There were 15,935 alcohol-related traffic fatalities in
1998. One out of every nine intoxicated drivers involved in those
fatal crashes had a prior conviction for driving while under the
influence of alcohol within the previous three years. The FBI
reports that in that same year, there were 14,088 murders. Of those
homicides, 9,143 involved firearms.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the debate of the day is about gun control. What about
drunks-behind-the-wheel-of-a-car control?
</P>
<P>
   Only 23 states classify driving under the influence as a felony.
In some of those states, it takes as many as four DWI convictions
before the offender heads into felony territory. New York
classifies the second and subsequent offenses within 10 years as a
felony.
</P>
<P>
   Enough already.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it? Isn't it time to do more to stop the killing?
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 19, 1998, St. Louis Rams linebacker Leonard Little was
out on the town celebrating his 24th birthday. He slammed into a
car driven by a 47-year-old St. Louis woman, Susan Gutweiler,
leaving a husband without a wife and a 15-year-old son without a
mother. Little pleaded guilty to involuntary manslaughter and
received a sentence of 90 days in jail, four years of probation and
1,000 hours of community service.
</P>
<P>
   That's not enough. Why, Little even played in the Super Bowl
this past January. It's long past time to start taking drunken
driving as seriously as it should be. Public service announcements
_ ``Friends don't let friends drive drunk'' _ aren't going to get
the job done.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody who climbs behind the wheel drunk is playing Russian
Roulette with the lives of others. Just because it's legal to
drink, and just because it's legal to drive, doesn't mean the laws
should nod and wink at anybody who drinks and drives at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   Enough already. Isn't it? Isn't it time to quit getting caught
up in the wrong debate and do something to stop the killing? Isn't
it time to fight back against the DrunkDrivingDefense.com forces?
</P>
<P>
   Stop giving drunken drivers third and fourth chances. Treat the
combination of a drunk and a car as a lethal weapon, not an
accident. Revoke a license for 10 years on the first conviction for
driving drunk. Tack on a felony conviction _ and stiff prison
sentence _ to anybody caught trying to drive with a revoked
license.
</P>
<P>
   Get tough. Get serious. Either that, or learn to live with the
possibility of becoming a cold body and colder statistic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 1229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
