<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 12:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5396 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-25 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CALIFORNIA POLITICS SUFFERS A GREAT LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's hard to think of a more appropriate tribute
to the life of John Jacobs than a moment of silence in the
California Legislature, a moment of silence called Wednesday
morning by a choked-up John Burton.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just that Jacobs wrote the definitive book, ``A Rage
for Justice,'' on Burton's late brother, Rep. Phillip Burton, who
saved the landscape of the Bay Area and remade the political
landscape of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just that Jacobs wrote the definitive piece, ``The
Making of a Comeback,'' on the struggle that went into John Burton
becoming president pro tem of the state Senate, among Jacobs' many
definitive political columns.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just that Jacobs, the political editor of McClatchy
Newspapers and former political writer for the San Francisco
Examiner, was one of the best in the business, respected by
everyone he wrote about. That is, with the exception of Clint
Reilly and a few other political consultants.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, the Legislature desperately needed a moment of
silence.
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday's embarrassing uproar about Insurance Commissioner
Chuck Quackenbush, everybody in Sacramento could use a week of
silence to reflect on the humane and democratic values Jacobs stood
for.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what Jacobs would have written about Quackenbush's
strange showdown with state Sen. Jackie Speier's insurance
committee, but that was one of the great things about his column.
You never knew what he'd write, except it would be insightful.
</P>
<P>
   He understood the nuances and nastiness of personality conflict,
ambush and counter-ambush. But he also never forgot what insurance
commissioners and legislators are paid to do. Namely, serve the
people.
</P>
<P>
   He wouldn't forget that politicians are as flawed as the people
they represent, but he wouldn't sink into cynicism and write them
off as an innately comical or criminal class.
</P>
<P>
   In times like this, the times of Gore and Bush, Davis and
Quackenbush, I wish John were around to call.
</P>
<P>
   There I was, an ordinary guy, watching the television news and a
political pro wrestling match, perhaps called ``The Quackster
Strikes Back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Quackster'' _ that's what they call Quackenbush in
Sacramento. It's the kind of cheap nickname that would never make
it into a column by John Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush walked into Speier's committee battered by charges
of misusing his office and being cozy with the insurance companies
he's supposed to regulate. Then, in a quick turnaround, he
pile-drived his tormentors with an incriminating e-mail,
triumphantly escaping the arena until the rematch.
</P>
<P>
   Pro wrestling _ that's the way many of us see politics. Jacobs
saw politics as baseball, as something complicated, real and
elegant in its slow way.
</P>
<P>
   Television is where most Americans learn what little they know
about politics. There are diminishing numbers of political writers
like Jacobs capable of understanding it as a human process, and
describing it in understandable ways.
</P>
<P>
   The Quackenbush fiasco, as shown on the news, seemed designed to
drive Californians into deeper political withdrawal. Without a
political writer to explain the drama, all TV showed was the flash
and shouting of WWF performed in suits.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush, who bears a striking resemblance to Niedermeier,
the ROTC commander in the movie ``Animal House'' (again, Jacobs
wouldn't say that), flummoxed Speier by reading a year-old e-mail
to her chief aide filled with advice about how to ``ambush'' the
insurance commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   One word is all it takes sometimes _ and when will people stop
using e-mail? That's what the average TV viewer, unaided by good
political analysis, came away with. As well as a bad taste in the
mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Speier told reporters she knew what an ambush really was, and
the TV showed footage of the airstrip ambush in which Speier was
wounded by Jim Jones' henchmen.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush's lawyer answered a question by saying, ``In the
immortal words of Teddy Kennedy, we'll cross that bridge when we
come to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, there was no tape of the Chappaquiddick bridge.
Still, this was sound bite journalism at its least toothsome.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs would have dug deeper than the distasteful surface of
this one.
</P>
<P>
   But Jacobs was never afraid to tell uncomfortable truths
straight out. In re-reading old columns of his, I found one from
three years ago about a public fiasco more notorious than anything
involving Chuck Quackenbush _ Jack Davis' birthday party with its
sadomasochistic sex show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the reportage that followed focused, predictably, on
the raunch and the sleaze, on who attended and when they left,''
Jacobs wrote. ``But there are deeper questions here that haven't
been raised: How did Jack Davis, a political thug, accumulate so
much power? Why was an invitation to his party so eagerly sought?''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs then described the political vacuum created in the
mid-1980s as strong San Francisco politicians ``died off or
disengaged,'' and consultants like Davis, ``answerable to no one,''
filled the vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   Being answerable to someone. That's the essence of our system of
government. Davis was at least answerable to Jacobs, and for the
sake of Jacobs' native city.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs ended his column, ``Davis is a living example of Lord
Acton's adage that power corrupts. But that doesn't mean an entire
city has to mirror his corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs was a tough guy, but a fair guy and usually right. I will
miss him terribly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
