<P>
   NY-JAZZ-FESTIVALS (New York) _ June is almost upon us, and jazz
clubs, independent concert producers and the big jazz festivals are
wrangling for the attention of New Yorkers. This means a bounty for
anyone interested in jazz (with Latin music, gospel and soul as
connected satellite genres) as the city becomes one big unofficial
festival, the best and most complete in the world. By Ben Ratliff.
</P>
<P>
   BAROQUE-ARCHITECTURE (Washington) _ ``The Triumph of the
Baroque,'' now on view at the National Gallery of Art, is a survey
of European architecture from 1600 to 1750 that reveals that
buildings, like people, can be overtaken by mass hysteria. For a
century and a half, European walls, doors, roofs, windows and
entire cities were contorted into quivering, writhing shapes. By
Herbert Muschamp.
</P>
<P>
   CHASE-PARRISH-ARTWORK (New York) _ William Merritt Chase and
Maxfield Parrish, a generation apart, were in their day very
popular artists. They had little else in common until the present
event: the conjunction of their current shows at the Brooklyn
Museum of Art. By Grace Glueck.
</P>
<P>
   MESOPOTAMIA-ARTWORK (New York) _ Anyone who has taken an
introductory survey of Western art has seen images of the works
that star in ``Treasures From the Royal Tombs at Ur,'' a sumptuous
exhibition at the Morgan Library. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   GREENAWAY-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Peter Greenaway's newest film,
``8{ Women,'' is, among other things, a homage to Federico
Fellini's 1963 masterpiece ``8{,'' fragments of which are shown
early in the movie. Reviewed by Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Takeshi Kitano, the director of
``Kikujiro,'' has been widely acclaimed for his violent, meditative
yakuza (gangster) movies, which explore the bloody deeds and uneasy
consciences of members of Japan's legendary criminal underworld.
Reviewed by A.O. Scott.
</P>
