<HEADER>
A5410 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l BC-RAPE-ONLINE-HELP-LADN     05-25 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAPE-ONLINE-HELP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE HELP FOR RAPE VICTIMS
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: For use after May 29, 2000. This story is being transmitted
early to accomodate holiday schedules.) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though its name contains the word ``rape'' and the
emergency code 911, this newly launched Web site is meant to be a
safe harbor for victims of sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Rape Treatment Center (RTC) at Santa
Monica-UCLA Medical Center are hoping the Web site,
www.911rape.org, will be comforting and useful to rape victims _
both locally and throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most rapes are never reported and most victims never tell
anyone,'' said Gail Abarbanel, director of the 26-year-old RTC.
``And the reason they don't tell anyone is because, to get any kind
of help, you have to really expose your identity. Some of them are
so ashamed they can't even speak about what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opportunity that never existed before because now
they can access the information with total anonymity.''
</P>
<P>
   The sub-sections of the site contain information specially
geared toward teens and a section for college students _ one of the
groups at highest risk of sexual assault. Site visitors can learn
about ``rape drugs,'' hear survivor stories, order information
materials and learn about treatment and their legal and medical
options.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting the site is a first step, says Abarbanel. After looking
over the information, a rape victim can decide whether to contact a
local crisis center or hotline, go to the police, or not take
further action. The site is designed to be a resource for victims
even if the assault took place years in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site received a launch party last week at the Bel Air
home of Paramount Motion Pictures Chairman Sherry Lansing. Lansing,
who produced the 1988 movie ``The Accused'' about a rape victim,
has long been a friend of the RTC. Appearing with Abarbanel at the
launch party was actor David Schwimmer, who has filmed a number of
rape awareness promos for NBC and who is on the RTC's board of
directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents look at the 'Net as an incomprehensible and
terrifying monster, and that's true,'' said Schwimmer, wearing a
white www.911rape.org T-shirt. ``We can also utilize it as a new
and powerful tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new site offers hopefully what people need _ a safe,
anonymous first step.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwimmer agreed to do the promos after Abarbanel visited the
set of his sitcom ``Friends'' and asked if any of the cast members
would be willing to help with outreach efforts. He later learned
his parents had been supporters of the organization for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire Gail's commitment and her work so much, and in the
past several years, I've come to know that some of my former
girlfriends and friends have been victims of rape,'' said Schwimmer
who has helped with RTC outreach programs that target college
students.
</P>
<P>
   Liability restrictions prohibit site operators from making
www.911rape.org an interactive site. Legally, all RTC officials can
do is post the number and address for their organization and for
rape crisis resources such as the Rape, Abuse and Incest National
Network (RAINN, 800-656-4673). Site visitors can then choose to
contact the RTC, RAINN or local resources directly. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 1249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
