<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5414 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l BC-YOGA-KIDS-LADN &LR;      05-25 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOGA-KIDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG LIVES TAKING SOME TWISTS AND TURNS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It almost sounds like the punch line of a New Yorker cartoon:
``Sorry, I'm afraid little Johnny can't come over to play after
school tomorrow. His sun salutations are weak, and I've grounded
him until he masters the up dog stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   But yoga for the young is no joke; nor is it strictly a matter
of new age parents schlepping their wee ones along to twice weekly
meditation sessions hoping some good karma will rub off. Claiming
the activities hold numerous benefits for growth and development,
instructors are teaching various forms of yoga _ including poses,
stretches and guided imagery _ to children of pre-school,
elementary school age and and even to those in the teen years.
</P>
<P>
   Programs based on the principles of Iyengar yoga _ one of the
oldest forms of the craft in existence _ have been incorporated
into an after-school program at the Gardener Avenue School in Los
Angeles. Once a week, students ages 7 to 12 of all ethnic
backgrounds are bending, stretching and contorting, often at a pace
adults couldn't handle.
</P>
<P>
   And they're loving every minute of it.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, what the kids are doing is not the type of yoga that
you'll see in a traditional adult session. Often the pace will be
faster. Depending on the age range, an instructor may mix in
pretend games or play activities. The program, invented by Encino
pre-school instructor Leah Kalish, is called Imaginazium, which the
kids shorten to ``Imagics.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the name, you can guess which part of a child is getting a
workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's creative dramatics, it's physical play, imaginative play
and it's storytelling. The goal is to really support them in their
creative expression,'' says Kalish, a former actor and dancer who
teaches at three Neighborhood preschools in the San Fernando
Valley. ``They have unbelievable resources inside them. I just try
to create the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoga is often perceived as a meditative activity _ something we
don't often associate as being necessary for energy-stocked
children. But as both yoga instructors and child psychologists
point out, childhood can be a stressful time, and even the younger
set can often use a little bit of centering and focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen tremendous change in kids' bodies as well as in
their psyches,'' says Sue Garfield who has taught a weekly class
for ages 7 to 12 through the Iyengar Institute of Los Angeles since
1994. ``I've had several boys on Ritalin and it seems the yoga
absolutely calms them. The faster I can move them, the better they
do.'' New York-based instructor Lisa Trivell says yoga can help you
with other favorite activities. Both in her classes and her book
``I Can't Believe It's Yoga for Kids'' (Hatherleigh, $16.95),
Trivell links yoga stretches to sports activities. Into basketball?
Exercises like the down dog and warrior back stretches will help
get you ready to start crashing the boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember taking gym class in school, and they never
emphasized stretching enough. Everything was always very
competitive.'' says Trivell. ``My kids are into all sorts of
sports, and it's important for them to take time out and work on
their posture and breathing, to tune into the muscles that are
tight.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoga can also offer other benefits _ anything from helping
children overcome shyness, to improving physical coordination to
simply giving them a relaxation technique to build upon throughout
their lives. With yoga, Garfield says, the teen years may become
less stressful.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're losing their mind with the amount of homework they
get, and their parents have them totally overscheduled,'' says
Garfield. ``With the older kids, yoga is wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   !folo!``Rooaaaarrr!!!''
</P>
<P>
   It's Monday morning, shortly before lunch, at Imagics class at
The Neighborhood School in Studio City. Starting from a crouched
sphinx-like position, with their arms flat and palms down on the
floor, nine small lions spring forward toward the center of a
circle, cutting loose with an energetic growl. As they move into
the roaring position, their backs arch and they're up on their
hands as their legs stay flat behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rooaaaarrr!!!''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly a favorite among the 5- and 6-year-olds at the
Neighborhood School, the lion pose, spring and roar is repeated,
although not before one student tells his instructor he nearly
bumped his head on the last lunge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you'll have to be a lion that's a little more
coordinated than that,'' Leah Kalish says with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Lion is popular. So are Shark, Octopus, Frog and
Do-Nothing-Doll. Most activities aren't quite so noisy. A few
minutes after lion, Kalish's is the only voice that can be heard as
she guides her students _ eyes closed _ in pursuit of a butterfly
through a magic doorway and into a magic forest.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you wonder,'' Kalish tells the children, ``what's going to
happen today.''
</P>
<P>
   A 45-minute Imaginazium class will contain, at most, 20 minutes
of pure yoga, says Kalish. The rest is a mixture of imaginative
play, charades-like games and working with imagery. Everything
needs a context, and it needs to be playful to engage a child's
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Kalish's students will talk to her about what they experienced
during meditative exercises. Another popular activity is sending
rainbows, in which the children concentrate on sending positive
energy to a friend or loved one, energy which, Kalish says, will
invariably be felt by the recipient. Our thoughts, the lesson goes,
can affect the way other people feel.
</P>
<P>
   The children take the language and activities of Imaginazium
back home. Kalish is constantly hearing from parents who want to
know about the imaginative stories their children are asking to
hear. Children are now instructing their parents to center
themselves, breathe out or use finesse instead of force.
</P>
<P>
   Kalish teaches only a handful of classes, but her Imaginazium
program and the Yoga Kit for Kids has found its way into numerous
school. Guided imagery may be used by a teacher as part of a
special education class, or in the home as a favorite pre bedtime
activity to be used by a parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to create more products that teachers can use,'' says
Kalish who has produced a video and hopes eventually to do a TV
show. ``That's really much more my goal than having my own school.
I envision Imagics and the tools I create to build structures that
teachers and kids can use in the ways they need to and when they
need to.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Charlotte Reznick, an educational psychologist who works
with imagery says she has seen the therapeutic benefits of
activities that keep children in touch with their minds, bodies and
spirit. She recognizes the benefits of the kids who uses yoga
techniques.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a kid has basic self-esteem, he can become even more
confident,'' says Reznick, an assistant professor of clinical
psychology at UCLA's graduate program. ``Even Einstein used imagery
to create the theory of relativity. He pictured himself floating on
a light wave.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's betting he would have made a killer octopus. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
