<HEADLINE>
GOOD BUSINESS FOR COMPANIES TO HELP EMPLOYEE CARETAKERS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For most of us, balancing a professional life and family is
challenging enough. But how can we be expected to keep all the
balls in the air when we must also add the responsibility of taking
care of a parent or elderly relative?
</P>
<P>
   There won't be any quick fix answers offered at the Work, Family
and Eldercare Conference on Friday in Sherman Oaks. But the
gathering will give working caregivers and employers the
opportunity to meet and discuss common obstacles and goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have a mixed audience, primarily from employee
assistance programs (EAPs) within large companies,'' said Steven
Barlam, a social worker and the chief professional officer of
LivHOME, an L.A. based elder care management company. ``But the
community is absolutely invited.''
</P>
<P>
   Barlam will be one of 13 speakers at the conference. He'll share
the stage with _ among others _ Dr. Paula Dromi from the City of
Los Angeles Department of Aging; Irene Wechsler of Eldercare; Dr.
Terry Eagan, medical director of Sherman Oaks Hospital's Premier
program and L.A. City Councilman Michael Feur.
</P>
<P>
   Barlam, who will discuss his company's model of elder care, says
people 85 and older make up the fastest growing segment of the
population. By the end of the year, the one third of the nation's
work force is expected to be between the ages of 40 and 54. It is
people in this age range who will quickly be facing decisions
regarding elder care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our society has never really been geared toward how to address
this,'' said Barlam. ``Some companies are taking a leadership role
by coming up with meaningful benefits and services that add value
to caregivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Many large companies have employee assistance programs that
offer information and referral services. It is then up to the
employee to seek out his or her own resources.
</P>
<P>
   But until recently, an average business's assistance program
probably was better equipped to provide information relating to
issues such as substance abuse and/or child care rather than elder
care matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The elder care area is growing now. More and more EAP's are
getting requests for information,'' said Barlam. ``Some companies
are offering informal brown bag lunches as a way to provide
information. It can be very cost effective.''
</P>
<P>
   EAP related matters become part of a company's balancing act.
With the state unemployment and national unemployment rate at a low
point, company administrators need to keep their employees happy or
they risk losing them. Strong resources to help an employee address
child care or elder care matters can make a difference, according
to Barlam.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they invest money in terms of taking care of and nurturing
their employees, it can positively impact their bottom line,'' he
said. The Work, Family and Eldercare conference will be held Friday
from 8 a.m. to 4 p.m. at the Radisson Valley Center Hotel, 15433
Ventura Blvd. in Sherman Oaks. Registration is $38 in advance and
$45 at the door. For information, call (800) 266-9406.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
