A5425 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-KIKUJIRO-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      05-25 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIKUJIRO-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SPIN ON AN OLD TALE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Takeshi Kitano, the Japanese Renaissance tough guy who writes,
directs, edits and even makes animated drawings for the films he
stars in, says that he wanted to upset people's expectations with
his latest movie, ``Kikujiro.''
</P>
<P>
   Mission sort of accomplished. While this is certainly a gentler
effort than the bloody, absurdist gangster films, ``Hana-Bi'' and
``Sonatine,'' that have made his international reputation,
``Kikujiro'' has all the now recognizable, eccentric hallmarks of
Kitano's unique filmmaking style. It also sticks quite stubbornly
to the conventions of its sentimental genre, the grumpy old
coot/cute kid on-the-road movie.
</P>
<P>
   Kitano does pull some nice, unexpected riffs out of the
tried-and-true situation, and he manages to keep the tone nicely
hard-boiled until the final, inevitably oversweetened stretch. The
too-long film does get repetitive in places, but it has a large
enough supply of oddball ideas to remain engaging even at its most
predictable.
</P>
<P>
   Kitano's gruff title character is an irresponsible bum whose
fed-up wife essentially orders him to escort a sullen 9-year-old
neighbor, Masao (Yusuke Sekiguchi), to a faraway town. It's summer,
all the chubby kid's friends have left for family vacations, and
he's determined to meet the mother he's never known (Masao lives
with his well-meaning but boring grandmother).
</P>
<P>
   Kikujiro instantly blows Masao's travel money at the race track,
forcing the mismatched duo to make their way across Japan by any
means necessary. This means lots of hitchhiking encounters with
assorted colorful wanderers, including a hippie-like writer, a
pleasant young couple who go out of their way to entertain the boy,
and two unusually timid and manipulable bikers.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout their adventures, Kikujiro wheedles, browbeats,
deceives and otherwise annoys people into helping them out. Some of
the film's best comedy involves properly behaved people's quizzical
reactions to this aggressively vulgar man. He's not very sensitive
toward the kid, either, but of course they bond over time and
Kikujiro presumably grows into a better person while teaching Masao
useful, if rude, survival skills.
</P>
<P>
   You've seen it all before, in every combination and language,
starting somewhere around Chaplin and, for a recent example, in
``Central Station's'' Brazil, with a few thousand of those Japanese
Tora-San movies sandwiched in between (for a genuinely alarming
take on the genre, try to find radical Japanese director Nagisa
Oshima's 1969 ``Boy'').
</P>
<P>
   But you've never seen it quite the way Kitano films it, against
austerely framed, spatially intriguing landscapes and through
numerous trick shots (from inside a champagne glass, reflected in a
spinning hubcap, through a dragonfly's multifaceted point-of-view,
etc.).
</P>
<P>
   If we didn't know where all of this was going from the first
frame, ``Kikujiro'' would be an expectation confounder of the first
order. As it is, it's a good, fresh gloss on reassuring cliches. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The film: ``Kikujiro'' (PG-13; language, mild violence, nudity). &QL; 
The stars: Takeshi Kitano, Yusuke Sekiguchi. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Written and directed by Takeshi Kitano. Produced
by Masayuki Mori and Takio Yoshida. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 56 minutes. &QL; 
Playing: Colorado, Pasadena; Westside Pavilion, West L.A. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
