A5433 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-VERSATILE-BISCOTTI-HN     05-25 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERSATILE-BISCOTTI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BISCOTTO, A SWEET TREAT, CAN BE JUST AS SAVORY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BONNIE WALKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Biscotti, those crunchy, twice-baked cookies,
usually appeal to our sweet tooth. We dip them into our dessert
wine or espresso and enjoy them flavored with cinnamon or cardamom,
or flecked with candied ginger.
</P>
<P>
   But, they have their savory side as well. Think, for instance,
of a crisp Parmesan and sun-dried tomato biscotto (the singular of
biscotti) served for dipping into a bowl of homemade minestrone. A
romano cheese and black pepper biscotto would certainly upstage
crackers on an appetizer table with the bowl of green olive
tapenade. Or, a few slices, made with fresh rosemary, might
accompany a bowl of chilly gazpacho, a few slices of hard cheese
and a brisk white Italian wine _ a warm-weather supper worth
setting the table for.
</P>
<P>
   The savory biscotto is almost certainly an American innovation,
and one that opens up a whole new world of possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   But, the original biscotto is quintessentially Italian.
</P>
<P>
   ``The derivation of the word is from cotto which means cooked,
and bis, which means twice,'' says Carol Field, Italian food expert
and author, whose books include ``The Italian Baker,'' ``Italy in
Small Bites'' and ``Celebrating Italy.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the cookies we know as biscotti have been cooked twice.
The dough is first shaped into a loaf and baked, then it is sliced
and the individual slices are baked again.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, the word biscotto is also used as a general term to
apply to all cookies, says Field, who spoke from her home in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most famous biscotti are from Prato,'' says Field. This
cookie, made with almonds, vanilla and a little orange zest, are
the shape and taste we have come to associate with biscotti.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll keep for a long time. As they're traditionally made,
there is no shortening, not butter or oil. A lot of them now are
being made with shortening, though, to make them softer,'' Field
says.
</P>
<P>
   Biscotti, she noted, also tend to be regional, being far more
common in Northern Italy (where Prato is) than in the south.
</P>
<P>
   Ezio de Rosa, chef and owner of Grissini Ristorante Italiano in
San Antonio, says he knows the particularly hard, sliced biscotti,
usually studded with almonds, as ghiottini. (He also notes that the
practice of dipping the cookie into a cup of espresso or coffee
seems to be more common in other parts of Europe than it is in his
own region of the country.)
</P>
<P>
   As an avid biscotti maker, I can say this about the cookie: Yes,
the dough is hard to stir and it has to be baked, sliced, then
baked again, which takes some time.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, making this cookie, sweet or savory, is an
uncomplicated task.
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``The Il Fornia Baking Book,'' author Franco Galli
describes his solution for working with the stiffness of biscotti
dough. He uses a hand-held mixer set at medium speed until the
dough is a ``rough, shaggy mass.'' Then he kneads it with
flour-dusted hands in the bowl until all the ingredients are well
mixed, turns it out onto a pastry board and kneads for another
minute or so.
</P>
<P>
   Two other cookie makers, authors Barry Bluestein and Kevin
Morrissey, who wrote ``The Complete Cookie'' (Doubleday, $25),
recommend using a sturdy, wooden spoon and we assume, a muscular
stirring arm.
</P>
<P>
   Field says, ``I use a stand mixer _ it's easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Another discovery I've made about biscotti: If you've made them
once or twice, beware the urge to make them again _ and again.
</P>
<P>
   Last Christmas, after deciding homemade biscotti would be just
the thing to give my wine- and coffee-loving friends as gifts, I
made a batch or two of almond biscotti. Then, I thought toasted
hazelnut and dark chocolate would be a good combination and looked
up a recipe to adapt for these.
</P>
<P>
   When I was through, I didn't like the texture and so made
another batch varying the amounts of ingredients. Then, it occurred
to me that gingerbread biscotti would be appropriate for the
holidays and ... you get the picture. I was hooked.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the oregano and basil are thriving in the garden, as
fresh tomatoes and other vegetables begin to grow on the vine,
biscotti beckons again. This time, savory is the way to go.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few other tips for making biscotti:
</P>
<P>
   For sweet or savory biscotti, use parchment paper on your baking
sheets. While greasing the pans with butter works fine, parchment
paper makes handling and cleanup easier.
</P>
<P>
   Bluestein and Morrissey recommend doing the second baking with
the biscotti slices standing up for crisp cookies _ lay the slices
down and bake the second time for really brittle results.
</P>
<P>
   Others fresh herbs, such as oregano or sage (use sparingly), can
replace the rosemary. Other hard cheeses, such as romano, might
replace Parmesan. Spices such as cracked black pepper or red pepper
are good, too.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Bonnie Walker by e-mail at
bwalker1(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
