<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5434 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-IMPROVISE-COOK-HNS &LR;      05-25 0313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPROVISE-COOK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ONE WAY TO IMPROVISE IN THE KITCHEN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RALPH WININGHAM  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A good cook, like the U.S. Marine Rangers in the Clint Eastwood
movie ``Heartbreak Ridge,'' has to be able to ``adapt, improvise
and overcome'' when faced with a cooking surprise.
</P>
<P>
   I recently defrosted a package of meat labeled ``feral hog
backstrap'' only to find that venison steaks were inside the
freezer wrap.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for a pork-chop dinner had to be scrapped, and I went
searching through the kitchen pantry to find ingredients to salvage
the meal.
</P>
<P>
   The following recipe is what I created in about the time I would
have needed to grill the pork chops.
</P>
<P>
   Be sure to stir the mixture once or twice while it is simmering
to keep it from sticking to the skillet.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   MAKE THE BEST OF IT SKILLET
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds venison round steak
</P>
<P>
   Ralph's Spice Mix, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Seasoned flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup cooking oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 cups broken spaghetti noodles
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 can cream of mushroom soup
</P>
<P>
   1/2 soup-can milk
</P>
<P>
   Cut the steaks into one-inch cubes and season with spice mix
(use your own combination of salt, black pepper, etc., if you
like). Place seasoned meat cubes and seasoned flour in a plastic
bag and shake well to coat. Heat oil in a cast-iron skillet over
medium heat. Brown floured cubes on all sides and remove to a warm
platter. Add onion, garlic, spaghetti (broken into pieces about an
inch long) and sugar to skillet. Cook, turning often until onion is
transparent and spaghetti is slightly browned. Add soup and milk to
skillet, stir well and then add browned meat. Reduce heat, cover
and simmer about 15 to 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Ralph Winingham at rwiningham(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
