<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5471 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-CISNEROS-SCHOOLS-HNS &LR;      05-25 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS-SCHOOLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HISPANICS SEE CISNEROS AS GOOD CHOICE TO HEAD L.A. SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JEANNE RUSSELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The only Hispanic member of the Los Angeles Board
of Education cannot hide her glee at the possibility of recruiting
former Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros to run the nation's
second-largest school system.
</P>
<P>
   But Cisneros says he does not want to be recruited.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, who now heads the Univision, the nation's largest
Spanish-language television network, has been considered for what
many see as an impossible job. He admits he may have the perfect
background to salvage the Los Angeles Unified School District, a
poor inner-city system so large it spans four telephone area codes.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros repeated Wednesday that he was flattered but
uninterested.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief interview outside the hotel where Univision
shareholders were gathered for a meeting, Cisneros said he twice
had asked school district officials to remove him from their short
list. Maybe he needed to ask them again, he mused.
</P>
<P>
   He then pointed out why he might excel at the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a big school district with huge problems,''
Cisneros said. ``They've got a man who was mayor of a big city, a
former Cabinet officer, who has shown he can solve problems of
poverty issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, was the mayor of San Antonio before he became
secretary of the Department of Housing and Urban Development in
1993, a post he held during President Clinton's first term in
office.
</P>
<P>
   During his seemingly unstoppable political rise, Cisneros was
the first Hispanic seriously considered as a vice presidential
candidate, but a costly and messy independent counsel investigation
into his payments to a former mistress derailed that ascent.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros pleaded guilty on Sept. 8, 1999, to a single
misdemeanor charge of lying to the FBI about the payments during
routine background checks on nominees for Cabinet posts. Cisneros
paid a $10,000 fine. In exchange for the guilty plea, a federal
judge dropped 18 felony counts that could have sent him to prison.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros opted for a lucrative and relatively private life as a
Southern California business executive. As Univision's public face,
however, Cisneros has charmed Los Angeles and is no stranger at
school board meetings, said Victoria Castro, a former junior high
school principal and the only Hispanic on the school board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can just speak from my perspective and that of the Latino
community,'' she said. ``He is revered.''
</P>
<P>
   Some who know Cisneros well say he remains tempted by the allure
of working to solve massive social problems. He might even see a
risky public service challenge as a route toward political
redemption, they say.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles school district is now undertaking a
reorganization into 11 smaller units under interim Superintendent
Ramon Cortines.
</P>
<P>
   With 711,000 students, the Los Angeles district ranks second
behind New York City schools in size.
</P>
<P>
   More than 70 percent of its students are Hispanic, and the
Latino community remains wary about the ouster by a newly elected
board majority of popular Superintendent Ruben Zacarias in
November, Castro said.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros is seen as someone who can also appeal to the business
interests that backed the new board members.
</P>
<P>
   Several other potential candidates, including Houston
Superintendent Rod Paige, have said they are not interested in the
Los Angeles job. Only one candidate on the list has lobbied for the
job: former Colorado Gov. Roy Romer.
</P>
<P>
   The L.A. school system wants to pay its new superintendent in
the $190,000 to $250,000 range.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, through his position at Univision, has been involved
in parental participation and literacy initiatives with the L.A.
schools.
</P>
<P>
   But after earning $600,000 in bonuses and $3.3 million off the
sale of stock options on top of his $600,000 base salary at
Univision for a total of $4.5 million in 1999, taking the school
job would be a considerable step down financially.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros can cash in additional stock options for about $5.2
million, according to the Univision proxy statement filed with the
U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission. If he were to stay at the
company, other stock options, now worth $15.4 million, would mature
in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During recent San Antonio stops, Cisneros' comments about
returning to his hometown and some type of public service have had
the effect of tossing kerosene on one of the city's favorite
political campfires: speculation about what he might do next.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Cisneros has steadfastly insisted he has not
fulfilled his obligation to Univision, but also has said he and his
wife, Mary Alice, would like to return to San Antonio in time for
his son John Paul, now in the sixth grade, to attend high school.
</P>
<P>
   Those who believe Cisneros is perhaps the lone Texas Democrat
capable of recapturing major statewide offices have urged the
charismatic favorite son to run for governor or U.S. senator.
</P>
<P>
   But Cisneros has said he is interested in education, perhaps
contributing to recent rumors that he might be a candidate for
chancellor of the University of Texas System.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Jeanne Russell by e-mail at
jeanner(at)express-news.net)
</P>
