<HEADER>
A5478 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-MINNAMON-OBIT-HNS &LR;      05-25 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINNAMON-OBIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PAMELA KNIGHT MINNAMON, BROWNIE CAMERA GIRL, DIES AT 68 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CARMINA DANINI  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pamela Knight Minnamon, whose photo as a young girl appeared on
packages of Kodak's popular Brownie cameras, died May 16 at her
home in Tucson, Ariz. Minnamon, who was 68, died at her home of
cancer, said her husband, Paul Minnamon.
</P>
<P>
   Born Dec. 30, 1931, in Rochester, N.Y., she was the daughter of
an Eastman Kodak executive and a homemaker.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1930s and 1940s, boxes containing the Brownie camera
were adorned with her photo. Introduced in 1900, the camera sold
for $1 and used film that cost 15 cents per roll.
</P>
<P>
   The Brownie's low price made it accessible to everyone. Found in
many homes in the early part of the 20th century, the Brownie led
many famous photographers, including the late Ansel Adams, to take
up photography.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in high school, we had a Brownie that we all used
and her picture was on the cardboard box,'' said her son, Timothy
Hanke of Newburyport, Mass. ``She was a very pretty little blond
girl and her photo appeared on the boxes for several years.''
</P>
<P>
   As an adult, Minnamon worked as an artist's model, her son said.
She also sang and, after graduating from Oberlin College in Ohio,
Minnamon auditioned at the Juilliard School of Music in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, she moved to San Antonio and got a job at the Witte
Museum. She worked as secretary to Mark Lane, director emeritus of
the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a real unassuming person and very reflective of
herself and the world,'' Lane said.
</P>
<P>
   She was cremated, and her ashes will be taken to the family
estate in upstate New York, her son said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to her son, she is survived by her husband, Paul
Minnamon of Tucson; her first husband, Peter Hanke of Austin,
Texas; three daughters, Maria Hanke and Jennifer Moore, both of
Austin, and Nora Hanke of Southampton, Mass.; two grandchildren,
John and Benjamin Hanke of Newburyport; two brothers, Francis R.
Knight III of Brainardsville, N.Y., and Lane Knight of Onchiota,
N.Y.; and one sister, Patricia Knight of Snyder, Colo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 1410EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
