</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-TAKEOVERS (Paris) _ The cutthroat tactics of the 1980s,
with vulture investors scouring the landscape for takeover prey,
didn't die out, they just found a new home: Europe. In the thick of
this trend is one of the brashest and most feared of the old-style
raiders, Asher B. Edelman, who is trying to outwit a venerable
French family institution, Taittinger, the champagne maker. There's
one big difference, though. While raiders used to slash and burn,
Adelman is staging a prolonged siege, having stalked the Taittinger
family since 1996. Beyond the clash of French provincialism and
American bluntness, larger stakes are in play. Old French family
companies are under pressure to perform or be taken over. And the
way companies protect themselves is a hot topic of corporate and
political debate. Moreover, luxury products are hot now, and the
Taittinger properties of Societe de Louvre, like the Baccarat
crystal works, are thriving. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
