<HEADLINE>
OUTSTANDING EFFORT PUTS NIXON IN WITH FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trot Nixon was a star high school quarterback in North Carolina
who was wooed by North Carolina State before signing with the Red
Sox, and sometimes it looks as if he's playing football on the
diamond. There is no more relentless player in Major League
Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday night's performance was extreme even by Nixon's
rugged standards. In the fifth inning, he seemed hellbent for
self-destruction when he somersaulted into the right-field stands
at Fenway Park in a vain attempt to grab a foul by Blue Jays
designated hitter Marty Cordova.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon disappeared into the crowd for almost a minute before
resurfacing clutching his sternum. After being examined by physical
therapist Rich Zawacki, he remained in the game, receiving a
resounding ovation from the crowd of 31,250. The 3,000 or so
survivors in the stands were even more appreciative several hours
later when Nixon's two-out, 11th-inning single set up Brian
Daubach's three-run homer that gave Boston a vital 6-3 victory. ``A
lot of people will think that was ridiculous, but I really thought
I had a bead on the ball,'' said Nixon. ``I get in the outfield and
I'm in a zone. It felt like I was playing football again.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon could have used the home-field advantage on this play. But
the fan nearest where he landed was more interested in dining than
helping the Red Sox' cause. ``The guy was eating his hot dog,''
said Nixon. ``He never moved.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't please Jeff Frye, who started at second base as part
of a lineup shuffle that manager Jimy Williams employed while
giving first baseman-DH Mike Stanley the night off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frito (Frye) yelled to the guy, `Don't you know you're
supposed to put the ball in his glove?' '' said Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   The right fielder almost came up with it on his own. ``I looked
at the film, and it looked like it went off the end of my glove,''
said Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon wasn't aware of that at the time because he was
preoccupied with the pain he was feeling in his chest. ``I hit a
cast-iron seat that's been there since the turn of the century,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the antique did no damage, though it did leave a couple of
red welts just below Nixon's neck. He would have preferred another
souvenir for his efforts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thrown for a loss
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett took offense when he was hit in the back by Toronto
reliever Pedro Borbon with two out in the seventh and the score,
3-3. Everett took a step toward the mound as he headed up the
baseline and, after being restrained, glared at Borbon all the way
to first.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the lefthander came off the mound with his arms
extended and upraised, as if to say, ``Why on earth would I try to
hit you in the seventh inning of a tie game?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Injury update
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate word on the condition of Jose Offerman,
who left limping after drawing the 11th-inning walk that launched
the decisive rally.
</P>
<P>
   Williams believes shortstop Nomar Garciaparra (hamstring) is on
target to be activated Saturday in New York, the first day he is
eligible to come off the disabled list. ``Just me hitting grounders
out there, he's making plays to his right, plays to his left,''
said the manager, ``so I think he's feeling pretty darn good.''
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Darren Lewis, who was on a 10-for-16 tear before
straining his left hamstring a week ago in Toronto, has been
available the past two games. ``It feels fine,'' said Lewis. ``I'm
ready to go. I'm the type of person who heals fast _ five or six
days and I'm ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Rod Beck (neck) threw 15 pitches in one inning of work,
striking out one, during extended spring training Tuesday in Fort
Myers, Fla. ``He threw better,'' said Williams, reviewing a report
from Florida. ``He's improving each outing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Get in the swing
</P>
<P>
   With interleague play on the horizon, Red Sox pitchers hit for
the first time since spring training. ``Bunt, slash, swing,'' said
Williams. ``I don't know about hit. Some of those guys can hit.''
The relievers hit better than the starters. With pitching coach Joe
Kerrigan throwing in simulated game situations, the bullpen beat
the rotation by an indeterminate margin. Ramon Martinez said
Kerrigan wasn't taking it easy despite his staff's rust at the
plate: ``He was trying to get everybody out. He didn't want anybody
to get a hit. He got hit hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
