<HEADLINE>
WHEN WINNING IS A NEW FEELING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ After four losing seasons, the Revolution seem to
have found a winning touch. They have a 5-3-4 record and are in
first place in the Eastern Division after a 2-1 win Thursday night
over Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning is contagious and not too many guys have experienced
it here,'' goalkeeper Jeff Causey said. ``Last year, we might have
gone down a goal and said, `Here we go again.' I'm not surprised by
how we are doing because we have the talent, just like any team in
the league. Maybe we have shocked everybody because we are winning.
But being in first place in the first third of the season doesn't
mean much. Now it is a matter of getting points, and it's important
to try to be in first place in the final third of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Colorado game (a 4-3 loss May 17) is always in the back of
our minds and we want to make up for it. When we get the lead, we
don't want to lose it.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonel Alvarez made a difference with a tireless performance in
midfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sits in the middle and organizes things,'' Causey said.
``Whether he speaks the language or not, you understand him with
his finger-pointing and he gets guys into position.''
</P>
<P>
   Midfielder John Harkes, who has missed two games with a calf
injury, is expected to return for Monday's visit to Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez on the move
</P>
<P>
   Luis ``El Matador'' Hernandez suffered a strained shoulder
during the Galaxy's 2-1 win over D.C. United last week. But that is
not what kept him from playing  &UR; last night &LR; . Hernandez was allowed
to return to Monterey to help his family move to Los Angeles. He
will return for Saturday night's game against San Jose in Pasadena,
Calif. . . . Foreign Menace Dept.: Before  &UR; last night &LR; , of the 15
goals surrendered by the Revolution this season, 12 (and 43 of the
last 68) were scored by players born outside the United States. In
five seasons, 130 of the 249 goals surrendered by the Revolution
were converted by players born outside the US.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Success story
</P>
<P>
   Colombia coach Chiqui Garcia has had success in the CONCACAF
region. Garcia guided Saprissa of Costa Rica to the 1995 CONCACAF
Champions Cup title with players such as Roy Myers of the
MetroStars and Paulo Wanchope of West Ham United. Garcia also
helped launch the career of Johnnier Montano, who is expected to
become the next Colombian phenomenon, while coaching America de
Cali. Montano was sent to Quilmes in Argentina and then to Parma in
Italy. Montano, 17, was prevented from joining either Colombia's
national team on this tour or the junior team in Toulon, France, to
remain with Parma for its playoff game against Inter . . . Benfica,
which was concluding a two-game tour of the US  &UR; last night &LR; , is the
most popular and historically successful club in Portugal, but the
team has struggled in recent seasons. Now, Benfica could be on the
verge of losing coach Jupp Heynckes, who may join the German
Federation as a coach, possibly of the national team. Possible
successors include Carlos Queiros, who guided Portugal to two
junior world championships and coached Sporting and the MetroStars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
