<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MEMORIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS FULLY IN CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ohio _ The press conference was about to begin, but an
anxious technician spotted a problem. He sprung into action, nearly
knocking over several cameras, and moved to adjust a microphone in
front of the player.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, there was even more confusion, so Tiger Woods took
it upon himself to adjust the instrument. The technician offered
instructions, seemingly fearful that something would be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Woods merely smiled. ``Trust me,'' he said, ``I've done this
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, it has become such a routine for Woods. So much so
that during these past few days of lead-up to the Memorial
Tournament, an event that is the life and blood of none other than
Jack Nicklaus, it is Woods who still commands most of the
attention. Almost every time he tees it up, he appears to be the
defending champion and that is the case here at Muirfield Village
Golf Club, where Round 1 begins Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago when he came to Nicklaus Country, Woods was still
tuning up a swing that had been reworked from those wild days of
1996-1998, when wedges would sometimes fly 120 yards, other times
165. The distance control was OK at The Memorial a year ago, but
his direction was slightly off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty neat,'' said Woods, flashing back to last year
when he held off Vijay Singh to win. ``I'm over there in the
jungles or the rough or the bunker or the trees, slashing it out,
on top of roots. It was fun to be that creative.''
</P>
<P>
   Fun because he closed with a 69_273, held off Singh by two
shots, and worked out the kinks in his radar enough to set in
motion a stretch of golf at which even the greatest player of our
time marvels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody has ever played a game as well as he's
played it in the last year,'' said Nicklaus. ``I had my stretches
where I never finished out of the top 10, but (considering) the
number of good players today, to do what he has done is probably
more astounding than my record.''
</P>
<P>
   Astounding is as good an adjective as any, for Woods, counting
last year's Memorial, has won 10 of the last 19 PGA Tour events in
which he has played. Three times he has been second, four other
times top 10, and only once has he been outside the top 20. The
expression ``raising the bar'' has been tossed about so often, but
truthfully Woods has pushed it so high most of his colleagues would
need an elevator to find it.
</P>
<P>
   Does he sense that many players are not looking to win, just
cash a check when they see that Woods has entered? He smiled and
nodded his head in the affirmative.
</P>
<P>
   Does that bother him? Another wide smile. ``No. I like it.''
</P>
<P>
   What's not to like? There is more money than he will ever have
the chance to spend _ and he's still just 24. There is fame. There
is enough raw talent to lend legitimacy to the notion that he could
surpass all of Nicklaus's records, a thought that just a few years
ago could have gotten you locked up on a charge of lunacy. And
there are awards, the latest of which fell into his hands
Wednesday, something called the Laureus Award World Sportsman of
the Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of blows your mind away, to have your peers all over
the world choose you,'' said Woods, carefully choosing all the
correct words, though no athlete has dominated a sport quite like
he has in the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   So efficient has he been that the mere switch of a golf ball is
headline news. Woods confirmed that he played a Nike ball in last
week's Deutsch Bank tournament in Germany (he tied for third) and
will do so again this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just testing it out,'' said Woods, who has had a business
arrangement with Titleist since he turned pro in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In professional golf circles, such a switch is an eye-opener.
Why mess with success as rich as Woods's, some colleagues wonder.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be an adjustment period. I don't care how good a
player you are,'' said Hal Sutton, whose switch to the Strata ball
has been credited with a resurgence in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Woods harbors no such fear, which shouldn't come as a surprise
to anyone who has watched him shape a 6-iron out of rough, around a
tree, and onto a green some 210 yards away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something I've always believed in is if you're going to try
something out, try it when you're playing well because then you
will actually know what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing well? Woods certainly qualifies on that account.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 1433EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
