<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5501 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-NOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      05-25 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SIGNATURE' HOLD TAKES NEW MEANING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The closing hole at Presidents Golf Course in Quincy is a par 3
that plays uphill, anywhere from 120 to 135 yards. Like the 17
holes that precede it, the 18th is short but difficult because of a
multitude of dastardly pin placements on a green with severe slopes
that don't allow you to get your tee shot close.
</P>
<P>
   Many a good player has made bogey there. A double bogey isn't
out of the question, and chances are on any given day, golfers are
spraying tee shots right, down a hill, and scoring 7s and 8s. Never
in your wildest dreams, however, could you envision taking 43
strokes to navigate the hole.
</P>
<P>
   But it happened to one unfortunate golfer Saturday in the first
round of the Norfolk County Classic. At least according to his
scorecard, that is.
</P>
<P>
   The player actually bogeyed the 18th to complete a backside 43
for a respectable 84, which would have made the cut into Sunday's
final round. But the 43 was penciled into the box where the 18th
hole score should have been, which so far as the scorekeeper was
concerned, meant a backside 82 and 123 total.
</P>
<P>
   The misfortune occurred because the player in question, in a
rush to get to his son's Little League game, quickly looked through
his hole-by-hole scores, saw they were correct, and signed the
card. He asked his marker to submit the card, which he did _ after
adding the ``43'' backside split into the wrong box. As a result,
the player did not make it into the second round.
</P>
<P>
   An innocent mistake in a small, unheralded amateur tournament?
Absolutely.
</P>
<P>
   An unfair punishment? Not at all. For as cruel as it seems, your
signature on a scorecard is your word that that is what you shot
for the day. Remember, the game for the most part is officiated by
the players themselves, which makes it the most honorable of all
sports. There is a long-established code of conduct for tournament
golf _ professional and amateur _ and paramount is the player's
responsibility to check his or her scorecard, make sure everything
adds up, and submit as their word of honor that everything is
correct.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds simple, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   So why are there golfing hearts aching all over the world
because of inadvertent gaffes?
</P>
<P>
   You know by now about Padraig Harrington failing to sign his
scorecard after the first round of the Benson &AMP; Hedges
International Open two weeks ago. He shot a third-round 64 to open
a five-shot lead, but was disqualified before the final 18 because
of that first-day oversight. Instead of winning $284,000 Harrington
got nothing _ except for the humbling lesson of a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   It was a lesson Roberto de Vicenzo learned at Augusta in 1968,
as did Jackie Pung in 1957 at the US Women's Open. And as painful
as that lesson is, at least the fellow at Presidents GC and
Harrington _ not to mention de Vicenzo and Pung _ only hurt
themselves with their carelessness.
</P>
<P>
   Which is more than we can say about Carl Pettersson, a senior at
North Carolina State, and Phil Gehring of Skidmore. Scorecard
snafus this past week robbed them of more than individual glory,
because teammates got hurt, too.
</P>
<P>
   Pettersson appeared to have shot a final-round 70 to finish at
5-under 208 during the East Regional at Glenmaura National GC in
Moosic, Pa. Not only was he medalist, but his great performance had
pushed his Wolfpack into the top 11, good for a berth in the NCAA
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the terrible realization that he had goofed.
Pettersson had made a double-bogey 6 at the eighth hole, but had
signed for a bogey. He told his coach, who told tournament
officials, who did what they must do, cold-hearted as it seems _
they bid Pettersson farewell from the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Had they counted the 6, Pettersson would still have been
medalist, but no matter. You sign for a higher score than you
actually shot (such as the NCC contestant and you keep the score;
you sign for a lower score than you actually shot and you get to
wear ``DQ'' next to your name. And in team competition that means
taking down your teammates, which is what happened to Pettersson
and NC State.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolfpack could not count Pettersson's score of 70; instead,
they had to take another player's 81. Instead of 860 and a
sixth-place finish, NC State fell to 901 and 14th, meaning there
would be no NCAA tournament play this year.
</P>
<P>
   If you are wondering how Pettersson feels, you may want to ask
Gehring. He was equally careless in the third and final round of
the NCAA Division 3 championship in Michigan. He marched to the
scorer's table with his scorecard in hand, signed for a 70, and
waited with teammates to celebrate the title.
</P>
<P>
   It barely got going when horror engulfed Gehring, but not so bad
that he couldn't show that he was a player of character. Gehring
told officials he had made a bogey-5 at the seventh, not the par
that he had penciled in.
</P>
<P>
   Gehring's name went from the leaderboard to the circular bin. He
was disqualified, and his team had to instead take its fifth
player's score of 79. That pushed Skidmore from first to third, but
in one man's eyes, Gehring may have been the winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed a lot of integrity to come back and correct the
error,'' said John Ervin, director of events at Bedford Valley GC
in Battle Creek, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Integrity. Golf is one of the sports that still embraces it.
It's just painful to be reminded of it through instances such as
these.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
