<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5508 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JAPAN-ECONOMIC-DATA-N     05-25 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECONOMIC-DATA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT SAYS IT WILL CORRECT ECONOMIC REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The government said Thursday that it would correct its
deliberate omission of data in its revision of statistics on
economic growth for the fourth quarter of last year when it
releases new economic figures on June 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Economic Planning Agency, which computes the gross domestic
product figures, denied that it had left data out of its
calculations because its inclusion might have shown that the
decline in economic activity in the October to December quarter was
steeper than originally reported.
</P>
<P>
   But it did say that when the data is included, the gross
domestic product in that quarter will have fallen 1.6 percent
rather than 1.43 percent, which was the figure the agency derived
in May by using an estimate rather than using available survey data
when it compiled its first revision of the figure.
</P>
<P>
   A sharper decline in the gross domestic product figure for that
period would likely make it more difficult for the government to
achieve its target of 0.6 percent economic growth in the fiscal
year that ended March 31, at a time when the ruling party is facing
an election and is keen to demonstrate its firm control of an
economy on the mend.
</P>
<P>
   The agency called a special press conference in response to
questions about a story on the omission that appeared in the New
York Times and on the paper's Web site on Tuesday. Prior to that
time, the press had not questioned the omission, although agency
officials insisted on Thursday that EPA Vice Minister Takashi
Nakanomyo had mentioned a problem with the data on capital spending
at a press conference held after the preliminary economic figures
for the fourth quarter were released on Mar. 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report was wrong,'' said Akira Sadahiro, head of the
agency's Economic Research Institute, according to Bloomberg News.
``There is absolutely no connection with political intentions. Our
handling of the data was rational.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times was not invited to the press conference. In
its original story, however, the Times quoted Masaaki Maruyama,
head of the national expenditures division of the agency, denying
any political motivation for the decision to omit data.
</P>
<P>
   Maruyama made a decision to omit information that showed that
capital spending by financial institutions had fallen far more
sharply than the agency estimated when it compiled its first
revision to the gross domestic product figure released in March.
</P>
<P>
   In its initial compilation of the gross domestic product, the
agency used an estimate of how much investment by banks, securities
houses and insurance companies had declined in the fourth quarter
by 3 percent. Based on that estimate as well as many other
components, the agency said in March that the gross domestic
product fell by 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the agency replaces that estimate with data collected
in a survey it conducts when it compiles its first revision to the
gross domestic product figure.
</P>
<P>
   But the revision announced on May 11 did not include the survey
data, which showed that capital spending by financial institutions
had slid by 37.3 percent, far more than the 3 percent the agency
had anticipated and more in line with data collected by the Bank of
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Maruyama said the agency had decided not to use the survey data
because there was no easy way to explain the discrepancy between it
and the estimate used in the original calculation. He repeated that
explanation Thursday, as did Sadahiro.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 1440EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
