<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5511 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-LEWIS-TRIAL26-COX     05-25 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-TRIAL26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prosecutors scolded for not turning over new evidence
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin and Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A Fulton County judge scolded prosecutors today for
not turning over to defendants a statement by a witness who changed
part of his story in the Buckhead stabbings case.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Alice D. Bonner ruled that prosecutors
violated the law by not turning over the new evidence, but she
denied a motion by one of the defendants for a mistrial and to
exclude the testimony of prosecution witness Jeff Gwen.
</P>
<P>
   Gwen had originally told police that NFL star Ray Lewis had
punched Richard Lollar, one of the two men stabbed to death Jan. 31
after a night of post-Super Bowl partying. Gwen later amended his
statement to say Lewis and Lollar were merely ``tussling.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Clint Rucker said there was no foul
committed by prosecutors because ``we did not hide it, conceal it
and we made the witness available to the defense for interview.''
</P>
<P>
   The law requires that any evidence favorable to a defendant must
be turned over by prosecutors to the defense. Lewis attorney Ed
Garland said the state never made Gwen available to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went through a lot of hoops to get him,'' Garland told
Bonner. ``Never were we made aware of that mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Harvey, lawyer for Lewis' co-defendant, Joseph Sweeting,
said he never was informed of Gwen's change either.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, 25; Sweeting, 34, of Miami; and Reginald Oakley, 31, of
Baltimore are charged with murder in the stabbing deaths of Lollar,
24, and Jacinth Baker, 21, both of Decatur.
</P>
<P>
   After the judge's ruling, Oakley's other lawyer, David Wolfe,
started the morning cross-examining Gwen, an Akron, Ohio, man who
was a friend of the victims and who has cut a rap CD, using the
stage name Chino Nino. Gwen, the victims, who were natives of
Akron, and several other Ohio friends were leaving the Cobalt
lounge minutes before the deadly fight occurred. Lewis and his
friends also were leaving the club.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe waded in on Gwen, reciting lyrics in the CD, trying to
portray Gwen as both a man who revels in violence and who lives a
split personality.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer asked Gwen, dressed in a blue jean jacket, what does,
``We're strapped'' mean?
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a pistol,'' Gwen responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does `We're strapped and ready to tear up the club mean'
?'' Wolfe asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean I do that,'' Gwen responded.
</P>
<P>
   Gwen had testified on Wednesday that his initial account of
Lewis striking Lollar was ``a mistake.'' Instead, he said Lewis and
Lollar both grabbed at each other's shoulders and pulled each other
back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   Gwen is one of only two witnesses who have told police they saw
Lewis throwing punches during the melee. Lewis' limousine driver,
Duane Fassett, is the other.
</P>
<P>
   Gwen is a key figure in the case because his words caused a
misunderstanding that led to the deadly melee. Gwen said he left
the Cobalt lounge and discovered his ride had left him but saw
Akron friend Chris Shinholster, who said he'd give him a ride.
</P>
<P>
   Gwen complained to Shinholster, using a profanity-laced racial
epithet.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley, who was walking by, overhead Gwen and rushed back at
them, Gwen and Shinholster testified.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis walked up and grabbed Oakley around the waist, pulling him
toward the limousine parked on East Paces Ferry Road. Gwen said he
saw Oakley holding a knife.
</P>
<P>
   Another man told them to stay back. That man held a knife but
was not a defendant, the two men testified. The two Akron men
testified this man was dressed in black, although Gwen said he wore
a leather jacket and Shinholster said he wore a mink coat. Gwen
also said that, during the ensuing fight, this man swung at him
with the knife.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination, both Gwen and Shinholster admitted they
were drinking and smoking cigar-sized marijuana ``blunts.''
</P>
<P>
   After court adjourned, Rucker, when asked about this
unidentified man, said, ``We're still dealing with that,'' and
indicated that the state's investigation is continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Baker and Lollar were walking behind Gwen and Shinholster. As
they passed the limo, Gwen said he heard Lollar say, ``(Expletive)
them, (racial epithet), this is OH-10,'' a reference to their
native Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley then came out of the limo and Baker smashed a champagne
bottle over his head, Gwen said, noting that he later saw Oakley
pull Baker's coat over his head and punch him four or five times in
the chest area. Baker died of stab wounds to the chest.
</P>
<P>
   Shinholster, a stocky construction worker, testified that after
Baker popped Oakley with the champagne bottle, he ran up and
appealed to the football star to control Oakley.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when Ray Lewis ran up'' to the fight, Shinholster said.
Lewis did not have a knife, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him to grab his dude; I asked him two or three
times,'' Shinholster testified. Lewis did not break up the fight,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He then heard Lollar scream, ``Get your hands off my cousin,''
referring to Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Shinholster said he then saw Oakley shaking Baker, who appeared
to be unconscious. Shinholster ran over to Baker and grabbed him by
the foot. ``I tried to get a reaction,'' he said, adding that he
did not get one.
</P>
<P>
   He then saw Lollar walk over with his hand over his chest saying
he had been cut. ``It was in a calm manner like it was a small
cut,'' he said. But Lollar fell to the ground oozing blood and
Shinholster ran.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
