<HEADER>
A5520 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-25 1493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK TO OLD BEACON HILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A rare opportunity to time-travel into Boston's
Edwardian era will be offered in a series of events sponsored by
Beacon Hill's Church of the Advent, at the corner of Mt. Vernon and
Brimmer streets on Beacon Hill, and the International Design
Symposium, an organization that hosts flower-arranging exhibitions
and study tours and that is celebrating its 25th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   The Advent 2000 committee of the church will host an Edwardian
Tea June 14 at 5:30 and 8 p.m., with actress Jessa Piaia playing
the role of Isabella Stewart Gardner, a congregation member at the
turn of the century. Founded in 1844, the Church of the Advent was
the first Anglo-Catholic parish in the United States, and the
notable 1880 building, designed by Boston architect John Hubbard
Sturgis, is a jewel-like version of early English Gothic style.
Advance reservations at $20 per person are required.
</P>
<P>
   Floral designers from many countries will participate in an
International Festival of Flowers, which will be previewed June 16
at 6:45 p.m. at the church. Seldom-seen sacred vessels inspired by
the the Gothic Revival and Arts &AMP; Crafts movements will be on
display, along with scores of arrangements, including a Victorian
carpet of flowers. A 7:30 p.m. concert of voices and instruments
from several historic periods will include the Choir of the Church
of the Advent with Mark Dwyer on the Aeolian-Skinner organ, the
Renaissonics, and the New England Spiritual Ensemble. A reception
will follow. Tickets are $10-$35. Call 617-523-2377 for
information.
</P>
<P>
   The International Festival of Flowers will continue June 17 from
10 a.m. to 5 p.m. and June 18 from 1 to 5 p.m. (admission $5-$8).
On June 17, from 3 to 5 p.m., Gilda de Garcia of Mexico, Yasuko
Manako of Japan, Kirk Pamper of Tennessee, and Andreas Verhejien of
the Netherlands will create flower arrangements employing lighting
and music at the Copley Theatre, 225 Clarendon St., across from
Copley Square. Tickets at $25, or combined tickets at $29, include
free parking in the Boston Common Garage (stickers available at the
church). Call the IDA at 781-326-8906.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Garden Club of America awarded John Wheaton
Trexler the Mrs. Oakleigh Thorne Medal for outstanding achievement
in garden design at its annual meeting in Cleveland. As executive
director of the Worcester County Horticultural Society since 1984,
Trexler has been instrumental in the development of the society's
132-acre Tower Hill Botanic Garden in Boylston, including building
a 25,000-square-foot Education and Visitors Center and
14,000-square-foot Orangerie complex. Under his leadership, capital
campaigns raised $14.2 million and membership climbed from 1,000 to
4,300. He also instigated a cooperative venture with Clark
University that offers college credit courses in horticulture at
Tower Hill. He was nominated by the Worcester Garden Club.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   June is the biggest month for garden tours. Here are some of
regional interest:
</P>
<P>
   June 2: The Concord Museum's Guild of Volunteers Fifth Annual
Garden Affairs Tour from 9 a.m. to 4 p.m. is a pleasant rustic tour
with eight gardens. They include an apple orchard, a spring-fed
pond, a winding river path, and a home with a grand two-story porch
draped in wisteria. Admission for nonmembers is $20 in advance and
$22 at the museum on tour day. Garden-related gifts will be for
sale at the museum shop and proceeds support education programs.
Box lunches can be reserved in advance for $10. If you have time,
check out nearby Blanchette Gardens, 167 Rutland St., Carlisle, the
area's best nursery for shade-tolerant perennials.
</P>
<P>
   Directions: Take exit 29 off Route 128 to Route 2 west to the
Cambridge Turnpike, which is the second stoplight after Route 128,
to the Concord Museum. For information, call 978-369-9763 or visit
www.concordmuseum.org.
</P>
<P>
   June 3: Aficionados of gardens and music are invited to Indian
Hills Music Center's Rhapsody in Bloom Garden Tour from 10 a.m. to
4 p.m. to visit five gardens in Shirley Center. Professional
musicians from the Indian Hill Symphony will perform. Tickets are
$20 in advance; $22 day of tour. A box lunch is available by
advance reservation for $10. Complimentary afternoon tea will be
served. Proceeds will benefit Indian Hill Music Center programs.
Directions: Take Route 2 10 miles west from Route 495. Call
978-486-0540 for reservations and information or visit
www.indianhillmusic.org.
</P>
<P>
   June 6: In 1995, the Gardens of the Back Bay walking tour took
place during a classic weather nightmare of lightning bolts,
thunderclaps, and sheets of rain. Now, five years later, Back Bay
garden club members have recovered enough to give it another try
from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. It begins with a complimentary continental
breakfast at the Boston Center for Adult Education, 5 Commonwealth
Ave., from 9:30 to 11 a.m. Box lunches and $25 tour tickets, which
include maps, will be on sale there to benefit neighborhood street
trees. The tour includes 13 seldom-seen private interior gardens
(as well as the front gardens) and several Victorian mansions and
house museums, including the recently restored Ayer mansion.
Afternoon trolleys will provide shuttle service between the
gardens. Complimentary refreshments will be served at the elegant
Burrage house at 314 Commonwealth Ave. from 2 to 4 p.m. Tickets may
be purchased in advance for $20 by calling 617-424-7186.
</P>
<P>
   June 16 and 19: The Sixth Annual Garden Tour is scheduled from
10 a.m. to 4 p.m. in Lyme and Old Lyme, Conn. Tickets are $20 day
of tour. Take exit 70 off Interstate 90 and follow the flower
baskets to tour locations. Call 860-442-2797, ext. 923, for
information.
</P>
<P>
   June 17: The 20th Annual Newburyport Garden Tour will be held 10
a.m. to 5 p.m., starting at the Cushing House Museum, 98 High St.,
Newburyport. Ten gardens in historic Newburyport, West Newbury, and
Newbury will include a mix of urban, suburban, rural, new, old, and
historic landscapes. This is always a good tour. Tickets in advance
are $12; $15 at the door. Plants, including cuttings from local
historic gardens, as well as refreshments, handcrafted items,
garden accessories, and books will be on sale at the Cushing house.
Proceeds support the Historical Society of Old Newbury. If you have
time, skip the box lunch and enjoy one of the area's many
restaurants. The shops in beautiful, newly vibrant downtown
Newburyport are also worth a look. From Interstate 95, take exit 57
and go 2.2 miles east on Route 113. After the intersection of State
Street, take the first left onto Fruit Street. The museum is on the
corner of Fruit and High streets. Call 978-462-2681 for information
or advance tickets.
</P>
<P>
   June 17: The Sixth Somerville Open Gardens Tour from noon to 4
p.m. will feature 16 private gardens. The $8 admission packet will
be available from 11:30 a.m. to 3 p.m. in front of City Hall, 93
Highland Ave., and will include garden descriptions and a map that
also highlights public spaces maintained by the Somerville Garden
Club, an urban garden club geared to working adults. Proceeds will
benefit these sites and the Somerville Arts Council. For
information, call Vilma Sullivan at 617-623-7896.
</P>
<P>
   June 23-24: Gardens Open for Blithewold Arboretum is actually
two tours. The first is at Watch Hill and Weekapaug, R.I., 10 a.m.
to 4 p.m. The second will be in Westport Aug. 18 and 19. Advance
purchase of joint tickets is $50, or $25 for a single series, and
$30 the days of the tours.
</P>
<P>
   Both locations are part of a summer colony with gardens designed
to peak when their owners are in residence. Watch Hill is a grand
Victorian-era colony with oceanside gardens, as well as surf
beaches and bird watching to rival Plum Island, that has remained
largely unknown to Bostonians. The more familiar Westport has the
Westport River and surrounding marshlands and ocean. Proceeds
support the Blithewold Arboretum in Bristol, R.I. For information,
call 401-253-2707 or visit www.Blithewold.org.
</P>
<P>
   June 29-30: The Third Annual Hidden Treasures of the Boothbay
Peninsula House and Garden Tour, 10 a.m. to 4 p.m., rain or shine,
will feature nine gardens, most with spectacular ocean views. Some
houses will also be open, as will be two artists' studios. Advance
tickets are $18, available with directions and a brochure through
the Coastal Maine Botanical Garden, Box 234, Boothbay, ME 04537.
Tickets are $20 on tour days. A boutique with garden gift items and
plants and an $8 box lunch can be reserved in advance through the
Botanical Garden office. Proceeds support the new Coastal Maine
Botanical Garden established in Boothbay four years ago on land
originally slated for development. Call 207-633-4333 or e-mail
cmbg(at)clinic.net for information and directions.
</P>
