<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5521 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-FALCONS-RETURN-BOS-2N     05-25 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALCONS-RETURN-BOS-2ND-LEAD-WRITETHROUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 30 FLOORS UP, PEREGRINES ARE BORN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Corrects spelling of peregrines in headline)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MAC DANIEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As six TV crews, three photographers and a bevy of
others eagerly recorded the event, state biologist Tom French
lifted a cardboard lid and introduced the world to the newest
residents of Boston's historic Custom House: four downy peregrine
falcon chicks, tiny symbols of one of the most unlikely wildlife
recoveries in history.
</P>
<P>
   The squawking three-week-old chicks, the largest clutch of
falcons born in Massachusetts this year, underscored the majestic
hunters' return from the edge of extinction, thanks in part to
their fondness for urban living. The parents can provide a steady
diet of pigeons and other city birds for their young perched 30
floors up. And by all accounts earlier this week, these chicks were
thriving.
</P>
<P>
   The cameras loved them. As French, assistant director with the
state Division of Fisheries and Wildlife, attached identification
bands to the birds and their parents angrily waited outside, the
chicks became fledgling media stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been around,'' said French of the frantic parents, who
have been nesting longer than any other peregrine falcon pair in
New England. ``They know what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been almost a year since peregrine falcons were taken off
the national Endangered Species List as they rebounded from the
devastating effects of pesticides such as DDT, and destruction of
their habitat. And while the birds remain on MassWildlife's
endangered list after only five pair have nested in the state,
that's a big improvement over 45 years ago, when there were no
falcons at all.
</P>
<P>
   Under the watchful eye of people such as French, who have built
falcon nests on top of skyscrapers from Boston to Chicago, the
birds have found that tall buildings make excellent hunting posts.
Of the 1,650 pairs of peregrine falcons in the nation last year,
experts estimate that 10 percent live in cities, including all of
the Massachusetts falcons.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a banner spring for Boston's falcons, in particular.
One pair sits atop the Custom House and two pair are nesting atop
the landmark Christian Science Church. Springfield and Fall River
are home to the other pairs.
</P>
<P>
   Known as the fastest flying bird in the world, the peregrine
falcon reaches speeds of up to 200 miles per hour while diving for
prey, which is often snagged in mid-flight. French said he has
found the remnants of 85 bird species discarded around the Custom
House nest site. The leg of a red winged blackbird, found on the
building's observatory deck Wednesday, probably came from the
marshes surrounding Logan International Airport, a favorite hunting
ground, French said.
</P>
<P>
   Switching homes between the Post Office Building and the Custom
House, Boston's peregrine falcons have been coming here since 1986,
when the enclosed nest at the Custom House was built. A year later,
another female falcon attacked and killed the female in the nest,
taking over both her mate and domain. The unique pair _ a
14-year-old male and a 9-year-old female _ have been coming back
here ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Boston's reaction to the ongoing falcon soap opera in its
midst has been tame compared to other places in Massachusetts. In
Springfield, live coverage of a similar peregrine falcon nest is
broadcast citywide. In Turner's Falls, they broadcast an eagle's
nest.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists say media attention helps raise awareness about such
birds, which have thrived in other urban environments like New York
City and Chicago. But adoring humans can become a problem if they
start to think of the falcons as pets rather than the wild animals
they are.
</P>
<P>
   In Springfield, which named its minor league hockey franchise
after the falcons, local school children have named them, and one
of the birds was stuffed after it dive-bombed into the side of the
building. When the pair didn't show up one year, their absence made
news.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, after one of the Springfield chicks became sick,
French said the phone calls never stopped as viewers demanded that
the bird be rescued. When the chick died, cable programmers had to
run a disclaimer along the bottom of the broadcast reminding people
to change the channel if disturbed by the carcass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had people calling for two days,'' French said, adding that
he and other biologists tending the nest chose not to remove the
carcass. ``All the other years were great. And, here we had a
death, and people suddenly realized it's not Disney.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been talk of similar broadcasts in Boston, but it has
never caught on here, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In the crowded top of the Custom House tower, French was asked
if the birds have names _ they don't _ while officials from
Marriott, which owns the building, got some pictures with the
chicks.
</P>
<P>
   But before the chicks were brought down to be tagged, a strange
thing happened. Outside, sitting on the narrow ledge outside one of
the windows, the chick's mother perched and, for more than two
minutes, checked out what was going on inside.
</P>
<P>
   The cameras whirred, and as the stare-off continued, it suddenly
was hard to tell who was watching who.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
