<HEADER>
A5522 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-25 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESCAPING, PAINTBRUSH IN HAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How do you revive your spirits after a day of pressure and
frustration? How do you restore your zest for life when so much of
modern living feels like a never-ending onslaught of bad news?
</P>
<P>
   This is an important question for the environmental activists
who are my friends and colleagues. This spring we targeted two
multibillion-dollar corporations, challenging the placement of yet
another cellphone antenna in a crowded eastern Massachusetts
neighborhood and playing a complicated game of political chess with
owners of the highly toxic Salem Power Plant. Now, despite some
progress, we find we know too much to be satisfied with our small
victories. Fly ash from the plant is still polluting local water
supplies, and the telecom industry will no doubt be back with other
plans.
</P>
<P>
   It seems there'll be no rest for the weary.
</P>
<P>
   The problems we're trying to ameliorate are so huge they're
capable of blotting out all of our other considerations. The
impulse to make more of a difference can fill every waking hour and
extinguish even the most enthusiastic advocate's joie de vivre.
When spring arrived and I was too busy to notice, I felt I
desperately needed an antidote to spending so much time in
opposition. I longed for a chance each week to focus on something
that didn't need reforming, especially by me.
</P>
<P>
   I decided to take up painting.
</P>
<P>
   It was Carla Mattioli's description of her watercolor classes in
Rockport that caught my attention: ``Sacred Cycle of the Plant
through Color. Includes nature observation, nature drawing and a
rejuvenating series of guided watercolor exercises on the theme of
plant metamorphosis.'' The word ``rejuvenating'' spoke directly to
my sense of spiritual exhaustion. I showed up for my first class,
ready for anything, along with one other student, a woman named
Susan.
</P>
<P>
   Mattioli believes in painting with the whole being, so we began
our first class with eurhythmic movements, visualizing various
colors as we lifted our arms and breathed deeply. Then Mattioli
gave each of us a striped sunflower seed and a round moonflower
seed. As we examined them carefully, she pointed out how easy it
would be to make wooden copies that would be identical in every way
except for the invisible life force hidden within the real seeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is proof that the nonmaterial world exists,'' Mattioli
said, so we tried to capture that aspect of reality in our pencil
sketches, placing radiating fields of energy around carefully drawn
seeds. Then we painted. In lemon yellow, going from dark to light,
we indicated energy pulsing out from the center of our
water-saturated paper. Using Prussian blue, we moved from high to
low intensity back toward the center, discovering the way the
colors flowed and changed as they came together.
</P>
<P>
   The room was filled with Mattioli's deeply hued, vibrant
paintings. A fountain murmured in a corner. Outside, a warm breeze
rustled the trees. Susan and I focused on the colors swirling into
one another at the tips of our sable brushes in a process that was
totally absorbing and soothing. Two hours passed in a peaceful
color-induced haze.
</P>
<P>
   In our second class, we concentrated on the sunflower sprouts
that Mattioli provided. We stood in a circle, responding to the sun
like seedlings before we began to sketch them. When it was time to
paint, we divided our paper into yellow sky above and blue ground
below. We dropped a dot of orange into the soil. Swirling yellow
through the blue, we portrayed the energy field around the orange
seed, then drew the green that resulted upward into a stem and two
tiny leaves. We were as oblivious of time as children. My tension
vanished into the streams of color that spread gracefully over the
damp surface of the paper.
</P>
<P>
   Next week we graduate from seedlings to leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Is this art or therapy? All I can say is that when I get home,
the flowers in my garden are brighter. I'm no longer blind to the
life energy in them. In addition, the miracle that transforms a
rock-hard seed into a fragile seedling has not been lost on me. It
suggests that some power, which operates beyond the reach of
corporations or citizens, is busy pursuing its own purposes, with
or without us. It feels amazing _ yes, even rejuvenating _ to walk
through a world in which millions of seeds have simultaneously
begun reaching toward the light.
</P>
<P>
   If I've gotten this much out of blue, yellow, and a single dot
of orange, what on earth will the rest of the rainbow do?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
