<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT IN THE MOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reading Helen Gurley Brown's essay ``Don't Give Up on Sex After
60'' in this week's Newsweek made me want to go lie down somewhere
and take a nap. Alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had sex last night. I'm 78, and my husband, movie producer
David Brown, is 83,'' the eternal Cosmo Girl begins.
</P>
<P>
   Let's pause for a moment and try to erase the image of the
wraithlike Brown and her spry husband gamely going at it.
</P>
<P>
   Can't get it out of your head, can you? Neither can I.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's essay is part of Newsweek's cover story, ``The Science
of Women's Sexuality.'' Female sexual dysfunction seems to be the
affliction du jour. Monday night CBS's ``48 Hours'' aired a segment
on the subject. Tuesday's USA Today had a page one story on a study
that found Viagra does nothing for women's sexual response.
</P>
<P>
   Science has known for years that the female libido declines in
the middle years. Now the search for a cure, if that's the right
word, has taken on a certain urgency. Why? Well, imagine all those
millions of men on Viagra turning to women who don't share their
pharmaceutically-induced passion and asking, ``What's wrong with
you?''
</P>
<P>
   And so, according to Newsweek, a dozen drug manufacturers are
``rushing headlong'' into research and development, trying to come
up with a pill, or something, that will do for women what Viagra
does for men. There's a lot of money in it for company that
formulates an effective drug.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a Viagra equivalent for women isn't proving to be easy.
Newsweek's John Leland writes, ``Women's satisfactions and drives
are more complex, organized as much around the health of the
relationship as the majesty that is orgasm.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are experimenting with all sorts of things,
including supplements of the male hormone testosterone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, great,'' my husband said when I told him about the
testosterone. ``Sex with a bearded woman. Just what I've always
wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not just declining libido that causes middle-aged women to
lose interest in sex. When you get older, getting ready for sex is
so time consuming. You have to prepare for it as if it were a
three-week vacation, make sure you have all the necessary supplies
and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see. First, a couple of Advil, to ward off headache. And
something to calm your intestinal tract. You don't want it acting
up in the middle of everything. Strap on the magnetic belt, so your
back won't kill you. Then the knee supports. OK, your teeth are in
place. You remembered the mouthwash. You have a battery of lotions
and lubricants at the ready. Now turn down the lights, because you
don't want him to get a good look at you. And you don't want to get
a good look at him, either.
</P>
<P>
   It's so humiliating. And it gets worse, if Brown's Newsweek
essay is anything to go by. She suggests that if you want sex but
don't have a man in your life, you should pay for one. She quotes a
``realistic'' friend: ``Between 50 and 60, sex is out there. If you
want it, you can connect. After 60, you have to supply the sled,
the snow and the dog team.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it worth it? Brown certainly thinks so, even if, as she
notes, you have to back out of the room when it's over so he won't
see ``that cellulite, those folds, those pooches.'' (You have to
hide the dog team?)
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex is one of the three best things there are,'' she writes,
``and I don't know what the other two are.''
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate? Scotch? An afternoon nap? Curling up with a magazine
that doesn't remind you of your deficiencies?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 1453EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
