<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUB SPOUT WON'T UNSCREW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Q &LR; . I have done a bit of plumbing, and I want to change the
spout in my tub. The spout comes out of the tub itself, and there
are two handles for the hot and cold water. I have tried to unscrew
the spout, without success; there is some corrosion, and I don't
want to fiddle too much with it because the wall is tiled. How can
I loosen the spout?
</P>
<P>
   FRUSTRATED
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  If this trick doesn't work, find a plumber, who will
probably apply the same trick. Put a hammer handle in the spout to
increase the torque, and twist straight. By straight I mean do not
angle the spout as you twist. Squirt some WD-40 or Liquid Wrench
(penetrating oil) if you can get to the threads. If a hammer handle
is too big, get a smaller hammer or use a large screwdriver.
Anything to get enough torque.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q &LR; . I just finished pickling my kitchen cabinets, and they look
great. Now I want to protect that nice pickled finish. What can I
put on that will not darken or turn everything yellow?
</P>
<P>
   NANCY ELLEN CHASE, Wakefield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A &LR; . I think the best thing you can use is a water-based
polyurethane varnish. Two coats should do it, and you will get a
minimum of yellowing. Any finish will darken, whether varnished or
not, but there is nothing you can do about that. Two caveats about
water-based polyurethane varnish: 1. It is not very resistant to
wear and tear; therefore, more coats are needed than with the
oil-based varnish. For your purposes, two coats should be OK, three
coats will be better. 2. Water-based polyurethane varnish is
milky-looking in the can, but clears up when applied. But thin
coats are essential because too thick of a coat will remain cloudy.
So, be careful and make sure all coats, particularly final ones,
are very thin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q &LR; . You always mention putting rocks or crushed stone in a sump
hole in the basement floor, where a sump pump is located. Is there
any reason not to put in crushed stone?
</P>
<P>
   LARRY ROOT, Stow, Vermont
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A &LR; . Not really. The stone is to help keep the sump neat and
clean; earth fill would would mix with water and could clog a pump.
Ready-made sumps, comprising a perforated plastic barrel, a solid
bottom, and a hole for the pump hose, are sold at Home Depot and
other building-supply stores.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q &LR; . I have a big deck, measuring 36 feet by 16. My wife wants
to paint it. Should a deck be painted? I am a bit skeptical.
Shouldn't it be sealed or stained?
</P>
<P>
   K.W., Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A &LR; . That is a mighty big deck, and whether it should be painted
or not depends on what we are talking about. If it's the floor,
give your wife the chance to paint it, but she must do the painting
(primer and two finish coats) and she must do the maintenance:
scraping, sanding, and repainting when it peels off. This is just a
heavy-handed way of saying, do not paint. Never paint a deck floor.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, either seal it with a clear sealer or stain it with a
semitransparent stain. In both cases, only one coat is needed. The
sealer has to be renewed each year; the stain can be redone in
three to five years. In both cases, no peeling. If the deck boards
are mahogany or cedar, you do not have to seal or stain them.
</P>
<P>
   The railings and deck framework are another matter. Stain the
framework. You can also stain the railings and balusters, using a
solid latex stain. But still, no paint!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q &LR; . The basement floor in my 1954 ranch is weird, with a
sloping floor. It has a 12-inch drop in a 40-foot span. That is not
so bad, but there are two rooms, one with a 3-inch drop in 6 feet,
another with a 9-inch drop in 20 feet. I don't mind the long slope,
but I'd like to level the floors in the two smaller rooms. But how?
A concrete man said he'd do it for $3,600.
</P>
<P>
   CHARLIE TASH, Boston
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A &LR; . That's a lot of money to lay new concrete, but is probably
not out of line, considering its size and the skills needed to make
the floors level. And to do a proper job, I think the whole floor
should be ripped out before new concrete is laid. That, obviously,
would necessitate the high cost.
</P>
<P>
   The floor may have been sloped on purpose to allow draining of
floodwater to the low end, where a sump would gather the water and
a pump would flush it away. If you get any water in the basement by
flooding or seepage, you have to solve that problem before doing
anything.
</P>
<P>
   If you can do the two rooms for less than $3,600, go ahead. Or
do them yourself with new concrete. The walls of the rooms are your
forms, and you can make the work easier by doing half a room at a
time, to allow maneuvering room and avoid having to work in the
concrete. If you add new concrete, make sure that does not lower
the ceiling too much. The most important thing if you do it
yourself is to apply a bonding agent to the old concrete so the new
will stick properly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q &LR; . Some of the slats in my gable vents went missing, and
squirrels got in the attic. I know I have to get the squirrels out
before sealing the attic, but someone suggested putting in a ridge
vent and closing the gable vents completely. Would that work, and
would a ridge vent (the person mentioned Cora-Vent) be
squirrel-proof? &UR;  &LR; KEN RAKIP, North Andover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A &LR; . Those slats did not go missing; I'll bet the squirrels
chewed them out to get in. At any rate, a ridge vent is an
excellent idea, and closing the gable vents is even better because
closing them is recommended when a ridge vent is installed. Be
sure, also, to install soffit vents, a continuous vent strip going
the full length of each soffit (the underpart of the roof
overhang). Gable vents, by the way, are those at each end of the
attic.
</P>
<P>
   And make sure the old gable vents are really sealed up tight.
The squirrels found a home in the attic that is warm and dry, and
unless you dispatch them or exile them far away, they will try
their hardest to get back in. The ridge vent is squirrel-proof; at
least I have not heard of any ridge vents succumbing to rodents.
</P>
<P>
   Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton chats online Thursdays, 1-2
p.m. To participate, go to http://www.boston.com and use the
keyword: Chat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
