<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5527 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-JUBILO-BOS &LR;      05-25 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-JUBILO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIVIL WAR'S AFTERMATH VIVIDLY EVOKED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE YEAR OF JUBILO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Novel of the Civil War &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Howard Bahr &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Henry Holt, 376 pp., $25 &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In abolitionist Henry Clay Work's song, ``the year of jubilo'' _
the time when ``the master's run'' and ``Lincoln's soldiers have
come'' _ holds the promise of ``the kingdom a-coming.'' But in
Howard Bahr's novel, June 1865, the first month of that ``year of
jubilo,'' is a dark and brutal time when the passions of the Civil
War had not been spent, but continued to flame.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Year of Jubilo'' is the second novel by Bahr, who teaches
English at a community college in Tennessee. But it will come to
most readers as his first, because his powerful and elegiac ``The
Black Flower'' received only limited circulation after its
publication in 1997 by a small Southern press _ and, as luck would
have it, was published the same month as the best-selling ``Cold
Mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   That misfortune should excuse Bahr if the first few pages of
``Jubilo'' seem to echo the homeward journey that is the center of
``Cold Mountain.'' But once Bahr has brought Gawain Harper, a
Confederate soldier, back home to the burned-out Mississippi town
where he had once taught English and where a woman named Morgan
Rhea is perhaps waiting for him, ``The Year of Jubilo'' becomes an
exploration of war's aftermath through the eyes of both soldiers
and civilians.
</P>
<P>
   As was the case with ``The Black Flower,'' Bahr is able to move
_ sometimes within the space of just a sentence or two _ from the
harsh language of brutal events to the poetry of enduring beauty.
</P>
<P>
   The occupying Union force holds only a tenuous control in
Cumberland, virtually under siege by a renegade force of
Confederate bushwhackers led by a cruelly vengeful smuggler turned
partisan commander who styles himself ``King'' Solomon Gault. The
inevitable battle is a furious charge through the Yankee camp by
Gault's renegades, who come perilously close to wiping out the
Union force and triggering a general insurrection.
</P>
<P>
   As was the case with ``The Black Flower,'' Bahr has compressed a
military action into just a very few pages, suggesting in
powerfully packed sentences whole chapters of lesser Civil War
novels: ``Gault saw the gun and drew back on the reins just enough
so that the column flowed around him. He was two files deep in the
column now, eight or ten riders ahead of him, their horses' hooves
throwing great clods of mud, and those eager ones were the first of
Gault's men to die. The canister raked them, horses reared or
tumbled headlong, men were riven, sliced, transformed. A severed
arm struck Gault in the chest, balanced an instant on the pommel,
then fell away. Gault was flecked with blood, with bits of flesh
and bone; his horse leapt over the fallen, and in an instant, he
was among the gunners.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bahr heightens the impact of these scenes by interspersing
them with tenderly domestic vignettes of townsfolk savoring the
first hopeful weeks of peace in the moments before they are swept
up in the unfolding horror. ``They were crossing the yard, Morgan
lifting her skirts from the mud, Gawain already shaping in his mind
the words he would only get to say once, so he better have them
right. A little cat had come from somewhere and was parading before
them, tail in the air. Suddenly, the cat darted away, vanished as
cats will do, and Gawain saw men running and at the same time heard
the firing down the road. But his mind refused the implications,
accepted only the weight of Morgan's arm on his own, the sound of
her laughing at the cat, their steady progress across the yard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Year of Jubilo'' is, at its richest, a novel about
veterans, not in the familiar World War II or Vietnam War setting,
but in the distant world of the Civil War. It cannot be just
coincidence that Bahr served in Vietnam, for he has made his own
the subject of the simultaneous hopes and dreads of the returning
soldiers, returning from ``the dark adventure'' in which their old
world ``had been consumed and left them with little but the taste
of ashes for their trials.''.
</P>
<P>
   As one of Gault's embittered vets tells it, ``like many another,
he had sustained himself with the belief that the wastelands
through which he had passed had no application to him _ that if he
could just reach home, he would find it magically unchanged, the
same people walking about the streets, the ground ready for the
plow, mail waiting for him at the post office.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all been to a strange country, all us boys,'' says a
veteran whom Harper has met on the road and who accompanies him on
his homecoming. ``I do not say that to condescend nor to elicit
sympathy, mind _ I only state it as a fact that you must agree to
if you are to begin to understand.'' And that understanding is what
Bahr wants to convey, too.
</P>
<P>
   Readers who were fortunate enough to have found ``The Black
Flower'' _ often by word of mouth or, later, in its paperback
edition _ will find that it was not a one-time-only achievement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
