u l BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-ART-BOS &LR;      05-25 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (l and f coding)  
 ROBERT BENTLEY INC. WROTE THE MANUAL ON CAR ENTHUSIASM  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Out of public view, in a long, narrow chamber, accessed
from outside by a large door at one end, a Porsche hangs on a lift.
It is being taken apart bolt by bolt, panel by panel, wire by wire.
These are valuable parts and what happens with them will help other
Porsches, in other places, perform better and longer.
</P>
<P>
   You would not expect to find a chop shop tucked up against a
stately, wood-sheathed building that once was a luxurious home on
Massachusetts Avenue near Harvard Law School. But here it is, with
one difference: Call it a chop shop with portfolio. Because the
meticulous disassembly of autos that goes on in this room is to
chop shops what brain surgery is to the making of sweetbreads.
</P>
<P>
   This shop, and the 150-year-old, multifloored and majestic
building to which it is attached, form the headquarters of the
publishing firm Robert Bentley Inc. From this building _ as books,
on CD, and over the Internet _ flows some of the world's finest
technical writing on automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   Auto manufacturers such as Porsche, Volkswagen, and Audi rely on
Bentley to produce the propietary, highly technical manuals and
technical bulletins that will be used within the industry. In
addition, Bentley publishes service manuals for auto enthusiasts
and small shops, as well as an array of enthusiast books written by
outside authors.
</P>
<P>
   It is probably not what Robert Bentley had in mind in 1950 when
he started the business _ as an importer of foreign books _ when he
could not lay hands on a copy of Kant's ``Critique of Pure
Reason.'' He went on from there to import the complete works of
Freud and charged the shrinks of that day for each book what they
charged for an hour of their time: $25.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1970s, Bentley was importing books on the MG and had
developed a relationship with Volkswagen. Robert Bentley retired in
1979 and by 1982, when his son Michael, who is now the company's
president, took over, Bentley was a publisher, not an importer, and
autos, not philosophy and psychology, were its staple.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the book-publishing (and, in effect, the electronic)
divisions of the business are broken up into two divisions: the
``enthusiast'' segment and the professional services group.
</P>
<P>
   The need for information for both groups has grown increasingly
critical, said Michael Bentley, as cars have become ever more
complex, with advances such as fuel injection, ABS systems, and
electronic controls, and model cycles have grown increasingly
shorter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our idea as a company,'' Bentley said, ``is to do the best
technical writing.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is why the cars featured in their manuals are taken
apart, in painstaking order, in that shop out back.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no literature to guide disassembly,'' he said. That
means that as a car is taken apart, its pieces must be spread in a
precise pattern across the shop. It can then be reassembled, with
photographs taken of the entire process.
</P>
<P>
   While not strictly part of the enthusiasts group, but certainly
available to the public, service manuals form a significant part of
the Bentley business. They offer manuals that include British
sports cars, German cars, Volvos, Saabs, Italian sports cars, and
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are for owners who want to know everything about their
BMW Z3,'' said Bentley.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they publish books by non-house authors that offer
technical, performance, and driving tips for a range of vehicles:
``The Jeep Owner's Bible,'' ``Toyota Truck and Land Cruiser Owner's
Bible,'' the ``Harley-Davidson Evolution V-Twin Bible,'' and
``Civic Duty,'' a guide to tricking out your Honda Civic.
</P>
<P>
   For the more esoteric enthusiast there are books on racing
aerodynamics, driving at high speeds, exhaust and intake systems,
fuel injection, and electronic systems. Bentley will also soon
publish the Road &AMP; Track Illustrated Automotive Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   Lighter enthusiast reading includes such titles as ``A French
Kiss With Death'' about Steve McQueen and the making of the movie
``LeMans''; ``Battle for the Beetle,'' a history of Volkswagen's
resurrection from the ashes of World War II; and ``Corvette 427,''
which details one man's two-year effort to turn a 1967 drag racer
into a street-legal machine.
</P>
<P>
   There are books on American cars and trucks, books on racing
technique, heroes and history, even a book celebrating the days
when high horsepower ruled Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The professional services group is basically a propietary area.
In this part of the operation, Bentley technicians, writers, and
editors, guided by the companies for which they work _ Porsche,
Audi, Volkswagen, the aircraft engine company Pratt &AMP; Whitney _
develop technical literature for in-house use. A perpetual give and
take _ both online and in person _ between Bentley specialists and
industry experts results in detailed manuals and bulletins that
break cars and engines down to the last bolt and gasket.
</P>
<P>
   The public can access Bentley offerings through
www.bentleypublishers.com. For the industry, the portal is
www.infofoundry.com. In the near future, Bentley says, the public
will be able to get online and develop a reparte, asking Bentley
experts questions and chatting among themselves about things
automotive.
</P>
<P>
   And it all takes place in an old and stately former home across
the river in Cambridge. Not the place you'd expect to find
merchants of speed and performance. Certainly not where you'd
expect to find a chop shop _ even one with portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 1458EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5536 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BILLBOARDS-RESURGENCE     05-25 1364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILLBOARDS-RESURGENCE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-SPEED TECHNOLOGY GIVES LIFT TO BILLBOARD INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo and a graphic are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the summer of 1987, a few years before digital imaging
helped revive a billboard industry that had grown overly dependent
on Joe Camel, and Mike Auterio was excited about his first day on
the job.
</P>
<P>
   For a rookie billboard painter, Auterio had landed a dream
assignment. He and his boss were to paint a likeness of Bud Light
mascot Spuds MacKenzie onto the giant Budweiser billboard affixed
to the south face of the old Boston Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``It stayed up for a whole year,'' Auterio says of a billboard
that took two weeks to paint.
</P>
<P>
   Today, high-tech printers can spit out billboard ads almost as
easily as the office copying machine can reproduce a boss's memo.
Ads are printed on big sheets of flexible vinyl that are later
tightly tied to a billboard's frame. Instead of two weeks of
painting, a new billboard can now go up in under an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Such technical advances have also almost single-handedly rescued
an industry that only a few years ago was thought to be in danger
of dying.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, critics who derided billboards as visual
pollution had reason to gloat about the medium's imminent demise,
and few would have predicted that industry would see a nearly 10
percent gain in 1999 as revenue reached $2.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for this gloom and doom was the Internet, which
threatened to divert ad dollars away from billboards on real-world
highways to banner ads on the Web's information highway.
</P>
<P>
   Even more ominous, the tobacco industry, once the industry's
biggest client, was spending less and less on billboard advertising
every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a sense of impending doom,'' says Liz Palumbo,
president and general manager of AK Media/MA of Stoneham, &UR;  &LR; Mass.,
one of the region's largest billboard companies. ``We were under
attack.''
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to high-speed technology, the industry is on the
rebound _ even though tobacco companies stopped all cigarette
advertising on billboards last year as part of their historic
settlement with state attorneys general.
</P>
<P>
   Being able to put up new billboards so quickly has brought the
industry a host of new clients from fashion houses such as the Gap
to Hollywood studios promoting new movies.
</P>
<P>
   Even dot-com start-ups have been turning to a medium that
debuted in the mid 19th century by putting signs up along railway
lines. By one estimate, dot-coms spent $100 million on outdoor
advertising in 1999, using billboards to drive traffic to their Web
sites _ or to catch the eye perhaps of a venture capitalist zipping
by in a Mercedes or a Lexus.
</P>
<P>
   This ability to get new billboards up quickly has created new
opportunities for billboard advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   During the Boston Marathon, for example, athletic shoe and
apparel maker Adidas-Salomon AG was able to create a special
billboard campaign tailored specifically to the race. A decade ago,
when billboards took weeks to paint by hand and stayed up for
months at a time, such a campaign would have been impractical, if
not impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Fast turnaround times have made so-called teaser campaigns more
popular. Recently some billboards went up with the cryptic message
of ``Carpe noctem'' and nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a Latin scholar knew the phrase supposedly means ``seize
the night,'' the billboards offered no other information. What was
being advertised? A dating service? A light beer? A new movie?
Motorists were left to wonder for two weeks. Then new billboards
went up. There was the same ``Carpe noctem'' message only this time
there was also an image of a Milky Way candy bar.
</P>
<P>
   Movie studios, in particular, think two-week billboard teaser
campaigns are highly effective.
</P>
<P>
   Painting billboards in all kinds of weather was an arduous job,
as rookie painter Auterio quickly learned 13 years ago when he was
painted Spuds MacKenzie on the side of Boston Garden.
</P>
<P>
   On a window-washer's scaffold high above Causeway Street, young
Auterio and his boss began work by covering the billboard's
previous ad with a coat of white paint.
</P>
<P>
   When the coat dried, the two men pressed a series of stencils
over the billboard's surface. Each of the 70 or so stencils bore a
small piece of the billboard's big picture, and just making the
stencils, a job done back at the shop, took nearly a week.
</P>
<P>
   After matching the right stencil to the right spot on the
billboard, Auterio would rub charcoal over the stencil. The
charcoal would leave a faint impression of the stencil's image that
had to be quickly retraced in red pencil.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had to work fast,'' Auterio says. ``Or the wind would blow
away the charcoal dust, and you'd have to start again.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a jigsaw puzzle coming together, the billboard's outline
would slowly take shape. Imagine a page from a paint-by-numbers
coloring book, only on the grand scale, and that was what Auterio
and his boss had to show for many days of work. To finish the job,
the pair used oil paints to color between the lines left by the
stencils.
</P>
<P>
   These days, as AK Media/MA's production manager, Auterio has
left his paint brush behind and taken up with the computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to work outdoors all the time, rain or shine,'' he
says. ``Now I work indoors.''
</P>
<P>
   When billboards were painted by hand, many big advertisers
stayed away from them. In the days of pencil and paint, putting up
200 billboards could mean using 200 different teams of painters,
and results were rarely uniform.
</P>
<P>
   That was unacceptable to fashion houses, which insist on
magazine-quality images that can be perfectly reproduced.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just that the skill of individual painters varied
widely. Their speed varied too. Some were fast. Some weren't.
</P>
<P>
   That was another drawback. When using TV, print, and billboard
ads, many advertisers aim to launch all phases of an ad campaign at
the same time, notes Francis J. Kelly III, chief marketing officer
of Arnold Communciations, a Boston ad agency.
</P>
<P>
   In the days of painting by hand, putting up 200 or 300 new
billboards around the country within a few days of one another
could be a logistical challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with digital imaging, billboard companies can guarantee
uniform results and timely installation.
</P>
<P>
   Putting up a billboard now differs a great deal from the days
when painters such as Auterio swayed high over Causeway Street.
</P>
<P>
   Today the process begins with an advertiser and its ad agency
agreeing on the image and message of a billboard ad. Next, a dummy
of the image is sent to a special printing shop, where it can be
replicated hundreds of times. At this point, a billboard is a sheet
of vinyl, which is often rolled up in a tube for shipping to
billboard companies across the country.
</P>
<P>
   To put up a new billboard, a company such as AK Media/MA will
dispatch a crew in a truck equipped with a crane. At a billboard
site, the vinyl is hoisted from the truck with the crane, then
lashed to the billboard's steel frame, much as a drumhead is
stretched tight over the hollow shell of a tom-tom.
</P>
<P>
   New technologies promise even more breakthroughs.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, residents now routinely see buses ``wrapped'' in an
advertiser's message. In New York and Los Angeles, the same
techniques have been used to ``wrap'' office buildings in ads.
Could such wraps soon be spotted in the Hub?
</P>
<P>
   As cable TV stations proliferate, as more and more new magazines
hit the newsstands, many advertisers are concluding that billboards
are one of the best ways to reach consumers bombarded from all
sides by marketing messages, says Nancy Fletcher, the president of
the Outdoor Advertising Association of America, a billboard trade
group.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with remote controls, consumers have grown adept at tuning
out 30-second TV ads. But as consumers spend more and more time
commuting in their cars, Fletcher says, billboards have emerged as
``the last unavoidable medium.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
