<SLUG> BC-HOME-SALES-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME SALES DROP 6.2 PERCENT IN APRIL 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN VAMES   
 c. 2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sales of existing homes dropped in April as home buyers
continued to feel the pinch of higher interest rates. Existing home
sales fell 6.2 percent in April to a 4.88 million annual rate, the
National Association of Realtors reported Thursday. The decline
comes on the back of an upwardly revised March home sales gain of
9.2 percent, which was initially reported as a 1.5 percent gain
last month.
</P>
<P>
   Year-over-year, sales of preowned homes were down 6.9 percent in
April, indicating that last-year's feverish housing market has
eased significantly since the Federal Reserve begun its efforts to
raise interest rates last June. The interest rate increases were an
attempt to slow the economy, which have so far resulted in a 1.75
percentage-point gain in short-term rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the market is adjusting to generally higher mortgage
interest rates with buyers switching to adjustable-rate loans, and
in some cases buying less expensive homes,'' said Fred Flick, vice
president of economic research at the Realtors association.
</P>
<P>
   According to mortgage giant Freddie Mac, the Fed's most recent
increase in short-term rates on May 16 continued to pusar
fixed-rate mortgaged climbed to a five-year high of 8.64 percent in
theor week and 7.23 percent the prior n rates adds signifige home
buyer. F 30-year fixed-rr month than for the same mortgage today.
</P>
<P>
   But even with demand slackening, the housing market remains at
historically high levels, and home prices in most regions are
continuing to rise. The national average existing home price in
April was up 4.6 percent year-over-year to $136,700 -- almost
double the rate of overall consumer inflation during the same
period. That suggests that in addition to higher mortgage rates,
the slower housing market may in part be due to a low supply of
available homes.
</P>
<P>
   That dearth of homes, however, may be reversing. The Realtors
association said the supply of homes, measured by months' supply at
the current sales rate, rose slightly to 3.9 months in April from
3.1 months in March. But still, the supply is 22 percent
lowersupply.
</P>
<P>
   ``More sellers are placing their homes on the market, so the
tight housing situation we've seen in many areas is now beginning
to ease,'' said Dennis Cronk, president of the Realtors
association. ``Our hope is this will bring a better balance between
buyers and sellers in those areas where multiple bids on homes have
become fairly common.''
</P>
<P>
   Regionally, sales in the Northeast declined most, down 7.7
percent from March and 9.1 percent year-over-year, even though
prices in the region rose 6.3 percent versus April 1999. Home sales
in the Midwest were down 5.3 percent from March, and down 7.8
percent from the prior year while sales in the South were down 7.2
percent from the prior month and down 4.5 percent versus the prior
year. Sales in the West were down 3.7 percent from March and 8.5
percent year-over-year.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 1513EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
