<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5555 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-COURTS-CASELOADS-HNS &LR;      05-25 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURTS-CASELOADS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TEXAS FEDERAL COURTS SEE LITTLE RELIEF AS CASELOADS MUSHROOM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARO ROBBINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Overloaded with smugglers and undocumented
immigrants caught along the Rio Grande, the federal courts from San
Antonio to El Paso together shouldered more felony cases last year
than any other region in the nation, data show.
</P>
<P>
   This distinction, which had belonged to courts in San Diego for
at least a decade, arrives at a time when federal prosecutors along
the Texas-Mexico border are bracing for more work.
</P>
<P>
   Come July 1, several county district attorneys along the border
have said they will no longer prosecute the small but numerous drug
busts made by federal agents at international bridges and
checkpoints. The federal agents often turn over smaller cases to
local officials rather than sending them to federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   If the county district attorneys follow through with their
threats, federal prosecutors in San Antonio and Austin will be
shifted to the swamped U.S. District Courts in El Paso and possibly
Del Rio and Pecos.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as courthouse staffs try to keep pace with deluged
dockets, they are making more mistakes, some of which have
potential to derail prosecutions, some officials say. Other errors
are fodder for appeals, however frivolous.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Bill Blagg, who oversees the San Antonio-based
Western District of Texas, is more likely to cringe than boast
about the milestone that came last year with filing nearly 3,800
felony cases, roughly four times as many as in the Dallas-based
Northern District.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather not be No. 1,'' Blagg said.
</P>
<P>
   Blagg expects to have an additional 500 cases a year once the
district attorney in El Paso stops prosecuting small drug busts
made by Customs Service and Border Patrol agents.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Blagg's counterpart in the Houston-based Southern
District of Texas expects the caseload to increase with at least
400 busts formerly handled by local prosecutors in Brownsville and
McAllen.
</P>
<P>
   Blagg sympathizes with the cash-strapped district attorneys, but
from his perspective, the small cases involve dime-a-dozen drug
couriers. Prosecuting them burns time better spent building cases
against significant smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all we do is prosecute `mules,' we're not doing our jobs
very well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As Blagg's caseload swelled last year, Texas' Western District
barely edged past California's Southern District, located in San
Diego, which had outpaced its border counterparts since at least
1990.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors there say a budget freeze and staff vacancies caused
filings to fall slightly to 3,700. But, with several new hires,
they said they are on pace to hit 4,000 cases this year.
</P>
<P>
   At least two proposals to increase the number of judges, clerks
and other courthouse staff along the border are pending in
Congress. No one knows yet if they will win support from lawmakers
in interior states. While the bills await action in Washington,
strains are beginning to show along the border.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Bill Putnicki, the chief clerk in Texas' Western
District, wrote a colleague that his staff, forced by the onslaught
of filings to work faster, seemed to be making more mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Putnicki noted problems with keeping track of
trial deadlines. Missing those deadlines can lead to _ but, he
said, had not yet resulted in _ charges being dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, defense lawyers are ready to capitalize on slip-ups
by judges, many of whom are doing double duty _ overseeing cases in
their own courts and helping out on the border.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 1519EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
