<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCK-REVIEW-APPLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIONA APPLE THROWS HERSELF INTO HER MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Lucky for Fiona Apple she packed her sweater, scarf,
and a full-length black coat.
</P>
<P>
   FleetBoston Pavilion opened its summer season Wednesday night,
but it felt more like a mid-winter gathering, with 2,500 fans
decked out in heavy jackets and, in one case, huddled under a wool
blanket.
</P>
<P>
   Waiflike and windblown, Apple clutched her coat around her for
protection from both the elements and, it would seem, the perils of
a large venue. She and her songs lose much in the translation to
the stage. They're like finely-cut gems that require the proper
setting to shine as fiercely as they can; in the open space, they
sacrifice definition and nuance.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say Apple didn't make a valiant effort. She was in
grand spirits, without a glimmer of the cranky, impetuous girl who
stormed off the stage at New York's Roseland Ballroom a couple of
months ago because the mix was off. Wednesday night, she pushed
hard to keep pace with the great washes of sound spewed by her
stunning five-piece band, and then pushed harder just to fill the
acres of air surrounding her _ shredding her voice during several
songs, including the show opener, the pile-driving ``On the
Bound.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple was like a feral animal on stage, caught in the emotional
maelstrom inspired by the music. She quite literally threw herself
into the songs _ flinging her limbs and her hair and her chaotic
vibrato, as well, to the winds during ``Criminal,'' a woozy and
brazen fit of honesty, and ``Mistake,'' a triumphant ode to messing
up.
</P>
<P>
   She alternately sat at the grand piano and stood center stage,
and the quieter moments found her more in control. ``Sullen Girl,''
from Apple's 1996 debut ``Tidal,'' revealed the torch singer
ambling through a smoky, dismally beautiful landscape. Likewise,
``I'll Know'' (from her recent, exquisite ``When the Pawn. . .'' )
was an agonizingly lovely study in intimacy _ all brushed strokes
and languid tones.
</P>
<P>
   Apple is the rarest of birds: a surprising-sounding pop artist.
She came out swinging on ``Fast As You Can,'' a complicated
kiss-off whose crazy rhythms flowed through her like jolts of
electricity. ``Paper Bag'' was equal parts Tin Pan Alley and Paul
McCartney, a piano ditty with the dark soul of a sensitive girl.
And though it was next to impossible to re-create the quirky,
layered studio orchestrations that hang like ornaments on her
tremulous alto, the sound of this show was still captivating.
``Limp,'' for example, was a sea of glassy textures and burbling
keyboards.
</P>
<P>
   For an encore, Apple treated her audience to an unexpected
cover, sung to a scratchy instrumental tape, of Cole Porter's ``It
Was Just One of Those Things.'' She was, indeed, the antidote to
pop's current spate of cookie-cutter cutie-pies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 1524EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
