<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5566 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-25 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WOMEN, PAID LESS THAN MEN, HAVE THINGS FIGURED OUT BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ At this time of year, one statistic that is
widely quoted _ and extremely deceptive _ is that the typical
female worker earns about 75 cents for every dollar that a man
earns. In a sense, it's a great statistic because you can use it to
support just about anything you want.
</P>
<P>
   Feminists certainly can use it to say that women are dreadfully
underpaid, but I prefer to look at it another way: It proves that
your typical male is about 33 percent stupider than your typical
female.
</P>
<P>
   All right, so neither perception is exactly accurate, mainly
because the statistic itself is dreadfully flawed. It simply
compares the salaries of all employed males and all employed
females, regardless of type of job or years of experience. So Bill
Gates fits into the same category as someone who asks, ``Do you
want fries with that?''
</P>
<P>
   When you have people of both sexes in comparable jobs with
similar experience, the gap is more like a dime than a quarter.
That's discrimination, certainly, but it may be based as much on
negotiating skills as blatant sexism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that women sell themselves cheap _ and
companies know it,'' Working Woman magazine says in an article on
its Web site (workingwoman.com). ``The vast majority of women at
every employment level do not price their skills at market value.''
</P>
<P>
   The remaining 15-cent gap is mainly because women frequently
interrupt their careers for long periods to raise children, and
tend to select lower-paying careers than men do. Sometimes they
don't have enough formal education to land a high-paying job, but
often they simply prefer work that is emotionally rewarding rather
than financially lucrative.
</P>
<P>
   And those who return to the work force after being absent for
several years might well feel insecure about their worth to a
company, so they underprice themselves.
</P>
<P>
   (Yes, we're talking in generalizations. There are millions of
exceptions.)
</P>
<P>
   Some people with a political agenda will rail at the unfairness
of it all, saying that society doesn't value the contributions that
women make, and that women are still victims of the male-dominated
workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Did anybody ever stop to think that maybe the women are the ones
who have it right? Instead of proving that women are underpaid,
maybe the statistic proves that men emphasize work too much.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. Women shouldn't be discriminated against.
They have every right to be just as obsessive about money as men
are. They should learn to negotiate tougher so they don't get
cheated, and the younger ones are already helping themselves by
finishing college in far greater numbers than their mothers did.
</P>
<P>
   But a lot of that 15-cent gap is because they have different
values than men do. And those values may be worth a heck of a lot
more than 15 cents.
</P>
<P>
   In the relatively few times when a woman becomes the CEO of a
large corporation, she is invariably asked how she manages to
balance such a heavy workload with the demands of her family.
That's a great question, but it's also a great question for a male
CEO. Yet somehow that never gets asked _ it's just assumed that his
wife takes care of it.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study of female high school students found that many
are avoiding technology careers, not because they're intimidated by
the work, but because they think it would make for a boring career.
</P>
<P>
   Would even the staunchest feminist want those girls to go into
technology simply so the 15-cent gap could be narrowed? I doubt it.
</P>
<P>
   Even after all of society's changes in the last 30 years, men
still feel pressure _ much of it self-imposed _ to get that big
paycheck, even if it means having a career they don't enjoy or
sacrificing a family life for the sake of a promotion.
</P>
<P>
   So how do male CEOs balance work and family? Badly, usually.
Passing the buck to your spouse isn't balancing work and family;
it's ducking responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Women need to learn how to negotiate better and fight sexism so
they can knock a dime out of that 25-cent pay gap. But they ought
to think long and hard about whether those remaining 15 cents are
worth it.
</P>
<P>
   And so should men.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 1525EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
