<HEADER>
A5588 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     05-25 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO EVERYTHING THERE'S A SEASON, AND THIS SEASON PROVED IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Questions, observations, opinions, annoyances and other oddities
in a television season we can finally call over:
</P>
<P>
   Is Tom Green human?
</P>
<P>
   Quick, what was ``Brutally Normal''? ``The Strip''? ``Safe
Harbor''?
</P>
<P>
   Canceled shows I'll miss most: ``Freaks &AMP; Geeks'' on NBC, ``Now
&AMP; Again'' on CBS, ``Get Real'' on Fox, ``Le Femme Nikita'' on USA.
</P>
<P>
   Canceled show I'll miss least: Showtime's ``Linc's,'' perhaps
the worst-written series in years.
</P>
<P>
   Renewals that astound: Showtime's ``Rude Awakening.'' Kiddin'
me?
</P>
<P>
   Most-watched program: Tuesday edition of ABC's ``Who Wants To Be
a Millionaire,'' at 29 million. Second: Sunday night's
``Millionaire.'' Third: ``Millionaire'' on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Least-watched: The first airing of WB's ``Mission Hill,'' at a
little less than 1 million. Next: The second episode of ``Mission
Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Most underappreciated: ``Beggars &AMP; Choosers'' on Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   Do we need three hours of ``Today''?
</P>
<P>
   I won't miss Vivica A. Fox, discarded from CBS' ``City of
Angels'' like a smelly sneaker relegated to the back porch.
</P>
<P>
   Bette Midler will be the latest film star to crash and burn on
network television.
</P>
<P>
   Has Tom Selleck's career been reduced to guest shots on
``Friends'' during sweeps?
</P>
<P>
   Most hilarious scene in a sitcom: Hal's (Bryan Cranston)
roller-disco number in Fox's ``Malcolm in the Middle.'' Utters Hal:
``That routine won me a gold medal, a macrame plant hanger and your
mother's heart, all in the same afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Leno or Letterman? Letterman.
</P>
<P>
   Regis or Kathie Lee? Regis.
</P>
<P>
   Star Jones or Lisa Ling? Ling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arthur'' or ``Blue's Clues?'' ``Arthur''
</P>
<P>
   ``Judging Amy'' will overtake ``NYPD Blue'' in the ratings, if
not next season, the season after that.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope ``Millionaire'' flops next fall and ABC is caught
with nothing with which to replace it. That would be sweet.
</P>
<P>
   More people now watch UPN than The WB. Oh my.
</P>
<P>
   How dismal is life for Fox? It hasn't launched a hit drama since
``Ally McBeal'' in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Latinos comprise 11 percent of the U.S. population and fill less
than 2 percent of speaking roles on television.
</P>
<P>
   1952: Elena Verdugo, the first actress of Latin descent to star
in a sitcom, played a Jewish secretary.
</P>
<P>
   1996: Puerto Rican actor Jimmy Smits is introduced as Victor
Sifuentes on ``NYPD Blue,'' a man of French and Portuguese
ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   2000: ``American Family,'' a drama about a Hispanic family, is a
sure shot to make the CBS schedule. Yeah, right. Says CBS President
Leslie Moonves when it doesn't: ``It wasn't a good fit at this
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Alex Nogales of the National Hispanic Media Coalition:
``It's dismal ... just dismal.''
</P>
<P>
   $750,000: The amount per episode each ``Friends'' cast member
will pocket next season, a salary bump of $625,000.
</P>
<P>
   $25,000: The amount it will take to fix the front porch of the
house ``Friends''' star Matthew Perry smashed with his car.
</P>
<P>
   1: The number of episodes it took for NBC to realize that ``The
Mike O'Malley Show'' lacked, well, growth potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ally McBeal,'' once one of the most intriguing series in prime
time, is now the most annoying. Where else could a major character
die and no one notice?
</P>
<P>
   With a dreadful ``Ally McBeal,'' a dreadful ``Ally,'' a dreadful
``Snoops,'' a wildly uneven ``The Practice,'' and a ``Chicago
Hope'' that couldn't be turned around, the projects of
producer/writer David E. Kelley should no longer be called
promising, sight unseen.
</P>
<P>
   Can't keep that Dick Wolf down, can we?
</P>
<P>
   Interesting how female characters in Steven Bochco's shows are
either too strong in the head or too weak in the knees.
</P>
<P>
   How fortunes for a sistah can change: Sanaa Lathan was virtually
ignored (except for the usual where-are-black-folks-in-TV inquiry)
at a press conference for the series ``Lateline'' just a few months
ago. Now the ``Love &AMP; Basketball'' star is besieged with interview
requests and TV scripts.
</P>
<P>
   How smart is CBS? It gets the NAACP off their backs by saving
the life of the high-profile black drama ``City of Angels,'' only
to send it out on a suicide mission next season against
``Millionaire'' on ABC and ``Will &AMP; Grace'' on NBC. I can hear a
CBS exec saying now, ``Hey, we gave it a shot, didn't we!''
</P>
<P>
   A season without Jennifer Love Hewitt. What shall we do?
</P>
<P>
   HBO's ``The Corner'' is this season's best miniseries.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have cable, your television is taking up space.
</P>
<P>
   Letters on Kathie Lee Gifford:
</P>
<P>
   ``... just despise the woman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``... just love that woman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With all that's going on in the world, should we really be
discussing this woman?''
</P>
<P>
   Are we still in the midst of a Jennifer Grey comeback?
</P>
<P>
   Couple with the best sexual chemistry: Willow (Alyson Hannigan)
and Tara (Amber Benson), the budding lesbian lovers of ``Buffy the
Vampire Slayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Couple with the worst sexual chemistry: Bryant Gumbel and Jane
Clayson of ``The Early Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Further proof that TV news anchors are merely actors playing
roles: Andrea Thompson leaves ``NYPD Blue'' for a news anchor gig
in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Nine words for the Daphne/Niles love commencement on
``Frasier'': Lois and Clark. Maggie and David. Thelma and Louise.
</P>
<P>
   If I hear, ``Is that your final answer?'' from one more
waitperson, it'll be their final breath.
</P>
<P>
   Best line: ``I've given up on TV,'' admits Shrug (Evan Handler)
on the canceled series ``It's Like, You Know.'' ``It makes up for
not reading.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 1537EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5598 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-HOLOCAUST-INSURANCE-H     05-25 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-INSURANCE-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; CHILDREN OF HOLOCAUST FILE CLASS-ACTION SUIT AGAINST INSURANCE
FIRM &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL DOUGAN &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c.2000 ?San Franciso Examiner &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Four children of people killed or persecuted
during the Holocaust have filed suit against one of Europe's
largest insurance companies, claiming the firm _ Assicurazioni
Generali _ has failed to honor policies purchased by their parents,
grandparents and uncles.
</P>
<P>
   The class-action suit could result in billions of dollars in
damages, according to an attorney for the San Francisco plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was filed Tuesday in San Francisco Superior Court by a
Los Angeles law firm and a nonprofit legal foundation on behalf of
San Francisco residents Ernest Smetana, Fritzie Wolf and Agnes
Heyman, and Marin County resident Paola Oreffice Kulp.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Carnicelli, head of Generali's American office in New
York, denied that his firm had treated the four Californians
unfairly and insisted that their attorneys had disseminated
``significant misinformation'' about his company.
</P>
<P>
   The suit seeks class-action status on behalf of as many as
20,000 Californians whose relatives were killed or persecuted in
the Holocaust and held insurance policies that were never honored.
</P>
<P>
   While this is the first class-action suit filed against Generali
in this state, other California residents have taken the company to
court. Los Angeles businessman Allen Stern, grandson of a Ukrainian
Jew who died in the Holocaust, established the legal precedent that
the Italian company can be sued in California because it does
business here.
</P>
<P>
   Several other California suits against Generali have ended in
confidential settlements.
</P>
<P>
   Smetana and Wolf, a brother and sister living in San Francisco,
claim their father, Hermann Smetana, purchased a Generali life
insurance policy in Austria in 1928. They believe an uncle also
bought insurance from the company.
</P>
<P>
   Heyman is the daughter of Mayer Friedman. She said he bought a
policy from Generali in Czechoslovakia naming her as beneficiary.
</P>
<P>
   Kulp said her parents and grandfather all had Generali life
insurance policies. Ironically, her father, Guilio Oreffice, and
grandfather, Gino Cavaglieri, were executives at Generali before
the war.
</P>
<P>
   All claim Generali was dishonest in denying their claims. The
lawsuit details their purported efforts, over five decades, to
obtain compensation from the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father had a brother and that brother had a daughter and
when that daughter returned from the concentration camp, she
managed to find (the policy papers) in the house,'' said Heyman,
76. She spoke at a press conference Wednesday announcing the
lawsuit, held at the Holocaust Memorial near the Palace of the
Legion of Honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's highway robbery, that's what it is,'' said Wolf, who
turned 90 on Monday. ``It's highly unfair. The money can never make
anything good, but they shouldn't profit by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney David Lash said the issue of Holocaust insurance
payments has reached a critical stage because of the age of the
plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day another Holocaust survivor dies and another
opportunity for justice dies with them,'' said Lash, who works with
the Bet Tzedek Legal Services, a nonprofit agency based in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   He said he expects the new suit to be resolved within a year or
two.
</P>
<P>
   Generali issued a statement late Wednesday claiming the company
has made more than $2 million in payments to Holocaust survivors
and their families, more than any other firm working with an
International Commission on Holocaust-era Insurance Claims.
</P>
<P>
   The Generali statement asserted that the company is ``committed
to the honorable treatment of Holocaust victims and their
beneficiaries,'' even though there is ``no legal obligation'' to
pay policies in Eastern European countries where the company's
assets were nationalized by communist governments.
</P>
<P>
   Generali was founded and run by Jews for most of its history,
although the company was ``Aryanized'' during the Holocaust period.
It is the largest insurance dealer in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The question of unpaid insurance claims for Holocaust-era
beneficiaries has been an issue since 1997, when a similar
class-action suit was filed against Generali in New York and state
Insurance Commissioner Charles Quackenbush launched hearings here.
At least five other European insurance companies also have been
charged with unfairly denying benefits to Holocaust victims and
their descendants.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, the state Legislature passed a bill requiring insurers
doing business in California to identify all policies sold to
Holocaust victims. Generali is currently challenging that bill in
court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 1545EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
