<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5600 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-STATE-ALCOHOL-HNS &LR;      05-25 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATE-ALCOHOL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CONCERN GROWS ABOUT ADS IN OUTDOORS PUBLICATION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUSSELL GOLD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ An advocacy group concerned about underage
drinking wants the Texas Department of Parks and Wildlife to get
rid of alcohol and cigarette advertisements in the annual guide to
the state's hunting and fishing rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Anheuser-Busch wants to have their (ads) on TV, we can't do
a great deal about that, but when our own state government steps in
and says let us help you relay these messages ... we find that
unacceptable,'' said Jim Haire, advertising chairman of Texans
Standing Tall, a coalition to prevent underage drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Haire brought his concern to the attention of the
state Sunset Advisory Commission, which is reviewing the operation
of the Parks and Wildlife Department.
</P>
<P>
   But changing the annual booklet, which says Texas Parks and
Wildlife prominently on the cover, will not be a simple matter,
primarily because the state sold the rights to publish the annual
guide to the Texas Monthly magazine for $100,000 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a misperception that we publish that and we don't,''
said spokeswoman Lydia Saldana, who said the department does
distribute the guide.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the annual guide was part of a larger push in the
Parks and Wildlife Department to aggressively pursue new funding.
</P>
<P>
   Texas spends $2.44 per person on state parks, the second-lowest
rate among the 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   In the past five years, Texas Monthly overhauled the annual
guide, adding articles and more advertisements printed on glossy
pages. A 1991 guide included only a single advertisement for Dodge
cars and trucks, Saldana said.
</P>
<P>
   There are seven pages of alcohol and cigarette ads in the most
recent guide, which was distributed to more than 3 million hunters
and fishermen. Ads for cars, off-road vehicles and fishing gear
cover another 14 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Saldana said the Parks and Wildlife Department was surprised by
the publication's evolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fair to say that we did not anticipate the number
and nature of ads that would be in the Outdoor Annual,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   David Dunham, a Texas Monthly senior vice president, said the
contract does not prohibit these ads. There is very little negative
reaction from hunters and fishermen, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The free guides are distributed at places where hunters and
fishermen purchase licenses. Dunham pointed out that children under
17 years old do not need a license and therefore would not
necessarily come into contact with the guide.
</P>
<P>
   The legal drinking age is 21.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Leo Berman, R-Tyler, introduced a bill in 1999 to
prohibit the Parks and Wildlife Department from being associated _
directly or indirectly _ with the promotion of alcoholic beverages.
</P>
<P>
   The bill never made it out of committee, due to pressure from
``beer distributors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Working with Parks Director Andy Sansom, he worked out a
compromise to make 50,000 guides with only a single hamburger
advertisement available to younger outdoorsmen through hunter
education classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the kids still have access to all the catalogues in the
Wal-Marts and everywhere else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, said Saldana, 100,000 guides without alcohol or
cigarette advertisements will be printed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Russell Gold can be reached by e-mail at
rdgold(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 1547EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5601 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-FILM-SHANGHAI-SPI &LR;      05-25 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SHANGHAI-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SHANGHAI NOON' HAS PLENTY OF KICK THANKS TO JACKIE CHAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: B  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stop me if you've heard this before. A Chinese guy wearing
Indian war paint, a braided waist-length ponytail and a blue silk
robe walks into an Old West saloon _ and it's Jackie Chan!
</P>
<P>
   Trust me, it's funny. Cowboys snicker, barmaids stand agog and
human dynamo Jackie transforms a simple barfight into a night at
the Chinese Opera.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie is Chon Wang, a boyishly sincere Forbidden City palace
guard in love with unattainable Princess Pei Pei (Lucy Liu in an
unusually docile performance). Seduced by romantic English fairy
tales she ``escapes'' to America, but her benefactors are not as
altruistic as they seem: A ransom note is left in her wake.
</P>
<P>
   Lovesick Chon accompanies the official retinue bearing the
ransom to Nevada, where he foils a train robbery, marries into a
wry Sioux tribe after sucking too long on a peace pipe, inherits a
horse smarter than Trigger and adopts both a guardian angel and an
unlikely sidekick.
</P>
<P>
   Owen Wilson, the garrulous would-be career criminal of ``Bottle
Rocket,'' is laid-back outlaw Roy O'Bannon, a gentle
philosopher-train robber who couldn't hit the side of the Rockies
with a rifle. Left for dead by his cutthroat gang, Roy and Chon
keep crossing paths and trading blows and banter, until Roy hitches
onto Chon's quest with hopes of pocketing a little royal gold for
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there's a bounty on their heads and a steely-eyed
marshal on their trail (Xander Berkeley, who cuts a sharp figure as
a corrupt lawman in black). It's going to take more than one
death-defying escape to get this gang who couldn't shoot straight
to their princess.
</P>
<P>
   This East-meets-Old-West action comedy is hardly original but
the unlikely team clicks. Jackie, well over 40, plays the gung-ho
rookie with a coy grin, a flying kick and a spirited, goofy charm.
Sardonic, low-key Wilson makes an inspired screen partner for
Jackie, his deadpan wit and a self-effacing patter balancing
Jackie's clownish mugging.
</P>
<P>
   Director Tom Dey strikes the right balance between white
hat/black hat showdowns, spirited action scenes and anachronistic
tongue-in-cheek punch lines (``My name is Chon Wang.'' ``John
Wayne? That's a terrible cowboy name!'').
</P>
<P>
   Jackie's furious moves are more often comic displays of
acrobatic slapstick than deadly showdowns but he tenses for the
climactic fight to the finish with a determined seriousness, his
grin turning grim and his eyes narrowing in concentration.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie doesn't have many years left for this kind of giddy
cinematic horseplay _ age is creeping into his face and he's not as
spry as he used to be _ but he still can turn a silly little action
comedy like this into a high-spirited, butt-kicking good time.
</P>
<P>
   Shanghai Noon. Directed by Tom Dey. Screenplay by Alfred Gough
and Miles Millar. Cast: Jackie Chan, Owen Wilson, Lucy Liu, Brandon
Merrill, Roger Yuan, Xander Berkeley, Jason Connery. Touchstone
Pictures. 110 minutes. PG-13 for sexual suggestion and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 1547EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5602 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-AMYIRVING-TEX     05-25 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-AMYIRVING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMY IRVING'S NEW FILM IS A GIFT FROM HER DIRECTOR HUSBAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Four years ago, Amy Irving appeared in husband Bruno
Barreto's Waxahachie-filmed ``Carried Away,'' a movie that didn't
exactly make her look like her normally radiant self. Which, the
actress admits, might just have been for the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody saw it,'' Irving laments during a Dallas stop. ``It's
one of the most beautiful films ever. But in it, in order for me to
play Dennis Hopper's childhood sweetheart, I had to age and look
really older and frumpier, and there's a very harsh love scene in a
kitchen with me naked, and it's not flattering. Ever since, I've
told Bruno he owes me a film in which I look really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Barreto responded with the romantic-comedy souffle ``Bossa
Nova.'' The charming, lightweight film is a valentine to Irving,
who is lovingly photographed as Mary Ann, a Rio de Janeiro-based
widow who teaches English as a second language and attracts the
attention of a recently divorced businessman, played by Brazilian
star Antonio Fagundes. Barreto also filmed it as a bouquet to Rio,
his hometown, where seven other characters find themselves joining
Mary Ann in a game of romantic musical chairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he captured the Rio that exists when you're in love,''
Irving says of Barreto. ``I know, because when we've worked
together, we've always fallen in love.''
</P>
<P>
   Irving was actually pitched the film 11 years ago, during her
first trip to Rio with Barreto, whose best-known film is his steamy
1978 debut, ``Dona Flor and Her Two Husbands.'' At the time,
another filmmaker had the rights to the material, but after nearly
a decade of cajoling, Barreto acquired them to make the film for
Irving. The 46-year-old actress suits the film's lead character,
who, like the actress, is both down-to-earth and a little quirky,
with a bit of a hippie past.
</P>
<P>
   Despite brief A-list status in the '80s after roles in such
movies as ``Carrie,'' ``Yentl'' and ``Crossing Delancey,'' Irving
remains best-known for once being married to Steven Spielberg. But
her show-biz career pre-dates Spielberg, stretching back to when
she was all of 9 months old. That's when her father, Jules Irving,
who directed the San Francisco Actors Workshop, cast her as the
baby in a stage production of ``Rumpelstiltskin.'' Her mother,
Priscilla Pointer, is also an actress (she has appeared in several
of Irving's films).
</P>
<P>
   The family moved to New York when Irving was 11, but she stayed
in touch with her San Francisco roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every summer I would come and stay with some friends who lived
in the Haight-Ashbury district, so I kind of watched it all
happen,'' she says, referring to San Francisco's hotbed of '60s
hippiedom. ``I mean, it was happening when I got there. Right
across the street from me was this house called the Clayton House.
On the ground floor were the hippies and the flower children. On
the second floor were the Hell's Angels and their girlfriends, and
on the third floor were prostitutes. It was a very diverse area.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite that turn-on and drop-out atmosphere, Irving stayed
focused on her goal: a career in Hollywood. And after finishing
school and muddling through early professional hiccups such as a
miscast part in a 1975 episode of ``Happy Days,'' she broke through
in two Brian De Palma movies: 1976's ``Carrie,'' in which she
figures into the movie's hand-sprouting-from-the-grave conclusion,
and 1978's ``The Fury,'' in which she plays a telekinetic teen-ager
recruited to find a similarly gifted/cursed peer.
</P>
<P>
   No fan of horror flicks, Irving soon moved on to romances
(''Honeysuckle Rose,'' ``The Competition'') and minor stardom,
which she says taught her a few things about preserving her
offscreen image.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember coming in (to do interviews) for `The Competition'
to Dallas and Fort Worth,'' she says, referring to the 1980 film
with Richard Dreyfuss that centers on a piano competition more or
less based on Fort Worth's Van Cliburn competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was supposed to do a Q-and-A after the screening. The mayor
of Cowtown took me to all these honky-tonks. We were drinking
tequila, and then we had to come back to the film. I was out there
just saying anything, I was drunk as a skunk. I learned that you
have to have a little decorum and behave yourself during these
things.''
</P>
<P>
   That became even more important in 1985, when she married
Spielberg, with whom she had a son, Max, who turns 15 next month.
The marriage only lasted four years, but she and the director stay
in touch, especially when it comes to trying to urge along Max's
budding talent as a writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Max doesn't know how good he is,'' she says. ``He wouldn't let
me read (his stories) until I would tell him, `I want to see your
work.' I was so blown away by them. He didn't believe me. He'd say,
`You're my mom, you have to say these things.' I'd say, `No, this
is really good writing.' I sent them to his father, and his father
wrote him this fan letter back, and even signed it as `Steven'
instead of `Dad' so it was a professional thing, not a father
thing. Now I'm showing his stories to writer friends of mine,
because I want him to know _ he doesn't love writing, but it just
comes so easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this shouldn't come as a surprise to Irving, who
seems to have a knack for finding men whose talents show themselves
early. Like Spielberg, Barreto seems to have been born with a
camera in his hand _ Irving says that he made his first film when
he was 16 (his grandmother financed it). He did ``Dona Flor'' when
he was 20. (Spielberg was pushing 25 when his 1971 TV movie
``Duel'' put him on the map.) Irving never appeared in one of
Spielberg's movies, but with ``Bossa Nova'' she'll have appeared in
four of Barreto's, including the one that brought them together,
1990's ``A Show of Force.'' (The couple has a 10-year-old son,
Gabriel.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a love-at-first-sight experience,'' she says. ``I
didn't really believe in love at first sight, but when we met each
other, we recognized each other. And we had this lunch where he
asked me to do the film, and I kept thinking, `Oh, God, be
professional, don't get involved with your director, you've gotta
make a movie.' It was just stronger than both of us, and 10 days
into the film, we were in love. That was mutual. I'd never had that
happen. So I guess we're both romantics in that way.''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
