<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5603 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-ESTATE-TAX-0526-COX     05-25 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESTATE-TAX-0526-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE COMMITTEE APPROVES PHASE-OUT OF FEDERAL ESTATE TAXES
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Setting up a classic fight over whether tax breaks
favor the rich or the poor, a House committee voted 24-11 Thursday
to phase out the federal estate tax over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Ways and Means Committee action could be followed by a House
vote early next month. Three Democrats joined the committee's
unanimous Republicans in voting for the measure.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has indicated he would veto the bill in its
present form because it unfairly benefits the rich and might
jeopardize federal programs due to lost tax revenue. Clinton vetoed
a similar bill last year.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which has bipartisan support from 240 lawmakers in the
435-member House, would affect roughly 58,000 estates a year which
pay about $27 billion in federal taxes.
</P>
<P>
   When fully implemented by 2010, the bill would result in a loss
to the federal government of about $50 billion a year in taxes,
according to committee staff.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans hailed the measure as a boon to small business
owners and family farmers, but Democrats said it would affect
relatively few _ but very rich _ people.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, the committee chairman, said ``the
time has come to bury the death tax.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No American, no matter their income, should be forced to pay
60 percent of their savings, their business or their farm in taxes
when they die,'' Archer said. ``This death tax doesn't just affect
the rich, it affects Americans up and down the economic spectrum.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats questioned Archer's comments about the rate of the
tax and whom it affects.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Pete Stark, D-Calif., noted that the average estate tax
rate ranges from 15 percent to 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning by Democratic members, committee staffers said
that estate taxes are paid by the estates of about 2 percent of
those who die each year. Of those, about 3 percent are primarily
farm-related estates.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 percent of the estates that pay taxes _ typically those
valued at more than $5 million _ pay about half of the estate
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that estates valued at $20 million or more pay an average
of 15 percent in estate taxes, Stark said ``I'd like to hear the
case that that is an onerous rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning from Stark, committee staffers said they
didn't know of any estates that paid taxes at a rate of 50 percent
or more.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter from Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers and White
House Chief of Staff John Podesta, the administration said ``repeal
of these taxes would be fiscally unwise, would reduce the overall
fairness and progressivity of the tax system and would harm
charitable giving.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash., said the estate tax dishonors
``the hard work of those who have passed on....There is no moral,
social, or economic justification for this tax.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mark Foley, R-Fla., noted that First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton, in her Senate campaign in New York, recently told farmers
there that she thought the estate tax threshold should be raised to
protect family farms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not make this about rich and poor, let's make this about
fairness,'' Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, estates valued at less than $675,000 do not pay any
federal estate taxes. That exemption is scheduled to increase to $1
million by 2006. Family-owned businesses and farms are eligible for
a $1.3 million exemption. Property left from one spouse to another
is exempt from any estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill approved by the committee, the estate and gift
taxes would be gradually reduced beginning in 2001 and eliminated
by 2010. Rates would not be reduced below the lowest income tax
rate for an unmarried individual until the taxes were fully
repealed.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would phase out gift taxes and the
generation-skipping transfer tax over ten years.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, those who give more than $10,000 a year as a gift
must pay federal tax. The tax is calculated on a scale pegged to
the amount of the gift.
</P>
<P>
   The generation-skipping tax is imposed on transfers that exceed
$1 million in which the beneficiary is more than one generation
removed from the giver.
</P>
<P>
   On the web:
</P>
<P>
   House Republican Conference: www.gop.gov
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
