<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5607 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-ERIE-CANAL-HNS &LR;      05-25 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ERIE-CANAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LIQUID HISTORY: ERIE CANAL CHANGED AMERICA'S ECONOMIC
LANDSCAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ One hundred and seventy-five years ago, when it
was officially opened, the Erie Canal spurred what might be
considered the e-commerce revolution of its day.
</P>
<P>
   The 363-mile, 40-foot-wide and 4-foot-deep ``artificial river''
with 83 locks and 18 aqueducts altered the economies of New York
state and the nation practically overnight while changing long-held
verities of business.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the cost of transporting a ton of wheat dropped
from $100 pre-Erie to about $5 with the canal.
</P>
<P>
   The time it took to bring goods from farm to market also was
dramatically compressed. It took 20 days typically to move wheat
from the Genesee Valley, south of Rochester, overland by wagon to
Albany. The Erie cut the time to 10 days for wheat to move by canal
boat from the Genesee Valley through Albany and down the Hudson
River to New York City.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to cheaper and fresher products, the Erie _
colloquially known as ``Clinton's Ditch'' after its champion, Gov.
DeWitt Clinton _ created canal boom towns, spawned entrepreneurial
wealth and filled state coffers with toll revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Erie Canal brought phenomenal change in so many ways,''
said F. Daniel Larkin, author of ``New York State Canals'' and two
other scholarly books related to the Erie Canal.
</P>
<P>
   Larkin, a history professor at the State University of New York
at Oneonta and interim provost of academic affairs, joined in last
week's celebration of the 175th anniversary of the Erie Canal at
the State Archives here, where Larkin did much of his research.
</P>
<P>
   The festivities included canal songs, a play about canal
history, an appearance by a descendant of Gov. Clinton, DeWitt
Clinton Jones III, and an exhibit of documents on the Erie Canal
from the State Archives heretofore not displayed publicly.
</P>
<P>
   The archives event kicked off a yearlong celebration as part of
Gov. George Pataki's officially proclaimed ``year of the Erie
Canal'' meant to promote dozens of community canal festivals and
herald the recreational opportunities along its path.
</P>
<P>
   But where the Erie's 19th-century engineering feat still springs
to life is in the State Archives, home to 5 million documents (of
more than 150 million total) pertaining to the original Erie Canal
and its numerous reincarnations.
</P>
<P>
   Within the archives' holdings, some of the most compelling
materials are original surveyors' drawings bound into thick volumes
the size of folding card tables. When fully unfurled, these
panoramic views provide visual documentation of the canal in
12-foot spans on durable drafting paper.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent morning, Craig Williams, history curator with the
State Museum here and a canal scholar who previously worked at the
Erie Canal Museum in Syracuse, provided a guided tour through the
archives' Erie Canal holdings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Upstate New York had never seen a period of such prosperity
and change as the Erie Canal,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   The original Erie Canal took eight years and cost $7.5 million
(roughly $4 billion in present-day dollars) to complete. It was a
victim of its own astonishing success. In its first year, 217,000
tons of goods moved on the canal and $28,000 was collected in
tolls.
</P>
<P>
   But the narrow waterway was overwhelmed with traffic, and canal
operators faced boat-jams at the locks.
</P>
<P>
   A drive was begun right away to increase the capacity of canal
boats. The 4-foot-deep original Erie could handle boats with a
maximum weight of 70 tons.
</P>
<P>
   By 1835, the first Erie expansion was under way, widening the
canal to 70 feet, increasing its depth to 7 feet, straightening its
course to speed travel and installing double locks to prevent
backups. By doing this, canal boats could bulk up and carry more
than 200 tons of goods apiece, thus increasing profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   Williams pointed out the personalities behind the staggering
statistics of Erie commerce and reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   There was young Thomas Ebershed, a recent immigrant from
England, hired by the state canal department in the fall of 1839 to
make drawings for the enlargement. Ebershed left state service to
pursue his fortune in the California gold rush.
</P>
<P>
   Irish immigrant David Vaughan was a skilled surveyor and
draftsman, who came to New York in the 1840s. By 1851, he had made
his mark by embellishing his canal drawings with exquisitely
detailed watercolor scenes and witty captions.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Vaughan represents an Old World sensibility in mapmaking
and cartography and includes his own cultural attitudes in his
work,'' Williams said. ``He's a true artist and his engineering
drawings stand out from the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughan died in 1865 on the job, surveying land near Utica.
</P>
<P>
   But long before, when New York's economy turned sour in the
early 1840s, the state faced a cash-flow problem and abruptly
halted work on the canal enlargement in 1842.
</P>
<P>
   The unfinished enlargement remained on hold for more than a
decade until the recession passed and the state could afford to
invest money in the canal once again.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing the canal's capacity paid off, with cargo volume
topping 4 million tons annually at its peak in 1880.
</P>
<P>
   That's with seasonal operation, too, because the Erie Canal was
closed down in winter. The waterway was drained, silt was dredged
out and repairs were made to the wooden locks and the waterproof
mortar used to cement the cut stone walls.
</P>
<P>
   Before the winter shutdown, families who owned canal boats
traditionally traveled down the Hudson to New York Harbor and
rafted together in what amounted to floating villages until the
spring re-opening.
</P>
<P>
   Archives' records also debunk conventional wisdom that Irish
immigrants were primarily responsible for digging and constructing
the Erie Canal. In fact, the Irish accounted for perhaps 15 percent
of the 9,000 contractors and laborers who built the original Erie,
according to Larkin. The vast majority of the Erie workers, he
said, were upstate residents who lived along the canal.
</P>
<P>
   One of those local laborers was Brigham Young, future leader of
the Mormons, who lived along the canal at the time. In 1825, Young
was a painting contractor and he billed state canal superintendent
R. Matson $200 for painting a few lockhouses and bridges.
</P>
<P>
   ``That stretch of the canal that Young painted had actually been
in use; so my guess is that he was paid to spruce things up before
the opening ceremonies in 1825,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, a fourth and final major expansion was completed in
1918, with crude wooden mechanisms replaced by modern steel locks
on the Mohawk River's Barge Canal.
</P>
<P>
   The original Erie Canal changed attitudes of upstate culture as
well, according to Williams. As a result of the canal's commercial
revolution, religious revivalism swept upstate in the decades after
1825, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Larkin, who is currently writing a biography of Benjamin
Wright, chief engineer of the original Erie Canal, the myriad
phases of the canal underscore an elemental truth first tested and
proven in the state in 1825.
</P>
<P>
   ``Water was then and still is the cheapest way to ship
anything,'' Larkin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
