<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5614 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-HEZBOLLAH-JOY-INDEPEN     05-25 1753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEZBOLLAH-JOY-INDEPENDENT-FISK-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AZEEM!': HEZBOLLAH FIGHTERS LOOK AWESTRUCK AT GALILEE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...NOTE 3 trims, total 325; 1,475 uncut)   (This excellent 1,150-word (trimmed) ``separate-buy'' article is
from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR YOUR CONVENIENCE, THIS ARTICLE OFFERS THREE
OPTIONAL TRIMS, TOTALING 325 WORDS. TOTAL UNCUT IS 1,475.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   KFAR KILA _ They stood along the border fence and stared at the
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The Hezbollah men _ hundreds of them, in their combat fatigues
and with their rifles in their hands and their flak jackets over
their shoulders _ just stood in silence beside me and looked out,
awestruck, at the fields and orchards of Galilee.
</P>
<P>
   Bathed in the blue mist of dawn, Israel _ or Palestine as the
Hezbollah men called it _ looked almost holy. We could see the glow
of oranges in the trees and hear the water dripping from an
irrigation tap and, not so far away, see the red roofs of homes.
</P>
<P>
   The gunman beside me breathed in deeply. ``Azeem,'' he said.
``Incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was. Here they were, the bearded men who had routed one
of the world's most powerful armies, standing at last on the very
frontier of Israel after driving the last Israeli soldier the last
mile out of Lebanon. In fact, the Israeli border wire was only
three feet from us.
</P>
<P>
   And there was Sheikh Sami Khadra, one of the Hezbollah's senior
clerics, standing in his white turban and long black robes, staring
into Galilee.
</P>
<P>
   There was no overt hostility, no threat, no raised rifle. At one
point a white Israeli van drove down the other side of the wire,
the driver waving oddly at the Hezbollah men.
</P>
<P>
   Had the world gone mad? Sheikh Khadra did not think so. ``It is
a reality more than a dream,'' he said. ``But it is a sight we
could not have dreamed about. We have moved south and now, we hear,
the Jewish settlers over there are frightened and moving south.''
It was God's work, one of the Hezbollah men said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 175 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 300) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The sheikh's armed protectors searched the horizon for Israeli
troops. There were none to be seen. Just that morning mist and the
dew on the trees and the odd feeling that the Hezbollah war had
come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   The men who fought their way from Beirut had at last reached the
border and looked upon the land of their enemies and understood the
transitory nature of victory.
</P>
<P>
   Behind us a convoy of cars was waiting for the Hezbollah to fill
up a mine crater _ the Israelis had left a few hours earlier by
detonating all the Lebanese approach roads to the frontier _ and
loudspeakers perched on trucks vibrated with Muslim prayers.
</P>
<P>
   There were children in some of the cars and a woman who threw
rice and rose petals over the Hezbollah men, many of whom glowered
from Mercedes cars with smoked windows, rifle barrels resting on
their knees, two-way radios crackling. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Did they want to cross that border fence? It did not seem so.
The Palestinians had to secure their own liberation. That's the way
the conversation went beside the Israeli frontier wire Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Hezbollah had come to look, the most privileged sightseers
in the whole world. Over and over they used that same word:
``Azeem.'' ``Incredible.'' Only one man did I hear talking about
``the liquidation of Zionism.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the same all across southern Lebanon Wednesday, as if the
guerrilla victory had not been fully comprehended. But it was a
virtual rout.
</P>
<P>
   The ``South Lebanon Army'' _ Israeli's final protectors in this
dangerous land _ had abandoned their tanks and trucks and
ammunition and guns in the fields, the roads, their barracks and
their homes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM _ 75 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 600) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In the Christian town of Marjayoun, the home of Antoine Lahd,
the SLA leader, was systematically looted by gunmen from the rival
_ and venal _ Amal movement. They drove captured tanks through the
streets, the engines roaring as they crushed pavements and flower
gardens. A mobile artillery piece _ a big Israeli army gun _ was
driven around the town. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Israel had said it would not disarm the SLA. It didn't need to.
We saw some of them, young men with heads lowered, standing with
Hezbollah members who were reading through their identification
papers. But there was no revenge killing. No massacre. The
Hezbollah stayed out of Christian towns.
</P>
<P>
   Amal were not so disciplined. And I did begin to wonder whether
things might crack if the Lebanese army or the United Nations did
not bring some troops in here quickly. I think it was a visit to
the old SLA ``war'' memorial that worried me.
</P>
<P>
   The SLA's ``martyrs'' _ collaborators to the victors of this war
_ were commemorated in a Muslim-Christian shrine on a hill and a
garden in which each dead gunman's name, listed by town and
religion, was fixed on a brass plaque to marble walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eternity to our heroic martyrs,'' it says over the door. I
thought it might be the first place to be destroyed and when I
arrived there Wednesday, militiamen and civilians from nearby
villages were already looting the memorial, making off with sofas
and computers and chairs.
</P>
<P>
   I found one Shiite Muslim woman on her hands and knees, digging
up rose bushes from the garden with a crazed look on her face.
</P>
<P>
   And along the memorial wall, I discovered a tall, bearded man
with a knife, cutting one of the brass plaques off the marble. The
name was that of Akl Ibrahim Hashem, one of the most senior
officers in the SLA who was blown up by a Hezbollah mine on Jan. 3
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The bearded man held the plaque out to me with a laugh. ``I'm
taking this one because it is still fresh.'' And other men then
came to cut out more of the plaques. They were killing the dead.
</P>
<P>
   The Muslim villages were awash with yellow Hezbollah banners and
overzealous praise for their liberators. ``A special gratitude to
the Hezbollah'' on a poster in one formerly occupied village did
not have quite the ring of veracity.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Christian villages, the flags were only Lebanese and
the questions only about the date of the Lebanese army's arrival.
No time, we told them. No date. And the same goes for the U.N. But
I noticed how the Christians gathered not on the street but beside
their stone churches.
</P>
<P>
   And I watched the Amal men and their families looting their way
through SLA headquarters with a greed that bordered on madness,
making off with desks, old clothes, magazines, trucks, cars,
anything that was detachable from the buildings. The tanks they
drove were taken through the towns too fast, too many times.
</P>
<P>
   On the hilltop road above Marjayoun, the Hezbollah were more
careful. They planted their flag on a T-55 battle tank and sat
there in the afternoon sun as we drove past, nodding
acknowledgement at each motorist.
</P>
<P>
   But if anything symbolizes Israel's defeat and Hezbollah's
victory, it is the old Crusader castle of Beaufort.
</P>
<P>
   High above the Litani River gorge, it was bombed by the Israelis
when Palestinians used it as a mortar position in the late
seventies, then occupied by Israeli paratroopers _ at great cost _
in 1982. It was as impregnable a fortress for the Israelis as it
had once been to the knights of France.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, it was open to us all. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (THIRD OPTIONAL TRIM _ 75 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 1,250) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis had dynamited the approach roads and their
reinforced living quarters and their artillery bunkers. But we
could still climb through the smoldering wreckage of their most
powerful gun battery in Lebanon and clamber up the ancient Crusader
steps to the original ramparts
</P>
<P>
   There were children in party clothes, families picnicking in the
grass and an ice-cream van that came chugging through the
desolation to sell chocolate cornets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF THIRD OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,475) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   At the very top, where Israel's soldiers had only hours before
been peering from an observation platform, there was a stone
parapet and a massive Hezbollah flag in which the ``l'' of
``Allah'' is formed of a Kalashnikov rifle.
</P>
<P>
   So I climbed into the khaki-colored post from which Israel's
soldiers had looked out each night in fear and trepidation and, no
doubt, loathing for their enemies.
</P>
<P>
   And all before me was spread the land of Lebanon, up to the
2,000-year-old cedars of the Chouf Mountains, across to the snows
of Mount Hermon which Salahadin had once sent to Richard the
Lionheart as a cure for sickness and down to the flat, mellow lands
of Galilee. I could see the Mediterranean and the border of Syria
and half way to Haifa.
</P>
<P>
   And the message? That the Israelis lost and the Hezbollah won?
Definitely. But something else. That high-tech fighter-bombers and
precision artillery and massively armored soldiers are not
necessarily a match for people who think they have God as their
commander-in-chief.
</P>
<P>
   Not a happy thought for everyone living in the Middle East. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
