<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Friday:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-TEXAS-GOP (Austin, Texas) _ George W. Bush was denied a
governor's traditional role as chairman of the state delegation to
the Republican National Convention four years ago by the socially
conservative Texas Republican Convention. Now, as the party's
apparent presidential nominee, he has no plans to attend this
year's state convention in Houston. Bush spokesman Karen Hughes
says the governor likely will be campaigning in another state
during the Texas meeting. By CLAY ROBISON and R. G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-TENN (Nashville, Tenn.) _ Campaigning in his home state of
Tennessee, Vice President Al Gore proposes tax breaks to help
working families who need after-school child care. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-FUTURE (Washington) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Vice
President Al Gore are fighting for more than just the White House
this year. The presidential election winner could be handed a rare
opportunity to alter the direction of the Supreme Court. With the
court split 5-4 on major issues and several justices over the age
of 70, the next president could shape the court to an extent not
enjoyed by a chief executive since the early 1980s. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SECURITY-BREACH (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno,
stunned that undercover agents using fake cards identifying them as
law officers were able to penetrate 19 federal buildings, promises
to revamp her department's security system. That means guards will
stop giving preferential treatment to fellow law officers. We check
other federal agencies where security was breached. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   FUNDING-LOOPHOLE (Washington) _ The House will vote today on
whether to take a step toward closing the so-called ``527
loophole'' that allows political groups to raise and spend money
without identifying the financial supporters. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-SHUTTLE (Houston) _ The Atlantis crew prepares to leave
the international space station in good shape for the next visit in
July. Before disconnecting, the shuttle crew will give the station
one final boost into its proper orbit. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXAMINER-SALE (San Francisco) _ Clint Reilly, an unsuccessful
bidder for the San Francisco Examiner, broadened his legal attack
on the city's daily newspaper publishers, asking a federal judge to
permanently bar not only the Hearst Corp.'s purchase of the San
Francisco Chronicle but also its sale of the Examiner. By SETH
ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The trouble with determining the
appropriate legal consequences of Bill Clinton's misdeeds is that
no one is neutral toward him. After an Arkansas panel recommended
the harshest penalty it could _ disbarment _ one of the
participants insisted that the group ``approached this as we would
any other lawyer.'' Sure. And cows can fly. Clinton isn't just any
other lawyer, and there's not a soul in Arkansas that doesn't love
him or loathe him. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-DEATH-PENALTY (Washington) _ For the first time in
nearly 40 years, the U.S. military is preparing to execute one of
its own, an Army private convicted in 1989 of murdering two taxi
drivers in Killeen, Texas. Not much stands between Dwight Loving,
34, of Rochester, N.Y., and lethal injection at the Ft.
Leavenworth, Kan., federal penitentiary _ except President Clinton
and what his lawyers and other legal experts complain is a vague
and unfair bureaucratic process now under way in the Army. By ERIC
ROSENBERG.
</P>
