<SLUG> BC-NOON-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SHANGHAI NOON': NEW AGE MEETS OLD WEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes at end of review) 
 By A.O. SCOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``This is the West, not the East.'' So Roy O'Bannon (Owen
Wilson), a scruffy, laid-back outlaw of dubious competence,
admonishes his reluctant partner, an imperial guard from the
Forbidden City named Chon Wang (pronounced like John Wayne and
played by the incomparable Jackie Chan). In ``Shanghai Noon,'' Tom
Dey's slapstick kung fu horse opera, the twain meet in a series of
rousing comic collisions, but in the geography of global pop
culture they've never been all that far apart.
</P>
<P>
   The Hong Kong action films of the 1970s and '80s (where Chan
first became a star) owe as much to the spaghetti westerns of the
'60s as the spaghetti westerns owe to earlier samurai movies, which
in turn were inspired by the classic John Ford and Howard Hawks
cowboy pictures, which grew out of the old Tom Mix two-reelers, and
so on all the way back to ``The Great Train Robbery'' almost a
century ago.
</P>
<P>
   But who cares? Jackie Chan _ whose given name, Kong Sang Chan,
means ``born in Hong Kong'' _ is an entertainer whose appeal
transcends differences of culture, age and taste. The appreciation
of his genius requires no excursions into the history of cinema.
It's nonetheless worth noting that, in an age of widespread movie
star narcissism, when sullen vanity often stands in for seriousness
and lazy cynicism for wit, Chan recalls the icons of an earlier
time, the improbably graceful, silly clowns of the silent era:
Charlie Chaplin, Buster Keaton, Harold Lloyd, who are his deepest
source of inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Shanghai Noon'' his astonishing physical gifts find a
perfect counterpoint in Wilson's goofy verbal riffing. The two of
them are thrown together when Chon is dispatched to the rugged Old
West to rescue a kidnapped princess (Lucy Liu), and finds himself
transporting her ransom on the very train Roy and his gang have
decided to rob. Roy has a spacey, surfer-dude approach to outlawry,
and he mystifies the tightly wound Chon with his loopy New Age
pronouncements.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to relax,'' he admonishes Chon when they are forced
to share a jail cell. ``You are the most irritable guy I've ever
been around.'' Later, before a shootout with the main heavy, one
Marshal Van Cleef (Xander Berkeley), Roy's inner voice tells him to
``be the bullet,'' and he screams at his impatient adversary: ``I
won't let you cheapen this! A duel is a sacred moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie benefits from an unusually witty, high-spirited
script, by Alfred Gough and Miles Millar, the authors of ``Lethal
Weapon 4.'' There are moments that echo Mel Brooks' ``Blazing
Saddles,'' but instead of Brooks' borscht belt ethnic insult humor,
``Shanghai Noon'' traffics in the high farce of multicultural
misunderstanding. It tweaks stereotypes even as it spoofs
multicultural sensitivity. (``That's taken out of context,'' Roy
protests after Chon confronts him about some overheard anti-Chinese
remarks.)
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy to wring comedy from the history of Chinese
laborers and American Indians in the Old West, but somehow the
filmmakers finesse the issue without evading it entirely. And a
hint of upbeat patriotism finds its way into the mix. The first
English phrases Chon learns are ``America'' and ``happily ever
after,'' and his adventures are a raucous celebration of the
raucous, slapdash individualism that is part of the West's _ or at
least the western's _ most vital legacy.
</P>
<P>
   In an early, especially inspired sequence, Chon is taken in by
some Indians, for whom his rudimentary English might as well be
Mandarin. After a night of heavy peace-pipe smoking _ featuring a
hilarious montage of his increasingly pixilated face _ Chon wakes
up to find himself with a new wife (Brandon Merrill), a new name
(Fights-in-a-Dress) and a lot of face paint. (Later he turns up on
wanted posters as the Shanghai Kid, even though, as he points out,
he's not from Shanghai at all.)
</P>
<P>
   Resplendent in his Indian warrior-imperial guard get-up, he
walks into a saloon, where ... but just go see it, already. Chan's
fight scenes are like nothing else in the movies, and they're
staged without trickery or flashy special effects. The thrill is
like that of watching a great athlete or musician; it's a perfect
marriage of discipline and grace.
</P>
<P>
   It's also giddily, effervescently funny, like the complicated
Chinese drinking game Chon and Roy play in adjoining bathtubs or
the drunken horse routine that follows. There's a motley assortment
of villains (notably the feline Roger Yuan and the donkeyish Walton
Goggins) and some vague love interests lurking in the background _
the Indian bride and the fairy tale princess, who both seem like
pretty good sports. But ``Shanghai Noon'' is, in classic western
tradition, a celebration of male bonding, unabashedly juvenile,
boyishly risque and disarmingly sweet. Wilson and Chan have enough
chemistry to fuel a string of sequels.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so not all the jokes work, and the plot limps a little
toward the end. No matter. After the glum bullying of ``Gladiator''
and the noisy bombast of ``M:I-2,'' it's refreshing to see a movie
so good natured, so confident of its ability to provoke not queasy
awe or numb exhaustion but pure delight. ``You have a certain
nobility,'' Roy tells Chon in a moment of misty cowboy sentiment.
In the context of the movie, the line is pure hokum, but applied to
Chan, it's right on the money.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SHANGHAI NOON'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Tom Dey; written by Alfred Gough and Miles Millar;
director of photography, Dan Mindel; edited by Richard Chew; music
by Randy Edelman; production designer, Peter J. Hampton; produced
by Roger Birnbaum, Gary Barber and Jonathan Glickman; released by
Touchstone Pictures/Spyglass Entertainment. Cast: Jackie Chan (Chon
Wang), Owen Wilson (Roy O'Bannon), Lucy Liu (Princess Pei Pei),
Brandon Merrill (Indian Wife), Roger Yuan (Lo Fong), Walton Goggins
(Wallace) and Xander Berkeley (Van Cleef).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 110 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shanghai Noon'' is rated PG-13 (parents strongly cautioned).
It has a lot of high-spirited fighting and gunplay, which
occasionally has fatal consequences, and a smattering of salty
cowboy lingo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
