<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PASSION-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PASSION OF MIND': A WOMAN OF TWO MINDS ... OR TWO LOVES ... OR ...
 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Demi Moore stars in the dreamscape ``Passion of Mind,'' one of
those other-side-of-the-looking glass pictures. During the daylight
hours she's Marie and lives in a sun-dappled chateau in Provence
with her two daughters, writing book reviews for The New York
Times. And when she closes her eyes at night, she's living in
gray-blue Manhattan as Marty, a literary agent with her hair pulled
back to heighten the severity of her loveless life in the big city.
Fortunately she doesn't get around to reviewing any of the books by
authors she signed, or there could be a very nasty battle between
the two at Elaine's.
</P>
<P>
   Marie/Marty is aware of the assets and liabilities of both
states, though she is unsure which is reality and which a dream. So
Marie seeks the counsel of a friend about her roiling fantasy life,
while Marty does it the old-fashioned Manhattanite way: she talks
to a shrink, who never asks if she actually gets any rest during
her extremely active dream life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who I am anymore,'' she says in the opening
narration, and it's easy to see where that sentiment comes from.
It's the gauzy and underdramatized conception of the movie that
lacks passion; she wanders through both of her lives terribly
unfulfilled because she can't have what she wants: romance.
</P>
<P>
   The film really should be called ``Fashion of Mind,'' since the
decor in both of her unrealities seems like something conjured by
someone who has spent more time fantasizing about layouts in
Architectural Digest than meeting deadlines. Anyone with this kind
of specificity about the dwellings in her dreams has problems that
this movie can't be bothered to develop; most people can't even
remember what they wear in their dreams. In her New York apartment
she has a bust of herself that is meant to suggest some
psychological undercurrent but really looks like the kind of thing
she sculptured with Patrick Swayze in ``Ghost,'' another
fantasy-film landmark in Moore's career.
</P>
<P>
   With its dual and dueling-worlds structure, ``Passion'' may put
viewers in mind of last year's ``Sliding Doors,'' which starred
Gwyneth Paltrow, though it's much closer to the 1987 puzzle picture
``Julia and Julia,'' in which Kathleen Turner played a woman who
was married in one reality and involved in a soft-core romantic
blaze in another.
</P>
<P>
   There's a self-pitying side to ``Passion,'' with these ideal
existences that both cry out for the love of a good man. Stellan
Skarsgard is courting Marie in Europe, and the talented and
eccentric William Fichtner, who manages to vary his appearance with
every role, is the awkward and intense man seeking Marty's love in
America.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem with such movies is that the audience often
ends up feeling as if the creators themselves haven't committed to
a single world to focus on; it's hard enough to make one reality
work in movies and find a consistent tone for it. The tensions have
to be built on contrasts that aren't sharp enough in ``Passion,''
especially since Marty/Marie has most of the things women her age
would dream about. This situation also seems like the kind of ``you
can have it all but not really'' projection that a much younger
woman would have.
</P>
<P>
   To her credit, Moore is far too mature for the audience to
believe that she is trapped in this purgatory. It's a difficult
conceit to pull off, and not because she isn't working at it.
Marie's relationship with her children, though slightly idealized,
is thorny at times, as they compete for her attention, a grown-up
touch contributed by the star, who apparently has huge stores of
maternal warmth and patience. The director, Alain Berliner (``Ma
Vie en Rose''), gives ``Passion'' an anonymous polish, but there's
a definite sense that someone's hands are tied, perhaps by the
both-sides-now whininess of the script by Ron Bass (``Rain Man,''
``My Best Friend's Wedding'').
</P>
<P>
   Visually there's certainly a difference between the worlds,
thanks to Eduardo Serra's cinematography. And since Marie and Marty
are literally the day and night sides of the same woman, the halved
personas need to open up and learn to love again.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to take ``Passion'' seriously because it brings to
mind the kind of shallow psychology that wouldn't be out of place
in a history short about Sigmund Freud on ``ABC Schoolhouse Rock.''
If there's a sequel, perhaps Marie could have Marty represent her
for the sale of her book or, at the very least, negotiate the deal
for the made-for-Lifetime movie. Apparently she's the kind of
driven negotiator it would take to sell the mild Harlequin Romance
simple-mindedness of ``Passion of Mind.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `PASSION OF MIND'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Alain Berliner; written by Ron Bass and David Field;
director of photography, Eduardo Serra; edited by Anne V. Coates;
music by Randy Edelman; production designer, Pierre-Francois
Limbosch; produced by Carole Scotta, Tom Rosenberg and Bass;
released by Paramount Classics.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Demi Moore (Marie/Marty), Stellan Skarsgard (William),
William Fichtner (Aaron), Peter Riegert (Dr. Peters), Sinead Cusack
(Jessie), Joss Ackland (Dr. Langer), Gerry Bamman (Edward
Youngerman) and Julianne Nicholson (Kim).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 112 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passion of Mind'' is rated PG-13 (parents strongly cautioned).
It includes some rather desultory sequences of lovemaking and
strong language.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
