<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KNITTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `YARN LADIES' KNIT CLOTHING FOR INFANTS AND SENIOR CITIZENS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The two middle-aged women entered St. Peter's
Hospital here looking as if they were bound for a church bazaar or
country fair. Their plastic shopping bags were bulging with
crocheted blankets, knit sweaters and caps in pastel hues.
</P>
<P>
   Passers-by paid little attention.
</P>
<P>
   Which is how these self-described ``yarn ladies'' like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the quiet revolution,'' said Maria Mathisen, an organizer
of the loosely knit and anonymous skein of volunteers who crochet
and knit clothing for infants and senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The knitters and crocheters are as diverse as the recipients of
their free handiwork: troubled teenage girls in group homes, women
with church organizations, commuters who crochet on trains and
buses, and the homebound elderly. They prefer to remain behind the
scenes in this labor of love.
</P>
<P>
   One 98-year-old woman, for instance, has completed more than 100
crocheted lap robes for nursing homes without attention or reward.
She claims the work helps limber up her arthritic fingers and
provides other, less tangible benefits such as adding purpose to
her largely solitary days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knitting is therapy and it fills many needs,'' said Ann
Mulford of Burnt Hills, who is a co-organizer.
</P>
<P>
   On this morning at the hospital, Mathisen and Mulford delivered
a few of the dozens of hand-knit items of infant wear that they
provide each month to several local hospitals, including Albany
Medical Center, Ellis, Bellevue and Glens Falls.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy and Mark Novak of Albany accepted for their newborn
daughter, Sarah Kate, a pink and green knit cap, pink and white
blanket and pink pastel sweater dropped off by Mulford.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really great handiwork,'' Kathy Novak said, inspecting
the pattern. ``I always wished I'd learned to knit from my
grandmother, but I haven't.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the hall, Mulford gave Molly Nichols of Albany matching
green and pink pastel caps and sweaters for Nichols' twin infant
daughters, Chloe and Emma.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's adorable,'' Nichols said of the knit clothing. ``They'll
wear it home tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The parents really appreciate the fine hand-knit work,'' said
Margaret Wilkinson, a lactation specialist at St. Peter's. ``We're
very fortunate to have the volunteers.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson said the need for the knit and crocheted items is
especially acute with premature babies in the hospital's neonatal
intensive care unit.
</P>
<P>
   The yarn ladies take particular care in organizing knitting and
crocheting patterns in sizes to fit the premies. That's how the two
women met in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Mulford, 59, who's retired from a job at Dunkin' Donuts, gave
birth to a preemie daughter at St. Peter's in 1979. That same year,
Mathisen formed Milk for Life, a volunteer effort to provide human
milk to infants suffering illness or allergies requiring human milk
to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Mulford and Mathisen joined hundreds of volunteer donors who
solicited, donated, transported, stored, packaged and mailed breast
milk from 1979 to 1991, when the milk bank folded for lack of
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Mulford has teamed up once again with Mathisen, 50, a
former residential aide for retarded adults who was disabled on the
job. The yarn ladies, who don't have a formal name for the
organization, started the project about one year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Mathisen, who's been knitting since she was a teenager, found
that the disability left her stuck at home with time on her hands,
as well as leftover yarn.
</P>
<P>
   Mulford asked Mathisen to make a preemie hat. She did.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Mulford, a knitter with 45 years' experience, got her
friends at the United Methodist Church in Burnt Hills, an Albany
suburb, to lend their help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started delivering to maternity units at hospitals and
everyone kept asking for more,'' Mathisen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's grown into a wide network,'' Mulford said.
</P>
<P>
   Typical was the recent flannel blanket brigade. A Catskill,
N.Y., resident donated 15 yards of flannel, which was sent to
Mathisen, who passed it to Mulford, who enlisted the aid of her
church women's group. Church members added a backing layer, trimmed
the blankets in lace and cord work and completed 10 fancy blankets.
</P>
<P>
   In one year, the yarn network has grown to more than 100
volunteer knitters and crocheters from throughout the Capital
Region, as well as New Jersey, Connecticut, North Carolina and
Wisconsin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
