<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5631 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-E-PRIVACY-0526-COX     05-25 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-PRIVACY-0526-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LAWMAKERS, REGULATORS AND INDUSTRY DIVIDED ON ENSURING ONLINE
PRIVACY
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Everyone who spoke Thursday in the overflowing
Senate hearing room proclaimed that privacy should be protected for
online customers of dot.com businesses _ but hardly anyone agreed
on how to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Senate Commerce Committee were split over whether
new federal laws are needed to prevent electronic intrusion of
Internet consumers. The Internet industry generally thought
legislation was a bad idea and self-regulation was the way to go.
Even the Federal Trade Commission _ which earlier this week
recommended congressional action _ was divided over whether new
privacy standards should apply to traditional brick-and-mortar
businesses as well as to e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Chairman John McCain, R-Ariz., expressed hope that
the hearing ``will begin the process of developing (a) consensus
about the best way'' to ``enable consumers to protect their privacy
online.''
</P>
<P>
   The session was called in response to a report that the FTC
issued to Congress on Monday. After a four-year study, the agency
concluded that voluntary efforts to ensure privacy are not working
with e-commerce and legislation is needed to ``provide online
consumers the level of protection they seek and deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   The intense interest in the issue was demonstrated by the
lobbyists, journalists and regulators who filled all the seats in
the ornate chambers. They leaned against the walls, sat on the
floor and lined up on the marble stairs outside in hopes a seat
would open in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Internet firms routinely use high-tech means to collect and sell
information about people who visit their websites _ often without
adequately informing the online customers and giving them a chance
to ``opt out,'' FTC Chairman Robert Pitofsky told the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Studies show that as many as 92 percent of Internet users ``do
not trust online companies to keep their information
confidential,'' Pitofsky testified. These fears could hinder the
growth of Internet commerce, he warned.
</P>
<P>
   For these reasons, he said, a majority of the five-member FTC
believes Congress should act promptly on federal safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   However, Commissioner Orson Swindle made clear that he was not
among the majority in this ``embarrassingly flawed'' report.
``Industry self-regulation is working,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Thomas Levy concurred with the need for regulation
but said ``any legislation should apply to off-line commerce as
well.'' Otherwise, he said, the ``regulatory imbalance'' could
inhibit the growth of Internet business.
</P>
<P>
   However, Commissioner Mozelle Thompson said the Internet is
unique in its ability to instantly collect and distribute data
about unsuspecting users and that special rules are needed there.
</P>
<P>
   Opinions were similarly splintered within the committee.
</P>
<P>
   The need for legislation was endorsed by Democrats Ernest
Hollings of South Carolina, Ron Wyden of Oregon and Jay Rockefeller
of West Virginia, as well as Republican Conrad Burns of Montana.
However, Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., and John Ashcroft, R-Mo., said
not so fast.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry said he has doubts whether Congress ``has the ability to
move adroitly enough'' to ensure privacy on the rapidly evolving
Internet without jeopardizing development of this digital economy.
</P>
<P>
   However, McCain said the FTC report showed that too many
Internet businesses are not telling customers ``in a clear and
conspicuous manner'' what information they are collecting and
selling and don't give consumers ``meaningful choices'' on how that
data will be used.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses from the online marketplace, though, said the FTC was
wrong in its dire assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I entirely disagree with the conclusion that privacy in
cyberspace is woefully inadequate and that legislation is
necessary,'' testified Christine Varney. A former FTC commissioner,
she represented the Online Privacy Alliance, a coalition of over
100 Internet industry and trade associations, ranging from America
Online to Yahoo!
</P>
<P>
   Existing laws concerning health and medical privacy, credit card
theft and identity theft already apply to Internet businesses, she
said. New technology and software will soon stem the other abuses.
</P>
<P>
   For online information:
</P>
<P>
   www.ftc.gov
</P>
<P>
   www.privacyalliance.gov
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
