<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-ROLLOVER (Washington) _ The Transportation Department,
which has been trying since 1973 to find a way to reduce vehicle
rollovers, said Thursday that it wants to publish a simple ranking
of cars, vans, pick-ups and sport-utilities according to how wide
they are and how high their center of gravity is. Rollovers kill
nearly 10,000 people a year, more than a quarter of all the people
who are killed in vehicles, and the majority of those killed in
single-vehicle crashes, as when a car or SUV runs off the road.
Sport utilities and pick-up trucks, highly popular, are more
rollover-prone. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-NUKES (Washington) _ Gov. George W. Bush's proposal this
week to consider unilateral reductions in the American nuclear
arsenal was a bold break with decades of strategic doctrine that
may foretell the end of traditional theories of arms control. By
John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TEETH (Washington) _ Oral diseases, from tooth decay to
mouth cancer, threaten the health of poor people, minorities,
children and the elderly, despite vast improvements in dental care
over the past 50 years, according to a study made public by the
Surgeon General on Thursday. The report, which experts described as
the first comprehensive review of the scientific literature on oral
health, found that most Americans who are middle-aged or younger
can now expect to keep their teeth for life. But it also documented
important, and little-noticed disparities in care. By Sheryl Gay
Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-WENDYS-MURDERS (New York) _ Five employees are killed and two
others are wounded in a late-night robbery at a Wendy's restaurant
in Queens. The dead had been herded into a basement walk-in
refrigerator and killed with shots to the head. By David Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT8,9.
</P>
