<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5642 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SEAJETS-BAHAMAS0526-C     05-25 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEAJETS-BAHAMAS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 0526-COX &HT;    Fast ride (long wait) to Bahamas
 &HT;    By Joel Engelhardt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Never could it be said that my wife and I are
high-rollers. But then, even simple tourists shouldn't be treated
like this.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the SeaJets crew didn't offer kind words,
sympathetic stares and occasionally helpful advice. It's just that
they didn't _ and often couldn't _ deliver what the company
promised in its ads.
</P>
<P>
   Take that thing about the 99 minutes travel time from the Port
of Palm Beach to the Bahamas. On the face, it is true. Once the
SeaJets craft is throttled up, we literally flew across the ocean
at 50 mph, making the 67-mile trip to Freeport on Grand Bahama
Island in 99 minutes, give or take a few.
</P>
<P>
   But what they didn't say is that you might have to wait . . .
and wait . . . and wait . . . to depart.
</P>
<P>
   We lined up, like they told us when we ordered our tickets, an
hour before our 3:30 p.m. Friday departure time. Two lines, later
expanded to three, reached the back of the room as travelers drawn
by SeaJets $99 fare, including a night at The Bahamian Resort and
Casino, waited most patiently.
</P>
<P>
   At 3:30, our departure time, we were still in line, still 10
minutes from completing our check-in. We finally prepared to board.
But not so fast.
</P>
<P>
   The SeaJets check-in building is not near the boat, er plane, or
whatever you want to call the fast-moving hydrofoil.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the check-in building is not on Port of Palm Beach
property.
</P>
<P>
   So after standing in line with 100 people for an hour and
watching our departure time come and go, we moved outside to await
a bus. The first shuttle appeared, the crowd surged into the hot
sun and waited as 32 people boarded _ a full busload. The remaining
passengers moved back.
</P>
<P>
   After another 10 minutes and a bus ride through the port's
industrial complex to the waiting boat, we were ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the SeaJet was late, but we were told there would be free
soft drinks and chips aboard, plus $4 well drinks and $4
sandwiches. So we didn't think about bringing food.
</P>
<P>
   And it appeared all would be fine. The cabin is extremely
comfortable, much more so than a cramped airplane. It has two decks
and great sea views from everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The engines revved up, the crew scurried about and then the
engines droned to a stop. The captain announced that the port had
ordered the SeaJets ship to wait, while the Contessa cruise ship
pulled out of port. Twenty minutes passed. Passengers craned their
necks to watch the mighty cruise ship lumber away. Another 10
minutes passed and then the engines revved up. We slowly pulled
from our dock, (neatly perched between the births of the port's two
giant cruise ships) entered Lake Worth, slipped by Palm Beach,
dodged small recreational boaters and entered the open sea. Then
the crew opened the throttles and the Boeing jets roared to life,
skimming at 50 mph 14 feet over the waves.
</P>
<P>
   All was right. Except we were hungry. And Doritos were not our
idea of nourishment. The ship carried no sandwiches this day (nor
on our return). Chips, soft drinks and alcohol, especially alcohol,
kept the passengers happy. At least they didn't run out of chips.
</P>
<P>
   While the company, which began service last November, estimates
its on-time performance at 85 percent, a review of Port of Palm
Beach records shows that since January the ship came and went
within 10 minutes of its scheduled time about half the time. Delays
occasionally topped one _ and even two _ hours. Port officials say
the records are not always precise and can be off by as much as 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The delays come about for a wide range of reasons, including
immigration issues, tardy fuel trucks, luggage handling or
maintenance and repairs, SeaJets President George Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number one issue is safety,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the vessel was damaged when a locking mechanism
failed while at sea. It stopped running for a week. Repairs closed
SeaJets down again for two weeks at the end of April.
</P>
<P>
   The on-time performance should improve when the port opens a new
cruise terminal next year, eliminating the bus ride to the port,
Bradley said. Plus, the company pushed back its departures from
Freeport to allow more time to prepare.
</P>
<P>
   Once at sea, the trip flew by. The landing at Freeport was
quick. Check-in meant another line but it moved fast. Then there
was another line for taxis _ seven-seat minivans that lined up to
offer rides for $3 to $8 _ and then on to the hotel, a lovely place
originally called the Princess Resort and Country Club. We entered
the circular lobby and confronted yet another line from the front
desk to the front doors.
</P>
<P>
   It took an hour to check in. Hint: Go eat at one of the hotel's
excellent restaurants because the line should be gone by the time
you're done with dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and a few warnings about the hotel. Check to see if you're
in the towers or the country club _ they have different lobbies,
different check-ins. And that $12 tax that SeaJets warned you about
_ it's actually $15 per person, per night. And that king-size bed?
Forget it, they only have 20. Expect two double beds even if your
SeaJets reservation specifies otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   So, they say 99 minutes to the Bahamas. But beware. It took us
six hours from check-in at 2:30 p.m. to flopping down on our
separate hotel beds at 8:30 p.m. And on the way back? Another
two-hour wait to depart.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
