u l BC-TRAVEL-CRUISES0526-CO     05-25 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CRUISES0526-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cruises for everyone's budget
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In the old days of cruising, only the wealthy
could afford to travel by ocean liner. They packed their ball gowns
and tuxedos into steamer trunks and paid lots of money for the
privilege of dining and dancing their way to exotic ports.
</P>
<P>
   But nowadays, just about any working stiff can go on a cruise,
especially if you don't mind an inside cabin. You can take a
four-night cruise to the Caribbean that includes dining and dancing
for under $500. You just have to buy (or rent) your own gown and
tuxedo.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, if you have money and time to spare, you can
book a round-the-world, 105-day cruise on the Queen Elizabeth 2 for
just $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some great cruises for different budgets. Fares came
from the cruise lines and include taxes and port charges. Check
with travel agents for fares and special packages.
</P>
<P>
   HOW LONG: Three or four nights
</P>
<P>
   WHERE: Miami to Nassau or Cozumel
</P>
<P>
   For the price of a nice hotel room _ about $100 per day (per
person double) _ you can enjoy Las Vegas-style entertainment,
casino gambling, buffets and bingo on Carnival Cruise Lines' three-
and four-day Bahamas and Caribbean cruises. A three-night cruise on
the Ecstasy from Miami to Nassau is only $389 and a four-night
cruise from Miami to Key West and Cozumel is $399. The Ecstasy is a
stylish ship decorated in exuberant colors and neon lights.
Passengers tend to be singles and young couples who like to stay up
all night. The cruise to Nassau leaves every Friday and to Cozumel
every Monday.
</P>
<P>
   HOW LONG: Six or seven nights
</P>
<P>
   WHERE: New York to England, or Vancouver to Alaska
</P>
<P>
   You can ride in style from New York to England on the last
transatlantic liner, the Queen Elizabeth 2, for just $995 (per
person double) for an inside cabin for the six-night crossing. The
price includes economy air fare from London to 117 U.S. cities, and
all the old-world glamour you've seen on BBC period films. Another
option is Carnival's seven-night Alaska cruises from Vancouver to
Ketchikan, Juneau, Skagway and Sitka in June for $799 (not
including air fare).
</P>
<P>
   HOW LONG: Seven nights
</P>
<P>
   WHERE: Port Canaveral to St. Thomas, St. John and St. Maarten
</P>
<P>
   For a magical cruise to the Caribbean, there's the Disney Magic,
which will start sailing from Port Canaveral to St. Thomas, St.
John and St. Maarten in August. The fare for a great cabin with
private veranda and 1 1/2 baths starts at $1,383 (per person
double) in September and October. Rates start at $1,652 for a cabin
with balcony in August. There's nothing theme park-y about this
sophisticated ship, which has an elegant atrium (right), except for
occasional appearances by Mickey and Minnie and the Disney show
productions. No showgirls in thongs. First stop is Disney's private
island in the Bahamas, which has sandy beaches for families and one
for adults only.
</P>
<P>
   HOW LONG: Seven nights
</P>
<P>
   WHERE: Venice to Greece and Croatia
</P>
<P>
   Always wanted to go to Europe? You can do it the easy way on
Costa Cruise Line's CostaClassica's seven-night cruise from Venice
(in photo) to Bari, Italy; Santorini, Mykonos and Rhodes, Greece;
and Dubrovnik, Croatia. The fares start at $2,280 (per person
double) and include air fare from selected cities in the United
States, and two additional nights in Europe. The cruise line offers
similar cruises on the CostaAtlantica, the CostaVictoria and the
CostaRomantica to Greece, Turkey, Italy, Spain, France, Israel and
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   HOW LONG: 17 days
</P>
<P>
   WHERE: London to New York
</P>
<P>
   Lucky you _ smart and rich. This could be the cruise for you.
The all-suite Seabourn Pride, one of the most luxurious ships
afloat, will make a 17-day Northern Island Crossing Sept. 3,
leaving London and stopping in Scotland; the Faeroe Islands in
Denmark; Reykjavik, Iceland; Newfoundland and Nova Scotia; Newport,
R.I.; and New York. Fares start at $12,990 (per person double). Add
another $835 for air fare from the U.S. ($4,845 for first-class
air).
</P>
<P>
   Dreaming of something even more luxurious? You can book the
owner's suite for $30,400.
</P>
<P>
   Only 208 passengers live the sybaritic life in stylish
Scandinavian surroundings with a choice of open-seating restaurants
and a selection of services in the spa.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
