<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5645 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ETHIOPIA-ERITREA-ART-     05-25 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHIOPIA-ERITREA-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERITREA ABANDONS PART OF DISPUTED REGION TO ETHIOPIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ Eritrean troops abruptly pulled back Thursday
from a key town still in dispute with Ethiopia, in what may be a
decisive step toward the end of a war that has claimed thousands of
lives and crippled two nations.
</P>
<P>
   As ever in this two-year war, the sides could not agree on what
happened Thursday: Ethiopia said Eritrean troops fled after a
punishing, two-day assault on positions around the town of
Zalembessa, which Ethiopia claims as its territory. As such,
Ethiopia said it had all but won the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was simple,'' said Selome Taddesse, an Ethiopian
spokeswoman. The Eritrean army, she said, ``was smashed, kicked,
destroyed, devastated, humiliated and sent packing and running.''
</P>
<P>
   But Eritrea, which has suffered major defeats since Ethiopia
mounted an offensive on May 12, said it withdrew to comply with a
plea on Wednesday from the Organization for African Unity to end
the war. Eritrea sought the moral high ground, saying the war was
not worth so many lives and that the burden was now on Ethiopia to
pull back from the huge swath of Eritrean land it captured during
the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they will pull out,'' said Yemane Ghebremeskel,
a spokesman for Eritrea's president, Isaias Afwerki. ``I don't
think they are interested in peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Major questions, in fact, remain about whether either side is
ready for peace. There was still fighting Thursday along the
central front, though without the intensity of earlier battles. But
with Zalembessa, which Eritrea captured in June 1998, back in
Ethiopia's hands, Eritrea has lost a major strategic position,
perhaps so important that the war may now find its way to an end.
</P>
<P>
   That was, at any rate, the way Ethiopians took the news Thursday
in the capital city, Addis Ababa: Thousands of people thronged the
streets, beeping car horns and cheering for what they said was a
major victory. In Asmara, Eritrea's capital, the streets were
quiet.
</P>
<P>
   But relief groups said they would continue to work in western
Eritrea, where hundreds of thousands of people were reported
uprooted in the last week of fighting. The U.N. World Food Program
on Thursday sent 79 tons of high energy biscuits to feed nearly
40,000 Eritreans displaced in the west.
</P>
<P>
   The deliveries will continue, officials said, until the fighting
is over and perhaps beyond, depending on whether people are able to
get back home and plant crops. ``At the moment, it's unclear, it's
unpredictable, it's fluid,'' said Lindsey Davies, a World Food
Program spokeswoman in Asmara.
</P>
<P>
   The war broke out in May 1998, between two nations on the Horn
of Africa that were once the closest of friends. Eritrea, for
decades the northernmost province of Ethiopia, became independent
in 1993 with Ethiopia's blessing in a swell of good feeling after
fighters from north and south overthrew the military dictatorship
of Megistu Haile Mariam.
</P>
<P>
   Both nations were growing quickly economically, and their
leaders, Afwerki of Eritrea and Prime Minister Meles Zenawi of
Ethiopia, were both hailed by western nations as part of a new
breed of progressive leaders in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But the two countries never marked their 620-mile border, and
after months of skirmishes, Eritrea moved troops into the Badme
region, claiming it was theirs according to colonial boundaries.
Ethiopia said it had been invaded.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the war has been fought in fierce bursts, with both
nations, among the poorest in the world, spending what U.S.
officials said was $1 billion in weapons. Moreover, in a war of
modern weaponry between two large and well-trained armies, the
casualties have been stunningly high: Estimates run from 20,000
dead to perhaps triple that, from the fighting before May. The
Organization for African Unity said this week that thousands more
had died since.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On May 12, Ethiopia launched an offensive, saying that the cost
of the war was in fact too high, especially because about 8 million
of its people are facing severe food shortages.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia has gained ground with a speed that surprised many
military experts, particularly because the Eritreans were fighting
the kind of defensive war that they excelled at in their 30-year
guerrilla battle against Mengistu and the Emperor Haile Selassie.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia has said publicly that its only goal was to regain the
territory that Eritrea occupied two years ago. But in private,
Ethiopian officials have made no secret of their desire to destroy
Eritrea's military and, if possible, bring down Afwerki's
government.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Ethiopia feels it has inflicted enough damage, many
experts said, may determine whether the war will end soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The humiliation of Eritrea has long been an important part of
the Ethiopian plan,'' said one western military analyst in
Ethiopia, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible block to peace is the essential scrappiness of
Eritrea, a nation of only 3.5 million people compared to Ethiopia's
60 million. For 30 years, Eritrea held off the armies of Mengistu
and Haile Selassie, both of whom fought unsuccessfully to subdue
rebellions in Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea continued Thursday to cast this war in a similar light,
saying that Zenawi's government wants to conquer Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will continue the war,'' Ghebremeskel, the Eritrean
spokesman, said. ``The international community will know that their
agenda is something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Taddesse denied that Ethiopia had any designs on land beyond the
border, saying it would withdraw from the land it has taken in the
west as soon as Eritrea pulled its troops from the roughly 20 areas
it claims as its own. So far, she said, she saw no evidence of
their withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can assure you 100 percent,'' she said. ``The minute we
regain our territory, we will stop.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last several months, Ethiopia and Eritrea had accepted
all but the fine print of a peace deal brokered by the Organization
for African Unity. A major sticking point was that Eritrea wanted a
cease-fire before settling those final details; Ethiopia wanted the
cease-fire afterward.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly two weeks of fighting, Eritrea said Thursday that
the cease-fire could come later.
</P>
<P>
   The paradox of this war, if it does indeed end soon, is that
land along the border may still shift hands _ no matter how many
lives have been spent in the last two years. During the past few
days, there has been speculation that Eritrea would concede defeat
before it was completely beaten on the battlefield in order to
preserve a key element of the Organization for African Unity's
peace plan: a process for determining the exact borders by the old
colonial treaties and handing over land, if need be.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Organization for African Unity released a
document aimed at ending the war in which both sides agreed that
they were still committed to that process. Both sides repeated
Thursday that Ethiopia's latest gains should not change that.
''It's going to be a constant source of conflict if the border
isn't clearly defined and a perpetual reason for bloodshed between
the two countries,'' said Lea Brilmayer, a Yale law professor who
is a legal adviser to the Eritrean president's office.
</P>
<P>
   Taddesse agreed. ``The lasting solution to this problem,'' she
said, ``is going to be a demarcation of this border.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
