<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5648 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0526-COX     05-25 1663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0526-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Of course, the door remains open
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush met today in Austin with Colin Powell, one of the
Republican Party's most popular and potent political figures, and
heard Powell reiterate that he is ``not a candidate for vice
president.'' And Bush seemed to be taking him at his word _ at
least for now. A day earlier, Bush said in an interview with the AP
that Powell was not on his list of vice presidential prospects for
that very reason.``People who don't want to be considered for vice
president are not going to be considered for vice president,'' Bush
said. He said the same goes for John McCain, Bush's vanquished
primary rival who says he doesn't want to play second fiddle at the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   MORE MONEY, LONGER HOURS
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore proposed a tax credit for after-school expenses today as
part of an initiative to help working families. In a speech in
Nashville, Gore also said he wants every school to stay open late
and for the government to ``dramatically'' increase funding for
school-based programs known as 21st Century Learning Centers. They
help communities provide after-school and summer school programs.
Gore said he would devote $115 billion of expected federal budget
surpluses to educational programs. George W. Bush, too, has been
promoting education initiatives in an effort that polls have shown
appeals to women.
</P>
<P>
   BATTLE OF THE BUCKS: BLUE JEANS VS. BLACK TIE
</P>
<P>
   It's more money than either the Democrats or the Republicans
have ever raised in one night. President Clinton and Al Gore headed
a ``blue jeans and barbecue'' fund-raiser in Washington that
brought in $26 million. The haul topped the $21 million George W.
Bush collected in a single event several weeks ago. The Democratic
event attracted more than 12,000 people who paid between $50 and
$500,000 to attend. But the competition was vividly on display just
a few blocks away. The Republicans' annual House-Senate dinner,
featuring ex-President George Bush, brought in $14 million. While
diners at the black-tie GOP dinner ate goat cheese and corn
souffle, the Democrats wore jeans and open-necked shirts and ate
their barbecue on plastic plates.
</P>
<P>
   DISTASTEFUL, BUT THEY'LL DO IT ANYWAY
</P>
<P>
   Even while breaking all fund-raising records and upping the ante
for contributions, President Clinton and Al Gore championed
overhauling campaign finance laws. ``I don't think it's corruption
to take money to pass the Brady Bill, to pass the family and
medical leave bill, to pass the patients' bill of rights, to reduce
the deficit and get rid of the debt, instead of giving big breaks
to special interests,'' Clinton said to a standing ovation at the
gala. Said Gore: ``If you entrust me with the presidency, we can
all come back here and it won't cost much at all. We're going to
make meaningful campaign finance reform the law of the land.''
</P>
<P>
   PARTY POW-WOW AND THE POLLS . . .
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore was talking today with Democratic leaders from 34 states
gathering that comes as his poll numbers remain weak and some party
officials are questioning the low-key campaign he has run since
sealing the Democratic nomination in early March. During a two-day
meeting in Nashville, the Democratic state chairmen and vice
chairmen were hearing from not only the candidate, but Donna
Brazille, his campaign manager, Joe Andrew, general chairman of the
Democratic National Committee, and other Gore staffers and
strategists.
</P>
<P>
   . . . BET HE KNOWS THE NUMBERS, THOUGH
</P>
<P>
   On a National Public Radio call-in show, Al Gore said he doesn't
pay much heed to the polls, and said he wouldn't change campaign
strategy to improve his numbers. ``I am not trying to have an
impact on the polls,'' Gore told interviewer Diane Rehm. ``I am
trying to get a message across to the people.'' When asked if he
was having difficulty in getting that message to voters: ``The
process of communication that takes place in a campaign is not best
analyzed on a daily or hourly basis.''
</P>
<P>
   BUSH'S STRATEGY GETS RAVE NOTICES . . .
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has established a pattern with his campaign
that's being noted and lauded. The New York Times: ``He put forward
broad ideas with great appeal to the Republican base and then left
the details to be filled in later should he be elected.'' MSNBC:
``Bush has had a terrific spring in his first season in The Bigs.
Highly touted in the minors, roughed up last winter by John McCain,
Bush has methodically dominated the three-month stretch since Super
Tuesday ended the primary season last March. Al Gore, by contrast,
still seems to be fumbling at the bat rack.''
</P>
<P>
   . . . AND IT DOESN'T GO UNNOTICED BY DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   Two important Democrats on Capitol Hill _ Rep. Charles Rangel
(N.Y.) and Sen. Robert Torricelli (N.J.) are worried that George W.
Bush has made better use of the post-primary season than has Al
Gore. Rangel: ``People are starting to ask, `When does he get
started? When does he get focused? How did Bush catch up? When does
the show hit the road?' They're saying, `If this is a policy to lay
back and wait for the debates, then share it with somebody!'
There's no fiery speeches being given; we don't have the surrogates
out there.'' Torricelli described the problem: ``Until Al Gore
actually goes to Los Angeles and receives his party's nomination
and campaigns in his own right, he will still be identified by most
Americans as Bill Clinton's vice president. There is still not a
separate identity, and only the dramatic departure from Los Angeles
is going to create this new identity.''
</P>
<P>
   GORE STILL THE SECOND BANANA
</P>
<P>
   At the Democrats' big party, the MCI Center emitted
rock-concert-like shrieks when President Clinton was introduced and
Tina Turner's pulsating hit, ``You're Simply the Best,'' blared
through the loud speakers. Unfortunately for Al Gore, this is the
song his campaign staff has been road testing as his theme song.
And it underscored a sad reality for him: As at some of the other
Clinton-Gore joint appearances in the past, while Gore is meant to
be the star, Clinton steals the show. ``Four more years!'' could be
heard coming from the crowd as the president spoke.
</P>
<P>
   CHARACTER OVER RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush declared in Detroit that education is ``the new
civil right.'' With Michigan's popular Republican governor, John
Engler, at his side, Bush spent more than an hour discussing the
importance of equal access to education with students, teachers,
parents and volunteers at the Cornerstone Schools, a private
religion-oriented group of middle and elementary schools. ``We
can't have any gaps of hope in the country,'' he said. ``The
American dream is available for everyone, which means every child
must be educated.'' He also said he believes character education
courses should be available in every school: ``Public schools
should not mix religion in the classroom, but we should not fear
teaching values that are embraced by all religions.''
</P>
<P>
   FORGET THE MODERATION
</P>
<P>
   Focus on the Family head James Dobson criticized the Republican
Party and George W. Bush for sacrificing dedication to its core
principles in an effort to be all things to all people. Dobson said
he was speaking as a private individual and not as the president of
the tax-exempt conservative Christian ministry he leads. He said he
doesn't believe that Bush, if elected, would immediately try to
outlaw abortion and that the Bush campaign has sent ``messages to
conservative Christians that have been kind of scary.'' Focus on
the Family produces radio and TV shows and written material to
forward its goals.
</P>
<P>
   THE FENCE-SITTERS CAN MOVE NOW
</P>
<P>
   Now that Rick Lazio has replaced Rudy Giuliani as the GOP Senate
candidate in New York, voters have a starker choice. Lazio doesn't
share Hillary Clinton's unequivocal support for abortion rights,
increased penalties for gay bias attacks, or gun licensing. The
National Abortion Rights Action League had refused to choose
between Giuliani and Clinton, and its director, Kelli Conlin,
attended events supporting both. But Lazio opposes what abortion
foes call partial-birth abortions. He also is against federal
funding for abortions for poor women. ``I do not want to
criminalize abortion,'' he said. ``On the other hand, I want to
make it rarer, and I don't think just because we have a right that
we need to subsidize that right.''
</P>
<P>
   THE ONCE AND FUTURE MARION BARRY
</P>
<P>
   Marion Barry, once the very popular, very visible and very
imprisoned mayor of Washington, is telling friends he may run
again, this time for a return to the city council. Though out of
office for 14 months, Barry still has a large political following
in the city. But should he run, he faces a couple of major
obstacles: Harold Brazil, the person who holds the council seat
Barry is eyeing has no intention of going quietly, and Anthony
Williams, the present mayor, said he'd support Barry in just about
anything except a return to city office.
</P>
<P>
   BIG SCORE FOR LAROUCHE
</P>
<P>
   Political extremist Lyndon LaRouche captured 22 percent of the
vote running against Al Gore in the Arkansas Democratic
presidential primary in Arkansas, but the party already has
declared LaRouche and his followers to be personae non gratae at
the national convention. Still, the LaRouche followers were
ecstatic. ``This is amazing. We're shocked,'' LaRouche spokeswoman
Angela Vullo was quoted as saying in the Arkansas Democrat-Gazette.
``We're totally excited. It is incredible that this would happen in
Clinton's state.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
