<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-GORDON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORDON SAYS NO SWEAT TO PLAN FOR DOUBLE RACING DATES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LEE SCHEIDE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ For all the naysayers questioning Robby Gordon's
second attempt to drive the 1,100 miles of the Indianapolis 500 and
the Coca-Cola 600 on Sunday, the Winston Cup regular has just one
word: Baja.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, 31, has driven the famed Baja 1000 race solo on several
occasions. That is a distance of 1,032 miles in 17-plus hours of
nonstop bumping, bouncing and sliding through the dusty Mexican
wilderness, with his truck sometimes reaching speeds of 140 mph on
the few paved roads along the route.
</P>
<P>
   So the Californian shrugs his shoulders when asked about this
weekend's attempt at the Indy 500 on Sunday morning, then the
Coca-Cola 600 at Lowe's Motor Speedway in Charlotte, N.C., that
evening.
</P>
<P>
   The last driver to complete such a double is Tony Stewart, who
ran ninth at Indianapolis last year then finished fourth in
Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is harder than driving in Baja, nothing,'' Gordon
said. ``I love to race and I think that's the main reason that I'm
trying it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time behind the wheel and the distance isn't a problem
because I don't sit right on top of the wheel like some guys; I'm a
more laid-back, relaxed driver. And I'm in pretty good shape, so
I'm feeling pretty confident about Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Confidence has never been a problem for Gordon, at any level of
his career. A champion motocross rider, he graduated to off-road
racing at 16 and won the first event he entered.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after success in the Mickey Thompson Stadium Off-Road
Championship series, Gordon caught the eye of Jack Roush and moved
to the pavement of the IMSA series, winning four consecutive 24
Hours of Daytona.
</P>
<P>
   Chip Ganassi then offered Gordon a seat in the CART series for
eight races in 1992, which turned into a full-time ride for A.J.
Foyt the next season. From Foyt's garage, Gordon moved to Derrick
Walker's team, and in 1995 and 1996 he finished fifth at the
Indianapolis 500. But the Indy 500 was the highlight of Gordon's
1996 season, and after it finished he announced that he was moving
over to NASCAR to drive for Felix Sabates.
</P>
<P>
   Thus came Gordon's first attempt at the double, when he put his
own team together for the Brickyard. Weather foiled that attempt,
as the 1997 Indy 500 was postponed by rain, allowing Gordon plenty
of time to fly to Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   When he came back to Indy, finally getting in the car on the
following Tuesday, he had just passed Arie Luyendyk for the lead on
the restart when fumes in his cockpit caught on fire, causing burns
to Gordon's legs and hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``An 11-cent O-ring is what cost us that day,'' Gordon said.
``We researched it all the way back and found out that the O-rings
were wrong and that the manufacturer had put the wrong ones in the
bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good car and I thought that we would have a chance at
winning the race. After that, my deal with Felix soured some and I
ended up looking for somewhere to race.''
</P>
<P>
   That was with Cal Wells back in CART. Gordon had driven for
Wells in the Mickey Thompson series and was happy to be back with
his mentor. Not happy enough, though, when the Toyota engine proved
to be very temperamental, relegating Gordon to mid-pack finishes.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, Wells gave Gordon a chance for a different kind
of double _ racing at St. Louis in the CART race on Saturday, then
flying to Indianapolis to run the 500 on Sunday. After qualifying
fourth for the 500, the plan was set in motion.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's day ended early in St. Louis, however, as he crashed
out of the race. He more than made up for it on Sunday. Driving for
team owner John Menard, Gordon had the race in hand with less than
10 miles to go.
</P>
<P>
   What he didn't have, though, was enough fuel in his tank, having
to pit with less than two laps remaining and handing the victory to
Kenny Brack. Gordon finished fourth and with the impending move
back to Winston Cup for this season, figured his days of driving
the Indy 500 were over _ at least for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Until a month ago, when Menard decided to enter a second car at
the Brickyard. Since he is one of Gordon's partners in NASCAR,
Menard asked Gordon to drive and the double shift was on again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Robby's got a great chance to win here at
Indianapolis,'' Menard said. ``We came very close last year and
he's been running very well during practice and in qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he's been doing a solid job in Winston Cup and that's a
big race, as well, on Sunday. Hopefully, he'll be successful here
and then continue that success in Charlotte.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Lee Scheide by e-mail at lscheide(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
