<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`KIKUJIRO': BUDDY STORY DEPARTURE FOR JAPANESE DIRECTOR FAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.)  
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Takeshi Kitano, the director of ``Kikujiro,'' has been widely
acclaimed for his violent, meditative yakuza (gangster) movies,
which explore the bloody deeds and uneasy consciences of members of
Japan's legendary criminal underworld, often played, with volcanic
charisma, by Kitano himself using the alias Beat Takeshi.
</P>
<P>
   While he's not explicitly a gangster, this film's grumpy,
profane title character is another sensitive thug, whose every
phrase and gesture jabs like a dirty thumb for the eye of the
decorous, repressed, middle-class society he inhabits.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Kikujiro,'' which was shown at last year's Cannes and
Toronto film festivals, is something of a departure for Kitano, if
not for his alter ego. It's a sentimental comedy about a troubled
child and his unlikely, reluctant adult protector, part of a
subgenre that goes back at least to Charlie Chaplin's ``Kid'' and
that includes ``Gloria'' (twice), ``Central Station'' and a dozen
cornball kiddie road pictures whose names have been mercifully
forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   While the film doesn't sink to the level of, say, ``Cop and a
Half,'' a 1993 Burt Reynolds turkey, ``Kikujiro'' offers little
besides its setting that is likely to seem unfamiliar to American
viewers. There are some arresting visual touches _ Kitano is a
painter as well as a filmmaker _ and a handful of loose, whimsical
scenes. But the movie's humor is dissipated by its slow pace and
static scenes, and its emotional payoff is assumed rather than
earned.
</P>
<P>
   Kikujiro, referred to throughout the film simply as ``Mister,''
is a middle-aged layabout whose wife, perhaps to get him out of her
way, entrusts him with the care of her friend's young grandson,
Masao (Yusuke Sekiguchi), a mopey, moon-faced 9-year-old who longs
to find the mother who abandoned him. Mister promises to take him
to the beach, but they end up at the bicycle track, where the boy's
failure to pick winners provokes his new guardian to sputtering
rage.
</P>
<P>
   Mister's ill temper is matched only by his staggering
incompetence. He's a lousy gambler, a worse car thief (he doesn't
know how to operate a stick shift) and a disastrous hitchhiker. He
tries to stop passing motorists by feigning blindness, and then by
laying nails in the middle of the road in the hope of puncturing
their tires. When he fails to trick people into doing what he
wants, he insults them, and when that doesn't work, he threatens
violence.
</P>
<P>
   In time, Mister develops a soft spot for his young charge, and
the two set off on a slow journey through the Japanese countryside
in search of Masao's mother. Along the way, they encounter a
collection of misfits and eccentrics, including a pair of sensitive
bikers that Mister christens Fatso and Baldy (Great Gidayu and
Rakkyo Ide) and an itinerant poet (Nezumi Mamura). With Mister in
the role of demented camp counselor, they devise impromptu
amusements ``for the kid's sake'': swinging from trees, parading
around in costumes and playing the Japanese version of Red Light,
Green Light.
</P>
<P>
   Though it generally moves with painful deliberateness,
``Kikujiro'' musters occasional touches of shambling, playful
charm. The story is seen through the child's eyes, interspersed
with his lurid, stagey dreams and divided into chapters whose
titles _ ``Mister Is Strange,'' ``The Scary Man'' _ reflect his
innocent, baffled perspective.
</P>
<P>
   These dreamy touches can't compensate for the film's main flaw,
which is that the relationship between the two main characters
never really develops, in spite of all the time they spend
together. The boy spends most of the time looking at the ground and
frowning, and Beat Takeshi never lets go of his shtick long enough
to let anyone else in.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're just like me, kid,'' he says at the end. But there's no
sense that the two have really gotten to know each other, or
changed each other, even though the presence of syrupy piano and
strings assures us that they must have.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `KIKUJIRO'
</P>
<P>
   Directed, written and edited by Takeshi Kitano; in Japanese,
with English subtitles; director of photography, Katsumi
Yanagishima; music by Joe Hisaishi; art director, Norihiro Isoda;
produced by Masayuki Mori and Takio Yoshida; released by Sony
Pictures Classics.
</P>
<P>
   With: Beat Takeshi (Kikujiro), Yusuke Sekiguchi (Masao), Kayoko
Kishimoto (Kikujiro's wife), Yuko Daike (Masao's mother), Kazuko
Yoshiyuiki (Masao's grandmother), Great Gidayu (Fatso), Rakkyo Ide
(Baldy) and Nezumi Mamura (Traveling Man).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 116 minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Kikujiro'' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying parent
or adult guardian). It includes some profanity, mild violence and a
scene of attempted child molestation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
