<HEADER>
A5659 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-ART-N     05-25 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATER BABIES: THE ALLURING CHRIS-CRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., N.J., N.H., Calif., Australia)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By SUZANNE CHARLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was still in grade school when I had my first ride in a
Chris-Craft Racing Runabout. It was mid-August 1959, and Barnegat
Bay in New Jersey was pure glass. Taking my cues from my father _ a
sailor and ice-boater _ I had disdained ``stinkpots,'' the sailor's
term for motorboats. But when a friend invited me for a spin on his
father's gleaming wooden motorboat, I hopped in.
</P>
<P>
   A deft captain, my friend's father smoothly maneuvered us out of
the slip, careful to make no wake. On the bay, he smiled as he
opened the throttle full. We roared into the night, the
acceleration jamming me back into the red vinyl cushions. The long
sleek bow with its racy caulk lines lifted high out of the water;
phosphorescent spray flamed by the low freeboard like galaxies of
stars. I was thrilled: this must be what astronauts felt, shooting
though space.
</P>
<P>
   It is just such early memories that have made the 19-foot
Chris-Craft Racing Runabout one of the most popular classic boats
in the United States, according to Wilson W. Wright, the executive
director of the Chris-Craft Antique Boat Club, which is based in
Tallahassee, Fla. From 1947 to July 1954, 503 were built. ``They
were the Corvettes, the Thunderbirds of their era,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like their automotive counterparts, they can fetch high prices,
as much as $50,000 for a show-quality boat with original hardware
and motor. Boats in excellent condition but lacking what judges
term ``originality,'' because owners have added souped-up motors or
improved controls, are also popular. One, a 1953 Chris-Craft Racing
Runabout, is expected to fetch $25,000 to $35,000 at the New
Hampshire Antique and Classic Boat Auction on June 17 at Moody
Mountain Farm in Wolfeboro, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a basket case when I found it eight years ago,'' said
Gil Steward, who donated the boat for the auction to benefit the
New Hampshire Antique and Classic Boat Museum on Lake
Winnipesaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Restorers rebuilt the bottom and deck for Steward, a stockbroker
who also judges classic boat shows. He set to work rebuilding and
installing a small block Chevrolet 350 Ci-250 horsepower engine
with a Holley carburetor. ``I'm a hot rodder at heart,'' he said.
``I figure, conservatively, it will go 55 to 57 miles per hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Going fast is what these boats are all about. In the late 19th
century, Wright said, the first racing runabouts were custom-built
for gentlemen boaters on the St. Lawrence Seaway. By the 1920s,
several companies vied for the trade. Cigar-smoking Chris Smith,
the founder of Chris-Craft, took a lesson from Detroit and built
the first standardized runabout in 1922.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry Ford wanted to put a car in every garage in America,''
Wright said. ``Chris Smith wanted to put a boat in every
boathouse.'' Unlike Gar Wood, which produced runabouts one at a
time, with the same crew working on every detail of the boat, Smith
broke down the assembly into teams. ``Think of the Model A,''
Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   After World War II Chris-Craft became the largest manufacturer
of wood motorboats. The 19-foot Racing Runabout was the speedster
of the line, painted red-and-white or blue-and-white. Some claim
that this was a patriotic gesture to attract returning GIs, but
most historians believe they were painted because of the materials
used _ fir and cedar rather than the mahogany so prized for
brightwork. In 1949, when wood from the Philippines was available
again, the company built the boats in varnished Chris-Craft-grade
mahogany (actually, a mahogany relative called luan).
</P>
<P>
   Races, sanctioned by the American Power Boat Association or
informal, were held on summer weekends across the country, from
Long Island Sound to Lake Tahoe. Jack Savage, author of
``Chris-Craft'' (MBI Publishing), said there was even a race down
the Colorado River. The contest was between a 19-foot Chris-Craft
Racing Runabout and a specially built racer _ an archetypal battle
between the common man and privileged class. The assembly-line
Chris-Craft won when the custom boat's water-cooled engine lost
power because of the sandy river water.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1950s Chris-Craft stopped producing the jazzy Racing
Runabout, shifting its emphasis to larger leisure crafts with open
cockpits, more suited to America's growing families. A final blow
came when fiberglass took over the industry. By the 1970s the wood
Racing Runabouts were considered passe.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller and easier to store, most racers did not meet the fate
of many larger woodies, left to rot in some marsh or hauled to a
garbage dump and burned. Instead, they were stored in boathouses,
pulled out of the water on pulleys.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many of the antique Racing Runabouts can be found on or
near northern lakes, precisely because of those boathouses (sun is
hard on wood) and because in colder climes boats were seldom used
more than 40 hours a summer. (Freshwater is not a factor: while
easier than saltwater on engines and chrome, it is harder on wood
because of dry rot.)
</P>
<P>
   Anyone can learn the age of a Chris-Craft boat by giving the
Mariners' Museum in Newport News, Va., its hull number, from a
brass tag on the engine hatch. Chris-Craft kept meticulous records
and in 1985 donated its archives _ 55,000 plans, 25,000 photographs
and 105,000 hull cards _ to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was one hull card for each boat built from 1922 to 1980,
a little bit like a birth certificate,'' explained Jerry Conrad,
archivist for the museum. The hull card details when the boat was
built, the specifications, and to what town and dealer it was
shipped. The museum receives 1,200 to 1,500 requests a year.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of the classic racing runabouts no longer race as a
formal class _ Wright, a lawyer, ruefully talks of liability and
insurance _ but they attend vintage boat shows. The big ones
include the season opener in Mount Dora, Fla., in March; in Wiers
on Lake Winnipesaukee on July 29; and in Clayton, N.Y, and Tahoe,
Calif., in August.
</P>
<P>
   If two or three Chris-Craft racers should meet on the water?
Well, says Wright, maybe there will be an informal test of speed:
``It's a basic instinct.''
</P>
<P>
   George Johnson, who has been selling, riding and racing boats on
the Eastern seaboard for over half a century, estimates there are
probably 200 Chris-Craft Racing Runabouts in various conditions on
the lakes, bays and rivers of the country. Two companies _ Vintage
Marine in Mattituck, N.Y., and Golden Era Classics, outside Sydney,
Australia _ build replicas of the Chris-Craft Racing Runabout, for
those who do not want to go through the lengthy process of finding
and restoring an original.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 75 and living on Lake Winnipesaukee, has sold his two
antique Racing Runabouts and ordered two reproductions for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're nicer, stronger, faster, lighter,'' he said, adding
that what he really likes to do is take an evening spin, when the
water is still and the breeze is down, and the deep reverberating
sound of the motor echoes off the wooded hills.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
