<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5663 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-0526-COX     05-25 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-0526-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A MICROSOFT TRIAL THAT NEVER WAS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Microsoft legal document released at the close of
Wednesday's climactic judicial hearing revealed how the software
giant had hoped to soften the blow of being branded an abusive
monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   With the government pressing to cleave the software giant in
two, a beset Microsoft pleaded with U.S. District Court Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson to try the case again _ this time over how
to remedy its antitrust offenses.
</P>
<P>
   When Jackson said that he was prepared, after two years, to
close the case, the company's lawyers gave him a star-studded list
of defense witnesses. The ``offer of proof'' serves as a road map
of further courtroom testimony.
</P>
<P>
   According to that document, if seated in the witness chair,
Microsoft chairman Bill Gates and chief executive Steve Ballmer
would testify how the world's most valued software company would be
ruined if Jackson approved the government's far-reaching break-up
plan and curbs in the company's future conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Gates did not take the stand during the 78-trial. He appeared
instead on videotapes that the prosecutors used repeatedly to draw
sharp contradictions to the damaging e-mail he wrote in supposed
confidence to key corporate figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Gates' poor preparation for his deposition proved to be a
cardinal error because the government put him as much on trial as
the company itself,'' C. Boyden Gray, a Microsoft legal consultant
and a former White House counsel, said recently in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Had Microsoft put Gates at the witness stand, his deposition
could not have been shown in the courtroom, let alone played on
television.
</P>
<P>
   According to the document, Gates was prepared to testify about a
new computing platform that ``will provide system services to
software developers.'' That platform, he would say, ``enables them
to produce Web-based applications accessible from a wide-range of
devices, creating whole new ways for consumers to benefit from the
global network that is the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   That business plan, to be formally announced June 1, ``will cost
Microsoft billions of dollars to develop and is an extremely risky
venture with no assurance of success,'' as Gates' planned testimony
would have had it.
</P>
<P>
   But Gates would also have been cross-examined by David Boies,
the lead prosecutor for the Justice Department, who had sparred
with him during the 1998 deposition.
</P>
<P>
   Boies, for example, could have questioned Gates about his
decision last March to resign from the board of the Software and
Information Industry Association and to pull Microsoft out of the
trade group after it had written a friend-of-the-court brief to
Jackson critical of Microsoft's conduct during the liability phase
of the case.
</P>
<P>
   During the hearing, Jackson praised a subsequent brief from the
group that said: ``Those events shed a strong light on the remedy
issue now before this court.'' The brief added:
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft's power and wealth gave it the ability to both
punish its critics and retain battalions of lawyers, lobbyists and
publicists to undermine the government at every turn.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson made it clear on Wednesday that he wanted no part of a
second trial over remedies, even in a more condensed form than the
six-month preparation processes which Microsoft had sought.
</P>
<P>
   His surprise decision stunned the defense because in four
separate private conferences with Jackson the lawyers were led to
expect that they were entitled to a full hearing if drastic
remedies were put on the table. Even Boies said he expected an
extended procedure to be followed.
</P>
<P>
   For Jackson, however, that would be a trial too far.
</P>
<P>
   The judge is now all but ready to rule on Microsoft's fate,
filing a judgment that will almost surely split the company into
two or three parts. He has shown himself willing to risk that the
appeals court will not reverse a breakup ruling, which he will stay
pending the outcome of the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft says it would have appealed no matter what. But now it
says its appeal will also stress Jackson's unwillingness to give
Gates his day in court.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: For more information
www.microsoft.com/presspass/trial.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
