<HEADER>
A5667 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-GORPCOM28-COX     05-25 0429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORP </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 COM28-COX &HT;    Grads' stop before European rail junket: GORP
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, May 28.
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   All aboard, graduates. A leading online adventure travel guide
has your ticket to a post-academic rite of passage: exploring
Europe by train.
</P>
<P>
   This month, the Great Outdoor Recreation Pages (GORP.com)
launched ``Eurailing: A Great American Tradition.'' A
nuts-and-bolts primer on Europe's rail pass system, it is aimed at
the scores of graduating high school and college students who are
right about now throwing off their caps and gowns and strapping on
backpacks for a summer of Old World wandering.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the economy doing so well, more young people are
traveling the world,'' says GORP editor in chief Bill Greer, who
founded the site in 1995 with his wife, Diane. ``We thought we'd
take a look at one of the classic adventures.''
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the site can read a brief history of the pass
system, introduced in 1959, before accessing handy sections on
which of 16 different passes to buy.
</P>
<P>
   All-summer bums looking for a leisurely chug around the
continent will want to spring for the ``unlimited'' Eurail Pass,
good for three months of travel in 17 countries from Spain to
Finland. Travelers with less time or money may opt for the cheaper
Europass, which covers travel in France, Germany, Italy, Spain and
Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   Young rail-hoppers _ and travelers of any age on a budget _ will
click with the ``do's and don'ts'' and ``tricks'' sections, which
offer tips on how to squeeze the most value from your rail pass.
Thinking of training around Spain? Don't buy a ``single country
pass'' there _ GORP says Spanish Railways has jacked up the price
to get the most out of unsuspecting tourists.
</P>
<P>
   GORP is introducing two other adventure features this summer:
The Thru-Hiker series will offer dispatches from six hikers on the
Pacific Crest Trail, the Continental Divide and the Appalachian
Trail. And on June 18, GORP will sponsor cyclists in a
cross-country ride to benefit the American Lung Association and
offer a forum for site visitors to ask the riders questions and
post personal anecdotes.
</P>
<P>
   Though GORP has an online booking service for adventure
excursions, from trekking in Nepal to sea kayaking in Patagonia,
you can't secure Eurail passes through the site. To purchase a pass
or to find out about rates and schedules, call Rail Europe at
1-877-456-7245 or visit www.raileurope.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
