r t BC-GORPSIDE28-COX     05-25 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORPSIDE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet contains a world of travel tips for young adults
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, May 28
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can I get that diploma . . . to go?
</P>
<P>
   With commencement addresses still echoing in the air, America's
high school and college graduates are faced with one of the
greatest issues of their young lives _ where to venture for the
traditional post-matriculation vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Will it be rafting in Nepal or ralphing on Bourbon Street?
Whatever the destination, more and more young travelers are turning
to the Web to help them get there. And savvy sites are responding
with travel advice geared toward Generations X, Y and Z. With its
newly launched primer on Eurail passes, the eco-adventure site
Gorp.com is one of many Internet travel guides aiming to attract
the school's-out crowd. Among the others:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  STA Travel (www.statravel.com). ``This ain't your parent's
travel agency'' declares this sassy site, dedicated to student
travelers. STA offers advice on how to get a passport and book
budget accommodations, as well as information on airline and rail
pass deals. Visitors can book discounted airline tickets and, in
the ``Show and Tell'' chat room, share experiences with other young
globetrotters.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Council Travel (www.counciltravel.com). Billed as ``America's
student travel leader,'' this site posts listings of international
hostels (provided you purchase a $25 ``hostel membership'' card).
There's also a handy quick-search for round-trip student air fares.
Interested in continuing your education? Check out sections on
language courses, volunteering and study/work abroad programs.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Contiki (www.contiki.com). Online arm of the popular tour
operator that caters to travelers 18 to 35 with group excursions in
Europe, Africa, Australia, Canada and the U.S. New tours include a
12-day ``Taste of Tuscany'' tour, with stops in Siena, Florence,
Pisa and other Italian towns; and a 13-day ``Mediterranean
Highlights'' trip that visits Spain, France, Italy and Monaco.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  TrekAmerica (www.trekamerica.com). Tour operator's summer
program organizes group adventures in North America for 18 to
38-year-olds. Activities include whale watching off the Pacific Rim
National Park in British Columbia, exploring Mayan culture in the
Yucatan and rafting the Snake River in Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
