<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5671 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FASHION-WHITES28-COX     05-25 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-WHITES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Starting today, white's all right
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rules are meant to be broken. Especially when it comes to
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how old, bold or stylish we get, many of the dress
codes we were taught growing up _ like not wearing white pants,
suits or accessories before Memorial Day or after Labor Day _
remain etched in the back of our minds. Whether we follow them is a
matter of personal style.
</P>
<P>
   Take Porsche Foxx, an on-air personality at V-103/FM, for
example.
</P>
<P>
   She was eager to wear a pair of white pants to work a couple of
weeks ago, but didn't have the nerve to break the Memorial Day
rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a definite no-no,'' said Foxx, who joked about it on
air. ``I'd hate to walk out and have somebody talk about me.''
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to sandals, Foxx ignores the old rule about
not wearing them before summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been known to wear sandals most of the winter,'' she
says. ``I love my feet out.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of feet. ... The old rules say to keep them covered in
the workplace with closed-toe shoes. Sandals aren't businesslike.
And mules belong in the bedroom, not the boardroom.
</P>
<P>
   But that was then.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, sandals are being worn with business suits. We've
gotten a lot more daring with what we show and what we don't,''
says Mary Justman, director of fashion and modeling at Bauder
College in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   What about legs? A woman was supposed to wear stockings
year-round at work, regardless of how hot it was outside. Bare legs
were only acceptable in casual settings, such as the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's gone with the wind,'' says Georgia Lee,
southeast editor of Women's Wear Daily, the industry trade paper.
``Shoes have changed the whole approach to legwear. Hose looks
stupid with some of them. Bare legs have become a lot more
acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Amy Helton, public relations manager at Neiman Marcus,
believes nylons are still de rigueur in business and formal
settings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hosiery is so important,'' she says. ``It evens out your skin
tone and covers up scars and scratches, and it just looks a lot
neater.''
</P>
<P>
   Fashion designers are doing their part to revise old dress codes
with the styles they create. Leather and suede, traditionally worn
from October to April, appeared on the runways in hot miniskirts
and halter tops. Bright spring colors were shown for fall. Snow
white garments were as popular for winter as spring and summer. And
lightweight fabrics were paired with heavier textures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've become so advanced in the technology of our fabrics that
there's so many that can be worn year-round. We didn't have that
before,'' says Kevin Knaus, consultant and creative director for
Material World, a fabric trade show in Atlanta. ``Designers have
changed a lot of the rules. But the one rule that seems to really
stick in people's minds is not wearing white shoes before Easter.''
</P>
<P>
   Just for the record, here are some more ``old rules'' of summer.
Let your style conscious be your guide:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wear patent-leather shoes only after Memorial Day, or Easter
if you live in a warm climate.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  No white clothes, shoes or gloves after Labor Day. Ditto for
straw hats and sandals.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Never wear nude stockings with white shoes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't wear black or dark colors after Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Never wear pastels after Labor Day, except on cruises.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't wear sleeveless tops or dresses to work.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Match shoes, belt and handbag all year round.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't wear white or black to a wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
