<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MISSION26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Mission' victim of lame plot, effects glut
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Mission: Impossible 2'' is even less a big-screen expansion of
the beloved TV series than the first film was. It's not about
teamwork, but a showcase for Tom Cruise _ a star franchise that
tries to distract us from its lame plot with explosions and noisy,
incoherent chase scenes. Think of it as ``Die Hard'' with
salon-perfect hair. (Cruise's stylist deserves above-the-title
billing.)
</P>
<P>
   ``M:I2'' starts well, introducing IMF turncoat Sean Ambrose
(Dougray Scott), who plans to use a biologically engineered,
Ebola-like virus to ransom the world. Ethan Hunt (Cruise), first
seen dangling by his fingertips from a cliff wall (a sharp,
dizzying sequence), is summoned by his superior (Anthony Hopkins,
in a cameo) to foil Ambrose's plans.
</P>
<P>
   The key to this is professional thief Nyah Hall (Thandie
Newton), the best Bond girl Agent 007 never met. Hunt and Hall meet
cute during her latest jewel theft, and they're soon enjoying a
memorable brand of foreplay _ racing their convertibles along
whiplash mountain roads, sideswiping each other inches away from
sheer drops. Then, sex.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that Nyah was once Ambrose's lover. So, in a plot
twist swiped from Alfred Hitchcock's ``Notorious,'' Nyah's
assignment (should she choose to accept it) is to infiltrate the
baddie's compound by returning to his bed.
</P>
<P>
   After an hour, just when the movie needs to be coming together
and growing more complicated, it gets simple and dumb. There are a
lot of overamplified kung-fu fights, grenade detonations and a very
long motorcycle chase consisting of quick, tight shots that never
allow us to get a sense of real movement.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : Information about the Tom Cruise fan club,
chat room and more: www.ixplosive.com/run.html
</P>
<P>
   ``Mission: Impossible 2''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Starring Tom Cruise and Thandie Newton. Directed by John Woo.
Rated PG-13 for intense sequences of violent action and some
sensuality. At metro theaters. 2 hours, 6 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Cruise control lapses into autopilot in this noisy,
underscripted sequel.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
