<HEADER>
A5674 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-PASSION26-COX     05-25 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-PASSION26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A double dose of Demi can't heat up this `Passion'
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is double the Demi double the fun?
</P>
<P>
   Not really. But then, fun isn't exactly what the ex-Mrs. Bruce
Willis' new movie has in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passion of Mind,'' which could be subtitled ``The Double Life
of Demi,'' is a romantic fantasy/psychological drama along the
lines of ``Sliding Doors'' or ``Me Myself I.'' Moore plays a woman
who lives two lives simultaneously. In one, she's Marie, a widowed
mother who resides in a picture-perfect villa in Provence and
supports her two young daughters by free-lancing book reviews for
The New York Times. In the other, she's Marty, a high-powered,
unattached literary agent who spends her time rushing around the
gleaming spires of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The neat twist in Ron Bass' script, which he wrote over a decade
ago with Michelle Pfeiffer involved, is that both Marty and Marie
are fully aware of each other's existence. That is, Marie knows
that when she falls asleep in France, she'll wake up in Marty's
glossy Manhattan loft. And Marty knows that going to bed means a
trip to rural France the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   They also both realize that one of these lives must be a
fantasy, which is why both go to shrinks. But which life is real?
And if Marty/Marie could choose, which would it be?
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good. But where ``Passion'' runs into problems is the
way it tries to fill in both lives. The result, alas, is a kind of
glorified Lifetime movie, times two. In France, Marie meets a
handsome, available, sensitive novelist (Stellan Skarsgard) whose
book she once panned. In New York, Marty meets a handsome,
available, sensitive accountant (William Fichtner) whom she once
chewed out over a client. As both relationships become more
intimate, Marty/Marie freely discusses her other life with the man
of the moment. Instead of worrying about how thoroughly bonkers she
might be, they shrug and decide they're jealous of the other guy.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, director Alain Berliner made the marvelous ``Ma
Vie en Rose,'' in which a little boy was firmly convinced he was a
little girl. Berliner obviously knows how to handle dicey material.
But the trouble here is that ``Passion'' isn't dicey enough.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad, because the way everything ties together at the end has
a genuine emotional kick. But by the time we get there, our
emotional involvement with Marty/Marie has diminished. By half at
the very least.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For a detailed Demi Moore fan site:
www.geocities.com/Hollywood/9990/demi.html
</P>
<P>
   ``Passion of Mind''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Starring Demi Moore. Directed by Alain Berliner. Rated PG-13 for
sex.1 hour,
</P>
<P>
   45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A double fantasy that's, alas, half as effective as
it could be.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
