<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sweeps give way to reruns
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've said goodbye to May sweeps, which officially ended
Wednesday night. They were the sweeps in which practically all we
did was say goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   To ``Beverly Hills 90210,'' long past its heyday, but which
lives on, Stridex-pad-legacywise, on the WB.
</P>
<P>
   To ``Party of Five,'' ``Cosby'' and ``Boy Meets World.'' To
Andrea Thompson (Detective Jill Kirkendall of ``NYPD Blue''), who's
giving up acting to become a local news anchor. To ``X-Filer'' Fox
Mulder, whisked away by a spacecraft in the season finale; David
Duchovny will be MIA for the first part of next season.
</P>
<P>
   And to ``Spin City's'' Michael J. Fox, who exited graciously
Wednesday night after the most overdone and overplayed tear-jerking
promotional spots in TV history. Get a grip, ABC. You know Fox is
planning to come back to the show next season for guest
appearances; the head of ABC Entertainment announced it to
advertisers last week. Funny how that didn't make it into those
sappy promos.
</P>
<P>
   And so, moving forward, it's summertime, which means reruns are
in full bloom. But at least a lot of swimming pools are opening
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Friday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Making the Band'' (9 p.m. on ABC) _ A group of cute young
studs compete to become members of a boy band. This series ran for
three weeks a while back and bombed, but ABC is repackaging it and
trying again.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Teen People's 25 Hottest Stars Under 25'' (3:38 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   on WSB) _ No, that time is not a typo. WSB is pre-empting this
ABC hour of eye candy for a ``Monica Kaufman Close-Ups'' special at
8 p.m. and bumping it to the wee hours. Justin Timberlake of 'N
Sync hosts this hymn to young 'uns, some of whom are there on
talent (singer Charlotte Church, the cast of ``That '70s Show'')
and some mainly on looks (singer Mandy Moore, who makes Britney
Spears look like Aretha Franklin).
</P>
<P>
   Saturday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Dirty Pictures'' (9 p.m. on Showtime) _ Two weeks ago
Showtime ran ``Rated X''; now it's ``Dirty Pictures.'' But
``Pictures'' isn't as dirty as ``Rated X'' was. James Woods stars
as Dennis Barrie, the director of a Cincinnati art museum who got
into big trouble in 1990 for displaying sexually explicit
photographs by Robert Mapplethorpe. It's more an endorsement of the
First Amendment than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Guinness Book of World Records Primetime'' (9 p.m. on Fox) _
It's baa-aack! The show that gave us the tumor as big as the Ritz
tonight has a guy who can water-ski barefoot at 150 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Mission: Impossible Marathon'' (10 a.m.-5 p.m. on FX) _ With
the Tom Cruise movie sequel opening, cable's FX channel reruns some
of the original TV series, which aired from 1966 to '73. Fewer
chases and special effects, but it did have Martin Landau and
Barbara Bain.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Indianapolis 500''
</P>
<P>
   (11 a.m. on ABC) _ Around and around and around and . . .
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``On the Beach'' (8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   on Showtime) _ Aussies Bryan Brown and Rachel Ward co-star in
this remake of Nevil Shute's post-apocalyptic novel, originally
filmed in 1959 with Gregory Peck and Ava Gardner. Unlike the recent
live ``Fail Safe,'' ``Beach'' has been updated to modern times, but
it's still basically about a small group of survivors of a nuclear
war in Australia. Showtime shot it as a two-parter and now has
decided to air it all in one night, which might indicate just
getting it over with.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Twin Peaks'' (8 p.m. on
</P>
<P>
   Bravo) and ``Dune'' (8 p.m. on Sci-Fi) _ In a weird scheduling
coincidence, Bravo reruns the classic two-hour pilot to ``Peaks'' _
still an amazing slice of television, despite what happened to the
series later _ while the Sci-Fi Channel shows the widely disparaged
movie ``Dune.'' Both star Kyle MacLachlan, and both were directed
by David Lynch. Only ``Twin Peaks,'' though, has that damn fine
cherry pie.
</P>
<P>
   Movies
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Six Degrees of Separation'' (10:30 p.m. Saturday on Bravo) _
Kevin Bacon isn't in it, but Will Smith is.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Footloose'' (3:10 p.m. Sunday on TNT) _ Six degrees of Lori
Singer? Naw, that just doesn't work as well.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
