<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service has moved the following
entertainment/arts and travel articles this week and will move the
following business articles for release Sunday, May 28, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Moved in `e' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER-FILMS (Undated) _ Like death and taxes some things never
seem to change. Like summer movies. Always the same: fiery
explosions, knock-out special effects, thin plots, well-muscled
stars. Add to that nonstop television commercials, toys on the
shelves, action figures in the Happy Meal. It seems so formulaic.
Despite appearances, however, the summer blockbuster has changed
plenty since its birth, but the changes have been subtle and
cumulative. By Nancy Hass.
</P>
<P>
   LOCATIONS-FILMS (Paris) _ Romantic confusions of person and
place: Films like ``The Talented Mr. Ripley,'' ``The Beach,'' ``Out
of Africa,'' ``The Sheltering Sky'' and the recently released ``I
Dreamed of Africa'' have attempted to explore what happens when
people join hands and parachute into the wilderness of a shared
dream. Those who chase their fantasies to Paris or Kenya, Thailand
or Morocco usually learn that dreams are promises waiting to be
broken: love in a new climate withers as often as it blooms. By
Kristin Hohenadel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GIELGUD-REMEMBERED (London) _ John Gielgud, language and the
human soul. An appreciation by Benedict Nightingale.
</P>
<P>
   RUSKIN-THEATER (Undated) _ `The Countess' explores John Ruskin,
his wife, and her lover. By Lucinda Franks.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OPERA-HEROES (Undated) _ Arts, like athletics, needs heroes. Yet
opera heroes offer a unique twist: they live in the past. By
Matthew Gurewitsch.
</P>
<P>
   By JAZZ-SOLOS (Undated) _ The solo is certainly the primary
symbol of jazz to the outside world _ a rail-splitting statement
made within a rail-splitting music. In the history of jazz
criticism, solos have been taken as the highest mode of assertion;
there are more analyses of solos than those of rhythm sections, for
example, and they're much better-known pieces of criticism. And
most of the great heroes of the music have been powerhouse
soloists. By Ben Ratliff.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   TAKE-FO-MUSIC (New Orleans) _ By all means, this should have
been the time for Take Fo' to explode into the mainstream. The
music it popularized, a salacious, booty-shaking regional dance
music called bounce, has in the last year fueled some of hip-hop's
biggest hits. On radio stations around the country, every fan of
urban pop was dancing to Earl Mackie's music. Only they didn't know
it was his. By Neil Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   KATEY-RED-MUSIC (New Orleans) _ Katey Red may be one of the
first openly homosexual rap and bounce-music artist to earn respect
in this notoriously homophobic world. Add to that Katey Red's
chronic respiratory problems and a debilitating stutter, and you
have a most unlikely regional star, even in a city with a rich
culture of cross-dressing. By Neil Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   ARRAU-MUSIC-SOLOS (Undated) _ The recordings of Claudio Arrau
revisited. By Joseph Horowitz.
</P>
<P>
   PREMIERES-MUSIC (Undated) _ Premieres are unnatural births.
Humans, unlike Greek gods and new operas, enter the world helpless
and barely formed. An opening night, especially one preceded by
fanfare, speculation and promotion, has no chance at childhood and
adolescence. Often its midwives are inept and its expectant parents
unprepared. The new piece happens all at once and fully formed. It
relies on the wisdom and charity of audiences, critics and
performers faced suddenly with an odd phenomenon: the grown-up
infant. By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MARTINS-DANCE (New York) _ Tradition and innovation, discipline
and fun, at the School of American Ballet. Year after year, in the
dancing of the latest crop of advanced students, the workshops
present a glimpse of ballet's ideals. By Laura Leivick.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MARY-HARTMAN-TV (Undated) _ It was 1976 when Louise Lasser took
over the television screen as a confused, nervous, pigtail-wearing
American housewife. Anita Gates offers a retrospective on a
television show that captured the interest of viewers everywhere.
By Anita Gates.
</P>
<P>
   DINOSAURS-TV (Undated) _ This spring, the one-two punch of
``Walking With Dinosaurs'' and ``Raising the Mammoth'' heightened
the visibility of the Discovery Channel. But the public was already
watching, to the tune of 178 million households worldwide. How did
dinosaurs and woolly mammoths manage to compete with Regis Philbin
in popularity without giving away money? According to Dr. James
Powell, the head of Los Angeles County's Natural History Museum
Foundation, their appeal, especially to children, may be related to
their enormous size. ``They are fantastic, as in creatures of
fantasy _ as though they had been dreamed up by a science-fiction
writer,'' he said. ``They weren't. They lived, they breathed, they
fought, they bred, they bled, they died.'' By Thelma Adams.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ROME-ART (Rome) _ For years, the problem of how to be both
relevant and imaginative in the first summer of the new millennium
has tormented curators the world over. But nowhere has that problem
been solved as nimbly or as persuasively as in an exhibition in
Rome called ``L'Idea del Bello'' at the Palazzo delle Esposizione
on the Via Nazionale, on view through June 26. (The title can be
read in English as ``The Idea of Beauty'' or ``Beauty as an
Idea.'') By John Russell.
</P>
<P>
   GILBERT-ART (London) _ Sir Arthur Gilbert, a British-born art
collector long resident in Los Angeles, could not be happier. Last
week, the Gilbert Collection, comprising some 850 works of
decorative art, opened to the public in an elegant
late-18th-century palace on the banks of the Thames in central
London. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTIQUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUE-BOOKS (London) _ In its heyday a half century ago,
Foyle's, on Charing Cross Road here, was known the world over as
the people's bookstore, stocking five million books, mostly
secondhand, on every imaginable subject, on its 30 miles of
shelves. Now, the Foyle family and other heirs are selling William
Foyle's books at Christie's here in a sale described as ``the
largest British book collection to be auctioned in 20 years.'' By
Rita Reif.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-FLY-FISHING (Undated) _ At fly-fishing school, it's not
how many trout you catch, it's how you catch them. By Tim Golden.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-KAYAK-CALIF (Undated) _ Rolling on the river _ the
Salmon, in this case _ is a key lesson for kayakers. By John
Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-MOSCOW (Undated) _ A mystery fan looks in vain for the
bleak despair of old Moscow. By Marilyn Stasio.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ Kayaks and canoes are filling
remote waterways. How to find an outfitter that will guide you in
the wild. By Betsy Wade.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Lead item: Vikings return to
Newfoundland.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Lead items: Visiting Shaw's England,
Picasso's Paris.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIT-TRAINS (Undated) _ Service slips, fares baffle on
British trains. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will send the following money
and business articles for release Sunday, May 28.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ON THE SECTION FRONT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CALICO-DOTCOM (San Jose, Calif.) _ In November, 100 employees of
Calico Commerce were millionaires, at least on paper. Today only 20
are. With Calico's stock down 80 percent from its peak last fall,
the rest have watched their wealth melt away over the last five
months like snow in the hot California sun. But Calico, which makes
software designed to help companies sell their products over the
Internet, seems to be weathering the storm so far. By Alex
Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   HMO-CONSUMERS (Undated) _ A doctor refuses a treatment for a
sick child. State medical officials later find the treatment was
medically necessary, and that the doctor blundered. Can the doctor
escape punishment because he works as a medical director for an HMO
or other managed care company? That is the question in a federal
court lawsuit in Dallas that pits one of the nation's largest
health insurance providers, UnitedHealthcare, against Texas
officials who have proposed disciplining one of the company's
medical directors, the unseen but powerful officials who make the
behind-the-scenes decisions to approve or deny patient treatments.
By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-WATCH (Undated) _ Commentary on events from he week on
Wall Street. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSIDE THE SECTION: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PROFILE-HOLDEN (Northfield, Ill.) _ Profile of Betsy Holden, the
new CEO of Kraft Foods. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   ASSISTED-LIVING (Undated) _ Fueled by favorable demographic
trends, strong consumer demand and a robust economy, the
assisted-living industry was supposed to be mounting record profits
this year while expanding rapidly and reaching new stock market
peaks. That, at least, is what analysts were predicting three years
ago. It has not exactly worked out that way. By Terry Pristin.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-BOOK (Undated) _ A decade or so ago Dennis N.T. Perkins,
president of Syncretics Group, Branford, Conn., brought us ``the
moose at the table,'' the disarming metaphor that companies use to
mention the unmentionable. He devised that impish but effective
image as a way of coaxing business people into talking openly about
the sensitive issues that hang heavy over a discussion but that no
one dares mention. Now Perkins, a management consultant whose
clients include American Express, Bose, Citibank and Marriott, is
back with bigger game in mind. His new book offers lessons in
leadership ``at the outer limits of human endurance _ the place I
call The Edge.'' By Fred Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-BOOK-PERKINS (Undated) _ `Leading at the Edge: Leadership
Lessons from &QL; 
the Extraordinary Saga of Shackleton's Antarctic Expedition, by
Dennis N. T. Perkins.` Q&AMP;A with the author.
</P>
<P>
   ON-THE-JOB (Undated) _ Like most things in life, commuting is in
the eye of the beholder. Most of the time, it's an obligation, a
habit, no more than a repetitive journey from home to workplace and
back again. But once in a while, commuting becomes high adventure,
a source of laughter and the stuff of lasting memories. By Lawrence
Van Gelder.
</P>
<P>
   NEIGHBOR-LAWSUITS (UNdated) _ When neighbors sue neighbors ...
And they are doing it more than ever. By Vivian Marino.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INVESTING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Market Insight Q&AMP;A ... Subject to
come. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-DIGEST (Undated) _ Investing notes and news; Funds Watch.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-OFFMAN-RABBI (Undated) _ Investing With: Mayer Offman of
Carlson Financial Group, a day trading rabbi. By Hilary Rosenberg.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-DEAN&AMP;DELUCA (Undated) _ Are shares of Dean &AMP; DeLuca,
readying a public offering, a buy? By Sana Siwolop.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS COMMENTARY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ECON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Economic View: Social Security and older
workers. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   MIDSTREAM-COLUMN (Undated) _ Although our parents are very fond
of us, often those feelings don't run deep enough to take
investment advice from their reckless children. By James Schembari.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AUTOS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT-CARS-TAHOE (Beverly Hills, Calif.) _ When General Motors
put its huge Suburban on the treadmill and watched it lose about 20
inches around the midsection, it created the Chevrolet Tahoe and
the GMC Yukon, shorter, more manageable sport utilities with major
V8 power. What it lacked was a third row of seats and the bright
folks at Ford and Dodge didn't let GM forget it. Now the big news
is not only that GM will put a third seat in its Tahoes and Yukons,
but it split the third bench in half so that each part can fold
neatly out of the way for cargo. By Leonard M. Apcar.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
