<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5684 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-APPLES-PHILLY-ART-4TA     05-25 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-PHILLY-ART-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENAISSANCE ON THE SCHUYLKILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: NYT Photos 4,5,6 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ This is a city on second base, wondering if it
can make it all the way home.
</P>
<P>
   The old Philadelphia, which lived on manufacturing and banking
and lawyering, ran out of steam a half-century ago. Now the city is
betting a billion dollars and more that a new Philadelphia can
prosper on history and culture and tourism _ that people will come
here not merely for the obligatory visit to the Liberty Bell with
the kids but for several days of meetings, music, art, shopping and
good food as well.
</P>
<P>
   An unmistakable new energy has taken hold in Center City, as the
locals call downtown Philadelphia. Without losing its civilized
manners, the city has begun to bounce after dark; Walnut Street's
sidewalks are still crowded at 10 p.m. A Democrat, Ed Rendell, a
husky, dynamic former mayor, gets much of the credit for setting
the transformation in motion, but the first big payoff is this
year's Republican National Convention, opening here on July 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``People at the convention will see signs of a real renaissance
in key parts of the city,'' said Sen. Arlen Specter, who served as
Philadelphia's district attorney before heading to Washington.
``But don't delude yourself: 15 blocks from the center, enormous
problems remain.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia was, of course, America's original convention city,
beginning in 1774 with the Continental Congress, which two years
later produced the Declaration of Independence. But no major
political party has held its quadrennial powwow in the city since
1948, when no fewer than three of them did so (the Democrats, to
choose Harry S. Truman; the Republicans, to nominate Thomas E.
Dewey, and the Progressives, to name Henry A. Wallace).
</P>
<P>
   A lot has happened since then, too much of it bad. Philadelphia
lost many of its defining institutions, including The Saturday
Evening Post, once the nation's leading magazine; The Bulletin, a
powerful and venerable evening newspaper; the Pennsylvania
Railroad, one of the first great routes to the West; John
Wanamaker's department store, a pioneer of mass merchandising; and
the Philadelphia Athletics, who made baseball history under Connie
Mack. It had a surly white mayor, Frank Rizzo, whose
confrontational approach to blacks was typified by the nightstick
he once famously tucked into his cummerbund, and a star-crossed
black mayor, W. Wilson Goode, who in 1985 dropped a firebomb on the
headquarters of a radical group in his own city.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976 an outbreak of a mysterious respiratory disease killed
34 members of the American Legion attending a convention here.
</P>
<P>
   David Cohen, a co-chairman of the host committee for the
Republican gathering, defined the status quo ante in these words:
``People didn't have low expectations of Philadelphia; they had no
expectations of Philadelphia.'' They saw it, he said, as ``an old
city, falling apart, dirty and unsafe.''
</P>
<P>
   A first important step toward recovery was a new convention
center, which opened in 1993. Then, in 1996, 548,000 people came to
see a Cezanne exhibition at the Museum of Art _ many of them
suburbanites who hadn't been downtown in years, many others from
New York, Washington and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Local leaders realized that there was big money in culture.
Broad Street got a face-lift and a new name, the Avenue of the
Arts, and this year steelwork for a new, $245 million Regional
Performing Arts Center began rising there. Designed by Rafael
Vinoly of New York in emulation of London's 19th-century Crystal
Palace, it is scheduled to open in the fall of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   To house the hoped-for throngs of visitors, 5,000 new hotel
rooms have been added in the metropolitan area in four years. Two
of the splashiest new hotels and several restaurants have taken
over old banks; the metaphor is almost too apt.
</P>
<P>
   The much-admired PSFS building (the letters stand for
Philadelphia Savings Fund Society, though few remember that) is now
a Loews hotel, with all its architectural glories, including a
polished black granite base that bends around a corner,
miraculously intact. Designed by William Lescaze and George Howe in
1932, it was the first International Style skyscraper built in this
country, just at the end of the Art Deco era. Soon the old Girard
Trust Co., a little Ionic temple with a perfect dome, designed in
dazzlingly white Georgia marble by Stanford White, will be a
Ritz-Carlton.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia used to concentrate on food that filled big men up
fast: cheese steaks, hoagies, soft pretzels, L.D. Bassett's
world-class ice cream, scrapple (a Pennsylvania Dutch blend of
cornmeal and unmentionable pig parts), sticky buns and pepper pot
soup (a potent brew of honeycomb tripe and hot chilies). Most of
the traditional fare can still be found at the Reading Terminal
Market (often sold there by Amish or Mennonite women in white gauze
caps) or at Bookbinders Seafood House on 15th Street or both.
</P>
<P>
   BOOMING (AND SHRINKING)
</P>
<P>
   But now the city is a playground for foodies, with heroically
hip restaurants opening every month. These are no storefront
improvisations; by the end of the year, Neil Stein, who started it
all with a place called Striped Bass, will have opened five
sophisticated spots at a cost of $10 million. ``I think it will
work,'' he told me, ``if the economy holds up.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Nichols, who has watched the city's travails for years from
various posts at The Philadelphia Inquirer, sounded similarly
cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fate of Philadelphia really hangs in the balance,'' he
said. ``Can we live off this culture-dining-service boom, or do we
need more lunch-bucket jobs to keep the thing going?''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Look carefully on the side streets downtown, and you will see
vacant shops and even a few vacant buildings. The region's retail
nexus is not there but out in the suburbs, at King of Prussia, in a
megamall where Hermes and Neiman Marcus and other chic merchants
court the carriage trade. Jobs have fled the city, too, as
companies like CoreStates Financial and Bell Atlantic have closed
or shrunk their Philadelphia offices because of mergers.
</P>
<P>
   New stadiums for the Phillies and Eagles are all talk and no
action, and the ballyhooed DisneyQuest mall is just another hole in
the ground, its financing having collapsed. Rendell, now the
Democratic national chairman, must be devastated; the project had
so excited him that he told an English visitor, ``To call it
virtual reality is to call Michelangelo a house painter.'' The city
will now have to make do with a $300 million Family Entertainment
Center at Penn's Landing on the Delaware River, featuring a
children's museum, an 18-screen multiplex cinema, restaurants and a
wide range of shops. Not exactly the sort of thing that brings the
Renaissance to mind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   William P. Hankowsky, Philadelphia's industrial development
czar, acknowledged frankly that ``you have two contradictory
phenomena here at the same time: Center City is booming, with
people moving back downtown, while the population as a whole is
still in decline.'' With some exceptions, like Chestnut Hill, the
northern, western and southern parts of Philadelphia are worn and
worried. Between 1990 and 1998, the city lost 9.4 percent of its
population; of the 10 largest cities in the United States, only
Detroit and Philadelphia shrank, and Philadelphia shrank more.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphians tend to undersell Philadelphia. Is it the Quaker
heritage of dour understatement? Or the city's position halfway
between the nation's political capital, to the south, and its
economic and cultural capital, to the north? Could it possibly be
an inferiority complex?
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheering against the home team is a time-honored tradition in
Philadelphia,'' wrote the social historian E. Digby Baltzell.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, locals have allowed a Philadelphia-born
comedian of minimal talent, W.C. Fields, to fasten a joke to their
city like a barnacle. Asked what he wanted on his gravestone, the
great man is said to have replied, ``On the whole, I'd rather be in
Philadelphia.'' That one-liner has been repeated ad nauseam.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this has always been a richly endowed city, full of
distinctive neighborhoods, a center of artistic and intellectual
life since the days of Benjamin Franklin and the Peales, much loved
by those who live here. The population is less transient than in
most large American cities; Philadelphians may flee to the suburbs,
but most of them go no farther.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they call it Philadelphia or Philly, a nickname loved by
some and loathed by others, whether they are Rocky Balboas (or
Frankie Avalons or Vic Damones) from gritty, Italian-American South
Philadelphia or Tracy Lords from the wealthy, pastoral Main Line,
they are staunch loyalists.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia story started with that redoubtable Quaker,
William Penn, who laid out the city's grid in 1682. It was he, not
some latter-day adman, who named it the City of Brotherly Love, and
he who gave it many of its characteristics: its respect for
education (Temple, Villanova, Haverford, Swarthmore, Bryn Mawr and
Drexel, as well as the University of Pennsylvania, with its
celebrated Wharton School of Business, carry that tradition forward
today); its wide streets and its extensive parks, religious
tolerance and closely knit families.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Mark Twain got the picture. In Boston, he said, people
ask, ``What does he know?'' In New York they ask, ``How much does
he make?'' In Philadelphia, the crucial question is, ``Who were his
parents?''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some of those families can be frosty, snobby and self-satisfied,
their lives consecrated to the First Troop of the Philadelphia City
Cavalry, the Merion Cricket Club and the Union League Club (whose
brownstone clubhouse bears a plaque celebrating its loyalty to the
North in the Civil War). Many live in the western suburbs known as
the Main Line because the Pennsylvania railroad connected them on a
route running from Philadelphia to Paoli.
</P>
<P>
   Generations of young college students learned a mnemonic aid to
help them find their way home: ``Old maids never wed and have
babies,'' for Overbrook, Merion, Narberth, Wynnewood, Ardmore,
Haverford, Bryn Mawr.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But of course Philadelphia is not all socialites or Quakers or
Italian-Americans, and even if the current gamble succeeds, it will
not become a tourist target and little else, like Las Vegas or
Orlando. Anne d'Harnoncourt, the director of the Museum of Art, New
York-bred but devotedly Philadelphian by adoption, calls this ``a
city full of nooks and niches.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not just Rittenhouse Square, the traditional center of
patrician Philadelphia, bounded by mismatched buildings that give
it visual vigor, used every day by dogs and bums and
Frisbee-tossing adolescents and pram-pushing nannies and students
from the nearby Curtis Institute of Music, and celebrated for its
vitality by no less than Jane Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia is also the home of an old and eminent black
community, which has produced national leaders like A. Leon
Higginbotham Jr., who was a towering presence on the Federal
appeals bench; former congressman William Gray, who now heads the
United Negro College Fund; and William Coleman, a former
transportation secretary. And it is a river town; the Schuylkill
(pronounced SKOO-kul) ) is one of the city's delights, especially
on days when it is filled with sculls and eight-oared shells from
clubs along its bank. Grace Kelly's father and brother, both named
Jack, rowed there and won national titles.
</P>
<P>
   FROM GREEK REVIVAL TO POP
</P>
<P>
   The tide of the Revolution flowed through and around
Philadelphia. Washington crossed the Delaware just north of town,
lost to the redcoats at Germantown and spent the severe winter of
1777-78 at Valley Forge. But it is in the Old City, in the blocks
south of Walnut Street between Second and Sixth Streets, that the
drama of those astounding years comes to life.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is, as its promoters say, ``The Most Historic Square
Mile in America.'' Few visitors miss the Liberty Bell or
Independence Hall, where both the Declaration and the Constitution,
those two extraordinary products of Enlightenment genius, were
debated and finally approved. Even the history-averse are stirred,
though the fabric of the buildings has been mended as often as an
old sock.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Franklin was a dominant figure in the life of the city
and the young nation, so it seems fitting that he is buried nearby,
across the street from the Free Quaker Meeting House. His grave is
strewn with coins tossed by tourists mindful of his maxim ``A penny
saved is a penny earned''; the site of his house is marked by a
steel frame devised by Robert Venturi, a ``skeleton'' of the
original, much more evocative than a mere reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the red-brick houses where Washington and Madison
and the others lived during the decade from 1790 to 1800, when
Philadelphia was the nation's capital, still stand on the cobbled
streets, shaded by plane trees, south of the Independence National
Historic Park. You can sit in the pews where the Founding Fathers
sat (Washington used Pew 58) at Christ Church, whose six-sided,
209-foot steeple, built in 1753 and 1754, was the tallest structure
in America for more than a century. Influenced by the work of Gibbs
and Wren in London, the church is remarkable for its broad expanses
of clear glass.
</P>
<P>
   Some idea of the wealth of Philadelphia may be gained from late
Georgian mansions like Cliveden (1767), in Germantown, and Mount
Pleasant (1762), in Fairmount Park, the nation's largest urban
park. Cliveden, seat of the Chew family, still contains chairs and
a sofa by Thomas Affleck, one of the greatest Colonial furniture
makers. At the end of the 18th century, Philadelphia was the
leading American city. Once the government left, it never again
enjoyed that eminence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But it built as if it did. That was the doing mainly of Nicholas
Biddle, the city's social, cultural and financial star (and the
founder of its most notable dynasty of civic leaders). He returned
from a trip to Athens in 1806 with this in his diary: ``The two
great truths in the world are the Bible and Grecian architecture.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon the city was awash in Greek Revival temples, from the
Philadelphia Water Works (1819) along the Schuylkill River to
Biddle's own magnificent house, Andalusia (1836), high above the
east bank of the Delaware, with a grand, six-column-wide portico
designed by Thomas U. Walter. The Second Bank of the United States
(1819-1824), designed by William Strickland, parts of which
literally copied the Parthenon, is the masterpiece of the genre. In
this white marble temple, Biddle, the bank's president, fought with
Henry Clay against Andrew Jackson for control of the nation's
monetary supply, and lost. Monuments and Culture
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Biddle's day, Philadelphia has had a taste for the
monumental. A climax of sorts was reached in the exuberant Second
Empire City Hall (1872-1901), a hulking, multi-pavilioned mountain
of a building topped by a statue of the city's founder, William
Penn. The creation of Alexander Milne Calder, Penn stands up there
in a broad-brimmed hat, all of 37 feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Franklin Parkway, the city's ceremonial boulevard, is a
Calder-to-Calder-to-Calder triple play. Halfway along its length,
one comes to Logan Circle, which was modeled after the Place de la
Concorde in Paris; the fountain in the center is by A.M.'s son,
Alexander Stirling Calder. At the far end of the parkway, at the
top of the steps leading up to the Greek Revival facade of the
Museum of Art (remember them from ``Rocky''?), stands a bold red
stabile called ``The Eagle,'' by A.S.'s son, Alexander Calder.
</P>
<P>
   The transitional figure in Philadelphia architecture was Frank
Furness, whose taste for the exotic and the eclectic is evident in
the Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts. His enthusiasm for
certain kinds of foliate decoration communicated itself to a young
draftsman in his office named Louis Sullivan, who returned to
Chicago and became a pioneer modernist.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia has had two great latter-day modernists: Louis I.
Kahn, whose Richards laboratories at Penn (1960-64) turn the
unavoidable technological folderol into crisp design elements,
prefiguring the Pompidou Center in Paris, and Venturi, the father
of Pop architecture. For me at least, local buildings by Frank
Lloyd Wright (a synagogue in Elkins Park) and Helmut Jahn (the
Liberty Place skyscrapers) are less successful.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Art and the Philadelphia Orchestra are both ranked
among the top five or six institutions of their kind in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Founded exactly 100 years ago, the orchestra is older. Wolfgang
Sawallisch, its current music director, surprised many here by
presenting its subscribers with a centennial program composed
entirely of 20th-century music, from Scriabin and Poulenc to
Lutoslawski and Takemitsu. Many of the pieces had been given their
American premieres by the orchestra under Eugene Ormandy and
Leopold Stokowski, who introduced Stravinsky's ``Rite of Spring''
here in 1922. Joseph H. Kluger, the orchestra's president, said
that the programs of more-or-less modern music had given a boost to
single-ticket sales, brought the average age of audiences down and
provided ``an idea we plan to build on.''
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra has been housed for years in the Academy of Music,
a charming, 143-year-old opera house whose acoustics are poor for
symphonic music. Soon the orchestra will be the main tenant in the
new arts center, and a new conductor is expected to replace
Sawallisch, who is 76, once the move is made. The move is not
without controversy; the old academy may be the city's most beloved
building, and neither the Pew nor the Annenberg foundations, two of
the city's cultural mainstays, contributed to the new center's
cost.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, it will confer at least one indisputable benefit on
the city by opening more room at the academy for the Philadelphia
Opera, which has made considerable progress under Robert B. Driver,
and the Pennsylvania Ballet. Their growth has been stunted by a
dearth of free dates there.
</P>
<P>
   Across from the academy is the Wilma Theater, designed by Hugh
Hardy. Two Czech-born directors, Blanka and Jiri Zizka, present
works there by David Gow, Tom Stoppard and many others, in
productions that are often controversial but very seldom dull.
</P>
<P>
   A VAST BASTION OF ART
</P>
<P>
   The vast, honey-colored Museum of Art looks as if it had been
there for 700 years, not 70. It will soon get an annex _ an Art
Deco building across the street, which will provide 100,000 square
feet of additional space. Its holdings are enormous, ranging from
period rooms (including one by the great Scottish designer Robert
Adam) to impressive arrays of armor and Oriental art. It also
continues, in the tradition of the Cezanne show, to mount and
aggressively promote special shows, though I must confess that I
found the current exhibition of 18th-century Roman art a letdown;
for me, it's a struggle to accept Pompeo Batoni as a seminal figure
among European painters.
</P>
<P>
   But the museum's permanent painting collections more than make
up for that. Its old masters are dominated by the pictures
accumulated by John G. Johnson, the prototypical Philadelphia
lawyer, who appeared a record 168 times before the Supreme Court.
And his pictures (among them arresting works by van Eyck and
Giovanni di Paolo) are dominated by the majestic Rogier van der
Weyden portrayal of the Crucifixion with the Virgin and St. John
the Evangelist.
</P>
<P>
   The austere figures are shown against brilliant red hangings,
the Virgin crumpling in grief, Christ's loincloth lifted by some
mysterious force. It is the saddest, greatest painting in the
museum and one of the greatest in the United States. I have sat
before it a dozen times, always mesmerized.
</P>
<P>
   In another part of the building are assembled the brilliant,
before-their-time collections of Walter and Louise Arensberg and
A.E. Gallatin, notably Miros, Brancusis and Duchamps, including the
once-scandalous ``Nude Descending a Staircase.'' At the moment, the
modern galleries are being renovated, but that gives visitors a
chance to see (and compare) three large-scale masterpieces in one
small room: Leger's colorful, mechanistic ``City''; Picasso's
``Three Musicians,'' a pivotal example of Synthetic Cubism; and
Cezanne's architectonic yet lyrical ``Large Bathers.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the museum also prides itself on its paintings by
local artists, and it would be a mistake to miss Thomas Eakins'
``Concert Singer.'' But a greater Eakins painting, ``The Gross
Clinic,'' hangs at Thomas Jefferson University, and others are at
St. Charles Borromeo Seminary in Overbrook, where the painter
sought solace on Sunday afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
