<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5689 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MILITARY-DEATH-PENALT     05-25 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-DEATH-PENALTY-$ADV28-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ARMY WEIGHS FIRST MILITARY EXECUTION IN 40 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, May 28)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the first time in nearly 40 years, the U.S.
military is preparing to execute one of its own, an Army private
convicted and sentenced to death for robbing and murdering two taxi
drivers in Killeen, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Loving, 31, of Rochester, N.Y., killed his victims in
Dec. 11, 1988, near Fort Hood, Texas, where he was stationed as an
artillery gunner. A 31-hour murder and robbery binge netted Loving
a little more than $100, trial evidence showed.
</P>
<P>
   An eight-member military tribunal found him guilty in April 1989
and sentenced him to death.
</P>
<P>
   Loving, imprisoned on death row at the Ft. Leavenworth, Kan.,
federal penitentiary, has had his death sentence upheld by
successive military courts. In 1996, the U.S. Supreme Court
unanimously upheld his conviction. Two years later, the court
declined to hear another appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing stands between Loving and lethal injection in
Leavenworth's death chamber except President Clinton and what his
lawyers and other legal experts claim is a vague and unfair
bureaucratic process now underway in the Army.
</P>
<P>
   In a procedure unique to the military, all capital cases _ after
they have run their course through the military's judiciary _ must
be sent for a final review by the top civilian chief of the
service. In Loving's case, that is Army Secretary Louis Caldera.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary and the Army judge advocate general _ the
service's top lawyer _ assess the evidence in the case and then
make a recommendation to the president about whether the death
sentence should be carried out.
</P>
<P>
   That recommendation to the president is supposed to be based on
the Army secretary's judgment about whether the punishment fits the
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Uniformed Code of Military Justice, the regulations
that guide the military judicial system, the president has two
choices, once the military's recommendation reaches his desk. He
must either sign the prisoner's death warrant or commute the
sentence to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The last capital case to be sent for presidential review
involved a U.S. Navy sailor who was convicted of murder. President
Kennedy, in 1961, commuted the death sentence to a prison term
because questions had been raised about the defendant's sanity at
the time of the crime. That same year, Kennedy approved the
execution of a soldier who was hanged for rape and attempted
murder.
</P>
<P>
   That was the last time an execution was carried out against a
member of the military.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, in addition to Loving, there are five men sitting on
military death row _ two others from the Army and three Marines.
</P>
<P>
   Loving's attorney, Theresa Norris, of Columbia, S.C., asserts
that the life-or-death process starting in the Pentagon and ending
up at the White House is weighted against military defendants
because it takes place behind closed doors and allows defense
counsel little opportunity to press their case. For example, the
Army's Pentagon review process in the Loving case has been underway
for about 16 months. But aside from one clemency request Norris
submitted in late 1998, she has had no communication with Army
headquarters since.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get to death penalty in the military, there's no
provision for defense involvement,'' Norris said. ``I should be
able to respond to all recommendations (as the case travels up the
chain) but the way the system is set up, there is no opportunity at
all,'' she said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Sullivan, a former Marine Corps lawyer and military death
penalty specialist with the Maryland chapter of the American Civil
Liberties Union, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   The manual of courts marital ``outlines a very scant process,''
Sullivan said. It is ``extremely difficult for Loving's defense
counsel, because she doesn't know to whom to make the clemency
arguments. It's amazingly frustrating and unfair,'' Sullivan said
in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The Army's Judge Advocate General office defends the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The requirements are clear and well-defined,'' the office said
in written responses to questions from Hearst Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the service lawyers said, the clemency petition
Norris submitted in 1998 ``will be considered by all officials who
make a recommendation, prior to making any recommendation as to
approval or commutation of Pvt. Loving's sentence.''Martha Rudd, an
Army spokeswoman at the Pentagon, said service lawyers are
methodically reviewing the case ``to be fair to (Loving), to make
sure everything that happens in his case is by the book and takes
into account everything that's occurred in the last 40 years that
might be relevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Army lawyers declined to discuss when the service would complete
its recommendation and forward it to the president. Historically,
some cases have made it to the president's desk in a year, while
others have required two years of review.  &UR;  &LR;  &QL; (Eric Rosenberg can be
reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail address
eric &LR; hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
