<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5690 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-APPLE'S-PHILLY-ART-4T     05-25 1483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE'S-PHILLY-ART-4THTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PHILADELPHIA: Sunday afternoons.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Art is, in fact, almost omnipresent in and around Philadelphia.
In Merion, the truly fabulous Barnes collection (reserve in
advance) mixes rustic ironwork with paintings that people travel
thousands of miles to see. The Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine
Arts boasts a brilliant American collection, including superb works
by Gilbert Stuart, Winslow Homer and all the Peales. The museum at
the University of Pennsylvania houses the golden treasures from the
ancient Sumerian city of Ur, amid much else. And the Rosenbach
Museum and Library contains not only the rare books and manuscripts
accumulated by A.S.W. Rosenbach, a scholarly, piratical dealer who
helped to build the Folger Library in Washington and the Huntington
Library near Los Angeles, but also important antique furniture.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of attractions, along with travel
information:
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   FOUR SEASONS, 1 Logan Square, (215) 963-1500. The opulent,
flower-filled lobby tells the story: no expense has been spared
here. But as one of the hotel's executives says, ``The mahogany and
marble are the easy parts.'' The hard part is building a skilled,
attentive, kindly staff, and the Seasons succeeds superbly on that
count, too. The Fountain dining room, where Jean-Marie Lacroix has
presided since 1983, is the peer of any restaurant in town.
Computer connections, a bit dated, are to be modernized soon.
Double room: $240 to $320, weekends; $305 to $400, weekdays.
</P>
<P>
   LOEWS, 1200 Market St., (215) 627-1200. A tip of the Apple hat
to the Tisch family, which has converted the landmark PSFS building
into a hotel of ravishing Art Deco beauty. The old vault doors and
silvery sans-serif signs have been used to great graphic effect in
the lobby, amidst acres of rosewood and etched glass. The 583
bedrooms murmur ``Hollywood, 1930,'' with a chaise longue in every
one; a club-floor library holds vintage books. Double room: $175 to
$365.
</P>
<P>
   RITTENHOUSE, 210 West Rittenhouse Square, (215) 546-9000. The
harsh zigzag facade does little for the harmony of the urban
environment, though it gives the 128 guest rooms leafy views.
Otherwise, the Rittenhouse is hard to fault, with a central
location, an invitingly cool lobby and bedrooms swimming with
space. Each has a desk tucked into an alcove, a fax and a video
tape player, plus a dressing area and a marble bathroom with an
oversize tub and separate stall shower. The low-key service is
charmingly accommodating. Double rooms from $360; occasional
weekend specials from $200.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO EAT
</P>
<P>
   LE BEC-FIN, 1523 Walnut St., (215) 567-1000. When Paul Bocuse
visited Georges Perrier's formal little jewel box, with its
raspberry-pink walls and tapestry-covered chairs, he pronounced it
``a real restaurant, more like Lyons than New York.'' The cooking
is classical, lightened and brightened here and there with an Asian
spice like Sichuan pepper. European fish (loup, turbot) are a
specialty, as are desserts, dispensed from a calorie chariot five
levels high. Great cheeses; great, very costly French wines.
</P>
<P>
   FORK, 306 Market St., (215) 625-9425. With bare floors, an open
kitchen, and a fixation on freshness worthy of Alice Waters, this
is the perfect place for lunch on a tour of the city's Colonial
shrines. Try the satisfyingly rustic chicken-mushroom-barley soup,
a fishy or meaty salad and the chocolate cake with banana gelato,
plus a beer from the cosmopolitan list.
</P>
<P>
   PASION!, 211 South 15th St., (215) 875-9895. For my money,
Guillermo Pernot's nuevo Latino cooking is the most exciting in
Philadelphia at the moment. A superlative chili-laced ceviche of
Chilean sea bass and seaweed, presented alongside a scallop shell,
is served with big smiles in a tented room full of palms and bright
fabrics. Likewise, an Argentine mixed grill, a Haitian empanada and
the very best Chilean wines.
</P>
<P>
   PAT'S KING OF STEAKS, Ninth and Wharton Streets, (215) 468-1546.
This is the real deal: these are the folks who gave the world the
Philly cheese steak _ thinly sliced, quickly grilled beef, slapped
onto an Italian roll, slathered with Cheez-Whiz, topped with
onions. Pat's stands on a triangular traffic island in the heart of
Rocky country, South Philadelphia, across the street from an
asphalt basketball court. You order your sandwich at a tiny window
and eat it at a plastic table, right on the street. It's silly,
sloppy and, in its own way, sublime.
</P>
<P>
   STRIPED BASS, 1500 Walnut St., (215) 732-4444. The lofty
ceilings and the marble columns of this erstwhile banking hall,
built in 1927, always put me in a mellow mood, as do the Fortuny
lighting fixtures and the snazzy metal fish hanging overhead.
Terence Feury, an alumnus of Le Bernardin in Manhattan, has
refreshed a tired menu with distinctive, unpompous dishes like
crisp-skinned striped bass (what else?) served on a tangle of
bitter greens.
</P>
<P>
   SUSANNA FOO, 1512 Walnut St., (215) 545-2666. Born in Mongolia,
Sue Foo, as the local Asian grocers like to call her, is equally at
home with Asian and European culinary traditions. In a dining room
full of orchids and Asian art, she serves a trio of dumplings
(shrimp, duck, lobster), each in a deliciously different wrapper,
and dares to pair fish in a tangy, winy sauce with sweet rice.
Five-spice Pennsylvania venison is another hit.
</P>
<P>
   TANGERINE, 232 Market St., (215) 627-5116. This semi-nightclub
is the town's hot spot, so you have to put up with noise, semi-pro
service and dim, candle-lighted, souk-like passageways. But most of
the Moroccan fantasy food is well worth it, notably gnocchi with
dates and harissa and a honey-and-lamb tagine, cooked in a crockery
dish with a top shaped like a coolie's hat. The fish and the duck
are overdone. Comfortably low-backed leather chairs; dandy desserts
(chocolate cake streaked with tangerine) from Laurie Shapiro.
</P>
<P>
   ATTRACTIONS
</P>
<P>
   ACADEMY OF MUSIC, 1420 Locust St., at Broad Street, (215)
893-1999. The next program is the Pennsylvania Ballet's production
of ``Dracula,'' opening Wednesday and running through June 11.
Tickets: $15 to $86. The Philadelphia Orchestra begins its fall
season in Sept.; June 18-19, Harry Connick Jr.
</P>
<P>
   BARNES FOUNDATION, 300 North Latch's Lane, Merion, Pa., (610)
667-0290 (press 5 for reservations) or fax date, time, number of
visitors and credit card number to (610) 667-8315. Reservations are
required. Hours: September through June open Fridays through
Sundays, 9:30 a.m. to 5 p.m.; July and August, Wednesdays through
Fridays, 9:30 a.m. to 5 p.m. Admission: $5.
</P>
<P>
   INDEPENDENCE HALL, Chestnut Street, between Fifth and Sixth
Streets, (215) 597-8974. Free tours begin in the East Wing every 15
minutes, beginning at 9:15 a.m. Printed brochures are also
available in Chinese, French, German, Hebrew, Italian, Japanese,
Spanish or Russian. Hours: Daily, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. (Hours are
extended for some buildings on weekends and in July and August.)
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA MUSEUM OF ART, Benjamin Franklin Parkway at 26th
Street, (215) 763-8100. ``The Splendor of 18th-Century Rome,''
through Sunday. Ticketed show: $12.50 for adults; $9.50 for
students, the elderly and children. The audio tour is $5. Call:
(215) 235-7469. Hours: Tuesdays through Sundays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.;
Wednesdays to 8:45 p.m. Admission: $8; $5, children under 18,
students and the elderly; free on Sundays until 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA ACADEMY OF THE FINE ARTS, Broad and Cherry Streets,
(215) 972-7600. Through Sunday, the annual student exhibition and
graduate thesis exhibition, with more than 1,000 paintings, prints,
sculptures and mixed-media works. Most works are for sale. Hours:
Mondays through Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Sundays, 11 a.m. to 5
p.m. Admission: $5 ; $4, students; $3, those 18 and under; free to
members, children under 5 and everyone on Sundays after 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   THE UNIVERSITY OF PENNSYLVANIA MUSEUM OF ARCHAEOLOGY AND
ANTHROPOLOGY, 33rd and Spruce Streets, (215) 898-4000. In ``44
Celebrity Eyes in a Museum Storeroom,'' 22 celebrities pick their
favorites from the the collection; through Dec. 30. Hours: Tuesdays
through Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 4:30 p.m.; closed Sundays Memorial
Day through Labor Day. Admission: $5; $2.50, the elderly and
students; free for children under 6.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENBACH MUSEUM AND LIBRARY, 2010 Delancey Place, (215)
732-1600. Rare books, manuscripts, furniture, silver and painting.
Hours: Tuesdays through Sundays, 11 a.m. to 4 p.m. (Research
library open by appointment only.) Admission is by tour only: $5;
$3 for the elderly and students.
</P>
<P>
   WILMA THEATER, 265 South Broad St., at Spruce Street, (215)
546-7824. ``Cherry Docs,'' a drama by David Gow. Today at 8 p.m.
(tickets are $35); tomorrow at 2 p.m. ($25) and at 8 p.m. ($38);
Sunday at 2 p.m. ($30).
</P>
