<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5691 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-BBN-GIANTS-ROMP-HNS &LR;      05-25 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-ROMP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GRAND OLD TIME FOR GIANTS PITCHER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANK BLACKMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Shawn Estes was sitting next to pitching coach
Dave Righetti when the San Francisco Giants loaded the bases in the
fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he was going to go deep,'' Righetti said. ``I said
never mind about that. Just concentrate on your pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, Estes strode to the plate and hit the first
pitch he saw into the seats in left field for a grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just joking around,'' Estes said after going the
distance in a preposterous 18-0 victory over Montreal on Wednesday
night at Pacific Bell Park, the most one-sided shutout in Giants
history going back to 1900. ``I said I might as well go deep.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first grand slam by a big-league pitcher since Kent
Mercker did it for St. Louis against Florida on Sept. 2, 1998. It
was the first slam in a shutout since Fred Talbot did it for the
Seattle Pilots against the California Angels in 1969. It was the
first slam ever by a San Francisco pitcher. And it's the first slam
for a Giants pitcher since Monte Kennedy went deep July 3, 1949,
against the Brooklyn Dodgers at the Polo Grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a surreal feeling,'' Estes said. ``There's nothing
to compare to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone joked that maybe the memorable home run should have an
asterisk next to it because the ball is juiced this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' Estes said. ``I'll admit it. With the old ball,
it would have hit the wall or been caught. Thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   A gentleman named Alan Bown would like to say thank you to the
pitcher. He won $10,000 because it was the grand slam inning. That
must have been pretty surreal, too.
</P>
<P>
   Estes' grand slam and shutout in the same game are heady stuff,
something a player or a fan might go _ well, more than 30 years _
without seeing. Dusty Baker was impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was perhaps the best performance I've seen by a
pitcher,'' the Giants manager said.
</P>
<P>
   There was the potential for something even more remarkable. In
the eighth inning, Estes came to the plate with the bases loaded
again. The crowd was up and bellowing, perhaps aware that only two
players in baseball history have hit two grand slams in one game.
</P>
<P>
   And there was a roar when Estes slammed the second pitch he saw
toward the fence in left. But Tony Cloninger (who did it against
the Giants in 1966) and Fernando Tatis were safe. The ball died and
hooked foul into the seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit it off the end of the bat,'' Estes said. ``The fans got
excited about nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he lined a single into left field, driving home his
fifth run of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are good when a pitcher is asking you how many RBIs you
got after the game,'' said a smiling J.T. Snow, who also drove in
five runs.
</P>
<P>
   Estes was having a great time talking about his hitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather talk about hitting than pitching,'' he said.
``Hitting is not something pitchers are supposed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Estes was able to keep things in perspective. The Giants
began the night having lost nine of their previous 10 games. So
what they really needed was a strong pitching effort from the
lefty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely needed the win,'' Estes said. ``We didn't need a
grand slam.''
</P>
<P>
   The win really never was in doubt. San Francisco got on the
board immediately, scoring three times in the opening inning. Barry
Bonds, who left the game after the fifth inning when his calf
muscle tightened, doubled in the game's first run off Mike Thurman.
</P>
<P>
   Two innings later, Bonds preserved Estes' shutout by making a
diving, inning-ending catch of a sinking liner with a runner on
second. Then he came up in the bottom of the third and put a dent
in one of Thurman's pitches, the ball landing in McCovey Cove, the
distance from home plate estimated at 444 feet. It was the fourth
Giants homer, all by Bonds, to be entered on the Splash hits
counter.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds also was a contributor in the seven-run fifth, singling in
his third run. To that point, he was the star of the game. But then
Estes went deep. And when he completed the seven-hitter, he
deserved top billing even though Bonds finished a triple shy of the
cycle and Snow missed it by a double.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shawn's performance overshadowed great games by Barry and
J.T.,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Righetti said what impressed him the most is that Estes kept his
focus after the game became a blowout. Estes agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard,'' he said. ``As a pitcher, you don't want to show
up the other team by throwing them curves and changeups. But you
have a shutout to preserve. And you don't want to end on a bad
note.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't come close to doing that, preventing Montreal from
even getting a runner in scoring position the final seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   What with a slam, two near-cycles, a record shutout, and a big
money give-away, it was an unforgettable night at Pacific Bell
Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just one of those nights,'' Snow said. ``Some nights
you really can't explain things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
