A5695 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SECURITY-BREACH-HNS &LR;      05-25 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECURITY-BREACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GOVERNMENT PROMISES TIGHTER SECURITY IN WAKE OF BREACHES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Government officials promised Thursday to revamp
their security systems in the wake of stunning revelations that
undercover agents using fake cards identifying them as law officers
were able to penetrate 19 federal buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anytime that you expose vulnerabilities, it's a good
thing,'' Attorney General Janet Reno said at a news conference
here. ``We've already begun looking into ways to improve our
security.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a report issued Thursday by the General Accounting
Office, an investigative arm of Congress, a team of GAO
investigators began the undercover operation early this month. The
agents acquired bogus New York Police Department and U.S. Drug
Enforcement Administration badges and credentials _ some of them
cast-off movie props, others manufactured through commercially
available software packages or material downloaded from the
Internet, the GAO said.Over the next three weeks, the agents tried
to get inside 19 federal facilities, which included the FBI
building, the Pentagon, and the CIA headquarters in Langley, Va.
Sometimes they told guards that they were police officers there on
official business. On other occasions, they simply sought to walk
in unannounced.
</P>
<P>
   Each time, the agents, who were armed, succeeded. They got
inside the supposedly secure facilities without being screened or
made to pass through standard metal detectors, the GAO reported.
</P>
<P>
   In some visits, the agents were escorted through the building.
Even then, however, they managed to go unattended to a restroom
carrying briefcases large enough to hold substantial quantities of
explosives, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   But in other cases, the GAO, reported, ``escorts were not
required, and our agents wandered throughout without ever being
stopped.''At the CIA headquarters, which unlike other federal
facilities is closed to the public, the bogus cops faked out guards
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Although the agents had no appointment, they successfully talked
their way past the guard post at the compound's main gate and then
got past the guard station inside the main CIA building. Both sets
of sentries are supposed to check visitors' identification and
bags. The results of the undercover operation, coming on the heels
of major security breaches at the State Department, show that many
of the federal government's most sensitive sites ``are completely
vulnerable to `terrorism on the cheap,''' Rep. Bill McCollum
(R-Fla.), head of the House Judiciary subcommittee on crime, said
in a statement.McCollum held a hearing Thursday to examine the
troubling security lapses. It featured a videotape showing the
undercover agents quickly gaining entry into supposedly secure
sectors of the buildings, often without escorts or inspections.``In
a matter of 10 to 15 seconds, they were in,'' McCollum said at the
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassed officials at the Justice Department said they
already were taking steps to beef up security.
</P>
<P>
   According to one of the top department internal security
official, who asked not to be identified, visiting law enforcement
officers now will be subjected to a more rigorous security check in
which they will be required to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Surrender their firearms before entering the building;
</P>
<P>
   _ Pass through a metal detector and have their bags X-rayed;
</P>
<P>
   _ Have an escort while in the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt, the main problem that came out of this was that
professional courtesy between law enforcement officers allowed
these undercover agents to slip by,'' the official said. ``That
will change.''
</P>
<P>
   The official also said the department was considering the
possibility of issuing to Justice personnel new ``bio-metric''
badges that contain a computer chip allowing guards at any federal
government building to pull up a photograph or fingerprint of the
person issued the credential.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way to use new technology to our advantage, just as a
bad guy can use technology to his advantage,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   CIA officials refused to comment on whether they were changing
their security system. But Pentagon spokesman Craig Quigley said
military installations were taking steps similar to those at
Justice, including requiring law enforcement to surrender their
weapons before entering and to have an escort with them at all
times.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional investigation was spurred by a boom in the
online sale of fake police badges, driver's licenses, passports and
other forms of identification. Some realistic-looking fake IDs can
be bought directly on the Internet for as little as $10, while
other online merchants sell software so customers can make phony
IDs at home in unlimited quantities. Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine,
who has looked into the problem, was able to put her face on a
falsified Army Reserve identification card, a Connecticut driver's
license and a Boston University student ID, prompting her to call
last week for tougher federal penalties for making and using fake
IDs. Rep. Stephen Horn, R-Calif., worried about fake Los Angeles
police badges that have popped up in Southern California, has
proposed legislation to make it a federal crime to traffic in real
or counterfeit police badges.But the security lapses exposed by the
GAO agents represent perhaps the most serious threat posed by the
Internet ID business because they show how vulnerable many
supposedly secure facilities are to terrorism and spying, several
government officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked,'' McCollum said. ``With a massive expansion of
federal anti-terrorist security measures in the wake of the
Oklahoma City bombing (in 1995), I would never have thought this
could happen.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
