<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONIC YOUTH: `NYC GHOSTS AND FLOWERS' 
</HEADLINE>
  By ANN POWERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Self-exile can be a fruitful state, and Sonic Youth _ New York's
quintessential rock band _ tastes its gifts on their new release,
``NYC Ghosts and Flowers'' (Geffen). It views the time and place
that inspires Sonic Youth's breakthrough art rock _ Gotham, as
shaped by the shared lineage of the Beats, the hippies and the
punks.
</P>
<P>
   In eight graceful vignettes that blend noise rock and melodic
musing, the band regards its own history through a cosmic
viewfinder, the landscapes tinged blue by a distance that is both
literal (half the band now lives in Northampton, Mass.) and
emotional.
</P>
<P>
   Some songs are homages to elders like William S. Burroughs,
whose painting adorns the album cover. Others ruefully assess the
legacy of alternative rock. No one era or scene limits Sonic
Youth's focus; the foursome is at its most holistic, mixing punk
focus with compassionate poetic vision. There is room in this
42-minute album for many New Yorks and many Sonic Youths.
</P>
</TEXT>
