<HEADER>
A5702 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v BC-SPOT-BJT26-COXUPDATE     05-25 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 UPDATE &HT;    UPDATE
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Friday, May 26, 2000.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eds. Adds: ATTACK, GLUE, HAITIAN
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _To a beset Microsoft Corp, it is the
trial that should be, one that puts top honchos Bill Gates and
Steve Ballmer on the witness stand to show why a corporate breakup
fails to fit its purported antitrust crimes and would likely not
only ruin its business but also set back the New Economy. For
Microsoft critics, it was the trial that should have been, the
moment missed when Gates instead came across in the courtroom on
videotape as an ignorant lout. But for judge who tried the case,
now ready to bring down a heavy hammer on the software giant, it is
a trial too far. And on this issue he's got the final word. (Glass,
Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   E-PRIVACY _ WASHINGTON _ Industry representatives and senators
react Thursday at a Senate Commerce Committee hearing to the
Federal Trade Commission's call for stronger laws to protect
consumers' privacy on the Internet. (Dart, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
