<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5705 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BAROQUE-ARCHITECTURE-     05-25 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAROQUE-ARCHITECTURE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IDEAS TOOK SHAPE AND SOARED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Italy, Germany, France, Britain, Russia and the
Netherlands)   By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Speaking at a symposium held at UCLA in January,
the historian Anthony Vidler announced, ``All architecture is the
result of panic.'' Panic has broken out with particularly vivid
style in ``The Triumph of the Baroque,'' now on view at the
National Gallery of Art. A survey of European architecture from
1600 to 1750, the show reveals that buildings, like people, can be
overtaken by mass hysteria. For a century and a half, European
walls, doors, roofs, windows and entire cities were contorted into
quivering, writhing shapes.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by Henry A. Millon of the National Gallery along with
Guy Cogeval, Paolo Viti and Marie-Paule Vial, the show documents
the histrionics of Baroque architecture with about 100 artifacts,
including antique wooden models and period paintings of buildings,
gardens and urban vistas. Besides representing a style, the show
explores a state of mind. Simultaneously embodying fight and
flight, Baroque buildings look eager to escape the very reality
they wish to dominate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Triumph of the Baroque'' can be seen as a sequel to the
National Gallery's 1994 exhibition on Renaissance architecture,
which also featured large wooden models as its star attractions. In
Chapter 1 the models resembled Trojan horses: as expressions of
humanism, Renaissance churches and palaces subverted the authority
of the feudal institutions they were commissioned to glorify. In
Chapter 2 the subversion grows more complex.
</P>
<P>
   Baroque architecture was a theatrical art. Here's how history
set the stage: by 1600 all the instruments that would eventually
topple absolute authority came into play, but absolutism
concentrated ever greater power unto itself. Martin Luther's tracts
against the church, published in 1520, were best sellers. They were
significant not only because of their content, but because they
demonstrated the power of the press as well. Ideas could now be
easily circulated. In 1600 Descartes proposed his solution to
existence, a philosophical formula that predicated reality on the
capacity to doubt. Oh, and by the way, the Earth was no longer the
center of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   The word baroque, originally applied to architecture in a
pejorative sense, means irregular or misshapen. The show invites us
to watch absolutism become literally bent out of shape. The
Counter-Reformation granted people the right to question dogma,
provided they ultimately submitted to the church. The Baroque style
gave architects liberty to pursue infinite formal variations,
provided that they ultimately submitted to Classicism. ``The
Triumph of the Baroque'' offers a broad sampling of the results.
</P>
<P>
   The show is organized thematically. Designs from Italy, Germany,
France, Britain, Russia and the Netherlands are grouped into
sections on ecclesiastical, royal, military and commercial
buildings. Besides emphasizing the international reach of the
Baroque, this arrangement conveys the extent to which feudal
institutions had evolved toward the modern corporate culture. Call
it Baroque Inc.: travel specialists for the rich and holy, with an
array of services provided by church and state.
</P>
<P>
   The show starts (like Anita Ekberg) with a plunge into the Trevi
Fountain in Rome, a stellar tourist attraction that introduces two
themes coursing throughout the show: theatricality and psychology.
A precisely detailed wood-and-plaster model highlights the
fountain's theatrical dimension, for it depicts the palace facade,
sans palace, designed by Nicola Salvi for the Trevi's magnificent
sculptural tableau.
</P>
<P>
   Since the model does not include water, visitors will have to
imagine the Trevi's psychological dimension, or read Eleanor
Clark's 1950 book ``Rome and a Villa.'' Clark's chapter on Rome's
fountains may well be the finest depiction of the Baroque's
emotional atmosphere ever written. ``You walk close to your
dreams,'' she begins. ``In another minute, people in the crowd will
all be naked, or will have fish tails or horses' behinds, like the
characters in the fountains. . . . This is the vocabulary of our
sleep, and the key image is always water.''
</P>
<P>
   The fountains are pieces of urban infrastructure as well as
incentives to free association. Fusions of art and technology, they
bring the rational and the irrational together at the center of
public space. Bernini's Four Rivers fountain in the Piazza Navona,
also represented by models and paintings, shows that these
waterworks were political emanations as well. The fountain
advertised the relocation of the local water supply to the pope's
family palace.
</P>
<P>
   It is bizarre to move from this Mediterranean atmosphere toward
the gilded dome resembling Chinese bells that crowns St. Isaac's
Cathedral in St. Petersburg, but models of Russian Baroque
buildings are a highlight of this show. This is one of the first
occasions in which the Russian Baroque has been presented in a
European context. Millon says that Russian curators have been
besieged in the last decade with requests for material on
Constructivist design while models of Baroque buildings have
gathered dust.
</P>
<P>
   A model of Smolny Convent in St. Petersburg is the most
extraordinary of the Russian treasures. Designed from 1750 to 1756
by Francesco Bartolomeo Rastrelli, architect of the Winter Palace
and other St. Petersburg landmarks, the complex is a cross-axial
composition with a cathedral at the center, flanked by four smaller
chapels. Rastrelli's palette of gold, celestial blue and white, and
the repeating bays of his facades will put some viewers in mind of
Balanchine's ``Ballet Imperial,'' with its star ballerina, soloists
and precisely drilled corps.
</P>
<P>
   An enfilade of royal residences dominates the Baroque show's
second-floor galleries. The great palace of Caserta, court of the
Kingdom of the Two Sicilies, is the finest example of these.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by Luigi Vantivelli from 1756 to 1769, the project
induces a dreamlike state without recourse to water. The gentle
incline of Caserta's grand staircase, the use of indirect lighting,
the twisted pattern of the coffering within the building's domes
induce the sensation of suspended gravity. This is Piranesian
space, awesome and relentless. In comparison Versailles resembles a
poorly planned suburban mall.
</P>
<P>
   Gothic spires are for the soul, Renaissance domes for the mind,
Baroque facades for the senses. But there is no telling where
emotion, once aroused, will be directed. The most horrifying object
in the show is a model of the Great Kremlin Palace. Designed for
Catherine the Great by Vasily Ivanovich Bazhenov in 1769-70, this
is a vast dominatrix of a building, encircled by stones that
resemble the studs on a sadist's belt.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Psychological manipulation has a tendency to backfire. How long
would it take before people began to wonder what kind of sovereign
would want to appear in public dressed like a Mistress of Pain? Or
what kind of saint would want to recline in ecstasy on an altar,
like Bernini's sculpture of St. Teresa? In time the Baroque
emphasis on psychology would invite the public to question external
authority in all its forms. It would accelerate the modernity it
sought to retard.
</P>
<P>
   As Christian Norberg-Schulz remarks in the show's excellent
catalog, the Baroque era was a time of choices. People could choose
a different faith, a different occupation, or they could quit
Europe altogether. It was, that is to say, a time of competition,
an era that heralded the rise of the consumer and of the arts
dedicated to persuading consumers to make a particular choice.
</P>
<P>
   With Baroque architecture, space itself becomes a consumer
product. In a recent conversation Vidler observed that the
distorted forms and urban scale of the Baroque register the anxiety
that came with the collapse of the distinct boundaries that once
surrounded cities. The erosion of medieval fortifications and the
rise of new modes of transportation went far toward undermining the
traditional sense of place. Baroque spectacle helped to compensate
for the loss.
</P>
<P>
   Millon is correct to suggest that this show will hold special
appeal for a generation now preoccupied with computer morphing.
Scrolls; spiral columns; trompe l'oeil ceilings that extend
physical architecture into the firmament of heavenly illusion;
gilded wave crests; cornices folded and refolded to distraction;
facades drawn out horizontally to the vanishing point; arches,
saints and topiary endlessly repeated as if produced by a
malfunctioning keyboard: such devices easily outstrip most of what
I have seen on the monitor screens of today's design studios. They
should give pause to those who think that computer-generated,
so-called blob architecture has no place in the old
bricks-and-mortar world.
</P>
<P>
   The affinity between the Baroque age and our own, however, goes
deeper than the formal complexity common to both. We, too, have a
complicated relationship to power. In a sense it is the reverse of
the predicament in which church and state found themselves in the
17th century. Modern consumer society is committed to a way of life
that is constantly corroding authority and its traditional
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is this more evident than in our museums, and in the
increasing difficulty with which they seek to maintain a balance
between scholarship and entertainment, connoisseurship and
popularity. The Bilbao branch of the Guggenheim is merely the most
prominent in a vast proliferation of museum buildings designed in
part as pilgrimage destinations to lure tourist dollars. As such,
they are part of the corporate monoculture that many artists want
to resist.
</P>
<P>
   The Guggenheim's serpentine steel skin and the Piranesian
Turbine Hall of the new Tate Modern in London are formally quite
different, but both are innately Baroque in their appeal to the
emotions and in their ambition to set culture apart from commerce.
Yet they also stand for the increasing importance of culture in the
emerging global economy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I came away from this show convinced that we need more
museums, larger museums, better-financed museums, particularly in
the United States. The National Gallery show, sponsored by EduCap
Inc., presents only one-fourth of an exhibition originally
presented in Turin, Italy. I'm glad I didn't catch it there. The
National Gallery's 1994 Renaissance show was truncated, too, and
after seeing the complete edition at the Palazzo Grassi in Venice,
I found the abbreviated version a thorough letdown.
</P>
<P>
   A Baroque show four times the size might prove daunting for many
visitors. But then the point of this style was to overwhelm the
viewer. How amazing it would be to feel overwhelmed by it in the
nation's capital. The Baroque is everything Americans came here to
escape. And where can we go to flee the Baroque contortions of our
day?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
