<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5707 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-JAZZ-FESTIVAL-ART-     05-25 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-JAZZ-FESTIVAL-ART-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGHTS OF JAZZ, SWEET AND HOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT7 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(Eds: 4th take contains ticket and venue info.) 
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I vey-divey, as Lester Young would have said. June is
almost upon us, and as usual, jazz clubs, independent concert
producers and the big jazz festivals _ there are now three _ are
wrangling for the attention of New Yorkers. This means an
astonishing bounty for anyone interested in jazz (with Latin music,
gospel and soul as connected satellite genres, in the tradition of
the big festivals). There's no choice but to see it as one big
unofficial citywide festival, the best and most complete in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The Vision Festival, now in its fifth year, has been an
unexpected success, marshaling various strands of jazz bohemianism
into an 11-day series with the air of a community effort much more
than of a business venture. The Bell Atlantic Jazz Festival,
presided over by Michael Dorf, was once a midget slinging pebbles
from the cultural margins, but it has become the great enveloper,
taking up much of the burden of presenting jazz from all subgenres
and ingeniously marketing it on the Internet and its Knitting
Factory record label; this year's edition features more outdoor
events, many of them gigantic bills and some of them free. (This is
a positive development: it will help New Yorkers return to the
notion of festivals as something fun that spills all over a public
space, rather than self-contained, wallet-chewing affairs.)
</P>
<P>
   The JVC Jazz Festival, led by George Wein, has refined its
formula of the concert as major event to the point that more and
more of its bookings are closely modeled on successful shows from
earlier years; on the other hand, as an interesting turn, its
Symphony Space series is full of artists who were yesterday's
downtown rebels.
</P>
<P>
   To curb your frustration over the too-much blues, here's a list
of recommendations for the end of May and the month of June in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY NIGHT: Vision Festival, New Age Cabaret. The fifth annual
Vision Festival, which brings together much that lies on the wilder
shores of jazz and improvised music, continues through the weekend.
Friday night's program features the Michele Rosewoman Quintet, a
strong mainstream jazz project led by a New York musician who has
long been ahead of the curve with jazz's new rhythmic developments.
There's a trio with the alto saxophonist Rob Brown, the drummer
Hamid Drake and the violinist Mat Maneri, three of the most
talented musicians playing in the avant-garde. Kidd Jordan, New
Orleans saxophonist, is to share a quartet with the drummer Alvin
Fielder, who hasn't been heard much since the '80s; the adventurous
clarinetist Perry Robinson, in a quartet; and one of the festival
favorites, the quintessential, tear-the-walls-down ensemble called
Other Dimensions in Music.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   WYCLIFFE GORDON QUINTET, Village Vanguard. Some of the best
musicians make instruments seem small in their hands. The
trombonist Wycliffe Gordon is one of those; in almost every Lincoln
Center Jazz Orchestra concert, it is guaranteed that he will play
something _ maybe only a detail, not always a full-fledged
improvisation _ with such extraordinary deftness that he wins over
the audience completely. On one level, his band is as straight as
it gets: It's Ellington- and Basie-inspired, suitable for all ages.
But Gordon's manipulations of sound in his careful improvisations
(he is armed with several kinds of mutes) are as exciting as it
gets.
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY
</P>
<P>
   GUILLERMO KLEIN AND LOS GUACHOS, Jazz Standard. Klein, from
Argentina, has a broad view of what can be accomplished by a big
band; traces of Hermeto Pascoal, Steve Reich and Kenny Wheeler
filter through his music, and he achieves a choral effect in his
broad saxophone section. It's brilliant, colorful stuff, whispered
about hotly among musicians; after years of sporadic gigs, this
regular Monday night engagement at the Jazz Standard may prove to
be an important booking for one of the decade's most promising
young artists.
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY
</P>
<P>
   ERIC REED'S NEW YORK SEVEN, Village Vanguard. After years of
playing in a trio, it was great to see the young pianist Eric Reed
busy himself with some larger-scale arrangements last year. And the
band, more so than is represented on his records, is actually a
band: a fearsome one with a particularly swinging rhythm section,
boasting the bassist Barak Mori and the young wonder drummer Rodney
Green.
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY
</P>
<P>
   PAT MARTINO HIP-BOP TRIO, Iridium. Martino is one of jazz's
finest guitarists, with a limpid sound and a subtle mode of
expression. But he still likes to play in the earthy, funky context
he began with the 1960s in Philadelphia. His new trio includes
Larry Goldings, an organist, and a drummer, Idris Muhammad, one of
the funkiest players alive.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY
</P>
<P>
   ORNETTE COLEMAN, Bell Atlantic Jazz Festival, the Lawn, Battery
Park. This compressed display of Coleman's abilities has three
parts: ``Freedom Symbol,'' a composition for a 20-piece classical
chamber ensemble with a cadenza for each performer, which dates to
1989; it was performed at Alice Tully Hall several years ago, but
because of the nature of Coleman's art, it's quite different each
time. Then there's a performance by Global Expression Project,
which puts Coleman, the bassist Charnett Moffett and the drummer
Denardo Coleman in the context of three Indian percussionists; and
finally the Ornette Coleman Trio, with Charlie Haden and Billy
Higgins. These three _ usually with a fourth member, but no matter
_ have produced some of the most important music in the second half
of the 20th century. As they have proved in recent years, they're
still capable of making time stop.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   NEXT FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   CHARLIE HADEN'S QUARTET WEST WITH STRING ORCHESTRA, the Angel
Orensanz Foundation. The foundation, a beautiful, crumbling
synagogue on the Lower East Side, will be the co-star of this
concert. Never having heard a full orchestra fill its great space,
I can only imagine that Haden's romance-drenched love letters to
the 1940s and '50s might find their sweet spot there.
</P>
<P>
   JUNE 3
</P>
<P>
   URI CAINE'S GOLDBERG VARIATIONS, Jazz Standard. Caine's
``Goldberg Variations'' album, to be released in June on Winter &AMP;
Winter, is the latest installment in this pianist's continuing
series of rather ingenious takes on classical music. Here he takes
several dozen of Bach's ``Goldberg'' Variations and reinterprets
them with the help of singers, a swinging clarinet, a D.J. and
others. The performed version is not your everyday club gig; it
ends a week at the club for Caine, preceded by his jazz trio and
his radical Gustav Mahler project.
</P>
<P>
   JUNE 4
</P>
<P>
   MAX ROACH AND CECIL TAYLOR, Columbia University Steps. At Town
Hall in 1989, the last time Roach and Taylor played together in the
United States, their duet was one of the best shows I had ever
seen: full of each musician's usual patterns yet they found common
ground. Opening this concert is the rough-and-ready David S. Ware
Quartet, which has mellowed a little, judging from its new record,
``Surrendered'' (Columbia/Sony); a duet by the drummer Joey Baron
and the bassist Ron Carter; and Bob Stewart leading the LaGuardia
High School Jazz Band, a surprisingly mighty ensemble of
teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   JUNE 5
</P>
<P>
   ROSWELL RUDD AND BROAD STROKES, Bell Atlantic Festival, Knitting
Factory. The rehabilitation of the trombonist Roswell Rudd's career
in the last few years has resulted in some unforgettable local
performances: with the reunited New York Art Quartet last summer
and with Sonic Youth at the Church of St. Ann and the Holy Trinity
in Brooklyn Heights last winter, a show so good that even after
many minutes of Rudd's yawped declamations over the rock band's
ringing drones, you still wanted more. Here it is: Rudd's new
12-piece band Broad Strokes (can it really have three vocalists, as
advertised?) will be joined by three-quarters of Sonic Youth.
</P>
<P>
   JUNE 6
</P>
<P>
   GREG OSBY QUINTET, Bell Atlantic Festival, Knitting Factory.
This is a band that keeps getting better; if you want to hear the
future of jazz as art, look here. Osby, the saxophonist, plays
thin, pinpointed lines over a fluctuating rhythm section, the band
improvises its form onstage and the leader's connection with the
pianist Jason Moran has become one of the great partnerships in the
recent history of the music. If you've experienced Osby on record
as a little dry, see what happens when the band loosens up onstage.
</P>
<P>
   JUNE 7
</P>
<P>
   TIM BERNE, Bell Atlantic Festival, Knitting Factory. The
saxophonist is focused and voluminous; the four different bands he
is showing in one night aren't so much different personalities as
different mouthpieces for his brand of sprawling, contracting and
expanding, odd-meter music. Paraphrase and Big Satan are familiar
trios, but the next two groups, Quicksand and Composure, promise a
slightly different palette, with the involvement of the pianist
Craig Taborn; it's hard to remember the last time Berne played
alongside any kind of keyboards.
</P>
<P>
   JUNE 8
</P>
<P>
   MATTHEW SHIPP STRING TRIO, Knitting Factory. The boundary
between composition and improvisation is never blurrier than with
Shipp, the pianist, and his trio of piano, bass and violin; I had
heard the band's dark, slow, sweeping, abstract and volatile music
quite a bit on record and was still taken aback to hear it
replicate long album tracks pretty much as I remembered them. Then,
head over to the Blue Note to hear the outgoing, excitable
saxophonist.
</P>
<P>
   JAMES CARTER, Knitting Factory. From a different end of the
entertainment spectrum, Carter will be playing selections from a
rocking new record, ``Layin' In the Cut'' (Atlantic), which treats
the avant-funk of the early '80s _ the James Blood
Ulmer/Jamaaladeen Tacuma school _ as sacred texts. It's
exhilarating music and a good interpretive idea.
</P>
<P>
   JUNE 9
</P>
<P>
   ``AS LONG AS YOU'RE LIVING YOURS'': THE MUSIC OF KEITH JARRETT,
Jazz Standard. This gig, timed to an RCA record release of the same
name, isn't a bad idea because Jarrett's impressionistic written
music gets short shrift in deference to his stature as a soloist.
The band looks tempting, including the saxophonists George Garzone
and Jimmy Greene and the drummer Billy Kilson, one of the sparks of
Dave Holland's great new band.
</P>
<P>
   JUNE 10
</P>
<P>
   ROY HAYNES TRIO, Birdland. It sounds like a cliche, but at 75,
Haynes isn't slowing down: he's still the razor-sharp dresser,
master rhythm-displacer and loud snare-drum hitter he was in the
bebop days. He's so naturally modern it hurts, and his new record,
``The Roy Haynes Trio'' (Verve/Universal), with Danilo Perez and
John Patitucci, is a challenge to rhythm sections everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   JUNE 11
</P>
<P>
   LOS LOBOS, LOS VAN VAN, BARBARITO TORRES, DAVID SANCHEZ SEXTET,
BOBBY SANABRIA Y ASCENSION, Bell Atlantic Jazz Festival, Austin J.
Tobin Plaza, World Trade Center. Maybe it's only marginally jazz,
but what a wild bill, predicated only on improvisation, the Spanish
language and musical excellence. The Cal-Mex band Los Lobos seems
to have been around forever, and it may still be the best rock band
in America. The Cuban group Los Van Van could take the title of
best dance band in the world. Barbarito Torres' old, elegant style
on the lutelike laud is known to all followers of the Buena Vista
phenomenon. David Sanchez, from Puerto Rico, is a superior jazz
player, whether he's using the rhythms and forms of his island or
not. The percussionist Bobby Sanabria draws on some of the best of
the jazz and Latin players in New York for his octet.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   JUNE 14
</P>
<P>
   JVC TRIBUTE TO CHARLIE BYRD AND GEORGE VAN EPS, JVC Jazz
Festival, Kaye Playhouse. Plenty of festival tributes are about
love, respect and homage but tributes to guitar players inspire
more than that. JVC festival's annual guitar-a-thon concerts,
produced by Charles Carlini, tend toward flat-out obsession. The
long parade of guitarists who come out to play a few numbers can
seem a little daunting on paper, but these concerts build up a
rhythm of their own and the bated breath of guitar-players in the
audience gives these events a peculiar urgency. On the bill: the
rhythmically muscular Ron Affif, the quiet-as-a-mouse Gene
Bertoncini and the fluid utility players Howard Alden and Frank
Vignola as well as Bucky Pizzarelli, Mark Whitfield and others.
</P>
<P>
   JUNE 16
</P>
<P>
   JOAO GILBERTO, JVC Jazz Festival, Carnegie Hall. Early this
year, Gilberto, the bossa nova originator, put out a new record,
``Joao Voz e Violao''; he has been both reviled for it (by those
who wish he would record some new songs) and praised for it. You
can't help liking the voice deepened with age and the Swiss-watch
sense of rhythm negotiated between his guitar and his singing, with
no orchestrations to get in the way. But the album, to be released
in the United States in June, is close to what he delivered two
years ago at a similar Carnegie Hall concert, which was
extraordinary. Most of us would settle for a replica. If you
haven't seen him before, go.
</P>
<P>
   JUNE 17
</P>
<P>
   PETER BROETZMANN TENTET, Hammerstein Ballroom. In the last
decade, Broetzmann, the German saxophonist, has become something of
a father figure for American free-jazz musicians, especially in
Chicago, where the jazz bohemians are studious and organized and
win MacArthur prizes. His Tentet, filled with the cream of the
Chicago out-jazz scene, leans toward written arrangements _ a good
thing for Broetzmann, whose bellowing tone could rip a hole in the
wall and who has more musicality than he often lets on. (At the
Ballroom, he is opening for Sonic Youth.)
</P>
<P>
   JUNE 18
</P>
<P>
   JOHN LURIE AND THE LOUNGE LIZARDS, JVC Jazz Festival, Symphony
Space. It's the 20th-anniversary concert for a band that nobody,
initially, could have predicted would last. The band has come so
far from the jokey, awkward ``fake jazz'' it started out with that
you need to revise your opinion, if you heard it then and haven't
paid attention since. In the new Lounge Lizards, African and Asian
music sits comfortably with good old American humor and pathos, and
sometimes the band will play something so richly Ellingtonian that
even Wynton Marsalis would approve.
</P>
<P>
   JUNE 20
</P>
<P>
   RUBEN BLADES, JVC Jazz Festival, Carnegie Hall. One of the great
singers and lyricists in popular music, Blades since the early '70s
has combined political acuity with a strong, communicative musical
enthusiasm; he doesn't condescend to his audiences by
overmoralizing when he sings about political issues. His latest
record, ``Tiempos'' (Sony Discos), recorded with a new young band
called Editus, combines all kinds of music from South America into
a coherent whole. Opening is Orquesta Aragon, the Cuban charanga
band whose dynastic history dates to the late 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   JUNE 21
</P>
<P>
   ELVIN JONES AND CECIL TAYLOR, Blue Note. Jones, the drummer, and
Taylor, the pianist, played a duet at the Blue Note last winter,
and its subtleties were striking: Jones used mallets for almost the
entire set I caught. It's nice to see this relationship worked out
in the more casual atmosphere of a jazz club rather than the
one-time-only big-ticket hoopla of the festivals and their second
time around will be worth another visit.
</P>
<P>
   JUNE 22
</P>
<P>
   ``FROM SPIRITUALS TO SWING,'' JVC Jazz Festival, Carnegie Hall.
This concert honors the famous 1938 and 1939 Carnegie Hall concerts
produced by John Hammond (the recorded version has just been
reissued on Vanguard) that brought together Count Basie's big-band
swing, boogie-woogie and stride piano from Meade Lux Lewis and
James P. Johnson, and the sanctified harmonies of the Golden Gate
Quartet. In the even more eclectic year 2000 version, the
participants include the present version of the Basie orchestra;
the singers Dianne Reeves and Angelique Kidjo; the New Orleans
patriarch Allen Toussaint; and Harlem's ecstatic, trombone-heavy
shout band, the McCollough Sons of Thunder.
</P>
<P>
   JUNE 23
</P>
<P>
   CASSANDRA WILSON AND CESARIA EVORA, JVC Jazz Festival, Carnegie
Hall. Here's a double bill that makes sense. Putting Wilson's
recent music up against true-blue jazz singers always has always
created an imbalance and causes headaches as listeners wonder if
her artful, chanteusy, folk-Americana is jazz or not. Evora, the
charismatic morna singer from Cape Verde, strikes much closer to
the cloudy-day emotional territory that Wilson aims for.
</P>
<P>
   JUNE 24
</P>
<P>
   ARETHA FRANKLIN, JVC Jazz Festival, Avery Fisher Hall. Franklin
is still a house-wrecker, and a performer so imposing that her mood
is easily transmitted to her audience. If she's happy or
frustrated, it becomes part of the performance and you're taken up
in it _ which is what performances ought to do anyway.
</P>
<P>
   JUNE 25
</P>
<P>
   BRIAN BLADE FELLOWSHIP, Village Vanguard. Blade, a former
sideman for Joshua Redman and one of the greatest drummers to have
come along in the last decade of American music, writes music for
an expanded small group that doesn't sound like anything in jazz.
It's sentimental, sometimes slightly hymnlike music, arranged for a
steel guitar and two saxophones; it's a bit cinematic, but for a
very private, interior sort of movie.
</P>
<P>
   JUNE 27
</P>
<P>
   MILTON NASCIMENTO, Beacon Theater. As generations of new
listeners keep discovering treasure-trove records like ``Clube da
Esquina'' (Blue Note/Capitol) Nascimento's small but committed
American audience has grown beyond the jazz world that first
accepted him in the '70s. Back from a period of illness, he still
has the voice, with that almost religious quality of purity and its
rich emotional currents.
</P>
<P>
   JUNE 29
</P>
<P>
   HAPPY APPLE, Tonic. This trio from Minneapolis plays jazz as if
it doesn't have any hangups about what anybody's going to call it.
Among its quirks are an electric bassist who has not been
particularly influenced by Jaco Pastorious, and a general subtext
of indie-rock subversion.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Following the Beat
</P>
<P>
   The Vision Festival, which began last Friday, runs through
Monday. All shows are at New Age Cabaret, 23 St. Marks Place, East
Village; www.visionfestival.org. Tickets are $20 an evening. The
Bell Atlantic Jazz Festival runs from Thursday to June 11 at more
than a dozen venues. Prices generally range from $20 to $70, with
food and drink minimums in some cases. There are a few shows with
tickets ranging from $2 to $8, and many outdoor events are free.
Information and tickets: (212) 343-8805. The 28th annual JVC Jazz
Festival opens on June 12 and runs through June 24, with shows at
nine venues in Manhattan and one in Englewood, N.J. Tickets range
from $20 to $75, except for one event featuring Bobby Watson and
Horizon at the Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture, for
which tickets are $9 and $12. Information and tickets: (212)
501-1390 or on line at www.festivalproductions.net. Here are
day-by-day listings for performances recommended in Ben Ratliff's
critic's notebook article.
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY: Vision Festival, featuring Michele Rosewoman
Quintessence, 7 p.m.; Rob Brown Trio, 8; Kidd Jordan-Alvin Fielder
Quartet, 9; David Budbill and William Parker, 10; Perry Robinson
Quintet, 11; Other Dimensions in Music (Roy Campbell, Daniel
Carter, William Parker, Rashid Bakr and Matthew Shipp), midnight.
Tickets: $20.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY: Wycliffe Gordon Quintet, Village Vanguard, 178 Seventh
Avenue South, at 11th Street, West Village, 9:30 and 11:30 p.m. and
1 a.m. Cover charge: $20 plus $10 drink minimum. (212) 255-4037.
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY: Guillermo Klein and Los Guachos, Jazz Standard, 116 East
27th Street, Manhattan, 8 and 10 p.m. Cover charge: $15 with a $10
food and drink minimum. (212) 576-2232.
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY: Eric Reed's New York Seven. Village Vanguard, 178
Seventh Avenue South, at 11th Street, West Village, 9:30 and 11:30
p.m. Cover charge: $15 plus $10 drink minimum. (212) 255-4037.
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY: Pat Martino Hip-Bop Trio. Iridium, 44 West 63rd
