<HEADER>
A5712 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-CAR-INDY-WATTLES-HNS &LR;      05-25 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-WATTLES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     OVERCOMING TRACK TRAGEDY, WATTLES RETURNS TO RACING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LEE SCHEIDE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The battles have always been from within for Stan
Wattles, growing up with dyslexia, dysgraphia and perception
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing, however, prepared him for May 1, 1999, and the depths
to which he would have to plunge to soothe his soul.
</P>
<P>
   Competing in the Indy Racing League event at Charlotte, N.C.,
Wattles hit the wall in Turn 4. His car broke up, by design, to
absorb most of the energy from the crash. Wattles walked away from
the crash, unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   In the stands, however, fans were not as fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   As a tire from Wattles' car bounced down the track after the
incident, it was struck by another car and launched into the crowd,
killing three people and seriously injuring several more.
</P>
<P>
   The race was canceled and, for all intents and purposes, so was
Wattles' racing career. He continued to the next race, the
Indianapolis 500, but his heart and mind weren't completely focused
on the task at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know the risks you take as a racecar driver when you get
behind the wheel of a car,'' Wattles said. ``Someone coming to
watch the race shouldn't have to fear getting hurt or worse while
they are there. It was the worst thing that has ever happened to
me, and I lost my desire, my drive, my passion to get into a
racecar. I was here during Indy last year, but I wasn't really here
the way I needed to be, and that hurt the entire program.''
</P>
<P>
   Wattles, 38, knew that continuing to think about the accident in
Charlotte wasn't going to help him on the racetrack. So he pulled
out of the fast lane, shutting down his team's operation and almost
shutting down himself as he looked for answers to the questions
that continually swarmed in his head.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Jill, spent many hours discussing the accident.
But in the end, Wattles knew that any healing had to come from
within. So the personable driver fell back on something that helped
him through his tough educational situations as an adolescent:
martial arts.
</P>
<P>
   Using the meditation techniques learned long ago, Wattles, a
black belt in tae kwan do, began the therapeutic process.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to heal the outside, I had to heal the inside
first,'' Wattles said. ``My wife and I had some long talks about
racing and the injuries, everything. Racing had been such a passion
for me, and after Charlotte, I didn't want anything to do with
racing. I just wanted to get away and start healing.''
</P>
<P>
   While off the track, Wattles found another healing outlet in his
children. Because his business, Metro Racing Systems, kept him on
the move, he hadn't enjoyed the quality time that he wanted with
his family. That all changed after the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great to know that they were there for me when I needed
them,'' Wattles said. ``I had a pretty hectic schedule, with
business and racing, and they kind of took a back seat to all of
the that. The past year, I've spent so much more quality time with
my family, and that's what I want to continue to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Another thing Wattles found he wanted to continue, after several
months of soul searching, was his racing career.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't want the burden of being the team owner and making
sure all the small, logistical details were worked out. All Wattles
wanted to do was show up and drive.
</P>
<P>
   He got that chance, driving in some World Sports Car events last
summer. Just getting to the track was a victory for Wattles, while
getting behind the wheel proved to be the catharsis he needed.
</P>
<P>
   With each passing lap, he could feel his passion for racing
being rekindled.
</P>
<P>
   That's why, when his cousin, Greg Wattles, came back from the
Indy Racing League opener in January and asked if he was ready to
do this again, Stan Wattles was receptive to the idea of driving
again.
</P>
<P>
   After months of planning, buying cars and putting all the wheels
in motion, Wattles and the rest of his team rolled through the
gates of Gasoline Alley earlier this month, having come full circle
in dedication and desire.
</P>
<P>
   Wattles proved that by going out and qualifying at more than 220
mph. He will start Sunday's 84th Indianapolis 500 between Jimmy
Vasser and Robbie Buhl.
</P>
<P>
   And he knows just how lucky he is to be back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never, in a million years, thought that I would be back
racing at Indianapolis Motor Speedway,'' Wattles said. ``When we
came back through the gates, everything about last year seemed to
slip away, and I was focused, really focused on doing a better job
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget what happened in Charlotte, but I know that
it was an accident, out of my control. But it's time to move on,
and this is part of that process for me as a racecar driver, coming
to the Indy 500 and racing the best in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Lee Scheide by e-mail at lscheide(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
