<HEADER>
A5713 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PERU-POLITICS-500&AMP;ADD     05-25 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-POLITICS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT SUGGESTS THAT RUNOFF ELECTIONS MAY BE POSTPONED 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ President Alberto Fujimori is strongly hinting that
the runoff presidential election scheduled for Sunday will be
postponed at the last moment to satisfy foreign critics who say the
political process has been tainted by an array of irregularities
and fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``The possibility for an adjustment of the election date
exists,'' Fujimori said in an interview late Wednesday night in the
government palace. ``We are in a fluctuating situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori's conciliatory comments contrasted sharply with his
public statements earlier this week in which he rejected calls by
the Clinton administration, the Organization of American States and
several European and Latin American governments that the election
be put off several weeks so independent monitors had time to
inspect computer software designed to count presidential ballots.
</P>
<P>
   The electoral crisis had been gathering momentum since Alejandro
Toledo, the opposition candidate, dropped out of the race last
Thursday saying there was no reason for him to compete in a
fraudulent election. He said he would re-enter the contest if it
were postponed by several weeks with guarantees for a free vote. A
wave of strikes and street demonstrations followed, and Fujimori
was forced to duck eggs and fruit thrown at him while he made a
speech in the city of Arequipa before a national television
audience.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations peaked Thursday and grew increasingly
violent. A small group of protesters attacked the offices of the
National Elections Commission, the highest government body that
supervises the elections, and broke windows and damaged a door with
rocks, pipes and at least one molotov cocktail. Scores of people
were arrested in the northern jungle city of Iquitos for blocking
roads, and the police used tear gas to clear protesters gathering
in front of the government palace in the capital. Truck drivers and
teachers staged a strike in the Andean city of Cuzco, a Toledo
stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a growing number of influential businessmen have
warned that holding an uncontested election on Sunday could mean
years of economic sanctions and tensions with Washington that could
impede investment and growth. Their arguments were strengthened
through the week as Peruvian bond and stock prices dropped sharply,
the currency came under sudden pressure and foreign financial
institutions issued risk warnings that threatened to increase
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori was careful to say that the final decision of whether
the election will take place Sunday is in the hands of the National
Elections Commission, but he left little doubt of where he stood.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the international community, Fujimori said: ``They
are looking for a signal of flexibility. OK. If the National
Elections Commission wants a change of date, it's convenient for
me.'' He added that the five-member panel, over which he has strong
influence, would probably make its decision on Friday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Fujimori's appeasing remarks were matched Thursday by
Eduardo Stein, the head of the Organization of American States
election observation team, who has been a strong critic of the
government's handling of the campaign and vote count in the April 9
first-round balloting. The former Guatemalan foreign minister gave
a cautious endorsement of a computer test
</P>
<P>
   conducted by Peruvian election authorities Wednesday night,
raising expectations that a clean vote count is possible.
</P>
<P>
   But Stein said he still wanted the election to be postponed so
that his technicians had ample time to review the computer vote-
counting software.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days there have been mixed signals about the Fujimori
government's intentions to loosen controls over an election process
that critics say has so far been tilted in Fujimori's favor.
Several television stations allied with the government have begun
broadcasting Toledo commercials and coverage of his rallies, while
tabloid newspapers thought to be directed by Fujimori's
intelligence service have softened their negative coverage of
Toledo's personal life.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, three unidentified men on Wednesday night broke
into the offices of an opposition journalist said to hold
incriminating videotapes of Vladimiro Montesinos, Fujimori's
intelligence chief, meeting with election officials. The
journalist, Fabian Salazar, said the burglars tied him up and
tortured him as they demanded that he reveal his sources within the
intelligence service who gave him copies of the tapes, which
apparently were made by Montesinos himself.
</P>
<P>
   Salazar said they cut through his left wrist to the bone with a
saw during their questioning. He was hospitalized after his
videotapes, archives and computer discs were stolen. Human rights
activists said Salazar's descriptions of his ordeal, which were
verified by doctors, may represent the worst example of torture in
Peru in at least two years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
