<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5717 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIES-CHAN0526-COX     05-25 0408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-CHAN0526-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stars make `Shanghai Noon' a western with real kick
 &HT;    By Alison Macor
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ East meets West in the pleasantly silly
action-comedy ``Shanghai Noon.'' Affable kung fu master Jackie Chan
buddies up to the equally appealing Owen Wilson (``The Minus Man,''
``Armageddon''), and the rather unlikely combination works like a
dream.
</P>
<P>
   Like some of Chan's movies, ``Shanghai Noon's'' kooky plot takes
a back seat to the multitalented actor's awesome stunt work and coy
comedic sense. The film also gets a big boost from Chan and
Wilson's low-key on-screen camaraderie, and ``Shanghai Noon's''
outtakes _ Chan's delightful version of Hitchcock's on-screen
cameos _ reveal that their fun spilled over behind the camera, too.
</P>
<P>
   Set in 1881, ``Shanghai Noon'' begins in the Forbidden City,
where Chan serves as humble Imperial Guard Chon Wang. When the
emperor's feisty daughter, Princess Pei Pei (``Ally McBeal's'' Lucy
Liu), is spirited away to the States by her American tutor, the
lovesick Chon Wang volunteers to rescue the princess from a bleak
future of indentured servitude to an exiled guard (Xander Berkeley)
presiding over a Chinese work camp in Carson City, Nev.
</P>
<P>
   This introductory bit of business sets up a cute exchange
between Chan and Liu, and the trip west provides some predictably
funny culture clashes. But the real entertainment begins when
Wilson's hunky, easygoing outlaw Roy O'Bannon reluctantly takes
Chon Wang under his wing as he searches for the princess.
</P>
<P>
   Roy introduces Chon Wang to his unexpectedly Zen approach to
living outside the law, and in return Chon Wang teaches Roy a thing
or two about honor.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Shanghai Noon'' amply showcases Chan's physical prowess,
an extended montage in which Roy tries to woo Chon Wang's Native
American wife _ don't ask _ is a particularly clever use of
Wilson's languorous charm.
</P>
<P>
   Although we don't necessarily watch a Jackie Chan movie for its
riveting story, the plots aren't always as annoyingly intrusive as
in ``Shanghai Noon.'' Tom Dey's direction works best when it allows
Chan and Wilson's comedy to take center stage and uses the movie's
period setting as mere background detail. A particularly drawn out
finale tests our endurance, but the promise of those outtakes is
reason enough to stick around.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
