<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5719 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-COX-ISRAEL-INTEL-$ADV     05-25 1533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-ISRAEL-INTEL-$ADV29-1STLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: in 42nd graf, deletes xxx partly owned by National
Semiconductor xxx
 &HT;    WITH GOVERNMENT SUPPORT, INTEL A GIANT IN ISRAEL
 &HT;    (1200&AMP;ADDS)
 &HT;    With Photos; box attached at end of story.
 &HT;    With ISRAEL-CHIPS-$ADV29.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Mon., May 29, And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRYAT GAT, Israel _ This meadowland in central Israel was once
the domain of the Philistines and their warrior, Goliath. Now it is
the land of Intel, a much more welcome giant.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's boxy semiconductor plant on the edge of this depressed
town dominates the rural landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, Arab shepherds still bring their livestock to graze.
Inside, workers in the dust-free ``clean room'' produce advanced
microprocessors _ chips _ for computers all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   The company's might seems to stretch the boundaries of this
small country.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.6 billion plant was the largest ever private investment
here. The government chipped in $600 million, the biggest such
corporate subsidy in the country's history. And, last year, Intel
bought Israel's DSP Communications for $1.6 billion, the largest
such acquisition in Israeli history.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Intel is pitching its boldest move here yet with the
proposed construction of another semiconductor plant. At a cost of
maybe $3 billion, it would be, of course, the biggest investment
the country has seen.
</P>
<P>
   But, Israel now has its own firm footing as a high technology
center. It is not as needy and almost certainly will not agree to
hand out as much money for another plant as it did in the
mid-1990s, when the deal was made for the last one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole conditions in 1994-95 were different. The whole
circumstances have changed,'' said Israeli Minister for Industry
and Trade Ran Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intel is an example of the advantages that have been offered,
and will not be offered to the same extent any longer,'' said
Yaacov Yisraeli, president of the Israel-American Chamber of
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Cohen met in New York with Intel executives to
discuss the plan. He and Finance Minister Avraham Shochat formed a
commission to decide what Israel can offer. The commission will
take several weeks to make recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Intel's track record here, which goes back nearly 30
years, will be in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   The link between the world's biggest make of computer chips and
the tiny Jewish state started with Dov Frohman, an
American-educated Israeli. He joined Intel in 1969 and developed
the EPROM semiconductors, the first devices that allowed computers
to store information even after power was turned off.
</P>
<P>
   Frohman, now a 61-year-old Intel vice president, is known for
his long gray beard and a style that is casual even by Israel's
informal standards.
</P>
<P>
   As the story goes, Frohman wanted to move to Israel from the
United States in 1974. The company appeased him by sending him to
establish its first overseas design center. He put it in Haifa with
just a $300,000 investment.
</P>
<P>
   Intel would add its first overseas manufacturing plant in 1985
in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the government of late Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin made the deal for the Kiryat Gat plant.
</P>
<P>
   Israel was just starting to realize the great potential the
hi-tech industry could offer a country low on natural resources,
and friendly neighbors. Rabin wanted to steer prosperity toward
depressed towns like Kiryat Gat, about an hour's drive south of Tel
Aviv. With just 20,000 residents, the town has little industry and
unemployment that hovers around 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The plant opened in June 1999 and projects exports exceeding $1
billion a year. Intel employs about 1,700 workers and uses another
1,700 as contract workers from local firms.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of five Intel producers of processors in the advanced
.18 micron technology _ a figure measuring the tiniest distances
possible between components on processors.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, there are few severe Intel detractors. The $600
million government incentive has nearly all been doled out.
</P>
<P>
   Amos Samuel, monitoring Intel's activities for the government,
gives a mixed, but generally positive, review.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not too bad,'' he says. ``We were hoping it would do better,
but all in all the progress is fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuel, while refusing to discuss specific terms, said Intel has
not done enough to work with local universities or share knowledge
with local companies.
</P>
<P>
   He gave the company high marks, though, for its involvement in
community projects, such as work with schools, and for establishing
teams to work on its other commitments.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a company big enough to make the locals play by its
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli workers, known for being as unruly as they are
innovative, are getting used to Intel's tight safety and security
regimes. Government inspectors grudgingly let Intel employ Jewish
workers on the Sabbath, a violation of Israel's laws _ albeit
inconsistently enforced _ to preserve country's Jewish nature.
</P>
<P>
   Amit Anter Kertes, Intel's Israel spokesman, said the Kiryat Gat
plant has already added more than $790 million to the Israeli
economy. Nearly 60 percent of that was for construction of the
plant. Intel also claims it helped Israeli firms market $132
million in products, and paid $69 million for goods Intel bought
from local suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   The figures do not include salaries for its workers.
</P>
<P>
   The company also graduated and hired 90 Israelis from its own
nine-month course aimed at bringing local residents up to the
skills level needed in the plant. The course will soon start again.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's arrival raised higher hopes among local
residents. Anter Kertes acknowledges, ``They have a lot of
expectations and many of them we can't meet.''
</P>
<P>
   On the streets of Kiryat Gat, a town largely of small tenements
filled with working-class Israeli natives and Russian and
Uzbekistani immigrants, employment at Intel is a dream few count
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is good the government gave the money. But a lot of people
here thought that it would mean work for people who live in Kiryat
Gat,'' said Maya Azirov, a 40-year-old native of Uzbekistan who
runs a delicatessen with her husband. ``You need a lot of training
to work there.''
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, Kiryat Gat lacks English speakers. Though the
sign outside the plant spells Intel in English and Hebrew, inside
it is largely an English world.
</P>
<P>
   Koko Fahima, a member of the Kiryat Gat City Council, estimates
that less than 15 percent of workers at the plant are from Kiryat
Gat. Company figures do not dispute that, but note that 60 percent
of the workers are from the larger region around the small town.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a $600 million investment the government could have gotten
a lot more,'' Fahima said, calling Intel a ``superpower.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he's quick to note that Intel has lead to the creation of
50 new companies in the town.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   It's had other effects. Benny Uzinskau, a 25-year-old laborer
who worked for an insulation contractor at Intel, said he was
surprised that the company fined workers for not wearing their
helmets on the job or for smoking where they shouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first it was difficult. But you get used to it.'' Uzinskau
said.
</P>
<P>
   Near the plant, the town's fire station commander Tzion Saban
said he's learned a lot from Intel's fire control experts. A
hotline connects the plant directly to the station.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   But, whether another Intel plant will soon be nearby depends on
how much Intel and Israel still feel they need each other.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Israeli parliament lowered the amount the
government can pitch into a project to 24 percent. That's down from
the nearly 38 percent it gave Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Israel also has other chip makers competing for government
grants. They include Tower Semiconductors, which is offering to
build a new plant in a consortium with Toshiba Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Intel officials say they are evaluating sites near
other plants in Ireland as well as in Arizona, New Mexico, Oregon
and Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Industry and Trade Minister Cohen said he considers Intel a good
corporate citizen, but notes that he talks to companies all the
time that want to come here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel is one of the advanced economies all over the world,''
he said. ``We do not need one project to change Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow's E-mail address is: larryk(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   -----------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   INTEL:
</P>
<P>
   Arrived in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Employees in Israel (not including contract employees): 2,500.
</P>
<P>
   Facilities include: Jerusalem, semiconductor plant
</P>
<P>
   Haifa, design center
</P>
<P>
   Kiryat Gat, semiconductor plant
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem, Intel Capital, investing in Israeli companies.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Intel Corp.
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.iaei.org.il for Israel Association of Electronics
Industries.
</P>
<P>
   www.amcham.co.il for Israel-America Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   www.export.gov.il for Israel Export Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
