<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5720 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-DIGITAL-L.A.-COLUMN-L     05-25 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-L.A.-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANIMATION COMES TO LIFE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, when Terry Thoren founded the World Animation
Festival, there wasn't much going on in the field, at least not in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The theatrical shorts business that had been home for such
geniuses as Looney Tunes directors Tex Avery and Chuck Jones was
dead, Disney was reeling from the disastrous box office results for
``The Black Cauldron'' and television was a backwater of insipid,
poorly drawn kiddie cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   No more. These days, the world of animation is a wonderful one
indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got so many opportunities. There's animation everywhere
now,'' said Thoren, CEO of Klasky-Csupo, the Hollywood-based
animation company that has scored TV hits with such clever shows as
``Rugrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Tote up the changes since 1985: Seven animated films will be
released this summer from just about all the major studios' newly
hatched animation divisions; ``The Simpsons'' are finishing their
10th year as one of the most celebrated and deeply thoughtful
sitcoms in TV history; and cable television and the Internet have
embraced animation as crucial parts of their entertainment
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   The World Animation Celebration, which hits Hollywood this week,
will try to cover all that's happening now in the business and art
of animation, in film, television and on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   And with 1,400 contest entries from 66 countries, along with a
series of special events, business panels and spotlights on the
latest in Japanese, Polish and Czech work, it's truly a worldwide
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Events will mostly be held at the Egyptian Theater and the
nearby Roosevelt Hotel on Hollywood Boulevard. Among the highlights
is the Tuesday night world premiere of ``Heavy Metal 2000,'' the
sequel to the 1981 animated cult movie. ``The Simpsons'' creator
Matt Groening will be honored in a salute on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, film veterans Don Bluth and Gary Goldman (``The
Rescuers,'' ``An American Tail'' and the insanely cool-looking new
``Titan A.E.'') are among a number of notables receiving lifetime
achievement awards. Next Saturday, film critic Leonard Maltin will
join director Brad Bird in talking about the creation of last
year's criminally overlooked ``The Iron Giant.'' The show wraps up
Sunday with an overview of the year's best work.
</P>
<P>
   The festival will also feature a conference on the TV animation
business; a trade and recruiting show; the ``Big Internet Animation
Pow Wow;'' and a panel on creating feature-length animation.
</P>
<P>
   That latter panel, featuring key members of ``The Blair Witch
Project'' creative team, will focus on making and marketing
inexpensive, independent-film style animation for grownups, said
Thoren.
</P>
<P>
   Thoren said he believes there's a market out there for modestly
budgeted, grownup-oriented animation. His company is making its own
such project, an as-yet unnamed R-rated film based on the works of
Charles Bukowski (as well as a big-budget ``Rugrats'' sequel for
Thanksgiving).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a market everywhere in the world for this, but
someone has to feed the market,'' Thoren said.
</P>
<P>
   One important aspect will be to establish, as the ``Blair
Witch'' folks did so well, an Internet presence early on, where the
film's characters and mythology can be introduced, Thoren said.
</P>
<P>
   Animators looking for outlets for their work can also hit the
Roosevelt, where most of the big Web sites that carry animation
will be taking pitches in their hotel cabanas.
</P>
<P>
   All told, it truly will be a world celebration. For more
information, schedules and ticket prices, go to www.wacfest.com.
The festival runs from Tuesday through Sunday, with some
adults-only events starting as late as midnight. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Steely-eyed character &QL; 
Speaking of fabulous animation, the 3-D computer-generated ``Max
Steel'' (on the WB Network's Channel 5) was just the subject of a
Net experiment that points to some interesting possibilities in
online entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, the Max Steel animated character was turned into a
computerized puppet online. Using technology from Rotor
Communications, the character moved and talked online, responding
live to e-mail from fans who wrote in during a live chat session.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first-ever live streaming event for an animated
property,'' said David Palmer, vice president of marketing for
``Max Steel'' producer Sony Pictures Family Entertainment Group.
``It's digital puppeteering. It really is pretty cool technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology something like this was shown off at the Virtual
Humans 3 conference in Los Angeles about 18 months ago, using a
computer-generated W.C. Fields to interact on a big television
screen with an audience. Behind the scenes sat a Fields
impersonator with a series of sensors attached to his face and body
that controlled the on-screen persona.
</P>
<P>
   Where that was used as an example of what could be done at trade
shows and similar events, the Max Steel event focused on the more
complicated process of being online, and dealing with potentially
huge audiences.
</P>
<P>
   It proved a moderate success, with thousands of kids downloading
the required plug-in from Rotor to take part. More importantly, it
points to some fascinating possibilities for new kinds of online
entertainment, said Rotor Vice President Adam Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up to now, most interactive programming ignored what the
Internet is about: a lot of people connected together and having a
shared experience,'' Tyler said.
</P>
<P>
   What about a live animated show where the audience can control
the direction of some plot points, for instance, or be polled about
questions posed by the character, or talk with each other and the
character?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at what's been immensely successful on the Net,
it's e-mail, chat, even eBay; they all embrace the notion that
thousands of people are sharing information and they're all
connected,'' said Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   Combine it with animation and some cool stuff can happen.
Animation can travel better over slow Internet connections than
video, and allows for wildly different kinds of images.
</P>
<P>
   It's a promising direction that the new Sony division _ which is
also doing computer-generated, 3-D animation for TV shows based on
``Starship Troopers'' and the videogame ``Heavy Gear'' _ is
pursuing, Palmer said. Shows like the ``Max Steel'' event are still
too costly and actors' rights issues haven't been cleared up yet,
but Steel yourself, this could end up being cool. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Up to bat &QL; 
It's kind of a dodgy idea (sorry), but Los Angeles' Boys of Summer
will be hosting their fifth Dodgers.com Night tonight at their
Elysian Park home.
</P>
<P>
   They'll be giving away computer wrist rests and will have an
online chat with some of the current players, former manager Tommy
Lasorda and former player Steve Garvey, among other activities.
Dodger.com officials boast that it's been named best team site five
years in a row by USA Today's Baseball Weekly. If you're a fan of
the boys in blue, take a swing by www.dodgers.com. &QL; 
-- To reach David Bloom with stories, tips and other information on
the intersection of art, entertainment and technology, e-mail him
at davidbloomearthlink.net or call (818) 713-3678. This column and
related material can also be found all week at www.dailynews.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
