<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5727 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      05-25 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ There is a line that appears a couple of times in
``M: I-2'' (though not quite as often as the series' patented
rubber-mask trick, which never seems to fail even though all the
spies already know it). It's a nifty bit of deconstruction: ``Any
search for a hero must begin with what a hero requires _ a
villain.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Towne, one of Hollywood's most respected screenwriters,
explains that it is with all action franchises, from 007 to Batman.
The genesis of each installment is not in the hero but in the
hero's quest, and that means a villain with a plausible and
nefarious scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps some moviegoers are wondering what Towne, the author of
``Shampoo,'' ``Chinatown'' and other classics, is doing on a John
Woo shoot-'em-up, even one that stars Towne's frequent superstar
collaborator, Tom Cruise. Some might even be expecting Towne to
peel off a rubber mask and be revealed as, oh, Shane Black or Jeb
Stuart or some other action-flick specialist. But the project was
not without its allure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since the end of the Cold War, people have been looking
for a good villain,'' said Towne, dressed in track shorts and
T-shirt, as he sipped a cappuccino at his Pacific Palisades home.
For a while it was Arab terrorists. Then it was arms dealers or
renegade Russians or evil Washington bureaucrats. Nothing seemed to
work quite so well as those old standbys, the Nazis and the KGB.
</P>
<P>
   Towne said he was watching ``60 Minutes'' a few years ago when
he saw a segment about new boutique antibiotics that kill specific
strains of viruses. He filed the idea away. A bit later he was
reading an article in National Geographic about Eskimos and a weird
strain of virus found frozen in the Arctic ice. The dime dropped.
How's that for a villain? A pharmaceutical company that makes a
super-killer virus just so it can sell people the antidote!
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tricky writing for a franchise series like `Mission:
Impossible' because there are certain things that you know you
cannot do,'' Towne said. ``The single biggest challenge is to
convince the audience that the hero might die.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, if not the hero, at least the hero's love interest or
sidekick.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing you can work with is the emotional life of your
hero,'' Towne said. ``If there is a romance, will the girl
survive?''
</P>
<P>
   Towne, who had a hand in writing the 1996 ``Mission:
Impossible'' movie, was involved in the sequel early on but dropped
out when he went to direct ``Without Limits,'' for which Cruise was
co-producer. Several other writers _ Towne estimates seven or eight
_ were brought into the sequel, and several plot lines were flirted
with. But by the time Towne returned to the project after
completing ``Without Limits,'' the filmmakers had returned to the
original virus idea.
</P>
<P>
   Towne said the ``M:I-2'' team took to heart some of the
criticism of the first film: that it was needlessly complex and
that too many crucial plot points were buried beneath sound cues
and the rattle of explosions.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't want to abandon all the complexity; they figured the
puzzle was part of the pleasure of the series. But extra efforts
were made to ensure that all crucial plot points were given enough
space and time to register with the audience.
</P>
<P>
   As for the key to Cruise's hero, the super-agent Ethan Hunt, it
is, Towne said, in the actor's own basic character.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a risk taker,'' Towne said. ``Tom loves risks. And
that's what drives Ethan.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the ``Impossible'' part of the title that attracts the star
and the character, Towne said, as much as the working out of the
mission. Hunt always seems to solve problems by doing something
riskier than anyone else would dream of trying, yet he somehow
manages to be in full control in the process. Like a character from
Greek mythology, he puts on wings and flies toward the sun, but he
does not fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the key,'' Towne said. ``He looks like Icarus, but he
is really Daedalus.''
</P>
<P>
   The wax does not melt from Tom Cruise's wings. ``He knows the
limits of adhesion,'' Towne said.
</P>
<P>
   THE PUBLIC PULSE
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, back when people wore leisure suits and Steven
Spielberg and George Lucas were inventing the summer blockbuster,
Hollywood's most lucrative period began on Memorial Day weekend and
ended on Labor Day. Well, it's been many years since that was true,
with more and more summer-type blockbusters opening in mid-May,
then early May and now, as with this year's ``U-571,'' in April.
</P>
<P>
   So this Memorial Day weekend, the summer movie season is well
under way.
</P>
<P>
   There are already two huge successes _ Ridley Scott's
``Gladiator'' and Disney's ``Dinosaur'' _ and ``M:I-2'' is widely
expected to be the third. There have also been some notable
failures, like ``The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas'' and the bona
fide disaster of ``Battlefield Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Can we learn anything yet about what audiences are hungry for
this year?
</P>
<P>
   ``In the digital age, perhaps movies are as much about the
places they take you as the stories they tell,'' said Walter
Parkes, who with Laurie MacDonald is jointly head of production at
DreamWorks, which released ``Gladiator.''
</P>
<P>
   Parkes and MacDonald, who were also executive producers of
``Gladiator,'' this week signed a new six-year deal with Dreamworks
that will allow them to continue their administrative duties while
producing some of their own movies, including films for Spielberg,
one of the studio's principals.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Wick, one of the producers of ``Gladiator,'' said
audiences seemed ready for new things.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is, it's one of those periods where there's a little
bit of fatigue with the same-old, same-old,'' said Wick, whose
producing credits also include the recent ``Stuart Little'' and the
coming ``Hollow Man,'' an invisible-man thriller. ``There is no
question that there is an appetite for unusual things.''
</P>
<P>
   While this summer season has its share of sequels (``M: I-2,''
``The Nutty Professor 2: The Klumps,'' ``Pokemon 2000'') and some
car-chase action films like those popular in previous summers
(``Gone in 60 Seconds''), there are also a lot of big, expensive
movies with unusual settings: second-century Rome in ``Gladiator,''
colonial America in ``The Patriot,'' North Atlantic fishing grounds
in ``The Perfect Storm.''
</P>
<P>
   And there are ``dinosaurs like nobody's ever seen before,'' Wick
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the moment, it's better to go into the marketplace with
something that feels new,'' he said. ``Maybe it's just an old
genre, like sword-and-sandal movies, given new life with new
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
