<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5728 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-FLORA-LEWIS-MAY25-NYT     05-25 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORA-LEWIS-MAY25-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADERSHIP IS NOT JUST A SKILL  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 775-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of the FLORA LEWIS column.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text.) 
 &HT;    
 By FLORA LEWIS  
 c.2000 Flora Lewis  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by The New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, MASS. _ It is a commonplace nowadays to hear people
who are discussing public affairs bemoan the absence, or even the
failure, of leadership.
</P>
<P>
   It is true in most democratic countries, and even in some where
the complaint is that there is too heavy a hand on the helm without
accountability. But even a shallow probe shows how little the vague
wish for better organization of society reflects concrete meaning.
</P>
<P>
   What is meant by leadership? What should it do and be careful
not to do? How far should people insist on what they want from
their governors and how far should they let themselves be chivied
or cajoled to accept what they are told?
</P>
<P>
   A recent conference at Harvard jointly sponsored by the Kennedy
School of Government and the world leadership group of the
InterAction Council bogged down immediately as a few dozen well
practiced minds came up with endless answers.
</P>
<P>
   It was like the Supreme Court justice who once said that he
couldn't define pornography but he knew it when he saw it. The
purpose was unexceptionable, to promote ``enlightened leadership''
both in the U.S. and in the rest of the world, and to draw up
standards.
</P>
<P>
   The former heads of government who compose the InterAction
Council have been struggling to outline the responsibilities of
good leadership for years, and now the Kennedy School has a special
center for studying and teaching this elusive skill.
</P>
<P>
   There is a widespread sense that the need for good leaders is
more urgent than ever. The philosophic attraction of anarchy,
sometimes intense in the 19th century as the way to get rid of bad
government by getting rid of all government, no longer has even
theoretical appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Some American conservatives argue that government is the
problem, not the solution, but they are always asking government to
make other people observe the rules they approve. There are just
too many people and society is far too complex to leave its
organization unsettled.
</P>
<P>
   Two important changes add new urgency to the sense that
leadership which provides both smooth functioning and direction to
deal with change is absolutely essential.
</P>
<P>
   One is the challenge of technology to the way people are
accustomed to doing things and which they can see don't work as
needed any more.
</P>
<P>
   The other is the weight that the market idea has taken on,
overwhelming so many other factors that are still respected or
admired but which somehow can't compete.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint about globalization, its degrading and destructive
aspects, is really not about removing barriers but about
commercialization, about money becoming the measure of all. That is
not new, but the degree of money-mindednes has reached new
extremes.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing is what really matters, not only in merchandise but in
sports, entertainment, politics. A young American of the new
mindset even argued recently that the weakness of the euro,
Europe's new common currency, stems from the failure to promote it
with adequate energy and imagination, maybe handing net chocolate
coins.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to market money, without stopping to realize he would
still want to seek a return for what he sells.
</P>
<P>
   Opinion polls form an adjunct to the modern market, though it
often becomes quite unclear just who is the producer and who the
consumer, and when they trade places.
</P>
<P>
   A medical metaphor was offered to the dilemma of leadership, on
the grounds that a good and kindly doctor must also offer
well-judged doses of the truth to be dispensed according to the
patient's capacity.
</P>
<P>
   What people want to hear, which polls serve to amplify, may be
far different from what they need to know to deal wisely with
current and foreseeable problems.
</P>
<P>
   The leader may have to face a trade-off between popularity and
the courage of integrity, which the market of the ballot boy may
take its time about punishing and rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   But who is to say that the leader really does know better and
really can better distinguish between sturdy truth and promotional
pap? It's useful to discuss leadership and remind ourselves of its
inevitable role, if only also to remember that we keep changing our
minds about what we think we want.
</P>
<P>
   It is profoundly risky to reduce the idea of democratic
discourse, the exchange of grievances and aspirations, to a matter
of skills and techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching enlightened leadership should basically be about clear
thinking and good ethics, and that is how followers can and should
judge those who seek their support. We need first a better idea for
ourselves of what we want. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Flora Lewis is the former foreign-affairs columnist
for The New York Times. She is the author of five books, including
``Europe: Road To Unity'' and ``Europe: A Tapestry of Nations.''
Her articles have appeared in the International Herald Tribune, The
New York Times Magazine, The Atlantic, The Economist, France-Soir,
Life, The London Observer, The New Yorker and many other
periodicals. Last year she won the Overseas Press Club's Award for
Lifetime Achievement.) &QL; 
