<HEADER>
A5731 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FLY-FISHING-HNS &LR;      05-25 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLY-FISHING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TRYING TO MATCH THE HATCH CAN FRUSTRATE THE BEST FISHERMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRED LeBRUN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Even for the most experienced dry-fly fisherman,
the timer starts ticking and the adrenaline kicks in when the hatch
materializes.
</P>
<P>
   When those first few anticipated slim-winged insects with long
arched bodies leave their nymphal shucks and rise from the surface
of the water and flutter briefly in front of your nose, then seem
to disappear. When trout spontaneously dimple the water all around,
trout you had no idea even existed in this stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly the air over the stream and along the shores is alive
with thousands of delicately winged insects moving like battalions
of tiny helicopters. Your heart starts to pound, the hands fumble
for the bifocals.
</P>
<P>
   Show time, and who knows how long the show will last. Because
when the fluttering starts, you know all too well it's only a
matter of time before the hatch will fade just as dramatically.
There's no way of knowing when that will be. A few minutes, 20
perhaps. Forty on a good day. The angler has little time to
determine which mayfly or caddis fly it is that's rising; more
importantly, which is particularly interesting to those dimpling
trout.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy has to be settled, and fast. At which phase of the
mayfly's well-known cycle will the fisherman attempt to imitate the
natural? On the bottom, under the surface, on the surface, or
falling from the sky after mating? Each phase has its own patterns
of artificial imitations of fur and feathers, threads and snippets.
</P>
<P>
   The devil of it is that one day the trout will feed only on the
nymphs coming up from the bottom, another day on the emerging
mayfly when it's quite vulnerable, another day just on the spinner
falls of the spent and mated insects. And you can't always tell
which is which, even when standing there in the stream.
</P>
<P>
   To complicate matters, especially later in the season, several
different mayflies and a few caddis flies frequently will emerge at
roughly the same time, meaning that all the combinations and
permutations are multiplied by the number of different insects.
</P>
<P>
   As enormously complicated as all this seems, we still haven't
talked about which artificial fly patterns to consider, what style,
which size, or the delicacy of the leader tippet attached to the
fly. The lighter the tippet, the easier to fool the fish. The
lighter the tippet, the easier to lose the fish. Then you have to
decide whether to fish straight across, upstream or down, with or
without a dropper fly. The choices go on and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   One of the great charms of fly fishing is that there are an
infinite number of ways to fail.
</P>
<P>
   Yet fly fishers catch trout all the time, so it can't be that
complicated. And it isn't, generally. Although trying to match the
hatch and fool the fish is sometimes so complex that even the
crustiest veteran fails to solve the puzzle and walks away fishless
and muttering. It happens sometimes to the best of them, and often
to the worst of us.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, if you can't lose, the game isn't worth playing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a practical matter, much of what I just touched on _ and
there's a lot more to it _ is automatically assimilated into a fly
fisherman's technique and style, which develops with time and
experience. Those of us who have done it for a while go on
automatic pilot when the hatch starts, any hatch. We reach for
favored flies and tried and true patterns, the lightest tippet we
think we can handle, position ourselves and start to cast.
</P>
<P>
   Then it happens or it doesn't, and when it doesn't we go to plan
B and work our way down the alphabet and into a bottle of scotch.
Oh, it's the best game.
</P>
<P>
   Mayflies, caddis flies, stone flies and others hatch in a
regular serial rhythm year after year in timeless replay. Reciting
their names and when we can expect which to come off the water is
our catechism.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of May is the time for a particular mayfly called
an Ephemerella subvaria, the female being imitated by a Hendrickson
and the male by a red quill, two quite dissimilar flies. Although
we generally call this the Hendrickson hatch. Don't ask.
</P>
<P>
   To my mind this is the first predictable hatch of the season
that's a delight to fish because it rises at about the time the
school buses are leaving the yard. Typically this will go on for a
couple of weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
