A5736 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CAR-ATWOOD-COX     05-25 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-ATWOOD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    19-year-old joins Evernham, Elliott
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.C. _Bill Elliott's teammate at Dodge next year will
be a driver half the age of the former Winston Cup champion.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Evernham announced Thursday that 19-year-old phenom Casey
Atwood has agreed to join his team with Elliott, beginning with the
2001 season. Atwood is in his second full year on the Busch Grand
National Series.
</P>
<P>
   Evernham ``can definitely make a lot of people ready before they
are actually ready,'' Atwood said. ``In all honesty, if it had been
anything else except for this deal with Ray and Dodge, I wouldn't
have taken it. I would have stayed in Busch for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this was something you just can't pass up, with Ray's
knowledge and what he did with Jeff Gordon,'' Atwood said. ``And
then there is Dodge's heavy commitment to get back into stock-car
racing. I just felt like this was a winning situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Evernham served as Gordon's crew chief 1993-1999, guiding the
No. 24 Chevy driver to three Winston Cup championships. He resigned
last year to lead Dodge's return to the major-league circuit and to
start his own team.
</P>
<P>
   His plan all along was for the team to consist of one veteran
and one rookie. He accomplished the first goal when Bill Elliott
signed on at the March Atlanta race. Atwood's agreement, which took
several months to work out, completes the search.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our idea is to build the team with Bill and keep the pressure
off of Casey,'' Evernham said. ``He is young, and we want to give
him the experience he needs with our team. We think he has a great
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup teams have been pursuing Atwood since soon after he
made his Busch series debut in 1998 at the age of 17. In his second
race, at Nashville, Atwood won the pole and finished second.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Atwood became the youngest driver to win a Busch
race, and he finished 13th in the final standings. After a dozen
races this season, Atwood has one pole and three top-10 finishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I ready for this step? I don't know,'' Atwood said. ``We're
definitely going to see. I'm not going to lie, though.... I'm
definitely nervous about moving up to Winston Cup. But I know I
have the best (support) behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   Atwood will drive the No. 19 Dodge Intrepid, which was
Evernham's old number when he was racing modifieds. Atwood also
plans to qualify for five of this year's final 23 Winston Cup
races.
</P>
<P>
   CASEY ATWOOD FILE
</P>
<P>
   Age: 19.
</P>
<P>
   Hometown: Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Racing history: Started go-karts at the age of 10. Competed in
13 Busch races in 1998, winning two poles and finishing an average
of 20th. In 1999, won at Milwaukee and Dover, took two pole
positions and had nine finishes in the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Ray Evernham scores a victory over his former employers
at Hendrick Motorsports by landing one of the most promising
drivers in NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
