<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, May 26, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of heavy showers and some potent thunderstorms will be
focused near a front separating seasonably cool air over the
Midwest and Northeast from hot weather in the South. Strong
shifting high-level winds accompanying a jet stream disturbance
will heighten the risk of scattered tornadoes across the central
Plains later Friday. Rains of 1 to 3 inches will be common by
Saturday morning from northwestern Oklahoma to southern Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Converging winds near a strengthening low-pressure center will
cause showers and some strong thunderstorms from the eastern slopes
of the northern Rockies early Friday to the Dakotas Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The record heat of recent days in the Southwest will abate, but
temperatures will remain above the seasonal average. The Northwest
will have variable clouds and a few mountain showers.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: WEATHER BREEDER
</P>
<P>
   Zones of great temperature contrast provide the breeding ground
for foul weather. On Wednesday, temperatures at several cities in
western and central Texas were near 110 degrees, setting records
for the highest ever recorded in May. In Mobridge, S.D., the
mercury plummeted to 35 degrees early Thursday, a record low for
the date. During the next few days, atmospheric motions will be
generated that will reduce the disparity. The result will be
recurrent potent thunderstorms and the risk of flooding rain in
parts of the Plains and Midwest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
