<HEADER>
A5741 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS &LR;      05-25 1973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BRIEFS ARE FILED IN SAN FRANCISCO NEWSPAPER TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SETH ROSENFELD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Former mayoral candidate Clint Reilly has
broadened his legal attack on San Francisco's daily newspaper
publishers, asking a federal judge to permanently bar not only the
Hearst Corp.'s purchase of the Chronicle but also its sale of the
Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst on Wednesday countered that Reilly's suit was baseless
and that he had slandered a host of people _ from Hearst executives
to Mayor Willie Brown and U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno _ with
false claims that the proposed newspaper deals were ``the product
of an enormous political conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fang family accused Reilly of suing The Examiner and the
Chronicle for endorsing Brown over Reilly in last year's mayoral
race. Reilly denied the claims.
</P>
<P>
   And in a rare legal split with Hearst during the trial, the
Chronicle said it did not believe the Newspaper Preservation Act
protected two clauses in its joint operating agreement with Hearst
_ clauses that Alioto contends illegally blocked other major media
firms from bidding against Hearst for the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   The claims and counterclaims came as lawyers in Reilly's
antitrust suit filed proposed legal findings in the nation's first
trial on a challenge to the breakup of a joint operating agreement
between two daily newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The briefs summarized each side's legal position and answered
questions posed by U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker, who will rule
on Reilly's contention that Hearst's proposed deals will illegally
reduce ewspaper competition in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The briefs set the stage for closing arguments May 31.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's complaint contends Hearst's plan to buy the Chronicle
and sell The Examiner to the Fangs will result in Hearst's owning
the only metropolitan daily paper in San Francisco, an alleged
illegal monopoly that will reduce editorial voices and increase
subscription and advertising prices.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph M. Alioto, Reilly's lawyer, has argued that Hearst's deal
with the Fangs, which gives them a subsidy of up to $66 million
over three years to offset publishing costs, is a sham because the
subsidy is insufficient and The Examiner will fold.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto previously asked Walker to permanently bar Hearst from
buying the Chronicle. But in his brief Wednesday, and in a proposed
amended complaint filed last week, he broadened his request by
asking Walker to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Block Hearst from selling The Examiner to the Fangs,
publishers of the free, thrice-weekly San Francisco Independent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nullify a part of Hearst's joint operating agreement with the
Chronicle that gives each partner the chance to outbid offers from
other potential buyers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Void another part that prevents partners in the agreement from
operating other newspapers within 60 miles of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst, the Chronicle and the Fangs have denied Reilly's claims
and Wednesday renewed their request that Walker dismiss his
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the parties' arguments on key legal issues:
</P>
<P>
   1) Does Reilly have standing to sue?
</P>
<P>
   Alioto said his client has standing under the Clayton Antitrust
Act as a consumer because he buys the Chronicle and Examiner and
would be affected by alleged price increases ``the hallmarks of
monopoly'' that he claims would result from Hearst's proposed
newspaper deals.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst and Chronicle counter that Reilly lacks legal standing
because he has failed to show he would suffer significant economic
injury.
</P>
<P>
   David Balabanian, the Fangs' lawyer, contended the suit was
Reilly's ``means of obtaining retribution against the newspapers
which opposed his mayoral candidacy and the man who defeated him.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly lost last year's mayoral race to Brown after spending
about $4 million of his own money on his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Wednesday, Reilly displayed a photo of his
father selling newspapers on a San Francisco street corner in the
1930s. He said he wanted only to ensure that San Francisco has two
strong competing newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   2) Is Hearst entitled to the failing-business defense?
</P>
<P>
   Hearst contends The Examiner is an economically failing
business, and that as a result it may buy the Chronicle and close,
sell or donate The Examiner without harming competition.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Halling, a Hearst lawyer, said The Examiner would lose tens
of millions of dollars a year if published outside its
profit-splitting agreement with the Chronicle, which he said
generates more revenue and in effect subsidizes The Examiner. The
Chronicle's daily circulation is 465,535. The Examiner's is
108,968.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, the papers evenly split combined revenue,
production costs and the ``net excess'' without regard to their
respective circulations. Each paper then pays its editorial costs.
Hearst has said that last year it netted about $20.5 million in
profit under the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   But even within the agreement, Halling argued, The Examiner is
failing because, Hearst's analyses show, The Examiner's share of
production costs far exceeds the revenue it generates.
</P>
<P>
   And after an extensive sales effort, Hearst could find no one
who would take The Examiner for free, and had to give the Fangs a
subsidy, Halling said. Reilly had tried to buy The Examiner and
requested a larger subsidy, according to Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto countered that the failing-business defense is not
available to Hearst, because it applies only when the company to be
acquired is a failing competitor and the purchasing firm is the
only available buyer.
</P>
<P>
   If the law did apply, Alioto said, Hearst cannot prove The
Examiner is failing.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst expects The Examiner to continue to net a profit through
2005, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Hearst has not tracked The Examiner's separate production
costs under the joint operating agreement, said Alioto, adding,
``The Examiner is not in fact failing.''
</P>
<P>
   3) Does the Newspaper Preservation Act require continued
publication of The Examiner and the Chronicle until 2005?
</P>
<P>
   The act says newspapers may form joint operating agreements that
would otherwise violate antitrust laws when one of them is in
danger of failing, so long as they remain editorially independent.
The law is meant to give communities the benefit of multiple
editorial voices.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto claims that in return for profitable immunity from
antitrust laws, the Chronicle and Examiner have a public duty to
publish until the agreement expires.
</P>
<P>
   He contends Hearst's plan to buy the Chronicle and sell The
Examiner to the Fangs ``is a misuse and perversion of both the
Newspaper Preservation Act and the JOA (joint operating
agreement).''
</P>
<P>
   Halling counters that the act is merely a voluntary exemption
from antitrust laws and does not require publishers to continue the
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The JOA is not a contract with the `public' as plaintiff
asserts,'' said Halling.
</P>
<P>
   4) Is competition improved or harmed by the proposed newspaper
deals?
</P>
<P>
   Hearst and the Chronicle contend that Hearst's purchase of the
Chronicle and shedding of The Examiner will improve competition,
because the Chronicle no longer will need to subsidize the failing
Examiner and can put more resources into the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle then could better compete against other media in
the greater Bay Area, including Knight Ridder, which owns the San
Jose Mercury News and Contra Costa Times, radio and television, and
the Internet, Halling said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Alioto more narrowly defined the competitive
battleground, saying it involves only daily newspapers in San
Francisco or the greater ``metropolitan area.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he argued, Hearst's sale of The Examiner will not
preserve competition because the Fangs' version of it ``cannot be a
competitive daily newspaper or even a colorable substitute for the
present paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Balabanian countered that the newspaper deals will increase
competition and that the Fangs have an ``excellent'' chance of
making the paper solvent.
</P>
<P>
   Balabanian contended that Hearst divested itself of The Examiner
to satisfy concerns of the U.S. Department of Justice, which was
reviewing the proposed deals.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department concluded the deals would provide
economic competition between newspapers in San Francisco for the
first time in 35 years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The state attorney general's office and the San Francisco city
attorney's office also reviewed and chose not to block the proposed
newspaper sales.
</P>
<P>
   5) Was there a conspiracy to obtain an illegal monopoly?
</P>
<P>
   Alioto contends that Hearst, the Chronicle and the Fangs have
engaged in an illegal conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto has claimed the Fangs offered to use their ``extensive''
political connections to help Hearst win support for its purchase
of the Chronicle in return for Hearst's agreement to sell The
Examiner to the Fangs. The Fangs are political allies of Brown, who
opposed Hearst's initial plan to buy the Chronicle. Alioto has
pointed to meetings about the deals that, at various points,
involved the Fangs, Brown, U.S. Sen. Dianne Feinstein and Examiner
Publisher Timothy O. White.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fangs have thereby joined and entered the pre-existing
unlawful combination between Hearst and CPC (Chronicle Publishing
Co.),'' Alioto said in his brief.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst, Chronicle and the Fangs deny the conspiracy claim.
</P>
<P>
   Halling contended that Alioto and Reilly had used the trial ``as
a platform for slander.''
</P>
<P>
   Halling labeled as ``outrageous'' Alioto's allegation that the
proposed newspaper deals are ``the product of an enormous political
conspiracy that included at least the Antitrust Division of the
Justice Department, Attorney General Reno, presumably the attorney
general of California, Mayor Brown, Sen. Feinstein, the Fangs and
Hearst.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker on Monday asked the lawyers whether their exemption to
antitrust laws under the Newspaper Preservation Act would still
apply if The Examiner could be made financially sound using changes
proposed by the Fangs.
</P>
<P>
   All the lawyers agreed that the act specified only that one of
the newspapers must be failing at the time the joint operating
agreement was formed.
</P>
<P>
   Walker also asked the lawyers to brief him on whether the act
protects two clauses in the Hearst-Chronicle joint operating
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The first gives each partner the ``first right of refusal,'' or
chance to outbid any offer for the other partner's paper. The
second prohibits any partner in the agreement from owning another
paper within a 60-mile radius of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto had argued that the clauses are inconsistent with the act
and allowed Hearst to gain a monopoly by unfairly blocking
potential suitors for the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Halling argued that the clauses are standard contract language,
and in effect were allowed by Congress when it passed the act.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-mile clause, he said, was meant merely to ensure that the
partners in the agreement avoided conflicts of interest that might
arise if they owned nearby papers.
</P>
<P>
   Halling cited testimony by Jill Greenthal, of the Donaldson,
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette financial investment firm, in which she said she
believed the clauses had no significant effect on her marketing of
the Chronicle. Greenthal said Hearst's $660 million offer was a
fair price and the highest bid.
</P>
<P>
   However, J. Thomas Rosch, a Chronicle lawyer, argued that the
Newspaper Preservation Act protects only functions necessary for
running the newspapers, such as printing, advertising and
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Rosch said the 60-mile and first-right-of-refusal clauses are
not protected, and must meet traditional antitrust principles. If
he is right, that would mean the clauses are potentially more
vulnerable to being nullified by Walker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 1828EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5743 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-PARKS-SNOWMOBILES-052     05-25 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARKS-SNOWMOBILES-0526-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ADMINISTRATION, CRITICS SPAR OVER SNOWMOBILING IN NATIONAL PARKS
 &HT;    By MIRIAM A. GARCIA
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration believes snowmobiling
should be limited in national parks, but critics said Thursday that
any cutback could cause economic harm and unfairly limit access to
nature.
</P>
<P>
   A Clinton administration official told a House hearing that
snowmobiles generate significant levels of air and noise pollution,
often harass wildlife and disturb visitors' desire for solitude.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Barry, a U.S. Interior Department assistant secretary,
said his agency wants to strictly enforce regulations on
recreational snowmobiling in the parks.
</P>
<P>
   But, referring to two of the nation's most popular parks _ Grand
Teton and Yellowstone _ he said the Interior Department will not
make any final decisions about those parks until the agency's
National Park Service has completed an environmental impact
statement.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, snowmobile supporters said restricting their use
also means restricting visitors' access to national parks during
the winter.
</P>
<P>
   `` Unless you are 20 years old and can walk through five to 10
feet of snow, you need a snowmobile to get around,'' said Bill
Manson from the American Council of Snowmobile Associations. ``And
that is denying us access to the parks.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Barry said: ``This is not about closing national
parks to the American public....It is about complying with the
law.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry acknowledged that the National Park Service has not
enforced its own restrictions which limit snowmobiling. But that is
understandable, he said, because ``there has never been
encouragement or support'' for strict enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important that we preserve our resources for future
generations,'' Barry said.
</P>
<P>
   The parks were created to preserve nature and allow people to
experience them in their natural state, said Michael Scott of the
Greater Yellowstone Coalition, an environmental group based in
Bozeman, Mont.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to accommodate ever-increasing visitor numbers in the
next century, parks must identify modes of visitor access which do
not endanger precious park natural resources,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Helen Chenoweth-Hage, R-Idaho, said new snowmobile models
can be built to reduce emissions and noise without hurting the
snowmobile economy, which several witnesses put at $800 million a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``These policies hurt rural Idaho, they hurt our economies and
our communities and they destroy the wonderful winter sport that is
enjoyed by thousands of Americans,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Garcia can be reached by e-mail at:
miriamg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
