<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-475(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATIONS, AND SOME TENSION, ALONG ISRAELI-LEBANESE BORDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also ISRAEL-LEBANON) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ As the Israeli troop withdrawal settled into a
reality, the Lebanese proudly celebrated a new holiday, National
Resistance Day, with a jubilant rally Thursday at the now empty
Khiam prison, which is notorious here for the reported torture of
guerrilla fighters by Israel's Lebanese militia allies.
</P>
<P>
   Cheering, flag-waving throngs defiantly transformed the place
that the Lebanese saw as a nightmarish symbol of their 22-year-long
occupation into the venue for a victory party. The prison, it was
announced Thursday, will be preserved in all its sordid disarray as
a monument to the depths of the misery that they overcame.
</P>
<P>
   A guarded hopefulness transfused the country as Lebanese tasted
the possibility that they might be entering a rare era _ however
limited _ without bloodshed. Beneath the hope, however, lay the
fear that Israel's threats to treat cross-border fire as an ``act
of war'' meant that the stakes were now much higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born in 1975,'' said Maya Abishaheen, a political
scientist in Beirut. ``And all I've seen is war. Maybe this is the
first day in my life when a bomb or a machine gun wasn't aimed at
someone in my country. It is such happiness. But we are so afraid.
Maybe now all it takes is a Katyusha rocket and they can wipe us
off the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Low-level tensions surfaced at the Israeli-Lebanese border
itself as the exuberance here mixed with the palpable hostility
toward Israel. In Kfar Kila, barely 10 feet from the Israeli town
of Metulla, curiosity seekers mingled with guerrilla fighters and
free-lance hooligans to create an alternately festive and
provocative scene.
</P>
<P>
   First some youths lobbed Israeli-grown melons back over the
border. Then the melons gave way to stones and firebombs, the
Israelis said in a complaint to the U.N. officials here. The U.N.
representatives asked key resistance leaders to hold back their
members, which they did, but the crowd was not solely theirs.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the barbed-wire fences along the border,
the Israeli parliament held a special meeting in the northern
border town of Kiryat Shemona, where Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
other officials said they hoped that Lebanon would see the
withdrawal as a gesture of peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appeal to you, President Emile Lahoud,'' Barak said. ``Let's
exploit the moment. Let's talk peace.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the Lebanese, peace with Israel is not yet part of the
vocabulary; it would be too abrupt. ``In Lebanon, the last shots
fired were two days ago,'' said Timor Goeksl, who has been the
spokesman for the U.N. forces in Lebanon since arriving on a
six-month assignment in 1978. ``There are a lot of dead, wounded
and destroyed people. It's going to be a long time before their
feelings of distrust and hostility go away.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Despite Barak's extended hand, the deep-seated suspicions on
both sides are mirror images of each other. Israelis see the Shiite
Muslim guerrillas who fought them in southern Lebanon as hell-bent
on violently challenging Israel's very existence; the occupation
was their excuse, Israelis say, which is why the Lebanese are now
coming up with reasons to invalidate the withdrawal and justify
continued fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese see Israel as a military powerhouse and occupier of
Arab lands, which has now promised to seize on any provocation to
re-occupy their territory or bombard them mercilessly. The
withdrawal is not a gesture of peace, they say, but a delayed
compliance with a U.N. resolution that ordered them out in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   A prominent, sophisticated Beirut journalist recounted, with
bemusement, what her young daughter said when she told her about
the withdrawal: ``Where will the Israelis go now, Mommy? To someone
else's land?'' The Hezbollah leaders, who have been careful to
present the Israeli retreat as a Lebanese victory and not just
theirs, are riding high. If outsiders like the Americans and the
Israelis label them as Iran-backed and Syrian-abetted terrorists,
here they are part of the social and political establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of Shiite Muslim sheiks granted interviews Thursday
during live coverage of the festivities, and they sounded as if
they were campaigning. Indeed, with parliamentary elections ahead
in August, they fully intend to capitalize on the moment. The
Shiite Muslim parties now hold 32 of 128 seats; six of those belong
to Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   In a scene that dramatized the precipitate changes of the last
few days, Iran's foreign minister, Kamal Kharrazi, flanked by the
Hezbollah fighters that his nation helped train, toured Lebanon's
border with Israel. He drove at the head of a motorcade through the
zone that Israel occupied until Wednesday, proclaiming the
withdrawal a ``victory for the region and the whole Islamic
world.'' At one point, the foreign minister left his car, climbed a
hill and gazed across at Israeli settlements with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   The television coverage of events in the south included clips
from this week's tumultuous events spliced into a music video of a
Lebanese pop singer crooning a jaunty tune: ``You should know,
invaders, who you are and who we are,'' the slick star sang under
disco lights. ``Humiliation has never been one of our traits.''
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese officials sent 100 additional police officers to the
southern zone, more than doubling the size of the force to address
the residents' fears of lawlessness. It was a sign that the
government was willing to move into the area even if it was not
ready to send troops there. But Hezbollah and other resistance
groups far outnumbered the officials, and they manned the
checkpoints and kept the order, even as their minions let loose
daylong fireworks from their automatic weapons.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. troops, whose number will increase to 7,900 from 4,500,
will not deploy to the border until the United Nations certifies
that the Israeli withdrawal is complete and Lebanon accepts its
certification. But they ran frequent patrols Thursday far deeper
into the zone than they were ever stationed, and nobody complained.
</P>
<P>
   Smiling broadly, the foreign soldiers in the blue helmets waved
at the Lebanese flocking into the south like tourists. ``Good, good
for you,'' a Ghanaian soldier kept repeating. Like the Finns and
the Indians and the Irish troops, he did not hide his relief at
spending his first day in the region freely above ground and not
hunkered down in bunkers during the daily cross-fire.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Stationed for 20 years on the northern edge of the zone, the
soldiers also appreciated moving into the heart of the area they
are supposed to monitor. Their supervisors, though, are wary about
the thousands of mines and the unexposed ordinance that lie
scattered along the border. U.N. officials here have secured maps
of some minefields from the Israelis and made urgent requests for
an engineering unit to de-mine the area.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations' Middle East envoy, Terje Roed-Larsen, met
with Lebanese officials Thursday to discuss how to expand the
troops' role and ease the way for the Lebanese government to
reassert its authority over the area. According to the Lebanese
prime minister, Selim al-Hoss, Hezbollah will also coordinate its
role with the U.N. forces and the government.
</P>
<P>
   Larsen made no comments after the meetings. He was peppered with
questions about Israeli radio reports earlier Thursday that Barak
had told foreign leaders that Israel would consider leaving the
Shebaa Farms region at the edge of the Golan Heights to avoid
prolonging the conflict. Lebanon has claimed the territory as its
own, even though it was under Syrian control when Israel occupied
the Golan.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's office denied the radio reports.
</P>
</TEXT>
