<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5748 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-NYT     05-25 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK APPEALS TO LEBANON'S PRESIDENT: `LET US TALK PEACE' 
</HEADLINE>
 (See also LEBANON) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRYAT SHEMONA, Israel _ Offering an olive branch to Lebanon a
day after withdrawing Israeli troops from its soil, Prime Minister
Ehud Barak of Israel traveled to this norther border town Thursday
and appealed to the Lebanese president, Emile Lahoud, to ``turn
over a new leaf'' and begin peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Barak addressed the Israeli parliament at its first plenary
session held outside Jerusalem, convened here to show support for
communities on Israel's northern frontier.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of this working-class town, hardened by years of
crossborder rocket attacks by guerrillas in Lebanon, expressed
skepticism that the withdrawal would bring lasting calm. One
demonstrator greeted the prime minister with a sign: ``Barak is
gambling with our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the legislators in a local auditorium, Barak made his
peace overture.
</P>
<P>
   ``From this podium at Qiryat Shemona, the city that was the main
target of aggression and terror from Lebanon, I appeal to the
government and people of Lebanon: We have left all your country's
territory up to the international border that is recognized by the
United Nations,'' Barak said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't covet a single inch of your land, we have no demands
of you, except to strictly preserve security along our common
border.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call on you, President Emile Lahoud: Israel extends its hand
in peace, with the vision of a common future that will be better
for the children of both peoples. Let us talk peace. Israel is not
an enemy of Lebanon.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak said that Israeli troops had only entered Lebanon because
it had become ``a hothouse for terror organizations and a base for
aggression against us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have an opportunity to turn over a new leaf,'' Barak
said. ``This depends on us, on you and on the Syrian government.''
Syria, which is the dominant power in Lebanon, is thought to be
highly unlikely to sanction peace talks between Lebanon and Israel
as long as its own negotiations with Israel to recover the Golan
Heights remain suspended.
</P>
<P>
   As Barak tried to turn the withdrawal to diplomatic advantage,
he received a cool reception from residents here, who are worried
that guerrillas might now attack them from across the border fence,
even though not a shot has been fired since the pullout.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting a falafel stand for a chat on the street, Barak was
asked by a woman whether he thought his ``gamble would pay off.''
</P>
<P>
   Yossi Gavrieli, from the neighboring community of Margaliot,
said that he expected crossborder shooting at Israeli army patrols.
Yitzhak Ohana predicted that Syria would sponsor guerrilla violence
to press Israel into returning the Golan Heights. He held up a sign
that said ``We welcome the boys home, but what about my children?''
</P>
<P>
   Tamir Raymond shouted at Barak: ``Come live here.'' He
complained that the prime minister only visited Qiryat Shemona when
it was politically convenient.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah and other armed groups in Lebanon will never leave
Israel in peace, Ohana insisted. ``The Arabs don't want us here,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Up the road at Metulla, a community separated by a fence from a
Lebanese village, Kafr Kila, there were demonstrations across the
border. Youths raised the yellow flags of Hezbollah on the fence
and hurled invective at people on the Israeli side.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will all die,'' shouted a youth.
</P>
<P>
   Smoke rose from an abandoned Israeli base that had been sacked
by villagers. Mobs of youths roamed the base and climbed the border
fence, taunting Israeli soldiers and pelting them with old shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``God is great,'' they shouted. ``Death to Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the crowd was a group of Palestinians from the Ein
al-Hilweh refugee camp near Sidon. Born and raised in the camp,
they had come to the border with Israel to get a look at what they
consider their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today I am looking at my country for the first time,'' said
one man. ``For the first time, I feel like a human being.''
</P>
</TEXT>
