<HEADER>
A5750 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-25 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JUDGING CLINTON, AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The trouble with determining an appropriate legal
punishment for Bill Clinton's notorious misdeeds is that no one is
neutral toward this most polarizing of presidents.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was painfully obvious this week when a committee
overseeing the practice of law in Arkansas recommended that he be
disbarred, the harshest penalty possible and one seldom imposed.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the six-person panel insisted that the group
``approached this as we would any other lawyer.'' Sure. And cows
can fly.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton isn't just any other lawyer, as everyone knows. It's a
safe bet there's not a soul in Arkansas, let alone the entire
country, who doesn't love him or loathe him.
</P>
<P>
   Who could be indifferent to or ignorant of the soap opera that
is his presidency?
</P>
<P>
   The committee cited Clinton's ``serious misconduct'' as grounds
for disbarment, specifically the fact that he lied under oath in a
deposition in the Paula Jones sexual harassment case by denying he
had a sexual relationship with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky. The president will fight the recommendation, which his
advisers feel is excessively punitive and unfair.
</P>
<P>
   There are two sides to this. On the one hand, he is being held
to a tough standard because as president he is expected to set an
example and has a greater obligation to tell the truth than less
visible lawyers. On the other hand, lawyerly deceptions are rather
common, and he has a civil right to be treated fairly and not
punished by a negative double standard simply because of who he is.
</P>
<P>
   The federal judge who held him in contempt of court for failing
to tell the truth, Susan Webber Wright, recommended ``disciplinary
proceedings'' by the Arkansas bar, but did not argue for
disbarment. She was understandably irritated by the fact that some
of those lies were delivered in her presence.
</P>
<P>
   Several levels of sanctions are available, and clearly Clinton
deserves one of them. But the others are not as draconian as
denying the former law professor and state attorney general a
license to practice law. He says he doesn't intend to do so after
he leaves the White House, but it's the humiliation of the thing
that bugs him.
</P>
<P>
   More common penalties are reprimands and suspensions for a
specified period, which go into lawyers' records and inhibit their
ability to attract clients but do not freeze them out of their
chosen professional livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   In Arkansas, even lawyers who have defrauded clients and been
sent to jail usually _ although not always _ have been given a
legal slap on the wrist rather than disbarred.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing exactly parallels Bill Clinton's situation. How
could it? This guy invented new stuff, never before exposed as
presidential behavior. (Other presidents, we know in retrospect,
also strayed from their marital loyalties but were never caught so
decisively and spectacularly.)
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives like to compare Clinton with Richard Nixon to make
Clinton look worse and Nixon better, but Clinton does not have the
criminal instincts that Nixon did. Nixon was disbarred after being
named an unindicted co-conspirator by a grand jury for his
knowledge of a break-in at Democratic offices in the Watergate
complex and for impeding the investigation and obstructing justice.
He also demanded that his aides punish those on his enemies list,
he illegally tape-recorded associates, and he encouraged a second
break-in. We are talking real crimes here.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's sins are moral lapses, those of a selfish, powerful
man long accustomed to preying upon usually compliant women not his
wife. In this, he is like former Speaker Newt Gingrich, who had an
affair with a House staffer while simultaneously demanding
Clinton's impeachment for essentially the same behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The difference, conservatives say, is that Gingrich never lied
about it under oath. He was certainly just as disingenuous. But he
was never asked about it under oath. So here we split the legal
hairs.
</P>
<P>
   And that is the crux of Clinton's problem. Does lying under oath
stand alone as an unforgivable legal sin or do the subject matter
and the circumstances have any relevance? This was a personally
embarrassing subject, but his false testimony did not hurt a client
financially. Nor did it ultimately matter to anyone except the
perpetrator himself and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   But is it possible to treat a defiant president close to
retirement and loss of power just like any other lawyer on an issue
that is so emotionally and politically divisive? Or will the
temptation to bring him down overcome common sense and judicial
balance?
</P>
<P>
   The decision will be made by a few people with judicial power,
who themselves are part of the social elite and responsive to
political pressures both for and against Clinton. It is unrealistic
to expect that they will approach this latest chapter in the
Clinton saga opinion-free on the subject of our Bill.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
