<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   `American Beauty' in Short Supply
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty,'' Sam Mendes and Alan Ball's singular view of
suburbia, is video's top renter this week _ and that's with one
hand tied behind its back. Walk into Blockbuster stores around the
country and you will see only a fraction of the ``American Beauty''
boxes you might have. In some Blockbuster stores, you will find
``American Beauty,'' the Academy Award winner, only under the front
counter.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage has to do with revenue sharing. In the past
retailers bought cassettes and kept all the rental proceeds. Now
they buy the tapes at a much lower price, and share rental revenues
with the studios. In that way they can afford to supply many more
copies, thereby averting a major customer complaint.
</P>
<P>
   For various undisclosed reasons _ and price was not the only
factor _ Blockbuster and DreamWorks, which owns ``American
Beauty,'' could not reach a revenue-sharing agreement. So
Blockbuster bought ``American Beauty'' cassettes the more expensive
old-fashioned way, which means fewer copies in its stores.
</P>
<P>
   Since Blockbuster accounts for about 40 percent of the rental
market, any sizable drop in copies available in its stores
obviously depresses rental totals.
</P>
<P>
   Other chains and stores are carrying a full supply of the film.
A spokeswoman for DreamWorks said there were about one million
copies of ``American Beauty'' in circulation. In normal
circumstances Blockbuster might account for 400,000 copies, but
then the overall total could well have been higher had the chain
bought as many copies as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Blockbuster will not disclose how many copies of ``American
Beauty'' it displays. In urban stores 60 or more boxes may be on
the shelves, but ordinarily the number would have been considerably
higher. In some stores where ``American Beauty,'' an R-rated film,
is not in such high demand, the relatively few copies are kept
under the counter and must be requested.
</P>
<P>
   A Blockbuster spokeswoman said that keeping the videos up front
helped store managers explain the situation to customers
individually, but she added that concealment was also for
appearance's sake. ``We figured there would be so few up there, it
would just exacerbate the situation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Canadians' Music
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago Video Artists International, a distributor of
classical music and dance videos in Pleasantville, N.Y., began to
release programs from the archives of the Canadian Broadcasting
Co.'s English-language network. Now it's the turn of the CBC's
French network, which began its renowned music broadcasts in 1952.
Next week Video Artists International will begin to release tapes
by the pianists Alfred Brendel, Claudio Arau and Rosalyn Tureck;
the violinists Joseph Szigeti, Christian Ferras and Ida Haendel;
the singers Marilyn Horne, Leontyne Price and Jon Vickers; the
conductors Igor Markevitch, Charles Munch and Josef Krips; and many
others.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the broadcasts, recorded in 1976, the pianist Martha
Argerich performs Schumann's Piano Concerto and music by Liszt and
Ravel. Information: (800) 477-7146.
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   Man on the Moon Jim Carrey delivers an electrifying homage to
the comedian Andy Kaufman, but Milos Forman's film fails to answer
the question of who Kaufman was or how he got that way. All the
material is here: the uncanny impersonations, the wrestling matches
with women, the bombastic tirades of Kaufman's trash-talking alter
ego, the lounge singer Tony Clifton. But this remains a
surprisingly straightforward show-business rise-and-fall story. As
entertaining as that can be, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York
Times, it ``limits the film's ability to give Kaufman three
dimensions.''
</P>
<P>
   -1999. Universal. $107.37; DVD, $29.99. 118 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: May 30.
</P>
<P>
   Snow Falling on Cedars
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hicks' stunningly beautiful film, based on David
Guterson's novel, makes the mistake of retaining the book's
intricate flashbacks, which proves disruptive. In 1950 a young
Japanese-American (Rick Yune) stands trial for murder on the
fictitious San Piedro Island north of Puget Sound. That attracts
the interest of a journalist (Ethan Hawke), who years earlier had
an affair with the defendant's wife (Youki Kudoh) and relates to
the internment of Japanese-Americans during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   But the darting back and forth doesn't serve an adaptation that
is ``admirably high-minded and visually gorgeous but fatally
anesthetized by its own grandiosity'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   -1999. Universal. $107.37; DVD, $29.99. 126 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG-13. Release date: May 30.
</P>
<P>
   American Movie
</P>
<P>
   ``The American Dream stays with me each and every day,'' says
Mark Borchardt, the funny, garrulous subject of his own
documentary. For him, one of the those big, sterile houses he
craves will be just reward for the no-budget ``Blair Witch
Project'' knock-off he is making with the assistance of his Uncle
Bill and anyone else he can enlist. Along the way we discover
Borchardt, his own best character, in a film that by its end ``has
blossomed into much more than a portrait of one fiendishly
determined filmmaker'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   _1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $99.36; DVD, $27.95. 107 minutes.
Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   Julie
</P>
<P>
   In Mike Figgis' adaptation of Strindberg's drama, a wealthy
count's imperious, neurotic daughter (Saffron Burrows) spars
sexually with her virile, opportunistic footman, Jean (Peter
Mullan). These days the pairing might have at least led to some hot
sex, but here it is cause for a repressed, emotionally
sadomasochistic ritual of humiliation. Nor does haste help. ``The
dialogue may be crisply idiomatic, but there's finally nothing
realistic about the speed with which the characters hurtle through
their mood swings and power plays'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   _1999. MGM. $49.95; DVD, $24.98. 103 minutes. Closed captioned.
R. Release date: May 30.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   WHITNEY: THE GREATEST HITS. A Whitney Houston DVD roundup
includes all her music videos; commentary by the singer and an
interview with Clive Davis, the former president of Arista Records;
her premiere television appearance on ``The Merv Griffin Show'' in
1985; her television acting debut on ``Gimme a Break''; various
concert performances; views from behind the scenes at the making of
albums and videos; and 21 Houston favorites, from ``You Give Good
Love'' to ``I Learned From the Best.'' 2000. BMG. $24.98; also
available on VHS, $19.99.
</P>
<P>
   DEVIL'S ISLAND. With its trailer trash Icelandic style, Fridrik
Thor Fridriksson's film carves a vividly realized slice of life out
of the bleak landscape of Camp Thule near Reykjavik, an American
military base where, as Garrison Keillor might put it, the men are
drunks, the women unhappy and the children dysfunctional.
Nevertheless, they're a lively lot who number a witch who curses
God, a mother of three who escapes by marrying an American pilot
and her two grown sons, a boozy brawler and a shy, quiet potential
hero. The cast, Lawrence Van Gelder wrote in The New York Times,
``delivers performances so convincing and un-self-conscious that
`Devil's Island' at times seems to be a documentary.'' 1999.
Winstar. $89.98; DVD, $29.98. 103 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   GINEVRA'S STORY. Before the ``Mona Lisa,'' Leonardo da Vinci
painted ``Ginevra de' Benci,'' his first known portrait. Meryl
Streep narrates an exploration of Leonardo's original mysterious
lady by the National Gallery of Art in Washington. 2000. Home
Vision. $29.95. 57 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
