<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Friday, May 26 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-MEDIAONE (Washington) _ The Justice Department gave
conditional approval Thursday to AT&AMP;T's $58 billion acquisition of
MediaOne, giving AT&AMP;T control over more than a third of the
nation's cable television market. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   NY-TOBACCO (Albany, N.Y.) _ Gov. George Pataki on Thursday
vetoed a bill that would have made New York the first state to
require that cigarettes meet flammability standards, stunning the
Legislature and prompting Democrats and anti-tobacco groups to
accuse him of protecting the tobacco industry. By Richard
Perez-Pena.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Washington) _ Folo on the House passage of the
China trade bill and a look forward at possible difficulties in the
Senate. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-NUKES (Washington) _ Gov. George W. Bush's proposal this
week to consider unilateral reductions in the American nuclear
arsenal was a bold break with decades of strategic doctrine that
may foretell the end of traditional theories of arms control. By
John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   REFORM-PARTY (Tucson, Ariz.) _ The growing likelihood that
Patrick Buchanan will become the presidential nominee of the Reform
Party is producing a backlash from some party members and leaders
around the country. Efforts are under way to derail him and even
those who recognize the inevitability of it all wonder what the
party will look like in the future. There are fears that Buchanan
will force the party to take up social issues like abortion that it
has avoided. Some want Ross Perot to run again, although that
appears unlikely; some like Ralph Nader, and some think the party
should have no nominee at all this year. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   NY-WENDYS-MURDERS (New York) _ Five employees are killed and two
others are wounded in a late-night robbery at a Wendy's restaurant
in Queens. The dead had been herded into a basement walk-in
refrigerator and killed with shots to the head. By David Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT8,9,12.
</P>
<P>
   BROADBAND-HOUSING (Dallas) _ For a growing number of affluent
home buyers, high-speed broadband Internet connections are becoming
as important as a two-car garage, fireplace or new kitchen.
Recognizing this, some developers and builders are jumping into the
telecommunications business. Either by building and owning their
own neighborhood networks, or joining with telecommunications
companies, they are offering high-speed Internet connections,
bundled with cable and phone service, at discounts of up to $20 a
month from what this would otherwise cost. Their efforts are in the
very early stages. How developers eventually do against the
abundance of Baby Bells, cable companies and other providers
fighting to serve the residential market is anyone's guess. By
Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT17.
</P>
</TEXT>
