<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5764 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WEEKEND-REVIEW-575     05-25 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-REVIEW-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DIRTY PICTURES': A FILM THAT WANTS TO HAVE IT ALL WAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a decade of culture wars _ politicians nibbling away at
the National Endowment for the Arts, Congress and artists dueling
about what is fit for America to see _ there was a chilling
inexorability to the most recent skirmish, when New York's mayor
tried to cut off financing for the Brooklyn Museum of Art because
of a religious portrait in which one of the artist's materials was
elephant dung.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of public art exhibitions has been so co-opted by
politics, where else could things have gone?
</P>
<P>
   ``Dirty Pictures'' revisits a case that helped set off this
continuing battle: In 1990 the Contemporary Arts Center in
Cincinnati, and its director, Dennis Barrie, were charged with
obscenity after showing Robert Mapplethorpe's photographs, with
images of sadomasochism, homosexuality and naked children.
</P>
<P>
   It may be a sign of how accustomed we have become to such
conflicts that this earnest, pedestrian film is completely unable
to recapture what a galvanizing moment that was for both sides. It
would have taken a work with far more energy and dramatic flair to
convey the shock of that cultural moment.
</P>
<P>
   The film moves in several directions. It is partly a predictable
domestic soap opera. In a restrained performance, James Woods plays
Barrie as a man who never set out to be a crusader, but who feels
morally compelled to defend the First Amendment when he has to.
Though the film depicts both sides of the argument, it is
straightforward in its sympathy for Barrie, this script's hero.
Barrie's wife (Diana Scarwid) is socially ostracized, and their two
young sons are bullied at school. It is only a matter of time
before the patient wife is tossing vases around the living room.
</P>
<P>
   But the film is partly a courtroom drama, partly about politics,
as a conservative sheriff (Craig T. Nelson) goes after the museum,
and it is partly about the largest issue of all. As the forewoman
asks the other jurors about Mapplethorpe's work, ``Is it obscene or
is it art?''
</P>
<P>
   The film intends to show the convergence of all these elements,
but instead dissipates the impact of each.
</P>
<P>
   The title ``Dirty Pictures'' suggests a film that wants to have
it both ways, to be a serious work that titillates and seduces its
audience into paying attention. But it is cautious in its use of
the Mapplethorpe photography, and the images flash by quickly in
several sequences. Some are of flowers, some are portraits of
celebrities _ Susan Sarandon, Susan Sontag, Andy Warhol_ and some
are the images that set off the conflict. The film doesn't dwell on
graphic details; even if you are familiar with the photographs,
they go by so fast they can be difficult to identify.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Pierson, the film's director, also directed Woods in the
much better ``Citizen Cohn.'' Even the attempts at artistic touches
seem tame here: There are stylized images of the jury room, as if
the actors were on a bare stage; talking heads offer comments,
including William F. Buckley Jr., on the conservative side and Rep.
Barney Frank on the liberal side, but they are familiar platitudes.
``If you can't defend what is unpalatable to you personally, then
you don't actually believe in free speech,'' Salman Rushdie says.
</P>
<P>
   As an artist, Mapplethorpe was taken more seriously than most of
those whose work has set off cultural shockwaves. That makes
``Dirty Pictures'' even more of a lost opportunity.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   PICKING UP THE PIECES
</P>
<P>
   There are some movies whose existence is so baffling that ``The
X-Files'' could spend several episodes trying to sort out the
conspiracy theories behind their creation. The mystery behind the
witless, black comedy ``Picking Up the Pieces'' (airing 8 p.m.
Friday on Cinemax) is not why this film has gone straight to cable,
but why so many people who should have known better were sucked
into it.
</P>
<P>
   Woody Allen plays a New York butcher called Tex who has fled to
Texas, where he lives in a trailer with his dog, his 10-gallon hat
and his wife. She is a faithless former Mafia moll named Candy,
played by Sharon Stone with a baby-doll voice. The film looks as if
it took two days to shoot and cost 2 cents to make, though it was
directed by Alfonso Arau (``Like Water for Chocolate'') and shot by
Vittorio Storaro, one of the great cinematographers, whose films
include ``Reds.''
</P>
<P>
   At the start, Tex chops up Candy and scatters her body in the
desert. Soon her severed hand, with its shimmery blue nail polish,
turns up in the New Mexico town of El Nino and begins to perform
miracles. These are not clever miracles, but the kind in which a
flat-chested woman grows breasts before our eyes and a dwarf grows
a gigantic penis _ both discreetly obscured on screen. In no time
the magic hand makes El Nino a tourist mecca, to the delight of the
corrupt mayor (Cheech Marin).
</P>
<P>
   These cliches might seem to offer plenty of possibilities for
irreverent satire, but it would take a miraculous severed hand to
save this script, credited to Bill Wilson who's described by
Cinemax simply as ``a first-time screenwriter.''
</P>
<P>
   The film's humor is always lazy. We see a man in bed with a
beautiful prostitute, and he soon puts on his priest's collar.
Played by David Schwimmer with a slightly less hang-dog expression
than on ``Friends,'' the priest is, of course, in love with the
golden-hearted prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, a mean Texas sheriff _ toothpick-chewing Kiefer
Sutherland _ goes after Tex. The church sends in investigators,
including a bishop played by Elliot Gould and a nun played by Fran
Drescher, whose unchanging grimace makes hers the worst of the
film's many humorless performances.
</P>
<P>
   Allen has the only funny moments, including a scene in the
confessional. Tex sounds suspiciously like a Woody Allen character,
as if he had doctored his own lines. Maybe if he had rewritten and
directed the entire film, it might have added up to something.
</P>
<P>
   Did they all make a pact with the devil? Did someone drug their
drinks at a Hollywood party and make them sign contracts while
hallucinating? Whatever they thought going in, all the actors look
uneasy on screen, as if they were on a plane plummeting from the
sky and were putting on brave faces while they crash. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `DIRTY PICTURES'  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET Saturday on Showtime &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Frank Pierson, written by Ilene Chaiken, produced by
Michael Manheim, Hiro Narita, director of photography, and music by
Mark Snow. James Woods (Dennis Barrie), Craig T. Nelson (Leis),
Diana Scarwid (Dianne), Leon Pownall (Prouty), David Huband
(Sirkin), Judah Katz (Mizibov), R.D. Reid (Albanese) and Matt North
(Lobb). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `PICKING UP THE PIECES'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Friday on Cinemax
</P>
