<HEADER>
A5775 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-BUSH-BOS &LR;      05-25 0383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BUSH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRESH LOOK AT DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the ideas on security that George W. Bush offered Tuesday are
indicative of the coming presidential campaign, the election may be
more interesting and substantive than the pundits are predicting.
</P>
<P>
   Bush might be tantalizingly vague about some matters, but the
issues he addressed concern the gravest responsibilities of a
commander-in-chief. As Bush properly noted, there is a need to
question premises of the nation's nuclear doctrine that have
remained largely unchanged and unexamined since the sudden end of
the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   One Bush proposal on nuclear missiles that could greatly enhance
the security of Americans is his intention to ``remove as many
weapons as possible from high-alert, hair-trigger status.''
</P>
<P>
   The danger of an accidental or unauthorized missile launch could
be reduced considerably if the United States and Russia took
nuclear warheads off their missiles and stored them separately. A
sensible corollary was Bush's wish to end the launch-on-warning
posture that he called an ``unnecessary vestige of Cold War
confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   Tactfully, Bush also challenged the Pentagon's anachronistic
insistence on being able to destroy more than 2,000 outdated Soviet
targets many times over with nuclear warheads. ``The premises of
Cold War nuclear targeting should no longer dictate the size of our
arsenal,'' Bush said, justifying a reduction of this country's
strategic nuclear arsenal to the lower numbers _ 1,000 to 1,500
warheads _ that Russia would prefer in a START III treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's expressed will to deploy a grander missile defense system
than the Clinton administration is planning might seem to
contradict his aim of reducing nuclear arsenals. But the silver
lining in his remarks and those of his adviser, Condoleezza Rice,
is a willingness to explore missile defense concepts based on
boost-phase interception of missiles or laser technology. Either
might be more feasible than the current system dependent on
infrared sensors incapable of distinguishing decoys from warheads.
In this as in his other proposals, Bush displays a welcome
inclination to take a fresh look at costly and dangerous old
assumptions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 1910EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5776 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-EYE-BOS &LR;      05-25 0381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-EYE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISION ON EYE RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the last several years, US taxpayers have made impressive
investments in medical research, particularly in the quest to cure
or prevent diseases that are the biggest killers. Unfortunately,
proportionately less money has gone into other areas of research,
including diseases of the eye. While overall spending for the
National Institutes of Health has increased by 80 percent since
1985, it has risen by less than 40 percent for the National Eye
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   This is an imbalance that Americans could one day regret, as
baby-boomers approach the stage of life when age-related diseases
are more likely to seriously impair their vision or blind them
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Glaucoma, which afflicts more than 3 million Americans, takes a
particularly heavy toll among those aged 60 and over. Diabetic
retinopathy is the leading cause of blindness in people aged 25 to
74. The longer a patient lives with diabetes, which is sharply
increasing in incidence, the greater the chances this complication
will develop. Age also increases the likelihood of macular
degeneration, which afflicts fully 30 percent of all Americans over
75. There are 36.2 million Americans with eye diseases now; 45.7
million are expected to suffer from them by 2030.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, much of the progress in treating problems of
vision has come through improvements in surgery. Now, researchers
like those at Boston's Schepens Eye Research Institute expect that
many advances will come through investigation of the biochemistry
and neurobiology that make the miracle of sight possible.
</P>
<P>
   Such research consumes a large share of the National Eye
Institute's $450 million budget. An advocacy group for research in
this area, the Alliance for Eye and Vision Research, contends there
are many research projects deserving of new funding and advocates a
20 percent increase in NEI spending.
</P>
<P>
   Congress ultimately decides how to divvy up Washington's
health-research dollar, with advice from the National Institutes of
Health and others. As overall NIH spending goes up, decisionmakers
in Washington should have the foresight to make sure that vision
itself is not shortchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 1912EDT &QL; 
