<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PICKING A VICE PRESIDENT, BUSH CALLS HIMSELF AN `INDEPENDENT
THINKER' 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Faced with a new warning by a prominent
religious conservative against selecting a running mate who
supports abortion, Gov. George W. Bush on Thursday called himself a
``pretty independent thinker'' whose main criterion for choosing a
vice presidential nominee was an ability to assume the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spoke of his vice presidential search as he stood side by
side with retired Gen. Colin Powell, the Republican dream candidate
who refuses to seek elective office. Powell, prompted by reporters'
questions, repeated his desire to see the anti-abortion plank
removed from the Republican platform. And he once again insisted
that he would not be interested in being Bush's running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a candidate for the vice presidency and I'm not
seeking it,'' said the former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff. ``The governor knows that.'' But Powell left the door open
to consider a Cabinet post. ``In any other capacity one has to
listen when the president asks you to consider a job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The day's event had not been designed for talk of abortion
politics. In the garden of the governor's mansion, Bush and Powell
were signing an agreement between Texas and America's Promise, the
volunteer group that Powell leads to help the nation's youth.
</P>
<P>
   But the subsequent news conference quickly turned to the
jousting inside the Republican Party over Bush's choice of a
running mate. On Wednesday, James C. Dobson, a prominent religious
conservative, told reporters that Bush ``sounds a whole lot more
conservative when he is talking to conservatives and a whole lot
more moderate when he is talking to moderates.''
</P>
<P>
   Dobson accused Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential
nominee, of sacrificing the party's core principles and called on
him to choose a running mate opposed to abortion. ``The base in the
Republican Party is pro-life,'' he was quoted as saying. ``You
can't have it all and you can't win without that base.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked for his response, Bush did not acknowledge that he shared
Dobson's concerns, nor did he hint where his running mate would
stand on abortion. ``I appreciate advice,'' he said. ``I'm getting
it from all corners. But I'm a pretty independent thinker.''
</P>
<P>
   He insisted his political message is always consistent. ``It's
basically this: we're going to trust people, not government,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed several times on whether he was listening to either
conservatives or Republicans' who favor abortion rights, Bush
spelled out some of his criteria for selecting a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for someone who could be president, someone able
to fill that job,'' he said. ``I'm looking for someone who would be
loyal. I'm looking for someone who brings honesty and integrity to
the office, someone whose judgment I could count upon.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush repeated his position that the Republican platform's plank
against abortion should remain intact. Asked if he agreed, Powell
said: ``I would work to remove it. But good friends can disagree on
issues, so I don't see that there is a big fight over that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has been positioning himself closer to the political
center, faces a major decision on whether he can afford to select a
running mate, like Gov. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania, who backs
abortion rights. A New York Times/CBS News survey earlier this
month found that three of every 10 Republican voters polled said
they would be less likely to support Bush if he picks a running
mate who supports legalized abortion.
</P>
<P>
   As reporters tried and failed several times to draw Bush out on
how much he was weighing abortion in his choice of a running mate,
he seemed to grow impatient. ``I'm making an exhaustive search,''
he said. ``I've laid out the characteristics necessary for the vice
presidency. And at some point in time you're going to find out who
it is. And on that cheery note we will end.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Bush did flatly say, in an interview with The Associated
Press, that he was not considering either Powell or Sen. John
McCain of Arizona, taking them at their word that they did not want
the job.
</P>
</TEXT>
