<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CHINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIGHT LIGHT ON CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tucked into the dramatic House vote Wednesday to grant China
permanent normal trade relations is an amendment to establish a
23-member commission that will monitor human rights under the
communist regime in Beijing. That amendment, co-sponsored by
Democrat Sander Levin of Michigan and Republican Doug Bereuter of
Nebraska, should not be discounted as merely a face-saving favor to
members who were hesitant to cast a vote that could be used to
paint them as soft on communism or indifferent to human rights.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that the commission can exercise no leverage over the
commissars who throw citizens into jail for the crime of doing
their breathing exercises and meditation in public. Nor will it be
able to vote each year on renewing that country's
most-favored-nation status. But the vote that Congress did cast
year after year to maintain normal trade relations with China
hardly protected Chinese and Tibetans from the rulers in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there should be no illusions about what a human
rights monitoring commission can accomplish. But a sign of what its
potential might be was given by the Chinese government, which
called the commission an ``unacceptable'' attempt to ``interfere in
China's internal affairs and damage China's interests.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission, with members drawn from the House, the Senate,
and the executive branch, is to be modeled on the Helsinki
Commission, which also began with modest expectations when it was
formed in 1975 to examine human rights in the countries of the
Soviet bloc. The Helsinki accords, of course, benefitted from
treaty status and thus obligated communist governments of the
Warsaw Pact to tolerate outside monitoring of their human rights
records.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the new commission envisioned for human rights in
China might be used to assist Chinese democrats and dissidents much
as the Helsinki commission helped the Vaclav Havels and Andrei
Sakharovs behind the Iron Curtain _ by shining a bright, constant
light on their situation.
</P>
<P>
   Now that trade and human rights in China are to be decoupled,
there is more need than ever to show solidarity with the peoples of
China and Tibet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
