<HEADER>
A5785 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      05-25 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYMPATHY FOR JAPAN'S GOVERNING PARTY EBBS AFTER GAFFES FROM ITS NEW
LEADER
</HEADLINE>
  By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ When leaders of Japan's governing party met secretly
seven weeks ago to choose a successor to Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi, who was felled by a stroke, the idea was not only to ensure
a quick transition but also to perpetuate the party's long hold on
power.
</P>
<P>
   But to the growing consternation of party members, through a
series of gaffes and provocative statements the new prime minister,
Yoshiro Mori, has presided instead over a steep decline in the
government's public support, recent opinion polls indicate.
</P>
<P>
   The death of Obuchi on May 14 was once expected to give his
Liberal Democratic Party a strong sympathy vote in the
parliamentary elections scheduled for June 25. But now party
members are expecting a fight for their political lives.
</P>
<P>
   And most tellingly, in a system in which campaign money and
prestige traditionally flow from on high, the party's candidates
are playing down their connections to their embattled new leader.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of Mori's party have urged that the election be
postponed, but party leaders have resisted the idea. Hoping to
quell the dissension, Mori has announced plans for a news
conference on Friday to explain his recent remarks.
</P>
<P>
   The faux pas that has prompted the strongest reaction was a
remark Mori made last week to a Shinto religious group of lawmakers
that many felt alarmingly echoed Japan's militaristic past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan is a divine nation with the emperor at its core, and we
want the people to recognize this,'' Mori said.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister tried to quiet the tempest by saying he
supported Japan's democratic, pacifist constitution and was merely
urging more spiritual values for Japan's youth. But his failure to
retract the comment seemed to make things worse.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the week, support for Mori's Cabinet had dropped
to about 20 percent in newspaper polls, about half of what it was
after he took office.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other problems for Mori, including persistent
but unconfirmed press reports that he was arrested while
frequenting prostitutes as a college student, and that he had
improperly secured membership in an expensive private golfing club.
</P>
<P>
   Mori's chief cabinet secretary, Mikio Aoki, his schoolmate at
Waseda University, denied that Mori had been arrested, saying he
would have remembered the incident if it had been true. But Aoki,
who served in the same post under Obuchi, has been under fire
himself over his shifting explanations of the circumstances of
Obuchi's hospitalization and the secretly arranged succession.
</P>
<P>
   And on Wednesday, Mori was forced to acknowledge press reports
that he spoke at a wedding in 1995 that was attended by members of
a major Japanese crime syndicate. The prime minister said he had
not checked who would be present before accepting the invitation to
speak.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Mori has responded to the trouble, somewhat
awkwardly, by keeping out of view, or at least as quiet as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   For two weeks now, the prime minister has canceled his weekly
appearance at question time, the regular debate in parliament with
the opposition. And at a public appearance last weekend, Mori
joked, ``I will simply read what has been written for me,'' as he
pulled out a sheath of prepared remarks.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Mori, Kazuhiko Koshikawa, denied that the prime
minister was ducking question time, saying his failure to attend
was ``because of the rude way that the opposition parties treated
the prime minister during a meeting between the leader of the LDP
and leaders of the opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, the opposition has had a field day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like a child refusing to attend school,'' said Tsutomu
Hata, secretary general of the Democratic Party. ``The prime
minister should not run away from his job.''
</P>
<P>
   But from the perspective of some Liberal Democratic Party
candidates facing a tough campaign, what would be even worse would
be to have the prime minister speaking freely again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more he talks, the more our votes fly out the window,''
one of the party's candidates complained to Tokyo Shimbun. In a
headline on Wednesday, The Daily Yomiuri, another conservative
newspaper that is traditionally supportive of the Liberal
Democratic Party, said bluntly that ``one more gaffe could prove
one too many'' for Mori.
</P>
<P>
   With anxieties over the elections running high, few governing
party politicians were willing to speak about Mori this week,
either in criticism or in his defense.
</P>
<P>
   But one legislator, Yoshihide Suga, said the new prime
minister's ``divine country'' comment had given the opposition
``real momentum'' going into the elections and sewn fear in the
hearts of governing party members.
</P>
<P>
   ``LDP people have begun taking down posters with Mori on them,''
Suga said. ``At this rate, soon you won't find any posters with
Mori's picture on them in urban areas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
