A5791 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-TEETH-NYT &LR;      05-25 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-TEETH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURGEON GENERAL WARNS OF PERILS OF ORAL DISEASES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Texas, N.Y., Calif., Ore.)   By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Oral diseases, from tooth decay to mouth cancer,
threaten the health of poor people, minorities, children and the
elderly, despite vast improvements in dental care over the past 50
years, according to a study made public by the surgeon general
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The report, the first comprehensive review of the scientific
literature on oral health, found that most Americans who are
middle-aged or younger can expect to keep their teeth for life,
largely because fluoride in the drinking water is helping to
prevent cavities.
</P>
<P>
   But the study also documented profound and little-noticed
disparities in care that, it said, amounted to ''a silent epidemic
of oral diseases'' among the nation's most vulnerable people.
</P>
<P>
   Socioeconomics, inadequate education, poor overall health and
lack of access to care all play a part. While an estimated 44
million Americans lack health insurance, more than 108 million lack
dental insurance. Many children in poor neighborhoods never see a
dentist, the study found, and elderly people often lose dental
insurance when they retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had a tendency to separate oral health from the rest
of the body,'' said Dr. David Satcher, the surgeon general, in an
interview after releasing the study.
</P>
<P>
   Black men, the study found, have the highest rate of pharyngeal
cancers in the United States, and are less likely to survive than
whites. The percentage of people who had untreated dental cavities
was substantially higher among blacks than whites _ about twice as
many, according to the report. African Americans are more likely
than whites to have missing teeth, and also more likely to have gum
disease, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   The disparities were particularly great among children. The
study found that more than one-third of all poor youngsters from
ages 2 to 9 had untreated cavities, compared with 17 percent of
children who were not poor.
</P>
<P>
   And even children with health insurance often lack proper care;
a recent study, cited in the surgeon general's report, found that
among children covered by Medicaid, the government insurance
program for the poor, fewer than one in five had a preventive
dental visit during the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   To dentists who care for the poor, the findings were hardly a
surprise. With a grant from the Kellogg Foundation, a nonprofit
group, Dr. Allan Formicola, dean of the school of dentistry and
oral surgery at Columbia University in Manhattan, has arranged for
dental services at six middle schools in Harlem, Washington Heights
and Inwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing about double the rate of dental emergencies,
teeth that either need to be extracted or have root canal'' as the
national average, Formicola said. ``These are kids that are sitting
in class with toothaches. This is a problem, and it's neglected.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the study highlighted surprising links between
oral health and general well-being. Scientists, the report said,
are beginning to document associations between chronic oral
infection and diabetes, heart disease, stroke and even babies with
low birth weights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mouth can serve as an early warning system,'' the report
said, signaling trouble elsewhere in the body. Thrush, a yeast
infection in the mouth, is often a sign of infection with the virus
that causes AIDS. Joint disorders in the jaw might be a sign of
osteoporosis. ``The mouth,'' Satcher said, ``is a mirror for many
diseases that affect the body.''
</P>
<P>
   That point has often been lost on the public, including medical
professionals, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The surgeon general's report is very important, because it not
only looks at things like decay, and what groups are still
suffering disproportionately, but it also connects up the problems
between oral health and general health,'' Formicola said.
</P>
<P>
   Others said the study was long overdue. ``We're the stepchild of
health care in the United States,'' said Robert Klaus, president of
Oral Health America, a nonprofit organization founded by dentists'
professional groups.
</P>
<P>
   Fluoridated drinking water, which helps prevent cavities, is one
of the great public health achievements of the 20th century,
Satcher's report said. Yet the study found that fluoridated water
reaches only 62 percent of Americans served by public water
supplies. Seven of the nation's 50 largest cities, including San
Diego, San Antonio and Portland, Ore., do not have fluoridated
water.
</P>
<P>
   The 309-page report took three years to prepare, and Satcher
unveiled it Thursday before a group of 24 first-graders at the
Shepherd Elementary School here. The children are learning about
oral health, under the auspices of a government-sponsored pilot
program.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Satcher said the session was an eye-opener for him;
as the child of uneducated farmers in rural Alabama, he did not see
a dentist until just before he went away to college. ``There are
still too many families like that in this country,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
