<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woman has slurs carved on her body
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAPEVILLE, Ga. _ The chief of police is calling it one of the
most bizarre crimes his town of 6,500 people has seen in decades.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime after midnight Thursday a Hapeville woman was bound,
gagged and raped in the apartment she shares with her boyfriend.
But that wasn't enough, said Hapeville Police Chief Ed Attaway. The
assailant carved a racial slur across the woman's stomach with a
box cutter.
</P>
<P>
   When it was all over, he slung the woman over his shoulder,
walked three blocks and dropped her off at a club used for
Alcoholics Anonymous meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Police believe the woman, who is white, used either her nose or
her chin to dial 911 and lead authorities to the address where she
was found just after 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like this in Hapeville,'' Attaway
said Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Allen Herd said officers visited the woman the day before
the attack because she reported receiving threatening telephone
calls. When police arrived at her apartment just after 3 p.m. she
also found a note taped to her door.
</P>
<P>
   ``The note was of a threatening nature,'' Herd said. ``But I
recall seeing the words 'I love you' in there.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest questions lingering in investigators' minds
is why the assailant risked walking three blocks from the victim's
apartment on King Arnold Street to the Tara Club on North Central
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said it would have been difficult for someone to carry
the woman three blocks without being seen.
</P>
<P>
   It's likely the woman knows her attacker, police said. When they
arrived at the club, the attacker grabbed the woman's key chain and
selected the key to the club's door. He also took great pains to
hide his identity, donning a ski mask , gloves and a long-sleeved
turtle-neck pullover.
</P>
<P>
   The woman's boyfriend, who is black, and her ex-husband, who is
white, have been questioned. Both have been ruled out as suspects
for now.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
