<SLUG> BC-CONSECO-NORRIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: STEVE HILBERT MADE $172 MILLION _ AND RAN OUT OF CASH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.)   By FLOYD NORRIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Say this for Stephen Hilbert, the master salesman who built
Conseco Inc. into a giant insurance company even as critics
dismissed it as a house of paper sure to collapse some day: He
believed his own sales pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Hilbert was paid $119 million, not counting stock options, in
the 1990s, and $53 million more when he was ousted last month. But
both he and Conseco are now scrambling for liquidity as lenders
grow nervous.
</P>
<P>
   The depth of Hilbert's problems became clear when Conseco
reported that he had faced huge margin calls on his stock _ enough
to force him to take out an emergency $23 million loan from the
company before he got his severance check. Those margin loans are
in addition to the $181 million he owes on other loans, either to
Conseco or to banks on loans that Conseco guaranteed. The stock he
owns is now worth just $43 million.
</P>
<P>
   How does one man make $172 million and wind up owing far more
than that? A lavish lifestyle _ including renting a jumbo jet to
fly guests to a party on St. Martin for his sixth wife's 30th
birthday _ is only part of the answer. His debt is from buying
Conseco stock with borrowed money.
</P>
<P>
   Hilbert, now 54, built Conseco, based in Carmel, Ind., from a
tiny company to a member of the Fortune 500 through acquisitions. A
onetime encyclopedia salesman, he became a very prominent man in
Indiana, where the Indiana Pacers play at the Conseco Fieldhouse
and the Indianapolis Symphony performs at the Hilbert Circle
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Hilbert became a hero on Wall Street, too, praised for his skill
at cutting costs and delivering profits. ``We have not missed one
quarterly earnings number or one revenue target,'' he boasted last
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way there were complaints that he accomplished that
with misleading accounting. Four times _ in 1987, 1989-90, 1991-92
and 1994-95 _ the stock lost more than a third of its value,
usually as short-sellers ganged up. But each time Conseco
rebounded. From going public in 1985 through its 1998 peak, Conseco
rose at a compounded annual rate of 47 percent. Since the top, it
is down 91 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the short-sellers were again blasting Conseco, and
Hilbert saw opportunity after the stock price had been cut in half.
He borrowed $55 million to buy shares that are now worth $13
million.
</P>
<P>
   Why did the price fall so far? The last acquisitions, of health
care insurers and of Green Tree Financial, a company that finances
mobile home purchases, now appear to have been overpriced if not
completely foolish. Health insurance profits have plunged, and
Conseco is trying to sell the finance company for a fraction of
what it paid.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Conseco appears to be desperate for cash. In the first
quarter, it gave Lehman Brothers a 5 percent stake in the finance
company just for buying some assets for what Conseco's books said
they were worth. Conseco says it will have no trouble meeting its
obligations, which include $1.5 billion in debt that comes due this
year.
</P>
<P>
   There is no cause for alarm if you believe Conseco's books, but
confidence in those numbers has fallen just when banks are becoming
more cautious in their lending. Conseco needs to sell the finance
operations quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Conseco will probably survive. But its problems are real, and it
is hard to see how the stock can recover enough to salvage the
finances of Hilbert, a salesman who bought when he should have
sold. Don't tell that to Hilbert, however. ``I still,'' he said
Thursday, ``have tremendous faith in the people and operations of
Conseco.''
</P>
</TEXT>
