<SLUG> BC-MIDSTREAM-COLUMN-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDSTREAM COLUMN: A SOUND SLEEP AND A GOOD RETURN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, N.J., N.Y.)  (For release Sun., May 28) 
 By JAMES SCHEMBARI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   My parents have long told me their stories of growing up during
the Great Depression. I heard how my dad delivered groceries for a
dollar a week and how his family ate meat once a week with the
leftovers stretched, thinner and thinner, into the next few meals.
</P>
<P>
   For my father, James, 76, especially, the Great Depression has
had a lasting effect. He's eating much better now, but he refuses
to put his money into any investment where he isn't guaranteed to
get his principal back.
</P>
<P>
   He's not stuffing money into mattresses, but his insistence on
safety has meant he has sat out the bull market. Several of them,
actually. My lectures on the dangers of inflation and the
historical return of the stock market have not had as much effect
on him as those sparse chicken dinners. He puts his money almost
exclusively in certificates of deposit and savings bonds, and
that's that. The man will just not listen to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad,'' I say, ``don't put all your money into CDs. Diversify.
Try some mutual funds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Too risky,'' he says. ``I wouldn't be able to sleep at
night.''
</P>
<P>
   The sleep indicator is as important to my father's generation as
the GDP is to mine. We get frustrated seeing our parents' life
savings invested at 6 percent, but they expect to sleep very
soundly when it comes to their money. Although our parents are very
fond of us, often those feelings don't run deep enough to take
investment advice from their reckless children.
</P>
<P>
   Giovanni S. Testa, 43, of Livingston, N.J., said he has tried
for years to get his father, Marino, 75, also of Livingston, to
invest more wisely, but to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   ``With stocks, my father thinks he'll lose all of it,'' he said.
``I try to explain risk to him, but he didn't understand it.
Forgetaboutit. It was like talking to a wall, talking to my
father.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nemec, 54, of Hinckley, Ohio, never could get through to
his father, but he understood why.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tended to be quite nearsighted and ultraconservative,''
Nemec said. ``Let's face it, when a man has gone through the
Depression and World War II and then lived in a nice suburb, he
gets very comfortable with his station in life. My father was a
blue-collar worker and money came hard. He didn't want to take a
chance on losing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nemec's father died in 1992, and his mother, Lillian, 79, was
more open to change. He had her meet with his planner, Paul Hrisko.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big change for her and she asked an awful lot of
questions,'' said Hrisko, a certified financial planner who owns
Paul Hrisko &AMP; Associates in Cleveland Heights, Ohio. ``Is it safe?
Is it guaranteed? What are my chances of losing my money? It didn't
take one meeting. I had to come back several times. She was a bit
nervous. The more I discussed it with her, the more she was willing
to take the next step to a more aggressive portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   Hrisko said children must explain the investments, and their
risks, fully and clearly. Children should also help their parents
clarify their goals, which will determine how much risk is
acceptable: is the money for them, their children or their
grandchildren? The key, Hrisko said, is that the parent must trust
the child.
</P>
<P>
   The senior Testa moved slowly into mutual funds after his son
persuaded him to see an investment adviser and he saw how
diversification could keep his risk low but increase his return.
Gail Rosen, 41, of Martinsville, N.Y., talked to her father for
years about leaving savings bonds behind. He resisted at first, but
he trusted her enough to move some money into mutual funds. Now
he's hooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad has a computer and watches his funds online,'' said
Rosen, an accountant. ``Now he tells me how I'm doing on my
investments. He's so addicted that my mother hates it that he's on
the computer all the time. Like some wives lose their husbands to
golf, she's lost him to the computer.''
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Irving Horowitz, 72, of Monroe Township, N.J., said
he changed after his daughter showed him how much money he was
losing to inflation and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's an accountant, so I listened,'' he said, eventually
moving money into funds and individual stocks. ``Since I retired, I
have made a hobby of it.''
</P>
<P>
   My father's hobby is his garden. And keeping his principal safe.
I know his greatest concern is not for his children or his
grandchildren, but for my mother, Mary. He wants to leave her
secure and comfortable if anything happens to him. If his principal
is safe, he knows she will be, too.
</P>
<P>
   He could have a better strategy, but that's not a bad one. It's
a heartfelt plan that this son is going to stop arguing with.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
