<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5798 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ABOUT-CARS-TAHOE-ART-     05-25 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-TAHOE-ART-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEVY TAHOE BIG ENOUGH FOR A TREK TO TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 28) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By LEONARD M. APCAR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Five years ago, when General Motors ran
its huge Suburban through a buzzsaw, cutting a 20-inch slice from
its length, it created the Chevrolet Tahoe and the GMC Yukon:
shorter, more manageable sport utilities with major V-8 power that
could seat up to six people and practically tow a mountain.
</P>
<P>
   What the new sport utilities lacked was a third row of seats,
like the one in the Suburban, and the bright lights at Ford and
Dodge didn't let GM forget it. In a year, Ford brought out the
Expedition, with three rows, and a year later Dodge crammed a third
bench into its slightly smaller Durango.
</P>
<P>
   Now the big news in this part of the market is that GM has not
only put a third seat in its Tahoes and Yukons, but it split the
third bench in half so that each part can fold neatly out of the
way for cargo.
</P>
<P>
   Big deal, you say? Well, the geniuses at Ford and Dodge didn't
think of it, minivans don't have it, and if you don't see the
advantages of this, then you didn't just drive more than 1,300
miles on a family vacation with four, sometimes five people, and
six, sometimes eight, bags.
</P>
<P>
   I did so in a Tahoe and I would do it again. We folded up one of
the far back seats and loaded three big pieces of luggage in its
place. Then we stashed three smaller pieces behind the remaining
seat, which my 11-year-old son used at his base camp. My
10-year-old daughter settled into her own perch in a window seat in
the middle row, and my wife and I commandeered the front buckets.
</P>
<P>
   We picked up grandma and her two small bags for one leg of the
trip (5 hours, 300 miles), and when the bags were unloaded we put
the rear seat in its full, upright, locked postion and comfortably
carried seven, including four adults, on a day trip.
</P>
<P>
   We spent out vacation in Texas, where full-sized sport utilities
are about as common as taxicabs in Manhattan. The neatly packed
dark-gray Tahoe caught the attention of several bystanders at gas
stations (it did tend to guzzle the stuff) and in hotel parking
lots. The onlookers marveled at the convenience of the back seat
and how much we had stuffed around it. They also gulped at the
sticker, which exceeded $41,000, including $760 for the optional
third seat, on the well equipped test truck.
</P>
<P>
   The full-sized sport utility market just keeps growing. Never
mind these vehicles' voracious appetite _ I averaged about 14.8
miles per gallon over all, in both city and highway driving _ and
their less than pristine record on emissions. People like them
because they increasingly seem like minivans on the inside while
looking downright unstoppable on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   The interiors of the Tahoe and the Yukon have both grown more
comfortable. The top of the line LT and SLT, respectively, have all
the usual power this and leather that. An Autoride feature,
standard on the Yukon and optional on the Tahoe, automatically
adjusts the ride with the load. Cup holders abound and
air-conditioning, available with separate controls for the rear
passengers, includes vents in the ceiling. Outside a Dairy Queen in
Salado, with the thermometer display on the rear-view mirror
registering 102 degrees outside, nobody in the back complained that
they lacked cool air.
</P>
<P>
   The trick to making the third seat convenient is making it easy
to get to. The Durango's middle seats are split in a 40-20-40
proportion; the outer portions fold out of the way to allow access
from either side.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and GM use an 80-20 configuration that allows entry only
from the right. The Tahoe seat easily lifts and folds better than
that of the Expedition, which requires tilting a heavy seat out of
the way. I also thought the Expedition's passageway was tight.
</P>
<P>
   Look for the seating competition to heat up, too, when Ford adds
a third row to its next-generation Explorer and Toyota brings out
its full-sized Sequoia in the fall. That truck's second and third
seats are ingenuously designed for easy tilting and removal, and
caused a stir among executives from competing companies when the
Sequoia was shown at the Detroit auto show in January.
</P>
<P>
   Once you're in the back 40 of the Tahoe, though, the seat is not
exactly a box at the Met. Ford and Chevy both angle the seatback to
allow greater headroom. This can be disconcerting at first. (Dodge
raised the Durango's rear roofline.) And all three manufacturers
have seating for three people including two positions with shoulder
straps. They have also raised the seat up a bit to give greater
visibility. GM has two adjustable headrests back there; the Durango
has two fixed ones and the Expedition has none. Only the Expedition
can be ordered with rear windows that pop out to serve as vents.
</P>
<P>
   Adults would not want to sit in the rear for long. My son, who
is just over 5 feet tall, thought it was great. But he also kept
the seat in front of him folded down to stretch out on long drives.
</P>
<P>
   The redesigned Tahoe and Yukon, which are virtually identical
under the skin, use essentially the same new frame that underpins
the redesigned Suburban, the GMC Yukon XL (formerly known as the
GMC Suburban) and the full-size GM pickups. By virtue of its fewer
welds and stress points, the ride is quieter, smoother and more
car-like.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, the Tahoe is also easier to drive, partly because the
entire feel of the truck is softer and more welcoming. The turning
radius is considerably smaller, making maneuvers in parking lots
more realistic.
</P>
<P>
   Gripes were few. I don't like the power seat adjustments on the
sides of the seat. Also, the ceiling light in the rear hardly
illuminated the cargo area. Dodge smartly puts its lamp in the
hatchback and lights the entire loading area. The GM hatch, though,
is made mostly of aluminum which makes it light and easy to shut.
</P>
<P>
   GM's trim and finish quality stills gives me pause. During out
trip, one air vent fell out of the ceiling when one of our children
fiddled with it; the louvers on another came apart, and a piece of
seat trim repeatedly fell off. Both the Tahoe and the Yukon had an
occasional squeak coming from the padding around the steering
column.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, though, these were modest flaws in a much-improved
family truck.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
