<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5800 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SPOLETO26-COX     05-25 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOLETO26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As flag flap eases, excitement and ticket sales rise leading
into mega arts event
 &HT;    By Tom Sabulis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ In the hours leading up to today's opening of
the 24th Spoleto Festival USA, things are beginning to return to
normal.
</P>
<P>
   French aerialists are swinging from the live oak trees in
Washington Park. The set for Bertolt Brecht's ``Mother Courage and
Her Children'' has fallen on the show's technical director and
broken his kneecap. The opera singers are complaining about their
costumes, but even these protests are milder than expected, given
the emotional constitution of divas.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, they are acting very unoperatically,'' says
Nunally Kersh, the festival's 34-year-old producer, charmed by her
good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   As if on cue, ticket sales are also bouncing back for the
Southeast's largest multidisciplinary arts event, a $6.2 million
cultural hurricane that will produce 125 performances of 40 events
over the next 17 days.
</P>
<P>
   The upbeat box office is a tad surprising. As recently as last
weekend, sales were down 10 percent from last year's recordbreaking
pace, partly due to the NAACP tourism boycott of the state prompted
by the Confederate flag controversy. But things picked up earlier
this week, shortly before South Carolina Gov. Jim Hodges signed
legislation Tuesday that will remove the flag, which many regard as
a racist symbol, from the Statehouse in Columbia on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday, the festival had experienced a few ``very good
days'' _ meaning sales in excess of $25,000 per day. General
director Nigel Redden says sales were 30 percent to 40 percent
higher Monday and Tuesday over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tickets have taken off, and it's high time,'' Redden says.
``It's not simply the resolution of the flag issue, although that
has been a weight on us. It's also that every year has its own
rhythm, and this year they (ticket sales) are late.''
</P>
<P>
   Politics has only added to the hectic atmosphere leading up to
the festival, which has been known to draw 60,000 people, according
to Spoleto spokeswoman Marie Lawson, though Chamber of Commerce
estimates are higher. Three acts have canceled to honor the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People's
boycott, which is still in effect, in protest of the decision to
move the flag to a Confederate memorial site near the Capitol. In
the latest change, boycotting singer Dianne Reeves has been
replaced by another jazz act, the Marcus Roberts Trio (June 3 at
the Cistern).
</P>
<P>
   For many of the performers warming up in this sweltering city's
intimate, brick-lined downtown Wednesday and Thursday, the flag
issue wasn't an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's moved beyond it,'' Redden says, driving to a
series of rehearsals and interviews, talking over the annoying
ping-ping of his borrowed car's warning system. On these short
trips, Redden refuses to wear his seat belt. What could be a more
appropriate metaphor for the man who runs this sometimes
seat-of-the-pants event?
</P>
<P>
   Members of the French circus Les Colporteurs certainly have
other things on their minds than flags. In one of the city's
pocket-size parks, they've strung a network of cables, balancing
wires and rope swings in the overhanging trees and are rehearsing
their aerial artistry for today's opening-ceremony performance at
noon.
</P>
<P>
   Making its Spoleto debut, the circus is in town to perform
``Filao,'' based on the Italo Calvino novel ``The Baron in the
Trees,'' under a big tent in Cannon Park. Today, however, it will
take advantage of Charleston's arboreal splendor to create a
special opening-day treat in Washington Park, not far from City
Hall, where official ceremonies take place. When Redden arrives to
check out the progress, he's immediately swept into conference with
Kersh, who has been talking in fluent French about ``liability
issues'' with circus bosses.
</P>
<P>
   Along with curious residents and tourists, Deirdre Valente, the
circus's American producer, stands nearby and surveys this surreal
scene, as performers hang upside down from tree branches and loll
on rope swings while officials talk fine-print contract minutiae on
the ground below.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charleston is so hospitable about all this,'' says the New
York-based Valente. ``This is much closer to what happens in
Europe, artists living and working in your midst all the time.'' If
not swinging in your historic trees.
</P>
<P>
   Valente, 40, says she discussed the flag issue with the circus
early on and recommended they perform at the festival. ``Spoleto is
a shining example of what diversity is all about. It doesn't
further anyone's cause by picking on Spoleto.''
</P>
<P>
   Next stop, the Garden Theatre, for the final dress rehearsal of
``The Silver River,'' a fusion-opera melding Eastern and Western
music, dance and mythology, which also features a working waterfall
that runs downstage into a wading pool. Standing at the back of the
theater, dressed in wrinkled white T-shirt and khakis, David Henry
Hwang, the Tony winner (``M. Butterfly'') who wrote the ``Silver
River'' libretto, turns slightly philosophical about his first
Spoleto experience. ``It's been a little complicated,'' Hwang says.
``Everyone has had to work out the flag issue in their own way.
Otherwise it's very pleasant. It's the only place I've ever worked
where everyone in my company is happy with where they're staying.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the strangest sight at Spoleto this year is Middleton
Place, the 18th-century plantation some 15 miles out of town, where
sculptor Joel Shapiro has erected more than a dozen of his bronze
sticklike creations on the greensward leading into the grounds.
These minamalist forms stretch and run and dance across the open
space, charging the country-estate atmosphere with an urban
kineticism. That is, until you spot the plantation's herd of sheep
grazing around them.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting nearby, on a work break, tour guide Joann Kautz gazes at
this field of beams. What does she think of the sculpture? ``Not
much,'' she says. ``It doesn't really fit in with the rest of the
grounds. But it's interesting to see the sheep out there. Our poor
cow came out this morning and mooed all the way through.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : Visit the Spoleto Festival online:
www.spoletousa.org/
</P>
<P>
   Spoleto Festival USA
</P>
<P>
   Through June 11 at various locations throughout downtown
Charleston, S.C. For information or tickets: 877-386-7765 or
www.spoletousa.org.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Sabulis writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
