<HEADER>
A5802 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ON-THE-JOB-$ADV28-NYT     05-25 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-THE-JOB-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVENTURES IN COMMUTING: TALES OF FLYING CARS AND TREES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 28) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like most things in life, commuting is in the eye of the
beholder. Most of the time, it's an obligation, a habit, no more
than a repetitive journey from home to workplace and back again.
But once in a while, commuting becomes high adventure, a source of
laughter and the stuff of lasting memories.
</P>
<P>
   One day, my commuter train struck a car carrier, which had
bottomed out on a grade crossing,'' writes David Katz, a geneticist
who lives in Evanston, Ill. ``No one was injured, and the sight of
a flying Acura was memorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the rest of the day, when asked by co-workers how I was
doing, I opined that I felt like I had been in a train wreck. No
one seemed to believe that I really had been in a train wreck. It
was April 1.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the day after a hurricane had left much debris on the
road,'' writes Dianne Olsen, recalling a morning when she was
commuting in her tough old Saab through Westchester County, from
her home in Pleasantville to her job as a marketing coordinator in
Ossining. ``A pile of what I thought were twigs appeared in front
of me,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it wasn't twigs. It was a big ol' tree branch, and it
poked itself right through the front of my car,'' said Olsen, who
has since moved to Poughkeepsie, N.Y. ``I pulled off the road at
the first opportunity and was so happy. The branch wasn't sticking
into my radiator, just wedged beneath the headlight assembly. But I
couldn't pull it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I drove the next mile to work, intending to call a garage
and bring my car in for repair. People in the office kept remarking
(I couldn't make this stuff up), `Did you know you have a tree
branch sticking out of your car?' It happened so often that I
finally told everyone: `Yes, and can you believe it? That tree just
ran right out of the forest and attacked my car. I never saw it
coming.'''
</P>
<P>
   During his years as a human resources executive in New York
City, Ronald J. Rakowski, who lived in northern Fairfield County,
Conn., sometimes commuted on the lightly traveled branch line to
Danbury, which was near his home.
</P>
<P>
   One snowy Friday night, ``the Danbury-bound train was struggling
as it left the main New Haven line _ more than an hour late _ and
headed north,'' Rakowski writes. ``Hearing that the train had lost
one of its engines and that the remainder of the trip would be very
slow, I headed for the bar car for a libation and a snack or two to
soothe my growing hunger pangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the regulars seemed to have enjoyed more than his share
and was slumped against the bar with his head nestled comfortably
atop his folded arms.''
</P>
<P>
   From time to time, when the train halted to let passengers off,
the snoozing regular would demand to know the name of the stop,
then return his head to the comfort of his arms. At Branchville, he
asked the usual question, and after being told, settled back in
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately,'' writes Rakowski, ``there's an incline between
the Branchville and Redding stations that the underpowered train
couldn't conquer. So it slowly backed down to the station we had
just left and jerked to a stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in the car shouted, ``Branchville!''
</P>
<P>
   The regular looked up, squinted and said, ``We must be going
around in circles.'' Then he returned to his rest.
</P>
<P>
   The engineer tried the Branchville-Redding incline again, the
climb made harder by the icy conditions, and once more the train
slipped back. All eyes were on the regular as the train halted at
the same station for the third time. He lifted his head and asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Branchville,'' came the reply.
</P>
<P>
   He blinked, straightened up and grabbed his briefcase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, thanks,'' he said as he staggered off. ``This is my
stop.''
</P>
<P>
   One morning last fall, on the way to her job as an occupational
therapist at the Little Rock Veterans Administration Medical
Center, Sarah Smith was driving along a rural road adjacent to the
Arkansas River when a doe tried to soar over the roof of her car.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't make it, and as I jumped out to see if I could help
her, I locked my keys in the ignition with the engine still
running,'' Smith writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next oncoming vehicle stopped to offer assistance, and the
first thing I could stammer was, `Do you have a gun?' Now, I was
thinking of putting the doe out of her agony, but the driver raised
his eyebrows, looked scared and jumped back in his truck and went
to call the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``The SWAT team _ one officer _ arrived with sunglasses and a
rifle (at 7 a.m.), shot the deer, and since I had no need of the
meat, had me wait in the patrol car while he called for backup to
pick up the carcass and bring a tool to open my locked door.
</P>
<P>
   The wait was spent looking over the officer's shoulder as he
used the on-board computer to solicit recipes for venison. I saw
venison chili, crockpot venison, venison sausage and deer kabobs
offered for the latest road kill.
</P>
<P>
   The officer kindly called my office, but as usual the
communication was garbled, and by the time I arrived, only two
hours late, my colleagues had me crashed and dead by gunfire or
animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the last word on commuting should be left to Ralph
Slovenko, a professor of law and psychiatry at Wayne State
University in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Butcher, a member of the British Parliament, has come up
with an interesting proposal,'' he writes. ``He has urged his
government to allow jugglers and acrobats to perform on the
highways to soothe the jangled nerves of motorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``With traffic moving so slowly, there's hardly the possibility
that an acrobat could be killed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
