<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-POWELL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH HOLDS HIGH-PROFILE MEETINGS WITH POWELL, AFRICAN LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PEGGY FIKAC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It was part photo opportunity, part political
speculation, and hard-enough work as far as creating a presidential
candidate's event goes.
</P>
<P>
   When Texas Gov. George W. Bush had back-to-back meetings at the
Governor's Mansion Thursday with South African President Thabo
Mbeki and retired Gen. Colin Powell, carefully-placed flags were
strategically taped to their poles to avoid the prospect of
flapping in a dignitary's face.
</P>
<P>
   Children were brought in as a backdrop for the press conference
with Powell; high-ranking state officials were placed in
high-profile spots; and little red wagons carefully arranged to
signify Powell's crusade for youth.
</P>
<P>
   The comments from Bush and Mbeki, who were accompanied by their
wives and corralled by a velvet rope as they spoke, lasted less
than two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, I said if all goes well, I look forward to working
with him. I'm not trying to drag him into U.S. politics. And he
said, `I don't want to be drug in,''' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Powell expressed hope that his appearance with Bush would
showcase their dedication to children, while reporters asked mainly
about presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   Bush signed an agreement touted nationally by Powell, called the
Governor's Promise Partnership, to continue promoting volunteer
efforts to boost young people's character and confidence.
</P>
<P>
   The two were accompanied by Bush's wife, Laura, and backed by
elementary-school children.
</P>
<P>
   Texas nearly three years ago was the first state to have a rally
to kick off the effort to help youth, Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   He cited advancements since then, including 27 Texas
``Communities of Promise'' that he said bring together volunteers
and leaders to help youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a great partner in the great state of Texas,'' Bush
told Powell, the former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he would like the meeting to convey, Powell said,
``What I would like this picture to say is that these two concerned
Americans have a commitment to young people.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also made clear, ``I stand with this man. I support him
for president.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell said does not want to be considered as a potential
running mate for Bush, the presumptive Republican nominee. But
there is speculation he would have a place in a Bush
administration. The two have met three times in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   As the youngsters from nearby St. Martin's Lutheran School
watched, Bush was asked whether he might alienate his conservative,
anti-abortion supporters if he reaches out to those who are
pro-choice Republicans such as Powell.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has said reasonable people can disagree on
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing people are going to learn about me is I'm going to
make my decisions based upon what I think is right for America. I'm
going to base my decisions ... upon the principles that I think are
right for this country,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident I can unite the party and lead us to victory,
but more important, lead America to a better tomorrow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the role that Powell might play in his campaign and
potential administration, Bush said that Powell is a friend whose
advice he values.
</P>
<P>
   If one is asked to consider a job by the president, Powell
added, one must listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not looking for a job right now, but obviously I will do
what I can to assist the governor with advice and with friendship.
And in due course we can talk about whether or not there might a
role for me,'' Powell said, who headed the Joint Chiefs of Staff in
the presidency of the governor's father, George Bush.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
