<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-PARTY-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKELIHOOD OF BUCHANAN CANDIDACY RATTLES REFORM PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Calif., Wis., Ariz., Tenn., Col., Ga.)   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ The last time Reform Party leaders met, three
months ago in Nashville, tensions rose to such an extreme that two
women wrestled over control of a microphone, and the police were
summoned to prevent the rowdiness from growing worse.
</P>
<P>
   Now party leaders are fighting over much more than a microphone.
</P>
<P>
   The growing likelihood that Pat Buchanan, the conservative
television commentator and former Republican, will secure the
Reform Party's presidential nomination and the $12.5 million in
federal campaign money that goes along with it has created another
element of conflict within the loosely organized and often chaotic
party.
</P>
<P>
   Some Reform leaders are so worried that Buchanan and his
delegates will take over the party and force it to adopt a
conservative platform on abortion and other issues that they are
collecting signatures to draft the party's founder, Ross Perot, for
a third consecutive campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Another group opposed to Buchanan, led by the party's national
secretary, is quietly negotiating to have the Green Party
candidate, Ralph Nader, run for the Reform Party nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Still other party members are urging the leadership to endorse
no presidential candidate this year, rather than Buchanan, and to
turn efforts to building the party from the ground up by fielding
candidates in state, city and local campaigns. Moreover, Reform
Party leaders in at least two states, Colorado and Georgia, have
condemned Buchanan for some of his views and tactics and have
demanded he resign from the party.
</P>
<P>
   While it seems doubtful that the dissidents can prevent
Buchanan's nomination, the discord could complicate the nominating
process, making it less likely that the party's convention in Long
Beach, Calif., in August will end on a note of unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're unconventional, to say the least,'' said Gerald R. Moan,
a Tucson businessman who became party chairman just three weeks
ago. Moan replaced Pat Choate, Perot's 1996 running mate and a
close friend of Buchanan's. Choate had won the job at the chaotic
party meeting in Nashville but resigned because of an illness in
his family.
</P>
<P>
   For such a swirl of activity against him, Buchanan does not seem
especially concerned. ``He'd prefer that things not be this way,''
said Bay Buchanan, his sister and campaign manager. ``But we're
staying focused on what we're doing, trying to stay out of the
fray. It's really no different than any other party. People are
very unhappy when they don't get their candidate in the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's ascendancy in the Reform Party has largely come
through the graces of Perot, who has always encouraged disaffected
Republicans and Democrats to join the cause. In recent years, few
Republicans grew as disaffected as Buchanan, and by last year, as
Perot withdrew from public view, he made it clear that Buchanan
would be welcome in the party.
</P>
<P>
   For Buchanan, who spent years clashing with the Republican Party
leadership, that was the opening he needed, both for an
unobstructed path to the presidential general election, and for the
mantle as leader of a political party. And by winning 5 percent of
the vote Buchanan would ensure the party federal campaign money for
2004.
</P>
<P>
   But Perot and Buchanan have not talked in two years, according
to Bay Buchanan, although Russell J. Verney, a former party
chairman who remains close to Perot, said it had been closer to
five years.
</P>
<P>
   After Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota resigned from the party in
February, and Donald J. Trump, the New York real estate developer,
dropped out of the Reform Party presidential race _ each angrily
citing Buchanan's influence _ a vacuum was left in party
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to fill it, Buchanan has wooed delegates, placed
supporters in Reform Party state leadership positions and offered
his America-first, socially conservative views as a credible
alternative to the major party candidates, Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   To win the Reform Party nomination, a candidate needs a majority
of the votes of members who have either requested a ballot from the
party, registered as a party member in a state where the party is
recognized or signed a petition supporting a party candidate in a
state that has not recognized the party. Ballots can be cast in
person, by mail, phone or by the Internet from July 4 to the start
of the convention. But if two-thirds of the convention delegates
disagree with the popular choice, they can vote to overturn the
selection and pick another candidate.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For now, Buchanan appears unstoppable. With no viable
challengers, he is well on his way to securing the delegate support
he needs to assure the Reform Party nomination, and, as the rules
permit, to allow him as the nominee to rewrite the party platform
to include his positions on social issues _ a possibility, his
sister said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Based on Perot's showing in the 1996 election, the Reform Party
will automatically be recognized on the ballot in 20 states in
November; in addition, Buchanan has gathered enough signatures to
get the party on the ballot in at least more five states, and
expects to collect enough signatures to get the party or the
candidate on the ballot in all 50 states by the final state filing
deadline, which is Sept. 5 in Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   So much momentum by a single campaign might be expected to unite
a party starved for respect and credibility. But as Buchanan forges
ahead, so do his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plenty of the old-timers are still here, and they are very
concerned about Pat Buchanan,'' said Ira Goodman, the New Jersey
party chairman who is leading the effort to draft Perot. ``Our goal
is to go into the primary with an alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Goodman insisted that support among party members for Perot is
widespread. But drawing him back into a potentially loud and
contentious primary fight would seem a rather daunting challenge
for now. Perot has withdrawn from the political arena, a sign to
some that he is either disinterested in the current state of
affairs or disgusted by them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has not even asked to speak at the convention,'' said Moan,
the party chairman, who takes that to mean he will not attend. ``If
he comes, he'll speak. But if he doesn't come, that could be
interpreted as a rebuke to Buchanan.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Verney said he does not know what Perot will do, an assertion
that appears to leave open the possibility Perot may indeed be a
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't rule it out,'' Verney said, which was the same
response he offered six months ago. Only now, time is a factor, and
to qualify as a presidential candidate under the party's rules,
Perot would have to notify the leadership by July 1 that he intends
to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not launched a full-fledged campaign to be the next
president,'' Verney said of Perot, who has not granted an interview
in some time. ``But he hasn't ruled it out. If the members feel he
would be the best person to represent the principles, ideals and
goals, well, it has to happen by July 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Verney, who often represents Perot's views, was equally unsure
whether Buchanan's ultimate goal was to run for president or
rebuild the Reform Party in his own image.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strange strategy,'' Verney said of Buchanan's recent
aggressiveness. ``I don't understand throwing sharp elbows at
would-be friends. It makes you wonder whether his goal is to be
elected president on Nov. 7 or own a party on Nov. 8.''
</P>
<P>
   Both, Bay Buchanan said. ``Pat wants to be president and he
wants to build the party,'' she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While Goodman has been collecting signatures of support for
Perot, Jim Mangia, the Reform Party's national secretary, has been
talking to Green Party leaders about Nader's interest in running as
the Reform candidate. Despite Nader's leftward leanings, his
politics are not so different from the Reform platform on issues
like campaign finance reform and permanent trading status for
China.
</P>
<P>
   Problems lurk, however. Only 36 states allow a candidate to run
with the support of more than one party, and it remains unclear
which party, Reform or Green, would receive federal money for 2004
should Nader win 5 percent of the vote running on both tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe all this is too much for the Reform Party now. Donna
Donovan, the party press secretary, said that some members, ``as a
last-ditch option,'' believe the party should sit out the
presidential campaign this year and build for the future instead.
</P>
<P>
   While highly unlikely, such thinking reflects concern among some
party members that Buchanan will be the inevitable nominee. Not to
worry, said Bay Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the embryonic stage as a party,'' she said. ``Pat is
bringing in new blood and a new image to the party, I'm sure, and
we want to have a strong third party.
</P>
<P>
   ``So if it gets a conservative tint this time, someone else wins
four years later, and then it'll have a different tint.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
