</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELAN COURT ORDERS ELECTIONS POSTPONED 
</HEADLINE>
   By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ The Supreme Court on Thursday ordered the
postponement of the election scheduled for Sunday, saying that the
``reliability and transparency'' of the electoral process could not
be guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise ruling was rendered after the National Electoral
Council had conceded at a judicial hearing that it could not ensure
an accurate, timely and fair vote count. No new date was set for
the balloting, and the court ordered that all campaign activities
be suspended until the Congress, which President Hugo Chavez
controls, chooses a date.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing foreign reporters at a news conference here Thursday
morning, Chavez said he favored delaying the vote for president and
more than 6,000 other posts and that he thought it ``likely that
this will occur.'' He acknowledged that ``serious technical
difficulties'' had developed and urged the council to take the
appropriate steps ``to avoid a disaster'' that would tarnish the
country's image.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, 45, a former army colonel who led an unsuccessful coup
attempt in 1992, compared the situation to a baseball game in which
``the teams are in the dugout, the pitchers are warmed up, and the
fans are in the stands,'' but a heavy rain obscures and inundates
the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that situation,'' he added, ``the smartest decision for the
umpires is to postpone the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Chavez leading his main opponent and former comrade
in arms, Francisco Arias Cardenas, by a comfortable margin. It is,
thus, clearly in his political interest, as his supporters were
quick to recognize, to avoid a repetition of the situation in Peru,
where elections have been marred by accusations that President
Alberto K. Fujimori is manipulating the apparatus to reduce the
opposition vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``A delay is not going to change the results,'' Interior and
Justice Minister Luis Alfonso Davila said in a brief conversation
with reporters this morning. ``No matter when the vote is held,
Hugo Chavez is going to win, and win big.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Constitution that Venezuelans approved in December, no
elections were supposed to have been held until six months after a
new electoral code went into effect. But Chavez was eager to
capitalize on his popularity and win a new six-year term. The newly
established Supreme Judicial Tribunal, whose independence has been
questioned by opposition forces, ruled that the restrictions did
not apply retroactively.
</P>
<P>
   A tide of complaints about the ability of the National Electoral
Council, which Chavez forces dominate, to administer the vote had
been building. But as late as Wednesday night, council members had
continued to maintain that the complete vote would proceed on
Sunday, ``come rain or shine, thunder or lightning,'' as one of
them put it.
</P>
<P>
   The turnabout occurred after several days in which the members
and other government officials had sought to fix the blame for the
problems on the American and Spanish companies that were hired to
carry out the balloting. On Tuesday, the council president,
Estanislao Gonzalez, complained that the foreign companies had
violated their contracts by failing to meet deadlines to deliver
software and equipment. And he hinted at sabotage.
</P>
<P>
   In a news release, the American company said it was ``totally
dependent on having complete and accurate data from the National
Electoral Council.'' The statement said that some required data had
not been delivered as of Monday and that the electoral council had
requested more than 11,000 changes in the list of candidates to be
programmed into voting machines.
</P>
<P>
   In a last-ditch effort to avoid postponing the vote, Chavez sent
Air Force planes to the company headquarters in Omaha to fetch
computer equipment needed to program electronic voting machines
here. He also tried to enlist the American Embassy here in his
effort, saying that ``some gesture on the part of the United States
government'' was needed ``because this is a state problem.''
</P>
<P>
   A series of other incidents that involved the state political
police, known as Disip, had also clouded the picture and generated
concerns about the integrity of the vote. News accounts said police
agents entered the electoral council headquarters early Wednesday
and seized part of the electoral database.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Disip agents are said to have confiscated the
passports of and threatened harm to foreign technicians who are
working with the council. One Spanish employee was reported to have
had a pistol thrust into his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   The American and Spanish embassies have issued diplomatic notes
protesting what the Americans called ``the unconscionable
treatment'' of citizens at the hands of the political police.
</P>
<P>
   At the news session Thursday, Chavez acknowledged that ``some
excesses'' might have occurred and said the police conduct was
under investigation. But he maintained that abuses could ``occur
with the police anywhere in the world,'' pointing to how American
officials took custody of Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old from Cuba,
in Miami.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
