<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: CABINET MINISTER CHARGED
</P>
<P>
   Transport Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, a candidate for prime
minister in 1999, will be prosecuted on three criminal counts of
sexual assault and harassment, the attorney general's office
announced. A highly decorated former army officer and defense
minister, Mordechai has said he will resign, waive his
parliamentary immunity and contest the charges in court.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: JERICHO BAN LIFTED
</P>
<P>
   Authorities lifted a ban on travel to Palestinian-ruled Jericho,
imposed a week ago after the firebombing of an Israeli car there.
Palestinian authorities said they arrested three men in connection
with the attack, which left a 2-year-old girl hospitalized with
severe burns. Jericho is heavily dependent on Israeli tourist
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: CLASH ON SLAVE FUND
</P>
<P>
   The government rejected a plea from the private businesses that
state-owned companies help pay industry's share of the compensation
fund for Nazi-era slave laborers. The private companies are $800
million short of collecting its half of the $4.6 billion in
payments. According to fund officials, many companies are reluctant
to contribute until they receive a guarantee against lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   SWITZERLAND: PAYMENT TO JEWS
</P>
<P>
   Moving to close a painful chapter in its history, government
officials met to offer regret and sympathy to an elderly Jewish
brother and sister whose parents were gassed by the Nazis after
Switzerland expelled the family in World War II. The government
agreed to pay Charles and Sabine Sonabend $118,000 in a lawsuit
settlement. Bern has never before voluntarily agreed to payments to
make up for the deportation of thousands of Jews fleeing Nazi
troops.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE, SWEDEN: CROP DESTRUCTION
</P>
<P>
   France and Sweden ordered farmers to destroy about 1,500 acres
of oil rapeseed. The fields were mistakenly planted with some seeds
with herbicide resistance created by genetic modification, a
technique common in North America but not permitted in Europe. Less
than 1 percent of seeds sown in the acreage were involved,
according to estimates, and neither government knows exactly where
the fields are, but both governments hope farmers will cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND: BOMB-MAKING ARREST
</P>
<P>
   The police found bomb-making chemicals and devices in a Dublin
apartment and questioned a man they suspected of being a member of
the renegade Real IRA. The splinter group was reportedly
responsible for the 1998 car-bomb killing of 29 people in Omagh,
Northern Ireland, and is opposed to the peace accord, which is
facing a critical test in Belfast this weekend. The Ulster
Unionists vote Saturday whether to accept the Irish Republican
Army's offer to permit arms-dump inspections as reason to go back
into government with Sinn Fein, the IRA's political arm.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: E. COLI KILLS 4
</P>
<P>
   An E. coli bacteria outbreak in Ontario has killed four people,
hospitalized four more, and sickened hundreds more in Waterton, a
town 100 miles west of Toronto. Dr. Murray McQuigge, the town's
medical officer, charged that the local water company knew about
the contamination for several days, but did not admit it until
Sunday, after the company had changed a chlorination unit.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: BAPTISM DENIED
</P>
<P>
   Catholic priests in the border city of Mexicali have declined to
baptize the son of a young rape victim because her family chose an
abortion advocate to be the godmother. The victim, Paulina Ramirez,
14, gave birth on April 14 after failing to obtain an abortion in
Baja, Mexico. Silvia Resendiz, a feminist, said the clergymen urged
her to recant her support for abortion rights if she wanted to be
the boy's godmother.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   SRI LANKA: REBEL ULTIMATUM
</P>
<P>
   The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam had set a Friday deadline
for government troops who are battling to keep control of the
northern Jaffna Peninsula to surrender. The Voice of Tigers radio
said the separatist rebels were near a final assault on the city of
Jaffna. Soldiers who surrendered would be turned over to the
International Committee of the Red Cross, the Tigers said.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHANISTAN: U.N. AIDE KILLED
</P>
<P>
   Bashir Ahmed, a U.N. field worker, and six of his seven children
were killed when the Taliban bombed a town in territory controlled
by Ahmed Shah Masood, commander of the northern opposition
alliance. ``This is not the first time that indiscriminate aerial
bombardment or rocketing has killed Afghan civilians,'' said Erick
de Mul, U.N. coordinator for Afghanistan. ``Inflicting such
suffering is unconscionable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
