<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5821 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-ARREST-BOS &LR;      05-25 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-ARREST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT IS HELD IN NEWS ANCHOR'S KILLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Police carrying out one of the biggest homicide
investigations ever in Britain arrested a man Thursday in
connection with the shooting last year of Jill Dando, the most
popular female television personality on the BBC.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives from the Metropolitan Police arrested the man at his
West London apartment, not far from where Dando was shot on her
doorstep in fashionable Fulham last May 27.
</P>
<P>
   While three other men had been arrested for questioning and
released over the last year, police sources said detectives were
eyeing this latest suspect more intensely, holding him ``on
suspicion of murder.'' Under that legal catch phrase, detectives
can detain the suspect without charge for 36 hours, and can
petition a magistrate to hold him even longer.
</P>
<P>
   The detective leading the investigation has said he believes
Dando was killed by a stalker who was obsessed with her because of
her high profile as the BBC's most popular female personality.
</P>
<P>
   While police refused to identify the suspect, and are not
required to unless he is charged, one source said he was among the
original batch of suspects, which at one point numbered about 300.
</P>
<P>
   Dando's slaying, in the middle of the day in a city where such
acts of violence are rare, shocked the nation and led to one of the
most intense manhunts in British history. But police were
frustrated by the lack of solid eyewitness statements and spent
much of the last year chasing down fruitless leads.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors reported hearing Dando scream and saw a well-dressed
man in his late 30s or early 40s carrying a cellular telephone,
running from the scene. A police source described the suspect
arrested Thursday as being ``in that age group.''
</P>
<P>
   Dando, 37, had become one of Britain's most recognizable faces
by hosting the BBC program ``Crimewatch UK,'' which broadcast
stories about unsolved crimes so viewers could call in tips to help
police. It was a similar program, and the tips it yielded last
month, that steered detectives back toward the current suspect, one
police source said.
</P>
<P>
   Such was Dando's prominence in British popular culture that
within hours of her death Queen Elizabeth and Prime Minister Tony
Blair had expressed condolences to her family.
</P>
<P>
   Dando's popularity stemmed from her girl-next-door appearance
and demeanor. Besides the crime tip program, she hosted a popular
travel show. Dando, who occupied a place in British television
similar to Katie Couric on American TV, had been stalked by a
62-year-old male fan two years ago, but police doubt that he had
anything to do with her killing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
