<SLUG> BC-MESOPOTAMIA-ARTWORK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM UR, THE FIRST AND MOST FAMOUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Ill., Mich., Britain, Iraq)   By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mesopotamia, whose name comes from the Greek for
``between the rivers,'' is one of the places where it all began, a
cradle of Western civilization, like ancient Egypt. The rivers are
the Tigris and the Euphrates, and the land between is a flood plain
that today is in Iraq. It was inhospitable terrain: flat, arid and
lacking in indigenous plant life or useful materials like stone,
metals and wood.
</P>
<P>
   But in the seventh millennium BC it was settled by people whom
historians call Sumerians. By the late fourth millennium, the
Sumerians began to meet the requirements for ranking as a cradle of
civilization. They probably invented the wheel; they established
one of the world's first irrigation systems, essential to both
agriculture and flood control; and they created one of the first
written languages. The keeping of written records made large urban
centers possible _ most notably the city-states of Uruk and Ur _ as
well as an elaborate economy that included trade with places as far
away as Afghanistan (from which the Sumerians imported various
kinds of stone).
</P>
<P>
   Beginning about 3500 BC, the Sumerians also produced artworks of
lasting beauty. Some of these, belonging to the University of
Pennsylvania Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology, form the core
of ``Treasures From the Royal Tombs of Ur,'' a sumptuous exhibition
at the Pierpont Morgan Library in Manhattan. The show will travel
to the Oriental Institute Museum in Chicago in October and to the
Detroit Institute of Art in February.
</P>
<P>
   Everything in this show came to light between 1922 and 1934,
when archaeologists sponsored by the university and the British
Museum discovered and excavated a vast cemetery full of hundreds of
intact, often lavishly equipped tombs at Ur, the southernmost of
the ancient Sumerian city-states. Leading the team was C. Leonard
Woolley (1880-1960), an English archaeologist known for his energy
and meticulousness.
</P>
<P>
   Gertrude Bell, another archaeologist of the time, described
Woolley as ``a tiresome little man but a first class digger.'' At
the Morgan, photographs blown up to sepia-toned wall murals
indicate the substantial size of one of the main pits at Ur and
also the work force. But once the heavy work was done, Woolley
usually sent everyone away and did the most delicate,
time-consuming excavating himself, working face down in the dirt
with a knife and a little brush beside his wife, Catherine, who was
also an archaeologist, and one trusted assistant.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter quoted in the catalog, he describes the tedium of
stringing beads from this vantage point, the better to preserve the
order in which they were found.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has taken an introductory survey of western art has
seen images of the exhibition's stars. There is the so-called
ram-caught-in-the-thicket, a small sculpture of an avid ram made of
gold, lapis lazuli and silver, whose wool is ingeniously depicted
as rows of spearheadlike pieces of shell. He stands on his hind
feet, as if to graze on a gold tree. There is also the Great Lyre,
with its big prow-like bull's head bearded in lapis. Just below is
the lyre's four-tiered inlaid front panel, rich in intimations of
gods and myths to come.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's four scenes include one of the first appearances of
what art historians call the nude bearded hero as well as figures
and creatures that presage the Holy Trinity, the minotaur, the
clever beasts of Aesop and a scorpion-tailed man resembling a
devil. All the standard textbooks of Western art reproduce two of
these three items.
</P>
<P>
   It is, however, something else to see the real thing, and in the
company of nearly 200 other objects from the tombs, sensitively
lighted and displayed in nearly invisible vitrines. There have been
significant reconservations: the ram's feet, for example. After an
earlier conservation, they had hung oddly in the air in
reproductions published as recently as 1993; now they rest on the
tree's gold boughs, as if on the handlebars of a bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   The show also has gold, silver and carved stone vessels; vessels
carved in calcite, a pale translucent stone; tools and weapons;
and, perhaps most interesting, the small stone cylinder seals that
served important people as amulets and early identification cards.
(These are supplemented by a selection of Middle Eastern cylinder
seals from the library's own holdings, displayed in the East Room.)
Most prevalent is all manner of jewelry: headdresses, rings,
earrings, cloak pins, beaded necklaces and chokers, belts and even
a beaded cape worn by Queen Puabi, whose grave accounts for more
than half the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   The assembled objects suggest that the Sumerians lived well and
died even better. Not only were their bodies lavishly adorned and
surrounded by objects both useful and entertaining (lyres, for
example, and little lapis tablets that may be the first dominoes),
but they were also accompanied by attendants, themselves richly
adorned, along with oxen and carts. The burial was the culmination
of a feast and processional march into the tomb, where the animals
were slaughtered and the attendants either committed suicide or
were ritually killed.
</P>
<P>
   The objects in this exhibition suggest their own purely visual
criteria for qualifying as a cradle of civilization. While neither
as unbending nor as pure as the Egyptians, the Sumerians achieved a
consistency of style that operated over a range of media:
sculpture, incised relief, inlay and the incised cylinder seals,
whose cartoonlike narratives are made visible here with enlarged
photographs of modern clay impressions.
</P>
<P>
   Given the barbarism of human sacrifice, the style was
surprisingly buoyant, characterized by a wide-eyed innocence and
alertness that are also visible in Minoan and Etruscan figures.
(The Sumerian animals are also depicted with wide round eyes: those
of the bull on the Great Lyre, emphasized by repeating creases,
make clear why targets are known as bull's-eyes.)
</P>
<P>
   The recurrence of certain motifs from one medium to another is a
further consistency and indicates art's mirroring of life. The
sketchy lines visible around the heads of the tiny figures on the
cylinder seals are drinking tubes, like a long gold one, resembling
a bit of miniaturized plumbing pipe, in one of the vitrines. The
fringed garments worn by the figures are sheepskin, as verified by
a front panel for a lyre where a figure wears a garment incised
with the same spear shapes that appear in three-dimensions on the
back of the ram.
</P>
<P>
   An oddly shaped pouring vessel appears in the hand of an upright
lion in the front panel of the Great Lyre, and others like it are
in a vitrine. These vessels seem to have developed from the
bisected conch shells used for the same purpose, which are also in
the show.
</P>
<P>
   Lions are a frequent subject, especially impressive in a simple
cast silver lion's head with staring eyes of lapis and shell. Also
intriguing is a small, bedraggled copper relief that shows two
striding beasts facing in opposite directions, as they would nearly
2,000 years later in the stone reliefs of Assyrian art. That lions
were both a symbol of power and a real threat is apparent again in
the cylinder seals, where they are repeatedly shown attacking
domestic animals.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   One of the less expected pleasures here is the plentiful
jewelry. In addition to suggesting that beautification of the human
form is among the most ancient impulses, it also reflects a
continually evolving ingenuity and technology. In jewelry the
Sumerians made extensive use of three materials, all imported: red
carnelian, blue lapis lazuli and gold.
</P>
<P>
   This triumvirate _ a mineral version of the primary colors _
recurs in different ratios, combinations and motifs. In beads and
other elements of varying shape and size, it is a leitmotif that
grows surely and irresistibly into a major theme of the exhibition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
