<SLUG> BC-CANADA-ECOLI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E. COLI OUTBREAK LEAVES FIVE DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA _ Five people, including an infant, died Thursday and
doctors said they expect more deaths amid one of the worst
outbreaks of E. coli bacterial infection in Canadian history.
</P>
<P>
   A contaminated public water system in the Ontario farming town
of Walkerton was the source of the epidemic, although doctors said
a delayed reaction by town authorities was to blame for the
extraordinary number of cases.
</P>
<P>
   More than 700 people were ill with serious symptoms _ including
severe cramps, vomiting, and diarrhea _ while scores were admitted
to regional hospitals, including 20 children and elderly people who
remained in critical condition Thursday night, battling for their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's never been anything like this in Canada of this
magnitude, never,'' said Dr. Murray McQuigge, the regional health
officer. The town of Walkerton, 80 miles northwest of Toronto, has
4,800 residents.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians warned that there are almost certain to be more
deaths in coming days, saying that the warning issued by the public
water utility, which advised people to boil water, came far too
late to avert disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Statistically, we're expecting more deaths within the next few
days,'' said Dr. Gary Bajurny, an area physician. ``It's scary
because there are no good treatments for this.''
</P>
<P>
   Three children were in intensive care at Children's Hospital of
Western Ontario, two on kidney dialysis machines. Their prospects
for survival were considered poor.
</P>
<P>
   The most likely cause of the contamination was cow manure
carried into the public system during heavy rains and flooding on
May 12, according to the province's health and environmental
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Public health doctors raised strong concerns about water quality
last week, but the warnings were shrugged off by utility officials,
according to McQuigge.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could have been prevented,'' he said. ``We were given
assurances the water was safe even though we were already seeing
the first cases and were becoming alarmed.''
</P>
<P>
   The dead include a 2-year-old baby and an 82-year-old woman. The
three other victims were described as elderly.
</P>
<P>
   The very young and the very old are the most susceptible to
``Escherichia coli 0157:H7,'' the scientific name for a dangerous
strain of E. coli whose usual home is the digestive system of cows.
A benign strain of E. coli is the most common bacteria in the human
intestines.
</P>
<P>
   Small-scale outbreaks of E. coli poisoning are commonplace and
usually linked to tainted food, often undercooked meats. But
contamination of public drinking water supplies infecting large
numbers of people are exceedingly rare in North America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at an epidemic,'' McQuigge said.
</P>
<P>
   Walkerton's five schools and a day-care center were shut down
Thursday, and bottled water was distributed at crossroads by
emergency workers. Most local businesses closed and flags were
flown at half-staff.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital emergency rooms and medical clinics reported phone
lines jammed by hundreds of anxious callers, many suffering
symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   But modern medicine is largely impotent in the face of the
insidious germ. Doctors can do little more than advise patients to
consume large amounts of safe water _ to avoid dehydration _ and
let the infection run its course. In the worst cases, the bacteria
attacks the kidneys, causing serious damage and sometimes death.
</P>
<P>
   Angry residents stormed a news briefing held by Walkerton Mayor
David Thomson and accused public officials of negligence.
``Somebody should be held responsible,'' said Jacques Gosselin, a
resident of Walkerton who was briefly hospitalized with E. coli
poisoning last week. ``Lives have been lost. It's disgraceful.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials acknowledged Wednesday that the machine that injects
bacteria-killing chlorine into the town's drinking supply had been
broken ``for some time'' and that water samples taken on May 15
showed that Walkerton's water was contaminated. It was unclear why
authorities failed to warn residents.
</P>
</TEXT>
