<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORAL-HEALTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURGEON GENERAL FINDS `SILENT EPIDEMIC' IN DENTAL CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAJA MISHRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite significant leaps in dental care over the last century,
the teeth, gums and throats of poor and minority Americans are in
worse shape on average than the rest of the country, according to
the US surgeon general, who called it a ``silent epidemic'' that
severely drains national resources.
</P>
<P>
   In a report released Thursday, Surgeon General David Satcher,
the nation's top doctor, cited a lack of dental coverage among the
poor and a paucity of minority dentists as key causes of the
disparity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who suffer the worst oral health are found among the
poor of all ages, with poor children and poor older Americans
particularly vulnerable,'' wrote Satcher in the preface to the
report. ``Members of racial and ethnic minority groups also
experience a disproportionate level of oral health problems.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he chastised the public as a whole for its
lackadaisical approach to dental care, saying that tooth decay,
cavities, oral cancers and other dental ailments were needlessly
occurring in massive numbers.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time the surgeon general's office has taken aim
at oral health. The office has famously attacked tobacco companies
in the past and earlier this year evaluated the state of US mental
health services. Shedding light on racial disparities has been a
hallmark of Satcher's tenure as the nation's first African-American
surgeon general.
</P>
<P>
   Among the report's findings:
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Almost one-third of the US population, or 100 million
people, lack community water fluoridation, the treatment of
drinking water with chemicals that helps prevent tooth decay _
which is considered to be the greatest advance in dental health of
the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)About 108 million people lack dental insurance, 2 1/2
times the number of people who lack medical insurance.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Poor children have tooth decay at twice the rate of
children who are not poor. In addition, tooth decay is more likely
to go untreated among the poor.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)About 30 percent of people over 65 have no teeth as a
result of dental problems. The number is higher among those living
below the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)The five-year survival rate for white people with oral or
throat cancer is 56 percent. For African-Americans, it is 34
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts state legislators recently began studying these
income and racial disparities In March, a special commission of
dental experts that spent 18 months probing the problem offered
Beacon Hill a solution: reimburse dentists more for treating the
poor and some of the disparities will diminish. Dentists are
fleeing poor neighborhoods in droves because they lose money under
the current rates, they explained.
</P>
<P>
   The House recently passed a bill that would increase Medicaid
dental funding by $29.7 million, the amount recommended by the
commission. The Senate approved a $19.7 million increase. The
chambers are attempting to forge a middle ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty percent of untreated tooth decay in this country is
found in 25 percent of the population,'' said Robert Compton,
director of disease management for the Delta Dental Plan of
Massachusetts and a member of the commission. ``And this 25 percent
is mostly the poor, who don't have access to care.''
</P>
<P>
   Satcher's report urged all health care workers to stress oral
health to patients with the same emphasis usually reserved for
standard health care. He made a similar plea on behalf of mental
health earlier this year. Satcher also urged public officials to
include oral health when crafting public health policy and
increased efforts to recruit minority dentists.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst the mostly dry, clinical tone of the report, the
authors offered a striking, almost poetic, rationale for taking
oral health seriously: ``These are tissues whose functions we take
for granted, yet they represent the very essence of our humanity.
They allow us to speak and smile; sigh and kiss; smell, taste,
touch, chew, and swallow; cry out in pain; and convey a world of
feelings and emotions through facial expressions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
