<HEADER>
A5831 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GREENAWAY-FILM-REVIEW     05-25 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENAWAY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`8{ WOMEN': A FATHER AND SON LIVIN' LA DOLCE VITA 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes at end)  By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even when a movie aspires to the intricate structure and weight
of a knotty modernist poem, how good can it be when watching it
gives you the queasy feeling that you are taking a math exam? That
question could be applied to almost every work by the British
filmmaker Peter Greenaway, whose movies, to a greater or lesser
extent, feel like hybrids of art school essays and brain-tickling
puzzles.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Greenaway, at his best, can be a brilliant theoretician
and collagist. But there is often something forbiddingly inhuman
about his cinematic chess matches, which make Stanley Kubrick's
most elaborate cinematic games look like child's play.
</P>
<P>
   Greenaway's newest film, ``8{ Women,'' is, among other things, a
homage to Federico Fellini's 1963 masterpiece ``8{,'' fragments of
which are shown early in the movie. Just as Marcello Mastroianni
served as the director's alter ego in that film, here the main
character, Philip Emmenthal (John Standing), a middle-aged widower,
is apparently a stand-in for Greenaway. In charting the erotic
adventures of Philip and his son, Storey (Matthew Delamere), who
establish a private bordello on their Geneva estate, the movie is
Greenaway's personal take on a theme that obsessed Fellini: the
erotic mystery and power of women. Although ``8{ Women'' throws in
a group of nuns late in the game, its allusions to Fellini's
Catholicism seem halfheartedly dutiful.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Philip wonders out loud if Fellini slept with the
actresses who appeared in his movies or if he had Mastroianni do
this for him. When he asks his son how many filmmakers make movies
to satisfy their sexual fantasies, Storey replies that most
probably do. And so we are treated to Greenaway's fantasies, which
are pretty standard, although adorned with the stereotypical
British kinks (a fascination with undergarments and the posterior).
</P>
<P>
   But as ``8{ Women'' quickly reveals, the two directors are
really poles apart in their attitudes toward sex. Even though the
film flaunts full frontal nudity (both male and female) and plenty
of frank sexual talk, it is so visually and emotionally chilly that
its effect is often anti-erotic.
</P>
<P>
   When studying human flesh, Greenaway and his production
designers have a way of making even well-shaped naked bodies look
unappetizing. Plenty of beautiful women traipse through the movie,
but their skin appears chalky and porous. The actual sex, none of
it very explicit, is charged with neither passion nor even much
lust. The couplings have the feel of laboratory experiments during
which desire is analyzed to death.
</P>
<P>
   Fellini's women, especially the giant prostitutes he
contemplated with the awe of a little boy peering up at a mountain,
may have been threatening, but his Mediterranean slopes were steamy
and lushly foliated. Greenaway's women are as enigmatic and as
threatening as Fellini's, but most are photographed to appear as
chilly as corpses. This is odd in a film where shots frequently
allude reverently to famous nude paintings. As a seminar on the
changing image of women in art, the movie is a turn-off.
</P>
<P>
   Several of those who join the bordello are Japanese, imported
from Kyoto, where they exposed themselves to blackmail by their
addiction to gambling in pachinko parlors. These Asian archetypes
range from a dragon lady to a Madame Butterfly-like refugee from
the Kabuki theater who can respond to Philip only if he adopts the
disguise and manners of a Kabuki female impersonator. The gambling
theme is illustrated to tedious redundancy with images of tumbling
coins that along with the earthquakes that periodically rumble
through the movie are meant to symbolize love as an earthshaking
game of chance, a natural event that's inevitable and can't be
precisely predicted.
</P>
<P>
   In Greenaway's imagination, as in Fellini's, women end up
calling the shots. Having arrived at the bordello, the women
establish the rules. Then, one by one, they end up leaving the
estate.
</P>
<P>
   The most vivid and powerful female character, Palmira (Polly
Walker), is a free-spirited but demanding sensualist who gives
herself to Philip and ultimately kills him with her inexhaustible
libido. For the role of Beryl, a woman who loves horses and pigs,
Amanda Plummer sports a bizarre S-and-M getup reminiscent of her
bondage gear in ``Butterfly Kiss.'' Natacha Amal is Giaconda, an
avaricious baby-making machine who drives a hard bargain and sells
her newborns for $25,000 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   With its stiffly staged, symbol-laden visual tableaus, ``8{
Women'' unfolds like an art history textbook. What it reveals is
finally less than meets the eye. Its message is quite simple and
all too familiar: when it comes to sex, all men are little boys.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `8{ WOMEN'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Peter Greenaway; director of
photography, Sacha Vierny; edited by Elmer Leupen; production
designer, Wilbert Van Dorp; produced by Kees Kasander; released by
Lions Gate Films.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: John Standing (Philip Emmenthal), Matthew Delamere (Storey
Emmenthal), Polly Walker (Palmira), Amanda Plummer (Beryl), Toni
Collette (Griselda), Kirina Mano (Mio), Vivian Wu (Kito) and
Natacha Amal (Giaconda).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 120 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
