<SLUG> BC-GORE-SCHOOLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICE PRESIDENT PROPOSES AFTER-SCHOOL EXPANSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ Returning to his home state Thursday, Vice President
Al Gore proposed spending $11 billion over 10 years to expand
after-school programs and provide a new tax credit to help families
pay for after-school activities.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting a YMCA classroom with parents and small, squirming
children, Gore said he wanted to help working parents concerned
about their kids coming home to empty houses and vacuous television
shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``After-school for millions of children can make the critical
difference and help parents raise the children that they love,''
said Gore, who was kicking off a series of addresses about
pressures on the American family, with a talk about fatherhood
still to come.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told his audience that children are most at risk for drugs
and violence between 3 and 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fill up that time with useful activities,'' he urged.
``After-school doesn't have to be a time for mischievous hands and
idle minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore proposed:
</P>
<P>
   --Expanding programs to provide children in failing schools with
extra after-school help while their school is being turned around.
</P>
<P>
   --Giving a new after-school tax credit to families with children
6 to 16 years old, providing up to 50 percent of the cost for
after-school expenses according to income.
</P>
<P>
   --Challenging every school to extend its hours for after-school
programs.
</P>
<P>
   --Some federal financial help for recruiting and training staff
for after-school programs and for expanding programs such as the
YMCA and Big Brothers/Big Sisters.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, Gore met with state party chairmen and attended a
Democratic National Committee fund-raiser. The state party chairs,
including representatives from New Hampshire and Maine, spent the
day meeting with top campaign officials and consultants before
hearing from Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, a spokesman for Gore, said the state officials
were discussing plans to coordinate local and state races with the
presidential campaign, in order to maintain a unified message.
Similar discussions took place last month with Democratic mayors
from around the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
