<HEADER>
A5838 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CHASE-PARRISH-ARTWORK     05-25 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHASE-PARRISH-ARTWORK-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO PAINTERS, FAR APART, INTERSECT IN BROOKLYN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., France)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ William Merritt Chase (1849-1916) and Maxfield
Parrish (1870-1966), a generation apart, were in their day very
popular artists. Each wielded a brush with true virtuosity; Chase
in a filtered Impressionist style seen as ``high'' art, Parrish in
a tight, finicky illustrational mode that left out no detail. They
had little else in common until now, with the conjunction of their
shows at the Brooklyn Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   It is a matter of logistics: the Chase show was ready just as
the touring Parrish show was scheduled to make its Brooklyn stop.
But the simultaneity of these two very American exhibitions will,
it is hoped, direct attention to one of the world's most important
collections of American art: the 2,500 paintings, sculptures,
watercolors and pastels dating from 1720 to 1945 in the Brooklyn
Museum collection. (Its American galleries are to undergo an
extensive reinstallation and reopen in July 2001. The department is
also working on a long-awaited catalog of the American collection.)
</P>
<P>
   Of the shows, the more aesthetically significant is ``William
Merritt Chase: Modern American Landscapes, 1886-1890,'' organized
by Barbara Dayer Gallati, curator of American painting and
sculpture at the museum. Chase had a long, distinguished run as a
painter, teacher and art politician, but Gallati zeros in on the
five-year period when his career was at low tide. She has come up
with new insights about the Brooklyn and Manhattan paintings Chase
did in those years.
</P>
<P>
   The 35 oils and pastels in the show are important not so much
for their scenic content, engaging as it is, but because they are
the first paintings in which an Impressionist style was used to
depict American subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Although many of his urban park and coastal scenes are quite
familiar, Gallati wondered why some of the works, long identified
as sites in Central and Prospect Parks, did not really look like
those places. Closer inspection revealed misidentifications. Some
of the Prospect Park scenes, for instance, really depicted Tompkins
Park (now called Von King Park) in Bedford-Stuyvesant _ today much
modified from its appearance in Chase's time _ and the Brooklyn
Navy Yard.
</P>
<P>
   Having corrected those longstanding errors, Gallati began to
examine the genteel Brooklyn and Manhattan scenes of 1886 to 1890,
reflecting a privileged, upper-class view, in broader cultural
terms. Chase painted them, she writes in the show's catalog, not
only because they were part of his Brooklyn surroundings at the
time; he also wanted to present them to the world as examples of
``civilized urban landscapes'' that accorded with the European
avant-garde model of modern life.
</P>
<P>
   A group was shown at the 1889 Paris Exposition Universelle, one
of the great world's fairs, where they were the only American views
that referred to a specific American city and its environs.
</P>
<P>
   Their presentation at such an august event, Gallati argues,
means that they had special significance for the artist.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the paintings marked a transition in Chase's style.
Their airy lightness was in sharp contrast to the dark, Old
Masterish tones of the Munich school in which he was trained,
criticized by American art writers as too European, writes Gallati.
</P>
<P>
   The more avant-garde Impressionist manner in which he did the
park paintings was no less European, but because the Impressionists
had no role in training Americans, as the Munich teachers did,
Chase effectively silenced his American critics while setting
himself up as a peer of his innovative French contemporaries.
</P>
<P>
   Three paintings in the Brooklyn show were among those exhibited
at the Paris fair. One, ``A City Park'' (1887), showing a
fashionable woman with her dog, seated on a bench along a wide path
in Tompkins Park (previously identified as Central or Prospect
Park), looks particularly French in its bright atmosphere, strong
compositional perspective and seeming spontaneity of observation.
Chase's focus on isolated women in public spaces, suggests Gallati,
was his way of defining the spaces in terms of feminine refinement.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly for the same reason, ``Afternoon in the Park'' (circa
1887), an elegant pastel of his wife, Alice, in a salmon pink gown
and straw hat with red trim, is set amid sunlit greenery in the
park of the Brooklyn Navy Yard. The spot was near the Naval Lyceum,
a museum and library founded in 1833 by naval and marine officers
but no longer in existence.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier transitional painting of Chase, a lovely small oil of
1886, shows her sitting pensively in a rowboat, presumably on the
lake in Prospect Park. Its tight cropping and thin, form-modeling
passages of paint show Chase's effort to move away from the
turgidity of the Munich style.
</P>
<P>
   After moving to Manhattan in late 1887 or early 1888, Chase
began to paint in Central Park, producing peaceful scenes like
``The Lake for Miniature Yachts'' (1888), formally known as
``Conservatory Water.'' Combining landscape with figures, unusual
for that time, it shows a broad expanse of path with children
attending toy boats. A flotilla bobs on the shimmering water, with
a middle-distance landscape of greenery as background.
</P>
<P>
   Its avant-garde compositional strategies, cued by European
construction of pictorial space, show Chase's efforts to be modern.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Bit of the Terrace'' (circa 1890), focuses on one of Chase's
favorite Central Park locales, the Bethesda Fountain Terrace, here
portrayed as a peaceful setting for women and children.
</P>
<P>
   In the foreground a decorous infant, dressed head-to-toe in
white, plays with a red ball while its mother strolls nearby.
</P>
<P>
   This bland scene contrasts with the usual depictions of more
strenuous park activities in illustrated magazines and newspapers:
games, concerts, carriage driving, skating. Chase, according to
Gallati, wanted to support the idea of the park as a source of
spiritual elevation and refinement, the view held by its designers,
Frederic Law Olmsted and Calvert Vaux.
</P>
<P>
   Chase's urban landscapes ended with his move to the Shinnecock
Hills on Long Island's East End after the summer of 1890, where he
headed a highly successful summer art school devoted to plein-air
painting. As a sort of finale, a wonderful Shinnecock beachscape is
included in the show: ``Wind Swept Sands, Shinnecock, Long Island''
(circa 1894), an austere, lonely portrayal of dunes on a gray day.
</P>
<P>
   Informed by the more expansive view of landscape he had acquired
in painting his park scenes, Chase's Shinnecock paintings serve as
aesthetic ancestors to many a view of eastern Long Island by his
20th-century successors.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 2023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0259 </DOCNO>
