u k BC-OPED-WEBSPEAK-YERGIN-     05-25 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-WEBSPEAK-YERGIN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STICKY ROAD TO A KILLER APP 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Friday, May 26, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by OPED clients. Nonsubscribers can use this
article only by special arrangement. For purchase information, see
end of text. 
 By DANIEL YERGIN    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago content was going to be king on the Internet. Last
year it was all about selling to consumers. This year, especially
as the Internet retail stocks plunge, it's e-business _
company-to-company commerce. If you want to keep up with something
moving this fast, you need to know how to talk the talk of the new
world.
</P>
<P>
   First, do not speak of markets or sectors. Say ``space,'' as in,
``They're in some of my space'' or ``We want to dominate that
space.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't think of space as a vacuum. It is filled with
verticals. These are something like industry sectors. What you must
do with a vertical is ``drill down'' into it until you hit paydirt,
famously called a killer app _ a lucrative niche to mine.
</P>
<P>
   The phrases B2C, as in business to consumer, and B2B, for
business to business, must roll off the tongue as easily as ``good
morning'' and ``good night.'' B2B drives down costs by
disintermediating _ cutting out middle steps and companies from the
business chain. It's great unless you are the one being
disintermediated. For future positioning, it would be wise, as
well, to begin practicing D2D, as in device-to-device, and
m-commerce, for mobile commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business model'' should be mentioned a lot, mainly because no
one really knows which Internet business models will work. And
because another big question, reflected in the Nasdaq's troubles,
is how one can actually make money from the Internet, it's good to
mention ``revenue models'' frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Even if your models are shaky, you know what you want to
attract: eyeballs. And what you want from those eyeballs is
stickiness _ that is, repeat business, people coming back to your
site again and again. That means what you are really seeking are
``sticky eyeballs.''
</P>
<P>
   You already know, of course, about the new economy and the old
economy. But be sure to use the terms in the preferable way _ not
as nouns, but as modifiers, as in new-economy valuation or
old-economy thinking. Space is new economy. Market is old economy.
Got it?
</P>
<P>
   Legacy, with all its warm old associations of something
gratefully inherited, like money or values, has turned decidedly
negative. Now legacy is your existing business, with all its
commitments and incentives and organization, holding you back and
preventing you from moving in Internet time. The past is no longer
prologue; it's a drag.
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, the basic rule to remember, one whose
codification has been attributed to a number of people, is a
sobering one. ``If you don't cannibalize your business, someone
else will.'' Sticky eyeballs and all.
</P>
<P>
   (Daniel Yergin, chairman of Cambridge Energy Research Associates
in Cambridge, Mass., is co-author of ``The Commanding Heights.'')
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the OPED
package and other features. &QL;
</P>
