<HEADER>
A5842 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CHASE-PARRISH-ARTWORK     05-25 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHASE-PARRISH-ARTWORK-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: 20th-century successors.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   While Chase dealt with the here and now _ however sanitized _ in
his paintings, Parrish pursued a never-never world of chaste but
titillating young women and knightly men in pastoral landscapes
that melded medieval towers with New England forests, Western
gorges and the deep blue skies of fairy kingdoms.
</P>
<P>
   The show here, ``Maxfield Parrish: 1870-1966,'' organized by the
Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts and the American Federation
of Arts, presents more than 140 paintings, drawings, prints,
photographs, illustrations and ephemera by this deep-dyed fabulist,
the son of an upper-caste Philadelphia Quaker family.
</P>
<P>
   Reproductions of his paintings sold like hotcakes to a mass
market audience, and he also made a more than respectable living as
an advertising and magazine illustrator.
</P>
<P>
   As an illustrator, he could be considered the father of Norman
Rockwell, although his powers of invention were greater. His gift
for design is evident in modernistic creations like ``School Days
(Alphabet),'' a 1908 cover design for Collier's magazine. In it a
riotous swarm of alphabet letters stream from the pages of a
child's open textbook, burying him as he attempts to learn his
ABCs.
</P>
<P>
   An exacting draftsman as well as a clever colorist, Parrish
accomplished his impeccable oil paintings by the painstaking
application of many thin layers of transparent glazes over bases of
monochrome ink or paint.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the more familiar Parrish chestnuts are on view here,
like ``Daybreak'' (1922), the first painting he created
specifically for reproduction as an art print. A beautiful young
maiden, robed, lies on a marble-columned porch as a luminous dawn
breaks over a majestic mountain range. A young goddess, naked,
presumably Dawn, leans over the maiden to witness her ecstatic
awakening. To sexual ripening? Whatever, it has been estimated that
by 1925 this essay in veiled eroticism could be found on the walls
of one out of every four American households.
</P>
<P>
   In quite a different vein is the mural ``Old King Cole'' (1894),
a large triptych originally done for the University of
Pennsylvania's Mask and Wig Club in Philadelphia. A coy, cartoony
rendition of the nursery rhyme, it shows the merry king on his
throne, serenaded by his fiddlers three and attendants bearing pipe
and bowl. (In 1905 Parrish reworked the King Cole theme into a
mural for the old Knickerbocker Hotel on Times Square; in 1935 it
was transferred to the St. Regis Hotel in Manhattan, where it
remains on view today in the King Cole Bar.)
</P>
<P>
   Parrish never regarded himself as more than a popular artist
(``My skies were too blue,'' he told me in an interview shortly
before his death), but the revival of ``high art'' interest in his
work that began with the advent of Pop Art continues.
</P>
<P>
   There is enough in this show _ particularly his graphic art and
some fine landscapes _ to sustain that interest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 2023EDT &QL; 
