<HEADER>
A5845 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-BROADBAND-HOUSING-ART     05-25 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADBAND-HOUSING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET-READY HOUSES ARE FINDING A HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Calif., Pa., Texas, Fla., Va., Ariz., Mich., Ohio)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT17 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Levine wanted what many people would in a new house, a
safe neighborhood and low upkeep. But what really sold him on
Centennial, a 900-home development north of Indianapolis, was the
wiring _ a ready-to-use, high-speed Internet connection as well as
cable and phone service, all provided by the builder.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet service is ``so much faster than anything I've ever
seen,'' said Levine, a retired surgeon who moved in with his family
in March. Since Internet access no longer requires a phone line and
can go to more than one computer, ``nobody complains, `Gee, I can't
get online,''' he said. ``While one kid is doing research, the
other one is talking to her friend.''
</P>
<P>
   For a growing number of home buyers, high-speed Internet
connections are becoming as important as a two-car garage,
fireplace or new kitchen, prompting some developers and builders to
jump into the telecommunications business. Either by building and
owning neighborhood networks, or joining with telecom companies,
they are offering Internet access, bundled with cable and phone
service, at up to $20 a month below the typical cost. Instead of
different bills, people might pay one fee _ perhaps $50 for
Internet and cable _ through a homeowners' association.
</P>
<P>
   Their efforts are in the early stages. Most wired developments
have sprouted just in the last year. How developers eventually do
against the abundance of regional phone companies, cable companies
and other providers is anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we began to see during the last couple of years is a huge
explosion in demand'' for these connections, said Glen Barnard, who
runs the e-commerce business at Kaufman &AMP; Broad Home, a Los Angeles
builder.
</P>
<P>
   Builders also see a way to have continuing revenue from these
services _ perhaps 10 percent of the total fees _ and this steady
income would be most welcome in a business that has its ups and
downs. ``Wherever possible,'' Barnard said, ``we want to have an
ownership interest in the infrastructure we're putting in.''
</P>
<P>
   High-speed, or ``broadband,'' access has been slow to reach many
homes, even in centrally located or wealthy neighborhoods,
frustrating consumers used to speedy connections at work. One type
of service, a digital subscriber line, is often not available to
homes more than three miles from a phone company switching station.
Even then, some homeowners have faced delays in getting hooked up.
The other popular method, cable-modem service, has its own
problems, including slowdowns at peak times.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few million American households have either service, even
though analysts estimate that about 40 percent of the population
uses the Internet. According to Jo Chapman, director of surveys at
the National Association of Home Builders, only 5 percent of new
homes come with ``structured'' wiring, the fatter in-home pipe
needed to get the most from broadband service. But that should grow
rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Broadband is already a must for some home buyers. Moving from
Redmond, Wash., recently, Ed and Judy Bott looked at 40
developments in Arizona before settling on DC Ranch, a new wired
community in Scottsdale. The development has it all _ including
structured wiring in every home _ and is served by US West. ``Not
having high-speed access would have been a deal-breaker,'' said
Bott, an author and magazine editor who telecommutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Botts know firsthand how difficult it can be getting the
right set-up: Their old home in Washington was supposed to have
structured wiring, but the job was done poorly, they say, causing
an expensive retrofit. ``We went through a painstaking process,''
said Bott, a public relations director for a Scottsdale technology
company.
</P>
<P>
   At Toll Brothers, a luxury builder in Huntingdon Valley, Pa.,
executives have set up their own subsidiary to build and own
broadband networks within Toll developments. Other builders, like
Kaufman &AMP; Broad, are weighing revenue-sharing arrangements with
companies that will wire new communities, similar to deals already
struck by owners of some office buildings and high-end apartments.
Some big service providers, like SBC Communications, US West, and
Cox Communications, are seeking large builders and developers to
wire planned communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is working down the same path,'' said Richard
Beckwitt, general partner of Encore Venture Partners, a fund whose
major investors include a Texas builder, D.R. Horton. Encore is
searching out Internet-related businesses that dovetail with
homebuilding, including broadband delivery. ``We're trying to get
some ownership of the stream of revenue that passes through the
Internet, the cable, the telephone lines after the house closes,''
Beckwitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Some builders are taking a slower tack, unsure of how well all
this will fare against established telecom companies. To keep
buyers from sticking with old-line providers, some developers are
including their brand of service in neighborhood association fees.
</P>
<P>
   One risk is that the capital spending required could be lost if
newer technologies proliferate. ``The question for us is whether
what is cutting-edge today will still be leading-edge tomorrow,''
said Jim Zeumer, director of investor relations for Pulte Corp., a
builder in Bloomfield Hills, Mich. ``You can spend a lot of money
laying whatever kind of pipe, then tomorrow, somebody has solved
wireless, and all of a sudden you've got a whole new ball game.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Pulte is already testing some new ideas in Arizona. ``We
are looking at other business structures we could roll out on a
more nationwide basis,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 2027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5846 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-BROADBAND-HOUSING-2ND     05-25 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADBAND-HOUSING-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: he said.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Centex Corp., a Dallas builder that has been a leader in
diversifying into areas like lawn care and home security, is
proceeding cautiously. But Randy Luther, a vice president at its
Centex Homes unit, said signs point to broadband becoming a much
more important feature, especially as the first generation to grow
up with computers starts buying homes. Many houses not built with
structured wiring _ a feature Centex is pushing _ will be at a
disadvantage in the resale market in five years, he said. ``It's
not a question of if it's going happen. It's a question of when.''
</P>
<P>
   For a lot of homebuilders, ``How they do it is still very much
up in the air,'' adds John Stanley, an analyst at UBS Warburg.
``It's probably a few years down the road before it means anything
to the bottom line.'' But for most big builders, ``They've come to
the conclusion they're leaving some money on the table'' if they do
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity exists because developers own the land that
carries the wiring from homes to the outside world. This is
especially true in developments in outlying suburbs and planned
communities, where developers own the easements, providing a
barrier to entry against cable, telephone and other rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The importance of this ``last mile'' or ``first mile'' in
existing neighborhoods has helped drive some big mergers, like
AT&AMP;T's acquisition of Tele-Communications and Mediaone, and America
Online's deal for Time Warner. Existing providers of telephone and
cable service, meanwhile, plan to spend billions of dollars getting
old-fashioned lines and wires in shape for high-speed service. Huge
investments have been made in technologies bypassing the last mile,
like satellite dishes and fixed wireless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Developers have realized the first mile of real estate, which
we previously gave away, is perhaps the most valuable real estate
in the country,'' said Paul Estridge Jr., president of Estridge
Companies, which built Centennial outside Indianapolis. Estridge
has formed a company, First Mile Technologies, to wire new
developments. First Mile hopes to expand by cutting deals with
other developers, offering them up to 10 percent of the revenue
from services it sells their home buyers. Estridge estimates that
for homeowners, the service could be 15 percent or more cheaper;
for now, Centennial residents get it free while the company sorts
out pricing.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the only glitch is that residents have had phone calls
routed through a cellular network, though Centennial says they will
be linked up with a regular network in few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   At Toll Brothers, executives recently announced a new unit,
Advanced Broadband, which is wiring two new developments in Florida
and one in Virginia. But Toll plans to expand that business and
also to join forces with other builders and developers, said
Michael Zammit, managing director for telecommunications at Toll.
He expects the new Toll unit to help cash flow by 2002. ``Clearly
it's a direction we see ultimately taking the company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another start-up, Dynamic Telecom Engineering, of Cleveland, has
signed revenue-sharing deals with several builders, including
Beazer Homes USA and Kaufman &AMP; Broad. Dynamic Telecom will wire new
developments and pay the builders 10 percent of its revenue, with
some builders also getting an equity stake, said the president, Eli
Asher.
</P>
<P>
   Some big phone and cable companies are also seeking out deals
with developers. In addition to DC Ranch, US West, the Denver-based
phone company, has similar arrangements planned or underway with at
least a dozen other big developments, said Vickey Callen, vice
president and general manager of the broadband services unit.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, Newhall Land and Farming, a large developer
outside Los Angeles, said it had cut a deal to have SBC's Pacific
Bell unit provide video, broadband and phone service to every new
home in Newhall's Valencia and Newhall Ranch communities. Robin
MacGillivray, a Pacific Bell executive, said some such agreements
call for revenue sharing with the developer, depending on what
state regulations permit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Developers are realizing that they need to offer their
customers more than just news, weather and sports,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
