<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5848 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-BUSH-NUKES-2TAKES-NYT     05-25 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NUKES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: BUSH BREAKS NEW GROUND WITH PROPOSAL FOR MISSILE DEFENSE
SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush's proposal this week to
consider unilateral reductions in the American nuclear arsenal was
a break with decades of strategic doctrine, a break that may
foretell the end of traditional theories of arms control.
</P>
<P>
   In Bush's vision, still lacking in many details, the threat of
global annihilation _ known in arms control theory as mutual
assured destruction _ would no longer govern relations between the
United States and other nuclear powers. The size of the American
nuclear arsenal would no longer depend on the number of warheads
Russia possesses, nor be set in lengthy and painstaking arms
control negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   And the defensive shield against nuclear weapons that he
proposes to build _ significantly larger than that envisioned by
the Clinton administration _ would be shared with American allies
and, perhaps one day, with Russia or even China.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these ideas have been percolating among a bipartisan
body of experts in the arms control community for years.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was President Ronald Reagan, who trumpeted the idea
of slashing offensive nuclear weapons and relying instead on a a
defensive shield that would render nuclear missiles obsolete. And
at Reykjavik in 1986, Reagan also agreed with Mikhail Gorbachev,
the former Soviet leader, to the principle of eliminating all of
their nuclear weapons, before he was pulled back by his advisers.
</P>
<P>
   But 15 years later, arms control is suddenly back at center
stage in a presidential campaign that was expected to focus on
domestic policy. And some of those same men who pushed Ronald
Reagan away from his radical views on arms control are now advising
Bush, the presumptive Republican nominee, as he gives new voice to
the idea of large cuts in offensive weapons coupled with
construction of missile defenses, and places it squarely on the
current political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton will push his own arms control agenda in
Moscow in 10 days when he meets with the Russian president,
Vladimir Putin, to discuss further cuts in long-range warheads. The
administration is offering to make some of the cuts if Moscow
accepts changes in a 1972 treaty, to allow the fielding of a
limited missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his advisers argue that it is long past time for a
radical reassessment of nuclear theory. The idea of holding
populations hostage to annihilation is worse than immoral, they
say, it is irrelevant. They complain that Clinton has wasted much
of the decade since the end of the Cold War by clinging to the Cold
War orthodoxy of using the specter of massive retaliation to deter
any nuclear power from contemplating a first strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's way past time for some fresh thinking about the structure
of military capability in light of the kind of world we now live
in,'' said George P. Shultz, the secretary of state in the Reagan
administration and one of Bush's foreign policy advisers. ``That
really hasn't been done.''
</P>
<P>
   Shultz, who was a well-known skeptic on Reagan's vision of a
space-based umbrella to shield America from incoming missiles, said
that his thinking has evolved on missile defenses because of the
rapid advance of technology. He said that Bush knows that current
technology cannot produce an impermeable nuclear shield any time
soon. But, he added, ``it's not too much to say there is a
reasonable prospect to interpose a thin layer of defense out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Blechman, a nuclear analyst at the Henry L. Stimson Center
in Washington and a Democrat, called this sort of talk ``a
breakthrough in Republican thinking.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is talking about going down to numbers that are lower
than the military is currently willing to go,'' Blechman said.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Bush is discussing the possibility of making such
reductions unilaterally, rather than in a process of years-long
negotiations with Russia or China over accuracy, throw-weights,
basing modes, build-downs and timetables.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that he envisions a sweeping review of American
strategic needs by the Pentagon that will help establish the
optimal size of the nuclear force. He will then challenge Russia to
match American reductions in weaponry. His chief foreign policy
adviser, Condoleezza Rice, calls these ``reciprocal unilateral
measures'' and describes them as a simpler and less time-consuming
way to do arms control than the interminable talks that have
dominated arms control efforts with Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as another Bush adviser put it: ``The governor said he was
going to figure out what we need, reduce to that level and
encourage the Russians to do the same. We're not going to build
stuff we don't need just because Russians have stuff they don't
need.''
</P>
<P>
   But that was precisely the calculation that governed the arms
race of the second half of the 20th century: The superpowers kept
building up their stockpiles to match the other, far beyond the
needs of deterrence or any possible military requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore had hoped that such questions would not
become central to the presidential campaign this year. He and other
administration officials believed they had neutralized much of the
Republican fervor for a robust missile shield by moving toward a
decision this year on a limited system of land-based national
missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But Bush portrayed the administration approach as timid on two
fronts. He proposed a broader missile shield to appeal to
conservatives and deeper weapons cuts than the Clinton
administration has been willing to entertain.
</P>
<P>
   Since the days of the missile gap and duck-and-cover drills,
four things have changed the nuclear equation in fundamental ways.
The Soviet Union fell apart. Advances in technology have held out
the promise of missile defenses that may be at least partially
effective. Years of arms control agreements have reduced the
numbers of nuclear weapons by thousands with no apparent impact on
the relative security of the United States and Russia. And a
handful of smaller nations, among them North Korea and Iraq, have
made strides toward developing nuclear weapons of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his advisers argued this week that U.S. doctrine has
not kept pace with any of these developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``While deterrence remains the first line of defense against
nuclear attack, the standoff of the Cold War was born of a
different time,'' Bush said in a speech at the National Press Club
on Tuesday. ``Yet almost a decade after the end of the Cold War,
our nuclear policy still resides in that already distant past.''
</P>
<P>
   He proposed a series of measures that would alter that policy,
including building a defensive system that would cover all 50
states and could be extended to protect allies in Europe, the
Middle East and Asia. In addition to holding out the possibility of
large unilateral cuts in nuclear arms, he said that most American
nuclear weapons should be removed from hair-trigger alert status.
He offered reassurance to Moscow and Beijing that the American
system of missile defense, although it would almost surely entail
abrogating the Anti-ballistic Missile Treaty of 1972, was not aimed
at neutralizing their arsenals of long-range weapons.
</P>
<P>
   That is an argument that has so far been rejected by those two
countries, especially by China, whose relatively small nuclear
force could be rendered irrelevant by even the limited anti-missile
system favored by Clinton. Both countries argue that the old system
of deterrence that Bush derides as outdated is still the most
reliable method of keeping the nuclear peace. Chinese officials
have said they might have to accelerate their own nuclear program
if the Americans build an anti-missile shield.
</P>
<P>
   Gore quickly issued a statement rejecting Bush's ideas as risky
and irresponsible. He said that Bush wanted to resurrect the
discredited Star Wars program of the Reagan era and flaunt American
military superiority over Russia, China and every other nation. And
he chastised Bush for opposing the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty,
which was defeated in the Senate last fall on a largely party-line
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's response drew a rebuke from Bush's advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Scowcroft, the national security adviser to President
George Bush and a retired Air Force general, said that construction
of missile defenses should not be seen as a threat to the nuclear
forces of Russia and China nor as an incentive for them to beef up
their arsenals to overwhelm American defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow has sufficient political and financial reasons for
continuing to draw down its nuclear stockpile, he said, while
Beijing is likely to continue its nuclear buildup regardless of
what the United States does because it faces growing threats in its
own region.
</P>
<P>
   ``This goes back to the cooperative concept,'' he said. ``We
tell both of them, `North Korea is a problem for us; it's a problem
for you, too. How can you help us, by changing the threat or
helping us deal with it?'''
</P>
<P>
   In a floor statement delivered on Thursday, Sen. Joseph R. Biden
Jr., the senior Democrat on the Foreign Relations Committee,
praised Bush's ideas _ up to a point. He applauded his intention to
undertake a thorough review of America's nuclear posture and
endorsed his plan to take weapons off high-alert status. He agreed
that the size of the American nuclear arsenal could safely be
reduced far below current levels.
</P>
<P>
   But Biden also said that Bush held an unrealistic view of the
feasibility and cost of missile defenses and said that a radical
revision of decades of deterrence would be unnerving to allies and
adversaries alike.
</P>
<P>
   The senator urged Bush and Gore to remove the question of
missile defenses from the current political debate and allow the
next president to study the matter outside of the electoral arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longest-lasting foreign policy debate is not likely to be
settled any time soon,'' Biden said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
