<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5850 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-LEWIS-OZONU0526-COX     05-25 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-OZONU0526-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Witness: Defense used intimidation
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When he eased his taxi up onto the Buckhead murder
scene in the early hours of Jan. 31, Patrick Ozonu unwittingly
became a witness in the murder trial of NFL star linebacker Ray
Lewis and two co-defendants.
</P>
<P>
   The magnitude of events didn't hit, Ozonu says, until he spurned
interview requests from the Lewis defense team and found himself
subjected to ``intimidation tactics'' by their hired investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, defense attorneys and witnesses friendly to Lewis
have continuously alleged use of such heavy-handed tactics by the
prosecution and Atlanta police _ a complaint uttered again in court
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Ozonu, who could testify as early as today, says Lewis
investigators falsely accused him of being in possession of a
stolen cell phone, then suggested they could clear up the problem
if he'd meet with them. The Nigerian native also alleges receiving
a follow-up call from someone impersonating an Atlanta police
officer, which would be a felony.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Paul Howard said he has a copy of the tape
recording Ozonu made of the calls and plans to weigh filing charges
after the high-profile murder trial concludes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take the allegations very seriously, and we intend to look
at them closely,'' Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Garland, Lewis' attorney, downplayed the situation, saying it
was just a ``misunderstanding'' between his investigators and
Ozonu. He added that Ozonu has since visited his office.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators working for the Lewis defense team continue to
portray Ozonu as an ``insignificant'' witness, over-reacting to
what they describe as the routine practice of trying to determine
what a witness will testify to before trial. They also question
Ozonu's credibility, noting that he sought $300 when they attempted
to interview him. Ozonu says it was the cost of his time.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's unlikely he can identify any suspects, the
41-year-old cab driver has told police of pulling his empty white
minivan into the intersection and seeing at least six men pummeling
one man and another on the ground bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   To document the alleged tactics of two of the investigators
retained by Garland _ former Atlanta police officer Dale Hendrix
and Bill Siebert, both licensed by the Georgia Board of Private
Detectives and Security Agencies _ Ozonu began tape recording their
telephone calls to his apartment. He later played the tapes for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   During a March 15 call, Hendrix is heard telling Ozonu that it's
come to his attention that Ozonu is in possession of a stolen cell
phone _ reading back a number which isn't to a cell phone, but is
Ozonu's home phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to play hardball with me, I'll play hardball with you
as far as the cell phone,'' Hendrix warns. ``The cell phone might
concern the Atlanta Police Department. . . . Are you willing to
stay out of jail? If the information I have is correct, you're
going to be needing to stay out of jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my information that you got a stolen cell phone. It's my
understanding the cell phone came from a crime scene.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ozonu expressed anger that his boss had been told the
allegation by Hendrix, the investigator handed the phone to
Siebert, who described himself as being with Bell South Mobility.
Siebert tells Ozonu that Atlanta police and the FBI confirmed the
phone was stolen, and offers to help Ozonu clear the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Siebert initially denied (to a reporter) talking with Ozonu.
Then, asked if he ever called on behalf of Bell South about a
stolen cell phone, said: ``I was running something down on a
possible (stolen) phone, and. . . I was (visiting) Bell South
Mobility security at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell South Mobility spokeswoman Julia Russo said of Siebert:
``We show no such person being associated with this company.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the conversation with Hendrix and Siebert, Ozonu
received a call from someone posing as an Atlanta police officer,
who identified himself as Detective Ryan and later as Detective Tom
Russell. Neither is employed by the department, said Atlanta police
spokesman John Quigley. The telephone number the caller left with
Ozonu rings to a local accountant's office.
</P>
<P>
   Both investigators deny any unethical behavior in their dealings
with Ozonu, or any knowledge of the person misrepresenting himself
as a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrix, an 18-year veteran of the Atlanta police force, retired
in 1998 after a federal jury acquitted him on charges that he
illegally received payments to provide security at an apartment
complex. He was represented by Don Samuel, a member of Lewis' legal
team. Hendrix is appealing revocation of his certification by the
Georgia Peace Officer Standards &AMP; Training Council.
</P>
<P>
   The tactics Hendrix and Siebert are accused of using in dealing
with Ozonu could put them at odds with regulations of the Georgia
Board of Detective &AMP; Security Agencies, empowered to bring
disciplinary action against licensees who commit dishonesty or
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't project a good image for the private detective
industry when you have people not only misrepresenting themselves
as police officers but intimidating a witness,'' said Gene
Staulcup, board chairman. ``I understand they want to see what
(Ozonu) has to say, and they're representing their client to the
best of their ability _ but we all have to operate within the
confines of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
