u s BC-BKN-HAWKS-KRUGER0526-     05-25 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-KRUGER0526-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kruger vows to listen, learn
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hawks general manager Pete Babcock and his new
coaching hire, Lon Kruger, sat on the dais, earnestly answering
questions. Twenty feet away, club president Stan Kasten stood
beaming the approval he has expressed about the new guy in town.
</P>
<P>
   Against the wall, wearing his Arizona warmups, young point guard
Jason Terry stood. He listened intently as Kruger spoke about his
aspirations in Atlanta and his reasons for coming. A few times
Terry nodded. Kruger responded to one question by saying he had a
lot to learn from his players. ``I'll learn from them more than
they'll learn from me.'' Later, he said, ``I'll listen to them more
than they'll listen to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Some in the audience at the Philips Arena practice gym winced,
because half the Hawks squad is 20 to 24.
</P>
<P>
   Terry raised his hand in a reassuring gesture.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's college-coach talk,'' said a player one year past his
four-year career under Lute Olson. ``They listen to you. Then they
tell you what to do, and then you go out and you do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kruger also said he believed in hard work, the basis of his
philosophy after 18 years as a head coach at four colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Terry wanted to hear that. He and Alan Henderson have been in
the gym every day since the worst season in franchise history ended
last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want is for him to let every player on this team know
that being in the gym on a daily basis is not only expected but
demanded,'' Terry said. ``It's not, `Well, it'd be nice if you can
come down,' but that you have to be here . . . . When we get that,
then I'll know we're moving forward as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Kruger, 47, ``is the best basketball coach (available) we could
possibly hire for the long-term future of the franchise,'' Babcock
said after signing him to a five-year contract at $2 million a
year. Babcock listed among Kruger's strengths ``strong sense of
discipline, structure, aggressive defense, great character.''
</P>
<P>
   Kruger contradicted a report that he had turned down the Hawks
at one point in the negotiations. ``I never said no. I listened
until I said yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the appeal of the job was the young roster, he said. He
knows Jim Jackson, Roshown McLeod and Lorenzen Wright. He spoke on
the telephone Wednesday night with Dikembe Mutombo, and he met with
Terry and Henderson after their morning workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they want to work hard and get it done,'' the coach
said. ``Otherwise, I wouldn't want to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Kruger went back to Champagne, Ill., Thursday to say goodbye to
his Illinois team. He will be back next week to begin assembling a
coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Terry said he would be waiting for him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
