<HEADER>
A5864 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-NEIGHBOR-LAWSUITS-$AD     05-25 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEIGHBOR-LAWSUITS-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEING NEIGHBORLY SOMETIMES ISN'T NEARLY ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 28) 
 By VIVIAN MARINO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The quaint little village of Antwerp, N.Y., seemed like an ideal
place for Stephen and Vici Diehl to escape the noise and nuisance
of city life and to indulge their passion for nature photography.
</P>
<P>
   What they found instead was a different type of noise and
nuisance.
</P>
<P>
   Several years after settling into their four-bedroom 1827 Greek
revival home on 1.5 acres 40 miles from the Canadian border, they
said, their rural serenity was shattered by a neighbor playing
amplified Christmas music on outdoor loudspeakers, blaring
intermittently every day during the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   The neighbor is the First Congregational Church of Antwerp, with
whom the couple has been bickering in and out of courtrooms for six
years. ``We just said, `Please turn down the volume,' but they just
didn't want anybody telling them what to do,'' said Diehl, 49.
</P>
<P>
   Disputes between neighbors about loud noise, offensive odors,
intrusive pets or wayward vegetation have been going on for
centuries, and the exchanges can become rather unneighborly. The
summer months, when people spend more time outdoors and new faces
are most likely to move in to neighborhoods, are the peak season
for disputes, legal experts say.
</P>
<P>
   When neighbor-to-neighbor arguments find their way to court,
they are generally based on two kinds of claims. One is
interference with what is called quiet enjoyment of one's property,
a common-law right with ancient roots; the Diehls' dispute with the
church is an example. The other common claim is of actual or
potential reduction of property values.
</P>
<P>
   While having a good neighbor probably won't raise the value of a
home, a bad one certainly can lower it, said Cora Jordan, a
Mississippi attorney and author of ``Neighbor Law: Fences, Trees,
Boundaries and Noise'' (Nolo.com, 1999). She noted that a
dilapidated house or grounds, a home-based business that draws
traffic or makes noise, or drastic changes made to one property in
a neighborhood can reduce what buyers are willing to pay for nearby
homes. ``If your property value is affected, you can sue,'' Jordan
said.
</P>
<P>
   There are no reliable national figures on neighbor-to-neighbor
legal disputes, but experts say the number is steadily growing, as
homeowners become more aggressive in defense of quality of life and
what is usually their largest investment by far, their homes. A
hint can be gleaned from figures on civil disputes handled through
state-sponsored mediation, a faster and cheaper alternative to a
formal trial. Of the 40,860 cases of all kinds referred to New
York's network of 62 mediation centers in fiscal 1999, a quarter
were neighbor-related disputes; divorces and other domestic
disputes, commercial disagreements and landlord-tenant quarrels
make up much of the rest.
</P>
<P>
   When neighbors go to war, noise is the No. 1 casus belli
everywhere. Among city apartment dwellers, parking and pets also
rank high, according to Debra Shime, program director for a
mediation center in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Suburban Hatfields and McCoys commonly feud over boundary
encroachments (a new driveway or fence that creeps over the
property line), trees and bushes (which might block a neighbor's
view or sunlight), and eyesores.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we're so modern with our cell phones and gadgets, but
people are having the same types of problems with their neighbors
as they did 300 years ago,'' said Mark Warda, a Florida attorney
and author of ``Neighbor vs. Neighbor,'' (Sphinx Publishing, 1999).
The book chronicles some bizarre quarrels, including a 1920s suit
over a honk of a car horn that allegedly set off a chicken riot in
which 720 birds perished. (The chicken farmer lost.)
</P>
<P>
   Neighbor-law experts say litigation ought to be the last resort.
The first step should be calmly approaching neighbors about a
problem, and if that fails, writing a letter. And Jordan suggests
researching local ordinances to see if a valid complaint exists
before involving local authorities or suing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is, people don't always know their neighbors,''
Warda said, ``so they may feel uncomfortable. Years ago, you could
go over to the neighbor and say, `Hey Joe, could you please get
your dog to stop barking while I take a nap?'''
</P>
<P>
   The Diehls, who said the church's holiday music drove them
indoors, kept them up nights and forced Diehl, 51, to take a leave
from his position as a photography professor at Rochester Institute
of Technology, tried to resolve the problem with the church
directly before suing, but without success.
</P>
<P>
   The church's lawyer, Henry Leader, said the church tried turning
the volume down and moving the loudspeakers, but nothing satisfied
the Diehls. ``Nobody else complained,'' he said. ``There was even a
petition by some of the other residents asking for the music to
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally the dispute came before a federal judge, who ordered the
church to refrain from playing its amplified holiday music for two
years, a ruling that expires this winter. Leader said that though
the crux of the case was ``really freedom of speech,'' it is
unlikely the music will resume.
</P>
<P>
   The limits to constitutional rights become an issue in cases
like a recent one in Little Rock, Ark. Jennings Osborne, who owns
the Arkansas Research Medical Testing Center, used to put up a
dazzling display of 3 million Christmas lights on his main
residence and two adjacent lots. Neighbors sued to make him tone
down the display, arguing that traffic jams of onlookers from miles
around prevented them from enjoying their own property during the
holidays. He lost, and appealed on First Amendment and other
grounds all the way to the Supreme Court, which declined to hear
the case.
</P>
<P>
   But there is an epilogue: Walt Disney Co. officials offered to
buy Osborne's lights _ all 350 miles of them, along with 32.2 miles
of extension cords _ and they are now on display on the back lot at
the MGM Studios theme park near Disney World in central Florida.
</P>
<P>
   When a dispute revolves around enforcement of local ordinances,
codes and community rules, a third party such as a town board or
homeowners' association often becomes involved, and winds up in
court against one party or the other. An example is the long battle
between Nelson Peltz, the chairman and chief executive of the
Triarc Companies, and his neighbors in the wealthy Westchester town
of Bedford over his commuting habits.
</P>
<P>
   Peltz built a helipad on his 100-acre estate and began using it
occasionally to travel between his home and his office 40 miles
away in Manhattan. The noise of his helicopter irritated the actor
E.G. Marshall and other neighbors, who complained to the town
government that the flights violated zoning laws. The town sued
Peltz successfully to keep him from using the pad. He switched to
using an old airstrip elsewhere on the property, which he contends
is legal because the strip predates the town zoning law. The town
sued again, and the case is pending.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, ``there are still complaints coming from neighbors
about late-night helicopter landings that are preventing some
people from sleeping,'' said Joel Sachs, the town's attorney. The
aggrieved neighbors, he said, see ``no reason why he can't hop in
his car and drive to the airport, five minutes away.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
