<SLUG> BC-INDY-COUNTDOWN0526-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When A.J. talks, Salazar listens
 &HT;    By Dave Lance
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Racing legend and team owner A.J. Foyt has yet to
advise Eliseo Salazar about his finances, what to eat or when to be
in bed.
</P>
<P>
   Off the track, Salazar can do what he wants. On it, he's all
ears, hanging on the four-time Indianapolis 500 winner's every
word.
</P>
<P>
   Foyt's advice is something like, ``Go fast,'' and Salazar has
been the obedient pupil. Racing in Foyt's G-Force/Oldsmobile last
Saturday at Indianapolis Motor Speedway, Salazar completed his
four-lap time trial in 223.231 mph, which put him in the front row
in the third position for Sunday's Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way (Foyt) said we were going to do it; peak on
Saturday,'' Salazar said. ``He's won this thing four times. I'll do
whatever he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out and did what he said and we got (third). So what
can I say?''
</P>
<P>
   Salazar also started Indy on the outside in row one in 1996, but
hopes this time he has better success in the race. Citing nerves,
Salazar crashed into Arie Luyendyk leaving the pits on lap 98.
</P>
<P>
   That was before Salazar, a 44-year-old native of Santiago,
Chile, hooked up with Foyt. He joined Foyt's racing team this
season and has seen immediate dividends with two top five finishes
in Indy Racing League events.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the experience from A.J., I'm much more relaxed,''
Salazar said. ``We can't wait for Race Day.''
</P>
<P>
   A friendship has formed between the two, but not so much that
Foyt has taken up Salazar's native language, Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can say chile con queso,'' Salazar said, ``but that's about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Foyt was probably saying something unprintable during Salazar's
last lap of qualifying. Salazar averaged 223.410 his first three
laps, but said he lost concentration and made it around the track
in 222.695 on the last.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like he said, he looked at the (darn) computer and he had run
a 223.7,'' Foyt said. ``All of a sudden he got in the corner and he
lost concentration. Then he had to get out the best he could.''
</P>
<P>
   He did, and put himself in a position other drivers would envy.
Too bad for Salazar no one seems to notice. The line for Salazar's
autograph is always a short one. His comments concerning
19-year-old phenom Sarah Fisher didn't help endear him to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   After the two crashed last month in Las Vegas, Salazar said,
while leaving the infield care center, ``This is serious stuff.
This is not for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Salazar has since apologized, but the damage was already done:
He had insulted a fan favorite who has raced since she was 5.
</P>
<P>
   Salazar apologized last week and congratulated Fisher on
qualifying for Indy.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 19 years old, I was racing small cars in Chile,'' Salazar
said. ``And here she is at the Indy 500. I said things I regret,
but I feel like I helped her a lot because look at all the
publicity she's received.''
</P>
<P>
   Salazar hopes he gets all the press on race day, as winner of
the Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
