<HEADLINE>
EPA ORDERS ASBESTOS CLEANUP IN MONTANA  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The federal Environmental Protection Agency has ordered
W.R. Grace &AMP; Co. to clean up the site of mining operations the
company once owned in Libby, Mont., where tests found dangerous
levels of asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   Grace mined vermiculite for 27 years in the Libby area, and the
operations sent tons of asbestos dust into the air. For years, area
residents have blamed the asbestos for illnesses and deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA began testing in the area last year after a series of
newspaper articles focused new attention on the unusual mortality
rate of former mine workers and members of their families.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement with the EPA, Grace will clean a site once
used as a products transportation center in Libby. Also, agency
officials said the federal government would clean another Grace
mining site just outside of Libby and seek reimbursement from the
company afterward.
</P>
<P>
   EPA officials said they expected the cleaning of both sites to
be completed this summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
