<SLUG> BC-VW-AUCTION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SALE: A ROCK-SOLID VW 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Perhaps you considered buying a New Beetle, but
decided the $16,000-and-up car wasn't roomy enough. Now you have a
chance to buy one with no inside space at all, at an estimated
price of $70,000-plus. Oh, yes: This one doesn't run. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is, in fact, a lump of clay with four wheels, a full-size
model for the final design of the Volkswagen on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   The clay model is due to be auctioned on June 8 by Christie's in
New York, as part of a sale of 20th century decorative arts called
``Masterworks: 1900-2000.''
</P>
<P>
   The model would seem to be a white elephant in the sale, which
includes furniture by Charles Rennie Mackintosh, the Scottish
architect and designer; a town house at 242 E. 52nd St. designed by
Philip Johnson, and a prototype of a streamlined pencil sharpener
by Raymond Loewy, whose designs included the sleek '53 Studebaker
Starliner. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to create a catalog of the best of the 20th century
in art and architecture,'' said Lars Rachen, head of Christie's
20th century decorative arts department. ``When we came to the end
of the 20th century in developing our wish list, we thought about
what really represented the '90s movement of revolutionizing
product and brand.'' Rachen said a life-size clay model elevated
the Beetle to the realm of sculpture. He persuaded VW, which will
reap the proceeds, less Christie's commission, to offer the model
for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's expects the model to sell in a range of $70,000 to
$100,000, though Rachen concedes that there is little basis on
which to make estimates. No full-size auto clays are known to have
been auctioned, he said. Typically, automakers reuse the clay in
other models, or it is destroyed as designers take measurements for
molds needed in production. VW's designers provided instructions on
how to care for and repair the clay, which will eventually crack. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The model, of steel, wood and foam covered with modeling clay,
is 59 inches tall, 68 inches wide and 161 inches long. It weighs
nearly 2 tons; the wheels turn. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Freeman Thomas, one of 18 designers on the original New Beetle
team, who now heads the design department at DaimlerChrysler, said:
``I'm sure someone would want to have it in their collection. I
hope it is bought by someone who will preserve it and appreciate
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said it was sad that VW was not keeping the model.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were me and I were Volkswagen, I would never, never sell
something like that at any price,'' he said. ``It is part of their
history.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just as difficult to place an estimate on the worth of the model
is to guess who will buy it. Rechen said he hoped that a museum,
perhaps one that specializes in applied arts or design, would bid.
</P>
<P>
   The model will be on view in the climate-controlled galleries at
Christie's, 20 Rockefeller Plaza, starting June 3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 2045EDT &QL; 
