u a BC-GLUE0526-COX     05-25 0328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLUE0526-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glue gets girl out of sticky situation
 &HT;    By Duane D. Stanford
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - When a potted cactus fell on 6-year-old Kailey
Browning, more than 600 hard-to-see spines stuck in her arms.
</P>
<P>
   At the emergency room, doctors weren't sure how to remove the
needles without putting the little girl through excruciating pain.
The odd solution _ Elmer's glue.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mark Stegelman, an Emory Eastside Medical Center
pediatrician, poured the glue on Kailey's arms, dried it with a
surgical lamp and peeled away the little girl's hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I wanted to do was get my daughter out of pain and here he
was with something so simple,'' Lory Browning said.
</P>
<P>
   Stegelman, who uses credit cards to flick bee stingers out of
patients' skin, got the glue idea from an Atlanta doctor who
recently learned about it at a pediatric conference in cactus-rich
Nevada. Because kids do the darnedest things, Stegelman said,
pediatricians often share innovative ways to deal with their
unusual predicaments _ like running into a cactus in Georgia. After
locating a fresh bottle of glue at the hospital's maintenance
office, Stegelman slathered it all over the soft underside of
Kailey's arm. Staffers and nurses gathered to watch.
</P>
<P>
   The glue took about 45 minutes to dry into that grayish-clear
hard coat kids like to call ``skin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As we peeled it, we could see the spines in the glue,''
recalled Stegelman, who used tweezers to remove the last 70 or so
the glue didn't get.
</P>
<P>
   The glue method saved hours and as much as $200 over tweezing
the spines, the doctor said.
</P>
<P>
   Kailey is back to riding her bike and playing Nintendo. She has
just a few spines left under the skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever they come out of my skin two or three days from now,
they will probably hurt,'' she predicted, ``but all I have to do is
put Elmer's glue on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
