<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5875 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-BOS &LR;      05-25 1826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES STRUGGLE WITH THE UNFAMILIAR: LOSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ They were ``scruffin'' and scrounging, unsure of
themselves, wondering if their missing shortstop meant as much to
their team as this, a team that had lost itself for two weeks. A
team in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs? The Tigers?
</P>
<P>
   No, the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious we've been frustrated,'' said Yankee lefthander
Andy Pettitte, who came through Wednesday night when Roger Clemens
couldn't the previous night. ``We were in a little slump.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been this way for years for the Yankees, who've loomed
head and shoulders above the rest of baseball for the last two
seasons. But with Derek Jeter out, the team in a full-scale hitting
slump, second baseman Chuck Knoblauch again bizarrely bouncing
throws in the general direction of first base, and no pitcher able
to step up and stop the slide until Pettitte Wednesday night, there
were traces of doubt in Yankee eyes and Yankee voices. Even if it
is only May.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not used to this,'' said Pettitte. ``We're very
unfamiliar with this losing. We've spoiled ourselves with how much
we've been winning and it's tough when you're not used to losing.
When you start losing when you're not used to losing, it's all the
tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   In consecutive games, Sunday in Cleveland and Tuesday in
Chicago, the Yankees had been shut down by young pitchers just
recalled from the minors the previous day. Manager Joe Torre had
been unusually frank in his disappointment with the
still-inconsistent Clemens (``It's frustrating when you expect a
well-pitched game and you don't get one''), who gave up a three-run
homer to the White Sox' Brook Fordyce in Fordyce's second at-bat of
the season Tuesday night as Chicago chased Clemens in the fifth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question the team is down,'' Torre said Tuesday.
``You could just sense that everybody knew we needed to turn this
around and there was a lot of screaming and yelling in the dugout,
but it wasn't to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, battered and bruised in body and spirit, had lost
eight of 11 games entering Thursday night's game against the White
Sox and James Baldwin, the American League's hottest pitcher. The
combination of the slump and the prospect of facing Baldwin left
the Yankees unwilling to look as far into the future as this
weekend, when the Yankees meet the Red Sox in a three-game set that
begins Friday night at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not talking about the Red Sox,'' said the Yankees' Paul
O'Neill. ``We've got things to do before that series.''
</P>
<P>
   Like winning.
</P>
<P>
   Not the division, not the penannt, not the World Series. Just a
game or two or three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we can put together a stretch now,'' said Pettitte
after the Yankees pounded out a season-high 18 hits in Wednesday's
12-4 win over the White Sox. ``We've got to continue to battle
through this slump.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rocket needed a lift
</P>
<P>
   A night earlier, the fried chicken and barbecue ribs had gone
virtually untouched by the players after Clemens had failed
miserably (4 IP, 7 H, 6 R, 6 ER) when he was most needed. The
Yankee clubhouse was glum.
</P>
<P>
   Newcomer Lance Johnson had embraced Clemens in the locker room,
saying the pitcher ``needed some love and I was just trying to do
whatever I can to lift spirits.'' Yankee spirits were low.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is getting tired,'' said catcher Jorge Posada. ``It's
getting tired, you know, the losses. We've got a good team but it's
not happening. We're not doing whatever it takes to win; it's
frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Torre, ``There's no magic formula to breaking slumps. You
just have to hitch it up and grit your teeth a little bit and fight
your way through it.''
</P>
<P>
   All baseball teams struggle like this, but for the last two
years, it seemed the Yankees were immune to the game's ebbs and
flows. The Yankees never struggled. And now that the depths had
swallowed up the Yankees, the experience was unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you, we go up there to the plate and it seems every
pitcher is coming right at us and getting us out,'' said Posada,
whose bat (.345) has stood out amid the slump. ``It's so
frustrating offensively. We go out there and we try to do too much.
We've just got to go out there and play as a team, as a lineup, and
not as individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter has been out with an abdominal strain and is eligible to
come off the 15-day disabled list Saturday but Torre said he is not
sure how soon his shortstop will return to full duty. Jeter will
play in a minor league game Friday. Even with Jeter out, said
Posada, ``We can't worry about that; he's not with us. The rest of
us have got to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' slump resulted in the usual New York tabloids'
Fantasy League trades, such as New York obtaining the Cubs' Sammy
Sosa (the laughter in Chicago could be heard in Milwaukee), Tampa
Bay's Jose Canseco, and a few other sluggers.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, of course, will return to winning, but it is
unclear if this is the same dominant Yankee team of the last two
years. Clemens has been inconsistent, staff ace Orlando ``El
Duque'' Hernandez is 4-4 with a 3.95 ERA, the .270 team batting
average was among the worst in the league, and, on a team no longer
dominant, the sheer fright of a Knoblauch throw to first base, for
example, takes on more meaning than the mere peculiarity it was
last year.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the pitching that concerns Torre.
</P>
<P>
   A baseball team ``bases its effort off its starting pitcher,''
Torre said Tuesday, ``and anytime a Roger Clemens gives up three
home runs it's a letdown for the team. There's no question. It's
not an excuse. But the combination of our trying to get the big hit
with Roger not having his best outing, that combination had made it
more frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees weren't hitting, Torre conceded, ``but I'm more
concerned about our pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Yankees don't seem to have is the one pitcher, such as
the Red Sox' Pedro Martinez, who can personally heal a team's
ailments. Pettitte, as usual, has been clutch but ``El Duque'' has
been hittable, David Cone is 1-3 with a 5.75 ERA, and Clemens has
struggled.
</P>
<P>
   When Clemens was asked about his inconsistency, he lapsed into
his usual pitcher-speak about ``velocity'' and ``location'' rather
than the grander picture of pitching well from game to game.
</P>
<P>
   Is he frustrated? Clemens was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my velocity was plenty good,'' came the Clemens reply,
``and I think I could probably take a little off (his velocity) to
try and locate better. I was sharp at times . . . but that ball to
Fordyce, I left too much of it out over the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre, meanwhile, said, ``I always get surprised when this
happens because of the fact that he's Roger Clemens. His stuff was
good, but his location was way off.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bernie Williams? ``We've overcome a lot of adversity in the
past,'' he said. ``This should be no different than those other
times. It just happens to be we're playing bad right now.
Hopefully, we'll get out of it sooner than later.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Batters out of order
</P>
<P>
   Going into Thursday night's game, Williams had batted second six
times as Torre had tried to fill at least part of the Jeter void by
putting his most dependable hitter in Jeter's spot. ``It's very
important for the top of our lineup to hit well if we're going to
win,'' said Torre. ``That's why I put Bernie in the No. 2 slot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a prototypical cleanup hitter anyway,'' said Williams.
``I don't hit any different batting second.''
</P>
<P>
   What he tries to do every at-bat, whether he's second or fourth,
is ``to try and react to the situation facing me,'' said Williams.
``If it's moving the runner, I'll try my best, and if it's driving
him in, I'll do my best, too. After you hit (second) the first time
in the lineup, after that it doesn't matter. You'll be facing
situations that call on you to do a lot of different things.''
</P>
<P>
   No difference, though.
</P>
<P>
   Williams has gone 9 for 31 in the second slot.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the bottom third of the order that has devastated the
Yankees. No matter whom Torre places in the seventh, eighth, and
ninth positions, he is left with Mendoza Line hitters.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's game, for instance, the Yankees loaded the bases
with one out in the second inning against White Sox lefthander Mike
Sirotka. But Ricky Ledee (.215) waved feebly at a third strike and
shortstop Clay Bellinger (.176) looked on futilely as Sirotka fired
a third strike past him. Once again, no runs from a prosperous
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, said Williams, it's early in the season. True, two years
ago at this time, the Yankees had vaulted far ahead of their rivals
by now, and by this time last year, had begun to inch away from the
Red Sox. Still, said Williams, ``Only a quarter of the season has
been played; what? Sixty games. There are still a lot of things
that can happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've got to do is make sure the guys who are healthy,
stay healthy. Hopefully we'll go back to the way we're capable of
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are ``a team that goes out there expecting to win
every game. And when we don't win, we're the first ones to ask the
question: `What's wrong with us?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have been asking that question time and again the
last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In motion with clutch hit
</P>
<P>
   The final score Wednesday night was 12-4, but that final score
was most deceptive. New York was trailing, 2-1, in the seventh
inning when Johnson had the at-bat of the week, if not the month,
for the Yankees, when he pinch hit with two on. The Yankees had
squandered many such opportunities during the slump but this time
Johnson, the former White Sox, drove a single to center, setting
off a seven-run explosion that was highlighted when O'Neill cleared
the bases with a double off the left-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what the situation was and how I needed to come
through,'' said Johnson. ``The team's been in the slump and I knew
I had to be aggressive up there to make things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It is seldom said publicly by baseball players, but Johnson said
``luck'' is a primary ingredient in slumps. ``We just needed to get
some luck on our side, to have the hits fall in that hadn't been
falling in,'' said Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   But in the joy of the Yankees' locker room, the players eating
their postgame chicken and ribs after the win, there was one dark
undercurrent. Knoblauch was back to firing throws to first base of
which a Little Leaguer would be ashamed.
</P>
<P>
   On past Yankee teams, this mattered little. ``It's a head
thing'' with him, said Torre, who noted that Knoblauch had been
throwing normally up to now. But on a 2000 Yankee team that doesn't
seem dominant enough to pull away from its rivals, an eccentricity
can grow into much more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
