<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-CORZINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE CANDIDATE SMASHES SPENDING RECORD FOR A PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ In a race that threatens to redefine the limits
of what it costs to run for the U.S. Senate, Jon Corzine has
already spent nearly $25 million on his race for the Democratic
nomination, more than three times as much as anyone has ever spent
on a Senate primary and within striking distance of the most money
ever spent on an entire Senate election.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey primary for the seat being vacated by Sen. Frank
Lautenberg is not until June 6. But as of May 17, Corzine had spent
$24.9 million on his contest with former Gov. Jim Florio, according
to documents filed Thursday with the Federal Elections Commission.
The previous record for spending in a Senate primary is believed to
be the $8.1 million spent by Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., in his
1998 race against Geraldine Ferraro and Mark Green.
</P>
<P>
   The record for spending in an entire Senate race is now held by
Michael Huffington, the Republican millionaire who lost to Sen.
Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., in 1994 after pouring nearly $30
million into his campaign, $28 million of which came from his own
fortune. The record for any statewide primary is the $38 million
spent by Al Checchi, an airline executive, in an unsuccessful bid
for the Democratic nomination for governor in California in 1998.
Because of its size and array of major media markets, California is
regarded as by far the most expensive state to mount a political
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine is likely to exceed Huffington's record even before
primary day. Since May 17, for example, Corzine has boosted his
purchases of television commercials in New York and Philadelphia by
50 percent, to $2 million a week, which is itself said to be a new
high for New Jersey political campaigns. And in the last week of
the primary campaign, Corzine is expected to spend close to another
$2 million on get-out-the-vote efforts, like hiring street workers
to knock on doors and telemarketers to make phone calls to his
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in uncharted territory, here, and I don't think anybody
knows how high it'll go, except possibly Mr. Corzine himself,''
said Larry Makinson, executive director of the Center for
Responsive Politics in Washington. ``My sense is there's a whole
generation of sons and daughters of political consultants who'll be
going to the best Ivy League schools by the time this campaign is
over. And this could do for the profession of political consulting
what Watergate did for investigative journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio has accused his rival of trying to ``buy the election,''
and Thursday, several advocates of campaign finance reform took up
that refrain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you have a race with this kind of huge money,''
said Fred Wertheimer, president of Democracy 21, a Washington
public policy group, ``it takes you one step closer to a system
dominated by very wealthy people, or people who are completely
indebted to their campaign donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of choice we're given in the congressional
campaign finance system today, and it's a bad choice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine defends his campaign expenditures as necessary for a
political newcomer running against a household name like Florio.
And many experts say that New Jersey can be a particularly costly
place to run for statewide office, because the state has no widely
watched television station of its own, forcing candidates to
advertise on TV stations in both New York City and Philadelphia _
the nation's first and fourth most expensive media markets,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the hardest place in the world to communicate, to pop
through to the voters and get a message through, and Corzine's
running against someone who's universally known,'' said Hank
Morris, a consultant who has run campaigns in New York and New
Jersey, including Schumer's in 1998. ``There are only two ways to
get through to the voters in New Jersey: to communicate over a
very, very long time, which is what Florio's done, or to spend a
very large amount of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Since last summer, when Corzine paid thousands for consultants
to polish his presentation skills and help develop his political
platform, he has presided over the Rolls-Royce of campaigns. But in
the six-and-a-half-week period covered in his most recent FEC
filing, his spending accelerated, paying out a total of $14.6
million, or more than $300,000 a day.
</P>
<P>
   In that period, his campaign bought $10.7 million worth of TV
and radio commercials, and $946,595 of newspaper ads. It spent
$337,607 on postage for direct mailings. It paid its consultants
$446,972, its canvassers $133,590, and its pollsters $639,600 _ at
a time when those pollsters still had not begun conducting nightly
tracking surveys.
</P>
<P>
   Over 47 days, the Corzine campaign paid 44 different catering
bills totaling $113,063.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Florio's shoestring campaign spent all of $1.1
million over the same period, $900,000 of that to purchase TV
advertisements that began running only on Wednesday, 10 weeks after
Corzine's television campaign started. All told, since last year,
Florio has spent $1.9 million running for the Democratic nomination
_ meaning that he has now been outspent by more than 13-to-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``One would want some kind of financial balance in our campaign
process,'' said Wertheimer, of Democracy 21. ``And whatever the
appropriate balance might be, this huge sum far exceeds it. You get
to a point where it appears like someone is buying a seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio continued Wednesday to describe Corzine's spending as
``obscene.''
</P>
<P>
   ``However this thing turns out, he's going to be the poster boy
for campaign finance reform,'' Florio said, likening his rival to
``the oligarchs in Russia who are buying places in power, buying
the government.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our own new set of oligarchs, and they have a new
champion,'' Florio added. ``Or maybe it's a co-champion, between
Steve Forbes and Jon Corzine.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's co-campaign manager, Steven Goldstein, responded
equally harshly. ``Jon Corzine has spent one dollar for every lie
Jim Florio has told in this campaign,'' he said, adding that
Florio's $2.8 billion 1990 tax hike as governor remained of greater
importance to the New Jersey electorate than the subject of
campaign finance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters will care far more about the billions of dollars Jim
Florio has taken out of their pockets than the millions Jon Corzine
has taken out of his,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
