u f BC-NEWENGLAND-ECONOMY-BO     05-25 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWENGLAND-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGION'S ECONOMY IS EXPECTED TO COOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This may be as good as it gets.
</P>
<P>
   Even as business activity and hiring in New England continue to
sizzle, area economists warn that growth in the region will begin
to slow this year amid rising interest rates, a weaker stock
market, and a vexing shortage of workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy currently is on fire,'' said Mark Zandi, chief
economist atRFA/Dismal Sciences, at the annual outlook meeting of
the New England Economic Project. ``You could easily argue that New
England is the strongest economy in the country, bar none.''
</P>
<P>
   That's been true only twice since World War II, Zandi said
Thursday, and not in the past 15 years. But Boston is seeing signs
of a peak, from higher prices on goods and services to a slowdown
from the spike in home building.
</P>
<P>
   The very foundation of the region's rise _ the high-tech boom
and the rise of personal investing _ make it more vulnerable than
the rest of the country in an eventual downturn, Zandi said. Scores
of start-ups could find themselves short of money and mulling
layoffs or sales to larger rivals, he suggested. Similarly, the
area's many mutual fund companies and investment houses could
struggle if the market dives further.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate future is reasonably bright. Economists are
projecting growth for the region to top out at 4 percent this year
but to stay in the upper 2 percent range through 2004. Employment
growth is expected continue at half its recent pace, to about 1
percent annually. Real income growth is expected slow to 1.9
percent in 2004, down from 4 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The wild cards in the forecast: technology and the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Economists at Thursday's outlook conference apologized for past
predictions of gloom that turned out wrong. They said it was hard
to foresee that the so-called ``wealth effect'' from the stock
market would keep individuals and companies spending money for nine
straight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economists have really underestimated the role of technology
in economic growth,'' said Stanley Feldman, associate professor of
finance at Bentley College and director of the economic project.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment nationally has been below 5 percent for five years,
down from a 7 percent average in the prior 20 years. Gross domestic
product, notching a vigorous 5.4 percent in the first quarter, has
been running at 4 percent for five years, up from 3 percent for the
prior 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, workers are more efficient than ever, thanks in large
part to better technology. Productivity is still improving about 3
percent annually; from 1974 through 1994, the average didn't hit 2
percent. More people own homes than ever, and nearly half the
country owns stocks, up from one-third a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   New England has the lowest jobless rate in the country, at 2.5
percent. Personal income has jumped about 6 percent for three
straight years and is expected to do the same in 2000. And consumer
confidence is scraping the very top of the scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost impossible to find any sense of gloom or
pessimism,'' said John Gorman, president of Opinion Dynamics, which
measures confidence for the economic project.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, dot-com millionaires still grace the covers of magazines
and companies can't find enough employees. But the dramatic growth
in the regional economy in recent years won't continue, said
Charles Cogan, a professor at the University of Southern Maine.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time, we really, really mean it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Economists from each state in the region pointed to similar
problems on the horizon. They said growth will slow because there
simply aren't enough workers for big companies like Cisco and IBM,
which are expanding here, to hire. Too few workers and the recent
jump in energy prices will push up prices.
</P>
<P>
   Boston is expected to see a 4 percent jump in the consumer price
index this year, up from 2.5 percent last year and the biggest rise
in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Other risks in the economy include a surge in borrowing and
lower savings rates, especially among people earning less than
$40,000, the US median household income.
</P>
<P>
   As a region, New England faces a transportation crisis, said
Michael Gallis, a North Carolina economist. Distracted by the Big
Dig and without a solid plan for its seaports, airports and roads,
he said, the region is at risk of locking itself out of the global
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It represents a real threat to the region,'' Gallis said.
</P>
<P>
   The economists made clear that the states will be spending
hundreds of millions of dollars to improve roads, shipping ports,
and regional airports in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   The key may be to accomplish those plans before the next
recession. Jeffrey Carr, a Vermont economist from Economic and
Policy Resources Inc., said he expects no recession through 2004.
Even then, he said, ``Upturns don't die of old age.'' His view: The
Federal Reserve could kill this longest expansion in history.
</P>
<P>
   A worse case scenario, said Edward Deak, a professor at
Fairfield University in Connecticut, is that the Fed could hike
rates another 2.5 points in a year, much more than Wall Street
expects. That would surely slam the brakes on the market, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Look out seven or eight years and the picture becomes far more
grim. By then, this wave of Internet innovation will be maturing,
suggested Dennis Delay, senior economist at the Public Service Co.
of New Hampshire. And the baby boomers will start taking money out
of those retirement funds that have helped fuel the bull market.
</P>
<P>
   Said Zandi, ``New England has benefited the most and it will be
hurt the most if the market stumbles significantly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
