<SLUG> BC-FUNDING-LOOPHOLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS REJECT CAMPAIGN REFORM EFFORT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Lloyd Doggett, D-Texas, failed Thursday to win
approval of a measure that would force tax-exempt political
fund-raising organizations to disclose their contributors and
expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, aimed at curbing the growing power of groups that
secretly raise and spend millions to influence elections, was
defeated in the House 214-207, with most Democrats supporting it
and most Republicans voting against it.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was offered as part of motion to recommit a bill
that repeals the 102-year-old federal excise tax on telephones.
That bill passed overwhelmingly, after Republicans turned back
Doggett's motion.
</P>
<P>
   The Doggett proposal, which was also rejected by the House Ways
and Means Committee for a second time Thursday, is designed to
crack down on so-called ``stealth PACs'' or ``527 organizations''
that get special tax breaks by claiming to be political
fund-raising groups but avoid federal campaign disclosure laws by
denying any political affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   The groups qualify for tax-exempt status under Section 527 of
the Internal Revenue Service Code, which permits them to keep their
fund-raising and spending activities private.
</P>
<P>
   Doggett's proposal would force the groups to file their donor
and spending records with the IRS or lose their tax-exempt status.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans argued that they needed more time to study
whether other tax-exempt groups should be forced to disclose their
fund-raising and spending habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is against full disclosure. But today is not the time
and this is not the place for this debate,'' said Rep. Amory
Houghton, R-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   He urged his colleagues to wait for a package of tax code
revisions being drawn up by House Ways and Means Committee Chairman
Bill Archer, R-Texas, that may end up closing a number of loopholes
that allow groups to conduct campaign activities in secrecy and
without any regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Doggett, however, accused Republicans of trying to delay action
on his legislation until the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 527 is not some type of new secret aircraft, but it is the
superweapon that can undermine this election,'' Doggett said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Republicans won't support his proposal because it
will end up costing them valuable support in this year's campaigns
from 527 groups with ties to House Majority Whip Tom DeLay,
R-Texas, and other Republican leaders.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay is being sued by the Democratic Congressional Campaign
Committee for allegedly using the organizations, at least three of
which are run by or were organized by former aides and associates,
to help Republican candidates avoid federal election contribution
and spending limits. DeLay has denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   One DeLay-affiliated group, the Republican Majority Issues
Committee, is planning to raise and spend $25 million on
advertising, polling, mailings and other campaign activities in at
least a dozen congressional races this year.
</P>
<P>
   As Doggett's motion was being voted down Thursday, the Federal
Election Commission was taking up a proposal that would force 527
organizations to register with the FEC, which would require them to
report their expenditures and the identities of their contributors.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was offered by FEC Commissioner Karl Sandstrom, a
Democrat, who has described 527s as little more than ``political
slush funds.'' At the FEC meeting, he said the groups are engaged
in an ``audacious circumvention'' of federal campaign laws, which
were enacted after the Watergate scandal to promote full disclosure
in federal elections.
</P>
<P>
   The FEC is not expected to act on Sandstrom's proposal before
the November elections. The commission, however, may hold public
hearings on it before then.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
