u e BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT &LR;      05-25 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A STAR REBUKED BY EQUITY
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a mild rebuke, a disciplinary panel of Actors
Equity has ruled that Patrick Stewart, the star of Arthur Miller's
``Ride Down Mount Morgan,'' will have to make a formal _ but not
public _ apology to the Shubert Organization for a curtain speech
he made attacking the play's producers.
</P>
<P>
   The speech, in which Stewart accused the Shuberts of failing to
promote ``Mount Morgan,'' prompted the Shuberts to file
disciplinary charges against Stewart accusing him of unprofessional
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing several hours of testimony on May 11, the panel,
composed of five union members, made its decision.
</P>
<P>
   A 10-day appeal period ended Thursday, and several people
familiar with the decision said Stewart would not appeal it.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who has won critical praise for his role as a defiant
bigamist in ``Mount Morgan,'' made the speech at the matinee and
evening performances of ``Mount Morgan'' on April 29. He said he
felt ``frustrated and helpless'' because of what he considered the
producers' lack of support for the play.
</P>
<P>
   The Shuberts countered by saying that more than $1 million had
been spent on promoting the play, which received good reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Under Equity rules, an actor found to be behaving in an
unprofessional manner can be fined or, in extremely rare cases,
expelled from the union.
</P>
<P>
   TONY TELECAST LINEUP
</P>
<P>
   The Tony Awards announced the schedule Thursday for the June 4
telecast, and the entertainment lineup was no surprise: seven
musical numbers (from three revivals and four new musicals), and a
big opening number from the host Rosie O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   As for the plays, Keith Sherman, a spokesman for the awards,
said the plays would be part of ``a videotaped package'' devoted to
both new work and revivals. Last year's approach _ a medley of
lines from a half-dozen plays _ was widely viewed as a failure.
</P>
<P>
   One small surprise Thursday: Nathan Lane will help O'Donnell
with the hosting duties. His official title? Special guest star.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had toyed with saying `The Tony Awards, hosted by Rosie
O'Donnell, valet parking by Nathan Lane,''' he said. ``But they
thought this was better.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KEVIN SPACEY STEPS UP
</P>
<P>
   As far as pinch hitters go, there are not many people you'd
rather have in your dugout than Kevin Spacey.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask the current cast and crew of ``Cobb,'' the 1989 drama
by Lee Blessing about the irascible baseball legend Ty Cobb who
starred for the Detroit Tigers in the early years of the century.
The show, which received good reviews but has had only decent
audiences, was to have closed its run at Theater 3 on West 43rd
Street last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But then Spacey entered the game. Last Thursday night, Spacey, a
recent Oscar winner for ``American Beauty,'' saw ``Cobb'' during a
sweep through New York between films. The draw, he said, was
Matthew Mabe, who plays the title role and was an understudy last
year in ``The Iceman Cometh,'' in which Spacey starred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured I should go to support Matthew,'' said Spacey.
``Plus, I never knew anything about Cobb.''
</P>
<P>
   What he found so impressed him that when he heard about the
imminent closing, he pulled out the theatrical equivalent of a
Louisville Slugger: his checkbook.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Spacey nor officials at the Melting Pot Theater Company,
the producers, are saying how much money Spacey gave, but it was
enough to extend the run at least two weeks. Spacey has been
phoning ``anybody who'll take my call'' to get producers to see the
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the kind of theater I like to encourage,'' Spacey said.
``I don't mind kicking up a little dust to get people to pay
attention to something like this.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `SWEET SMELL'
</P>
<P>
   In the canon of loathsome megalomaniacs, they don't get much
better than J.J. Hunsecker.
</P>
<P>
   Portrayed by Burt Lancaster in the 1957 classic, ``Sweet Smell
of Success,'' Hunsecker is a powerful Broadway columnist whose
career of dishing gossip and innuendo has hardened him into a dark,
ruthless cipher.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Hunsecker is a character most actors would love to
play. Now, with a workshop of the musical version of ``Sweet
Smell'' in the offing, John Lithgow has landed the role. Brian
d'Arcy James will play Sidney Falco, the scurrilous press agent
portrayed by Tony Curtis in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Lithgow is probably best known now from the television show
``Third Rock From the Sun.'' But he won a Tony in 1973 for ``The
Changing Room'' and was nominated two other times.
</P>
<P>
   The six-week workshop, which begins on June 26, will conclude
with two sets of performances for potential producers at the
beginning of August. It is not, unfortunately, open to the public,
but the production itself is aiming for a Broadway debut in the
spring of 2001.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG PLAYWRIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   A youth movement (of sorts) has taken hold at Manhattan Theater
Club.
</P>
<P>
   The theater, which scored a critical hit this week with
``Proof,'' by the 30-year-old playwright David Auburn, has
announced a 2000-2001 schedule packed with all manner of talented
30-somethings.
</P>
<P>
   Heading the list is David Lindsay-Abaire, also 30, whose newest
play, ``Wonder of the World,'' opens the season on Stage One. The
show, about a woman who leaves her husband in search of adventure,
had its world premiere at the Woolly Mammoth Theater in Washington
this week. On Stage Two, the playwright Melanie Marnich, 37, will
stage her play ``Blur.''
</P>
<P>
   Another new voice, Rebecca Gilman, 35, will also be produced on
Stage One with her ``Boy Gets Girl,'' a drama about a woman who is
stalked by a stranger.
</P>
<P>
   In the sole nod to seniority, the latest from Alan Ayckbourn,
61, his ``Comic Potential,'' fills out the schedule on Stage One.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 2052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
