<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIPP-PRIVACY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 OFFICIALS REBUKED FOR TRIPP DISCLOSURES 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH BECKER  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Secretary of Defense William Cohen reprimanded his
spokesman, Kenneth Bacon, and another senior defense official
Thursday for releasing information to a journalist in 1998 from the
private personnel file of Linda Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's action came after a two-year investigation by the
inspector general of the Defense Department concluded earlier this
month that Bacon and his former assistant, Clifford H. Bernath, had
violated the federal Privacy Act by disclosing confidential
material from Tripp's Pentagon employment file.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the Justice Department found no reason to bring
criminal charges against the two officials.
</P>
<P>
   In his reprimand Thursday, Cohen expressed disappointment in
Bacon but said there was no evidence that his spokesman had
intended to harm Tripp in answering a reporter's inquiry two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to an inquiry from The New Yorker Magazine, Bacon and
Bernath told a reporter that Tripp had incorrectly stated on a
security clearance form that she had never been arrested. Jane
Mayer, a New Yorker writer who was working on a profile of Tripp,
had asked the officials whether the Pentagon employee had disclosed
a long-ago arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp's tape recordings of telephone conversations she had with
Monica S. Lewinsky led Kenneth Starr, who was then the Whitewater
independent counsel, to begin investigating President Clinton. That
investigation led to Clinton's impeachment in the most serious
presidential scandal since Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   Mayer asked the Pentagon spokesman whether Tripp had admitted on
her security clearance form that she was arrested in 1969 on a
charge of grand larceny that was later dismissed. On Bacon's
instructions, Bernath searched the file and discovered that Tripp
had not mentioned the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The Privacy Act prohibits the government from disclosing
employee records in most instances without the consent of the
employee
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said Thursday that while he respected Cohen's decision, he
believed that his conduct had been lawful under the federal Freedom
of Information Act, which makes such information available to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly never occurred to me that the Privacy Act would
preclude disclosing how a public figure recorded a public arrest
record on a security clearance,'' Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the chief state prosecutor of Maryland
dropped criminal wiretap charges against Tripp, concluding the only
criminal case against a major figure in the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp has filed a lawsuit against the White House, the
Department of Defense and Bacon, asserting that they had conspired
to intimidate her and that they had violated her rights under the
privacy act.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Bacon released that information, it had a devastating
impact on Linda Tripp's credibility during a crucial phase of the
Lewinsky investigation,'' Stephen M. Kohn, a lawyer for Tripp, said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Kohn said he would ask the president to overturn what he called
a mild rebuke, since the reprimand will not be included in Bacon's
personnel file. He said he would ask the president to take
immediate disciplinary action, which could include firing Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   In a news release, Bacon argued that the two-year investigation,
including 95 interviews, had found that there was no evidence of
White House involvement in his handling of the New Yorker request,
and that his only motive was ``a desire to be responsive to an
urgent media inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This matter is an extremely small part of a large and painful
national drama, which is why it has been studied by the Office of
Independent Counsel and the Justice Department, both of which
decided no further action was appropriate,'' Bacon said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 2055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
