<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5885 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-SULLIVAN-CLAYTON-     05-25 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SULLIVAN-CLAYTON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' CLAYTON WAS OUT OF LINE, BUT NOT A ROCKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Royce Clayton voiced an opinion last week. A
strong one.
</P>
<P>
   It may not have been one some people agree with, but if it came
from Clayton, you can be sure it was heartfelt, sincere and
carefully considered.
</P>
<P>
   In this case he was probably too harsh in his judgments about
teammate Chad Curtis. Curtis may be a fourth outfielder, but he has
been a valuable addition to the Rangers and saved them from
disaster when both Rusty Greer and Gabe Kapler went down with
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Like Clayton, though, Curtis] is strong-willed and opinionated
with heartfelt beliefs. They both took a stance they sincerely
believed, and it caused hard feelings. It was unfortunate there was
a problem, but it needed to be addressed, regardless of who was
right or wrong. Those in Rangers' management only fool themselves
if they think otherwise, and the problem was not simply that
Clayton went public.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton's preference from the beginning was to keep the dispute
within the clubhouse, but however he voiced his views, attention
must be paid.
</P>
<P>
   There are some athletes who like to pop off without knowing what
they are talking about. John Rocker is the ultimate example. Barry
Bonds does it all the time, and his San Francisco Giants teammates
only roll their eyes and ignore him, knowing it is Barry being
Barry.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton is not John Rocker. He is a person of substance, as
former club president Tom Schieffer observed when giving him a
four-year contract. Clayton's work in the community speaks for
itself. He is active in the Sickle Cell Foundation, the Jackie
Robinson Foundation and the Arlington school system. He is building
a youth ballpark in Lancaster.
</P>
<P>
   He is not given to controversy, but he does not back down. He
believes Major League Baseball should do more to promote baseball
in inner cities, at least as much as they do in Latin America. He
believes baseball hasn't done enough to promote the hiring of
African-Americans and Hispanics for managerial and front-office
positions, and he was willing to voice his concern in spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   His opinions should carry weight. It should not matter that he
is African-American. Yet it is obvious that he has received no
small amount of backlash for what he said last week.
</P>
<P>
   I asked him this week about the proposal to raise the pitcher's
mound and he begged off, saying, ``I don't think I'm going to have
any opinions for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in this case discretion is the better part of valor, but
it's obvious the flap has affected him. He was as hot as anybody in
the Rangers' lineup until the storm erupted; now he's struggling
with the bat again. He was hitless in 14 at-bats going into last
night's game.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis, in a testament to his character, has been truly
forgiving. When Clayton made a nice running catch Saturday night,
Curtis was there first with the high-five and the slap on the back.
He is willing to move on. Clayton should be allowed to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   He is not Alex Rodriguez or Nomar Garciaparra, but he is an
important part of the team. After Ivan Rodriguez, he is the
Rangers' second-best defensive player and a major contributor on
offense. The Rangers started taking off when he moved to the lower
half of the order and started crushing the baseball.
</P>
<P>
   He also loves to have fun. Clayton plays baseball with joy,
realizing that it truly is a game. If it's not fun, it's not worth
doing. But right now it's not fun and that's not good, for him or
the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   As Clayton said, the damage is done. But for the Rangers' sake,
the damage was limited and, as the season progresses, the wounds
will heal and he will be the player he should be.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no ignoring the person he is. {T.R. Sullivan writes
a column for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.} &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 2056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
