<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-MEDIAONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T CLEARS STEP IN BID TO PURCHASE MEDIAONE GROUP
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: (AT) is used in 6th graf in place of the symbol, which is
unreadable by some computer systems.) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department approved AT&AMP;T's proposed
acquisition of the MediaOne Group Thursday, giving the telephone
giant control over more than a third of the nation's cable network
for television, high-speed Internet access and online telephone
service.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, which requires the companies to sell their
interest in Road Runner, the nation's second-largest cable Internet
service, clears a significant regulatory hurdle. The companies now
await a decision, expected soon, by the Federal Communications
Commission. The staff of the commission has raised concerns about
the companies having too much control over both cable systems and
programming. Federal regulations prohibit a company from owning
more than 30 percent of the nation's cable systems and by some
estimates, AT&AMP;T would control more than 40 percent once it
completed its purchase of MediaOne.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors and consumer groups have also asked the FCC to force
the sale of more assets to assure that the marketplace for cable
television, high-speed Internet access and online telephone service
remains competitive.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed merger was valued at $58 billion when it was
announced a year ago during a wave of consolidation in the
telecommunications and high-speed Internet markets. Those deals
have posed a particular challenge for antitrust regulators because
of the complex interlocking ownership interests between cable
operators, programmers and high-speed Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   Both AT&AMP;T, which will be the nation's largest cable operator
when it completes the purchase of MediaOne, and Time Warner, which
will be the second largest, share interests in the same high-speed
Internet and programming companies.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, for instance, has a controlling interest in
Excite(AT)Home, the largest cable modem service, while MediaOne has
a substantial interest in Road Runner, the second-largest service.
Time Warner, which is being acquired by America Online, also has a
large interest in Road Runner. Moreover, MediaOne and Time Warner
have large interests in Time Warner Entertainment, a programming
and cable operating company.
</P>
<P>
   As its market share in the long-distance telephone business has
begun to erode, AT&AMP;T has embarked on a whirlwind of acquisitions to
transform itself into a company that will be able to offer
consumers a basket of services _ television, Internet service along
with local, long-distance and wireless telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, it has alarmed consumer groups and competitors
who are concerned that the the company is turning into an Internet
version of the powerhouse monopoly that it was before the
government broke it up 16 years ago. The critics have urged federal
officials to force AT&AMP;T to sell its interest in programming
operations and cable modem services.
</P>
<P>
   While officials at the Justice Department agreed with the
arguments over MediaOne's interest in Road Runner, they did not
find antitrust problems with other aspects of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The merger as proposed would have had an anti-competitive
impact on the emerging broadband market,'' said Joel Klein, the
assistant attorney general in charge of the antitrust division.
``The divestiture assures that AT&AMP;T will not acquire undue leverage
in its dealings with broadband content providers, and American
consumers will be the ultimate beneficiaries.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T executives hailed the decision, which they said they had
anticipated from the moment the deal was announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Road Runner divestiture is an obligation we always assumed
we would face, and the decree proposes both a schedule and process
that are fair and feasible,'' said James Cicconi, AT&AMP;T's general
counsel. ``We expect to gain FCC approval of the merger shortly.
After that, our intention is to close the merger as quickly as we
can. Customers are clamoring for broadband, digital cable
television and choice in local phone service. Our acquisition of
MediaOne will greatly increase our ability to deliver all of those
highly sought consumer services.''
</P>
<P>
   But consumer groups said the decision fell short of assuring
competition in the emerging market and urged the FCC to force the
companies to sell more assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an important first step, but we're disappointed that AT&AMP;T
was not also required to divest the cable systems and programming
they jointly own with the second-largest cable company, Time
Warner,'' said Gene Kimmelman, co-director of the Washington office
of Consumers Union. ``This begins to disentangle the web of
ownership between the two largest cable companies. The FCC should
now use its rules to split apart the programming networks and cable
systems that the two companies jointly own.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the staff of the FCC recommended that, because AT&AMP;T
had such a large market share of cable systems, the company should
relinquish either some control over those systems or some of their
interests in programming. Staff officials suggested that could be
accomplished by measures like divesting its programming units,
Liberty Media and Rainbow Media Sports Holdings Inc., or MediaOne's
interest in Time Warner Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, which is expected to issue its decision soon,
may adopt those recommendations, reject them or pursue another
course. But its hand in negotiating with AT&AMP;T was significantly
strengthened last Friday when a federal appeals court, reversing a
lower court decision, upheld the constitutionality of the
regulations that limit how much of the cable industry one company
may control.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
