<HEADLINE>
SHIITE MILITIA POISED TO BROADEN ITS BASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KHIAM, Lebanon _ The yellow flag of Hezbollah snapped in the
wind Thursday, high over the notorious prison complex of drab
cement buildings here.
</P>
<P>
   The storming of this prison, where opponents of Israel's
occupation were held and reportedly tortured, has become the symbol
of liberation to the guerrillas who this week forced the retreat of
Israel from Lebanon. It is their Bastille.
</P>
<P>
   And as Lebanon celebrated a new date on its calendar _
``Liberation Day'' _ the Shiite Muslim militia, Hezbollah, credited
with defeating the Israeli military, seized on this symbol.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah knows the importance of symbols such as Khiam, and is
likely to use them for political gain in the coming months. The
withdrawal of Israel paves the way for the Iran-backed group to
complete its transformation from military organization to ascendant
political force as Lebanon heads toward parliamentary elections in
July.
</P>
<P>
   ``This day should be called National Hezbollah Day,'' said Nizar
Hamzi, a political scientist at the American University of Beirut,
who is a specialist on the rise of Hezbollah. Currently, Hezbollah
as a political party has 20,000 registered members. It holds only
seven seats in Lebanon's 120-member Parliament, but its influence
far exceeds that. It has been known to attract 100,000 people at
its rallies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hezbollah has a broad base of support that is growing broader.
They are seen as heroes here now,'' said Hamzi. ``Their campaigning
for this summer is well underway, and they will do very well.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Islamic fundamentalism espoused by Hezbollah is met with
anxiety by those who feel its strict Islamic conservatism could
upset Lebanon's pluralism. Many Christian groups have watched with
concern as heavily armed Hezbollah guerrillas have paraded on tanks
confiscated from abandoned Israeli posts.
</P>
<P>
   Moving quickly to address such fears, Hezbollah has assured
Christians that the power vacuum left by the withdrawal of Israel
and its Christian-led proxy militia, the South Lebanon Army, would
be filled in an orderly fashion and that there would be no acts of
revenge against those Christians who have stayed in the region.
</P>
<P>
   It was a message reiterated by Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi, who gazed over Lebanon's border with Israel for the first
time Thursday during a tour of what Israel had called the security
zone.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on top of a hill controlled by Israel less than three
days ago, Kharrazi looked down on the nearby settlements of Israel,
the avowed enemy of Iran.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a victory promised in the Koran to the people who
exhibit patience and steadfastness,'' Kharrazi said at a rally of
the Shiite Muslim Hezbollah guerrillas in Bint Jbeil, in the former
occupied area.
</P>
<P>
   Former inmates Thursday led impromptu tours of the prison,
describing the different chambers where beatings took place, and
how the 140 men held here were forced to live amid filth and
overcrowding.
</P>
<P>
   Khiam was run by the South Lebanon Army. Human rights groups
have reported extensively on interrogation methods at Khiam that
included torture and in some cases led to death. Israel had
persistently denied the allegations. But in a recent court
affidavit, the Israeli military said that agents of Israel's
internal security service, the Shin Bet, were involved in
``everything having to do with gathering of intelligence and
questioning'' at Khiam.
</P>
<P>
   From all over the country, tens of thousands of people have been
flooding into Khiam and other sites.
</P>
<P>
   The streets were jammed with traffic by those who came to see
homes that they had been forced to abandon when the Israelis
invaded the area in 1982. Some came to see family and friends they
had left behind, and others to leave fresh flowers on overgrown
graves.
</P>
<P>
   In the village of Dibin, Ibrahim Yassin, 52, was back in his
hometown for the first time in 22 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the blood and bravery of Hezbollah that achieved
this,'' said Yassin. ``I don't think anyone will forget what they
did for our country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
