u f BC-AIR-MERGER-NYT &LR;      05-25 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU LIKELY TO SCRUTINIZE UAL-US AIRWAYS DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The European Commission said Thursday it would probably have to
review closely the competitive aspects of UAL Corp.'s proposed
takeover of US Airways.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement did not come as a surprise _ James E. Goodwin,
the chairman and chief executive of UAL, had said he expected the
deal would be subjected to scrutiny by the commission _ but it is
another hurdle the companies must clear to complete UAL's $4.3
billion acquisition of US Airways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have been surprised if they had said they wouldn't
look at this,'' said James Higgins, an airline industry analyst at
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. However, the US Airways-United
combination ``doesn't change the balance of power that much in the
North Atlantic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It primarily improves United's ability to pull traffic off the
East Coast,'' Higgins said, ``and traffic emanating east of the
Mississippi produces two-thirds of the traffic across the North
Atlantic.''
</P>
<P>
   United offers trans-Atlantic flights to six European cities from
Washington Dulles International Airport, Kennedy International
Airport in New York, Logan Airport in Boston, Newark International
Airport, Chicago O'Hare, San Francisco and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways offers service to Paris; Frankfurt, Germany; Madrid,
Spain; Rome; Munich, Germany, and London's Gatwick Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trans-Atlantic is by far the largest international presence US
Airways has, but they don't have much international presence,''
Higgins said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors focused on the challenges facing United Thursday,
casting a pall over the entire airline group.
</P>
<P>
   Airline stocks moved lower on Wall Street, and none fell harder
than US Airways. The company's shares, which jumped on Wednesday
after UAL's announcement of its $60-a-share cash offer, slumped $4
Thursday to $45. UAL fell for a second day, closing at $52.50, down
37.5 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of United's biggest competitors, AMR Corp., parent of
American Airlines, and Delta Air Lines, also fell. AMR lost
$2.9375, to $27.125. Delta closed at $50.4375, down $1.0625.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to worries about the implications of the merger, an
increase in oil prices did not help the group, nor did the
performance of the overall market.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins of Donaldson, Lufkin, which downgraded airline stocks
Thursday, said that ``given the uncertainty in the industry,
investors aren't going to care about fundamentals unless they are
negative.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Murphy, an analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, said he
was ``nonplussed'' by Thursday's move in airline stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it is a good thing for the marketplace to rationalize
the assets,'' he said. ``There is a lot of misunderstanding and
hysteria going on that we have told clients to buy into. This is an
opportunity, not a problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
