</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-ISRAEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PULLOUT STIRS UNCERTAINTY IN ISRAELI BORDER TOWNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRYAT SHEMONA, Israel _ Simon Champion is a real-estate agent
with an unusual pitch: Buy two apartments and get the third free.
And if that's not enough, the price of each three-bedroom apartment
has dropped by nearly half, to $36,000.
</P>
<P>
   But he still can't find any buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't sold an apartment since January,'' bemoaned the
37-year-old real-estate agent in Kiryat Shemona, an Israeli town
that borders Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, nobody wants to buy because the situation is too
risky, and you know what, if I had the money, even I would move
from here,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's withdrawal from south Lebanon this week after 22 years
of occupation had broad support throughout the country, but in the
northern towns that border Lebanon, the pullout has created an
almost unbearable uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Kiryat Shemona is one of the towns on the front line. Even when
Israeli troops patrolled the 9-mile deep ``security zone'' in south
Lebanon _ set up to protect Israel's northern communities from
attack _ Hezbollah guerrillas were able to rocket the area with
Katyushas, forcing people to spend days in underground shelters.
</P>
<P>
   But now that the soldiers have pulled out, residents don't know
whether to be happy that young Israeli men will no longer die in a
foreign land or fearful that the withdrawal makes it even easier
for Hezbollah fighters to attack.
</P>
<P>
   Although so far the border is quiet, the question is what will
happen in a few weeks, after Hezbollah fighters and their
supporters who have moved into south Lebanon stop celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``My children won't even go to the bathroom alone at night, they
are too scared that a bomb will fall on us after all the nights and
days we have had to spend in bomb shelters,'' said Yossi Aboudy, a
49-year-old resident of Kiryat Shemona.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to find someone who is not glad that our soldiers
have come home, the question is whether this will succeed in
bringing peace or instead will bring more war,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak Thursday convened a special session of
the Israeli Parliament in Kiryat Shemona to assure residents that
the state was behind them. Barak's government has promised to give
nearly $400 million to the northern communities for security and
economic development.
</P>
<P>
   The money is certainly needed. Hezbollah's attacks on the north
crippled the local industries, which could not fill orders when
their Israeli workers were in bomb shelters. Now, these industries
have the added problem of losing their Lebanese workers, who used
to cross over every day to work in factories, farms, and in the
tourism sector.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a lot of work still to be done to fortify the
sinuous border that in some communities cuts behind people's
backyards or runs along the narrow roads that wind their way
through the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not sure if I am an optimistic pessimist about the
withdrawal, or a pessimistic optimist,'' Knesset member Tommy
Lapid, from the liberal Shinui Party, told the approximately 100
local residents who attended the Knesset meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that we come here when you have problems to
show support and then we go home and forget, but hopefully this
time, we won't forget you,'' said Lapid.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Kiryat Shemona's 24,000 residents are not waiting around
to see if Barak's government keeps them in mind or maintains peace.
When Israel's proxy Lebanese militia started to collapse last week,
about half of the residents went to stay with friends and relatives
in other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The question is how many will return.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have left Lebanon a long time ago, even before we
entered, but there's no way my family is going to stay here
anymore,'' said Avraham Yosef, a 45-year-old taxi driver who bought
an apartment in Jerusalem three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   He came to Kiryat Shemona 25 years ago, started a family, bought
a house and came to love this small town where everyone knows one
another, the air is clean, and the scenery almost bucolic.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the Hezbollah attacks that grew in frequency
with each passing year as the rebels gained more support in
southern Lebanon for their fight to oust Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not afraid for myself; it's my children I want to save,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
