u i BC-CHINA-TRADE-HONGKONG-     05-25 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-HONGKONG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG FACES LOSS OF LUSTER TO MAINLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CHINA-TRADE) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ For a city that has prospered as an intermediary
between the Chinese economy and the outside world, Hong Kong has
lobbied hard to help China win full membership in the world's club
of trading nations.
</P>
<P>
   Now the U.S. House of Representatives has voted to give China
permanent normal trade status, bringing normalized trade relations
closer to reality and easing China's accession to the World Trade
Organization. And Hong Kong has to begin facing the consequences of
its successful campaign, one that has been driven at least as much
by politics as by economics.
</P>
<P>
   A China more open to commerce with the outside world, many
experts say, will jeopardize Hong Kong's historic role as a trading
post.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that companies are going to do business
directly with China,'' said Robert C. Broadfoot, the managing
director of the Political &AMP; Economic Risk Consultancy here. ``It's
not a question of if, but when, you're going to have shocks to Hong
Kong's role.''
</P>
<P>
   Broadfoot contends that in the long run Hong Kong will benefit
from China's integration into the global economy, because the
overall volume of China-related trade will grow.
</P>
<P>
   But in the short term, China's march into the World Trade
Organization will pose a thorny challenge. As a former British
colony and now a semiautonomous region of China, Hong Kong is a
separate trading entity that already has its own membership in the
WTO.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's stock market reflected this ambivalence, falling
slightly on Thursday while shares in the mainland Chinese cities of
Shanghai and Shenzhen roared ahead.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, more than $52 billion worth of goods passed through
Hong Kong's port bound for mainland destinations. Broadfoot
estimates that a third of that traffic will disappear after the
United States and other countries start shipping directly to
mainland ports.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise in air travel, Hong Kong could lose its role as a
gateway to China. As part of the WTO negotiations last year between
the United States and China, Beijing agreed to increase the
frequency of commercial flights, which would enable more American
cities to have more direct flights to mainland Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
   That could hurt Dragonair, a Hong Kong carrier that serves many
mainland cities. It stands to lose Western passengers who fly to
Hong Kong and transfer to planes to popular Chinese destinations
like Xian or Guilin.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's position is further threatened by Taiwan, whose new
president, Chen Shui-bian, has signaled that he is open to
negotiating direct trade links with China. In 1998, Hong Kong's
container port handled nearly $10 billion worth of Taiwanese
exports bound for China. If Taiwan and China were to break down
these barriers, some of that trade would also bypass Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once China gets into the WTO, Taiwan would presumably get into
the WTO soon as well,'' said Eden Woon, director of the Hong Kong
General Chamber of Commerce. ``That means that Taiwan would have to
deal more directly with China.''
</P>
<P>
   With all the troubling implications, why did Woon and other Hong
Kong officials push so energetically for the House to pass the
bill?
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason is political. Beijing has made gaining entry
into the trade organization the centerpiece of its economic agenda.
In Hong Kong, where politicians and business leaders try to outdo
each other to be seen as loyal to the motherland, supporting the
trade campaign was a natural.
</P>
<P>
   Even Martin Lee, Hong Kong's most prominent pro-democracy
leader, traveled to Washington to lobby for the bill. Lee, a
longtime critic of Beijing, said his motives were political rather
than economic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to support the 1.2 billion people of China, not the
Chinese government,'' Lee said. ``I see in this bill a reasonable
possibility that China will change its culture toward observing the
rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Other supporters argue that Hong Kong can retain its middleman
role _ with a few tweaks _ as a provider of services to the next
generation of foreign companies that try to get into China. Hong
Kong, with its legions of lawyers, accountants and consultants, is
quite likely to remain a valuable guide for those companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to handle all this trade, China will have to have a
very well-developed service sector,'' said Victor K. Fung, the
chairman of the Hong Kong Trade Development Council and the owner
of a trading firm. ``In the short run, it will be very difficult
for China to ramp up those services.''
</P>
<P>
   But some more old-line Hong Kong industries will have to
redefine themselves. With the United States set to lift import
quotas on Chinese textiles and textile products by 2005, Woon
predicted that many Hong Kong clothing makers would move their
factories to the mainland to take advantage of lower production
costs. Hong Kong, he suggested, could recast itself as a center for
Asian fashion design, rather than a manufacturing center.
</P>
<P>
   China's entry into the trade organization is also quite likely
to deprive Hong Kong of its thriving gray market in goods like oil,
cigarettes and agricultural products. Those are smuggled from
mainland China by the truckload and exported from Hong Kong so that
they will be subject to lower tariffs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its expected negative effects on some Hong Kong
industries, China's trade campaign has made people here recognize
that their economic fortunes are inextricably tied to the mainland.
It seemed no coincidence that last week Hong Kong announced a $12
billion expansion of its rail system, including a direct link
between central Hong Kong and Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's government estimates that China's joining the WTO
would add more than 5 percent to the territory's gross domestic
product over the next decade. It also predicts that investment by
Hong Kong companies in China will explode. Local companies have
already poured in a cumulative $156 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Because Hong Kong and China would retain separate memberships in
the World Trade Organization, officials said Hong Kong would not
necessarily gain access to Chinese markets earlier than other
countries. But business people here are lobbying for special
treatment. Even without it, officials say, Hong Kong will flourish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not mind if multinational companies go directly to
China,'' the government's chief spokesman, Stephen Lam, said. ``As
long as the pie gets bigger, even if we get a smaller piece, it
will still be more than enough for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 2101EDT &QL; 
