<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5891 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-GATEWAY-IXL0526-COX     05-25 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATEWAY-IXL0526-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CFN, Gateway deal is a dual marketing tool
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - The Consumer Financial Network, a unit of
Atlanta-based iXL Enterprises, has received a $150 million
investment from Gateway Inc., the second-largest direct personal
computer seller.
</P>
<P>
   CFN develops Web sites for corporate intranets that offer
information on employee benefits and a variety of financial
services. Companies use that service to communicate with their
employees. CFN also operates a site for individual users that
offers similar services called Youdecide.com.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway will work with CFN to market its PCs and Internet access
to the companies that use CFN. It hopes to sell its PCs that way
through company-sponsored employee purchase programs.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction is expected to close in June and is subject to
regulatory approval.
</P>
<P>
   For Gateway, the deal is part of its plan to find new ways to
market its products to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks Gray, an analyst at Technology Business Research, told
CNet it's likely that there will be more employer PC deals as
hardware makers continue to seek alternative ways to market their
products.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this investment we have a tremendous marketing partner
for CFN,'' says Bert Ellis, chairman and CEO of iXL. ``It's a very
valuable asset, and it's a great combination of hardware, software
and ISP we can use to go after the corporate portal opportunities
that exist.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal gives Gateway access to 4 million employees who use the
CFN intranet program, and CFN gets access to the Gateway customer
base. ``Together they can bring enterprise portal or
business-to-enterprise solutions corporate environments,'' said
Jonathan Ballon, chief marketing officer of iXL Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Ballon says the employee desktop is the last uncharted territory
and Delta Air Lines, American Airlines and Ford Motor Co. have made
commitments to provide PCs to their employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It lets the company have a relationship with its employees
beyond the office and by bringing in CFN, they have access to CFN
and all of its offerings.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballon says the benefit for iXL is that it validates the
company's initial investment in CFN. ``It's the most mature of our
ventures and the first one out of the nest,'' he says. ``It shows
we know what we are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The purchase by Gateway will dilute iXL's stake in New
York-based CFN to 48.5 percent from a majority interest previously.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
