<SLUG> BC-GORE-TENN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE PROPOSES EXPANDING AFTER-SCHOOL PROGRAMS  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Saying he wanted to provide children with
``more time for learning and less time for trouble,'' Democratic
presidential contender Al Gore on Thursday proposed expanding
after-school programs through a combination of tax credits for
parents and additional federal spending.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing parents, teachers, and community leaders at a YMCA,
the vice president noted that changing family trends, including the
increasing number of households in which both parents work and the
large number of teens who are left unsupervised in the early
evening hours, had increased the pressure on government to provide
some help.
</P>
<P>
   Without parental guidance, he said, ``too many children fall
prey to a culture of chaotic values.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that too many teen-agers do not have anything to do
when school lets out, which can lead to trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember idle hands are the devil's workshop,'' he said.
``There is some wisdom to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore noted that a number of boys and girls playing basketball at
the YMCA had told him that if they did not have the after-school
program there, they would be home watching television. He said one
boy said he watched the ``Jerry Springer'' show, which often
features participants talking about their sexual problems.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage more after-school programs such as the ones run by
the YMCA, Gore proposed an $11.3 billion package that includes $5.3
billion in tax credits for parents who enroll their children, ages
13 to 16, in after-school programs. The credit could be for up to
half the cost of the care, depending upon the taxpayer's income.
</P>
<P>
   Parents with children younger than 13 already can qualify for a
child-care tax credit. The new credit for teen-agers would be part
of the $250 billion tax cut Gore is proposing.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also proposed spending $6 billion to expand
the 21st Century Learning Centers, an existing program that helps
communities set up after-school and summer school programs. The
program serves 850,000 children. The new funding would come from
the $115 billion education plan advocated by Gore.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore advocated government help, he also underscored the
need for parental responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government doesn't raise children. Parents do,'' he said. ``No
government program can teach a child right from wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The after-school proposals are part of a broader family values
agenda that the candidate said he will lay out in the coming weeks.
Next week, Gore said, he plans to talk about the role of fathers.
</P>
<P>
   After the YMCA appearance, Gore spoke to state Democratic Party
chairmen from around the nation meeting in Nashville, the capital
city of Gore's home state.
</P>
<P>
   His address to the state leaders came as Gore has slipped
slightly behind Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican
contender, in national polls, and as party officials are
questioning the low-key campaign the vice president has run since
sealing the nomination in March.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the chairmen were at least outwardly unconcerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is so new and he's a nice guy, but he's one of those guys
you want to go out and date in college,'' said Molly Beth Malcolm,
Democratic chairwoman from Texas. ``You know you'll have a good
time, but he's not who anybody wants to marry.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
