<HEADER>
A5895 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBO-STOLEN-BASES-DECL     05-25 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-STOLEN-BASES-DECLINE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY RUN WHEN YOU CAN TROT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chad Curtis was a rabbit, a speedster, when he first broke into
the major leagues with the California Angels. He stole 43 bases as
a rookie in 1992, and was fifth in the American League with 48 the
following season.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Rangers' outfielder has two steals in four
attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis admits he's not as fast as he used to be. He has added
muscle in the past few years, and is tied for third on the team
with six homers. But he says his lack of steals has at least as
much to do with philosophy as physiology.
</P>
<P>
   He bats in front of Ivan Rodriguez and Rafael Palmeiro, sluggers
who are a threat to hit the ball out of the park every at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to watch them swing the bat,'' Curtis said. ``I can't
be making outs. If I was hitting lower in the order and the guy
behind me was struggling a little bit, I might see if I can get in
scoring position for him, take a gamble. But you don't need to
gamble with guys like Rodriguez and Palmeiro behind you.''
</P>
<P>
   Change the names and the team, and those words could be echoed
throughout baseball. Why risk stealing when the next guy can hit it
out of the park, at almost every spot in the order?
</P>
<P>
   The increase in home runs throughout baseball this year has been
accompanied by a decrease in stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk-reward factor isn't as high with a stolen base
because you've got guys in the eighth and ninth spot hitting 20
home runs,'' said former Rangers catcher and current Seattle
Mariners broadcaster Dave Valle. ``The stolen base isn't as
important. I don't think managers use it as much as they used to.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, there were 1.90 attempted steals per game in the
American League and 2.15 in the National League. This year,
attempts are down to 1.71 per game in the AL, 1.77 in the NL.
</P>
<P>
   In both leagues, the home-run leader has a higher total than the
stolen-base leader. In the NL, Mark McGwire has 20 homers, Luis
Castillo 18 steals. In the AL, Jason Giambi has 17 homers, Johnny
Damon 16 steals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more of a speed game in the National League, but even
that seems like it's changing now with all the power going over
there,'' veteran catcher Joe Oliver said, referring to McGwire and
Ken Griffey Jr. changing leagues in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in steals can be attributed to other factors,
including a dearth of speedsters. AL runners attempted to swipe
2,564 bases in '92, Curtis' rookie year, or 2.26 per game. They
haven't come close to that total since.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me, Kenny Lofton, Pat Listach, a few other guys, all came in
the league at the same time, and we tore it up for a couple of
years,'' Curtis said. ``Everybody started saying, ... `We'd better
start paying attention.' Kenny Lofton still steals them because
he's just that fast. I'm not that fast. I was taking things that
they were giving, and they're not giving them as much anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariners infielder Mark McLemore, who stole 25 bases as a rookie
with the Angels in '87, said the slide step, a pitching delivery
with almost no leg kick, is much more prevalent now than when he
broke into the majors. The quicker delivery makes it more difficult
to steal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see more and more guys going to it,'' McLemore said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest factor for the decrease in steals, however, appears
to be the reliance on the home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, there's only a few guys who steal bases,'' said
Tampa Bay infielder Ozzie Guillen, who stole 36 bases for the
Chicago White Sox in 1989. ``Before, everybody was running. Now,
everybody can hit home runs. If you're the leadoff guy and you
don't get to second base while the No. 2 hitter is up, you're going
to shut it down because the third and the fourth hitters are going
to drive you in.''
</P>
<P>
   There's even less running in Rangers games than there is
league-wide. There were 1.41 attempts in the team's first 44 games.
Rodriguez's presence behind the plate is a huge factor. Only the
very best runners try to steal on the best arm in the game. But the
Rangers don't run much, either. They've attempted 32 steals, only
two more than their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``What running game?'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``I've
never believed in running for the sake of running. Certainly, now,
with the way guys are swinging the bat and hitting homers, why take
a chance? You have to look at the percentages. Is this an
out-and-out gamble if we do it, or are the odds in our favor? Who's
the pitcher, who's the catcher, who's the runner? Am I running just
to run, or running to try to win a ballgame? Have I got a better
chance of this guy getting a hit, or this guy stealing a base?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer in Arlington, as well as other locales throughout
baseball, is to let the hitter swing the bat.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 2111EDT &QL; 
