<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5896 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-RAC-ST.-JULIEN-JOCKEY     05-25 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-ST.-JULIEN-JOCKEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARLON ST. JULIEN'S STAR ON THE RISE AMONG TOP JOCKEYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ There was no blanket of roses awaiting
Marlon St. Julien after he rode Curule in this year's Kentucky
Derby. Considering the colt and his stablemate China Visit were
long shots at 22-to-1, St. Julien wasn't counting on a trip to the
winner's circle.
</P>
<P>
   But he got the next-best thing when he dismounted from Curule
(pronounced Koo-RULE) after he finished a better-than-expected
seventh in front of horses such as Captain Steve, War Chant, Anees,
The Deputy and High Yield.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Sheik Mohammed al Maktoum and the people who handle Curule
were ``very, very happy,'' St. Julien said. ``They did say, `We'll
be in touch.' That was a plus for me.''
</P>
<P>
   They've been in touch with St. Julien about riding Curule in the
Belmont Stakes on June 10. Curule is listed as a probable for the
race, and the stable's contract rider Frankie Dettori, who rode
China Visit in the Derby, is scheduled to ride in the Epsom Derby
in England the same day as the Belmont. Nothing will be determined,
however, until next week at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   But St. Julien, 28, thinks it's another positive sign for his
career. Another indicator could come Monday when St. Julien returns
to Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie for Lone Star Million Day. He
was the leading rider at Lone Star in 1997 and '98 before he left
last year to ride the circuit between New Orleans and Kentucky full
time.
</P>
<P>
   But the way his schedule looks for Lone Star Million Day, it's
almost like he never left. There are seven stakes races scheduled
on Monday's card, and St. Julien has promising mounts in at least
three of the races.
</P>
<P>
   He is aboard track-record holder Caro's Royalty in the $100,000
Lone Star Park Turf Sprint; multiple stakes winner Go Lib Go in the
$200,000 USA Stakes, and Oaklawn Park stakes winner Really Polish
in the $200,000 WinStar Distaff. It's possible he will have a ride
in the Grade III Lone Star Park Handicap on Spinelessjellyfish, a
horse based on the West Coast who might be shipped in by trainer
Jenine Sahadi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been looking forward to coming back to Lone Star even if
it was just to ride in a claiming race,'' St. Julien said. ``I have
family, my aunt and uncle, living there. A lot of friends. It's
pretty much like going home.''
</P>
<P>
   Home for St. Julien originally was Lafayette, La. But he is now
based in Louisville, Ky., where he is in the top five in the jockey
standings at Churchill Downs. Going into this week's races, St.
Julien was in a tie for third at Churchill with Robby Albarado and
Calvin Borel. They were one victory behind Shane Sellers and 14
behind all-time leading Churchill rider Pat Day.
</P>
<P>
   St. Julien has been given the star treatment this year. He has
appeared in prominent ads promoting cellular phone service in the
Louisville area along with Sellers and Albarado.
</P>
<P>
   He also has made contacts that have reached into Canada. Last
weekend, he won a Grade I stakes race at Woodbine Racecourse in
Toronto aboard 3-year-old filly Zoftig.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's easy to sell,'' said former jockey Randy Romero, who
serves as St. Julien's agent. ``He's got a great personality. He
acts the way a jockey should act. I'm getting better just by being
around him.''
</P>
<P>
   Such placement in the community for a black jockey hasn't
happened in decades. St. Julien's ride aboard Curule in the Derby
marked the first time an African-American has ridden in the race in
79 years. The moment was not lost on St. Julien.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just beginning to get educated on the history of horse
racing,'' St. Julien said. ``But I had a lot of time to myself in
the post parade because Curule doesn't have a pony with him before
the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tears came to my eyes. It was a feeling I've never had in
horse racing.''
</P>
<P>
   It looks as though St. Julien will have a chance to get that
feeling again. And it might come through his association with Sheik
Mohammed's Godolphin Stable.
</P>
<P>
   The Sheik has announced plans to become more involved in
American racing. He will send a stable of 2-year-olds from Dubai to
the United States under the supervision of Eoin Harty, a former
assistant to Bob Baffert.
</P>
<P>
   St. Julien has a shot to ride some of those horses. He's made
the contacts. He's an easy sell.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 2112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
