<SLUG> BC-BBC-BAYLOR-UNDERDOWN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH INTANGIBLES, BAYLOR SENIOR BETTER THAN THE AVERAGE BEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During a particularly rocky stretch early in the season, Baylor
coach Steve Smith decided to bench second baseman Preston Underdown
in favor of freshman Tim Hartshorn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat Preston down for 10 games because he didn't seem to be
hitting that well,'' Smith said, ``and it provided a great
opportunity to get Tim some playing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed, however, that we went 3-7. Gradually, it dawned on
me that Preston is doing some things for us out there that don't
necessarily show up in the boxscore.''
</P>
<P>
   Underdown has been in the lineup since, and will be at second
base tonight at 7 when the top-seeded Bears (45-14) face Southwest
Texas State (33-27) in the first round of the NCAA Regional at the
Baylor Ballpark. Second seed Florida (41-21-1) will face San Jose
State (36-20) in the afternoon game at 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   A senior from Phoenix who grew up an Arizona State fan,
Underdown arrived at Baylor almost by chance and has, over the past
four years, grown with a program that has become a national power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always dreamed of being a Sun Devil,'' he said, ``and ASU
showed interest in me coming out of high school. But Baylor invited
me for a visit because they had seen me when they came out there to
look at another shortstop. I came here and I liked what I saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing fancy, but they said they were going to be a winning
program, and that they were building a new stadium. The plans for
that were already in place, and they were very direct about what
they wanted to accomplish, and I decided I want to be part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a culture shock ... you could say Phoenix and Waco
are at opposite ends of the spectrum ... but now I love it here.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been a teammate of Kip Wells, now in the Chicago White
Sox pitching rotation, and Jason Jennings, the 1999 national player
of the year. Now, he is a senior looking back on a steady climb to
the top ... almost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was disappointing to go out in the final game of the Super
Regional last year,'' he said. ``Especially when we carried a lead
into the eighth inning. I've thought about the fact that this is my
last chance to get to the College World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost a lot of talent off that team, and when the season
started I was really wondering how we would respond. This is a
different type team _ we don't hit the long ball much _ but I think
we've got the pitching to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   And the defense. Originally a shortstop, Underdown has proven
himself the quintessential left-side infielder, able to do any job
that needs doing. He has led a nomadic existence between third,
short and second and said, ``As long as it helps the team, I don't
care that much where I play.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitting .291, he is known as a clutch hitter _ he hit .600 at
this juncture last year to help the Bears reach the Super Regional,
and has won games with two-out, ninth-inning home runs. Last year,
he drove in the run that ended a 22-inning game against Houston.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, he has the glove that never misses.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a coach can specifically remember every error a guy has
made,'' Smith said, ``It's a sign that the guy's having a real good
year.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Underdown has made four in 244 chances, a .984
percentage. It is becoming clearer to Smith why he put him back in
the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have succeeded,'' he said, beaming proudly, ``despite my
coaching.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 2112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5898 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-RAC-PRICE-RED-BULLET-     05-25 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PRICE-RED-BULLET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED BULLET MAY NOT HAVE IT IN HIS BLOOD TO GO BELMONT DISTANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would be understandable to hear the words ``50-50'' coming
out of the mouth of Neil Drysdale. When it comes to a trainer
making plans for the next race, Drysdale's light seems stuck on
``yellow'' for caution.
</P>
<P>
   But now it seems that Drysdale practically has Fusaichi Pegasus
already loaded into the starting gate for the Belmont Stakes in 15
days. And now it's trainer Joe Orseno who's uncommitted regarding
Red Bullet's half of the rematch after he beat up on Fusaichi
Pegasus in the Preakness Stakes. His odds of making the Belmont are
``50-50'' Orseno said.
</P>
<P>
   When the people in the racing office at Belmont Park said they
had received word that Red Bullet would run in the Belmont, Orseno
quickly rebutted. No decision would be made, he said, until he
spoke with Frank Stronach, the owner of the colt.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for this deliberation aren't obvious. The colt is
reported to have looked fine upon his return to the racetrack for a
brief jog two days ago. His race in the Preakness was visually
impressive.
</P>
<P>
   This one takes some digging. And once you've found what you're
looking for, you can make a hypothesis _ a hypothesis, not a
declaration of fact _ that the owners of Red Bullet know the colt
is suspect at the 11/2 miles of the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   That's five-sixteenths of a mile longer than the Preakness,
which is a considerable distance in horse racing. These horses have
never raced this far, and likely won't again.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does Stronach own Red Bullet, he owns the colt's dam, a
mare named Cargo. Stronach said he delegates breeding decisions to
his son Andy.
</P>
<P>
   Not withstanding their one breeding to Unbridled four years ago,
which produced Red Bullet, it appears the Stronachs have little
faith that Cargo is the type of mare that will produce horses
capable of winning at the classic distances.
</P>
<P>
   Look at their breeding decisions with Cargo. At first, the
Stronachs tried mating her with stallions known for some endurance,
if not always known for aptitude at classic distances. Cargo
produced a colt by Miswaki, but he hasn't won a race. Then came Red
Bullet, followed by a Meadowlake colt, now a 2-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Before Red Bullet hit the track as a 2-year-old, before they
could see how Unbridled's stamina influence would click through
Cargo, the Stronachs made a drastic switch in their breeding
philosophy with her. They sent her to Lite The Fuse, a winner of
six graded stakes races on the East Coast _ all sprints. And as Red
Bullet began to blossom and began to show he might be a Triple
Crown player early this year, Cargo was sent to Lucky Lionel. He's
a young, unproven stallion by Mt. Livermore who was known for
setting a track record at Santa Anita at 61/2 furlongs.
</P>
<P>
   Lite The Fuse and Lucky Lionel are nice horses, and there's
every reason to believe the resulting foals will be talented
runners. But don't expect them to run very far.
</P>
<P>
   If the Stronachs were gung-ho on Cargo being able to produce
winners of Triple Crown races, they'd keep knocking on the door of
stallions such as Unbridled. In the future, another Mr.
Prospector-line stallion named Fusaichi Pegasus might make a good
match for Cargo.
</P>
<P>
   Those horses could add endurance to Cargo's sprinting
background. Despite the fact that she's by endurance stallion Caro
(he sired '88 Kentucky Derby winner Winning Colors), Cargo never
won past a mile in her racing career. At distances of a mile and
11/16 miles, she went 1-for-6.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, about this information given to jockey Jerry
Bailey that Cargo was a ``freak'' on a wet track: According to the
past performances on file at The Jockey Club, Cargo never raced on
a wet surface.
</P>
<P>
   Her dam, Aerturas, (the second dam of Red Bullet) never raced
past seven furlongs.
</P>
<P>
   Breeding racehorses is a funny business. Some people have bred
for distance and got sprinters. Some horses bred for speed have
been able to carry their turn of foot at the classic distances.
Some horses bred to race on grass had to be switched to the dirt to
win. Remember Cigar?
</P>
<P>
   Breeding is a game of faith. And now, judging by their own
decisions, it appears the Stronachs' faith in Red Bullet going 11/2
miles is shaky. {Tim Price writes a column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram.} &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 2112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
