<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDY-IRL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS MOTOR SPEEDWAY SEEN AS KEY TO IRL GROWTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Indy Racing League founder Tony George envisions
Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth as the foundation of a series
schedule that could expand to as many as 15 events in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   George said Thursday he and Eddie Gossage, the executive vice
president and general manager of TMS, have signed a sanctioning
agreement replacing the three-year deal that expired last year. The
multiyear contract provides for TMS to retain its two dates in the
same June/October slots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're OK with Texas. There is an agreement and we've worked
through all the issues,'' George said before the start of
Carburetion Day activities at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway, site
of Sunday's Indianapolis 500. ``We would love for them (TMS) to
continue in that role as the first race after the 500.''
</P>
<P>
   The IRL's Casino Magic 500 is scheduled June 10 at TMS.
</P>
<P>
   Gossage also campaigned for and secured the league's
season-finale beginning in October 1999, when Greg Ray of Plano
clinched the driver's championship. The current season will end in
Fort Worth with the Mall.com 500 on Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by 84 years of history and tradition, the Indianapolis
500 remains the cornerstone of the renamed Indy Racing Northern
Light Series. But TMS has emerged as the second-most popular venue
on the schedule, which was reduced to nine races this season. The
1.5-mile TMS quadoval played host to the series' inaugural night
race in June 1997, and has been the first event run after the Indy
500 since.
</P>
<P>
   TMS gives the IRL, in its fifth season, another race to build
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've established something of a tradition,'' George said of
Gossage and the TMS staff. ``We're looking to trying to establish
more of our events on a traditional (basis) and create some
continuity. One of the things we've lacked the last three or four
years is continuity.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage said he and George came to terms on the new contract
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony may have signed it, but I haven't gotten it yet,''
Gossage said from Fort Worth. ``It was a real easy negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've agreed to run the IRL and plan to have a formal
announcement about the particulars on race weekend. It'll be two
stops here for several years. It's an important part of our
schedule. We think it's a great, great series. What's happened at
Indy this month shows this is a strong, viable series on its own.
I'd love to have a CART race here, too. But the IRL has been great
for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first race after Indy makes that special. The Casino Magic
500 traditionally draws the biggest open-wheel crowd outside of the
Indy 500. We're very proud of that. And the season-finale makes
that a real happening as well. We're going to build on those
things.''
</P>
<P>
   The league was aiming for a 10-race schedule this season, but a
``TBA'' date scheduled for Sept. 10 was deleted this spring. The
league will visit the new Kentucky Speedway at Sparta, Ky., for the
first time on Aug. 27. George announced this month that the IRL
will race at the Kansas Speedway in Kansas City, Kan., on July 8,
2001, and at the Chicagoland Speedway in Joliet, Ill, on Sept. 2,
2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got about eight races firm that we know will be part of
the (2001) schedule,'' George said, ``and about six or seven others
in play. Any number of those six or seven may turn out to be firm
in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had Midwest races in the past on the schedule,
other than Indianapolis. We're looking forward to going to Illinois
and Kansas City, and we'll continue to look for other opportunities
in the Midwest and other areas.''
</P>
<P>
   George said the possibility of including an IRL race during the
annual SpeedWeeks festivities at the Daytona International Speedway
in Florida in February has been discussed with officials of
International Speedway Corp. Such an agreement would put the IRL's
single-seat, open-wheel cars, which reach speeds in excess of 220
mph on the relatively flat 2.5-mile Indianapolis Motor Speedway, on
the even faster 33-degree banked turns of the 2.5-mile Daytona
track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not there yet (at Daytona),'' George said. ``I think we
can run about anywhere we want, safely.''
</P>
<P>
   George said the league's annual season-opener at the Walt Disney
World Speedway in Orlando, Fla., is in jeopardy because of
scheduling conflicts at the resort. But George said four tracks on
the 1999 Championship Auto Racing Teams' schedule _ The Milwaukee
Mile, Michigan Speedway, California Speedway and Gateway
International Raceway outside St. Louis _ are being scouted by the
IRL. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
