<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Justice Department Clears AT&AMP;T Deal for MediaOne
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department approved AT&AMP;T's proposed $58 billion
acquisition of MediaOne Group, giving the telephone giant control
over more than a third of the nation's cable network for
television, high-speed Internet access and online telephone
service. The decision requires the companies to sell their interest
in Road Runner, the nation's second-largest cable Internet service.
The companies now await a decision by the Federal Communications
Commission, which is considering requests by competitors and
consumer groups to force the sale of more assets.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of UAL and US Airways Fall
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission said that it would probably have to take
a close look at the competitive aspects of United Airlines'
proposed $4.3 billion takeover of US Airways. And investors focused
on the challenges facing the deal, sending shares of both companies
lower. US Airways slumped $4, to $45, while UAL, United's parent,
fell 37.5 cents, to $52.50.
</P>
<P>
   Floor Plans With Internet Access
</P>
<P>
   For a growing number of home buyers, high-speed Internet
connections are becoming as important as a two-car garage or
fireplace, prompting some developers to jump into the
telecommunications business.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in African Diamond Company
</P>
<P>
   An African diamond company plans to sell shares on the London
Stock Exchange, offering investors a stake in a venture that
includes as partners the embattled governments of Congo and
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks Fall, Led Lower by Goldman
</P>
<P>
   Stocks slumped, led lower by financial shares after Goldman
Sachs told analysts that its second-quarter profit would fall short
of expectations. The Dow Jones industrial average dropped 211.43
points, or 2 percent, to 10,323.92. The Nasdaq composite index fell
65.26 points, or 2 percent, to 3,205.35, erasing an earlier gain of
2.9 percent. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index declined 17.53
points, or 1.3 percent, to 1,381.52.
</P>
<P>
   Japan to Correct Economic Data
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government said it would correct its deliberate
omission of data made in a report on economic growth. The new
figures will show a 1.6 percent decline in gross domestic product
for the October-to-December period, rather than 1.43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Card Duel at Senate Hearing
</P>
<P>
   Credit card company executives clashed at a Senate hearing over
an antitrust lawsuit accusing Visa and MasterCard of restricting
competition by barring member banks from also issuing American
Express or Discover cards. Visa and MasterCard ``operate a closed,
self-serving, self-perpetuating system,'' said Harvey Golub, the
chairman of American Express. MasterCard's chief counsel fired
back: ``If American Express gets its way, neither competition nor
the consumer wins.''
</P>
<P>
   $8 Billion Sold in TV Advertising
</P>
<P>
   Even after a season that saw ratings declines for most programs,
executives from the six broadcast networks said they pulled in
record amounts of money from advertisers in the upfront sales
market, racking up a total advertising take of $8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner and Disney Finish Deal
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner and Walt Disney completed a deal that allows the
cable company to continue carrying ABC stations for six years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
