<SLUG> BC-BBO-SELIG-REALIGNMENT-TEX </SLUG>
 
SELIG SAYS REALIGNMENT NOT IN PERIL (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball commissioner Bud Selig said the decision to delay the
owners' meetings scheduled for June was to allow more time to work
on scheduling scenarios, and not a sign that his realignment plan
is in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   If so, that means the Rangers still would move from the American
League West to the Central next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working on the same plan at this point,'' Selig said.
``There's no snags at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Team owners tentatively were scheduled to meet June 13-14, when
they would vote on realignment for next season. Selig's plan would
shift the Rangers from the West to the Central, the Arizona
Diamondbacks from the National League West to the AL West and the
Tampa Bay Devil Rays from the AL East to the NL.
</P>
<P>
   The most likely scenario has four divisions of four teams each
without a wild-card playoff entry in the NL, and two four-team
divisions plus a six-team Central in the AL, which would have a
wild card.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have said the plan is unwieldy because of the different
number of divisions in the leagues, the wild card in one league and
not the other, and because it might be more difficult to make the
playoffs from the six-team AL Central.
</P>
<P>
   Those critics include the players' union, which has the right to
approve major changes in the structure of Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Selig, though, said his goal is to go to an unbalanced schedule,
and realignment is the best way to accomplish it.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said that devising a schedule that works for most of
the teams is taking time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working on a series of options so that when we finally
come forth with a plan that we think produces the best schedule, we
will be able to say to everybody we've run every other
alternative,'' Selig said. ``That's the only reason the meeting was
delayed. We can't produce a schedule that pleases all 30 clubs. I'm
trying to do one that pleases as many as possible and is the right
schedule. We're testing every conceivable structure for a schedule,
and that's what is taking the time right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig said he hopes to have an owners meeting in early-to-mid
July. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
