<SLUG> BC-PATIENT-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATIENTS' RIGHTS COMPROMISE FOUNDERS IN JOINT COMMITTEE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The outlook for legislation defining patients'
rights turned bleak Thursday as House and Senate negotiators issued
an unusually negative report on their efforts to strike a
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``These talks are stalled,'' said Sen. Edward M. Kennedy,
D-Mass., as he walked out of a conference committee meeting
Thursday evening. Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, said, ``We are making
zero progress.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior Republican negotiator, Rep. Bill Thomas of California,
said that ``it's going to be very difficult'' to reconcile the
bills passed by the Senate last July and by the House in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's akin to mating a chihuahua with a Great Dane,'' Thomas
said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas and other lawmakers said part of the problem was that
House and Senate Republicans had not reached complete agreement
among themselves on several major issues. For example, Thomas said
that ``we agree to disagree'' on the number of people who should be
protected by any new federal standards for health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Many provisions of the House bill would apply to more than 165
million Americans, about three times the number covered by
comparable provisions of the Senate bill.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., who is chairman of the conference
committee, said, ``Most people would say the chances of success are
not great, but we've worked very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's meeting included 13 members of Congress and lasted
about 75 minutes. Much of the time was spent discussing whether
patients should have new rights to sue health insurance plans for
injuries caused by the denial of care. Republicans repeatedly
insisted that Congress must not impose any new legal liability on
employers who sponsor health plans for their employees. Democrats
complained that Republicans seemed to be worrying more about
employers than patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent one hour in there, and I did not hear the word
`patients' mentioned once,'' said Sen. John D. Rockefeller IV,
D-W.Va. ``Everything is about one tiny section of the bill''
dealing with the liability of employers.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress said that there was no agenda for Thursday's
meeting, and that lawmakers gave no instructions to staff members
about what to do next week, when Congress is in recess. The recess
began Thursday evening, with both houses of Congress scheduled to
reconvene on June 6.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said it was still possible that the pace of
negotiations could pick up after Congress reconvenes. Rep. Charlie
Norwood, R-Ga., who supports the same bill favored by many
Democrats, said he was losing patience with the conference
committee and was seeking other ways to move a bill through
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't get a bill, or at least a tentative agreement in
writing by the week we come back from Memorial Day, we must move
past the conference,'' Norwood said. ``I am willing to pass this
measure through any legal means that may be necessary.'' He did not
give details.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Kennedy said, ``We've got other options.'' He said
Democrats could offer their proposals on the Senate floor as
amendments to other legislation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
