<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-REESE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' REESE CHANGES OUTLOOK AFTER NECK INJURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Safety Izell Reese shakes his head as he looks
around the Dallas Cowboys locker room at the carefree, cocksure
rookies, who see themselves as invincible and believing they will
play forever.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers when that was his attitude.
</P>
<P>
   As an unheralded sixth-round pick from Alabama-Birmingham two
years ago, Reese caught the Cowboys' attention with his play on
special teams and was tabbed as the team's free safety of the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran safety George Teague won the starting job last season,
but it was considered only a matter of time before the youthful
Reese claimed a permanent place in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Those days seem long ago to Reese, 24.
</P>
<P>
   A bulging disk, which sidelined him for the final eight games of
the 1999 season and required Daryl Johnston-like neck fusion
surgery on Jan. 4, has put his career in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Reese's goal now is to just play again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good,'' Reese said. ``I'm not having any problems and
it's not bothering me from moving. The real test is when I start
having real contact. That won't be until training camp. I'm just
taking it one day at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Johnston, though he returned from 1997 neck surgery to
play in 1998, is being forced out of the game because of more neck
problems last season, the Cowboys are taking a wait-and-see
approach with Reese.
</P>
<P>
   According to the team's trainers, he has responded well from the
surgery and is on schedule with his rehabilitation. After
participating in only limited drills during the first minicamp and
quarterback school, Reese went through all the workouts with the
team during the recent four-day quarterback school, which ended
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   It's expected that a healthy Reese would stabilize the Cowboys'
questionable safety situation. Excluding Reese, the players behind
starters Darren Woodson and Teague range between young and
inexperienced.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Kaiser, Chris Akins, Sean Key, Jasmine Tramel and Beau
Morgan have no NFL starts and a combined total of three NFL seasons
to their credit.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Dave Campo, however, said he wants to see how
Reese reacts mentally and physically to contact in training camp
before considering him part of the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Reese understands the uncertainty. Heck, he has had doubts
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston's and Michael Irvin's situations haven't helped,
either. Irvin is expected to retire this off-season because of neck
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been scary from the beginning,'' Reese said. ``I knew
before the surgery that I might not be able to play again. I knew
there was a chance my career could be over. It really got
depressing after the surgery. I sat in my house with that neck
brace on for almost two months doing nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Reese said conversations with Johnston and Irvin helped him get
out of the doldrums. He said Johnston, who had the same surgery
three years ago, has been very supportive.
</P>
<P>
   Reese is also buoyed by the fact that his injury was not as
serious as Johnston's and that it was diagnosed early in his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that was positive for me is that I am young,'' Reese
said. ``My body has recuperated well from the surgery. I feel good
now. I'm healthy. I actually feel better now than I did before the
surgery. It's still scary. But I'm confident I can make it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Reese's confidence is rooted in the knowledge of how far he has
come. He walks in his closet and looks at the neck brace every day
as a reminder of what he has gone through.
</P>
<P>
   But whether he makes it back or not, he said he has been altered
by his experience and hopes it can serve as a lesson for others.
</P>
<P>
   ``When something like that happens, you realize you have taken a
lot for granted,'' Reese said. ``You learn to appreciate the simple
stuff about life and health, not just football. That's what I try
to tell these rookies coming in. It's easy to take a lot of stuff
for granted. You have to make the most of every moment. Situations
like this make you aware of a lot things. That's what it did for
me.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
