<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5908 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CHINA-TRADE-NYT &LR;      05-25 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE HARD-DRIVING GOP GAVE CLINTON A TRADE VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Rep. Tom DeLay came to work on Wednesday, he
was still a vote or two shy of the bare-minimum 150 Republicans he
needed to help push the China trade bill over the top.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, the Republican whip, lined up lots of help. Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas was recruited to cajole several wavering
Republicans. So was Gen. Colin Powell. Dozens of pro-trade
lobbyists and corporate chieftains fanned out on Capitol Hill to
buttonhole the last dozen or so undeclared members for what both
camps predicted would be a nail-biter.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next crucial hours, those calls and an array of other
influences paid off, as virtually every undeclared Republican, and
even a few others who had been written off, broke DeLay's way. In
all, 164 Republicans joined 73 Democrats to grant China permanent
normal trading status, wiping out economic restrictions rooted in
Cold-War policy for a quarter century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, they surprised me a little bit,'' said DeLay, whose
bare-knuckle approach to head-counting has earned him the nickname
``The Hammer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Members in the last few hours really turned around and
understood how important this was,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The bill now goes to the Senate, where some critics were already
preparing amendments that could upset the delicately crafted
measure.
</P>
<P>
   Normalizing trade with China was a victory for the Clinton
administration, but House Republicans had their own reasons for
voting three-to-one in favor of the bill. Passage insured that
Republicans' corporate benefactors would fully benefit from a
market-opening accord Washington and Beijing negotiated that
slashes Chinese tariffs on a wide range of farm and industrial
products and removes some barriers to American service providers,
like banks and telecommunications companies.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republican leadership closed ranks behind the bill,
which is usually enough to guarantee victory. But they needed to
produce two-thirds of the yes votes, and had a tough sell with many
Republicans who balked at rewarding a trade plum to a Communist
government that they say persecutes religious minorities and
represses its own citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing simple about this,'' said Rep. Bob Schaffer
of Colorado, one of the last conservative Republicans to climb down
off the fence in favor. ``The 51 percent of this bill that's good
only barely outweighs the 49 percent that is truly deplorable.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders said a number of factors helped sway
undeclared members in the final days and hours to provide the
unexpectedly large margin of victory. An amendment creating a
commission to monitor human rights in China won half a dozen
Republicans and many more Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans lined up Chinese dissidents who said that the bill
would improve the rights of religious minorities, arguing that
persecution cannot survive the advent of the Internet. Rep. David
Dreier of California, a chief Republican supporter, enlisted Billy
Graham, the Protestant evangelist, to endorse the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Two dozen Republicans with national security concerns were
steered to Powell or Rep. Porter Goss, a Florida Republican who
heads the House Intelligence Committee, for reassurance that
engaging China would likely undermine the Communist government. ``I
told them, the more open a society the better opportunity we have
of getting results,'' said Goss.
</P>
<P>
   Many members cited increased trade and national security
benefits as reasons to vote yes. These broader merits, combined
with the home-district considerations, collectively sealed the
decisions of many borderline supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key factor for me was that this was the last best hope to
save family farms in middle and eastern Tennessee,'' said Rep. Van
Hilleary of Tennessee, who said Europe's agreement with China last
week on Beijing's entry into the World Trade Organization also
convinced him that U.S. jobs were at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a few members who were leaning yes needed a touch of
outside help to reach their decision. Bush, the presumptive
Republican presidential nominee, spoke to a handful of Republicans,
including Rep. Ernie Fletcher of Kentucky, who was impressed by Mr.
Bush's commitment to improving human rights in China.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Cox, a California Republican and outspoken
critic of China, endorsed the measure after provisions in the human
rights commission were strengthened. Rep. Elton Gallegly, R-Calif.,
said backing the bill was easier after he spoke to Agriculture
Secretary Dan Glickman about keeping a ban an Argentine oranges
which could introduce a citrus-killing insect into southern
California orchards.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Spencer Bachus, an Alabama Republican with steel mills in
his district, voted in favor after Republican leaders agreed to
amend a separate spending bill to address his concerns about
imported coke, which is used in steel-processing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always sensitive to our members' needs,'' said Susan B.
Hirschmann, DeLay's chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   By the roll call, all but a handful of the 15 or so Republicans
who started the day on the leaders' lists as undecided voted yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been counting votes for a long, long time and never in my
life have I seen that many undecideds break in favor of a
position,'' said Nick Calio, a bill supporter who was former
President George Bush's top lobbyist on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The China bill's 40-vote margin of victory in the House,
237-197, would seem to give it unstoppable momentum as the
legislation now moves to the Senate for consideration, probably
next month. Passage in the Senate, which is usually considered more
pro-trade and internationalist, had appeared more certain.
</P>
<P>
   But lurking in the Senate are critics like Jesse Helms, the
North Carolina Republican who heads the Foreign Relations
Committee. Helms, a fierce foe of the Beijing government, said
after the House vote that he would not allow the Senate ``to simply
rubber-stamp the president's plan to reward the Chinese
Communists.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents do not have the votes in the Senate to kill the House
bill, but amending it _ the right of any senator _ would force
House and Senate negotiators to hammer out a compromise of the
competing chambers' bills. The House would then have to cast a
second vote on the revised bill.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters vowed today to push for speedy Senate passage of a
clean House bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be efforts to derail this by using amendments and
other parliamentary means,'' said Sen. Chuck Hagel, a Nebraska
Republican who supports the measure. ``But we have to keep this
moving.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
