<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUTTLE CREW `READY TO WRAP THIS UP' AT SPACE STATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Atlantis astronauts gave the international space
station a final nudge to a higher altitude on Thursday and prepared
to depart the rejuvenated orbital outpost.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle crew docked with the uninhabited, two-room station
earlier this week to overhaul a faltering electrical power system
and make other refurbishments to prepare it for the overdue arrival
of the Russian crew module in July.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantis crew plans to depart the station Friday at 6:07
p.m. CDT, each of its tasks successfully executed. The astronauts
are scheduled to land at 1:18 a.m. CDT Monday at the Kennedy Space
Center in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready to wrap this up,'' said astronaut Jeff Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The station has towered nearly 80 feet above an airlock in the
shuttle's cargo bay since the two spacecraft linked Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday, Atlantis commander Jim Halsell and pilot Scott
``Doc'' Horowitz fired the shuttle's steering thrusters to gently
boost the station to an altitude of 234 miles, an increase of 10
miles. Combined with similar maneuvers Wednesday and Tuesday, the
station circled nearly 28 miles higher than when the astronauts
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The station has been losing one mile to two miles per week in
recent months because of a temporary increase in solar activity.
The increase causes the Earth's atmosphere to balloon to new
heights, creating new frictional drag on orbiting satellites.
</P>
<P>
   For several hours Thursday, it appeared the shuttle crew might
have to extend its stay to correct what appeared to be a problem
with a new storage battery. It had been installed in the station's
Russian segment as part of the power system overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   However, experts in Russia traced the difficulty to ground
circuitry, clearing the way for the five-man, two-woman shuttle
crew to conclude their visit Friday night, as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, the station's six power storage batteries began
to falter prematurely because of an overly aggressive charging
procedure at the Russian ground control facility.
</P>
<P>
   Four new batteries were installed by the Atlantis crew.
</P>
<P>
   At least three batteries are necessary for the addition of the
crew module in July. Russian economic and rocket problems have
stalled the large module's development and launching by more than
two years, slowing the addition of other components.
</P>
<P>
   During their visit, the shuttle astronauts also repaired an
American external cargo crane and replaced a faulty NASA
communications antenna.
</P>
<P>
   The astronauts enhanced the air ventilation system, installed
new smoke detectors and fire extinguishers and transferred exercise
equipment, computers, food, water and clothing.
</P>
<P>
   All of the gear will be in place as the first resident
astronauts and cosmonauts begin to arrive in November.
</P>
<P>
   However, should the crew module experience further delays, the
repairs made by the Atlantis crew should keep the station safely
orbiting until astronauts can return.
</P>
<P>
   The United States serves as the managing partner for a 16-nation
consortium involved in the assembly of the international station.
</P>
<P>
   The first components, a Russian propulsion, power and guidance
module and a smaller American one with ports to interlink a
half-dozen other modules, were coupled in Earth orbit in December
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership envisions a sprawling state-of-the-art orbiting
laboratory for research in physics, biology and medicine when the
station is fully assembled in late 2005.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
