<SLUG> BC-CAR-HADDOCK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALIBU DUO TEAM FOR BAJA 500
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM HADDOCK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
LOS ANGELES _ For John Clark Gable, the Tecate/SCORE Baja 500 is
old hat. For Dodd Darin, the 500-mile off-road race through the
Mexican peninsula will be a new experience.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pair from Malibu have decided to team up in the Tropy Truck
division for this year's June 3 Baja 500 with high expectations and
future races in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Gable, son of actor Clark Gable, has competed in off-road racing
in Baja for nearly two decades. He got his start in racing on
off-road motorcycles when he was 5 and growing up on his father's
22-acre Encino ranch.
</P>
<P>
   But he injured his knee in an accident while racing at Indian
Dunes in 1982. As a result, Gable switched from dirt bikes to
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Darin, the son of singer Bobby Darin and actress Sandra Dee,
followed a similar path. Darin and Gable have been friends since
they were 5 and used to ride their dirt bikes on the Gable ranch.
Darin later switched to racing go-karts. Some 33 years later, Darin
still sees a future in open-wheel racing. He wants to eventually
become a CART team owner with Gable and sees the Baja 500 as a
great way to gain exposure for his goal.
</P>
<P>
   While Darin, 38, has his sights on eventually owning a team,
Gable is more concerned with the immediate future of racing in the
Baja 500.
</P>
<P>
   This will be Gable's first Baja 500 since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been going down and doing some pre-running,'' said
Gable, 39, who is also racing motocross to get himself in shape for
the Baja 500. ``I got to get used to driving again.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Darin, he may only drive the ArtoftheStars.com-sponsored
Trophy Truck for one or two stages of the race. His main
responsibility will be as navigator for Gable. And if not for a
challenge from Gable, Darin's sole responsibility would be as
navigator.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he didn't think I could do it,'' Darin said. ``So
it was a bit of bravado on my part. I just want to be competitive
on the stages I drive. I'm looking forward to it. It should be
quite an experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Darin said he wants to continue racing after the Baja 500 in
open-wheel competition, perhaps the Barber-Saab series. Gable said
he wants to try and race in the Baja 2000 in November and continue
in off-road racing in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Rod Johnson of Canyon Country, the defending Irwindale Speedway
NASCAR Super Late Model champion, scored a win after track
officials disqualified the first- and second-place drivers from
Saturday night's race.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Walker of Canyon Country and Brandon Loverock of Santa Fe
Springs lost their prize money and points. Walker was penalized for
using noncomforming parts in his engine. Loverock was penalized for
using nonconforming cylinder heads. Walker also had to forfeit his
$1,000 prize for winning the Food 4 Less ``Fast 4 Shootout,'' a
four-lap trophy dash.
</P>
<P>
   Rip Michels of Mission Hills won the NASCAR Grand American
Modified main event, his second victory in three races this season.
And if not for a blown engine on opening night, Michels might be
perfect this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't getting greedy,'' Michels said. ``Sometimes things go
right and sometimes they don't. Right now they're going right for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   In other action at Irwindale Speedway, Bob Reed of Riverside won
the NASCAR Mini Stock main; Jon Zernikow of Monrovia won the
Legends car main; and Darren Young of Gilbert, Ariz., won the
Mechanix Wear Speed Trucks main.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Hornaday Jr. of Palmdale, the top rookie on the NASCAR Busch
Grand National Division, will be making his first trip for a points
race to Lowe's Motor Speedway for Saturday's Charlotte 300.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean he doesn't have any experience at the
1.5-mile oval.
</P>
<P>
   Driving identical convertible Winston Cup cars, Hornaday beat
NASCAR Winston Cup driver Jimmy Spencer during last year's Summer
Shootout at Lowe's Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   While testing at Dover Downs this week, Hornaday was clocked at
29.005 seconds, nearly .2 seconds faster than the pole qualifying
time for the Busch series race there last year. As a result, crew
chief Gere Kennon decided to use the same car at Lowe's Motor
Speedway this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great test at Charlotte two weeks ago and I was
pleased with how we gained on everyone all day long,'' Hornaday
said. ``We didn't start out real good, but Gere, Steve (Hmiel) and
everyone on the NAPA Auto Parts team kept thrashing and we were as
good as anyone on the second day. But then we went to Dover and
that car was awesome. It was the best Busch car I have ever driven.
We all decided we had to bring the Dover car to Charalotte and so I
am even more excited than I was before.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering the Charlotte 300, Hornaday holds a 10-point lead in
the rookie standings, ahead of Kevin Harvick of Bakersfield.
Hornaday is also fifth in the overall standings, but has yet to win
a race this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fifth in points and that's great, but we want to win
races,'' Hornaday said. ``Everyone on this team is used to winning
races, and we haven't won yet. So I'm disappointed. Don't get me
wrong. I'm not upset with how we've run, but (team owner) Dale
Earnhardt expects victories. And Ron Hornaday does too.
</P>
<P>
   Pasadena High graduate Richie Hearn qualified 23rd for Sunday's
Indianapolis 500. He will be driving the Pagan Racing Team
Dallara-Aurora in the race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
