<HEADLINE>
TRAINING CAMP TO REMAIN FREE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Dallas Cowboys owner Jerry Jones will be content
to let rival owner Daniel Snyder of the Washington Redskins one-up
him in charging fans admission to attend training-camp practices
this summer. The Redskins announced this week that fans attending
two-a-day workouts at the team's Loudoun County facility, just
north of Dulles International Airport, will have to pay $10 per day
(children 12 and younger are free), plus $10 parking, beginning
July 20.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys will remain admission-free and parking-free during
their stay at Midwestern State University in Wichita Falls, July 17
to Aug. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think a lot of our training camp,'' Jones said Thursday,
``but we also think it's a unique time for our fans ... so we won't
be doing that.'' JONES SUPPORTS 14-TEAM PLAYOFFS
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jones is in favor of the NFL's proposal to expand the
playoff format from 12 teams to 14 teams, beginning in 2002 when
Houston makes it a 32-team league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like adding two more (playoff) teams,'' Jones said. ``With
(expansion), I think it will be exciting for at least two more
cities that time of year, and I think it will create more
incentive.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones returned to Valley Ranch on Thursday after spending the
previous three days in Baltimore at the NFL owners meetings. Also
under study was a plan to seed playoff teams, which would increase
the incentive for teams to keep winning even after they clinch
their divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Discussion will continue. There are arguments for and against an
8-8 division champion being seeded above a 9-7 wild-card team.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a point yet to be determined,'' Jones said. ``But since
we're looking at it, we might as well look at that, too. The fact
that you won't be playing as many teams within your division (under
a four-team division format), gives to that consideration. And I
would entertain it.'' UNDERWOOD SETTLING IN
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Dimitrius Underwood continues to be as impressive
with his ability on the practice field as he does in being a
non-story off it.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas is the third NFL stop for Underwood, a first-round pick
in 1999, who failed in Minnesota and Miami. His career since
getting out of Michigan State has been marred by psychological
problems, including a suicide attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an on-going thing ... (but) I feel very good about the
direction he's headed. I don't want to put any added pressure on
him. He's working on some issues,'' Cowboys coach Dave Campo said,
adding that coaches, teammates and team counselors continue to be a
support system for Underwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taking it one day at a time,'' Underwood said. ``I'm not
worried about the past; I'm not worried about the future; I'm
taking it one day at a time. This is a great opportunity for me ...
and I'm going to run with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Underwood, who is 6-foot-6 and normally plays at 290 pounds,
presently tips the scales at 305.
</P>
<P>
   ``My problem usually is trying to keep weight on,'' he said.
``What I hear about (the heat in) training camp, I'll lose it quick
enough.'' BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Wide receiver James McKnight missed the final day of voluntary
quarterback school Thursday to attend an out-of-town wedding.
``He's done a great job this off-season (coming back from major
knee surgery in August). He's excused,'' Dave Campo said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Defensive end Ebenezer Ekuban ``really gets my attention,''
said Jerry Jones, explaining that the second-year player has bulked
up without losing his burst. Jones also was impressed this week by
cornerbacks Charlie Williams and Kevin Smith. The latter normally
plays at 185-190 pounds, but weighs 200 for the first time in his
life.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
