<HEADER>
A5918 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES26-CO     05-25 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES26-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   NAn interview with STEVE GRISSOMSteve Grissom will be behind the
wheel of the No. 44 Pontiac this week, substituting for regular
driver Kyle Petty. Grissom, a 36-year-old native of Gadsden, Ala.,
who honed his skills on the short tracks around north Georgia, will
drive for the team in Sunday's Coca-Cola 600. Grissom is a Winston
Cup veteran and former Busch series champion, and he drives the
Petty Enterprises entry in NASCAR's Craftsman Truck Series. He also
is the testing the Dodges that Petty Enterprises will run next
season. He spoke with members of the media earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are your thoughts going into this weekend's race?
</P>
<P>
   A: While I appreciate the opportunity, I don't care very much
for the circumstances. I'm just glad I have the chance to do
something to help out the family. This was a terrible deal, just
horrible, and I know how rough it has been on me personally, so I
can't begin to imagine how bad it has been for Kyle, Pattie,
Austin, Montgomery Lee and the rest of the family. Driving the car
this week gives me a chance to give them something back, to do
something for them. I'm sure Kyle can use the time away. I know the
first time I walked through the doors at Petty Enterprises they
treated me like family, and I've been one of the family ever since.
As part of the family, this is my contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Have you set any goals for this race?
</P>
<P>
   A: Our goal all week is to make everybody proud of us. I know
(crew chief) Bobby Leslie and the guys on the team are going to do
everything they can to give us a good car. Most of all, we want to
make Kyle proud of us.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How difficult is it to step into an unfamiliar car?
</P>
<P>
   A: Usually a one-race change like this can be pretty difficult.
A team getting used to a driver, especially a driver they know they
are going to have to get used to only for one race, is tough to do.
They know how they set things up for Kyle, now they have to set
things up for somebody totally different. Knowing these guys some
helps a lot. I know them; they know me. I have a good bit of
Winston Cup experience, so that should help some. And I've turned a
lot of laps at Charlotte, so that ought to help some too.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How important is it for you personally to be running again in
a Winston Cup race at Lowe's Motor Speedway?
</P>
<P>
   A: The speedway isn't far from my house, and I drive by there
almost every day. I've missed running a Winston Cup car there.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR HEADLINES
</P>
<P>
   An exhibition of wrecks.sport has an event quite as intense as
NASCAR's The Winston. Last week's all-star extravaganza started
with 20 drivers and finished with only a dozen -- with a lot of
wrecks in the 70 laps in between. What is the reason behind the
overly aggressive driving -- the record $500,000 purse for the
winner or plain ol' competitive juices? The answer is both. That
was proved when cars nowhere near the front pack mixed it up. The
most fortunate aspect of the non-points event was that no one was
seriously injured in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Weekend for Adam.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   Pettys will go on.Kyle Petty, skipped The Winston and Sunday's
Coca-Cola 600 but will return to the No. 44 Pontiac. The King said
his son will be behind the wheel at Dover, Del., next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Surprise at Hendrick.it is the low-key third member of Hendrick
who is the talk of the track. Jerry Nadeau earned a spot in The
Winson and finished fourth. He will start on the outside pole
Sunday. It is the best streak in the young driver's Winston Cup
career.
</P>
<P>
   LEADERS OF THE PACK
</P>
<P>
   1. Dale Earnhardt Jr. It has been feast or famine for Earnhardt,
rookie driver of the No. 8 Chevrolet, who is red hot after winning
The Winston on Saturday night at Lowe's Motor Speedway in
Charlotte. Earnhardt also won the Charlotte 600 pole. He has posted
victories at Texas and Richmond but crashed in Atlanta, Bristol,
Darlington and Talladega. Earnhardt has three top-10 finishes in
eleven points races. He won't win the championship, but this
third-generation driver seems likely to win again in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   2. Ward Burton. He often is overshadowed by his brother, Jeff,
but Ward has been making his own headlines this year. After winning
at Darlington, one of the toughest stops on the circuit, he is in
position to contend for the points title. Crew chief Tommy Baldwin
now is regarded as one of the best in NASCAR. The worry is whether
the impending move to Dodge in 2001 will hurt their championship
aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   3. Bobby Labonte. He will be a solid favorite to win the 600
Sunday night in Charlotte. Bobby leads the Winston Cup points
standings but by only three points over Ward Burton after recent
struggles, including the wreck at Talladega.
</P>
<P>
   4. Jeff Burton. A streaky driver with a streaky team. The No. 99
Exide Ford team has been plagued by some bad luck while leading
races, including the Cracker Barrel 500 at Atlanta, but don't count
out the Roush Racing team.
</P>
<P>
   5. Mark Martin. He doesn't win as often, but he seems to be in
the top five every week. He is third in the points standings, and
many racing people think this could be the year for the title. His
off-season back surgery has been a success.
</P>
<P>
   FREE FALLIN'
</P>
<P>
   1. Tony Stewart. Stewart is happy only when he wins. He is not
winning this year. He finally led his first lap of the season at
Richmond. He could've and should've won the even, but was nudged on
pit road by eventual winner Dale Earnhardt Jr. After the race
ended, Stewart almost ran over several spectators as he revved up
his engine on the way to the garage. In The Winston last week, he
was criticized by the Burton brothers for trying to run over Mark
Martin. Stewart later apologized to Martin.
</P>
<P>
   2. Johnny Benson. Benson, who nearly held off the Fords in the
Daytona 500, has had little success since. He started strong but
was hindered by an early season DNQ. The Tyler Jet Motorsports team
needs a strong 600 to gain momentum for the long summer.
</P>
<P>
   3. Geoffrey Bodine. Bodine, who survived one of the worst
crashes in the history of Daytona International Speedway in
February, is driving the No. 60 Chevrolet. But suddenly, he is
involved in the rumor mill. After crashing Saturday night at
Charlotte, it seemed that team owner Joe Bessey was ready to pull
the plug on Bodine. But Bessey will let the Chemung, N.Y., driver
stay on for now.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE RISE
</P>
<P>
   1. Steve Park. The No. 1 Chevy driver has surpassed Mike Skinner
as ``the best Winston Cup driver not to win a race yet.'' He is
part of the hottest team in racing, with Dale Earnhardt Jr. his
on-track partner. Although overshadowed by Little E's victory at
The Winston, Park also earned accolades for winning The Winston
Open qualifying race. He had a shot at the trophy in the main event
before being bumped and turned around by Joe Nemechek.
</P>
<P>
   2. Jerry Nadeau. The newest driver at Hendrick Motorsports had
the best moments of his career during The Winston all-star weekend.
Nadeau won a spot on the front row for The Winston Open in
qualifying. He earned a spot in the main event by winning the No
Bull Sprint. He kept up the hot streak by finishing fourth in the
all-star race. If Nadeau can stay consistent, he will justify the
sponsorship dollars of Michael Holigam Homes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Ken Schrader. He has performed miserably in qualifying this
year. Schrader is in his first year with MB2 Motorsports and the
team has struggled to develop chemistry. Despite troubles, the
veteran driver ranks 16th in the points and has a chance at the top
10. Schrader has a lot of momentum after finishing 12th in
Richmond, and he could surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
