<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    15 refugees found on stopped sailboat
 &HT;    By Jill Taylor
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT SALERNO, Fla. _ A sheriff's marine deputy noticed a 35-foot
Morgan sailboat riding low in the water in the Manatee Pocket
Thursday and found 15 refugees hiding below decks when he boarded
the boat for an inspection.
</P>
<P>
   Martin County Deputy John Howell was joined by Florida Fish and
Wildlife officer Clay McDonough in trying to keep track of the nine
men and six women until Border Patrol arrived.
</P>
<P>
   One man jumped on the deck and dived overboard, making his way
to Rocky Point before McDonough caught up with him in the yard of a
home on Williams Way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were jumping fences . . . until he finally stopped,'' said
McDonough as fire rescue workers treated the man for low blood
sugar.
</P>
<P>
   The man carried a passport identifying him as Sean Leon Osborne,
23, of the northern South American country of Guyana. He was
treated at the scene and turned over to immigration officials who
planned to take him to West Palm Beach for processing and then to
Krome detention center in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Because the remaining refugees, eight others from Guyana and six
from Haiti, never set foot on American soil, they were to be
transferred to a Coast Guard cutter and scheduled for immediate
deportation.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne, who carried photographs of a young woman and a child
with his passport, will have the opportunity for a hearing to
contest deportation.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they think the group boarded the sailboat in the
Bahamas, the latest in a series of refugees to arrive in Martin
County in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Sailboat captain Harold Emil Fredrick, 48, of Lake City, was
arrested on warrants out of North Florida charging him with
violating probation, worthless checks and failing to appear in
court on a felony drunken driving charge.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also were researching ownership of the 1976 sailboat,
the Summerwind, which was registered out of St. George Island in
Florida's Panhandle and whether it might qualify for seizure under
state or federal laws.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
