<HEADER>
A5922 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-AUTO-ROLLOVER-ART-NYT     05-25 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-ROLLOVER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT PLANS TO RANK VEHICLES BY ROLLOVER RISK 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Transportation Department, which has been
trying since 1973 to find a way to reduce vehicle rollovers, said
Thursday that it wanted to publish a ranking of cars, vans, pickups
and sport utility vehicles that it said correlated with their
tendency to turn over.
</P>
<P>
   Rollovers kill nearly 10,000 people a year, more than a quarter
of all the people who are killed in vehicles. Of the deaths in
sport utility vehicles, 62 percent are in rollover crashes; for
vans and pickups, the figure is just over 40 percent, and for cars,
22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The government's main tool for safety is setting crash test
requirements, but to reduce rollovers it proposes using a public
ranking instead, based on the width of vehicles and the height of
their center of gravity. The agency now uses rankings for front-
and side-impact performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Empowered consumers will have added ability to judge more
aspects of a vehicle's safety performance,'' said Transportation
Secretary Rodney Slater. With the ranking, Slater said, consumers
can ``make choices based on reason and reflection, rather than just
the style and appearance of a given vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   He and other officials said they hoped the rankings would
encourage manufacturers to make their vehicles lower and wider.
</P>
<P>
   But some safety advocates said a better approach would be
establishing performance standards. ``A highway safety issue that
takes 10,000 lives a year and costs $30 billion deserves a more
effective response,'' said David F. Snyder, a spokesman for the
American Insurance Association.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers Union, the publisher of Consumer Reports, whose
petition to the government in 1988 for a rollover standard produced
Thursday's announcement of a grading system instead, said that it
was pleased with the result, but that requiring live tests would
have been better.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we evaluate any product, we make every effort to test
that product in as close to real-world conditions _ i.e., having
the product perform its essential tasks, _ as we can,'' said Dr. R.
David Pittle, senior vice president and technical director at
Consumers Union. Cars should be tested, Pittle said, on how well
they perform and avoid accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The auto makers have argued, though, that rollover tests do not
produce consistent results. Vehicles ride on springy suspension
systems and thus vibrate, said Gloria J. Bergquist, a spokeswoman
for the Alliance of Automobile Manufacturers. They may roll because
of the oscillation, Bergquist said, but if the government ranked
the vehicles' tendency to roll on a course, and then changed the
shape of the course, the ranking would change.
</P>
<P>
   The ranking system that the Transportation Department now plans
to use consists of one-half the track width of the vehicle divided
by the height of its center of gravity, a ranking called the static
stability index. The department will use the scores to award stars,
from one to five, to separate the vehicles into classes, as it
already does for front-impact and side-impact performance. More
stars means less tendency to roll.
</P>
<P>
   Bergquist said that might have some value, but that ``some
issues are just too complex to be reduced to an icon.''
</P>
<P>
   But Joan Claybrook, a former head of the National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration and now president of Public Citizen,
an advocacy group, said that resorting to a ranking instead of a
rule was particularly unhelpful for the class of driver most likely
to roll a car, young people who do not choose cars with safety in
mind.
</P>
<P>
   The department estimates that there are 228,000 vehicle
rollovers a year. Sometimes vehicles roll over in the course of a
collision with another vehicle, but the vast majority are
single-vehicle crashes. Of the 25,000 people seriously injured in
these crashes, most are not wearing seat belts, and more than half
are fully or partially ejected from the vehicle in the course of
the crash, sometimes with the vehicle then rolling over them.
</P>
<P>
   The agency had been working on a performance standard, but
dropped that approach in 1994 because it said it could not
determine a measure that would predict rollover likelihood. Since
then it has been working on the grading system that was announced
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The safety administration, the part of the Transportation
Department with jurisdiction over light-duty vehicles, including
cars, vans and most sport utilities, said a grading system would be
faster to implement, compared with a crash-test program, and that
the agency was well set up to run it.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal announced Thursday will be open for public comment
for 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   Agency officials acknowledged that road conditions and driver
behavior were big influences on the likelihood of a rollover. But a
study of 186,000 crashes over a five-year period found that the
stability index correlated well with the incidence of rollovers,
department officials said.
</P>
<P>
   That study, based on cars built in the '90s, found that cars
generally get five stars, the highest rating, or four; minivans get
two or three; sport utilities, one to three, and pickups, one to
four.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
