<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE STILL PLANS TO RECOMMEND SPLITTING MICROSOFT IN TWO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A government official close to the Microsoft
antitrust case confirmed that the plaintiffs will not seek to break
Microsoft into three or four companies.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, the Justice Department and 17 of the 19 states
Friday will file a slightly modified version of their original
proposal to divide the company in two.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that's what the judge decides to do is another question.
</P>
<P>
   The judge who ruled Microsoft is an unlawful monopolist could
enlarge on the Justice Department's proposed remedies if he wishes,
according to past Supreme Court cases.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Microsoft sank $4.06 a share Thursday, to close at
$61.50, one day after U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson
abruptly ended the two-year-old trial saying there were be no
further hearings. Proposals now will be submitted in writing and,
if the judge follows the plan he outlined Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   By his detailed questioning in the three-hour hearing Wednesday,
capped by a request that a new copy of the plaintiffs' proposal be
filed by Friday, Jackson strongly suggested he will embrace a
breakup plan of some sort.
</P>
<P>
   That Justice Department's plan, filed April 28, proposes
splitting the Redmond giant into an operating-system company and an
applications company. It also imposes restrictions on Microsoft's
business conduct.
</P>
<P>
   But past Supreme Court antitrust cases give judges broad
discretion to fashion remedies as they see fit. So Jackson could
pick and choose among several remedy proposals filed by ``friends
of the court'' on the plaintiffs' behalf.
</P>
<P>
   One amicus brief, which Jackson praised as ``excellent,''
advocates dividing the company into three entities, respectively
handling applications, the Windows operating system and the
Internet Explorer Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's admiration of that proposal in open court touched
off media speculation that the judge was considering a three-way
breakup of the company. The judge expressed concern at several
points that the Justice Department proposal did not go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   But at the hearing's conclusion Wednesday, he asked the Justice
Department only to submit a ``clean copy'' of its proposal. One
government official said later that day that the Justice Department
understands Jackson's request to mean ``tweaking or fine-tuning''
the proposal rather than broadening it to split the company into
three pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Those tweaks may include points touched on by Jackson during the
hearing, including:
</P>
<P>
   _Changing key definitions, including the definition of
``Microsoft'' itself
</P>
<P>
   _Adjusting limits on how much Microsoft stock an investor can
own before being forbidden from running, working for or investing
in the other company
</P>
<P>
   _Increasing government control over the breakup, because, as
Jackson said, ``I do not believe that Microsoft will be a willing
participant in it.''
</P>
<P>
   _Expanding the disclosures Microsoft must make, possibly even
requiring the company to release key source code to the general
public.
</P>
<P>
   The question of stock limits was raised in a letter written by
Microsoft co-founder and board member Paul Allen of Mercer Island.
Whether Microsoft should be forced to disclose its source code
arose in a pointed question Jackson asked Microsoft: ``Isn't
forfeiture a traditional equity remedy?''
</P>
<P>
   No, it isn't, at least not in antitrust law, answered Microsoft
attorney John Warden. And if Microsoft were forced to forfeit its
intellectual property, ``the conduct remedy alone would disable us
from competing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has continued to hammer away at the style
of Microsoft's competition, citing most recently a collection of
e-mails as as evidence that a structural remedy is needed to ensure
that Microsoft doesn't use its market power in personal computers
to dominate other products, like cell phones, set-top boxes and
handheld computers.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. Chairman Bill Gates warned Nokia Oyj in 1998
that Symbian Ltd.'s choice of the Java programming language would
be ``just declaring war on us,'' according to e-mails that were
unsealed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason for them to do this except to attack
Microsoft,'' Gates wrote in messages made available in the
government's case. ``In any of these areas, we can provide things
as good as Sun (Microsystems Inc.) and things that work with the
PC.''
</P>
<P>
   Symbian is a group that includes Nokia, Ericsson AB, Matsushita
Electric Industrial Co., Motorola Inc. and Psion Plc as members.
Sun, Microsoft's rival, developed Java. Sun and Microsoft compete
in markets ranging from server software to programs written in
Java.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't let Sun win in this,'' Gates wrote in June 1998.
``Sun has no reason they should be chosen here'' by Symbian. He
also said that if Symbian chose to use a proprietary browser or
aggressively promote Sun's Java programming language, ``we should
do the most extreme things we can,'' including possibly not working
with the group on television set-top boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft was adamant in its response.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent these e-mails have anything to say about the
current case, we believe they actually undermine the government's
arguments,'' said Mark Murray, a Microsoft spokesman. ``At the
heart of both of these e-mails is Microsoft struggling to respond
to intense competition from a number of very powerful companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever remedy Jackson chooses, he must craft it into a
comprehensive final order, which will probably take at least a
month, said University of Baltimore law professor Bob Lande. The
entry of that order concludes the trial and is the final step
before an appeal can proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has said it will begin appellate proceedings
immediately upon entry of the order. Most lawyers connected with
the case believe that any restructuring would be stayed pending the
appeal's outcome but that the conduct-based portion of the remedy
would quickly go into effect.
</P>
<P>
   Wire service material was included in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
