<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 
 PERSONALS: Steve Young Starts His Own Team This Year 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
San Francisco 49er quarterback  &UR; Steve Young &LR; , 38, and his
wife, &UR; Barbara Graham &LR; , 31, are expecting a baby late this year,
says People magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The couple married in Hawaii on March 14, at which time Young's
agent and spokesman,  &UR; Leigh Steinberg &LR;  _ apparently prophetically _
pronounced them ``a perfect fit.'' Young is the oldest of five
siblings. In response to questions about family size at the time of
the wedding, Steinberg said, he was sure Young's ``vision is `the
more, the merrier.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Young's football career has been on hold since a series of
mishaps early last season forced him to the sidelines; he is said
to be leaning toward retiring from the sport.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE THINGS THEY DO TO PETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Filmmaker  &UR; Ethan Coen  &LR; talks with  &UR; Jennifer Jason Leigh  &LR; in the
latest issue of Interview, as part of that magazine's series of
photo essays on stars and their pets. Leigh has two dogs, Bessie
and Otis, and both she and Coen are outraged by various countries'
insistence that dogs be quarantined when they cross borders. Leigh
mentions that her dogs were once held for two weeks when she went
to Tanganyika on a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear in some countries they cross-train them in
quarantine,'' says Coen. ``They have people in lab coats who teach
them, like, to snap at flies when they hear `Heel!' or vice versa,
just to mess with you when you get your dog back.''
</P>
<P>
   Leigh says that her dogs have never snapped at flies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mention it as an instance,'' says Coen, ``as a form of
psychological warfare. I mention it as a possibility. I don't claim
to be able to substantiate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Leigh asks how this could be done. ``Would the guys in white lab
coats speak all the languages of the tourists that leave their pets
in quarantine?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I mention it as a hypothetical,'' says Coen. ``It's something
to think about. Like why don't we have a word for the sound of a
dog's jaw snapping at flies?''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Tail extensions for dogs _ fur-covered finger cots,
perhaps, that fit over short tails and are secured by belly straps?
_ are one of the beauty possibilities for canine visitors to
Pets.com's Dog Day Afternoon, on June 11 at Speedway Meadow in
Golden Gate Park. The event, a fund-raiser for PAWS, Pets Are
Wonderful Support, is produced by Design Industries Foundation
Fighting AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; IN THE 'HOOD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Smithsonian/Folkways released its first  &UR; Malvina Reynolds &LR; 
compilation _ ``Ear to the Ground: Topical Songs 1960-1978'' on
Tuesday, May 23. Bay Area songwriter Reynolds, who wrote ``Little
Boxes,'' was legendary for her music, her wit and her politics.
</P>
<P>
   _ InStyle magazine reports that at Arista Records' 25th
anniversary party, hosted by  &UR; Clive Davis &LR;  in Hollywood Hills, San
Francisco's own  &UR; Stanlee Gatti &LR; , who planned the decor, used 10,000
Leonadas roses. Roses are Gatti's trademark, but hey, 10,000 is
chopped liver. A Personals check found that the party planner used
50,000 at a dot.commer wedding on Treasure Island in March (only
2,000 at a SFMOMA benefit in January, but that was for a
nonprofit).
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``All of a sudden, smiling fellows come to you with millions
of &LR; 
 &UR; dollars. Most actors are not rich kids. It's a dream and those &LR; 
 &UR; dollars are irresistible, but the actor dies.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Nick Nolte &LR;  describing the Hollywood star system, in the
Times of London.
</P>
