<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5930 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WASH-RWANDA-ART-NYT &LR;      05-25 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASH-RWANDA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RWANDANS PRESENT MESSAGE OF PEACE THROUGH DANCE IN WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURDY, Wash. _ The sharp wooden spears and all the ankle bells
posed a bit of a problem. They are, after all, not exactly standard
prison fare. But for the visiting dancers from the National Ballet
of Rwanda, who said they were spreading a message of reconciliation
as widely as possible during their first appearance in North
America, officials at the Washington Corrections Center for Women
made an exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want all kinds of Americans to see that people can move
forward together,'' said Eugene Kayihura, the first counselor at
the Rwandan Embassy, explaining the dancers' unusual detour to the
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hutu, Tutsi, Twa, they can dance together,'' Kayihura said,
listing the three main ethnic groups in Rwanda. That African
country was ravaged by the civil war in 1994 that left more than
500,000 people dead and turned millions more into refugees. ``Yes,
what people know now of Rwanda is genocide. You go on the Internet
and you type `Rwanda,' and the first thing you will see is
`genocide.' The genocide happened. But we believe this is a sign of
what can happen in the post-genocide era.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rwandan dancers came here for nearly a week of performances
at the Seattle International Children's Festival. True to its
reputation as one of the largest and most far-reaching arts
festivals for young people in the country, the program last week
succeeded in bringing a striking array of troupes from around the
world. Among the performers were the Ho Chi Minh City Water Puppet
Theater from Vietnam; the Lakota Sioux Indian Theater; the Bustan
Abraham contemporary ensemble, featuring Jewish and Arab musicians
from Israel; and the B'net Marrakech, a music and dance troupe from
Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   But no group generated more attention than the Rwandan dancers,
and none seemed to carry a stronger message for old and young alike
that ``dance can make everybody more peace-loving,'' in the words
of Buregeya Deo, 33, one of the 15 dancers in the group, formally
known as Imparage: The Hutus, Tutsis and Pygmies of Rwanda. (The
Pygmies are also known as Twa.)
</P>
<P>
   The group is a unit of Rwanda's national ballet, whose origins
date to 1974, but which was torn apart, as was most everything else
in the nation, by the roughly 100 days of insanity six years ago,
when many Tutsi and moderate Hutu were killed by Hutu extremists.
Most current members of the ballet were refugees, and many had
family members killed.
</P>
<P>
   There was, then, some irony in the fact that the dancers agreed
to end their American visit with a trip to the women's prison here,
which was arranged by festival organizers, prison officials and Pat
Graney, a Seattle choreographer who runs an arts program, called
Keeping the Faith, for imprisoned women.
</P>
<P>
   And even though the dances, many focusing on harvest and
courtship themes, involved exuberant and even joyous outbursts of
singing and foot-stamping, there were at least small signs that
fear and tension persist.
</P>
<P>
   As this reporter conducted an interview Thursday after the
prison performance, one of the Rwandan dancers gently touched his
arm when she saw him write the word ``Hutu'' in his notebook. ``Why
did you write `Hutu' in there?'' she wanted to know. Reading back
part of what she had just said to him, he replied, ``All our people
are Rwandese _ not Hutu, not Tutsi, Rwandese.'' Yes, she nodded
vigorously, that was the point she wanted to make.
</P>
<P>
   Some dancers, the Rwandan officials accompanying them said,
probably have relatives in prison for the 1994 slaughter. There was
intense mutual curiosity during a discussion after the dancers,
many dressed in flowing bleached headdresses, performed. Some
dancers said they found maximum-security conditions for the women
here preferable to the prison-like circumstances they had endured
in refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion was animated, despite being slowly translated
back and forth into English, French and Kinyarwanda, the Rwandan
language.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have our own war going on in America right now,'' one of
the inmates said. But just as she started to explain, another
inmate cut in, saying, ``I'm sure our war is nothing compared to
yours.''
</P>
<P>
   Since recreating their ruined costumes and drums and finding a
new home in Kigali, the Rwandan capital, the dancers have appeared
in several European countries and in South Africa. Plans for their
trip here started when the Seattle festival's producing director,
Brian Faker, saw them last summer in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I totally fell in love with it,'' Faker said of the African
dances, which deal with folklore but not with the tragedy of the
genocide _ not yet, anyway. ``And it's exactly the kind of program
we want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month Paul Kagame took the oath of office as Rwanda's first
Tutsi president, calling on all Rwandans to shun ethnic divisions,
and the nation's director of folklore and ballet, Bernardin
Rutazibwa, who came with the dancers, said he hoped they could help
spread that appeal, and that they would make more visits to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just would like to show the world that we are not as
disunited as people might think,'' Rutazibwa said. ``And I think
this is more eloquent than a bunch of political speeches.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 2146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
