<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5934 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-TEXAS-GOP-HNS &LR;      05-25 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TEXAS-GOP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TO SKIP TEXAS CONVENTION OF REPUBLICANS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush plans to skip next
month's Republican State Convention in Houston, four years after
the party denied him a governor's traditional role of leading the
state delegation to the GOP national convention.
</P>
<P>
   And while a presumptive presidential nominee usually gets a
state convention to name some delegates of his choice to the
national party convention, rules changes made by the Texas party
two years ago could deny Bush any say in who will attend the
national convention expected to nominate him for president.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Republican Party spokesman Robert Black was surprised to
learn Bush will not be at the state convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had assumed our governor would be attending our
convention,'' Black said this week.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's decision to campaign elsewhere during the June 15-17
gathering is evidence both of his confidence about winning Texas in
the fall and of his ongoing conflicts with the religious social
conservatives who dominate the state party and vex him at a
national level.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush tried to focus attention on a meeting with retired Gen.
Colin Powell on Thursday, the governor also had to defend himself
against an attack by James Dobson, president of the Colorado-based
conservative group Focus on the Family. Dobson accused Bush of
sacrificing the core principles of the Republican Party by refusing
to rule out selecting a running mate who favors abortion rights,
and by meeting last month with gay Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The Log Cabin Republicans of Texas, a gay rights group, blasted
Texas GOP leadership Thursday for denying them a convention booth
at the state convention for the third time.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Labinski of Austin, president of the group, said Texas
Republican party leaders are ``out of touch with mainstream voters
and mainstream Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Bush admonished state party leaders to stop
``name-calling'' after a party executive said the Texas GOP did not
want ``a group of transvestites, cross-dressers or Log Cabins.''
</P>
<P>
   As to the governor's missing the convention this year, Bush
spokesman Karen Hughes said his schedule is built around winning
the presidency, not any past disagreements with Texas Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most finite resource you have in a campaign is a
candidate's time,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 160-some days between now and the election, and we are
trying on those days to reach out to voters who have not made up
their minds in the presidential campaign in key states,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said Bush's schedule is not final but that the campaign
plans to have him in Kentucky and Florida during the Texas
Republican Convention. She said his wife, Laura, likely will speak
to the Texas gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, the likely Democratic candidate, also
has not committed to speaking to his party's Texas state convention
June 9-10 in Fort Worth, but state party conventions in Georgia,
Montana, Wisconsin and Washington are competing for Gore's
attention that weekend. Bush and Gore are tied in Wisconsin and
Washington public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   As vice president and presidential candidate in 1988, the
governor's father spoke to the Texas GOP convention, but during his
1992 re-election campaign President Bush sent his wife, Barbara.
The president spoke later that summer at the Republican National
Convention in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1996 Texas GOP convention, Gov. Bush lost the
honorary national convention role as delegation chairman when
anti-abortion state convention delegates tried unsuccessfully to
block U.S. Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison's appointment as an at-large
delegate to the GOP gathering in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison and people selected by Bob Dole's presidential
campaign that year normally could have expected to be
rubber-stamped as national convention delegates. But anti-abortion
forces threatened to block the entire delegate list because
Hutchison was not viewed as fervent enough in her anti-abortion
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush supported Hutchison, who eked out a national convention
spot during a state convention vote. But the state convention gave
the delegation leadership slot to then-state party Chairman Tom
Pauken.
</P>
<P>
   Bush should have been expected to name delegates to this year's
Republican National Convention in Philadelphia. But changes made
two years ago in state party rules could deny Bush his choices as
well as the selection of any statewide officeholders, including
Hutchison.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bush's uneasy truce with social conservatives has been tested by
his search for a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Coalition founder Pat Robertson and former
presidential candidate Gary Bauer have warned that if Bush picks a
vice presidential candidate who supports abortion rights, he might
find social conservatives staying home on election day.
</P>
<P>
   Dobson on Wednesday accused Bush of sacrificing the party's core
principles to appeal to swing voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people believe the only way to win the White House is to
build a big tent, but if you stand for everything you stand for
nothing,'' Dobson said, calling for Bush to name an anti-abortion
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he appreciated Dobson's advice, but added that he is
an ``independent thinker'' and is getting advice from Republicans
of many different philosophies about whom he should pick as a
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing people are going to learn about me is I'm going to
make my decisions based on what I think is right for America,''
Bush said. ``And in all due respect to who you quoted (Dobson) and
others, I'm confident I can unite the party and lead us to
victory.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
