<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-BLOCH-BOS </SLUG>
  
 RICHARD BLOCH, A COMPUTER PIONEER, IS DEAD
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   BOSTON _ Richard M. Bloch, who helped design and program the
first automatic digital computer, has died at age 78.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Bloch, of Marlborough, Mass., died Monday of cancer in Oak
Knoll Healthcare Center in Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   As chief operations officer at Harvard University's Computation
Laboratory, he played a key role in the development of the Mark I
digital computer. And his inventions included the standard
procedure for automatic error detection known as parity check, used
in virtually all computers, as well as barcode technology for
computerized scanning of information.
</P>
<P>
   He also developed some of the first applications of computers to
online processing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a legend of the business, a wonderful, graceful man,''
John Cullinane, founder of Cullinet Software, said Thursday. ``He
co-authored papers with John von Neumann. He taught programming to
Grace Hopper, who later invented COBOL (an early computer
language). He was 21. She was 43.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Bloch was born in Rochester, N.Y., the son of Harry and
Tillie Bloch, owners of a printing business. He attended Harvard
College on full scholarship and became captain of its golf team.
After graduation in 1943 he served as a lieutenant in the Navy,
then returned to Harvard after the war as a research associate in
its engineering division.
</P>
<P>
   There followed a series of jobs in Boston's growing computer
industry: general manager of the computer division at Raytheon
Corp., vice president for technical operations at Honeywell Inc.,
vice president for corporate development at Auerbach Corp., vice
president of the advanced systems division at General Electric Co.
</P>
<P>
   He was a director of Cullinet, and chairman and CEO of
Artificial Intelligence Corp., Niche Data Systems, and Meiko
Scientific Corp.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime resident of Newton, Mr. Bloch summered every year in
West Dennis.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife of 40 years, Ruth, and seven children:
Charlote Johnson Zembko of Bolton; Lawrence of Belmont; Emily
Martin of Bolton; Debra Ellingwood of Framingham; Susan
Bloch-Nevitte of Toronto; Kathryn Swarts of Houston; and Richard of
Huntington Beach, Calif.; and eight grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 2152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
