<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETIRES FROM CHRISTIE'S 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain, Germany, France, Italy)  
 THE PROUD MET UNVEILS A PRIZE; GUGGENHEIM POSTPONES KOONS SHOW
UNTIL 2003 or 2004; PS1 AND MOMA MERGER IS COMPLETED; FINDLAY(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After four months of conservation and restoration,
the Metropolitan Museum of Art has hung a recent acquisition: ``The
Lamentation'' by the Italian Baroque painter Ludovico Carracci.
</P>
<P>
   The museum bought the painting for $5.2 million at Christie's in
January. The price was huge, considering that the estimate had been
$300,000 to $500,000. But at auction all it takes is two serious
bidders, and in this case the Met's competition was the Museum of
Fine Arts in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Painted around 1582, ``The Lamentation'' is a sprawling image of
Jesus that stretches the full width of the canvas, which measures
37{ by 68 inches. Not only are works by Carracci rare, but the
painting itself is also considered exceptional.
</P>
<P>
   ``It marks the beginning of the Baroque,'' said Andrea Bayer,
assistant curator of European paintings at the Met. ``The
naturalist treatment of the body of Christ is incredible and was
painted from a live studio model.''
</P>
<P>
   The painting had been in a South American collection, with no
artist's attribution. But when it arrived at Christie's, Anthony
Crichton-Stuart, head of the old master paintings department,
noticed that ``there were two old labels on the back marked Palazzo
Tanari in Bologna,'' he said. ``Alessandro Tanari, who died in
1639, was an important collector of contemporary Bolognese
painting.''
</P>
<P>
   Crichton-Stuart said the painting was stylistically similar to
others by Carracci, most notably in the angular faces, the
exaggerated perspective and the coloration.
</P>
<P>
   The Met already has four paintings by Annibale Carracci, the
artist's far better-known cousin. This is its first painting by
Ludovico. The museum is organizing ``The Beginning of Baroque:
Carracci at the Metropolitan,'' which is to open on July 7 and will
include paintings, drawings and prints.
</P>
<P>
   KOONS REDUX
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Koons, the 1980s art star who drifts on and off the art
world's radar screen, is making yet another comeback. Prices for
his work have been soaring: one collector paid $1.8 million at
Christie's in November for a porcelain sculpture of a seminude
blond woman hugging a Pink Panther. Last week another paid $1.7
million there for a sculpture of a woman sitting in a bubble bath
clutching her breasts.
</P>
<P>
   Another Koons creation, a 43-foot-tall terrier puppy made of
live flowers, is being installed at the site in Rockefeller Center
where the Christmas tree stands every year. Thursday
``Split-Rocker,'' a 40-foot-tall topiary _ half pony, half dino _
with 75,000 live flowers in the shape of a giant child's rocking
toy was unveiled in the Benoit XII Cloister in the Papal Palace in
Avignon, France.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a while everybody wanted to know what happened to Jeff,''
said Lisa Dennison, deputy director and chief curator of the
Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum, who has been closely involved with
Koons' work. For years the museum has been planning a major Koons
retrospective. It was unofficially scheduled for this month, then
officially announced for next May. Now, Dennison said, the
Guggenheim hopes to hold the exhibition in the fall of 2003 or the
winter of 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the delays have been due to the high costs of
fabrication and technical difficulties in making the works that are
part of ``Celebration,'' a series of large-scale sculptures and
paintings. Because of their size and the materials _ stainless
steel and plastics that are hard to manufacture _ they require
special use of foundries, a cost that has nearly bankrupted some
dealers who hoped to produce the pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Koons wanted to finish the ``Celebration'' series before the
retrospective, Dennison said. He also wanted to have a body of new
work that could be shown for the first time at the Guggenheim.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago Koons returned to the Sonnabend Gallery,
which has handled him on and off since 1986. In November the
gallery showed some of his ``Easyfun'' series, a dozen large tinted
mirrors based on generic cartoon animals, including a sheep, a
donkey, a bear, a kangaroo and a cow. Now Sonnabend is working with
galleries in Europe to present a series of ``Easyfun'' shows that
also include paintings and one sculpture. The shows are to be in
London, Berlin, Paris and Milan. Larry Gagosian is also planning a
show of Koons' work in his Los Angeles space in March.
</P>
<P>
   Opening on Oct. 26 at the Deutsche Guggenheim Berlin will be a
show of several new paintings commissioned for that space. ``The
work will probably travel to Bilbao,'' Dennison said. ``Then it
will enter the collection of the Guggenheim Museum and Deutsche
Bank.''
</P>
<P>
   `WE'RE COOKING'
</P>
<P>
   Although it has been 15 months since P.S. 1 and the Museum of
Modern Art announced their intention to merge, the deal was
approved by the New York State Board of Regents only a month ago,
and the two institutions met just last week to approve a new board.
It has 27 members: 18 nominated by PS 1 and approved by the Modern,
and 9 nominated by the Modern and approved by PS 1. ``The deal is
done,'' said Glenn D. Lowry, director of the Modern. ``We're open
for business and we're cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   RETIRE? HARDLY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Findlay has taken early retirement after 16 years at
Christie's. But that doesn't mean he plans to stop working. William
Acquavella announced this week that Findlay, whose most recent job
at Christie's was international director of fine arts, would become
the director of the Acquavella Galleries on East 79th Street in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The new post will entail buying and selling art, Acquavella
said, as well as helping with the administration of the gallery.
``I'm ready to concentrate on a smaller number of paintings and a
smaller number of collectors,'' Findlay said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of his work at Christie's involved working with dealers and
collectors in Southeast Asia. ``He was our ambassador there,'' said
Edward Dolman, Christie's chief executive worldwide. Replacing him
in Asia will be Toshihiko Hatanaka, who works for Christie's in
Tokyo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
