u a BC-WENDYS-MURDERS-1STLD-     05-25 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WENDYS-MURDERS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACRE ON MAIN STREET: 5 SLAIN AT WENDY'S IN QUEENS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Changes Toyota Maxima to Nissan Maxima in 12th graph of 2nd
take; ``hole'' deleted in 5th graph of 1st take; adds 15th graph
with description of suspects; adds name to byline.) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT8, 9, 11 and 12 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Graphic and map are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW and WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was just past closing time at the Wendy's on Main
Street in Flushing, Queens. Two men, one short and one tall,
knocked at the locked front door, calling out for the manager by
name.
</P>
<P>
   The manager, 27-year-old Jean Dumel Auguste, seemed to know the
men, and he led at least one of them down to the store basement
where he kept a small office near the employee changing rooms and a
large walk-in refrigerator-freezer.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after, Auguste used the store's intercom system to
summon his small night crew down into the basement for a meeting.
Six employees made their way down the back stairs into the cool,
musty basement.
</P>
<P>
   It was a death trap.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, on one of the busiest strips in Queens, a
massacre began to unfold _ a crime so grisly, so ruthless that it
left some of the city's most experienced homicide investigators
sickened. When it was over Wednesday night, all seven employees had
been shot, all of them at close range, all in the head. Five were
killed, including Auguste. A sixth was fighting for his life
Thursday night, and the seventh survived, his cheeks pierced by a
bullet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most horrendous crime scene I've ever witnessed in
my nine years as district attorney of this county, and as people
know, I've been to a lot of crime scenes,'' Richard Brown, the
Queens district attorney, said Thursday, as hundreds of police
officers hunted the city for two suspects, and as relatives,
stricken with shock and grief, gathered at a nearby Sheraton Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the crime appeared to have been carefully
planned and timed, and they focused their initial investigation on
former Wendy's employees. Indeed, customers said that in the
moments before the restaurant's closing time, there was no hint at
all of what was to come.
</P>
<P>
   A young couple sat at a front table, quietly finishing their
food. One employee went about emptying trash bins. Others were
wiping down tables and counters. At 10:55 p.m., a regular walked in
and ordered one of the night's last meals, a junior bacon
cheeseburger, a baked potato with sour cream and chives and a
salad.
</P>
<P>
   By 11 p.m., the store was empty but for seven employees, and the
front door was locked. In the most haunting disclosure,
investigators said that a passing police officer tried to stop in
for a hamburger shortly after closing time but was shooed away. A
senior police official said the officer reported that he was waved
away by a man and a woman standing at the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's very possible that could have been the robber
standing there with the female,'' the official said. ``The cop
tells us there is a guy and a girl standing at the door saying
we're closed. His sense was they seemed friendly. But could he have
been standing there with a gun at her back? It's possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Once in the basement, the employees _ Ramon Nazario, 44; Anita
C. Smith, 23; Jeremy Mele, 18, Ali Ibadat, 40; Patrick Castro, 23,
and Jaquione Johnson, 18 _ were quickly subdued at gunpoint, police
officials said. The gunmen used duct tape to bind hands behind
backs and gag mouths. At some point, plastic bags were slipped over
the heads of all seven employees, and they were forced into the
large walk-in unit that combines a refrigerator section and freezer
section. And then they began to shoot, apparently determined to
leave no witnesses to their theft of as much as $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Thursday night how the men made their getaway.
Police officials said they believed that the two men might have
slipped out a side door after stealing the manager's keys. But a
woman at a nearby bus stop also told the police she saw two men
leave from the front door.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 90 minutes or so, two of the wounded, Castro and
Johnson, worked themselves free. Castro called 911 from a basement
telephone connected to the fax machine in the manager's office.
``We're in the basement,'' he managed to say, despite the bullet
wound to his cheeks. ``We're locked in.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson considered Castro his closest friend at Wendy's,
Johnson's family said. The two sometimes walked home together. Now,
Castro dragged Johnson upstairs, where they waited for the police
by the front counter. Johnson, who had a bullet lodged near the top
of his skull, was in Castro's arms. According to police
investigators, Castro was in such a daze that he did not even
realize he had been shot in the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   The first officers arrived at 12:52 a.m. The first paramedics
arrived a minute later. Seeing two wounded men inside, the officers
smashed through the glass of the locked front door.
</P>
<P>
   As Johnson and Castro were taken to a hospital, the officers
followed a trail of blood down the stairs to the basement, where
they confronted the carnage. There was blood everywhere _ on the
walls, on the floor, on boxes of food. Four of the employees were
already dead. A fifth died on the way to New York Hospital Medical
Center in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first Emergency Medical Service paramedics on the
scene described his reaction to a superior. ``He said to me, `You
trained for this, you're prepared for this. But you're never
prepared for this. These were kids. They were teen-agers. This was
a massacre.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said they believed the weapon used was a
.380-calibre semiautomatic handgun. Police said they were unsure
whether more than one was used in the attack.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
