<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRIATHLON-TRIALS-TEX </SLUG>
 
IT MIGHT BE HOT, BUT TRIATHLETES LIKE iRVING TEST 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ This much we know. It has been months since
somebody spotted sharks in Las Colinas' Lake Carolyn.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, as visiting Olympic triathlon hopefuls have
probably noticed, it's not getting any cooler in North Texas. So,
choose your poison.
</P>
<P>
   Those who raised eyebrows when Irving was selected to be U.S.
triathlon's gateway to the Sydney Olympics are missing the prime
selling point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great course; very similar to Sydney,'' said San
Antonio native Jennifer Gutierrez, who has already qualified for
the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   There is no world famous opera house, such as the one from which
the triathletes will enter the water in Sydney. There is no
bustling harbor, as in Sydney with its reportedly shark-inhabited
waters.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, at the U.S. Olympic Triathlon Trials this weekend,
competitors will plunge into the relatively tranquil waters of a
manmade lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be some contact; there's usually contact the whole
way,'' said Ryan Bolton of Colorado Springs, Colo., one of the
men's race favorites. ``It's part of the equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this should be a pretty fast swim. The lake there is going
to be almost like swimming in a cloudy swimming pool.''
</P>
<P>
   The triathletes will swim 1,500 meters, roughly nine-tenths of a
mile. For first-time triathlon watchers, the tansition area at the
corner of O'Connor Road and Las Colinas Boulevard will provide an
engaging show.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll be absolutely amazed at how fast things happen in the
transition area,'' Bolton said. ``Transitions are free time. At
this level, every second is important.''
</P>
<P>
   The triathletes will emerge from Lake Carolyn and run to their
bike racks. They'll shed their goggles and swim cap as they're
putting on sunglasses and cycling helmet. Bolton swims in a
skin-tight jersey that he also wears during the 40-kilometer (24.8
miles) bike ride. Other triathletes stuff their jerseys into their
swimsuits and don them on the jog to the bike.
</P>
<P>
   There's no time to stop and slip on cycling shoes, so they are
already clipped into the bicycle's pedals. The triathletes begin
pedaling with their feet on top of the shoes and gradually slip
into them as they trek down the course.
</P>
<P>
   There is one tricky turn, where the cyclists are racing downhill
and have to negotiate a 90-degree turn from Mills Lane onto
MacArthur Boulevard. But the out-and-back stretch of MacArthur
should be fast _ ``It'll be screaming,'' Bolton predicted.
</P>
<P>
   On the final, running leg, the course sports three hills, the
most challenging of which is a straight up-and-down trek along
Goodson Drive that should serve two purposes. It will help separate
the field, and give the lead runners a sense of where they stand in
the pack.
</P>
<P>
   The 10K (6.2 miles) run will decide the race, and that's where
Bolton's strengths come in. At the University of Wyoming, he was an
All-American in cross country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm firing right now,'' said Bolton, who has been training for
the past month in Fort Worth. ``Everything is going perfect. In my
mind, I'm where I need to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Two places on the Olympic team are up for grabs for both the men
and women. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
