<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5945 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LEWIS-TRIAL0526-COX     05-25 1379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-TRIAL0526-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Key witness, conflicting testimony
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy and Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Limousine driver Duane Fassett, billed as the state's
star prosecution witness in the Buckhead stabbings case, sighed
audibly several times as he testified Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe that was the air going out of the prosecution's murder
case against NFL star Ray Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Fassett, a slight, haggard-looking man and clearly a reluctant
witness, failed to deliver several key pieces of testimony
prosecutors had expected against Lewis, 25, and co-defendants
Reginald Oakley, 31, and Joseph Sweeting, 34. The three men are
charged with stabbing to death Richard Lollar, 24, and Jacinth
Baker, 21, after a night of Super Bowl partying in Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   In previous statements to police, Fassett told investigators he
saw Lewis deliver a blow to the midsection of one of the victims
and that he heard Oakley come back to the limousine and say, ``I
stabbed mine,'' and Sweeting say, ``I stabbed mine, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County District Attorney Paul Howard played off the
expected drama of the limo driver's description of the punch Lewis
allegedly delivered to Lollar by displaying a swinging uppercut
during his opening statements to the jury Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But when questioned Thursday by Howard, Fassett described a
completely different action. Demonstrating what he saw, Fassett
cocked his fist back over his head _ then said, ``I didn't see him
throw the punch; I didn't see it land.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassett also said that when Lewis raised his hand, the Baltimore
Ravens linebacker was trying to break up the fight. ``Knock that
(expletive) off,'' Fassett recalled Lewis as saying. He said Lewis
repeatedly tried to get his friends back into the limo before
things got out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   At least twice, Howard asked Fassett about what Sweeting and
Oakley said when they were in the limo, driving away. Each time,
Fassett said he did not recall.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' lead defense attorney, Ed Garland, was clearly overjoyed
by Fassett's reluctance and cross-examined him for only two
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   He asked Fassett about three instances when Lewis told his
friends, ``Get back in the car.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What he was doing was to stop there from being a problem,''
prompted Garland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir,'' the witness responded quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray Lewis didn't do anything to cause, aid or encourage
anybody to stab anyone with a knife, did he?'' the attorney asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No sir, not that I could see. Not at all,'' responded Fassett.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all the questions I have,'' said Garland.
</P>
<P>
   The courtroom, packed for Fassett's long-anticipated testimony,
resounded with laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, during a break, Assistant District Attorney Clint
Rucker said to a reporter, ``He's wrestling with it; look at him.
He doesn't want to hurt his friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, at the end of the day, Howard dwelled on the positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it went well,'' the prosecutor said. ``He explained
what happened, what happened afterwards, the cover-up. He was
stronger than I thought he was going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard said he planned to try to get into the record the highly
incriminating statements Fassett allegedly overheard Oakley and
Sweeting make through the upcoming testimony of Atlanta Police
Detective Ken Allen, who headed the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Possible witnesses to come include limo passengers Jessica
Robertson, Keiva Wells and Rehana Grant; Atlanta police Lt. Mike
Smith, who took a statement from Lewis in which the 24-year-old pro
football player lied to investigators; cab driver Patrick Ozonu;
and crime lab technicians who will trace the victims' blood from
the crime scene to Lewis' hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   Fassett's testimony comes on the heels of witness Jeff Gwen's
backing away from a statement to police that he, too, saw Lewis
throw a punch at Lollar. Instead, Gwen testified that Lewis and
Lollar were ``tussling,'' grabbing at each other.
</P>
<P>
   Fassett and Gwen are the only two witnesses who told police they
saw Lewis throw a punch at either of the stabbing victims.
</P>
<P>
   Before Gwen finished testifying Thursday morning, Superior Court
Judge Alice D. Bonner scolded prosecutors for not notifying the
defense about Gwen's changed statement.
</P>
<P>
   Rucker contended there was no foul committed by prosecutors
because, he said, ``We did not hide it, conceal it, and we made the
witness available to the defense for interview.''
</P>
<P>
   The law requires that any evidence favorable to a defendant must
be turned over by prosecutors to the defense.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his testimony, Fassett looked almost ill. While he
was on the stand, his wife sat on a bench outside the courtroom and
wept. At the close of Fassett's testimony, the judge told him he
might be recalled. The former Army medic's body sagged; he buried
his face in his hands. Fassett then left the courtroom, sat down
next to his wife and sobbed. ``He was in a very rough, unenviable
position; he was just in agony because he loves Ray Lewis,'' said
David Irwin, Fassett's attorney. ``He was totally overtaken by
stress and nerves. He hadn't eaten and was running on only nicotine
and coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses' freezing up is not uncommon, said former Cobb County
District Attorney Tom Charron. ``Especially when you have a friend
of the defendant. You always brace for it,'' the former prosecutor
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Spix, an Atlanta defense attorney who is monitoring the
trial for WXIA, said Fassett's testimony hurt the prosecution
because Howard promised jurors the limo driver would tell about
Lewis' punch and about his co-defendants' admitting to stabbing the
victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say the death knell rang, but anyone watching
that knows there's trouble in River City,'' Spix volunteered. At
the same time, he added, Fassett did make a strong case against
Oakley and scored points against Sweeting.
</P>
<P>
   Howard also was able to elicit some testimony from Fassett that
appeared to be damaging to Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Fassett said that after the fracas he saw Lewis, Oakley and
Sweeting quickly walking back to the limousine from the
intersection where Lollar and Baker lay mortally wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Fassett said at some point he heard the All-Pro linebacker say
that ``his football career wasn't going to end because of this.''
Fassett also admitted Thursday in court he had first told police he
didn't know who had rented the limo.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why, Fassett responded, ``I was told to say nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who told you to say nothing?'' asked Howard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray,'' responded Fassett, sighing heavily and rubbing his
face.
</P>
<P>
   He said he opened up after police handcuffed him and took him in
for questioning. Fassett said he saw Oakley chase Baker and that he
was ``grabbing him by the back of his shirt and flipping him.''
Baker, he said, landed on his neck or head and then Oakley punched
him at least twice while he was on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Fassett said he saw Sweeting struggle with a man prosecutors say
was Lollar. Lewis was standing near Lollar at the time, he
testified.
</P>
<P>
   Seconds later, Fassett said, he saw Sweeting punching one of the
victims while he was lying in the street.
</P>
<P>
   John Bergendahl, who represents Sweeting, highlighted numerous
inconsistences in Fassett's prior statements to the police.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 31, Fassett told police that ``everyone'' got out of the
limo when the fight began. Thursday, he said only Lewis, Oakley and
Sweeting left the limo.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you said today only three people got out of the limo,
that was incorrect, wasn't it?'' Bergendahl asked.
</P>
<P>
   Fassett, as he did on several occasions, paused long and hard
before answering. ``I forgot,'' he finally replied.
</P>
<P>
   Bergendahl reminded Fassett that he initially told police he
thought Sweeting struck one of the victims over the head with a
champagne bottle, when in fact it is now unrefuted that it was
Baker who cracked Oakley over the head with a Moet bottle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were wrong about that, weren't you?'' Bergendahl asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things happened so fast that night,'' Fassett replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't know what was going on, did you?'' the lawyer
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Correct,'' Fassett replied, letting out another audible sigh.
</P>
