<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-REACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE CHEER HOUSE VOTE   ON FREE TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI _ ``Have a drink from America!'' Paul Shyu sang out
happily, toasting a visitor with a Pepsi in one hand and a Sprite
in the other.
</P>
<P>
   Like practically everyone here in China's commercial capital,
Shyu was celebrating the news Thursday that the US House had passed
the measure normalizing trade with China.
</P>
<P>
   Shyu, the food division manager of a gigantic Taiwanese-Chinese
warehouse store that imports more than 10 percent of its products
from the United States, has his own ideas about who got the better
end of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``China, of course,'' he said. ``They will get a reduction on
import tax into the US for Chinese goods. America's trade deficit
with China will definitely increase.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. But as Shyu quickly added, American producers and
farmers _ not to mention importers like himself, and his customers
_ will also benefit. ``More products will come to China from the US
at lower tariffs. That's why I'm very happy for our business,''
Shyu said.
</P>
<P>
   Strolling through his spic-and-span megastore that has
registered 250,000 members since it opened six months ago, Shyu
pointed to pallets stacked high with Lay's potato chips and
Carnation milk powder, to refrigerated trays of Washington State
apples, California grapes and Florida oranges.
</P>
<P>
   While many human rights activists and labor unions on Capitol
Hill denounced the congressional vote as a sell-out Thursday, here
in China, there was jubilation among Chinese and American investors
and consumers. From supermarket checkout counters to factory
assembly lines to the cubicles of Internet startups, the refrain
was the same: freer trade will benefit both sides. What's more,
insisted many in the American business community, freer trade will
open China to influences from the outside world, making it
impossible for the leadership in Beijing to suppress the
aspirations of a rapidly changing nation.
</P>
<P>
   With its hard-won battle in the House of Representatives
complete, the measure now goes before the US Senate, where it is
expected to pass. China also appears poised to enter the World
Trade Organization, the global body that sets trade rules. If
Congress had refused to normalize trade relations with China, China
could have deprived US businesses of the privileges it will offer
the rest of the world through WTO.
</P>
<P>
   American business leaders expressed relief Thursday that the
measure passed, and insisted that US jobs will never be lost en
masse to China. In the case of perishable foods or automotives, for
example, shipping US goods made in China to America is either too
time-consuming or too costly, so there will always be a need for US
factories, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no plans to build cars here and ship them to
America,'' declared Philip Murtaugh, executive vice president of
Shanghai General Motors, the largest joint-venture in China. But
``in today's global economy, it's absolutely unrealistic to believe
that goods can be produced only in the USA and be shipped
everywhere else.'' Buicks made here, for example, have been
modified in more than 600 ways to suit the Chinese consumer and
China's road conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Presiding over a spotless, state-of-the-art automotive plant,
Murtaugh argued that free trade is a win-win proposition, nothing
more than common sense and self-interest for all concerned. Last
year, his plant churned out 20,000 Buick sedans and vans for the
Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to sell US goods in China, China's economy has to
grow, and the only way to do that is to create jobs in China. You
can't create consumers if you don't create jobs,'' Murtaugh said.
His blue-uniformed, goggle-wearing line workers are paid $2.20
hourly plus a comparable amount in benefits _ far above the wage at
Chinese state-owned auto factories, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shanghai GM has also created jobs for Americans, he asserted. In
the last five years, GM imported $1.6 billion of American
components and equipment to build the factory and produce its
vehicles _ parts and machines that would have come from Germany or
Japan if Daimler-Benz or Toyota were here instead.
</P>
<P>
   The WTO deal will lower the average tariffs on components
imported to China from 45 percent to 10 percent within six years,
and Murtaugh expects to import $250 million annually in American
components within a few years.
</P>
<P>
   With its bare concrete floors, rusting machines with green
patinas and the smell of wet grain in the air, the factory floor at
Shanghai Oils and Fats Factory No. 1, a 66-year-old state-owned
soybean processing plant, couldn't be more different from Shanghai
GM's facility. But with 80 percent of the soybeans it uses to make
cooking oil and animal feed imported from the United States, the
celebratory mood here Thursday over normalized trade relations was
the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they hadn't passed PNTR, it's possible China would have set
quotas on the import of US soybeans,'' said Liu Huihui, acting
director of the factory, using the acronym for permanent normal
trade relations. ``My workers were worried that if it didn't pass
and we couldn't get soybeans from the US, they would lose their
jobs,'' he said. ``So everyone is very happy today.''
</P>
<P>
   Liu's plant imports $15 million in soybeans a year, and he is
looking forward to lower tariffs. He said he has heard of the
debate in the US congress, and says Americans shouldn't be so
worried about their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``More US products will come to China now, and we are such a big
market of 1.3 billion people, so don't worry!'' he said ``US
investment will also bring American people to China, and those are
job opportunities, too. I suppose that with more Chinese factories
wanting to import soybeans now, the price will go up, so that's
good news for US farmers.''
</P>
<P>
   Another winner from the deal is Shanghai Hormel Foods, which
makes American-style hot-dogs, sausages and bacon _ as well as
offerings for Chinese taste buds, such as sausage with rice wine
and pig tongue.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Robert Wahlert hailed the decrease in duties on
the meat he imports from the United States, and insisted that
Hormel will keep its plants in the United States for the American
market, at the same time that it creates a consumer base with
plants in China.
</P>
<P>
   As for the debate over whether to do business with China's
repressive leadership, Wahlert believes trade can only help China's
political situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some things about human rights, religious expression
and political freedoms that aren't to my liking here,'' admitted
Wahlert, a Babson College graduate. ``But one doesn't change that
by ignoring or embargoing it _ it certainly hasn't worked with
(Cuban leader Fidel) Castro. Access to Western products, Western
ideas, and Western media can only help China decide and change for
itself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
