<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5955 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-LEONE-JOURNALIST-BOS &LR;      05-25 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEONE-JOURNALIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUEST FOR ADVENTURE MOTIVATED SLAIN REPORTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The year was 1989. The go-go Massachusetts economy Kurt
Schork had used to finance his taste for driving fast cars,
courting beautiful women, and pursuing social justice was going
sour.
</P>
<P>
   Schork, who was living in Pelham, Mass., near the University of
Massachusetts, volunteered to help with the annual fund-raising
drive of the area's public radio station, WFCR.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not like him to volunteer for that sort of thing,''
said Joseph Henefield, a close friend of the brilliant development
executive since undergraduate days on the North Dakota prairie. ``I
asked him why.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said this was going to be his year of living Asiatically,''
Henefield said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Schork, who had made a career first as a public planner in
Lowell, Mass., and at the State House, then as a private developer,
wanted to meet Deborah Wang, a talented young reporter with WFCR.
</P>
<P>
   Within two years, he had moved with Wang to Hong Kong, where he
launched the search _ for truth, for thrills, for the edge. The
pursuit took him to the front ranks of the world's foreign
correspondents, to the front lines of the world's most brutal
conflicts, and, on Wednesday, to his death, in an ambush in Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
   The 53-year-old correspondent for Reuters was a daredevil, said
friends who mourned him Thursday, but also a Rhodes Scholar who
instinctively sided with underdogs, and a journalist unsurpassed
for energy and open-mindedness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kurt was one of the biggest idealists you could meet,'' said
Frank Keefe, who met Schork at the University of Oxford in the
autumn of 1969, when both were Rhodes Scholars.
</P>
<P>
   Schork finished high school in Rockville, Md., and went to
Jamestown College in North Dakota on a football scholarship. He
made the All-American team for schools in Jamestown's division,
Henefield said, but revulsion at the Vietnam War changed him ``from
being a typical jock to finding pleasure in his intellect. Kurt,
like many of us, began to question what we knew, what we were
taught, what we were seeing'' because of the war.
</P>
<P>
   Schork came to Massachusetts from Oxford because his first wife
was going to law school at Boston University. He spent a miserable
year as a writer at the Mitre Corporation, a major defense
contractor, then got a planning job in Lowell with help from Keefe.
When the new governor, Michael S. Dukakis, made Keefe state
planning director, Keefe made Schork his assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Schork worked on Bill Bradley's first campaign for US Senate, in
1978. But when Dukakis was ousted from the governor's chair in that
same year, Schork's career as a public official ended. For the next
10 years, he made money as a private developer and spent it freely,
on fast motorcycles and faster cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a very nice Porsche, and on the highways he was
infuriatingly legal,'' Henefield said, but he would go out on
unused runways at Westover Air Force Base and do 150 miles per
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Once Schork moved to Hong Kong, his transformation was swift.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day, I got a picture in the mail of some mujahideen with
Kalashnikovs, in tribal robes, with head wraps and beards,''
Henefield said. ``I had to stare at it a while before I realized
one of them was Kurt.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schork ``really was not just a thrill-seeker,'' said
Christopher Lydon, who served with him on the board of the
now-defunct Boston Observer, and worked with Deborah Wang at WGBH.
``He wanted to know the world, take chances, and come out of it a
thoughtful, wise, good person.''
</P>
<P>
   Keefe said Thursday that the nature of Schork's death was no
surprise, and that the correspondent would not have lived his life
any other way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
