   (NYT35) NEW YORK -- May 25, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 28 --
INVEST-DEAN&AMP;DELUCA -- As of Friday, Dean &AMP; Deluca - which hasn't
turned a profit in seven years - had not set a price for its
initial public offering (expected in five to six weeks), nor had it
announced how many shares it would make available. But the company
hopes to raise about $69 million to finance a major expansion. A
customer checked the fruit at a Dean &AMP; Deluca in Soho. (Andrea
Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) LAGOS, Nigeria -- May 25, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 28
-- NIGERIA-HOPE-COX-4 -- Chuba Egolum's time in the United States,
including three years obtaining an MBA in Atlanta, taught him to
appreciate basic things longed for in a place like Nigeria, where
his company drills wells and builds water distribution systems.
Just to stay in business, Egolum must cope with daily annoyances
most Americans would confront only during a natural catastrophe.
``When I pick up the phone, most often it is dead,'' he says.
``This is what it is to do business in Nigeria.'' (Seamus
Conlan/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) ABUJA, Nigeria -- May 25, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 28
-- NIGERIA-HOPE-COX-3 -- Farouk M. Lawan, the chairman of Nigeria's
House ethics committee, is drafting the country's first
comprehensive ethics legislation, intended to stem the tide of
corruption in a region often considered one of the most corrupt on
earth. ``If there is one single thing that has retarded the
economic development of Nigeria, it is the issue of corruption,''
said Lawan. (Seamus Conlan/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) LAGOS, Nigeria -- May 25, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 28
-- NIGERIA-HOPE-COX-2 -- Twenty years ago, Nigeria was poised to
assume the role of an African superpower. Today it is a shambles.
For 17 years this vast country, which is about the size of Texas,
Georgia and Florida combined, was ravaged by military juntas that
wrecked the economy, impoverished the people and depleted the
national treasury. Signs of neglect are everywhere. Nigerian
fishermen work a river in Lagos near an old dilapidated section of
houses. (Seamus Conlan/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) LAGOS, Nigeria -- May 25, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 28
-- NIGERIA-HOPE-COX-1 -- Nigeria, a member of OPEC, has received
about $280 billion in petroleum revenues since the early 1970s -
only to be squandered or stolen by successive corrupt regimes. The
heavily guarded offices of Chevron Oil dwarfed the market on a
street in Lagos. (Seamus Conlan/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- May 25, 2000 -- CREDITCARD-ANTITRUST -- The
credit card business is viciously competitive. Philip J. Purcell,
Morgan Stanley's chairman, told a Senate panel in February that
Discover Card was being hurt by anticompetitive practices. (Ruby
Washington/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
