were in their day very popular artists. They had little else in
common until the conjunction of their current shows at the Brooklyn
Museum of Art: a critical survey of work by Parrish, and a group of
outdoor scenes painted in Manhattan and Brooklyn by Chase. The
works include Parrish's ``School Days (Alphabet),'' left; and
Chase's ``Afternoon in the Park.'' (Brooklyn Museum of Art/The New
York Times)
