</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-TAKEOVERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE'S TAITTINGER BECOMES AN AMERICAN RAIDER'S QUARRY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ As Europe's economies and bloated companies streamline,
the Continent has become the latest playground for American
leveraged-buyout specialists.
</P>
<P>
   The cutthroat tactics of the 1980s, with vulture investors
searching the landscape for takeover prey, have fallen somewhat out
of fashion in the United States. This phenomenon, it turns out, did
not die, but migrated across the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   In the thick of this trend is one of the brashest and most
feared of the old-style raiders, Asher B. Edelman, who is trying to
outwit a venerable French family institution, Taittinger, the
Champagne maker, luxury-goods producer and top-of-the-line hotel
company.
</P>
<P>
   But while corporate raiders used to slash and burn in relatively
brief battles, Edelman is conducting a prolonged siege, having
stalked the Taittinger family since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   At one level, the battle has evolved into a clash of personal
and corporate styles. Taittinger is represented by its chairman,
Claude Taittinger, 72, and his niece Anne-Claire Taittinger, chief
executive of the Societe du Louvre, the company that is the main
Taittinger asset. They have been scrambling to transform Louvre
from a French heirloom into a leaner, American-style corporation,
and they refuse to deal with Edelman.
</P>
<P>
   But they face a formidable foe with potent allies, including the
New York investor Guy Wyser-Pratte. Through a combination of legal
savvy and sharp financial elbows, Edelman has been transferring the
skills he honed in the United States to pursue Louvre. And
Wyser-Pratte has successfully laid siege to another French
institution, Groupe Andre, which owns a Champs-Elysees shoe shop,
Chaussures Andre, and the Kookai fashion chain.
</P>
<P>
   For Edelman, giving up seems the furthest thing from his mind.
``There's every reason to stay in, and to continue to push for
change,'' he said by phone from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the clash of French provincial style and American
bluntness, larger stakes are in play. As the Andre case showed, old
French family companies are under pressure to perform or be taken
over. Moreover, the way companies protect themselves is a hot topic
of corporate and political debate. Several French companies, like
the conglomerate Vivendi and the bank Societe Generale, have
recently limited stockholder voting rights, sending minority
shareholder groups to the barricades.
</P>
<P>
   Luxury products are hot now, and the Taittinger properties of
Societe du Louvre, like the Hotel de Crillon in Paris and the
Baccarat crystal works, are thriving. Edelman thinks that breaking
Louvre into separate companies could vastly enhance its value. But
the Taittingers say that a loss of family control would weaken the
company's image.
</P>
<P>
   Early this month, in a Paris court, Edelman contested the
Taittinger family voting rights in Societe du Louvre. A decision is
expected early in June. But even if the court rules against him,
Edelman says he will not give up.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle can be wearing, as each side tries to push on as
though the other does not matter. The history of the battle goes
like this:
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Edelman began buying shares in Taittinger SA, the
holding company that owns the Champagne maker and more than half
the voting rights in Societe du Louvre. He also went after Louvre
itself, bringing his holdings and those of his allies to about 25
percent. At a stockholders meeting in 1998, Edelman's group
presented a list of 52 questions about the company's inner
workings, including delicate matters like whether family members
used company apartments rent-free or held fictitious jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Such methods, tastelessly aggressive by Taittinger standards,
are part of Edelman's corporate arsenal. In the '80s, he was feared
for his assault on companies like Datapoint, a computer concern he
took over after a long and bitter battle. By the early '90s,
Edelman, an avid art collector, retired to Switzerland and opened a
gallery. His reputation had become one of lavish living more than
financial acumen. In 1996, his sale of a Jasper Johns painting for
$3 million drew attention, as had his sale two years earlier, for
$5.8 million, of a 23-room Manhattan apartment overlooking the East
River.
</P>
<P>
   But by the mid-'90s, he was back at work, running Edelman Value
Partners from New York, investing mainly in undervalued French and
Swiss stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the sniping, his continuing struggle has had its playful
moments. When Claude Taittinger said in an interview that if the
Taittingers wanted to paint the Crillon pink, ``we can, and Edelman
can't,'' Edelman responded by having a can of pink paint delivered
to Taittinger's home.
</P>
<P>
   In this spirited give-and-take, Edelman has been clear about his
motives. He says there is great value to be unlocked in Louvre. He
wants to shed nonluxury businesses and focus on the Concorde hotel
chain and its flagship, the Crillon, where stars and statesmen
congregate; the midpriced Envergure hotel chain, and a luxury-goods
division centered on a revived Baccarat.
</P>
<P>
   Edelman makes no secret of wanting to ride the wave of demand
for luxury. France remains Europe's, and the world's No. 1 tourist
destination, and Societe du Louvre's chief luxury hotels, which
also include the Hotel de Louvre in Paris and the Martinez in
Cannes, are hot properties. Baccarat he sees as a glass company
around which to build a luxury-goods group in the style of Louis
Vuitton or Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first bought in, we thought we would enter into a
basic cooperation agreement,'' he said. ``We now see it
differently. Whether through a takeover or a proxy fight, in either
event we have a plan for three different public companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyser-Pratte agrees. Societe du Louvre, he said in a telephone
interview, is ``highly, highly undervalued,'' adding, ``The value
of the assets is two, two and a half times the value of the
shares.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Taittinger wants no part of a breakup. ``We have a very
great sense of security,'' she said in her black wood-paneled
office on the edge of Paris. As for Edelman's continued pressure,
she remarked: ``It's nothing new. There's no rational explanation
for it.''  &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   What she wants is to keep Louvre together, to keep focusing on
its main businesses. Over the next five years, she wants to double
the number of rooms in the Envergure hotels and to spread into
markets like Spain, Italy and Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Taittinger, a slight, engaging woman of 50, was educated in
sociology and urban studies, and says her passion was for urban
planning. Asked why she joined Louvre in 1979, she hesitated, but
an associate who knows her well said, ``Duty.'' In 1997, after
running several divisions, including a line of perfumes and
Baccarat, she succeeded her father, Jean, then 70, as chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``A family company must be run like a company,'' she said,
adding that family-owned companies have it harder in France, where
envy of wealth is a national sport, than in Germany or Italy.
</P>
<P>
   But the Taittingers are not just any family. Nine Taittingers
are listed in ``Who's Who in France.'' Taittinger's father was
mayor of Reims and French minister of justice in the 1970s. Her
uncle, Pierre-Christian, was a senator; her brother, Jean-Frantz,
is a member of Parliament. Yet business has always been the
family's inclination. Ms. Taittinger's son recently dropped out of
college to join a dot-com company.
</P>
<P>
   By shedding nonessential businesses like ELM Leblanc, a heating
concern, and a controlling share in the private Banque du Louvre,
and then sprucing up the perfume and glassware businesses through
increased marketing and more closely controlled distribution, Ms.
Taittinger raised revenue by 10 percent a year, to 677 million
euros in 1999, now $617 million. Net profit has risen 52 percent
since she took over. Now, Baccarat plans four new stores in the
United States, including locations in Los Angeles and Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the changes, she acknowledges, came partly in response
to Edelman's pressure. ``I have to thank him for the opportunity,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wyser-Pratte accuses her of arrogance. ``It's the Marie
Antoinette story,'' he said. ``Let them eat cake.''
</P>
<P>
   Edelman, for his part, says the improvements are not enough.
Claude Taittinger, he said, now brags that Louvre is ``run in the
Anglo-Saxon fashion.'' But he added, ``They've been put in a
position where they have to run it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the changes, he said, the hotel chains and
luxury-goods businesses have yet to fully exploit the Internet. The
company should sell costly hotel buildings, like the Crillon, he
says, and concentrate on hotel management. To bolster his
arguments, he commissioned a study by Jones Lang LaSalle, the real
estate firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company is basically un-run,'' he concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Taittinger says she does not need the advice. What separates
the family from Edelman, she says, is a question of credibility.
``And then,'' she adds, ``there is Datapoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Datapoint stands out as perhaps the muddiest chapter in
Edelman's career as a turnaround artist. Under Edelman, Datapoint,
once a leading-edge producer of computer networking equipment,
collapsed, crushed by losses and a series of irregularities. In
1996, when Edelman was still registered as holding 20 percent of
its voting shares, Datapoint settled a lawsuit over a fraudulent
Texas land sale after a jury had ordered Datapoint to pay $63
million in penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Five years earlier, Edelman agreed to pay almost $437,000 in a
settlement with the Securities and Exchange Commission, which had
accused him of delaying the disclosure of Datapoint stock
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   But the past does not interest Edelman. ``If I were to go
away,'' he said of Societe du Louvre, ``they would go back to the
way they used to run it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
