<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS SAY BUSH ISN'T A KEEPER 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Gov. George W. Bush may be a fun date, but
he's not the kind of guy you want to settle down with. So says the
chairwoman of the Texas Democratic Party, Molly Beth Malcolm, one
of more than 70 Democratic officials from 34 states who met here
Thursday with Vice President Al Gore and his senior campaign staff.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore has been lagging in the public opinion polls
behind Bush, the meeting Thursday was not an emergency session but
a long-planned chance for the campaign to coordinate with its state
emissaries. Many left the impression that they were not worried
about an election more than five months away, although they were
trying to prepare for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the basic tenets of politics,'' said Paul Berendt,
Democratic chairman in Washington state, ``is that you don't fight
the battle in May that you need to fight in October.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless the state officials said they thought it would be
useful for the Democratic National Committee to begin its $30
million advertising campaign for the vice president soon.
</P>
<P>
   The officials also said they recognized that voters seemed to
like Bush's personality more than Gore's, but they suggested that
the more voters saw of Bush, the less they would like him.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm put it most graphically: ``He's the guy you want to go
to the ballgame with, he's the guy you want to come to your party
because he's going to be lots of fun. But it reminds me of when I
was in college. There were lots of guys who were lots of fun to go
out with, and you wanted them at your party, but when it came time
to settle down, he wasn't the one you're looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, at a low-key fund-raising reception Thursday night, Gore
mentioned his vanquished Democratic primary foe, former Sen. Bill
Bradley, with some graciousness, a hint that the icy relationship
between the two might be beginning to thaw.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 2216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5966 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MEAT-INSPECTION-NYT &LR;      05-25 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEAT-INSPECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE REJECTS FEDERAL SALMONELLA TESTS IN TEXAS MEAT PLANTS
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Texas) By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge in Texas on Thursday struck down the Agriculture
Department's inspection standards for meat-processing plants,
saying they do not fairly measure sanitary conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The standards, and the laboratory tests used to enforce them,
were the foundation of the 4-year-old government effort to limit
meat and poultry contamination by salmonella.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, A. Joe Fish of federal District Court in Dallas, said
the tests measure the quality of the meat brought into a plant, but
not necessarily the conditions of the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Fish ruled Thursday that federal law did not give the government
the authority to close a meat processing plant based on the
bacterial tests.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said the agency would take
``whatever legal steps are necessary'' to overturn the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling applies only to ground beef processing plants in the
northern district of Texas. But beef from those plants is shipped
all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture Department plans to continue to enforce the
standards in processing plants and slaughtering plants elsewhere in
the country and will continue to test for salmonella in
slaughtering plants in the northern district of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups say that if the ruling were upheld it could
force the Agriculture Department to return to the poke-and-sniff
system, in which inspectors smelled for contamination, that had
been in effect since the beginning of the century.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision leaves the shell but cuts out the heart of
USDA's efforts to prevent food poisoning,'' said Caroline Smith
DeWaal, food safety director of the Center for Science in the
Public Interest, a consumer advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   But Steven F. Spiritas, president and chief executive officer of
Supreme Beef, said the company was pleased with the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision confirms what we have said from the very
beginning, that USDA's use of the salmonella test to determine the
sanitary condition of the processor plant is flawed and outside the
scope of USDA's authority.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In December, Fish had ruled that the U.S. Department of
Agriculture could not shut down the plant of the company that had
brought the lawsuit, Supreme Beef Processing. The government had
removed its inspectors, which are legally required for a plant to
operate. The closing of the plant in Dallas, which had failed three
salmonella tests, was the first under the new regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few weeks later the plant was forced to recall 180,000
pounds of ground beef because one sample of the beef tested
positive for the deadly bacteria E. coli O157:H7.
</P>
<P>
   In his decision Judge Fish said, ``Because the USDA performance
standards and salmonella tests do not necessarily evaluate the
conditions of a meat processor's establishment they cannot serve as
a basis for finding a plant's meat adulterated.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Indeed a plant could, in theory, be completely
sanitized from top to bottom but if the meat in it tests positive
for salmonella, the USDA could withdraw its inspectors, effectively
closing a plant that is sanitary.''
</P>
<P>
   Ninety percent of the large beef processing plants in the
country and 84 percent of the small ones have systems in place that
keep salmonella-tainted beef out of their plants, and they are in
compliance with the Agriculture Department's salmonella standards.
Two other plants have failed inspections three times, but have
agreed to make changes to come into compliance.
</P>
<P>
   Since the department's regulations requiring salmonella testing
went into effect, studies show salmonella contamination of ground
beef products has dropped by as much as 50 percent. And according
to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, food poisoning
dropped in 1999 for the first time in many years. The disease
control agency said the new inspection system deserved part of the
credit for this improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Salmonella can be deadly for young children, the elderly and
those with weakened immune systems. Last year about 600 deaths and
1.4 million illnesses were attributed to salmonellosis.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Tucker Foreman of the Consumer Federation of America
called on the Agriculture Department to stop purchasing ground beef
for federal programs, especially those serving children, like the
school lunch program. Last December the department canceled its
contract with Supreme Beef for hamburgers for the school lunch
program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
