<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5968 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-BOOK-ART-$ADV28-2     05-25 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOK-ART-$ADV28-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL MANAGERS RELATE TO THIS GRIPPING TALE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 28)  
(Editors: Publication notes appear at end of article.
BIZ-BOOK-PERKINS, a 500-word sidebar, contains Perkins' 10 rules of
leadership.) (ART ADV: Photo NYT29 has been sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FRED ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A decade or so ago, Dennis N.T. Perkins, president of the
Syncretics Group in Branford, Conn., brought us ``the moose on the
table,'' the disarming metaphor that companies use to mention the
unmentionable. He devised that impish but effective image as a way
of coaxing business people into talking openly about the sensitive
issues that hang heavy over a discussion but that no one dares
mention.
</P>
<P>
   Now Perkins, a management consultant whose clients include
American Express, Bose, Citibank and Marriott, is back with bigger
game in mind. He is a connoisseur of leadership in circumstances of
great peril. His new book, ``Leading at the Edge: Leadership
Lessons from the Extraordinary Saga of Shackleton's Antarctic
Expedition,'' offers lessons in leadership ``at the outer limits of
human endurance _ the place I call The Edge.''
</P>
<P>
   This thoughtful work has the feel of a lifelong obsession. An
Annapolis graduate, Perkins woke up to genuine leadership in
Vietnam, a brutal and unforgettable academy. At one point he found
himself in command of a Marine convoy running a bloody gantlet
along Route 1 from Chu Lai to Da Nang. Caught in a withering
ambush, shaken and confused, he urged his column forward,
concluding that the risk of crossing an open field of fire was
better than sitting tight in the bull's-eye of the killing zone.
(``A man sits as many risks as he runs,'' Perkins quotes Henry
David Thoreau.)
</P>
<P>
   Perkins builds his corporate leadership text around the
astonishing story of the British Imperial Trans-Antarctic
Expedition, led by Sir Ernest Shackleton. In December 1914,
Shackleton and 27 others sailed from South Georgia, an island in
the Southern Ocean, bent on becoming the first to cross Antarctica
on foot, a trek expected to take three months.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Shackleton and his troop endured more than 600 wretched
days of endless cold, near-starvation, scanty shelter, misery and
despair before they struggled back to South Georgia. Their ship
became icebound and was eventually crushed.
</P>
<P>
   For months, the party clung to an ice floe, but as the floe
melted, the desperate men took to the frigid sea in open boats.
They found a toehold on a small island, but that proved untenable,
so Shackleton and five others struck out in a life boat for help
some 800 miles away across the world's most storm-swept seas.
Barely surviving that ordeal, they then clawed their way across New
Georgia's icy mountain ranges to safety.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins offers us Ernest Shackleton as the model leader, a
captain obsessed with the welfare of his men. Cautious or daring as
circumstances required, Shackleton was a rock. An inventive and
insistent cheerleader, he refused to let the enfeebled company give
up. He insisted on maintaining equity and mutual respect, and he
saved the most onerous tasks for himself. Incredibly, not a man
died.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good, but what does all this have to do with meeting
a payroll?
</P>
<P>
   Perkins has distilled 10 principles from these survival
experiences, and he offers them as a guide for business leadership
at the edge (though it's never entirely clear what, in business,
``the edge'' means). The 10 principles, the backbone of the book,
are expounded in the Shackleton saga. Taken out of that adventurous
context, they seem mostly unexceptionable, if not routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never lose sight of the ultimate goal, and focus energy on
short-term objectives.'' ``Set a personal example with visible,
memorable symbols and behaviors.'' ``Minimize status differences.''
``Find something to celebrate and something to laugh about.''
``Reinforce the team message constantly: `We are one _ we live or
die together.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Leading at the Edge'' reads like two different accounts _ a
gripping adventure story and an orthodox management manual _ that
never really marry. To stitch the two together, each chapter on the
Shackleton expedition concludes with questions and some ``lessons
for leaders.'' The lessons tend to be shopworn episodes from
management lore, like Andy Grove's pivotal decision to get Intel
out of memory chips or James Burke's famous response to the Tylenol
tampering scare or Scott McNealy's resourcefulness at Sun
Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins does include four business cases where he applies his
principles in detail. Abstract and dry, lacking pertinent detail,
the case studies cannot measure up to the survival saga. They tend
to depict executives who obtained outstanding results by greatly
improving communications with the rank and file.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Creighton revived Weyerhauser from mediocrity. Pat Russo
led a turnaround at AT&AMP; T's Global Business Communications Systems.
These executives' efforts, as impressive as they were, pale in
comparison to Shackleton's: Russo gave subordinates her home
telephone number. Shackleton led a terrifying sail across polar
seas.
</P>
<P>
   The only case that comes to life involved loyalty and devotion.
It is the tale of Aaron Feuerstein's rebuilding of Malden Mills
after its disastrous fire in December 1995. At 70, his life work
consumed in flames, Feuerstein could have pocketed the insurance
proceeds and retired. Instead, he vowed to rebuild his mill and
save his employees' livelihoods. Struggling against enormous odds,
Feuerstein and his loyal workers managed to get Malden's Polartek
lines back in production within months.
</P>
<P>
   Why do the two halves seem so out of kilter? In truth, precious
few business decisions are made ``at the edge,'' with life or limb
in peril. Perkins argues that ``the edge'' of endurance can be
subjective. ``I've seen people more upset about missing deadlines
or giving presentations than Marines under automatic-weapon and
mortar fire.'' But we all know that business teams do not ``live or
die together.'' It is romantic (or foolish) to frame the stakes
that way.
</P>
<P>
   When a business fails, it is dismantled or reorganized; people
lose jobs but most find other ones. Failure is a cleansing of the
economy. If a chief executive falls short, typically he or she is
given a comfortable departure, and a new aspirant comes in to
tackle the job. Business problems are serious but not lethal.
</P>
<P>
   One wonders how the valiant Shackleton would fare in today's
business world. In his circumstance, the ultimate goal _ survival _
was indisputable. In today's bewildering environment, reaching
agreement on fundamental goals may be half the battle. Though
Shackleton's people might grumble or bicker, they were hardly free
to listen to a headhunter and depart for a more promising
enterprise. (MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
