<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0354 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5970 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-BOOK-$ADV28-2NDTA     05-25 0270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOK-$ADV28-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
Undated: promising enterprise.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shackleton is the leader as father figure, a heroic provider who
shouldered the weight and made the decisions. He had loyal
lieutenants but not equals. He listened to others but chose the
path himself. Today's business leader is less a hero than a first
among equals, an enabler who inspires commitment and exists to
bring out the best in his or her people. The talent is unwilling to
rely so heavily on someone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leading at the Edge'' has a wistful air. The lessons are
shaped for warriors and adventurers but directed at managers, who
are neither. At some level Perkins is looking for the ideal company
commander.
</P>
<P>
   Only in the recounting of miraculous survival does the writing
come alive _ not only the tale of the Shackleton expedition, but
also of Steven Callahan, who, with indomitable ingenuity, survived
76 days in a five-foot rubber raft in the Atlantic, warding off
sharks and spearing fish for food. Or the Navy patrol plane that
crashed in the North Pacific, consigning the crew to two small life
rafts. (Five of 15 died, but the survivors buoyed their spirits by
chanting, ``Toga, toga, toga,'' after John Belushi in ``Animal
House.'') Or the Texan who, bitten by a coral snake, bit off the
snake's head and used the snake's skin for a tourniquet.
</P>
<P>
   Put that one in the office manual.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LEADING AT THE EDGE'
</P>
<P>
   Leadership Lessons from the Extraordinary Saga of Shackleton's
Antarctic Expedition.
</P>
<P>
   By Dennis N.T. Perkins (with Margaret P. Holtman, Paul R.
Kessler, Catherine McCarthy)
</P>
</TEXT>
