<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5972 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-BOOK-PERKINS-$ADV     05-25 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOK-PERKINS-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
10 RULES FOR LEADING ON THE EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 28)  (Sidebar with BIZ-BOOK) 
(Editors: Italics suggested for the rules.) 
 By FRED ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From analyzing how Ernest Shackleton saved all the members of
his marooned expedition to Antarctica, Dennis N.T. Perkins, author
of ``Leading at the Edge,'' has distilled 10 rules of leadership:
</P>
<P>
   1. Never lose sight of the ultimate goal, and focus energy on
short-term objectives.
</P>
<P>
   His expedition goals dashed, Shackleton embraced the new goal of
bringing every man out alive, and he pursued that objective in
every waking hour, as Perkins demonstrates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. Set a personal example with visible, memorable symbols and
behaviors.
</P>
<P>
   Crossing the frigid seas, Shackleton stood in the bow, exposed
to the elements. When it became necessary to travel light, he
conspicuously discarded his gold watch, gold lighter and gold
coins.
</P>
<P>
   3. Instill optimism and self-confidence, but stay grounded in
reality.
</P>
<P>
   Shackleton drew the best from his crew, mainly by keeping them
busy. He kept up a cheerful demeanor even while sharing dire news.
</P>
<P>
   4. Take care of yourself: Maintain your stamina and let go of
guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Take care of himself, Shackleton did not. His every thought was
for his crew. Shackleton made mistakes, but never dwelled on them.
</P>
<P>
   5. Reinforce the team message constantly: ``We are one _ we live
or die together.''
</P>
<P>
   In everything he did, Shackleton required sharing and mutual
reliance.
</P>
<P>
   6. Minimize status differences and insist on mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
   Shackleton insisted that officers and crew bear the ordeal
equally. He took his turn at kitchen chores and refused to accept
larger food rations.
</P>
<P>
   7. Master conflict _ deal with anger in small doses, engage
dissidents, and avoid needless power struggles.
</P>
<P>
   Shackleton demoted a bully and stared down a would-be mutineer,
but accepted grousing as an essential outlet. He took personal
charge of the most difficult crew members.
</P>
<P>
   8. Find something to celebrate and something to laugh about.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, Shackleton roused the enfeebled men to celebrate
June 22, 1916, Midwinter's Day of their second grueling Antarctic
winter. They mustered a musical and poetry revue in 26 acts.
</P>
<P>
   9. Be willing to take the Big Risk.
</P>
<P>
   On Elephant Island, Shackleton concluded that starvation was
near. So he led a crew of five in an unprecedented open-boat sail
across the globe's most tempestuous waters.
</P>
<P>
   10. Never give up _ there's always another move.
</P>
<P>
   When their ship was crushed, they sought to drag their lifeboats
hundreds of miles to open water. When that proved impossible, they
camped for months on an ice floe. As the floe melted, they set out
in boats for distant land. Stymied there, Shackleton sailed for
South Georgia. It then took four forays to find and rescue the men
left behind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 2219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5973 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-TOUR-BUSES-NYT &LR;      05-25 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TOUR-BUSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLE TOURS GETS REPRIEVE AS CITY TRIES TO SHUT IT DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Armed with what it called new evidence of illegal
activity, the city's Consumer Protection Agency argued Thursday for
the immediate revocation of the licenses of New York Apple Tours,
the bus company accused of repeatedly violating city, state and
federal laws.
</P>
<P>
   But Judith Gould, administrative law judge, declined to rule on
the matter, postponing the hearing until Friday. She said the
company had not been given an adequate chance to review the
allegations and was faced with documents and evidence so new that
some of it had not been seen until the hearing was under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see that the licensee has had an opportunity to put on
a defense here,'' Gould said.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing opened with testimony from Renee Stanley, 47, who
said she saw one of the company's double-decker buses strike and
kill a 71-year-old pedestrian on Monday, the accident that led to
the city's emergency motion to close the company.
</P>
<P>
   It ended with testimony from Thomas Fullington, an assistant
director of the State Department of Motor Vehicles, who described
scores of possible violations of state bus driver standards that
his office found when it began investigating the company's driver
files on Wednesday. Fullington said the files did not include
current driving records and medical examination results for many
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, the hearing began 45 minutes after an Apple bus
with tourists on board rear-ended a U.S. Postal Service truck on
Fifth Avenue. No one was injured, but the police gave seven
summonses to the driver for such violations as a defective rear
taillight, no working horn, insufficient air pressure for the
brakes and other problems, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Paulsen, the lead lawyer for the tour company, objected
repeatedly to the details that were the foundation of the city's
case, saying their last-minute introduction was a violation of due
process. Paulsen said that a temporary closure would ``put this
company out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the chance, he said, the company ``will debunk much of
what has gone on here today.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayim Grant, president of the company, also said that the city's
case was overstated, and that his company was trying to accommodate
the demands of the authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing was attended by a dozen employees of the tour
company, who said they would lose their livelihoods if Gould ruled
in favor of the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
