<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-NCAA-CHAMPIONSHIPS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANFORD PLAYERS MEET FOR NCAA WOMEN'S TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ Introducing the NCAA Division I women's singles
champion ... (fill in the blank) ... from Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford's Marissa Irvin, a graduate of Harvard-Westlake High,
and Laura Granville each earned semifinal victories Thursday at
Pepperdine and will meet today at 1 p.m. for the championship. The
winner will give Stanford its 11th women's singles title and first
since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In the doubles semifinals, Pepperdine's Paola Palencia and Ipek
Senoglu lost to Cal's Amy Jensen and Claire Curran 6-3, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great day for the school,'' Stanford coach Frank
Brennan said. ``This is the first time in my 21 years here that we
have an all-Stanford final.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no coaching (in the final). My assistant and I
will sit back, watch them play and enjoy an iced tea.''
</P>
<P>
   Brennan only had to coach one of his players Thursday.
Granville, ranked No. 3 in the nation, blitzed Georgia's Aarthi
Venkatesan 6-0, 6-1, while top-ranked Irvin struggled to beat
UNLV's Katarina Malec 3-6, 6-1, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   Granville, a freshman, was broken to start the match but won the
next 12 games with a dominant serve and hard, accurate ground
strokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has ice water in her veins,'' Brennan said. ``She's
probably the best mental player I've ever seen in college tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Venkatesan raised her arms in mock celebration after winning a
point in the second set, but Granville, who Brennan referred to as
``The Assassin'' earlier this week, closed out the match with
little flair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really happy with the way I'm playing right now,''
Granville said. ``It feels good to take a lot of confidence out on
the court every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin didn't have a lot of confidence Thursday, particularly in
her serve, which was dreadful in the first set against Malek. Irvin
almost completely abandoned her first serve at one point in the
second set, but played a strong game from the baseline and regained
her composure in time to rout Malek in the final two sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a grueling week, and I haven't played anywhere near
my capability,'' Irvin said. ``I will need to play much better
(against Granville).''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin and Granville last met two years ago in a junior
tournament (Granville won in three sets) and both participants
expect a close match.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laura is playing real well right now,'' Irvin said, ``but if I
play the way I should, it shouldn't be a problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
