<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORRY: LAKERS NEED DO-OR-DIE ATTITUDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ A loss tonight at the Rose Garden won't end the
Lakers' season. But acting as if it would might not be a bad idea,
says Robert Horry.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers and Portland Trail Blazers are tied 1-1 in the
Western Conference finals, and a loss would leave the Lakers
trailing in a series for the first time in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to go in there like if we lose this game, it's
over,'' Horry said. ``We've just got to go out there and play hard.
Don't think about the next game, just go out there and say, `Hey,
this is the last game of the season, we've got to win one to
advance.' You've got to have that kind of mindset. I'm not saying
that if we don't win this game, it's the end of the series, but go
out there with that kind of mindset. Go out and play hard and lay
it all on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   So do his teammates share and understand that approach?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so,'' Horry said. ``Everybody's been kind of anxious
to get out there and get another game under our belt. The way we
had our last performance, everybody's eager to go out there and
play hard and get some things done.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, that wasn't always the case in practice the last
two days.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were supposed to be hard (workouts), but they weren't,''
Horry said. ``A lot of guys are banged up, so a lot of guys really
seemed like they were trying to hold themselves back and not go out
and stress themselves too much. But as long as you get the thought
process and get it mentally down, I think that's what we got. But
physically, we didn't really get it done in practice. It doesn't
worry me I'll tell you after tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the Lakers are uncommonly upbeat, having had three
days to forget the 106-77 embarrassment of Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson referred to the team's mood as ``very
buoyant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident,'' Shaquille O'Neal said. ``We're kind of
upset we didn't play as well of a game in Game 2 as we did in Game
1, but it happens. Nobody said it was going to be easy. And this is
a true test for us. We've been stepping up to tests all year, so
this is another one we have to step up to.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing new: Although the Lakers were thumped in Game 2, Jackson
said no major adjustments are necessary for Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just decisions,'' he said. ``I think people have
to make good decisions. When we go to help (on defense), we make
decent decisions. ... And I can understand that they got on their
heels defensively, and that's a bad sign. When you get on your
heels defensively, then you can't play for fear of fouls or
whatever. You can't be concerned about fouls in this game. If you
are, if you're concerned about what a referee's going to call, then
you put yourself in jeopardy and the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Old legs: Jackson said Glen Rice, hampered by a sore right knee
in Game 2, looks ``much better'' and he expressed no concern over
the lack of zip from 36-year-old Ron Harper, who played an
ineffective 15 minutes on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't like Harp's decisions,'' Jackson said. ``I
wasn't nursing him or anything else. I just didn't think he got
loose when he came out to play, and I didn't think he made good
decisions with the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Little-used rookie swingman Devean George sprained
his left ankle in practice Thursday and was sent to the hospital
for X-rays. His status was uncertain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
