<HEADLINE>
CRAYON LAB TESTS CONFLICTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW SCHNEIDER and CAROL SMITH  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Binney &AMP; Smith, makers of Crayola crayons, Thursday said an
independent laboratory had tested its crayons and found that they
do not contain asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   RJ Lee Group of Pittsburgh, an EPA-approved laboratory, said it
conducted three types of tests on two crayons and issued a report
to the company stating the crayons did not contain asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   The findings conflict with results obtained by two independent
government-certified labs who did tests at the request of the
Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   The labs used by the P-I have reconfirmed the existence of
carcinogenic tremolite and anthrophyllite fibers in repeated tests
of three brands of crayons -- Crayola, Prang and Rose Art. In
testing those brands, the labs found asbestos in 32 of 40 crayons
tested. Both RJ Lee Group and the labs used by the P-I used
multiple testing procedures, including polarized light microscopy
(PLM), transmission electron microscopy (TEM) and scanning electron
microscopy (SEM).
</P>
<P>
   Ken Bunting, the P-I's executive editor, said Thursday, ``The
P-I reported this story with balance, and great care. The tests
about which we reported were repeated numerous times. We have no
reason to doubt the findings of the government-certified
laboratories we commissioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have given all the results provided to us to the Consumer
Product Safety Commission,'' Bunting added, ``and we have
encouraged the labs to cooperate fully with the commission.''
</P>
<P>
   Other media organizations, school districts and government
agencies throughout the country said Thursday they are also testing
crayons for asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   KIRO, Channel 7, the CBS affiliate in Seattle, hired Orion
Environmental Laboratories test to crayons, chalk and other
products containing talc Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked through the microscope and I must admit I was
surprised to see fibers of tremolite clearly visible in the
Crayola,'' said Donna McNeal, director of the lab.
</P>
<P>
   McNeal said she also found asbestos in the foreign-made chalk
sample supplied by the TV station, and that the CPSC had been
notified of their findings.
</P>
<P>
   Binney &AMP; Smith said Thursday it also had turned over its new
results to the CPSC, which is conducting its own testing.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, Richard Lee of RJ Lee Group said: ``We
examined the optical properties of the minerals, as well as the
crystal structure of the talc and finished crayons, by PLM, TEM,
and SEM.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination of those techniques, which definitively
determine whether or not asbestos is present, confirmed that the
talc used in Crayola crayons and the finished products do not
contain asbestos and are safe for consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Binney &AMP; Smith Chief Operating Officer Al Hunyadi said in a
statement: ``These findings reaffirm the commitment to safety we've
upheld for nearly 100 years. Consumers who use Crayola products at
home and in school can continue to feel good about using them.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, while the CPSC continued its testing, the
Environmental Protection Agency in Washington prepared a briefing
sheet for its regional offices to use if they are asked about the
safety of crayons.
</P>
<P>
   In the paper, the agency said it ``would suggest that until more
information is available on this matter that crayons not be used.
This would be particularly true for children at ages generally 3
years old or younger, where there is a likelihood that they could,
and would, put the crayons into their mouths.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency's paper also said, ``While extremely low levels of
asbestos in crayons may not pose much of an actual risk to
children, any exposure would be unnecessary.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Public Health -- Seattle &AMP; King County issued an
advisory cautioning prents about household environmental hazards,
including asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main message for parents at this point is to make sure
that their children are not eating non-food items, crayons
included,'' said Alonzo Plough, director of the agencly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recent study just helps to remind parents of the hazards
that may be associated with consuming non-food items.''
</P>
<P>
   In its advisory, the health department also said: ``Although
there is no safe level of exposure level to asbestos, crayons are
not the only potential source of asbestos exposure in the urban
environment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
