<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TOBACCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. GOVERNOR VETOES BILL REQUIRING SAFER CIGARETTES
</HEADLINE>
  By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki announced Thursday that he had
vetoed a bill to make New York the first state to require that
cigarettes meet fire-safety standards. He said that such a
requirement might encourage bootlegging, and urged the Legislature
to send him an amended version of the bill that dealt with his
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The veto, made late Wednesday night, surprised legislators in
both parties, and prompted Democrats and anti-smoking groups to
accuse the governor of protecting the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the measure had hailed it as a breakthrough that
would prevent hundreds of accidental fires and dozens of deaths
each year. They said it could prod Congress to adopt national
fire-safety rules, which have been considered several times since
the 1980s, when tobacco companies first test-marketed
less-flammable cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said that he agreed with the bill's goal of requiring
that all cigarettes sold in New York starting in late 2002 would
have to stop burning when they are not puffed for a time. ``The
principle of New York taking the lead to make sure we have
fire-safe cigarettes, I wholeheartedly support,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that for him to sign a bill achieving that goal, the
Legislature needed to make a number of changes in the legislation
in the three weeks remaining in this year's legislative session.
``I am hopeful that they can sit down with our staff, work out
these details, and send the bill back with these changes and I will
sign it into law,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor and his aides said that less-flammable cigarettes
might not be welcomed by consumers, creating an incentive for
bootlegging, the importation from other states of cigarettes that
did not meet New York's standards. That would deprive the state of
cigarette tax revenue as well as frustrate the law. One of the
changes the governor sought would stiffen the penalties for
bootlegging.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of the bill brushed aside the governor's
objections as disingenuous or trivial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this was the governor desperately searching for an
excuse to veto,'' said Assemblyman Alexander Grannis, the Manhattan
Democrat and a bill sponsor. ``This was all about the governor
protecting big tobacco, about big tobacco money to Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Grannis said he would ask the Assembly to override the veto, an
idea that the Democratic majority will discuss next week. Senate
officials said the Republican majority in that chamber almost
certainly would not override the veto of a Republican governor.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco companies had lobbied against the bill, asserting that
state-by-state fire-safety standards would burden them. ``We're
supportive of a federal standard, and really believe that that is
the way to promulgate regulations and standards on fire safety,''
said Mike Pfeil, vice president for communications at Philip Morris
USA.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-tobacco groups say the industry's real concern is that
less-flammable cigarettes would cut down sales, because a smoker
who walks away from a lit cigarette for a time would find a stub
that could be re-lighted, rather than a pile of ash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the governor's handed a major victory to the tobacco
companies,'' said Blair Horner, legislative director of the New
York Public Interest Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   Grannis and aides to Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver said the
Assembly had no immediate objections to the governor's conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Both houses have already agreed to some of the changes Pataki
requested, including fines for retailers who sell cigarettes that
fail to meet the standards, and giving the tobacco companies six
months after the rules are published to comply with them, rather
than 30 days, which the vetoed bill provided.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Assembly and the Senate unanimously passed the bill,
which was supported by consumer groups, health groups like the
American Cancer Society and the American Lung Association,
firefighters' groups, and anti-tobacco organizations, more than a
month ago. But until Thursday, the governor and his aides
repeatedly refused to say what he thought of the bill, or even of
its basic goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how disappointed we are in the governor,''
said Gerald J. Day, vice chairman of the Firemen's Association of
the State of New York. ``Why did he wait until the last minute? He
had 37 days to sit down and work these problems out and he did
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki demanded new penalties for bootlegging and a ban on
Internet sales of cigarettes for shipment to customers in New York.
Internet sales evade payment of the state's tobacco taxes, could
circumvent flammability rules, and can enable minors to buy
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco companies are already selling some cigarettes that stop
burning on their own under some brand names. Some use paper that is
thick enough in places to stop burning. Others have altered the
chemical composition of the paper.
</P>
<P>
   The companies have found that the less-flammable cigarettes are
no more expensive to make, and that consumers like them as much as
standard cigarettes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
