<HEADLINE>
GALAXY EXHIBITION GAME POSTPONED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The Galaxy postponed its friendly Monday with
Persepolis of Iran until a later date because the Iranian
government took issue with U.S. immigration policies.
</P>
<P>
   This was supposed to be the second exhibition of the season for
Los Angeles, which played to a 1-1 draw with Chivas of Guadalajara
on April 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unfortunate that we had to postpone this match because
we planned it knowing the Iranian community would like to see one
of their country's legendary clubs play on U.S. soil,'' said Sergio
del Prado, the Galaxy's vice president of business operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nevertheless, the Iranian government had issues with U.S.
policies needing the traveling party to be photographed and
fingerprinted upon entering the country. We are now waiting for a
resolution to this impasse in order to reschedule the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who purchased tickets for the Persepolis match may receive
a refund or use those tickets for Saturday night's match against
San Jose and Iranian striker Khodadad Azizi at the Rose Bowl. Just
take the tickets to will call and ask for an exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy felt the absence of Mexican striker Luis Hernandez
and injured defender Robin Fraser in Wednesday's 2-1 loss to New
England the first defeat of the season for Los Angeles (6-1-5).
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Danny Califf made his first start at central defense,
striker Sebastian Vorbe made his second start and St. Francis High
and UCLA graduate Peter Vagenas made his MLS debut, scoring a goal
in the 94th minute of injury time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made some substitutions and people didn't know where to
go,'' said Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid. ``We had a good phase for
about 10 to 15 minutes in the second half and we didn't capitalize
on a couple opportunities. Overall, we were not a good team
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Creating scoring chances has become a lingering problem. Striker
Cobi Jones (four goals, two assists) hasn't scored since April 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had chances but we didn't finish,'' said Schmid. ``We
haven't had a forward score a goal in a month. That's something
that obviously has to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Defender Ezra Hendrickson will serve a one-game suspension
Saturday after receiving a red card in Wednesday's loss. Fraser is
also questionable with an ankle sprain, but Hernandez rejoins the
team after spending a week in Mexico with his pregnant wife.
</P>
</TEXT>
