<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH-PENDER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET WORTH: TECHNOLOGY STOCKS GO ON VACATION DURING DOG DAYS
OF  SUMMER
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By KATHLEEN PENDER 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's becoming a well-known fact that the stock
market, especially the tech sector, tends to swoon in the summer
and perk up in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the meltdown came a month or two earlier than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that hordes of investors _ glued to CNBC,
MarketWatch.com and their ilk _ discovered this phenomenon and
jumped the gun like baseball fans who leave in the eighth inning to
avoid traffic?
</P>
<P>
   And if so, is it possible that the market will snap out of its
malaise a month or two early, as investors try to front-run a
rebound?
</P>
<P>
   That's the question I put to investment professionals this week.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a question they like to answer, because timing the
market is an invitation to look stupid, especially because nobody
knows exactly why stocks slump during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The reason most analysts give is that European countries, which
consume a lot of technology products, take a five-week vacation.
</P>
<P>
   And American consumers tend to buy fewer PCs, and more barbecue
grills, in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the year, sales presumably pick up because many
corporate technology buyers have ``use-it-or-lose-it'' budgets.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, earnings sink during the spring and spurt in the
fall, and stock prices follow. But that argument doesn't hold much
water because earnings are usually quoted on a year-over-year basis
to avoid such seasonal variations.
</P>
<P>
   Ned Zachar, director of research with Thomas Weisel Partners,
gives this possible rationale: ``In tech investing, buyers tend to
look at sequential earnings.'' If a company's earnings dip from the
second to the third quarter, for example, ``that gives people who
are largely momentum-oriented a reason to get out,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   I think it's more like one of those traffic jams that have no
apparent cause, where you inch along for several miles and then
suddenly it breaks up, without any evidence of a wreck or
construction project.
</P>
<P>
   About the only seasonal factor that seems to make much sense is
that investors shovel money into the market just before April 15,
the deadline for investing in IRAs, to get a tax deduction for the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reasons, several studies have shown that over the
long term, stocks on average tend to turn down in May and up in
October or November.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic example of this comes from Ned Davis Research
and works like this:
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you invest $10,000 in the S&AMP;P 500 on the sixth trading
day of May and sell on September 30. You do nothing with the money
for six months. Then you reinvest your $10,000 plus any profits (or
minus any losses) the following May, and sell the following
September 30. This goes on year after year.
</P>
<P>
   Now assume you do the same thing, except you buy on October 1 of
each year and sell on the fifth trading day of May.
</P>
<P>
   If you did this during the past 50 years, you would have ended
up with $13,772 if you owned stocks from May through September, or
$560,926 if you owned stocks from September through May. This is
not a typo.
</P>
<P>
   A similar study by stock market historian Yale Hirsch, using a
holding period of May 1 through October 31 (instead of September
30), showed only slightly less-dramatic results. In his case,
during the same 50 years you would have $21,582 if you owned stocks
from May through October, and $363,367 if you owned stocks from
November to May.
</P>
<P>
   Ned Davis repeated this study using a well-diversified basket of
technology stocks, instead of the S&AMP;P 500. The results _ also
astonishing _ are shown in the chart on this page.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these long-term studies cloud the fact that in any
given year, you might do better buying stocks in the spring and
selling them in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The studies also ignore taxes and commissions, which would eat
greatly into your profits under both scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   Davis warns against putting too much stock in long-term
patterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like you've got one foot in the refrigerator and one foot
in the stove _ on average you're comfortable,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he says, it doesn't make sense to ignore
seasonal factors, which may indeed be changing as they become more
widely known.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the traditional ``January rally,'' which followed
year-end tax loss selling, seems to have moved into December and
become a ``Santa Claus rally'' now that many investors see it
coming.
</P>
<P>
   So, is the same thing happening with the summer swoon?
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts think the market started selling off in March not
because investors were anticipating a summer slowdown, but because
they finally realized that the Fed's interest rate hikes would take
a toll on high-valuation stocks.
</P>
<P>
   And most of them think the market will pick up when it becomes
clear the Fed is finished raising rates. And how will investors
know when the Fed is done?
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be some body language that comes out with the text
of the release,'' says Zachar. He doesn't know when that will
happen, but ``I think they're closer to the end than the
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   He thinks companies will report ``very solid second-quarter
results'' starting in mid-July. In addition, a lot of institutional
investors are sitting on a lot of cash that they can put into the
market when they feel better about interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get those things working for you, you could see the
market going to higher levels,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Bakar, director of research with Chase H&AMP;Q, thinks the
market ``will remain very volatile, with still a bit of a downward
trend in the near term. I think things will bottom in late summer,
early fall. There is going to be a clear rally between now and the
end of the year. I wouldn't be surprised to see stocks go up ahead
of the November election.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Skrainka, chief investment strategist with Edward Jones &AMP;
Co., says, ``This is just such an unusual time for technology, I'd
rather rely on common sense, judgment and traditional measures of
value rather than a calendar approach.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also thinks it would be foolhardy to wait until fall for
a rally. ``We've seen a 2,000-point decline in the Nasdaq. If we
see some stunningly good values this summer, we're going to tell
people to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   SO I'M NOT AN ENGINEER: Several readers let me know I made a
mistake in Wednesday's column on fiber optics when I wrote,
``information travels on glass fiber at the speed of light, many
orders of magnitude faster than electrons can move over copper wire
or coaxial cable.''
</P>
<P>
   Electrons also travel at the speed of light. What makes fiber
optics so much faster than copper or cable is ``its higher
modulation speeds and the ability to send multiple transmissions
through the same fiber simultaneously,'' says Anthony Muller, chief
financial officer with JDS Uniphase.
</P>
<P>
   Reader John E. Gibbons of Antioch, Calif., commented that the
growth of fiber optics could be hampered not just by a lack of
trained engineers but also by a shortage of workers ``who can
install the fiber and operate equipment designed to minimize the
tearing up of streets. As installations move more rapidly to
urbanized areas, the process may be dramatically slowed in some
unexpected ways.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kathleen Pender at  &LR; kpender(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
