DiSARCINA IS OUT FOR THE YEAR 
(For use by LANG partners) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Shortstop Gary DiSarcina will miss the rest of the
2000 season after athroscopic surgery revealed a small tear to his
rotator cuff in his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lewis Yocum repaired the tear and trimmed the outer layer of
the labrum during the procedure Thursday morning at UC Irvine
Medical Center in Orange. Recovery time for this type of injury is
normally nine to 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of DiSarcina, 32, leaves the Angels to consider their
future at the shortstop position, both immediate and in the long
term. DiSarcina is making $3.25 million this season in the final
year of a four-year, $11.7 million contract. The Angels hold a
$3.45 million option for 2001, but general manager Bill Stoneman
said it is too early to determine what the club will do.
</P>
<P>
   ''I talked to him today and said to him the question would come
up with respect to his contract,'' Stoneman said. ''His response
was the same as mine. It's too early to get into that.''
</P>
<P>
   If it is the end of DiSarcina's career with the Angels, he will
have played in exactly the same number of games (1,086) as his
predecessor Dick Schofield, ranking fourth on the club's all-time
list.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the short time I've known him, he obviously is a
determined, competitive and team-oriented type person,'' Stoneman
said. ''His presence on the field is missed, and not just what he
does for you with his glove and with his bat.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Angels do with DiSarcina after this season might be
determined how the shortstop position is handled this season. Benji
Gil is starting at shortstop now, but the Angels plan to bring up
Justin Baughman from Triple-A Edmonton to be their starter. When
that will be isn't known, but if he shows he can be be an every-day
shortstop at the major-league level he might be their long-term
solution.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Justin continues to play well, he might be an answer for
us,'' Stoneman said about this season. ''If (Edmonton manager)
Garry Templeton tells me he is ready to play major league
shortstop, that'll be good enough for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Baughman, 25, originally was a shortstop when the Angels drafted
him in 1995 before they moved him to second base. They were
grooming him to be their every-day second baseman before he broke
his leg in five places in the Mexican Winter League in 1998. He was
out of action until this spring and began the season at Double-A
Erie, but has since been moved to shortstop and promoted to
Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Gil, who has started 34 games at shorstop and played 39 overall,
is hitting .207 and committed a team-high 11 errors.
</P>
<P>
   ''Benji has performed pretty well for us so far,'' Stoneman
said. ''We know he's booted a few balls, but he's also made some
plays some people wouldn't have made. He hasn't hit .300 but he's
performed as well as we expected him to perform.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Scott Schoeneweis beat Brad Radke and the Twins
Thursday. Up next: Chuck Finley and the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   The game has a little more meaning for Schoeneweis, who watched,
listened and learned from the veteran Finley while the two were
teammates with the Angels. Schoeneweis didn't know Finley would be
his counterpart in his next start on Tuesday until told by a
reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's great, I'm excited about that,'' he said. ''It's one of
those games years later I'll look back on. It's a chance to pitch
against a guy who pretty much took me under his wing.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis is off to a 5-2 start this season, but said he
doesn't need to prove anything to Finley.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not going to try to impress him,'' Schoeneweis said.
''Just try to keep the team in the game. When you go against a guy
like Chuck, and a guy like (Brad) Radke today, you've got to have
your A- game.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Seth Etherton joined the team in Minneapolis Thursday
just in time to watch the game, then fly with the team to Kansas
City, where he'll make his major league debut tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Etherton was 2-2 with a 4.43 ERA in seven starts for Triple-A
Edmonton, and said he had ''no idea'' he was going to be called up.
</P>
<P>
   Etherton will be the third of the four prized pitchers who began
the 1999 season at Double-A Erie to reach the majors, joining Ramon
Ortiz and Brian Cooper. Matt Wise, currently at Edmonton, is the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not one who gets too nervous,'' Etherton said. ''It's an
opportunity to do what I can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
