<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-TWINS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS WIN SIXTH OF THEIR LAST SEVEN, 3-1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYT Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ It might not be much, but the Angels reached
unchartered territory with their 3-1 victory over the Minnesota
Twins Thursday afternoon before 13,552 at the Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Schoeneweis returned to the form that made him 4-0 in
April with 7 1/3 strong innings, and Mo Vaughn hit another home run
as the club won its sixth in seven games to improve to 25-22, the
first time they've been three games over .500 since the end of the
1998 season when they were 85-77.
</P>
<P>
   They also completed their first three-game sweep of the Twins
since 1996 and their first sweep in Minnesota since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for the Angels was tempered a bit by word that
shortstop Gary DiSarcina will be lost for the season with a small
tear of his rotator cuff in his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   But it has been a season in which the Angels are doing it with
contributions from everyone, from recently called-up minor leaguers
to the big names like Vaughn. And on a day when Twins pitcher Brad
Radke gave up only two runs in eight innings, the Angels managed to
get what they needed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't say enough about these guys,'' said Angels closer Troy
Percival, who pitched the ninth and earned his 14th save. ''If we
need eight runs, we get eight runs. If we need 10 runs, we get 10
runs. And the guys in the bullpen ahead of me have done a great
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival was quick to note that beating the Twins isn't the same
as beating the Yankees or the Indians. But the point is to win the
games they're expected to win.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're supposed to beat teams like that,'' he said. ''In the
past, they've out-scrapped us. We're showing we can do what we're
supposed to do to be a championship team.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Mike Scioscia said the sweep wasn't as important
as a consistent approach the team is taking to the ballpark every
day.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not thinking sweeps,'' Scioscia said. ''All we knew is
we were facing Radke, who is one of the best pitchers in the
league. Schoeneweis matched him pitch for pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis had struggled before Wednesday. He was 4-0 with a
3.15 ERA in his five starts of April, but in his first four starts
of May, he was 0-2 with an 8.64 ERA. Thursday, he pitched into the
eighth inning for the first time in five starts, and gave up only
one run and six hits. A good sign for Schoeneweis was that his
sinker was working -- he got 19 outs on ground balls.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of their guys are young and so they're aggressive at the
plate,'' Schoeneweis said. ''That falls into my game plan of
swinging early (in the count). I can count only a few pitches that
didn't go where I wanted it to, and that's why I got so many ground
balls.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He pitched a great game,'' Scioscia said ''He mixed his
pitches well, threw inside well and had a good sinker going.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more important for Schoeneweis was that he was not affected
by his recent struggles, Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He hasn't really flinched during his tough stretch,'' Scioscia
said. ''He pitched like he did the first four or five starts. You
always want to get back on the horse and he did. Hopefully he'll
ride that into his next start.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn gave the Angels a 1-0 lead with his 17th home run of the
season in the first inning, extending his hitting streak to 12
games, and Schoeneweis held the lead until the fifth when Butch
Husky doubled, went to third on a single by Brian Buchanan and
scored on Marcus Jensen's grounder to third.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels broke the tie in the eighth when Darin Erstad singled
with one out, then scored all the way from first on Orlando
Palmeiro's bloop single. Palmeiro's hit landed in left-center
field, where left fielder Jacque Jones knocked the ball into center
field trying to keep the ball from taking a big hop on the
artificial turf.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad never hesitated and scored easily.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was scoring the second it was hit, in my mind,'' Erstad
said. ''There are so many obstacles (for the outfielders), the
lights, the roof. I was always taught run hard until they catch
you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels scored an insurance run in the ninth on Matt
Walbeck's RBI double.
</P>
</TEXT>
