<SLUG> BC-JUGGLER-BALANCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 KEEPING WORK AND HOME LIVES APART  &HT;     By VICKY ELLIOTT 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Beth Sawi was an instrumental force in launching
Charles Schwab &AMP; Co.'s online operations five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the long hours took their toll on the senior executive of
the discount brokerage. As the mother of two young children, she
felt like a packhorse, exhausted from balancing two heavy loads,
her work at the office and her responsibilities to her family.
</P>
<P>
   After stepping back and taking a long look at the situation, she
began to find ways to meet the expectations of her employer without
neglecting those closest to her.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, she has helped reshape the corporate culture at
Schwab to be more receptive to the personal needs of its staff. And
she has become an expert on the subject, speaking around the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Sawi, author of a newly published book ``Coming Up for Air: How
to Build a Balanced Life in a Workaholic World,'' is dealing with
changes in the workplace that firms across the country must tackle
in order to retain their employees.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies have responded, offering flexible work schedules
that allow workers to telecommute and work fewer days of the week.
</P>
<P>
   But Sawi, 48, Schwab's chief administrative officer and
executive vice president, believes much more needs to be done. ``We
haven't established any system to say how many hours it's OK to
work,'' she said. ``We're still hanging on to the old working day
of 8 to 5, and yet, with electronic access, there's that tendency
to say: `I need to talk to them as markets open up in London or
Krakow or Singapore.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sawi knows full well what those long days are like. Working for
American Express and Citibank in New York in the early 1980s, she
put in 12-to-14-hour days.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, she moved to San Francisco to join her husband, David,
when Schwab was a small brokerage house with only a few hundred
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, the birth of her son put an end to her long
hours, because she had to be home at 6 p.m. She found she had to
use her considerable negotiating skills to carve out more space for
her personal life.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, when her daughter was born, she arranged to
work part time.
</P>
<P>
   But she soon returned to a heavy schedule to spearhead the
company's drive into online trading. Meanwhile, she became so
interested in the tension between work and family life that she
began to speak on the subject and teach classes on it in the
company.
</P>
<P>
   As chief administrative officer, she oversees human resources at
the company and has used her position to promote changes that allow
for a healthy balance between work and personal life.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab permits some telecommuting and compressed 12-hour
three-day weeks. Among the course offerings of its in-house
``university'' is one on ``life balance.''
</P>
<P>
   The firm also offers paternity leave of up to three months and
was one of the first to set up facilities for nursing mothers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it has subcontracted LesConcierges to handle many
chores that in the 1950s that would have been performed by a
stay-at-home wife. Employees, for example, can use the service to
take care of their dry-cleaning, arrange a party or price out how
to fix the gutter at home.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab's most recent perk, which Sawi helped push through, is a
four-week paid sabbatical for those who have served five years with
the company, up to the level of vice president. Employees can add
this to their two weeks of vacation.
</P>
<P>
   By European standards, of course, two weeks of vacation a year
would be considered woefully insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Sawi experienced this firsthand last year, when she spent a year
in Florence to write her book. Her exposure to the Italian work
ethic taught her how to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   On Sundays, she said, she couldn't buy an onion _ because none
of the stores were open. On weekdays, at midday, she would stand
helplessly outside a shuttered storefront despite the sign on the
window saying it should be open.
</P>
<P>
   ``They stopped working, by Jove!'' she recalled, ``and they
simply didn't care that I needed to buy a chicken for my
children.''
</P>
<P>
   However irritating this was, it gave her a different cultural
perspective on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are social costs to the conveniences we expect as
American consumers,'' she said. ``You wander into a 24-hour Safeway
at 3 a.m. and wonder if you would like to be the person who has to
work there. But that's what our economy demands.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans have much to learn, she said, from the relaxing pace
of the good life that brings Italian families together over meals.
</P>
<P>
   Sawi said she remembers a time in her own life when things were
less hectic. During the 1960s, when she was growing up in San
Bernardino County, Calif., people were still talking about what
Americans would do with the leisure time that was coming their way.
</P>
<P>
   Offices shut down when the switchboard operator went home, and
you couldn't receive a call after 5:30 p.m. whether you wanted to
or not. Then, you had to wait for the mail boy to come by the next
morning to bring your letters. People would come home for lunch
because their commute was no longer than 10 to 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It was on her train rides into San Francisco from Berkeley,
Calif., that Sawi first started mulling over the question of how to
hold the line on her work hours. Now, she recommends people use
their commute for what she calls ``directed daydreaming'' _
figuring out their personal priorities and sticking to them
``despite the pressures the outside world might apply.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she finds that cultivating outside interests helps
boost productivity. ``If your life out of the workplace is hollow
or empty or unfulfilled, you'll just go home and watch old TV
shows,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you have an opposite force in your life, it helps
invigorate you. You say: I really want to get this project done
because I have something else to do that really matters to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sawi strives to practice what she preaches. Although she still
puts in almost a 10-hour day, arriving at work by 8 a.m., she makes
sure that she has taken care of the last e-mail at the office by
5:30 p.m. And her weekends are devoted to the family.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 2317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
