<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6101 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-HOMES-MARKET-SFCHRON &LR;      05-25 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMES-MARKET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HOUSING MARKET SLOWS IN BAY AREA  &HT;     By CAROL EMERT 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After a four-year housing boom, sales of
existing Bay Area homes slowed sharply last month and prices are
expected to begin moderating soon.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the number of previously-owned homes sold in the
nine-county Bay Area plunged 20.2 percent against April 1999 to
6,263. That's an 8.3 percent decline compared to March, according
to a report by DataQuick Information Systems, a real estate
research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Economists attributed the downturn, which was the biggest such
drop in five years, to rising interest rates, a tumble in
technology stock prices and the Bay Area's chronic housing
shortage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to see a continued, gradual cooling trend in both
prices and sales from the higher rates,'' particularly since a
half-point increase in short-term interest rates last week was not
reflected in the April numbers, said Tom Lieser, executive director
of the UCLA Anderson Forecast.
</P>
<P>
   But while the number of home sales is clearly falling, price
relief has not yet registered. Median Bay Area home prices rose to
$358,000 in April, up 22.6 percent from April 1999 and 4.7 percent
for the month, according to DataQuick.
</P>
<P>
   Economists say median prices may be skewed by sales of
multimillion-dollar homes, since the super-wealthy are not as
sensitive to interest rate increases as other home buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you usually observe during times of rising mortgage rates
is the high-end houses tend to be less vulnerable (while) demand
falls off quickly in the lower end of the market,'' said Bruce
Smith, an economist with the California Department of Finance.
</P>
<P>
   That theory was borne out by a report from the California
Association of Realtors, which found that Los Altos, Calif.,
chalked up the biggest price increase of any California city last
month. Its median home sold for $1.4 million, said the report
released yesterday. Other chi-chi Peninsula communities showed
similar activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect the month-to-month changes to start showing
declines within several months, particularly if we see mortgage
rates continuing on up,'' said Lieser.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually home sales should decline to close to their historic
rates of 3 to 4 percent annual growth, although when that will
happen is anybody's guess though, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of high-end homes are likely to moderate, too, if
technology stocks remain lackluster.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of cash gains realized from stock option grants
jumped to $51 billion in California last year, more than double the
$25 billion recorded in 1998 and more than triple 1997's $15
billion, according to Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The state predicts that option income will decline 25 percent to
$39 billion in 2000, although any forecasts involving stock prices
are unreliable, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   More interest rate increases are likely too, especially after
yesterday's Commerce Department report confirming that the U.S.
gross domestic product jumped 5.4? percent in the first quarter,
economists said.
</P>
<P>
   In April, 30-year fixed mortgages had jumped to an average of
8.15 percent from 6.92 percent in April 1999, according to the
Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Smith dates the housing boom from March 1996, when resales of
California homes surprised economist by jumping 30 percent against
March 1995.
</P>
<P>
   That month turned out to be a watershed. Home sales in 1996 grew
16 percent, compared to a 12.2 percent drop in 1995, and have been
booming ever since.
</P>
<P>
   April's slowdown is of concern to the state because it indicates
housing is becoming an even greater constraint to job growth, Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area added 2.4 jobs for every new unit of housing built
in the 1990s, compared to 1.7 jobs per unit in the Los Angeles
basin and 1.6 jobs in Sacramento, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence, Gov. Gray Davis last month proposed a
one-time, $200 million grant for communities that approve new home
permits, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area, where anti-development sentiment has kept
home-building behind other parts of the state, is the major target
of the new fund because its potential for job growth is so great
but its housing supply is so squeezed, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carol Emert at  &LR; cemert(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
