<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-EXPORTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BAY AREA COMPANIES PONDER OPPORTUNITIES IN CHINA  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With a new era in U.S-China trade relations
about to dawn, John Schwartz of Livermore, Calif.'s Wente Vineyards
prepared to fly to China this weekend to rewrite his company's
marketing and pricing strategies for that country.
</P>
<P>
   High import duties have turned a $10 bottle of Wente wine into
an expensive luxury item costing as much as $180 in Beijing. But
tariffs on U.S. wine are set to drop from 65 percent to 14 percent
when China enters the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to know our wines will be more affordable for the
Chinese consumers, although this is only the first step,''
Schwartz, Wente's vice president of international operations, said
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the U.S. House of Representatives approved giving
China permanent normal trading status, Bay Area companies in
industries as diverse as wine and computers were drawing up new
game plans to take advantage of the huge potential market in China
that may finally be opening up to the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bay Area is primed to be the biggest winner in the country
from what is coming out of the agreement,'' said Sean Randolph,
president of the Bay Area Economic Forum, a San Francisco alliance
of local governments and corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, the Bay Area's booming computer-related industries
are expected to be the biggest winners once China officially
becomes a member of the WTO and the trading status issue clears the
U.S. Senate. Some projections predict sales of technology products
to grow by 20 to 40 percent per year.
</P>
<P>
   Agreements China has made to enter the WTO would dramatically
lower tariffs that make American goods more expensive than products
from other countries, which in turn ``positions us very strongly to
take advantage of that growing market,'' Randolph said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, China accounted for a fraction of California's exports
of computer equipment, worth about $27 billion last year, said
Bruce Smith, an economist with the state Department of Finance.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith said one important trend showed China's potential:
While computer exports to other nations essentially remained flat
during the last four years, sales to China increased nearly
doubled, adding about $380 million to the state's economy from 1996
to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, China in upgrading it's industrial and retail methods
and as a middle class grows in China, there's clearly a demand for
computers, some of which are going to be built in California,''
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   But other industries are licking their chops as well. The Wine
Institute of San Francisco believes the domestic wine export market
in China could in the next decade equal the current market in
Japan, now worth about $100 million a year in sales.
</P>
<P>
   American wine sales in China now generate about $7 million in
revenue, ``still a trickle,'' said Wine Institute President John De
Luca. ``But we're hoping the rivulet could become a torrent.''
</P>
<P>
   California farmers also hope to harvest more profits after
agricultural tariffs drop from an average 37 percent to an average
15 percent, said California Farm Bureau spokesman Bob Krauter.
</P>
<P>
   For example, tariffs on oranges, grapefruit and lemons are
scheduled to plummet from 40 percent to 12 percent by 2004, Krauter
said. Sunkist Growers Inc., which began shipping oranges in March
when China dropped a 20-year-old Medfly pesticide restriction, is
now forecasting it will sell about $500 million in oranges in China
in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Growers of everything from broccoli to tree nuts are also
looking for a bump once China's tariffs on those products drop
anywhere from 13 to 71 percent by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   But economist Bruce Smith said he has doubts California's
agricultural industry will gain as much as the technology sector.
China, after all, has the same variety of climates that can grow
almost any crop found in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wonder in the long run if China will ever be a major
agricultural market for us,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   And businesses will still have to contend with a developing but
still uneven set of business laws, said San Francisco international
law attorney David Schnapf.
</P>
<P>
   Schnapf's firm advises several Internet companies that are
already doing business in China. ``We advise them there's a lot of
uncertainty, and that a good solid relationship is as good as any
solid legal document that you can draft,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Benny Evangelista at  &LR; bennye(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
