<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALPERS-INVEST-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NEW INVESTMENT CHIEF JOINS CALPERS  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Daniel Szente helped oversee $3.5 billion in
assets as vice president and research director of Pennsylvania's
McGlinn Capital Management. His work is about to become a whole lot
more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Szente, 52, was named Thursday as the new chief investment
officer of the California Public Employees Retirement System
(CalPERS), which, with $175 billion in assets, is the nation's
largest public pension fund.
</P>
<P>
   His appointment follows a string of departures by some of the
fund's top investment officials, who have been lured away by
high-paying jobs in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Szente said in an interview that it's too soon to say how
CalPERS' massive portfolio will change under his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``CalPERS is already on the right track,'' he said. ``The real
challenge now is to keep it going in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   This won't be easy. Although CalPERS boasts impressive
diversification in its investments _ basically, it owns a piece of
almost everything _ the fund now has nearly two-thirds of its cash
in stocks, and, as any investor will attest, the market has not
been the friendliest of places lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm short-term cautious,'' Szente said. ``But I'm not terribly
concerned about the market from a long-term perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   While adding that CalPERS' current investments appear ``very
appropriate,'' he admitted that recent market volatility will
almost certainly affect future returns.
</P>
<P>
   Szente declined to discuss particular sectors or individual
stocks that he sees as being especially promising.
</P>
<P>
   But he noted that ``technology is going to be a driver for the
future'' and that tech companies will be increasingly attractive as
their sky-high valuations come down to earth.
</P>
<P>
   Szente will assume his new post at CalPERS on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to his current gig at McGlinn, he served as assistant
director of investments for the State Teachers' Retirement System
of Ohio and as manager of the Howard Hughes Medical Institute's
equity portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan has an excellent blend of public and private experience,
investment savvy and leadership qualities that are ideally suited
to furthering our investment strategy,'' CalPERS' chief executive,
James Burton, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Szente's appointment followed an announcement a day earlier from
Guy Jaquier, CalPERS' senior real estate investment officer, that
he will resign June 9 to become executive vice president and chief
investment officer of San Francisco's AMB Property Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Bob Boldt, CalPERS' No. 2 investment officer, said
he too would be cleaning out his desk to pursue a career in the
private sector.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Sheryl Pressler, Szente's predecessor as CIO, left
to take a senior post with Atlanta's Lend Lease Real Estate
Investments, the largest manager of pension funds' real estate
assets.
</P>
<P>
   And Patrick Mitchell, CIO of CalPERS' sister fund, the
California State Teachers' Retirement System, said last week that
he will make his exit in July to join a venture-capital firm.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Welty, head of Welty Capital Management in Lafayette,
Calif., said CalPERS will continue having a hard time holding on to
talented investment officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just too highly structured there as far as pay goes,'' he
observed.
</P>
<P>
   In the private sector, Welty noted, top investment officials can
make upwards of $400,000 a year, perhaps as much as $1 million with
performance bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Szente will be paid $260,000 annually. Other top CalPERS
investment officials are paid about $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   CalPERS now holds more than $116 billion in U.S. and
international stocks, $44 billion in bonds, $9 billion in real
estate and $6 billion in private held investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The larger pool of assets makes it harder to invest,'' Szente
said. ``Just finding enough prospects can be very, very
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he will rely on CalPERS' 100-person investment staff to
help him acclimate to the higher asset elevation.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; davidlaz(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
