<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMOSUIT-RACKET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PHYSICIANS TAKE HMOS TO COURT  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the first lawsuit of its kind, the California
Medical Association has accused three of the state's largest,
for-profit HMOs of running what amounts to an illegal racket.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed Thursday in federal court in San Francisco,
charges Blue Cross, Pacificare and HealthNet with violating the
Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act (RICO).
</P>
<P>
   The suit says the three HMOs, which cover nearly 2 out of every
3 insured Californians, promised patients full health care
coverage, then failed to provide enough money to pay doctors to
provide that care, engaging in organized fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Suing health plans for fraud isn't new. Last year, a group of
Southern law firms, enriched by fees earned in tobacco lawsuits,
began suing HMOs in other states for the same RICO act allegations.
</P>
<P>
   But observers said yesterday's lawsuit by the CMA, the largest
doctor's group in California, marks the first time physicians have
used racketeering laws to try and force HMOs to pay doctors more
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the HMOs) have knowingly not supplied us with enough
money to take care of patients,'' said Dr. J.C. Pickett, CMA's
outgoing president. ``That is the root of this whole suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Five of the six law firms representing CMA are from the same
group of Southern law firms that were involved in the tobacco
settlements and pioneered the use of RICO against HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   HealthNet spokeswoman Lisa Kalustian called the racketeering
charges ludicrous and said the case would only suck money out of a
health care system that is already burdened by soaring drug and
hospitalization costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only winners are the lawyers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Zelman, president of the California Association of Health
Plans, the state's HMO lobby group, said he was disappointed that
CMA filed suit instead of continuing negotiations that the two
lobbies started last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a specific allegation against a specific health
plan,'' Zelman said. ``This is a shotgunlike attack on managed
care.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the 47-page lawsuit targets the common practice of
capitation used by for-profit and nonprofit HMOs alike.
</P>
<P>
   Under capitation agreements, HMOs pay doctors a fixed monthly
fee for each patient, whether the patient is well and never comes
in for a visit or gets sick and requires costly tests and
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The CMA suit says HMOs set ``capitation rates to physician
groups at unconscionably low levels which defendants know are not
adequate to cover the medical services defendants promised to
provide.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickett, the former CMA president, said capitation rewards
doctors for shunning sick patients who need them most.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am being paid not to see patients,'' Pickett said. ``The
less of them that come in my office, the better I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Capitation agreements are negotiated between health plans and
doctors groups. The CMA argues that such negotiations favor HMOs,
because a few health plans control most of the patients in
California, giving them far more power than doctors, who are
divided into hundreds of groups.
</P>
<P>
   The CMA is trying to change state and federal laws to let
doctors band together to bargain as a group with HMOs. At present,
such group bargaining runs afoul of antitrust laws; doctors, being
small businesses, cannot band together to set prices. The CMA's
attempts to exempt doctors from antitrust laws have so far been
stymied by opposition from HMO lobbyists who argue that doctors
would become a price-fixing cartel.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's CMA suit is therefore only the latest in a series of
moves by doctors interested in finding a new bargaining lever.
Pickett said CMA is hoping the suit will result in a negotiated
settlement ``to open up the capitation agreements and get more
money.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Tom Abate at  &LR; abate(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
