<SLUG> BC-KOREA-MASSACRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-G.I. IN A.P. ACCOUNT CONCEDES HE DIDN'T SEE KOREA MASSACRE
</HEADLINE>
  By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Edward L. Daily, the Korean War veteran whose unsettling
recollections of gunning down civilians made him the most
sought-after witness to the killings, now agrees that he was not on
the scene, the Associated Press said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Presented with military records showing that he was serving with
another unit miles away on July 26, 1950, when a group of civilians
cowering under the double arches of a concrete railroad trestle
were killed, Daily told the AP: ``I have to agree with your
records. I can't dispute them.''
</P>
<P>
   The admission came after two weeks of mounting questions about
the credibility of the veteran who was one of nine named sources
cited in the AP's Sept. 29, 1999, report, which was the first to
show that Americans had taken part in the killings. Last month, the
AP report was awarded a Pulitzer Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Daily's admission came after reporters for the military affairs
Web site Stripes.com and U.S. News &AMP; World Report published
evidence raising doubts about his presence on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Wolman, the AP's executive editor, said in a statement
Thursday, ``While we remain confident of the central findings of
our coverage, AP is dismayed that Ed Daily cannot authenticate his
account of the events at No Gun Ri.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolman added, `` Daily is obviously haunted by his service in
the Korean War even as he struggles to understand and explain the
version of events he provided to AP, to the Army and to other news
organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the wire service's original report about No Gun
Ri, the Defense Department set up a commission to look into the
scope of the killings _ estimates of the number of victims run from
below 50 to more than 300 _ and whether the soldiers who shot the
refugees were acting under direct orders. Daily was one of three
soldiers who spoke of direct orders, either in the original report
or on videotapes available on the AP's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The question of direct orders is of paramount importance to
military investigators, because such orders would be likely to
constitute a war crime. The AP's original report said high military
commanders had issued general orders to stop any refugees trying to
cross the front lines.
</P>
</TEXT>
