<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS IN BRIEF  

</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Utah, Calif., Texas)  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HOUSE: A FEUD LINGERS
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret in Utah that Rep. Christopher B. Cannon of the
3rd Congressional District and Rep. Merrill Cook of the 2nd, both
Republicans, are not the best of friends. Cook watched
incredulously a few weeks ago as Cannon nominated a Cook challenger
at the state Republican convention. So is Cook plotting his
revenge? Who should show up at Cook's front door the other Sunday
but Donald Dunn, a Democrat who is challenging Cannon. The Hill, a
weekly newspaper that covers Congress, said Dunn stopped in for
lunch and the two, acquaintances for years, talked about Cannon.
Cook says that they chatted only a few minutes. And if it was
Dunn's intention to fuel Republican discord, it would not work,
Cook insists. ``It's irritating that Chris is the one member of the
delegation who doesn't support me for re-election,'' Cook told The
Hill. ``But that doesn't mean that I don't support the Republicans
trying to retain control of the Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael Janofsky
</P>
<P>
   CONSERVATIVE PARTY IN THE NEWS
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party and the even lesser known Green Party are
getting some national coverage this year, thanks to Pat Buchanan
and Ralph Nader, the front-runners for their respective
presidential nominations. And recently the staunchly conservative
Constitution Party, which is hardly ever covered, has been in the
news, too, thanks to the conservative commentator Alan Keyes, a
Republican White House hopeful. He warned the other day that he
would jump to the Constitution Party should the Republican Party
weaken its anti-abortion stand. Then Howard Phillips, the party's
presidential nominee, announced at a press luncheon in Washington
that his party had quietly completed ballot access work in 30
states, no small political achievement if all 30 are eventually
certified. Together, he said, those states are worth 290 electoral
votes, 20 more than required to win. But he is not running to win,
he insisted, only to increase his party's visibility, expand its
base and advance its ``true conservative philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Irvin Molotsky
</P>
<P>
   INDIANS AND POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   California is the state where the most money is spent on
political campaigns. And in recent years, California's Indian
tribes have become the biggest-spending interest group in the
state, pouring about $114 million into campaigns since 1998. Why,
given that Indians account for less than 15 percent of California's
population? Statistics compiled by the California chapter of Common
Cause show that most of the money was spent on a successful
one-time effort to pass ballot measures permitting expansion of
reservation gambling, a move that is expected to eventually make
California second only to Nevada as a casino mecca. But the figures
pulled together by Common Cause, a private watchdog organization,
also show that the tribes are giving heavily to elect candidates,
dwarfing contributions by all other groups in recent years by
handing out $7 million. The second-biggest-spending interest group
in the state, Common Cause said, is the state prison guard union,
the California Correctional Peace Officers Association.
Representing security personnel in the country's largest prison
system, it gave $1.9 million to candidates over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH DAUGHTERS' DAY
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have a tear in my eye,'' Governor George W. Bush said
Thursday in Austin, Texas, as he prepared to watch his twin
daughters, Jenna and Barbara, graduate from Stephen F. Austin High
School and head off for college. ``They mean more to us than
anything in life,'' he went on. ``Today is a big day.'' Then,
making clear that he wanted to continue the family's effort to
shield the teen-agers as much as possible from the spotlight of
public life, he told reporters, ``You all aren't invited, by the
way.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Alison Mitchell
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Austin, Texas
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Cordova, Tenn., Memphis and Newburgh, N.Y.
</P>
