<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6121 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-LAKERS-NYT &LR;      05-25 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WALLACE FACTOR: BLAZERS' ASSET OR BIGGEST LIABILITY? 
</HEADLINE>
   By TOM SPOUSTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ He's an enigma and an All-Star, a technical
foul waiting to happen and a highlight film ready to roll. In two
mood swings so far, Rasheed Wallace has proved himself as the
Western Conference finals' wild card, capable of fouling his own
team's chemistry or personally escorting the Los Angeles Lakers to
the express-checkout lane.
</P>
<P>
   Playing only 16 minutes in Game 1 last Saturday, Wallace was the
Portland Trail Blazers' biggest asset and liability, scoring 11
points and being ejected for a menacing stare-down of the official
Ron Garretson. Portland lost by 15 points.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 2 on Monday, Wallace suddenly became his own
anger-management counselor, played 46 of 48 minutes and strafed the
Lakers for 29 points and 12 rebounds. He hit all three of his
3-point attempts in the decisive third quarter and Portland won by
29 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way everybody would love to see Rasheed play _
including myself,'' the Blazers' Scottie Pippen said.
</P>
<P>
   So, which Wallace will show up for Game 3 on Friday night at the
Rose Garden? The rage? Or the fury?
</P>
<P>
   His teammates are confident Wallace, who is in his fifth
professional season, has replaced his short regular-season fuse
with a mature playoff cool. The power of peer pressure in the Trail
Blazers' locker room after Game 1 certainly helped promote a change
in his attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might not have said it to anybody, but I know he was real
frustrated about the other day,'' the Portland guard Bonzi Wells
said. ``Like he let everybody down.''
</P>
<P>
   With the home crowd serving as Wallace's support group for the
next two games, the Lakers could again find themselves under
extreme frontcourt pressure. A focused Wallace can resemble Pippen
in his quickness and sleight of hand, appearing to be constantly
open on offense and everywhere on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tough match,'' said Portland's Greg Anthony, the former
Knick, who like Wallace struggled early in his career to find the
proper mix of emotion and intensity in his game. ``When he stays
under control and plays the way he did, it really bodes well for
us.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to have a happy medium there. The best way to develop
that is with experience and over time. That's something Rasheed is
doing a pretty good job of. Even from Game 1 to Game 2, he was
frustrated with a few calls that didn't go his way, but he didn't
allow that to deter him from doing his job. He's garnering
experience with that each day and each game.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace shrugged his shoulders and offered no insight into his
turnaround from villain to hero. ``Just playing ball,'' he said of
his 11 points during the Trail Blazers' 28-8 third-quarter blowout
of the Lakers in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``You pretty much feel like you're on a roll and can score at
any time,'' he said. ``They did the same thing to us in Game 1 when
they blew us up in that second quarter. That's just how it goes. If
you put a whole lot into it, it turns out to be a good story.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace's offensive production was only part of the plot. His
biggest impact came on defense, where he and Pippen helped center
Arvydas Sabonis stop Shaquille O'Neal, who scored only 9 points
through three quarters. Wallace also has spent significant time
guarding Kobe Bryant, who has 25 points in two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say I've shut him down,'' Wallace said. ``We've
been doubling on him, so it doesn't make sense for him to shoot
over a double or sometimes a triple team. So he just passes out
instead. It's just simple basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   To Portland Coach Mike Dunleavy, Wallace's play in Game 2 was a
simple case of the forward's channeling his energy toward the
Lakers instead of the officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference in Rasheed was about 20 minutes,'' Dunleavy
quipped afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to try and fool anybody,'' Dunleavy said
Thursday. ``I can talk all I want to Rasheed, say all I need to say
to him, say all the right things. But it comes down to him wanting
it. He's got to make that decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's heard it from me, from anybody and everybody you can
think of, all his coaches over the years, and at some point it's
got to become important to him. Last game was very important to
him, to step out and play the way he played.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said he has benefited from the presence of Pippen and
guard Steve Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot to have those veterans out there,'' Wallace
said. ``It makes my job easier because sometimes the refs might be
looking more at them, and that gives me opportunities to roam
around. Or vice versa. It's definitely an advantage for me.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
