<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI CAMPAIGN RETURNING $2.8 MILLION, PONDERS REMAINDER 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's disbanded Senate campaign
will soon begin returning nearly $2.8 million to thousands of
contributors across the country, and will enclose with the checks a
letter suggesting that donors give the money instead to Rep. Rick
A. Lazio, a Republican from Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani is required by federal law to return this part of his
campaign fund within 60 days of his withdrawal from the race, but
he's not required to include a letter supporting Lazio's Senate
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, this will mean that at least some substantial
proportion of the people that donated to my campaign will donate to
his campaign,'' Giuliani said during a news conference. The $2.8
million had been set aside in a separate account to be used only
for the general election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor also said that he would campaign for Lazio in the
Senate race within the next week, but that he would skip the state
Republican Party's convention in Buffalo on May 30 to avoid
creating ``any kind of distraction'' from Lazio's nomination as the
party's candidate. Giuliani pledged once again Thursday to help
Lazio, who entered the race against Hillary Rodham Clinton, the
Democratic Party's candidate, less than 24 hours after Giuliani
withdrew because of his prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's actions are essential if he wants to run for office
again in New York with the backing of the state Republican Party.
Even though the mayor dropped out of the party's Senate race for
health reasons, there remains some hostility toward him because of
his protracted decision-making and the subsequent unraveling of his
personal life. On May 10, Giuliani announced publicly that he was
seeking a separation from his wife, but he did not privately tell
her first. Two days later, he appeared in public with Judith
Nathan, calling her his ``very good'' friend.
</P>
<P>
   John H. Gross, Giuliani's campaign treasurer, said Thursday that
when the campaign finished paying its bills _ including the $2.8
million it must return to contributors _ it would have slightly
more than $3 million left out of the $20 million raised.
</P>
<P>
   The disposition of the $3 million is likely of interest to
Lazio, as well as to state and national Republicans. It may also be
important to Giuliani's political future.
</P>
<P>
   Legally, Giuliani may keep the money for future political
campaigns, or he could donate it to charity. There is another
option: Although by law the mayor may not give the money directly
to Lazio, he could give it to state or national Republican Party
committees, which could then spend it on Lazio's behalf. And state
and national Republican party officias are eager for Lazio to catch
up to Clinton in fund-raising. As of March 31, Lazio had $3.5
million in his campaign fund, while Clinton had $6.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   There have been some indications Giuliani will give some of
those fund to Republican Party committees.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Giuliani spoke to Sen. Mitch McConnell, the
chairman of the National Republican Senatorial Committee, to
discuss what could be done with his remaining money. ``There's a
good chunk of change there,'' said a committee spokesman who asked
he not be identified. ``Senator McConnell outlined what we would
like to do if we had the funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Giuliani and Lazio campaigns, which have much to
gain from cooperation, continued in that spirit Thursday. Giuliani
said that his campaign was doing everything possible to help
Lazio's fledgling operation, and Giuliani's former campaign
manager, Bruce Teitelbaum, has presided at three meetings between
members of the Giuliani and Lazio campaigns this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congressman Lazio has been effusive in his praise for the
level of cooperation that he's getting from Bruce Teitelbaum and
the people that work for me,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether that cooperation would include the
Giuliani campaign's highly valuable mailing lists of political
donors that fed the mayor's prodigiously successful fund-raising
operation. Teitelbaum would only say that the two campaigns were
``continuing to talk'' about whether Lazio would get the lists.
</P>
<P>
   Teitelbaum also said the Giuliani campaign took in $44,000 on
Wednesday alone, all from people who wrote checks to the mayor
after he dropped out of the race. All money received after
Giuliani's withdrawal, Teitelbaum said, would be returned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
