<SLUG> BC-GLF-MEMORIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRAZAR HANDLES WIND AND ROLLS TO A THREE-SHOT LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Texas)   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ohio _ On a day when only three players broke 70,
Harrison Frazar broke away from the field.
</P>
<P>
   To call the first round of the Memorial Tournament a test would
be an understatement. Not only did tricky winds gust to 20 mph
Thursday, but the Muirfield Village Golf Club course has also been
toughened for this year's event under the watchful eyes of the
designer and the host, Jack Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   But Frazar grew up in Abilene, Texas., where golfers learn to
deal with wind as soon as they learn to grip a club. Thursday,
Frazar had an extremely firm grip on his game as he shot an
impressive 6--under 66 to take a three-stroke lead.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Perry and Tom Scherrer were tied for second place at 69,
while four players were tied at 70: Justin Leonard, Greg Norman,
Gabriel Hjertstedt and Greg Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   How solid was Frazar? He is the first PGA Tour player this year
to lead by three strokes after the first round. Thursday, he was
the only player who did not make a bogey. And though the par-5
holes have been made more difficult this year at Muirfield, Frazar
birdied all four of them.
</P>
<P>
   After two third-place finishes this year in Greensboro, N.C.,
and New Orleans, Frazar, at age 28, believes his first tour victory
could be forthcoming, perhaps even this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in Texas, which just makes you more comfortable when
the wind blows,'' said Frazar, who is 35th on this year's money
list with $524,085. ``You're used to hearing the wind whistle
through your hat, so the panic mode doesn't come in as much. I
don't get to the golf course and hope that it blows 20 mph. But if
it does, I feel like I've got a pretty good shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Frazar's work was far from done. Tiger Woods, the world's No. 1
player and the defending champion, was five strokes behind Frazar
after shooting an opening-round 71.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular player at this course remained Nicklaus, who
was honored Wednesday during an emotional ceremony, and who
provided some excitement Thursday. Nicklaus struggled for most of
his round, but he birdied three of the final four holes to finish
with a very respectable 75.
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to Nicklaus, at age 60, to finish strong. After making
an 11-foot putt for birdie at No. 15, he hit his approach shot at
No. 17 to six feet, then made the birdie putt. Then, after missing
the green on his approach shot at No. 18, Nicklaus ended the day by
chipping in for a birdie from 20 feet, as the gallery roared.
</P>
<P>
   ``From where I was, it was a lot of fun to finish that way,''
Nicklaus said. ``I struggled something awful with my putter, but I
finally made one at No. 15, and that opened up the floodgates.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also a good day for Nicklaus' son, Gary, who shot 72,
despite making bogeys on No. 16 and No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing what this golf tournament means to my father and to my
mother, I've wanted to play in this for a long time,'' said Gary
Nicklaus, a rookie on tour, who lost to Phil Mickelson in a playoff
last month at the BellSouth Classic. ``It's very special for me to
be here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 2342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0390 </DOCNO>
