<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6130 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-NYT     05-25 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER LOSING EWING EARLY, KNICKS LOSE THE GAME LATE 
</HEADLINE>
  By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The time and the place were eerily familiar when
the Indiana Pacers ran back to the other end of the court and
Patrick Ewing stopped still in front of his own bench six minutes
into Game 2 of the Eastern Conference finals Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   One year ago Ewing was in this same city, on the Pacers' floor,
when he partly tore his Achilles' tendon in the pregame layup line.
He played through that Game 2 only to miss the rest of the
playoffs. This time he could not make it any longer.
</P>
<P>
   With his playoff future uncertain, Ewing limped away from Game 2
Thursday night after he sprained the peroneal tendon in his right
foot. It was unclear as to whether the injury was related to the
sore foot he had that forced him to miss Wednesday's practice.
Ewing ducked into the locker room and did not return. In his
absence, there was the same desperate atmosphere the Knicks'
thrived in last season, but their supply of pixie dust ran out when
a struggling Latrell Sprewell missed a turnaround jumper that would
have tied the game with 5.8 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   After a 3-for-14 night, Sprewell hammered the ball into the
floor after the Knicks' very last chance slipped away, too. Dale
Davis missed two free throws but grabbed his own rebound, his 16th
of the night, and passed the ball to Jalen Rose, who dunked at the
buzzer to give the Pacers an 88-84 victory. The loss left the
Knicks down, two games to none, in this four-of-seven-game series.
Game 3 is Saturday afternoon at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   With foul trouble causing attrition, the Pacers took advantage
of the Knicks thinning talent in the last 30 seconds of the game.
As he grabbed a pass, Reggie Miller was crashed into on the
perimeter by an overzealous Allan Houston with 28 seconds on the
clock. Houston fouled out, and Miller hit both free throws to break
an 84-84 tie. Without Houston, Sprewell became the go-to man but
blew his chance in the closing seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Knicks nearly pulled it off. Just as the Knicks did
last year, they leaned on Larry Johnson for 25 points, Marcus Camby
for 11 rebounds and a team pieced together with a grab bag of
previously unused players. Chris Dudley, Kurt Thomas and John
Wallace all contributed. Coach Jeff Van Gundy tried everything,
including the use of a big backcourt, in the last three minutes of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   With Johnson's strength in the low post, the Knicks held a 67-61
entering the fourth quarter. The Knicks then found themselves tied
after losing a loose ball. On a miss by Jackson, Rik Smits came up
with the ball on the floor, went in for a dunk and was fouled with
3:01 by Camby. Smits converted the 3-point play and the game was
tied at 80-80. The game was tied again at 84-84 when Rose let a
17-footer fly as the shot clock wound down with 55.5 seconds left
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Rose led the Pacers with 24 points, while the Knicks were led by
Johnson and the 15 points by Houston, who was in foul trouble.
Fouls devastated the Knicks. They held the Pacers to 36 percent
from the field, but attempted just 18 free throws compared to the
38 by Indiana.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Knicks were in an adverse position without Ewing on the
floor. Not only were they missing his offense, but they were also
missing his presence on the boards. A makeshift group now had to
hold off a Pacers team that outmuscled them on the boards and
scored 102 points in Game 1 to become the first team in the
playoffs to score more than 90 against the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense can never stop,'' Van Gundy said before the game.
``This is a team that you can make one effort or two efforts, and
they can still get a good shot. For 24 seconds, our defense can't
stop. It's got to be tenacious and aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were all of the above, plus a little lucky, at the
beginning of the game. The menace from Game 1, Austin Croshere, had
open looks on the perimeter and some layup opportunities, but
missed everything in an 0-for-7 first half. Smits was also missing
the rhythm he had on Tuesday night and shot 1 for 7 in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   With an inspired 14-point effort by Johnson, the Knicks held a
43-42 lead at halftime. They grabbed the edge by holding the Pacers
to 33.3 percent shooting from the field and tying their opponents
in rebounding, 25-25. Because of foul trouble, Davis, Johnson's
bane in Game 1, played just 11 minutes and did not even attempt a
shot.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing's absence only temporarily discombobulated the Knicks in
the first half. They still had a low-post threat in Johnson. Even
before Ewing pulled up with his injury, the Knicks ran the ball
right through Johnson and right at Davis and then Croshere. By the
end of the first half, it was clear that no one could stop Johnson
in the post.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had a chance to get their thoughts together during
halftime and plan their approach without Ewing. They stuck with
Johnson. With Houston and Sprewell struggling to hit shots
consistently, Johnson did the work inside and outside. With just
under nine minutes left in the third quarter, he lined up on the
perimeter and hit a 3-pointer to give the Knicks a 51-47 lead.
Drenched in jeers from the crowd, Johnson unveiled the ``Big L''
and ran back down the court.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers came back to tie the game on a 3-pointer by Jackson
with 6:22 left. From there, the game became a series of punches and
counterpunches. Houston scored, then Miller blew by Sprewell on the
baseline and pulled up for a jumper. After a missed free throw by
Chris Childs, Miller gave the Pacers a 59-58 lead when Houston gave
him just a sliver of room to pop a 20-footer.
</P>
<P>
   But the Knicks would not fold. Camby and Dudley started
searching out rebounds and second chances. Johnson was there to
capitalize for the Knicks. In the closing minute of the third
quarter, he put down two field goals and helped the Knicks take a
66-61 lead heading into the fourth quarter. At this point, Johnson
had 21 points.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Knicks were responsive to dire circumstances.
When Ewing left the game with 5:29 remaining in the first quarter,
he had 4 points and the Knicks had a 14-10 lead. Thomas was on the
spot and came through with some good defense on Smits and a nice
jumper.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers could not seize control of the game despite the 12
first-half points Rose scored in front of Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' bench came through. Camby, Thomas and Childs
combined to score 15 first-half points. Camby was moving much more
assertively. He had five of the Knicks' 25 rebounds at the half,
that total tying the same Pacers team that had beaten them so badly
on the boards in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks established a different tone from the start, while
the Pacers seemed sluggish and not as sharp. The Pacers have tended
to fall off their edge after a big victory, and Coach Larry Bird
said his team had a tendency to be soft in prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's soft; that's a tough word,'' Rose said
before the game. ``But at the same time, we are a team that needs
to stay on edge. We like a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   So do the Knicks. And they had one once Ewing pulled up with a
foot injury.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
