<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICAN-DIAMONDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFRICAN DIAMOND CONCERN TO SELL SHARES IN LONDON
</HEADLINE>
  By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ For years, as diamonds from African war zones fueled
conflict, African diamond-trading has been associated with
secretive deals between warlords in the bush and unscrupulous
buyers who trade gems for weapons.
</P>
<P>
   As of next month, though, in a remarkable business deal, an
African diamond company plans to sell shares on the London Stock
Exchange, offering investors a stake in a venture that includes as
partners the embattled governments of Congo and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   What investors will be buying, essentially, are the pickings
from a billion-dollar diamond mine concession, granted by decree
from the Congolese government and guarded by Zimbabwean soldiers,
at the heart of one of Africa's most troubled, decayed and divided
nations.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwean troops have been in Congo since 1998 supporting
President Laurent Kabila's government along with Angola and Namibia
against rebels backed by Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the diamond company, Oryx Diamonds Ltd., will be
offered on the Alternative Investment Market, which is part of the
London exchange, on June 13. The company is a result of a merger
between Petra Diamonds Ltd., run from South Africa with registered
offices in Bermuda, and Oryx Natural Resources, incorporated in the
Cayman Islands but run from Oman. Shareholders are scheduled to
approve that merger formally on June 12.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is thought to be the first overtly commercial venture
involving two of the countries in one of Africa's most complex
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   It has produced a company keen to establish legitimacy at a time
when Western governments are campaigning to end Africa's linkage of
diamonds and war.
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey White, the deputy managing director, said the new
company had sought to avoid secrecy about its dealings in light of
potential adverse publicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have got nothing to hide,'' he said. ``We are a company
that believes there's a commercial opportunity far greater than the
risk associated with it.''
</P>
<P>
   White denied that the diamonds would be mined in a war zone.
``The area where we are is totally secure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company, moreover, has enlisted a former U.S. ambassador in
Oman and elsewhere, Frances Cook, and a high-ranking official of
the 54-nation Commonwealth, Moses Anafu, to join its board as
nonexecutive directors, according to public documents. ``I'm very
positive about this involvement,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   Its officers also include the chief executive, Thamer bin Said
al-Shanfari, a 32-year-old Omani businessman, who has invested
millions of dollars into the deal, and Adonis Pouroulis, a
30-year-old South African mining executive whose company, Petra,
already trades on the Alternative Investment Market.
</P>
<P>
   Petra's shares almost doubled, to 80 pence, or about $1.20, when
the deal was announced on May 18.
</P>
<P>
   According to a prospectus sent to shareholders, the company will
own a 25-year concession on a large area 20 miles south of
Mbuji-Mayi, Congo's main industrial diamond zone. A geologist's
assessment in the prospectus valued the concession at $1 billion.
The profits will be shared between the company, Oryx Diamonds,
taking 40 percent, and two companies with ties to the Zimbabwean
and Congolese governments.
</P>
<P>
   Osleg, meaning Operation Sovereign Legitimacy, a Zimbabwean
company with close ties to both the government of President Robert
Mugabe and to the commander of Zimbabwe's 11,000 troops in Congo,
will take 40 percent. And a company called Comiex-Congo-Operation
Sovereign Legitimacy, will take 20 percent, the prospectus says.
</P>
<P>
   Comiex is described variously in published reports as linked to
the Congolese Army and to Kabila. But David Price, a British lawyer
working for Pouroulis, denied that the company was seen as Kabila's
personal investment vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   According to diplomats, bankers and others, both Mugabe and
Kabila had close ties to it. The Congolese diamond concession, for
instance, was taken by decree from the Congolese state diamond
company, Miba, and given to Oryx with a six-year tax moratorium,
according to Jim Williams, an independent technical consultant who
prepared a report on the concession for the merger prospectus.
Williams called the concession's kimberlite diamond deposits ``a
future world-class resource.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal has nonetheless raised questions among senior diplomats
here about two important political issues: how it will affect
efforts to bring peace to Congo, and what role it will play in the
ferocious government campaign in Zimbabwe to secure victory in
parliamentary elections scheduled for June 24 and 25 _ the first in
20 years of independence in which Mugabe has faced a serious
challenge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
