u a BC-CRAYON-ASBESTOS-SPI &LR;      05-25 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRAYON-ASBESTOS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRAYON LAB TESTS CONFLICTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW SCHNEIDER and CAROL SMITH  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Binney &AMP; Smith, makers of Crayola crayons, Thursday said an
independent laboratory had tested its crayons and found that they
do not contain asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   RJ Lee Group of Pittsburgh, an EPA-approved laboratory, said it
conducted three types of tests on two crayons and issued a report
to the company stating the crayons did not contain asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   The findings conflict with results obtained by two independent
government-certified labs who did tests at the request of the
Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   The labs used by the P-I have reconfirmed the existence of
carcinogenic tremolite and anthrophyllite fibers in repeated tests
of three brands of crayons -- Crayola, Prang and Rose Art. In
testing those brands, the labs found asbestos in 32 of 40 crayons
tested. Both RJ Lee Group and the labs used by the P-I used
multiple testing procedures, including polarized light microscopy
(PLM), transmission electron microscopy (TEM) and scanning electron
microscopy (SEM).
</P>
<P>
   Ken Bunting, the P-I's executive editor, said Thursday, ``The
P-I reported this story with balance, and great care. The tests
about which we reported were repeated numerous times. We have no
reason to doubt the findings of the government-certified
laboratories we commissioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have given all the results provided to us to the Consumer
Product Safety Commission,'' Bunting added, ``and we have
encouraged the labs to cooperate fully with the commission.''
</P>
<P>
   Other media organizations, school districts and government
agencies throughout the country said Thursday they are also testing
crayons for asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   KIRO, Channel 7, the CBS affiliate in Seattle, hired Orion
Environmental Laboratories test to crayons, chalk and other
products containing talc Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked through the microscope and I must admit I was
surprised to see fibers of tremolite clearly visible in the
Crayola,'' said Donna McNeal, director of the lab.
</P>
<P>
   McNeal said she also found asbestos in the foreign-made chalk
sample supplied by the TV station, and that the CPSC had been
notified of their findings.
</P>
<P>
   Binney &AMP; Smith said Thursday it also had turned over its new
results to the CPSC, which is conducting its own testing.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, Richard Lee of RJ Lee Group said: ``We
examined the optical properties of the minerals, as well as the
crystal structure of the talc and finished crayons, by PLM, TEM,
and SEM.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination of those techniques, which definitively
determine whether or not asbestos is present, confirmed that the
talc used in Crayola crayons and the finished products do not
contain asbestos and are safe for consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Binney &AMP; Smith Chief Operating Officer Al Hunyadi said in a
statement: ``These findings reaffirm the commitment to safety we've
upheld for nearly 100 years. Consumers who use Crayola products at
home and in school can continue to feel good about using them.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, while the CPSC continued its testing, the
Environmental Protection Agency in Washington prepared a briefing
sheet for its regional offices to use if they are asked about the
safety of crayons.
</P>
<P>
   In the paper, the agency said it ``would suggest that until more
information is available on this matter that crayons not be used.
This would be particularly true for children at ages generally 3
years old or younger, where there is a likelihood that they could,
and would, put the crayons into their mouths.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency's paper also said, ``While extremely low levels of
asbestos in crayons may not pose much of an actual risk to
children, any exposure would be unnecessary.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Public Health -- Seattle &AMP; King County issued an
advisory cautioning prents about household environmental hazards,
including asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main message for parents at this point is to make sure
that their children are not eating non-food items, crayons
included,'' said Alonzo Plough, director of the agencly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recent study just helps to remind parents of the hazards
that may be associated with consuming non-food items.''
</P>
<P>
   In its advisory, the health department also said: ``Although
there is no safe level of exposure level to asbestos, crayons are
not the only potential source of asbestos exposure in the urban
environment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-00 2358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000525.0396 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6140 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-GALARRAGA-HNS &LR;      05-25 1554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GALARRAGA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ Ask Andres Galarraga about last year, and he'll tell you
about the landscapes he painted.
<TEXT>
<P>
   His face serene, Galarraga describes sitting in his back yard
with oil paints, capturing his swimming pool and lush Florida
vegetation, an exercise that calmed and soothed a restless spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Andres Galarraga about last year, and he'll tell you about
spending time with his family.
</P>
<P>
   A smile forms as Galarraga talks about getting to spend an
uninterrupted year with his three daughters for the first time,
each day more special than the last.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Andres Galarraga about last year, and he'll tell you how he
rediscovered religion.
</P>
<P>
   His eyes glaze a bit as he describes a dream in which God came
to him and chose to make his world whole again.
</P>
<P>
   Keep asking Galarraga about last year, and he'll eventually get
to those scary, anxious moments, when an uncomfortable, nagging
back pain was finally diagnosed as non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
</P>
<P>
   But last year wasn't about suffering through cancer for
Galarraga. Last year wasn't even about surviving. It was about
getting strong, both physically and mentally, and regaining control
of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to just come back,'' said the veteran first
baseman, who with his Atlanta Braves teammates will open a
three-game series against the Astros today at Enron Field. ``I
didn't want to just be in the lineup. I wanted to be able to help
the team.''
</P>
<P>
   His isn't the first story of an athlete to beat cancer. It isn't
even the first in baseball _ Eric Davis and Darryl Strawberry
survived the deadly illness, their ordeals bringing relief and
inspiration to Galarraga last year. But Galarraga might prove to be
the biggest success story.
</P>
<P>
   Diagnosed in March 1999, Galarraga not only rejoined his
teammates this season, he's one of the top offensive players in the
National League. Galarraga, 38, is batting .346, ninth-best in the
NL. He is fifth in the league with 43 RBIs and has 12 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   His numbers thus far are his best since his years in Colorado,
when he won the batting title with a .370 average in 1993 and had
47 homers and 150 RBIs in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first day of spring training, I was nervous,'' Galarraga
said. ``I was excited just to have the bat in my hand. I was just
hoping I could hit it hard again.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine months after he finished chemotherapy, no trace of the
cancer remains, inside or out. His hair, lost during the
treatments, has grown back, though a bit more gray than before. His
body, which bloated and ballooned with as much as a 40-pound weight
gain during the treatments, is a sleek and muscular 235 pounds, one
of the more fit bodies in the Braves' locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Though Galarraga will continue to be checked regularly for
recurrence of cancer, chances are excellent it will never return.
</P>
<P>
   ``His statistics aside, just the fact that he's back here, just
his presence itself is inspiring,'' teammate Chipper Jones said.
``He's the poster child for coming back from cancer. But I'm not
surprised. I knew that if anybody could beat cancer, it would be
Andres. He has an amazing spirit, an amazing heart.''
</P>
<P>
   But Galarraga admits that spirit was tested.
</P>
<P>
   It all started toward the end of the 1998 season. Galarraga had
been feeling some tightness and soreness in his back. It was more
uncomfortable than painful, so he simply played through it. As an
athlete who is fairly in tune with his body, he assumed it was
nerve pain that would ease when the season ended. It didn't.
</P>
<P>
   He knew he shouldn't ignore it. He saw doctors, had it X-rayed.
Nothing was found. He took an anti-inflammatory medication and
waited. But the pain wouldn't ease. Finally, as spring training
neared, he underwent an MRI. Doctors saw something that looked
suspicious and called him back for further tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a call and said, `Oh, my God, something's happened,'''
Galarraga said. ``I never, never, never imagined cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   It's still a word he has trouble saying. When he speaks of the
illness, he calls it ``lymphoma,'' choosing to eliminate the ``C''
word from his vocabulary. The disease had already touched his life
once, and it didn't have a happy ending. His father, Francisco,
died of stomach cancer in 1992, and Galarraga admits he hears
``cancer'' and thinks ``death.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard (the diagnosis) and felt like I was going to die the
next day,'' Galarraga said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors quickly reassured him that medical advances have made it
possible to survive non-Hodgkin's lymphoma. Galarraga decided he
would be one of the lucky ones. But he still had to inform family
and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest part was to tell my kids and my mother,'' he said.
``I just tried to smile and didn't say `cancer.' I said `lymphoma,'
which didn't sound as scary. I didn't want to say that word because
they would think I was going to die. We tried never to use that
word at home.''
</P>
<P>
   He told his fans in Atlanta and around the major leagues in a
handwritten and signed statement that was eventually published in
several newspapers. It read, ``I was looking forward to the '99
season, unfortunately, I'm hit with this setback. But I promise
you, I will be back.''
</P>
<P>
   His body, too, was tested. Galarraga embarked on a series of six
chemotherapy treatments three weeks apart. He would get treatments
in the morning. By nighttime, he would be sick to his stomach,
sometimes unable to get out of bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that first day, I was like, `Oh, my God, how much more
of this can I take?''' he said. ``(On those days), I didn't want to
talk to anybody, I didn't want to listen to anybody. I just wanted
to be alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Miraculously, chemotherapy days were the only time he felt ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never be in bed, never looked sick,'' he said. ``I was
always smiling. But there were days when my kids came home from
school and it looked to me like they'd been crying. We had to talk
about it. I had to tell them the truth always because their friends
in school would talk.''
</P>
<P>
   It helped that good news came almost immediately. After his
first two treatments, doctors did tests to discover whether his
body was responding. He nervously waited for word.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor came in and said, `Hey, it's 75 percent gone,''' he
said. ``I was so happy, excited. It really helped me mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   After two more treatments, the news was better. The tumor had
shrunk by 95 percent. That's when Galarraga began planning his
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had this dream,'' Galarraga said. ``God put his hand in my
body. I knew I was going to be better and I was going to play
again. I love this game. It gave me strength.''
</P>
<P>
   He rejoined his teammates in September but only as a sideline
spectator. He was there for the end of the regular season, the
playoffs and the World Series. He watched as the Braves batted .200
as a team against the Yankees. He vowed to return and right that
wrong this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``With me and Javy (Lopez), that's another 80 home runs, another
200 RBIs,'' said Galarraga, whose watched the postseason with
Lopez, who was out with a torn knee ligament. ``I know we can help
those guys to be in better shape to beat the Yankees or somebody
else.''
</P>
<P>
   First came plenty of hard work. He had to work to lose weight
and get back in shape, something he had never had to do before. He
hadn't been able to exercise, hadn't thrown, caught or hit for an
entire year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first day of spring training, I was like a little kid,''
said Galarraga, who turns 39 next month. ``Worse than a rookie. I
got there two days before the pitchers and catchers. I couldn't
wait.''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates and coaches could hardly believe what they saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect what we saw in spring training the very first
day,'' manager Bobby Cox said. ``He went through a very demanding
fielding drill as if nothing was wrong with him. He was hitting
balls 500-plus feet from the first pitch that was thrown. It's an
amazing, amazing story.''
</P>
<P>
   One with any number of happy endings.
</P>
<P>
   There was the charity game in his hometown of Caracas,
Venezuela, to benefit victims of Venezuelan mudslides.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ovation they gave me was for about five minutes,''
Galarraga said. ``I had to take my hat off three or four times. My
eyes were getting wet.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, finally, there was opening day.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga made a diving catch with bases loaded in the seventh
inning to keep the Braves and Rockies locked in a scoreless tie. In
the bottom of that inning, Galarraga drilled a home run off Pedro
Astacio to welcome himself back into the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a monkey off my back,'' he said. ``The bases loaded, a
diving catch, a home run. It was like a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the feel-good movie of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a fan of the game,'' teammate Bobby Bonilla said. ``I love
watching great players, and he's one of those. He's been one of the
best offensive players in the league over the last six or seven
years, and our game needs that. The game really missed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost as much as he missed the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like my rookie year when I wanted to be 24 hours in the
ballpark,'' Galarraga said. ``I love this game so much. I want to
be here forever.''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates believe he will be.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
